<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIEB GRABS PAC-10 HONOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three years ago UCLA's starting tight end, Brian
Richards, caught five passes in an offense that treated the
position as a necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, UCLA's starting tight end, Mike Grieb, was named
first-team All-Pac-10 in voting based as much on respect as
receptions. Grieb has just 11 catches _ 25 less than Oregon's Jed
Weaver, the second-team selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell the coaches respect a guy like (Grieb) because
they have to game-plan for him,'' Bruins quarterback Cade McNown
said. ``Anytime you have that much impact that coaches have to do
something, that's respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Grieb's spot on the first team was the only mild surprise for
UCLA, which placed eight players on the coaches' all-conference
team.
</P>
<P>
   They had two first-team offensive linemen, junior tackle Kris
Farris and senior guard Andy Meyers, and one second-team selection,
senior center Shawn Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   Junior receiver Danny Farmer, senior linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo and senior safety Larry Atkins were first-team
selections.
</P>
<P>
   McNown and Oregon's Akili Smith were named first-team
quarterbacks and co-offensive players of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Grieb said. ``A lot of it's based on
reputation from past seasons. I caught 20 passes last year and (19)
the year before. The coaches know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Close vote: Two first-team quarterbacks were picked for the
first time since 1982, when UCLA's Tom Ramsey and Stanford's John
Elway shared the honor.
</P>
<P>
   McNown and Smith had impressive credentials. Smith set a Pac-10
record with a passing efficiency rating of 170.4, while McNown has
guided the Bruins to an unbeaten season.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications, Smith was the first-team pick until Toledo
lobbied for McNown on a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team was picked prior to us talking, and we went from
there _ to not answer your question,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension: Toledo has suspended reserve cornerback Eric
Whitfield indefinitely for his involvement in the Oct. 4
altercation that caused Jermaine Lewis' one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo learned of Whitfield's participation through UCLA's
investigation of the incident. Whitfield admitted his involvement
in a meeting with Toledo on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A junior from Carson, Whitfield is the No.4 cornerback and plays
in certain passing situations. He will not play at Miami and his
status for the bowl game is undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Big mouth, big regrets: Ayanbadejo said he regrets postgame
remarks about USC quarterback Carson Palmer not being as good as
UCLA's scout-team quarterbacks, and he is considering sending a
note of apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him in front of the team and told him I was
embarrassed by his comments,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Shrug it off: The Bruins are treating Miami's 66-13 loss to
Syracuse as a fluke, much like their 66-3 victory over Texas last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to have a loss like that late in the season if the
team is composed of a lot of older guys,'' McNown said. ``But
they're young, and they can say, `This (week) is the start of next
year.' For an older team, it's tough to come back, but I think
they'll put a lot of that out of their minds pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has four senior starters _ three on offense, including
quarterback Scott Covington, and one on defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
