A6037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      12-01 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ Their final four opponents are a combined 15-33, and their
magic number is down to two. But if the Cowboys regain their NFC
East crown, they'll likely do it with a host of second- and even
third-teamers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Cowboys returned to Valley Ranch on Monday following a
three-day hiatus, the training room was the most popular gathering
spot. The weekly injury report is nine players long, with the skill
and secondary positions the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   Only receiver Ernie Mills is clearly unavailable for Sunday's
game at New Orleans. Four players are listed as questionable,
including cornerback/receiver/returner Deion Sanders. Four are
listed as probable, though they aren't likely to be 100 percent. In
NFL terms, probable means there's a 75 percent chance the player
will play. Questionable means 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a number of guys go down, but that's not unusual
from how it is any other year,'' quarterback Troy Aikman said.
``Other guys just have to step in and perform at a pretty good
level for us to continue to have success.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be easy against some of the Cowboys' lesser opponents,
but a lack of cohesiveness might come back to haunt against others.
The 8-4 record this year is largely the result of a 6-0 mark
against woeful division opponents, whom Dallas again will face when
it hosts the Eagles and Redskins in the final two weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, the Cowboys must travel to New Orleans
and Kansas City, both 5-7. To make matters worse, the Cowboys are
only 2-4 against non-division teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the rash of injuries is taking its toll. The biggest problem
spot has been at cornerback, where Sanders is suffering from a
sprained toe that kept him sidelined during last week's 46-36 loss
to Minnesota. On Monday, Sanders was wearing a boot cast on his
foot for the first time. His availability for the Saints should be
determined before the weekend, coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not out there by Thursday or Friday jogging around,
there's a high risk of reinjuring it, because he'll compensate,''
said Gailey, who would make no further comment on the likelihood of
seeing Sanders in action come Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith, the Cowboys' other first-string cornerback, is also
listed as questionable with a back contusion, and backup corner
Kevin Mathis, recovering from a fractured right forearm, is
probable. Safety Darren Woodson, another stalwart of the secondary,
is listed as probable with a sprained left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Thanksgiving loss to the Vikings, the Cowboys
were down to their fourth and fifth cornerbacks, Terry Billups and
Charlie Williams. Billups was recently promoted off the practice
squad. Both could see significant playing time and perhaps even
start against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get some sense of stability in our defensive
backfield where we can get back in the groove, because I thought,
at one time, we were in the groove,'' Gailey said. ``I don't see it
as we've got horrible players on the field, or as our scheme. It's
kind of been a domino effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' last three opposing quarterbacks _ Arizona's Jake
Plummer, Seattle's Warren Moon and Minnesota's Randall Cunningham _
combined for 1,025 yards passing. Minnesota receivers Randy Moss
and Cris Carter could make a highlight film of their afternoon in
Dallas. Moss had touchdown catches of 56, 56 and 51 yards, his only
three receptions of the game, not including a two-point-conversion
catch.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who allowed Minnesota to score touchdowns on its
first three possessions, rank 26th in the league against the pass
after allowing the Vikings 353 yards through the air.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cowboys are counting on their offense to bail them
out, that, too, could be a struggle in the upcoming weeks. Depth is
again a question at receiver, where Mills remains out after
undergoing intestinal surgery. Backup Jeff Ogden went down with a
right-shoulder contusion against the Vikings and is listed as
questionable. Tight end Eric Bjornson struggled with a sprained
left ankle but is listed as probable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurts us,'' Aikman said of Ogden's injury. ``We're thin
at wide receiver anyway. Then to lose another guy thins us out even
more. But we'll work around it. We may not be able to do some
four-wide stuff because we don't have enough guys, but we'll get
around it and do some other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The injuries leave Michael Irvin, Billy Davis and Patrick
Jeffers as the lone wideouts for Sunday's contest. And they're
coming off a game in which there were an uncharacteristic nine
drops by Dallas receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think with one game you start panicking,'' Aikman
said. ``That's not a problem that has generally happened with us.
Why it happened, I don't know. But I don't expect it to happen in
the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
