r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     12-01 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON STEAMED AS KINGS LOSE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In the aftermath of the Kings' latest calamity, coach
Larry Robinson found a succinct way to describe the spot his team
finds itself in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running out of tomorrows,'' Robinson said Monday
following a 3-1 loss to the Montreal Canadiens before a Molson
Centre crowd of 20,415 on election night in the province of Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   And Robinson is running out of patience _ with defensemen who
get caught out of position and with forwards who won't create
traffic in front of the net and accept the punishment that comes
with this basic task.
</P>
<P>
   What to do about this is another story, but Robinson did not
sound Monday like a man willing to go down with his sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to say, `Oh, it's not the right personnel,'''
Robinson said following the Kings' eighth loss in their past nine
games. ``But it comes to a point where, hey, how many chances can
you give them? Guys have been given a lot of chances to prove that
they can produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't produce, then it's going to come to a point
where (general manager) Dave (Taylor) is going to come to me and
say, `Hey, you know, either you get these guys going or we'll try
to get somebody else,' or I'm out of here. And I'll be damned if
I'm going to give up that easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not being successful and it's not the players'
fault, then who's usually the fall guy? So all I'm saying is, I'll
be damned if I'm going to be the fall guy here. We're doing all
that we can and so maybe it is that we have to change some of the
personnel here. They've been given the chance. They can't say that
they haven't been given a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest loss for the Kings (6-14-3), to a team that itself
had entered the game with seven losses in its past eight games, was
the usual unappetizing combination of bad luck and bad hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Saku Koivu scored the first goal for the Canadiens (8-12-2) on a
power play six minutes into the second period when, while falling
to the ice, he swatted the puck in front of the Kings' net.
Defenseman Sean O'Donnell, concerned about a Canadien behind him,
misplayed the puck, tapping it past goalie Stephane Fiset, playing
his first game after recovering from a pair of groin strains.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was stop it, cradle it, and fire it in the
corner,'' O'Donnell said. ``But it hit my stick, and you guys saw
what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third period, the Canadiens put the game away with
two goals 1:14 apart on 2-on-1s by Brian Savage and Martin
Rucinsky. Defenseman Philippe Boucher was caught up ice on the
first goal, and defenseman Mattias Norstrom was caught out of
position on the second.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Murray scored a meaningless goal with 3:33 to play,
enabling the Kings to avoid being shut out for the second straight
game and for the fifth time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Robinson spoke of recalling such players as forwards
Greg Phillips and Chris Schmidt and defensemen Jaroslav Modry and
Jan Nemecek from the minors if the current crew doesn't soon shape
up. He said he would use center Brandon Convery on Wednesday in
Toronto, only Convery's second appearance since the Kings claimed
him on waivers from Vancouver on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to score goals unless we get guys that are
willing to pay the price in front of the net,'' Robinson said.
``We're absolutely getting no traffic in front. We can tell them to
go there and we can show them what they can do, but we're not
allowed to jump on the ice and grab them by the scruff of the neck
and place them in front of the net and say, `Hey, you've got to go
here.' They've got to get some intestinal fortitude and sacrifice
themselves by going to the front of the net, getting traffic there.
It's plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Kings this season, it's been easier said than done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
