<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6052 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-JOHN     12-01 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-JOHNSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS INVEST $52 MILLION TO WIN THE JOHNSON LOT TERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a striking new silhouette on the downtown skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, a 6-foot-10 flame-throwing left-hander who was
one of the top free agents this winter, agreed to a four-year,
$52.4 million contract with the Diamondbacks on Monday, making him
baseball's highest-paid pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Johnson gets a $5 million signing bonus. He will
receive $7.35 million in 1999 and $12.35 million in each of the
following three seasons. Part of the salary will be deferred until
his retirement. Arizona has a $12 million option for 2003 with a $3
million buyout. The option would increase to $15 million if he wins
the 2002 Cy Young Award and to $13.5 million if he's second through
fifth in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona won out over three other primary suitors who had made
similar offers _ the Anaheim Angels, Los Angeles Dodgers and Texas
Rangers. The Diamondbacks now go from a 65-97 doormat in their
inaugural season to a team capable of making a strong run at the
National League West Division title.
</P>
<P>
   The signing of Johnson, combined with the recent additions of
right-handed starters Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso,
left-handed middle reliever Greg Swindell and versatile role player
Greg Colbrunn, has increased the optimism among Arizona's
front-office and coaching staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter welcomes the challenge of becoming an
instant contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, bring it on,'' he said. ``I'd rather have a lot of
expectations like that than no expectations at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who lives in the Valley, will hold a news conference
Wednesday at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Barry Meister, who with Alan Nero represented Johnson, is
relieved that the monthlong tug-of-war is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Randy and I'm happy for the Diamondbacks and
their fans,'' Meister said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two main goals here, and neither involved money.
One was, where would he be and find the most happiness for the rest
of his career and two, would there be an overwhelming commitment to
winning and getting a chance to get to the World Series. Arizona
has shown us a blueprint for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night, Jerry walked into Randy's living room and
said, `Bet on me. I'm going to make the club better.' He went out
and got Stottlemyre and Reynoso and said, `I'm not done,' and told
Randy, `I won't be done after I get you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The offers were just about equal. And Randy said, `All things
being equal, I'd rather be a Diamondback.' They involve the family.
They have a terrific manager, a nice mix of players . . .
hopefully, Randy can help drive the team forward so that in late
September, they'll be involved in two or three series that really
mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said his competitiveness led him to pursue Johnson and
the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exhilarating opening season for us,'' Colangelo
said. ``But we got our brains beat out too many times. We took a
lot of losses. I wondered what kind of honeymoon with the fans we
were going to have. I looked at the lay of the land and decided
that we had to go sooner rather than later, make more of an attempt
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a few pointed words for critics who say he is trying to
buy himself a pennant. The team's player payroll will rise from
$32.8 million in 1998 to the $53 million range, excluding deferred
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that really matters is reality, and what we are doing,
what Joe (Garagiola Jr., general manager), Buck and I, what
everybody is doing, is trying to compete. Why is it not OK for us
to do something and it's OK for the Yankees, or anybody else, for
that matter? I'll say again what I've said before _ if anybody asks
why, they should look in the mirror first and then go about their
own business.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first orders of business for Diamondbacks equipment
manager Chris Guth was to call Johnson's previous team, the Houston
Astros, about pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a 38-inch inseam,'' Guth said. ``They're probably so
long that we'll have to hang 'em outside the locker at the top
instead of inside. I think he's going to be fun to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   The business of upgrading the club also includes trades, and the
Diamondbacks might be involved in some of those, particularly since
there now is a surplus of starters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Johnson, Stottlemyre and Reynoso, there is
right-hander Andy Benes, the team's top winner in 1998 with 14, and
left-handers Brian Anderson and Omar Daal. Anderson won 12 games
and finished as the majors' top pitcher in terms of fewest walks
per nine innings (1). Daal won eight games while finishing fifth in
the NL in ERA with 2.88.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have begun to circulate that Anderson, the team's top
pick in the expansion draft, and/or Daal could be involved in a
trade, with Arizona receiving a starting outfielder in return.
Anderson has heard the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got three big horses now, and they certainly didn't sign
Armando for that kind of money ($5 million over two years) to put
him in the bullpen,'' Anderson said from his home in Ohio. ``So do
the math. I'm probably going be the guy to go. The Diamondbacks are
a class organization and I'd still like to be a part of it, but
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola could engineer a deal or two at the annual winter
meetings that begin Dec. 11 in Nashville. Or the team could sit
tight and see which teams want to add pitching, perhaps into the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson began his career with the Angels and then went to
Cleveland. He has admired Johnson's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to face him. Especially left-handed hitters. He
strikes fear,'' Anderson said. ``On days he would pitch against us,
some of the guys would say their knees had gotten a bit more sore
all of a sudden and wanted to sit out.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has 2,329 career strikeouts and a 143-79 record, but
there is more to his success than his fastball, according to Kelly
Stinnett, who will be one of his new batterymates with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a nasty slider that he uses to set up the fastball
and can throw it at any point in the count,'' Stinnett said. ``He
can throw the slider down and in, then come back with a 96-mph
fastball on the outside part of the plate. That fastball can be
unhittable. It's kind of scary. I'm just glad I'll be back a few
extra feet so I'll have chance to see it and catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor said when the team faced
Seattle last spring, Johnson was working on a change-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely more mature, more of a pitcher than he was in
his early days with Montreal,'' Connor said. ``He used to be a
`spinner,' moving around in his delivery, but when he became more
squared up is when he had more success. What you want to do with a
guy like that is not change too much but help keep him on track
with the stuff that got him where he is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
