<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6059 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OJ-JERSEY-COLUMN-LADN     12-01 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OJ-JERSEY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O.J. JERSEY UNWANTED IN THE LONG RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You never know.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somebody out there wants a genuine, never-been-washed, USC
football jersey O.J. Simpson wore when he ran for 205 yards and
three touchdowns in a 28-16 win over UCLA 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Kaye doesn't want it anymore. Neither does his nephew,
Mark Grobman, or Mark's father, Gene. They want to give the jersey
away to a charity to auction off or sell.
</P>
<P>
   They figure it would be dirty money they'd be collecting,
selling it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's much better that any money gained from selling O.J.'s old
college jersey go someplace where it could do some good. Maybe send
a message.
</P>
<P>
   Someplace like a shelter for battered women.
</P>
<P>
   Once, this No. 32 jersey was the pride and joy of these
families. They laughed and pranced about in it, each trying on the
jersey for pictures that went into the family album.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they framed it and hung it up on a bulletin board above
young Mark's bed with a program from the 1968 USC-UCLA game.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where it hung for almost two decades until Mark went
off to college and the jersey was returned to Uncle Mitch, who put
it away and forgot about it until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1994. Before the brutal deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a letter to O.J., care of NBC, where he was working as
a football commentator, to see if he wanted it back or wanted me to
give it to his favorite charity,'' Kaye said Monday, rummaging
through old boxes to find the jersey he had banished to the garage
after the slayings of Simpson's ex-wife Nicole Brown Simpson and
her friend Ronald Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, a Burbank physical therapist, was a student at the
University of Southern California back in 1968, learning his future
trade by helping out the football team on the sidelines, taping
players' ankles and assisting team physicians.
</P>
<P>
   After the University of California, Los Angeles, game, when O.J.
set two NCAA season rushing marks, Kaye pushed through a crowd of
reporters waiting to talk to the running back outside the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he had to hurry up and get undressed because the
reporters were waiting,'' Kaye said. ``I helped him pull off his
jersey, and walked out of the locker room with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, I gave it to my sister for her wedding
anniversary because we were all big USC fans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye isn't sure whether there is a statute of limitation on the
theft of football jerseys, but he's hoping it doesn't last longer
than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after trying to contact Simpson, via NBC, Kaye says
he got a call from O.J.'s secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said he would want it back and for me to send it to him,''
Kaye said. ``I told her I didn't want to mail it, that I wanted to
give it to O.J. personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me he was out of town shooting a film, but when he
got back they'd try to find a date where we could meet, and I could
give him his jersey back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, other events precluded that meeting,'' Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Simpson on Monday through his agent and
attorneys were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do now is give the jersey away to a charity,''
Kaye said. ``I don't want it around here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But that may be easier said than done. Betty Fisher, executive
director of Haven Hills, a nonprofit organization that houses and
counsels battered women and their children, expressed the majority
view of other charities and goodwill organizations I contacted
Monday about O.J.'s old jersey.
</P>
<P>
   It's tainted goods. They don't want to touch it. But they
wouldn't mind the money it might bring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody else auctioned off the jersey and donated the
money to us, I think I could justify that,'' Fisher said. ``But I
couldn't justify auctioning off the jersey ourselves. It just
wouldn't be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, there's such a chill on O.J. Simpson items right
now, according to sports memorabilia dealers, that they don't even
want to venture a guess on what his jersey might bring on the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing (with) O.J. sells. Cards, you name it,'' says Richard
Khoury, co-owner of Sports Memorabilia Etc. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a 1975 O.J. football doll set I can't give away.
People just aren't buying his stuff. At first (after the slayings)
everybody wanted it. Now they've backed away.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case anyone is interested in having O.J.'s old college
jersey _ even just to throw darts at it _ give me a call at the
paper, (818) 713-3749, and I'll pass the offer on to Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   We'll make sure the money winds up someplace where it will do
some good and maybe send a message.
</P>
<P>
   Someplace like a shelter for battered women.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 0032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
