<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`MESSIES-ANONYMOUS'-I     12-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`MESSIES-ANONYMOUS'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOBS HELPED BY ORGANIZATION FOR DISORGANIZATION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Florida)   (This quirky 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 By IMRE KARACS  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN _ Germany's most persecuted minority hide behind an
answering machine. You leave a message, and wait for the
conspiratorial return call. Five days later, the phone rings at
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``You called, Herr Crackers,'' a woman intones in a soft voice.
``We are the Messies.''
</P>
<P>
   There is barely enough time to grab a pen. The caller is
wrestling with a baby, and her two other small children are making
noises in the background. A perfect moment, then, to conduct the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Susanne Herms, she was teacher of English and
Religious Studies at a Gottingen grammar school before she started
planning a family. Now she is at home, and when she has some spare
time, she acts as the national coordinator for one of the
fastest-growing movements in the country: ``Messies Anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an American organization, invented by a Florida housewife,
which in Germany has found fertile soil. In just over two years, 40
local groups of ``Messies Anonymous'' have sprung up, organized _
if that is the right word _ by 300 contact persons.
</P>
<P>
   Herms, and the toddler who occasionally screams ``Mamma'' into
the receiver, are at the apex of this pyramid. What they and the
army of anonymous supporters who meet in secret locations up and
down the country have in common is their shameful secret: they are
disorganized.
</P>
<P>
   They rally behind the English word ``messy'' because the German
language does not have an equally forgiving equivalent. In their
native tongue their crime is ``Unordnung,'' the opposite of
``Ordnung,'' or order.
</P>
<P>
   Ordnung is what all Germans aspire to. To be lacking in Ordnung
is akin to being afflicted with bubonic plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a joke,'' Herms says. ``Many people laugh when you
miss an appointment or can't find your things. But there are
dramatic cases: people whose personal relationships break down
because of their Unordnung.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not punctual, you can lose your job. And you can
lose your friends if you don't dare to let them into your house,
because you're too messy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though you would never believe it, an estimated 10 percent of
Germans suffer from this ailment, and their numbers are rising.
</P>
<P>
   While scientists are coming to the conclusion that
disorganization is an inherited trait, the erosion of social
conventions is also blamed for increasing manifestations of this
aberrant behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Modernity and loose morals are wreaking havoc. A whole
generation of Germans has grown up never once having been clipped
around the ear for smudging the door handle in the kitchen. Some
others have, but they force themselves to be messy as a token of
rebellion against parental authority.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, young Germans protested against the world of
their elders by becoming urban guerrillas. Today they do it by
walking around with untied shoelaces.
</P>
<P>
   As the traditional society unravels, great changes are in store.
Soon it may no longer be commonplace to see the womenfolk of your
neighborhood sweeping the pavement in front of their houses at 8:25
every morning with a small broom and dustpan. There might even be a
noticeable decline in car hygiene in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, though, the disorganized must keep their
disability in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in Germany are successful at work, but they
hide their disorganized home life,'' Herms says. Those who want to
come out can go to meetings of ``Messies Anonymous,'' to meet
like-minded people and receive tips on how to cope.
</P>
<P>
   This being an American movement, there are sure-fire cures,
developed by its patron saint, Sandra Felton. She has identified
three types of messies: the ``hoarder,'' the ``time messy'' and the
``chaos worker.''
</P>
<P>
   In the German environment, the second syndrome is the most
socially crippling. Once the malady is diagnosed, each sufferer is
offered a cure of his or her own.
</P>
<P>
   It says a lot about the advance of American civilization in the
late 20th century that even the Germans are turning to a Florida
guru to learn about ``Ordnung.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain, for once, is sadly lagging behind in domesticating this
bit of Americana. Despite the obviously higher proportion of slobs
residing across the Channel, Felton's book, published 16 years ago,
has bombed in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the British publishers, this book doesn't suit
the British market,'' Herms says. ``British people who are
disorderly seem happy with their lifestyle.'' In Germany, though,
the book is selling like hot cakes. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this droll 750-word article, it must be purchased from
New York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New
York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
