<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-KICKERS     12-01 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-KICKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS BEGIN AUDITIONS TO REPLACE INJURED NEDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Jacke and Cole Ford will be the men on the spot today when
they audition for the Cardinals' place-kicking job, according to
league sources.
</P>
<P>
   Injured Cardinals kicker Joe Nedney also planned to be there,
hoping to see something that will ease both his and the team's
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney's season likely came to an end during the fourth quarter
of Sunday's 34-24 loss to the Kansas City Chiefs. He suffered what
initially was diagnosed as a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his
left knee when his cleat hung up while being blocked on a kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney and middle linebacker Ron McKinnon, who suffered a
sprained knee during the game but continued to play until the late
stages, underwent magnetic reasonance imaging Monday, but the
results weren't available because team physician Russell Chick was
in surgery most of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Both players were on crutches Monday at the Cardinals' training
facility. While McKinnon said he thought he might be able to play
by Sunday, a team source said it didn't ``look good.'' Nedney
talked like a man who knows his season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's the best-case scenario and I just have a sprained
knee, I'll be out for four games and that's all that are left,'' he
said, sounding despondent. ``If there is any way I could be back in
five weeks and play in a playoff game, I would be there in a
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my absence be the missing piece to whether or not
we make the playoffs, so I really hope somebody comes in and steps
up and help this team get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, a native of Tucson who starred at Sabino High School
before going to Southern Cal and on to a three-year career with the
Oakland Raiders, has made 33 of 35 extra points and 45 of 62
field-goal attempts, with a career-long 53-yard effort.
</P>
<P>
   Ford spent the first two weeks of this season as Buffalo's
kickoff specialist but was released.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke, who has playoff experience, spent eight years with the
Green Bay Packers and played one game last December with Washington
before being released after the season. He has made 306 of 311
extra points and 173 of 224 field-goal attempts during his career,
while connecting on field goals of 50 yards or more eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the job will have to handle both place-kicking and
kickoffs. Kickoffs, vital in the battle for field position, aren't
considered a strength for either kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever comes in will handle them both because we kind of
found out that (punter) Scott Player isn't a great kickoff man,''
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said. ``We would like to have a guy who
can do both, but if I have to chose one over another, I would opt
for the guy you are sure can kick it through the uprights. That's
how you get points.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedney knows exactly what Ford and Jacke will go through today.
He said he has been through five or six auditions himself during
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real gong show,'' he said. ``It's nerve-racking. If you
miss one and the other guy makes one, you start pressing and
watching the coach who is doing the evaluating and writing
something down. It's like taking a driving test while somebody
writes things down and tells you when your done if you passed or
failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who said he had never had a kicker suffer a serious knee
injury, labeled Nedney's loss disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was really becoming a consistent kicker,'' he said. ``Fans
and the media only see the kicking he does in games, but we watch
him kick five field goals a day in game-type situations. It's not
live but we have a rush and I've seen his consistency increase
dramatically during the year. He range has also increased
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel badly for Joe as a person because he has worked
extremely hard to become a consistent kicker, and this is
definitely a setback to him.''
</P>
<P>
   While ACL injuries once meant a full year out, improved surgical
procedures have lowered that time by as much as six months. Nedney
said he's heard it's even less for kickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way my leg swings, the ACL is not as important, and I've
heard it takes about three or four months,'' he said. ``If I need
the surgery, I want to get it done as soon as possible because I
plan to be ready for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once in my career, I think I have some stability with this
organization. I've worked hard and I don't think they will let it
go unnoticed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
