<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6076 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SWIM-HALL-AZR &LR;      12-01 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-HALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE CLEARS WAY FOR HALL TO SWIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Hall Jr. apparently will be in the starting blocks this
morning at a key international swimming event after a federal judge
in Phoenix issued a restraining order late Monday against the
federation that sought to ban him because of marijuana use.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Roger Strand issued the emergency order
after Hall's lawyer argued that FINA, the Swiss-based federation,
had effectively sought to double the three-month suspension
punishment it imposed upon Hall in June.
</P>
<P>
   Strand convened the hearing shortly after 5 p.m., accepting the
emergency request by Ed Hendricks and Michael Ross, lawyers for
Hall. Hendricks said Hall's appeal of the suspension was rejected
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Hall already had been barred from two international
competitions in the summer, Hendricks said that unless Strand
intervened, Hall would be unable to swim in two events this week in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a world-class swimmer with two gold medals and
you can't swim in major international events, you are not going to
be prepared for the next Olympics,'' Hendricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Strand granted the order after trying unsuccessfully to contact
a FINA representative by telephone in Lausanne, Switzerland, where
the local time was past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   But after expressing concern that by allowing Hall to swim, he
might be knocking another swimmer out of the water, the judge
ordered Hall's attorneys to be back in court at 7:15 this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Strand's decision to revisit the issue apparently held open the
possibility that he could rescind his restraining order before Hall
swims. Hendricks said Hall was scheduled to swim at 8 or 9 a.m.
Phoenix time. He said Hall also is scheduled to swim this weekend
at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hall received his three-month ban in mid-May. But in mid-August,
after Hall had missed the Goodwill Games and U.S. Senior Nationals,
FINA suspended the ban while it was reviewed by its doping panel.
</P>
<P>
   The panel last month restored the ban, giving Hall credit for
only two months. Hall's final appeal to the Court of Arbitration
for Sport was denied Monday, setting the stage for the hearing
before Strand. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
