<HEADLINE>
INJURIES MAY FORCE CARDI NALS TO SHUFFLE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If middle linebacker Ron McKinnon, who suffered what is believed
to be a sprained knee in Sunday's loss to Kansas City, doesn't play
on Sunday, it could force several changes in the Cardinals'
struggling defense.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon's backup, Mark Maddox, missed the Kansas City game
because of a knee problem, but Coach Vince Tobin believes he will
return for Sunday's game against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked Jamir Miller and Terry Irving at that spot and
when Ronnie couldn't go Sunday we put Terry there,'' Tobin said.
``But we could also put Jamir there and play Patrick Sapp at
Jamir's outside spot if Maddox can't play.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of McKinnon, plus that of defensive tackle Eric
Swann, who's still considering arthroscopic surgery next Monday
that would end his season, comes at a terrible time.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the Cardinals weak up the middle against the Giants,
who have rushed for 581 yards against them in their past three
outings, while outscoring them by an average of 27-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants have moved the ball in recent years by running
it,'' Tobin said. ``We have not been able to score much on them and
have been playing from behind, which has allowed them to pound the
ball. ``It's a double-edged sword. The offense can take a lot of
pressure off the defense by scoring early and making them play a
more conventional game than they have had to. I think our defense
will step up and play well down the stretch. The guys who are
playing are just going to have to step up to the challenge if Swann
and McKinnon can't play.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Likes moves &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tobin was pleased with the play of rookie cornerback Corey
Chavous and safety Kwamie Lassiter, each of whom made their first
starts against the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corey played pretty good for his first time,'' Tobin said.
``He got beat a couple of times, but most cornerbacks do get beat
at times. He was also in good position a lot of the time and made
an excellent interception that gave us an opportunity to get back
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kwamie played quite well. He made a lot of tackles and was in
the right position most of the time and came up and filled the
alley really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavous' interception was the first by a Cardinals' cornerback
other than Aeneas Williams in 39 games. &QL;  &QL; 
First downs &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Giants planned to fly to Tucson after Monday night's game
against San Francisco, where they will practice before coming to
the Valley on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Adrian Murrell's 31-yard run against the Chiefs was
the team's longest in 31 games, since Lashon Johnson ran for 31
yards against the New York Jets on Oct. 27, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Giants-49ers game, Cardinals receiver Frank
Sanders led the NFC in receptions with 64, three more than the
49ers' Jerry Rice. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
