<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-HOOPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LET UP BUT WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's already obvious USC doesn't need any lessons
on winning basketball games, but putting a complete 40 minutes
together remains a sticky subject.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans put away St. Bonaventure 91-82 before 2,070 at the
Sports Arena on Monday but would have felt a lot better if the game
had been 34 minutes long instead of 40.
</P>
<P>
   USC (4-0) led 82-57 with six minutes remaining and seemed primed
for a casual end to their blowout victory. But after starters Brian
Scalabrine and Brandon Granville were taken out, the Bonnies took
advantage by outscoring the Trojans 25-9. The game was never in
doubt, but a satisfying victory suddenly became another growing
pain for the youthful Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blow a 25-point lead down to nine points,''
Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, USC continues to be off to its best start in
10 years and continues to draw Top 25-poll votes. But nobody was
really celebrating after the Trojans defeated the struggling
Bonnies (2-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were ready to play,'' USC coach Henry Bibby
said. ``We got the victory. We got what we wanted. We didn't play
40 minutes. We didn't come out of the locker room ready to go like
I thought we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sensing the Trojans needed a shake-up and because
forward Jarvis Turner remains bothered by back spasms, Bibby gave
forward Greg Lakey his first start of the season. The move paid off
but for Turner more than Lakey. Turner came off the bench and
scored 16 points and grabbed six rebounds in 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when people go to the bench they get frustrated. I
wanted to give the team a boost and some life,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the back spasms. Turner said he felt ``so-so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also received a lift off the bench from Adam
Spanich, who had 18 points and four 3-pointers. In addition,
Scalabrine was his usual self, with 15 points and eight rebounds,
and Granville had 14 points and eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a pretty nice effort, if you erase those final six
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a mental lapse the last five minutes,'' Turner
said. ``We stopped playing hard. We kind of got complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   The players claimed their letdown had nothing to do with St.
Bonaventure, another relatively unimpressive team on the schedule
before USC has to play Kansas on Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually not in our nature to take teams lightly,''
Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Kevin Augustine had his best game of the season, since
returning to the team after being suspended during the preseason
for personal reasons. Augustine played 17 minutes and had seven
points and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back in shape,'' Augustine said. ``I definitely feel like
I am excited about the team again. I have the attitude that if I
get a minute, I just go in and play hard. I put myself in this
situation and this role and I'm accepting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Trojans are rated 22nd in the latest Jeff Sagarin
power ratings.... It might be time for sophomore forward Shannon
Swillis to consider switching from small forward back to power
forward. He didn't play a second straight game and is sitting
behind Spanich and Jeff Trepagnier. Freshman forward Sam Clancy
played just two minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
