<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT LEAVING WITH NO BITTERNESS  
 QB SAYS TRANSFER WAS ONLY OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-ELLIOTT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he called his release from the team a shock, Chad
Elliott said he intended to transfer anyway after realizing he
``would never be allowed to be on equal ground'' with starting
quarterback Ryan Kealy.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also said Monday he will not leave Arizona State with
hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The redshirt freshman did not accompany the Sun Devils to Tucson
on Thursday after being told by Coach Bruce Snyder that his
presence on the team would be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me in meetings and said, `What are your plans
for next year?' '' Elliott said. ``I told him, `I don't think I
have a future here and I don't think it would be in my best
interest to stay.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood that. He basically wished me the best of luck
and told me they weren't going to take me to the last game because
they didn't need any distractions going to UofA.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who received his official release from ASU on Monday,
said Ohio State and Tennessee are among the schools he is
considering. The Buckeyes have contacted ASU to seek permission to
talk to him, he said. The Volunteers are interested in him because
his best friend from high school, Dante Stallworth, is a receiver
there.
</P>
<P>
   If Elliott transfers to a Division I school, he will lose a
season of eligibility and would be required to sit out a year. He
does not intend to transfer to a Pac-10 schoolbecause that would
mean a loss of two seasons of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it was a shock to me how they did it at the last
minute, I'm happy overall with the way they've handled it,''
Elliott said. ``Coach Snyder could have really been angry at me and
said, `We're going to try to hinder your progress of trying to go
somewhere and trying to be successful.' He didn't do anything like
that at all. He understood what I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said he made the decision to release Elliott after his
recent body language suggested he wasn't focused on game
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes coaches, in trying to understand where a
player's coming from, will try to look for things that aren't
there,'' Elliott said. ``That's not how I felt at all. I practiced
hard. I was disappointed. I wanted to go to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said he began to evaluate his future at ASU after
watching his role change. He went from third string, to starter
against Stanford, to being pulled in the third quarter and then
``back to third string.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said he watched the Arizona game, which ASU lost, 50-42,
at a pizza parlor with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard,'' he said. ``I felt I should have been out there
on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott called Kealy and backup quarterback Steve Campbell
``great guys. I'll be able to take a lot from them. They really
helped me in becoming a college quarterback. They know a lot of
things I didn't know. They were like coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said he will complete the current semester at ASU and
then begin taking recruiting trips in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say I'm happy to leave, but in a way, I am
because I know I can go somewhere and get a fresh start, fresh
opportunity,'' he said. ``But there's no bitterness at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
