<HEADER>
A6082 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_YOUNGSTER     12-01 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_YOUNGSTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGSTERS NOW PLAYING ROLE IN COYOTES SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young guns.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld made a point of mentioning it
nearly every day during training camp. If the Coyotes were to truly
take it to the next level this NHL season, their batch of young
players would have to step up and contribute in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the kids are all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while there, our first line of (Jeremy) Roenick, (Keith)
Tkachuk and (Dallas) Drake, along with Rick Tocchet, was carrying
the burden of the offensive production,'' Schoenfeld said. ``It's
difficult to maintain a good winning percentage when you only have
four or five players that are putting out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the last few games, we've been spreading it out. . . .
That's what you need over the course of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have taken awhile, but the Coyotes' 20-something crowd of
forwards Daniel Briere, Brad Isbister, Shane Doan and Juha Ylonen,
and defensemen Oleg Tverdovsky, Deron Quint and Bryan Helmer are
every bit as responsible for the team's eight-game winning streak
and club-record 14-game unbeaten streak as Tkachuk, Roenick and
Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   Especially lately.
</P>
<P>
   Briere, 21, a rookie center, has chipped in two goals and two
assists, including a power-play tally Saturday in Los Angeles that
propelled first-place Phoenix (14-2-2) to a 4-0 victory and its
eighth straight win.
</P>
<P>
   Isbister, 21, a second-year right wing, snared two goals in a
three-game span. Doan, 22, a physical right wing in his fourth NHL
season, finally got off the scoreless sheet with two big assists
against the Kings. Ylonen, a second-year pro at age 26, has eight
assists and got his first goal Saturday in LA.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 22-year-old Tverdovsky and fellow blueliners
Quint, 22, and Helmer, 26, are taking care of business in the zone,
playing shipshape defense for a club that has set an NHL
post-expansion record by going 17 straight games of allowing only
two goals or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   And those three generally are labeled as ``offensive''
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have been doing the job and that's what we need,''
said Tkachuk, who with 12 goals through 18 games is on pace for his
third 50-goal season. ``Everybody is a big piece of this puzzle,
whether you're 35 or you're 25 or you're 19 or 20. It's big. The
younger guys are getting their opportunity to play, and they've got
to produce, and that's a big lift if guys like Jeremy, myself and
Dally get shut down. Same thing if it's Tocchet or `Gus' (Adams)
that gets shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need guys like these young guys, Danny, Izzy, Doaner and
Juha to step in, and that's what they're doing. That's depth.
That's what teams like the Detroit Red Wings have. You need guys
scoring goals on the third and fourth lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld has the Coyotes' young guns spread throughout the
lineup. Briere, for example, whose playmaking abilities and past
scoring exploits made former veteran Cliff Ronning expendable in a
trade last month to Nashville, is centering the No. 2 line between
Adams and Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   Doan has been busy on a defensive-oriented third line, playing
with Ylonen and Bob Corkum in the middle. Isbister, who's been up
and down from the minor leagues, seems to have found a home on the
fourth line with center Mike Stapleton and left wing Mike Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   But it's all interchangeable, which Schoenfeld proved in
Saturday's shutout over the Kings and an impressive 3-2 victory
over New Jersey earlier. At different times, Briere subbed for
Roenick on the first line, Ylonen subbed for Briere on the second
line, and Briere hooked up with Isbister and Doan on a forward line
the Coyotes have taken to calling the ``Kid Line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Shane a lot last year in Springfield (in the
American Hockey League) and I played with Izzy at the World Juniors
two years ago, and we've all had success before,'' Briere said.
``We tried doing it in the preseason this year and it didn't work,
for whatever reason, but . . . we know it can.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been times lately when the Kid Line has been on the
ice at the same time as Quint and Helmer, prompting some to
second-guess Schoenfeld's shift patterns. But it's hard to argue
with the results.
</P>
<P>
   It may change, but the kids know they're all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know who you're going to play with, but of course,
you'd love to play with Daniel and Izzy,'' Doan said. ``We're all
good friends and we get along great. But right now, we're all on
different lines and it doesn't matter because everyone is going
great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
