<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GREENBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE PITCH  
 D-BACKS' PRICE HIKES BRING STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo, the Diamondbacks' managing general partner, has
a message for those who are irked over the team raising ticket
prices after its first season: Yes, the club is fixated with the
bottom line. But not the one beneath a column of dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone thought we were a cash cow and we were putting money
in our pockets, that couldn't be any further from the truth,''
Colangelo said after the Diamondbacks signed pitcher Randy Johnson
to a four-year contract worth $52.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is run a business, put money into the
product. We're trying to build something people will be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans in turn responded immediately. Dianne Aguilar, the club
vice president of ticket operations, said a surge in season ticket
inquiries began when the news about Johnson surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't recall a day where we've been this busy, that early
and throughout the day,'' Aguilar said late Monday before the final
numbers had been tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices and sales and the financial implications of the
deal were not foremost on Colangelo's mind as he stood on the field
Monday at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now appears we can go out there every night and compete,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as a businessman, Colangelo is aware of numbers besides
Johnson's ERA.
</P>
<P>
   About 67 percent of last year's season ticket holders have
renewed so far. Some of those who didn't are disenchanted with the
increase, but club officials say most did not want to commit to a
full schedule of 81 games. Now, with the addition of Johnson plus
four other free agents, sales are sure to climb. Colangelo said the
goal is 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One fan who did renew his tickets said his faith in the
franchise has been restored. Joe McKenzie, a Phoenix accountant,
said he wasn't happy with the increase but was curious about what
the Diamondbacks would do in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see how quickly they were going to make the team
competitive,'' he said. ``I think they've made a pretty good first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   The signing of Johnson, one of the game's premier pitchers, caps
an early Christmas season for the Diamondbacks. They shopped for
another quality starter, Todd Stottlemyre, plus pitchers Armando
Reynoso and Greg Swindell and first baseman-outfielder Greg
Colbrunn. The price tag for all five comes to about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it appears the Diamondbacks' payroll took a huge
leap from last year's $32 million to $53 million so far. And
officially, it has. But through what Colangelo calls ``creative
structuring,'' a good portion of the salaries of Johnson,
Stottlemyre and third baseman Matt Williams have been deferred
until their retirements. Colangelo said that will reduce this
year's actual payroll to about $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   Club President Rich Dozer said the Diamondbacks broke even with
the cash last year, and that was after drawing more than 3.6
million fans. What about this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be close,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson in particular and a presumably better Diamondbacks
team that went 65-97 in 1998 might translate into added revenue.
Johnson was responsible for an additional 15,000 fans each time he
pitched in Houston last season. The Diamondbacks don't have room
for that kind of jump, but a full house when he takes the mound at
Bank One Ballpark is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   A better team also means better television ratings or even more
games on TV, which means more advertising, and it means more
souvenir sales, like those high-priced jerseys (look for lots of
Johnson's No. 51 popping up around town).
</P>
<P>
   ``I can quantify a pretty substantial return,'' Colangelo said.
``So it's not all negative cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   But mainly, Colangelo said the intent was to ``cut short
dramatically'' the time it takes to become competitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
