<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6084 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-RE     12-01 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROTATION BEST IN NL WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some day, probably not too far off, the folks in the
Diamondbacks' front office will chuckle in amazement at the
difference between the club's starting rotation in its inaugural
season and the one taking the mound in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks believe they're assured of playing meaningful
games next September after they landed prized free agent Randy
Johnson on Monday with a four-year contract worth $52.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson agreed to become the ace of the fledgling
franchise's rotation, joining the starting pitchers already on
board, it gave the Diamondbacks what many observers say is the most
menacing staff in the National League outside the Atlanta city
limits.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's arrival is expected to have a positive domino effect
on the rest of the rotation. Sliding Todd Stottlemyre and Andy
Benes back into the Nos. 2 and 3 slots will make them more
effective. And pushing back Omar Daal and Armando Reynoso into the
Nos. 4 and 5 positions gives the Diamondbacks the best rotation,
top to bottom, in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many clubs in the National League wouldn't want to have
that rotation?'' Florida General Manager Dave Dombrowski said.
``The elite No. 1 starters, there just aren't that many of those
guys. Everyone in baseball wants one.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was 10-1 with a 1.28 ERA in 11 starts for Houston
after being traded by Seattle on July 31, showed he is still
capable of being the most dominant pitcher in the game when he sets
his mind to it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of comments from some sage baseball people:
</P>
<P>
   Detroit GM Randy Smith: ``Whoo! That's a pretty impressive
rotation. It's a terrific staff. It's a staff you can consider that
of a contender. There's still some other questions, but you look at
the depth of the rotation and I think they're a threat. We've been
talking about their rotation here in the office for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Manager Lou Piniella: ``That's a pretty formidable group
of starters. Randy's definitely got a lot left and he showed that
after he got to Houston. He competes. He's one of the top five guys
in baseball, no question. I'm happy for him because he's staying
home and that was important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego GM Kevin Towers: ``What a dominant No. 1 does, more
than anything, is allow everyone else in the rotation to relax a
little. Kevin Brown did that for us last season and we ended up in
the World Series. Have they improved themselves? Most definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees GM Brian Cashman: ``They now have a chance to win every
day. To be able to put a starter out there who gives your offense
that chance is immeasurable. I'm just glad Randy Johnson's in the
National League and we won't have to contend with him. It's a
championship rotation, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside the rave reviews (which mean little since they're
coming in December), the Diamondbacks have more work to do before
they can become just the second expansion club to post a winning
season in its second season (the Angels did it when they went 86-76
in 1962).
</P>
<P>
   The ledger will show the club's payroll jumping to somewhere in
the mid-$50 million range. In upfront cash, though, $15 million
must be subtracted from that total, because Johnson, Stottlemyre,
Matt Williams and Bernard Gilkey are all taking deferred payments
for nearly half of their combined $32.5 million salaries next
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will pay an additional $20 million or so to the
remaining players on their roster, giving them a projected payroll
somewhere near $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how to improve the offense, which scored
more runs than only Tampa Bay, Pittsburgh and Montreal last season.
With Brian Anderson suddenly expendable, the club is willing to
listen to offers for the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   What can Anderson bring the Diamondbacks? Cleveland's Richie
Sexson and Anaheim's Jim Edmonds are possibilities. In addition,
with starting pitching being so scarce these days, at least in most
other cities, you never know what some club may be willing to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Now we'll find out just how important pitching really is. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
