<HEADER>
A6087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-impeach01-cox     12-01 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-impeach01-cox </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   House takes probe into fund-raising
</P>
<P>
   By Rebecca Carr
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998, Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Washington House Republicans are broadening the focus of the
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton beyond his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky to include alleged campaign finance abuses,
requesting the chief investigators of that probe to appear before
the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee will vote today on whether to
issue five new subpoenas, including one addressed to the president,
one to Attorney General Janet Reno and one to FBI Director Louis
Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's subpoena does not ask him to appear before the panel,
but it does seek memos related to alleged Democratic campaign
fund-raising abuses during the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is interested in memos authored by Freeh, and by
Charles LaBella, a former Justice Department prosecutor who headed
the investigation into campaign fund-raising abuses. Freeh and
LaBella were the only two out of the five supoenaed who were
expected to appear before the committee. And that could happen this
week.
</P>
<P>
   And despite his cooperation in the panel's impeachment
investigation, independent counsel Kenneth Starr also will receive
a subpoena. Investigators want documents from Starr that relate to
John Huang, the former fund-raiser for the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to expand the process came on the eve of the
Judiciary Committee's hearing into the consequences of lying under
oath. Today's witnesses will include Judge Gerald Tjoflat of the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. In 1994, Tjoflat
authored a strongly worded ruling upholding a perjury conviction in
a civil suit. Also appearing will be Pam Parsons of Atlanta, a
former University of South Carolina basketball coach convicted of
lying to hide an affair with a member of her team.
</P>
<P>
   In a search for new evidence of obstruction of justice by the
president, Republicans seek documents concerning several figures
from the campaign fund-raising scandal. The figures include
California businessman Johnny Chung, former Arkansas restaurateur
Charlie Trie and Mark Middleton, a former White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Dec. 31 deadline set by Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), the expansion of the impeachment inquiry
caught many on Capitol Hill off guard. Republican investigators say
they do not need an extension of their inquiry because they know
exactly what they want: a series of memos written by LaBella and
Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee has information that indicates that the memos
may contain evidence of criminal wrongdoing by the president,''
said Paul McNulty, senior spokesman for Republicans on the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans have tried to obtain the memos, but a
federal court told the Justice Department it had not shown
sufficient reason to hand over the full documents. They have
remained under seal because they contain grand jury information,
which must stay secret without a court order.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction at the White House was cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard these news reports about an expanded inquiry,
frankly, it seems very odd to us, but we will await the chairman's
explanation about what's going on before commenting further,'' said
Jim Kennedy, special counsel to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Today's hearing into crimes of perjury is an attempt to focus
the nation's attention on whether to remove Clinton from office for
allegedly lying under oath about his relationship with the former
White House intern and then obstructing justice and tampering with
witnesses to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important despite the political spinning from the White
House that perjury isn't important,'' said Georgia Republican Rep.
Bob Barr, a member of the Judiciary panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man needs to be impeached,'' Barr said. Congressional
failure to act would tell the American people that lying under oath
is a permissible act, and that is intolerable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats viewed the hearing with skepticism, deriding it as
a ``desperate public relations attempt'' to salvage the impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Committee Republicans long ago abandoned all pretenses of a
legitimate investigation and an honest inquiry into the standards
of impeachment,'' said Jim Jordan, the spokesman for the
committee's Democrats. ``Instead, they are lurching through a
series of increasingly trivial public relations stunts.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is preparing to begin debate on articles of
impeachment as early as next week. In an attempt to streamline that
process, the committee has canceled plans to question Robert
Bennett, the president's lawyer in the Paula Corbin Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican attempt to gain new information from Democratic
fund-raiser Nathan Landow failed Monday when he invoked his Fifth
Amendment right not to incriminate himself, declining to answer
questions about what he advised Kathleen Willey, a former White
House volunteer, to testify about her allegation that the president
made an unwanted sexual advance on her in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The tug of war between the committee Republicans and the White
House intensified Monday with Hyde frustrated by the lack of
cooperation from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a tersely written statement, Hyde had ``reviewed with
dismay'' the president's responses to 81 statements of fact
submitted to him by the committee on Nov. 5. ``Instead of shedding
new light on the key facts, the president chose to evade them,''
Hyde said. ``He did not challenge the truthfulness of the evidence.
Rather his responses revealed a selective ability to recall
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
