<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6089 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-01 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIS is how it is. This is how it starts.
</P>
<P>
   When you're trying to lift a basketball program from one era to
the next, you do things like this. You do kid things. You do
learning-curve things.
</P>
<P>
   One day, you look like a basketball fraternity along the lines
of the Sig Oops.
</P>
<P>
   There are turnovers, missed shots and bad plays in what turns
out to be an ICU kind of game against some P.U. team called IUPUI
(or, if you have the time, Indiana University-Purdue University at
Indianapolis).
</P>
<P>
   And you can only say OK. This Cougars team has a long, long way
to go.
</P>
<P>
   But two days later, you're playing a team with much more
formidable initials. You're playing LSU, which has a real history,
plays in a real conference and enters with a 3-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly you look like you're on the way back to the
glorious days of Phi Slama Jama.
</P>
<P>
   You win impressively, 67-55, and everyone walks out of the joint
humming the fight song, dreaming about the future and marveling
about the Iceman's cool kid named Gee Gervin, who's so good he
brings his own exclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Drexler knows all this.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that for every up, there are liable to be a couple of
downs. For every forgettable night like the loss to Sam Houston
State or the struggle with IUPUI, there will be nights like Monday,
when maybe everything didn't go right but enough did.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the best thing Drexler did between the IUPUI game
and Monday night was nothing.
</P>
<P>
   If Drexler is not careful, people are going to start calling him
``coach.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't rant over the sloppy effort against the P.U. team
Saturday night. He didn't snipe or bark about the mistakes. He
didn't even have practice Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to have those fresh legs,'' Drexler said. ``I didn't
want to practice just to practice. Basically, we're a young team.
Tonight, I thought we showed the mark of a good team. This was how
we like to play. This was Cougars basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a night that didn't just offer evidence that the
Cougars could be on their way to a bright future. It offered some
hints that Drexler might be more serious about this coaching gig
than most experts and fans around the country believed he would be.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the game, aside from the decision to rest his players
before facing the burly Tigers, Drexler handled an off-court
distraction involving freshman guard Moses Malone Jr.
</P>
<P>
   There was a complaint about playing time. Drexler talked with
Malone and Malone's parents about it but then stood his ground with
the talented guard, who Drexler believes needs work with his
defense and court control. Obviously, he does. Malone played just
11 minutes Monday, missing all three shots he took.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler also outcoached LSU's John Brady on Monday. Period.
Drexler mixed in some timely half-court traps and matchup zones and
had hustling inside men Chad Hendrick and William Stringfellow
rough up LSU big men Brian Beshara and Cedric Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked before the game that setting the tone defensively
would win,'' Drexler said, obviously sounding like a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if the second half was a case of adjustments at the
break, the fresh legs or simply pure luck? But the Coogs cut down
on turnovers while improving their shooting percentage, stretching
a rebounding edge and tripling their first-half steals.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the smartest move of all: giving the ball to the
cool kid. It was a coaching move only a former player could make:
``Son, be selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee Whiz was the biggest factor in this game's looking Slama
Jama-like, and never was he more of a factor than during UH's
decisive 15-3 run at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Gervin had 25 points on an array of twists and
turns. His pipe-cleaner arms swiped the ball from befuddled Tigers
at the most opportune times. His mostly expressionless face, like
his old man's, made Drexler look like a smart old coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to have a guard who's always cool under fire,''
Drexler said of Gervin. ``We expect great things from a lot of
guys. These are the guys you're going to hear about.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is how it all starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
