<HEADLINE>
KITNA SPARK PROVIDES A GLOW IN PREPARATION FOR JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ When Dennis Erickson decided to bench Warren
Moon last week, the Seahawks coach was hoping Jon Kitna could
provide a spark for the struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   What Erickson didn't know is how Kitna's presence at quarterback
would influence the other players.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's stunning, last-second victory over the Tennessee
Oilers, Kitna provided a spark that ignited even more than Erickson
could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, overall, that's as well as we've played all
year,'' Erickson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers support Erickson's assessment. The Seahawks produced
a season-high 296 passing yards, and the offense had its best
totals since the season-opening romp over the Philadelphia Eagles
in points scored (20), total yards (378) and third-down conversion
percentage (.420).
</P>
<P>
   The coaches altered the game plan a bit, using more
three-receiver, two-back alignments and going with quicker, shorter
passes. But it was more what the players did, than the formations
they did it from.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, the other players elevated their play around
Jon,'' offensive coordinator Bob Bratkowski said. ``People played
better than they've been playing and the unit played better than it
has been playing as a group. We didn't do a whole lot different. We
ran basically the same plays. We just executed them better than we
had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of those who elevated their performances were the
almost-forgotten James McKnight, who caught five passes for a
career-high 113 yards, and the often under-used Ricky Watters, who
caught seven passes for 63 yards and averaged 4.5 yards per carry
in rushing for another 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``That offense we got from James McKnight was what we were
getting from him last year and what we were expecting to get from
him all of this year,'' Bratkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna got production from the drop-prone McKnight by going to
him, even in clutch situations. Kitna also got Watters more
involved and let the emotional running back know he should expect
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon was looking for me,'' Watters said. ``He was telling me
before the game, `I'm going to look for you.' So I felt good about
it. It makes you want to get out there and get open because you
know he's going to get you the ball if you're open.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kitna-provided spark spreading to other players on
offense, Erickson said, ``Sometimes that's what a spark is. People
pick up their games because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   One good start deserves another, and Kitna will have to be even
better in this week's game against the 8-4 New York Jets at the
Meadowlands. The Jets' defense ranks fourth in the NFL, 18 spots
ahead of the Oilers, and has held four opponents to nine or fewer
points, including a 24-3 romp over the Oilers two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said Kitna will remain the starter for the remaining
four games, barring injury or a total collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing I'm concerned about is Jon improving this
week. He's going to have to play really well this week in New
York,'' Erickson said. ``The bottom line is consistency over a
period of time. It's not just one game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
