A6109 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN     12-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE FLEXES MUSCLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Cal State Northridge wanted to work on its
press and the dividends were so good it was pulled off by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors wanted strong half-court defense, and it worked so
well nary a Southern California College shot went in during the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, whatever the Matadors worked on worked. So well even
coach Bobby Braswell had to think of something to say after CSUN
routed Southern California College 92-50 Monday at home for its
second straight win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to think about this,'' Braswell said. ``This is a
difficult game for us from the beginning. Any time you're coaching
a game like this you're always concerned about the guys coming in
and not being focused. They were focused and did what they were
supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the game had merit in the Matadors' mind, and not just
because former UCLA standout Cameron Dollar coaches the Vanguards.
</P>
<P>
   It was scheduled at this juncture of the season in case CSUN
(3-2) needed a feel-good session before cruising the Pacific Ocean
to the University of Hawaii for a tournament which begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaii selected us to play in the first round, so it shows you
what they think of us,'' Braswell said. ``We told our guys in the
locker room they need to start thinking like champions. They need
to start thinking like they belong and not have a second-class
mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach you want to get your team to a certain level and
you want to get your guys thinking that they can win.''
</P>
<P>
   And against the Vanguards, clouded issues cleared a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Markus Carr (10 points, six assists, one turnover) continued to
put distance between him and Jason Crowe for the starting point
guard spot.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Minor continued his sharp shooting, making 6 of 10 from
3-point range for a game-high 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gave everybody a chance to work on things,'' said Minor,
who is 16 of 32 from 3-point range. ``When I was young all I would
do was shake-and-bake and drive to the basket so my dad told me to
shoot the ball from the outside. That's when I learned to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And much was also learned about CSUN's heralded forward Rico
Harris.
</P>
<P>
   He's a much better player when he gets involved in the offense
early. Albeit against inferior competition, Harris scored six
points early and finished with 17 points. He also grabbed 12
rebounds and didn't commit a turnover in posting the first
double-double by a Matador this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly do feel I'm better when I get into the flow early,''
Harris said. ``That's not for me to decide, though. It's for team
members to recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   But what this game did was set up the next two weekends for
CSUN, which carries much relevance in the college basketball
mid-major world. Since moving to Division I before the 1990-91
season, the Matadors haven't won an in-season tournament. During
the next 12 days they'll get that opportunity twice.
</P>
<P>
   After the Hawaii tournament, CSUN plays in Brigham Young's
tournament Dec. 11-12.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just more momentum going into Hawaii,'' Harris said.
``Now that we're on a winning streak we can go to Hawaii and prove
we can play hard and we could win the first tournament in (Division
I) school history.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
