<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TO ARIZONA? M'S NOT SURPRISED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The parting of company between the Mariners and Randy
Johnson is complete now. Johnson is the sweepstakes winner. He got
exactly what he wanted _ and wanted for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Johnson signed a deal with the Arizona Diamondbacks. He
is as rich as his pitching prowess will allow. Maybe Johnson, with
$52.4 million guaranteed, is richer than even he once imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, however, are still licking their wounds on this
public relations nightmare, though maybe it is time for the M's to
try to fix this, finally.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's contract with the Diamondbacks is a fairly humorous
development for a man who insisted he did not care about the money,
only about being wanted and a chance to contend for a World Series.
Now Johnson is one of the $13 million men.
</P>
<P>
   It was only about 18 months ago that $11 million was top dollar
for such an unusual commodity as Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't $11 million sound like it's about $2 million below
market for salaries now?'' Johnson's agent, Barry Meister, asked
from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It was Meister's way of saying the M's should not have balked at
paying Johnson ``Greg Maddux money'' back when the M's allegedly
still had a chance to sign Johnson. Call them parting words from
Meister.
</P>
<P>
   But the M's, too, had a parting shot for their former ace and
his people. Monday, Mariner president Chuck Armstrong decided to
take a few swipes at Johnson and his agents. The M's contend
Johnson's representatives had as much to do with Johnson no longer
being a Mariner as anything the Mariners did or did not do during
Johnson's tumultuous last 2{ seasons in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Johnson signed with the Diamondbacks. That's no surprise
to the Mariners,'' Armstrong said, deciding it was time to put a
spin on the Mariners' side of this contentious divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce was not only contentious, it became an industry
embarrassment. No one inside baseball (or outside among fans) could
understand how the most dominant left-handed pitcher in the game
could be allowed to stroll to Houston at the trading deadline for
three Astros minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners are convinced that the egg on their face is not
totally deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back to August of 1997, when this whole thing started to
go downhill, that is what we were told by Randy's agents: Randy
Johnson wants to play for Arizona,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   According the Armstrong, he and Lee Pelekoudas, vice president
of baseball administration, were ``summoned'' to Chicago in '97 to
meet with Johnson's agents, Meister and Alan Nero. It was during
this meeting that Armstrong was presented with what he calls ``The
Nero Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us not to exercise Randy's option (for $6 million
for the 1998 season), and if we did, then trade him to Arizona in
the offseason,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   What Nero then suggested, Armstrong said, is that the
Diamondbacks would make available a list of players the M's might
find suitable as compensation for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he told Nero, ``I'm not sure this is legal and
it's sure not ethical.'' The Mariners will not discuss whether they
looked for evidence that Arizona owner Jerry Colangelo tampered
with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   However, after that fateful August meeting in Chicago, it was
clear to Armstrong that there would be no good-faith negotiating
with Johnson's representatives for an extended contract to keep the
Big Unit a Mariner forever.
</P>
<P>
   The parting of ways began in earnest that day, although it took
Johnson a brief stint in Houston and Monday's new deal with Arizona
to complete it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it is the Mariners who must continue to search for a
way to restore a ton of lost credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson deal is only part of a string of under-explained
events that have people wondering just what the M's are up to, from
stadium politics to trading away too many players to no single
owner willing to become a club spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   But the Johnson boondoggle was significant. If the prolonged
trauma has not diminished the public's belief that the Mariners are
sincerely trying to field a contender, then why was the signing of
closer Jose Mesa last month treated with such overwhelming
skepticism?
</P>
<P>
   Is Mesa really much worse than Mike Timlin, who never came
through in a game that meant something to the Mariners but who
``flourished'' when the M's were out of contention in the second
half of '98?
</P>
<P>
   The aftershocks of Johnson's fall from grace have been
reverberating up until now. Now, though, the M's appear willing to
make public the details of a big deal gone sour. According to them,
Randy Johnson has now gotten everything (and more) that he and his
people once demanded of the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, but the Mariners still need an ace. They still need
to figure out how they can contend on a middle-class payroll
budget. They still need to sign Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez
to extensions sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   And, most importantly, they still need to demonstrate they can
wade through the muck and mire and still come out smelling like a
rose.
</P>
<P>
   Like Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
