<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-NINERS-NYT     12-01 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS DEFEAT GIANTS, 31-7 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For the New York Giants, it began with a bomb,
but it ended as just another dud.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense momentarily shed its staid, sober image on
Monday night against the San Francisco 49ers. Quarterback Kent
Graham approached Coach Jim Fassel before the game and said,
``Let's throw that baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel looked across the rain-soaked field at 3Com Park and
decided to throw caution to the wind _ and a pass into it. On the
Giants' first play from scrimmage, Graham connected with wide
receiver Ike Hilliard for a startling 48-yard pass play that led to
the first Giants touchdown in San Francisco in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   It left Giants players celebrating and dreaming big.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were not as impressed. With a cool efficiency, they
slowly rallied, scoring in every quarter and shutting out the
Giants for the remainder of the game in an entertaining 31-7
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' march to the playoffs continues, although they did
lose defensive tackle Bryant Young, who collided with his teammate
Ken Norton in the fourth quarter and sustained a gruesome injury _
a broken right leg.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Giants, remarkably, they could have been one game out
of the chase for the last wild-card spot in the National Football
Conference with a victory. And they are playing the team they are
pursuing, the Arizona Cardinals, next weekend. Their scant playoff
hopes dissolved further as their record fell to 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   The talent levels of these two teams was obvious, especially in
the fourth quarter. It was then that the San Francisco defense
thwarted every Giants drive and the 49ers offense wore down a
fatigued Giants defense.
</P>
<P>
   But even in victory, the mood at 3Com Park was somber as 49ers
players talked about the lineman Young and the effect of his
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a truly respected leader on this team,'' quarterback
Steve Young said. ``On defense, he is the man _ the guy they all
look up to. It's not an injury we'll overcome easily. But we'll
have to do our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the fourth quarter, the helmet of Norton struck
the defensive tackle's right leg at the end of a run by Graham.
Television replays showed defender's lower leg bending unnaturally
backward as Norton made his tackle attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see him because I was spinning around, but I heard
his leg crack,'' Graham said. ``I looked down and saw he was
hurting big time. It was like he had another joint in his shin. It
was a Joe Theismann-type injury. You could see how devastating it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham finished the game with 237 passing yards, completing 21
of 41 passes with one interception. After the game, Fassel said he
planned to start Graham against Arizona on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Kent made some really nice throws tonight,'' Fassel
said. ``He did enough things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was especially effective throwing to Hilliard, who had 6
catches for 141 yards.
</P>
<P>
   While the Giants were competitive for most of the game with the
49ers, the game was decided in the third quarter when the 49ers
slipped away from the Giants, scoring a pivotal touchdown after the
teams traded punts.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants got the worst of that exchange _ a poor Giants punt,
poor Giants coverage and a needless penalty giving the 49ers superb
field position for their scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the game by 14-7, the 49ers began their possession at
the Giants' 37-yard line. Less than three minutes later, Terry
Kirby scored on a 7-yard run, bulling over strongside linebacker
Marcus Buckley at the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 21-7, the Giants mounted a charge downfield with the
help of a 50-yard pass from Graham to Hilliard.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Giants were faced with a fourth-and-3 at the San
Francisco 25-yard line, Fassel decided to have his team attempt a
43-yard field goal even though it would still leave the Giants
behind by 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to play it safe looked that much worse when Brad
Daluiso, who strained his hamstring on the opening kickoff, missed
the attempt left of the goal posts.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' hopes of an upset disappeared with that miss.
</P>
<P>
   If that was a Giants' low point, then the Giants' first drive
was the team's high point of the game.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play, Graham faked a handoff to fullback Charles
Way, then immediately lofted the ball toward Hilliard, who had
gotten several steps behind San Francisco's Tim McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard made the catch, though he fell down before he could
advance the ball farther. It was a 48-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   In previous games, Hilliard's stumble might have come back to
haunt the Giants since their offense has routinely squandered
scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But in this first possession, the Giants could do no wrong. On
first down from the 49ers' 32-yard line, Gary Brown ran for 9 yards
around end.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, a huge hole opened for Way on a trap play to
the left side of the Giants' line. Way picked up 12 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And on the next play, Brown burst through a gaping hole in the
middle of the line and toppled into the 49ers' end zone. The last
Giants touchdown in a game played at 3Com Park, formerly known as
Candlestick Park, was a touchdown pass to Odessa Turner during a
34-24 San Francisco victory over the Giants in 1989. Monday night's
game is the fifth between the teams since that game.
</P>
<P>
   While the Giants were surprisingly spirited and efficient in
their first drive and most of their first-quarter play, for most of
the same quarter the 49ers seemed out of sync in all phases of
their game.
</P>
<P>
   But on a second-and-10 late in the first quarter, Young took one
step off the line of scrimmage and threw to his left, where Terrell
Owens was waiting. Hamilton, the Giants cornerback, threw himself
at Owens's feet. If Hamilton had made the tackle, it would have
been a 2-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   But Owens stepped over Hamilton's inexpert attempt, as he did
safety Sam Garnes's similar attempt a few yards farther downfield,
and then sprinted up the sideline for a 75-yard touchdown that tied
the score.
</P>
<P>
   On the 49ers' final possession of the half, Young orchestrated a
brilliant 13-play, 90-yard touchdown drive. The key play came on a
third-and-3 at the Giants' 10-yard line when Young ran for 9 of his
62 rushing yards in the game.
</P>
<P>
   A one-yard touchdown pass from Young to Irv Smith, who was
uncovered in the Giants' end zone, followed on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison Hearst, who had 166 yards on 20 carries, added a
70-yard touchdown run late in the game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
