<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR AND STAGE POWER 
VOICES REMEMBERED 
HOME TURF 
DEEP THOUGHTS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The London theater world loves Hollywood, especially
the revenues it promises. Monday, Nicole Kidman earned a special
prize from The Evening Standard Theater Awards for her role in the
Donmar Warehouse's ``Blue Room,'' now in previews on Broadway at
the Cort Theater for a Dec. 13 opening. Seeing a film star onstage
``focuses the attention of an audience who might otherwise never
give a thought to theater from one year to the next,'' the judges
said. The Academy Award-winning actor Kevin Spacey earned the
best-actor award for his acclaimed work in Eugene O'Neill's
``Iceman Cometh'' at the Almeida Theater. Other winners included
Sinead Cusack for best actress in ``Our Lady of Sligo,'' Michael
Frayn's ``Copenhagen'' for best play, and Trevor Nunn's revival of
``Oklahoma!'' for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the art world responded to the AIDS crisis in
general _ and specifically, the loss of its own _ by creating a Day
With(Out) Art. Tuesday the New York Public Library, the Museum of
Modern Art, the Brooklyn Museum of Art and the Cooper-Hewitt
National Design Museum are among the institutions paying tribute to
those whose voices were silenced. In honor of the 10th anniversary
of the event, Patience and Fortitude, the lions guarding the main
entrance of the library at 42d Street and Fifth Avenue, will don
the red ribbons that signify AIDS awareness. At 7:45 p.m., the
city's floodlit buildings and bridges will turn off their lights
for 15 minutes in memory of all those who have died from
AIDS-related illnesses. Information: (212) 627-9855.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems they're everywhere else, you're almost right. The
Emerson String Quartet makes its only New York appearance of the
season Wednesday at Carnegie Hall with the premiere of the String
Quartet No. 2 by Ellen Taaffe Zwilich. Proving it has mastered the
classics as well, the Emerson has programmed Sibelius' ``Intimate
Voices'' Quartet and Schubert's Quintet in C, assisted by the
cellist Carter Brey. Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   It's billed as a thinkers' convention, with participants
pondering the role of the director. That's the focus of the Joseph
Papp Public Theater/New York Shakespeare Festival's second annual
``Classic Colloquium,'' an all-day event designed ``to stimulate a
dialogue about classical theater on the eve of the new century.''
Among those harnessing their brainpower at the Colloquium, which
runs from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. on Saturday at the Public, 425 Lafayette
Street in the East Village, are the directors Barry Edelstein,
Michael Langham and Tony Kushner; the actresses Olympia Dukakis and
Regina Taylor, and George C. Wolfe, the festival's producer.
Information: (212) 260-2400.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
