<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NY     12-01 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' OFFENSE NEEDS A LEADER LIKE RICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco 49ers wide receiver Jerry Rice has
always been a player who wants to be the first option. As he grows
older, his skills no longer what they used to be, Rice watches
teammates like Terrell Owens, J.J. Stokes and Garrison Hearst get
the balls and the publicity. It infuriates him, and he speaks out
as he did last week, saying the team needs to throw the ball his
way more.
</P>
<P>
   He's Jerry Rice. He can do these things.
</P>
<P>
   While Rice was blasted as being selfish by people outside the
team, most of his teammates didn't blink. They know him. They know
he simply feels he can contribute and wants to do his share. And
that's what makes him a Hall of Famer _ Rice wants the ball, and he
will do whatever it takes to get it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants, who lost on Monday night to the 49ers,
31-7, could learn a few things from him.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Giants' offense _ of course, there are more
problems than there were raindrops soaking the 3Com Park turf on
Monday night _ is a lack of leadership. When you watch other
National Football League teams, there is always at least one player
on offense the team centers on. The good teams have more than one,
and the great teams have one at almost every position.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota has Cris Carter. Green Bay has Brett Favre. Atlanta
has Jamal Anderson. Pittsburgh has Jerome Bettis. And the players
don't have to be great. You could easily argue that the entire
offensive line of the Denver Broncos, most of whose members, if
they walked into a supermarket, would go unnoticed (except for the
$500 bags of groceries), is the leader of that entire 12-0 team.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their defense, which has leaders like lineman Michael
Strahan and linebacker Jessie Armstead, the Giants have no such
players on offense. Fullback Charles Way is the closest thing. But
he's such a classy guy, he would never say anything publicly
controversial, and sometimes that's what it takes. There is no one
on the Giants' offense who will stand at his locker and say Coach
Jim Fassel needs to open things up. Or if wide receiver Joe
Jurevicius burns defensive backs like toast in practice, publicly
ask why he isn't playing more in games.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, it was Strahan and Armstead who went into
an offensive meeting and berated the players. Why couldn't someone
on offense do that?
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Bettis went to his offensive coordinator and
told him he wanted more carries. When the meeting became public,
Bettis didn't try to play it down or lie and say it didn't happen.
After the meeting, his carries increased.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the Giants don't have players on offense who
have been to Pro Bowls or have three Super Bowl rings. But they do
have veterans with clout, like tight end Howard Cross and wide
receiver Chris Calloway.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a million miles between Carter and the
Vikings and the Giants. But it's not always about talent. Sometimes
it's attitude, and maybe all it will take is one player to state
the obvious: open up the offense, Jim. Just throw the darn ball.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of Rice's complaints is that he has been productive
this year. Coming into the Giants game, he had a team-high 61
catches, which would have led the Giants for the season in 61 of
their last 66 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's personnel, and it is philosophy. The Giants' offense
doesn't have the guns and is a few years away from truly competing
with the elite teams. But Fassel, a smart coach, needs to get back
to what got him hired. He has got away from being creative and
taking chances. On the Giants' opening series Monday night, he had
Kent Graham throw deep, and the strong-armed quarterback found wide
receiver Ike Hilliard, who is going to be a good player, for 48
yards. Three plays later, running back Gary Brown ran for an
11-yard score. That was good play-calling by Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Giants fell behind, 14-7, at the half, and the offense
went into a shell. The third quarter wasn't the time to get shy.
Graham has one of the league's strongest arms _ use it. What's to
lose? The Giants are out of the playoff race, and the 49ers have
one of the league's worst pass defenses.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, it seemed as if Graham got tired of the restraints
and decided to improvise. Late in the third quarter, Graham rolled
out and, spotting Hilliard, launched a deep ball. Hilliard was
covered, but he sidestepped Darnell Walker and scooped in a 50-yard
catch. If Graham didn't take the chance, the play would never have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pretty moment in an ugly season. And no, Rice was not
on the Giants' sideline, telling them to throw the ball to
Hilliard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
