<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-GARRITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN LEAGUE PURSUES SUNS' GARRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet another player with ties to the Suns may be looking overseas
for a place to play should the NBA's lockout continue.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Garrity, a 6-foot-9, 240-pound rookie forward whose rights
the Suns obtained in a trade on draft day with the Dallas
Mavericks, is being wooed by Kinder-Bologna, an Italian League
powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo acknowledged that the
Italian League team is pursuing Garrity, but he would not comment
further because of restrictions imposed during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity's Washington, D.C.-based agent, Lon Babby, said
Garrity's preference is to play for the Suns as soon as possible,
but Garrity hasn't ruled out going to Italy, especially if the NBA
season is scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's given it a lot of thought,'' Babby said. ``With each
passing day, it looks a little more attractive. But Pat's attitude
right now is that he has dreamed his whole life about playing in
the NBA. At this stage, he wants to be a Phoenix Sun and he wants
to be there and be ready when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his thinking now, but that could change if it looks
like the season may be canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity, who averaged 23.2 points and 8.3 rebounds a game at
Notre Dame last season, was drafted with the 19th choice of the
first round last summer by the Milwaukee Bucks. His rights were
traded along with the rights to German star Dirk Nowitzki to Dallas
for the rights to Michigan star Robert Traylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks then sent Garrity's rights, along with forward
Martin Muursepp, swingman Bubba Wells and a 1999 first-round draft
pick, to the Suns for Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   An NBA source familiar with European basketball said the
Kinder-Bologna club has had interest in Garrity since the Los
Angeles Summer Pro League, where Garrity was a standout performer.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity, who has been working out in the Valley with other
Phoenix players, apparently had little interest in the initial
attempts by Kinder-Bologna to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   But Kinder-Bologna reportedly is unhappy with forward Zarko
Paspalj, a former San Antonio Spurs player. The club renewed talks
in hopes of finding a replacement for Paspalj. Other players with
NBA ties whom Kinder-Bologna reportedly has interest in are free
agents Isaac Austin and Vlade Divac and the Suns' Muursepp.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Muursepp's name has cropped up in connection with
several clubs. Israel's Maccabi Tel-Aviv reportedly had agreed to
terms with Muursepp. That deal wasn't made, and now Muursepp
reportedly is considering a Greek League club, Apollon Patron.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix free agent Marko Milic is playing for a club in the
Turkish League. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 0207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
