<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-EX     12-01 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-JOHNSON-EXCLUSIVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON CALLS ATTITUDE KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, easily the largest building block in the
foundation of the Diamondbacks' brief history, is ready for The
Question.
</P>
<P>
   The game's most dominating pitcher, who agreed to pitch for the
Diamondbacks for the next four years in exchange for more than $52
million, will be waiting for the inevitable when he is introduced
to the local media Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going want to know how I could be 9-10 with Seattle
and 10-1 with Houston last year,'' Johnson told the ``Republic''
from his Paradise Valley, Ariz., home Monday night. ``I'll tell you
exactly how I did it. Because I was happy. It's a five-letter word.
I was much happier in Houston. I was happy with the environment I
was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying in Seattle. If anyone's ever seen me on the
mound, I pitch with a lot of emotion. When you've got an employer
screwing with your head, it's kind of tough. Look at Wade Boggs and
Roger Clemens during their final years in Boston and look at what
they did after they left. I'm human. I'm no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson began the 1998 season with the knowledge that Seattle
was not interested in having him back in 1999, even though in nine
seasons he had won 121 games, led the Mariners to the franchise's
only two playoff appearances, and captured a Cy Young Award
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's management publicly yanked Johnson on and off the
trading block a couple of times during the season. Johnson
eventually was sent to Houston in exchange for four prospects hours
before the July 31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pitch better in Houston,'' Johnson said.
``Velocity-wise there was nothing different. I was enjoying what I
was doing. This coming year I'm going to be extremely happy. It's
pretty special to be part of a community you actually live in as
well. I'm excited about that. This is where my home is, it's where
I want my family to be and where I feel I can make the biggest
impact of the teams that wanted me to pitch for them. Plus, why not
Arizona?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will anchor what now must be considered one of the top
rotations in the National League, if not all of baseball. He will
be followed in the rotation by Todd Stottlemyre, Andy Benes, Omar
Daal and Armando Reynoso.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the Atlanta Braves, no one has a rotation, front
and center, that can match Arizona's,'' Florida General Manager
Dave Dombrowski said. ``That's a championship rotation, no doubt
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 35, is aware of what will be expected from him.
Clearly, though, it's nothing he hasn't been prepared for in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I go people expect me to win,'' Johnson said.
``It's like the playoff games; I pitched quality games, good enough
to win. But we ran into another pitcher who shut down our offense.
There are times you might lose a game where you pitched well. I
don't look at anything as pressure. I look at coming here as a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pitched for teams that were picked to go to the World
Series and didn't. Our Houston team was supposed to go and we
didn't get out of the first round of the playoffs. The same thing
for our '97 Mariners team. It's discouraging. But there are no
guarantees in baseball. Just like there's no guarantee we're not
going to go the World Series or win the division this coming
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who turned down virtually identical offers from
Anaheim, Texas and Los Angeles, is cautious enough to realize the
Diamondbacks' chances of reaching the postseason in the coming year
remain remote. Nonetheless, he defended his decision to pitch for a
fledgling club over the more established ones he spurned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, the other teams might have better chance of
winning next year,'' Johnson said. ``But in the next four years I
think we will be competitive and go to playoffs. The City of
Phoenix will have an opportunity to watch this team grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, with all the new chemistry, it's going to take a
while for everyone to play together. By 2000, I assume we'll be
competing for a wild card at worst. At best, in 2001 and 2002 I
would say we'll be competing for an NL West title, if not sooner.
This year could be a magical and exciting year. It's not that bad
of a team. It had some holes that hopefully have been filled.'' &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
