<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6190 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUS-CRASH-FOLLOW-SPI &LR;      12-01 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-CRASH-FOLLOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE FIND PORNOGRAPHY, BULLETS AND BIZARRE NOTES INSIDE SUSPECT'S
APARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As they stepped inside Silas Garfield Cool's dreary
apartment, Seattle homicide detectives entered the macabre world of
a lonely man and his obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   In the dim light of a 40-watt bulb, detectives John Nordlund,
Gene Ramirez and Stephen O'Leary found a gallery of pornography,
concealed behind a blanket and an upright inflatable bed.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Metro bus schedules were stacked in an otherwise
empty bookcase near the front door. Notes written with a grease
pencil lay scattered about the kitchen, reminding Cool of the
simplest of tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't put plastic containers in oven,'' one read.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it appeared to be the home of a guy who just seemed to
drift further and further into isolation,'' O'Leary said. ``It was
as though a transient lived there, even though he had rented it for
13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, that isolated man, Silas Garfield Cool, 43, shot
and killed Metro bus driver Mark McLaughlin, causing the bus
McLaughlin was driving to careen off the Aurora Bridge.
Thirty-three passenger were injured, one of whom died the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, police confirmed Monday, took his own life with a single
shot from a cheap pocket pistol, ending the downward spiral of his
life and beginning an investigation that has yet to determine why
he killed.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight days before he erupted Cool was arrested by Mountlake
Terrace police for trying to peek at a young girl who was showering
at a public swimming pool. Cool tried to fool police by giving them
phony names, even assuming the identity of his apartment manager.
</P>
<P>
   As they sifted through the University District apartment last
weekend, where Cool's privacy and loneliness overlapped, the three
detectives found only scattered bits of puzzle _ scores of
videotapes, some in the process of being copied. Most were
commercial pornography, except for a few, including one that gave
them a start _ an old fright-film dubbed with gruesome irony:
``Horror Express.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin was driving Metro route 359 _ an express route. The
film, though, deals with space aliens who kill all the passengers
on a train and steal their memories.
</P>
<P>
   In the living room of the tiny apartment, the detectives found a
rocker or easy chair that looked as though it had never been used.
There were no signs of photos, mementos or keepsakes.
</P>
<P>
   Living room shelves yielded two holsters and ammunition matching
the guns Cool used Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the bathroom, every available shelf and all the counter space
was covered with lotions and shaving creams, some evidently having
sat there for years, rusted to the counters, their unopened caps
still on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing positive in there,'' O'Leary said Monday.
``Except for a dark side, the place just seemed to be devoid of any
personality. It was like a neutered presence, until you got to the
bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   There, the detectives found the darkness enforced by curtains
pinned shut. Behind a plastic blow-up double mattress leaning
against one wall, the officers found a collage of photos of nude
women.
</P>
<P>
   A blanket on a wire strung across the room concealed another
wall of pornographic photos, most trimmed from adult magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The only other decoration, O'Leary said, was an 8-by-10-inch
photo of Cool himself, apparently taken when he was younger and
living outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much disarray, so much disorganization,'' O'Leary
said. ``Nothing was focused in that place. There was nothing to
suggest a routine or a schedule in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, investigators matched Cool's left-index fingerprint to
one found on the magazine of a .380-caliber semiautomatic handgun.
Two bullets removed from McLaughlin's body were matched last night
to the gun. Cool apparently bought the guns legally, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators came up with more questions than answers when
they explored Cool's background and questioned family members who
were equally puzzled and distraught. They found no medication in
his apartment, except for vitamins and health supplements, and no
indication he had ever sought counseling or seen a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Cool was an only child, born May 14, 1955, in Sumatra to an
American oil company accountant, Daniel Cool, and his wife, Ena.
Both now in their 80s, they declined interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in Indonesia and Pakistan before settling in
middle-class Plainfield, N.J., in 1959. Cool went through the
school system, where he was known as a somewhat studious, good kid.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Birnbaum, the superintendent of North Plainfield Public
Schools, said Monday that she taught English and possibly other
subjects to Cool when she was a teacher at the high school in the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very nice, very quiet, very sweet, good student, and
I am very saddened by all of this because I can't imagine that
happening to him, to have something like this happen,'' Birnbaum
said.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum described North Plainfield as a safe, middle-class
suburban community, 25 miles west of New York City, that is a good
place to raise children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it kind of a modern-day Mayberry,'' Birnbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Van Winkle, detective lieutenant of the North
Plainfield Police Department, said Cool never had any run-ins with
the law and was considered a smart kid. ``He was squeaky clean. He
was one of those average guys who fit into the community,'' Van
Winkle said.
</P>
<P>
   Cool's high school class held its 25th reunion at a New Jersey
Elk's Club on Friday _ the day of the bridge incident.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known if Cool knew of the reunion, and some of the
organizers said they weren't able to contact him. But for many
people, such gatherings serve as a marker of time and stir emotions
about the past.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, Cool became an avid golfer, which he played
voraciously and which his father said contributed to his back
problem. In 1978, Cool earned a two-year degree in civil technology
in 1978 from nearby Middlesex County College in Edison, N.J., which
is about 20 miles from North Plainfield.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, he spent time in Durban, South Africa, although little
is known about his time there. In 1979, Cool drove cross-country to
Seattle in a vintage Ford Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   He settled into clerical jobs, already hindered by chronic back
pain, his family told police. One was as a draftsman for a Seattle
oil company. Co-workers told KOMO-TV he quit in 1983 after the
company denied his request for a leave to return to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1984 to July 1987 Cool worked in the King County
land-use department as a building inspector. It was one of his last
jobs. His father has told police his son hasn't been employed since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   A former co-worker, who asked that his name not be used, said he
and other colleagues believe Cool may have been asked to resign
from the county job, although he wasn't sure why.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 he moved into the apartment at 5625 15th Ave. N.E.,
where he lived until his death. His neighbors and landlord said
they never knew him as anything but a name on a mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Cool has several minor misdemeanor arrests in Seattle in the
late 1980s and early 1990s, when he used the alias of Steve Gary
Cool and gave a birth date two years later than his actual date of
birth.
</P>
<P>
   In Mountlake Terrace, Cool was arrested for obstructing a police
officer after visiting a public pool.
</P>
<P>
   The father of a 13-year-old girl called police Nov. 16 after he
saw Cool in the swimming pool area of the Recreation Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The father told police that on Nov. 9 he was standing guard
while his daughter was showering in a stall at the pavilion. He
said Cool approached the stall and started to look over his
shoulder toward his daughter. He told Cool to ``back off'' and Cool
complied. When the father returned to the pavilion on Nov. 16, he
saw Cool in the pool and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Cool's family told police that he swam at the pool to relieve
his chronic back pain. When he was stopped by police, he denied he
was involved in any devious behavior.
</P>
<P>
   After police ran the names, Cool clammed up and said, ``I want
to speak with my attorney,'' according to police reports.
</P>
<P>
   He was booked into the Lynnwood Jail as a John Doe for
obstructing police.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief court appearance Nov. 17, Cool, in a calm voice
corrected the spelling of his name, saying it didn't have an ``e''
and gave his first name as Silas.
</P>
<P>
   The judge set Cool's bail at $1,000 cash.
</P>
<P>
   Cool posted bail after contacting A Quick Bail Bond in Everett
and was released, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed against Cool, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Cool's booking photographs in the Mountlake Terrace case have
become a key piece of evidence. Detectives are using it in the
flier distributed to Metro bus drivers Sunday, asking if they might
have had some trouble with him that could have made him want to
hurt a Metro driver.
</P>
<P>
   Cool's family last saw him during one of his annual visits to
New Jersey, this one from Oct. 15 to 27. They noticed nothing
unusual about him, and he engaged in his usual habit of walking
each day, or lying down to control his back pain.
</P>
<P>
   Cool's last conversation with his parents, with whom he seemed
to have a good rapport, was on Nov. 22, and he left them with no
indication that he harbored anger or resentment, O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   Cool had been unemployed since about 1991 because of his back
pain, his family told police. Since then, his parents supported
him, sending him $650 a month. After his $475 rent, he was left
with $125 to live on and frequented the Union Gospel Mission for
food, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But the apartment where Cool lived his last 13 years, surrounded
by his most personal things, yields only more questions.
</P>
<P>
   He left the bathroom windows covered with aluminum foil. The tub
didn't appear to have been used much, which didn't match the
picture of Cool's clean-cut appearance. In it was a cardboard box
with dish towels to stack more hair care and body products that
were never used.
</P>
<P>
   The tub and shower area seemed to O'Leary to have been set up
like a little desk. And he owned lots of thongs of underwear and
some men's body building magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The only other non-pornographic reading materials were a few
National Geographics. Cool also appeared to have embarked upon a
project to convert old Beta movie tapes to VHS tapes.
</P>
<P>
   And the kitchen, with its notes and empty small liquor bottles,
held not even a spice. The refrigerator contained only some frozen
food, as though eating was a necessity to be completed in the
quickest and easiest fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just seemed to exist as though he never existed,'' O'Leary
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
