<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-SUPPORT02-COX     12-01 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-SUPPORT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas family court defends its role
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In his 10 years on the bench, Judge Jim Rausch has
seen it all before _ practically every day.
</P>
<P>
   Before him a mother stands, holding in her left arm a
curly-haired baby clutching a bottle. Standing adjacent to an
assistant attorney general is the father of another of her
children, a red and blue, star-shaped tattoo on his right forearm
and another tattoo circling his left arm just below the short
sleeve of his bright orange jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The back of his jumpsuit reads ``Bexar County Jail.''
</P>
<P>
   He owes $10,200 in child support, has not paid on it in almost
two years and explains he's been unemployed for a year. ``If I'm
working, I pay,'' he tells Rausch. ``If I'm not working, I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rausch looks him straight in the eye, his voice agitated. ``You
should have thought about that before you brought this child into
the world,'' he says. ``It's a tough world, isn't it, sir?''
</P>
<P>
   His judgment: six months behind bars for contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If $500 is paid,'' Rausch tells him, ``the court will release
you to electronic monitoring.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the prisoner gets back to jail, the $500 is paid.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, the money used to bail out these fathers comes from
the parent who is owed the child support.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it works, time and again. In two days last week,
four of 10 fathers Rausch either threw or kept in jail for
child-support violations came up with the lump sum the judge set
for their release. One _ a ``career case,'' Rausch called him _
said he couldn't muster more than $1,000 when the judge set $2,500
as the hurdle for his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the afternoon, his family paid the $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   In an often teeming courtroom, Jim Rausch speaks not so softly
and wields a big stick to collect child support _ one of Texas'
most beguiling social and political problems, with 1.1 million
active cases pending in the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Legislature searches for answers, Rausch and other
family law court masters who enforce state-supervised child-support
orders _ one of the few aspects of child support that seems to be
working _ stand to be replaced by an administrative process that is
among several proposals to resolve an almost unsolvable problem.
</P>
<P>
   A backlog of cases
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales consistently has defended his
child-support collection, pointing to a 300 percent increase since
1990 and to Texas moving from 14th to sixth in total collections.
But, just as consistently, mothers owed child support and the
lawmakers to whom they invariably complain have slammed the efforts
as ineffective, too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Dragged down by a $75 million computer that has not done what it
was supposed to do, the portion of paying cases lately has dropped
from 20 percent to 18 percent. And at the same time that caseloads
kept rising, the number in which paternity was established fell 13
percent by the end of the 1998 budget year.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the complexity of a growing social phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General-elect John Cornyn, for example, made child
support a campaign issue by saying Morales, who decided not to seek
re-election, collected only 18 cents of each dollar owed in child
support. But Cornyn's figures can be misleading because he refers
to an 18 percent collection rate for all child-support cases _ even
those in which paternity has not been established and payment
orders have not been drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Rausch and others worry that confusion results in a proposal to
cut people like Rausch out of the process _ and to reduce due
process _ to solve problems that Rausch says he rarely deals with
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very efficient _ not perfect _ but very efficient
judicial process,'' Rausch says of what he does, ``that resolved a
great number of cases in a short period of time yet did not deny
anyone their day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1998 budget-year tally by the Office of Court
Administration, court masters such as Rausch handled almost 175,000
legal actions filed by assistant attorneys general. Of those, the
judges disposed of 90 percent within three months.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly contempt citations
</P>
<P>
   On this Monday in Rausch's courtroom, enforcement actions
dominate the docket.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you just saw in the last two hours was 95 percent
contempt. I think I heard one paternity case,'' he says during a
morning recess. ``Paternity establishment is a small part of the
picture here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth floor of the century-old, Romanesque, red
sandstone and granite Bexar County Courthouse _ overseeing Main
Plaza, where justice has been dispensed in San Antonio for close to
300 years _ mothers and fathers called to Rausch's courtroom take
all available seats this Monday morning. More people crowd the
entry into the courtroom and spill outside the door into the
marbled hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys work in constant motion at its center. Deputy sheriffs
call for order again and again and again as people mumble and
whisper in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   His docket runs 93 cases when Rausch, who is responsible for
child support and other complex issues that go hand in hand with
it, begins calling cases at 8:30 a.m. He starts this ritual at the
same time four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Rausch breaks for lunch this day, at 12:53 p.m., he
will have finished all but three cases on his docket. Another hour
in the afternoon and he will be done.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, he will have conducted one hearing on past-due
child support for a father of a 13-year-old who was not told until
years later that the child was his. He will have held a formal
rights hearing at the same time for four fathers accused of
contempt _ and facing jail _ because they have not paid child
support. And he will have ruled in perhaps 30 other individual
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the efficiency, Rausch and the other 40 child-support
court masters in Texas _ judges who, as he does, can throw the book
at parents delinquent in their child-support payments _ work in the
gun sight of a proposal Morales endorses that might eliminate them.
In their place would be administrative hearing officers with power
to decide paternity and set child support but without authority to
enforce child-support orders.
</P>
<P>
   That administrative process, Morales says, would speed
child-support orders by hastening decisions establishing paternity
in cases where children have been born out of wedlock. These days,
that means as many as 30 of every 100 births in the state. Morales'
successor, Cornyn, advocates streamlined child-support
administrative proceedings not unlike those for revoking a driver's
license.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' proposal would put the burden of proof on men alleged
to be fathers, leaving it up to the men to contest an allegation in
a procedure that has no judicial protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, am sick and tired of taking away people's legal
rights to make up for the faults in this system,'' state Sen. Chris
Harris, R-Arlington, told a Sunset Advisory Commission hearing
recently.
</P>
<P>
   But the so-called expedited administrative procedure _ the
cornerstone of a legislative consultant's recommendation for the
attorney general's child-support division _ would do little, by
Rausch's reckoning, to dent the never-ending cycle of enforcement
problems he handles day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone in that assessment. A sunset commission staff
analysis of the consultant's report raised doubt about channeling
to a hearing officer decisions that needed a court's ruling _ and
throwing enforcement of a hearing officer's orders onto the crowded
caseloads that district judges now handle.
</P>
<P>
   Sizing up the parents
</P>
<P>
   At 49, his graying hair cut close in the style he wore as an F-4
Phantom fighter pilot in Vietnam, Rausch brings tactical zeal to
his work now. His instincts play off his experience in sizing up a
delinquent parent probably months or years past due in his child
support.
</P>
<P>
   For one father, who pleads that he has a new job and a son who
lives with him, Rausch threatens him with jail unless he can cough
up $800.
</P>
<P>
   Then, against the assistant attorney general's preference, the
judge orders the father to work release. A deputy cuffs him and
leads him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put them in jail and throw away the key,'' Rausch
says. ``What you want to do is get their attention and get a lump
sum.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his reasoning depends on 10 years of handling familiar
faces back again to be threatened or cajoled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't work that way _ `Thanks, judge, it'll be OK' _ it
doesn't work that way,'' Rausch says. ``It doesn't go away.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no closure. There's no closure to a child-support
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 0940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREARMS-REVENGE02-CO     12-01 1659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREARMS-REVENGE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gun industry assault seen by some as payback for crime in
streets
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After watching states wring billions from Big Tobacco,
U.S. cities are embarking on what lawyers describe as Tobacco II:
an all-out legal assault on the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch is simple: Guns wreak such mayhem in our cities _
about 35,000 Americans die from gunfire each year _ that
manufacturers should pay.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, both New Orleans and Chicago filed suit
against the gun industry seeking hundreds of millions of dollars in
damages. Lawyer Wendell Gauthier and other prominent plaintiffs
attorneys who led a class-action lawsuit against Big Tobacco are
bankrolling the New Orleans complaint, which closely imitates
lawsuits filed by states that sought compensation for public
expenses related to smokers' illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Mayor Marc Morial said his city's taxpayers have
suffered too long from unsafe guns and the industry's ``day of
atonement'' has arrived. Chicago Mayor Richard Daley said the gun
industry knowingly floods his city with deadly weapons, making it a
willing partner of ``gangbangers, drug dealers and other
criminals.'' Chicago used an undercover police investigation to
support its case.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell supports the lawsuits by New Orleans
and Chicago, according to a spokesman, and the city is seriously
considering its own challenge. City officials in Baltimore, Boston,
Los Angeles, Miami, Philadelphia and San Francisco also are
considering lawsuits against the gun industry. In New York, a case
scheduled to go to trial in January seeks to hold the whole
industry liable for the negligent distribution and overproduction
of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Although gun executives contend the lawsuits are without merit,
they say the daunting task of defending such an onslaught of
litigation could cripple an industry that has much less financial
firepower than the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very real chance that a lot of the handgun
manufacturers will have to declare bankruptcy and shut their
doors,'' said Jack Adkins, operations director of the Atlanta-based
American Shooting Sports Council, an industry trade group.
``There's a feeding frenzy going on out there and the gun industry
is red meat.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun industry executives say they are making and selling a lawful
product in compliance with federal, state and local laws and
regulations governing firearm distribution. They contend they
should not be blamed for abuse of their product any more than
manufacturers of cars, kitchen knives or axes are blamed when these
items are used to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard Law School professor Laurence Tribe, who helped
prepare some of the tobacco cases, believes the gun industry is
vulnerable. He notes that the new lawsuits sidestep arguments that
the Second Amendment's right to bear arms protects gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not be able to draw a straight line from the maker of
the gun barrel to the aorta of the victim,'' Tribe said. ``But in
the way the tobacco litigation paved the way it may be possible, if
the evidence is there, to hold gun manufacturers accountable for
the aggregate death and injury that can be directly traced to their
marketing of a deadly product.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits against the gun industry are nothing new. For decades,
individuals have sued gun manufacturers charging negligence for
faulty weapon-making, such as an injury or death caused by a hair
trigger. And lawsuits have been filed against dealers who sold
handguns without telling people how to use them or to people who
shouldn't be able to buy one _ felons, drunks, minors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a 14-year-old girl shot in the head by a neighbor who
didn't know the gun was loaded won an $11 million jury verdict
against a Philadelphia gun store. According to testimony, the
shopkeeper failed to in- struct the girl's mother on how to use the
.25-caliber semiautomatic handgun when she bought it. Raven Arms,
manufacturer of the gun,had settled for almost $1 million prior to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Kitchen, a Florida woman left a quadriplegic after a
gunshot wound, won a $12.5 million verdict against K-Mart Corp. in
1993. Kitchen was shot by her ex-boyfriend, who bought a
.22-caliber bolt-action rifle at K-Mart. The store sold him the gun
even though he had drunk a fifth of whiskey and a case of beer.
</P>
<P>
   But more recently, litigation against the gun industry as a
whole has grown more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   A federal lawsuit scheduled to go to trial in New York Jan. 4
names 46 gun manufacturers as defendants. The suit was filed by
families of two people shot and killed with illegally obtained
firearms. Their lawyers will argue thathandguns and their
ammunition are pathogens causing the injuries and deaths of
thousands of people, much like asbestos, Agent Orange or silicone
breast implants. They want a jury to find the industry liable for
marketing and selling handguns in a way that fosters the growth of
an underground market. This illicit gun market, the lawsuit claims,
enables youths and criminals to buy handguns easily and contributes
greatly to handgun violence in U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
   During pre-trial discovery in the New York case, lawyers
uncovered an industry whistleblower who has provided testimony
critical of gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hass, a former Smith &AMP; Wesson senior vice president of
marketing and sales, said the industry has been lax in trying to to
identify and investigate the retailers and wholesalers that sold
guns used to commit crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company and the industry are .. aware that the black
market in firearms is not simply the result of stolen guns but is
due to the seepage of guns into the illict market from multiple
thousands of unsupervised federal firearms licensees.'' Hass said
in an affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Hass also said gun manufacturers simply don't screen or
supervise sales beyond checking federal firearms licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of cases like this one, there's a growing body of
evidence,'' said Joshua Horowitz, director of the Washington-based
Firearms Litigation Clearinghouse. ``We believe at some point, a
jury will one day find that the gun industry is intentionally
marketing to criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry lawyers point to a recent jury verdict in Oakland
which shows gun manufacturers can win in court.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a jury found in favor of Beretta U.S.A. Corp., sued
by Griffin and Lynn Dix who claimed their 15-year-old son, Kenzo,
accidentally was shot and killed by a teenage friend because the
handgun was defectively designed.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claimed the death could have been avoided if Beretta
had installed an internal lock on the handgun. Gun-control
advocates said the product-liability case was the first of its kind
against a gun manufacturer. The jury voted 9-3 and 10-2 in favor of
Beretta on whether the handgun was defective and whether a defect
factored substantially in Kenzo's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping it gives some of these municipalities a good dose
of reality,'' Rudolph Pino, Beretta's national legal counsel, said
of the verdict. ``If they're thinking this is like tobacco
litigation where they're going to be getting hundreds of millions
of dollars, they'd better think again.''
</P>
<P>
   However, New Orleans plans to pursue its lawsuit, the first
filed by a city against the gun industry, even though it uses a
legal theory similar to the one that failed in Oakland. The city's
lawsuit claims that firearms are ``unreasonably dangerous'' because
manufacturers knowingly fail to include safety devices to prevent
children and other unauthorized users from firing guns.
</P>
<P>
   The city filed suit after the mayor's friend, Raymond Miles, a
well-known New Orleans gospel singer, was found dead on a street
corner Oct. 11 with two bullets in his back. The Chicago lawsuit
seeks $433 million in damages from 40 gun manufacturers and
dealers. The lawsuit charges the industry's marketing and sales
practices make it liable for the cost of gun violence under
``public nuisance'' laws.
</P>
<P>
   The industry saturates the market with handguns that could only
be used to commit crimes, according to the lawsuit. In Chicago,
which has one of the nation's strictest gun-control laws, it's
illegal to own a gun unless it was registered before 1982. (Atlanta
has no such ordinance.)
</P>
<P>
   Chicago used an undercover police operation to support its case.
Police officers, posing as street gang members, motorcycle thugs or
camouflage-clad soldiers of fortune, bought guns from suburban
dealers even though they had no gun permit and boasted they would
use the guns to commit crimes inside the city, according to the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins, whose Atlanta trade group has about 350 dealers and
manufacturers as members, accsuses the mayors of ``tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is litigation tyranny, with mayors thwarting the
democratic legislative process by going to the courts to establish
public policy,'' he said. ``By modeling their strategy on the
tobacco cases, handgun control groups are filing lawsuits like
throwing pasta up against the wall. They don't care if it's al
dente or well done or even if it sticks to the wall. Their idea is
to file as many suits as possible, knowing the industry cannot
defend itself against this onslaught.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Henigan, a lawyer for the Washington-based Center to
Prevent Handgun Violence and co-counsel in the New Orleans lawsuit,
concedes that the latest round of lawsuits against the gun industry
may not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact that more of these cases are getting before
juries now is extremely important because it creates huge
uncertainty for the industry and could in the end bring it to the
bargaining table,'' he said. ``They never know what the next jury
will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
