<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6380 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-AMISH02-COX     12-01 1922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-AMISH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amish carve own space in Sarasota nook
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ After a pitched game at the Pinecraft Park
shuffleboard courts, Omer Yoder is chatting with his friends Henry
Detweiler, Gideon Stoltzfus and Aubrey Hudson when it dawns on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only Yoder here tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The group around him _ the bearded men in black straw hats and
suspenders and women in bonnets and homemade dresses _ nod and
laugh. In fact, there is another Yoder. Lewis. But the joke is not
lost. To the outside, they know their world appears insular; its
strict tenets forbidding cars and TVs, portable phones and divorce
a little queer. Lest the funny hats obscure what this is really all
about, Stoltzfus reminds everyone:
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we want to be known by what we believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Florida Amish Country, the unlikely winter home of
the Schlabachs and Knepps and a small population of mostly retired
Amish and Mennonites.
</P>
<P>
   Belief is not what brought them to this pocket of Sarasota,
where streets have names such as Graber, Kruppa and yes, Yoder, but
it is what keeps them together.
</P>
<P>
   Over seven decades, they have forged a community 2 miles east of
Sarasota Bay where restaurants specialize in shoofly pie and
cheese, straw hats sell for $3.99 at the corner hardware store and
about a dozen churches offer varying degrees of doctrine. They
travel south by Pioneer Trails bus _ $99 round-trip from Ohio,
Pennsylvania or Indiana _ and get around town on over-sized
tricycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look at us as a cult because of the dress.
They have the idea that we're very exclusive,'' said Matthias
Overholt, whose family moved to the area 43 years ago and now runs
a produce stand. ``But anyone's welcome. Our church doors are open.
Our homes are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they struggle to maintain a separation, if only for the
sake of self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   No longer isolated
</P>
<P>
   Before the movie ``Witness,'' Amish communities existed to the
outside world largely as tourist attractions, like Colonial
Williamsburg. Then earlier this year, two Pennsylvania Amish men
were arrested and charged with buying cocaine from a local chapter
of the Pagan motorcycle gang. Police alleged they sold it to young
Amish indulging in their rumschpringes, a rite of passage starting
at about age 17 when young members get to taste the world and
decide whether they want to join the church. Suddenly, reporters
from places like the Washington Post and New Yorker were dissecting
the group.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, life for young members can be even more challenging
``because of the closer proximity to town, the beaches and the
leisure lifestyle,'' Overholt said. ``In a rural setting, it's
different. But here, they don't want to ride bikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, here they are, in a place of beaches and strip malls,
where life can be sometimes slow and sometimes sleazy, living in
white cottages and little urban ranch houses with miniature wishing
wells and windmills planted in their front yards.
</P>
<P>
   First arrivals started farms
</P>
<P>
   When the first members arrived from Ohio about 1925 to farm the
Florida muck for celery, they settled away from town, said Roman
``Bob'' Miller, whose grandfather and great uncle started the first
farms. Their isolation was as much as part of their convictions _
they believe true Christians should be ``nonconforming'' _ as a
longstanding tradition of persecution.
</P>
<P>
   The Mennonites and Amish, according to one of the many books
sold at the Der Dutchman or Dutch Haus restaurants in the
neighborhood, evolved from the Protestant Reformation of the 16th
century. A group in Switzerland, eventually called Anabaptists,
formed to create a purer church, one in which baptism was voluntary
and the church existed independent of the government.
</P>
<P>
   They were promptly slaughtered by both Reformers and the Church
of Rome. They survived only by meeting in secret, in caves and at
night.
</P>
<P>
   In 1693, a Swiss elder named Jacob Amman formed a stricter sect
_ the Amish _ because he believed the church was losing its purity.
</P>
<P>
   Amman believed if a member left the church or lied, he should be
shunned. He also introduced the dress code.
</P>
<P>
   Persecution in Europe continued, so members began migrating to
North America about 1720, settling in northern states such as Ohio,
Pennsylvania and Indiana. Over time, rifts between the old order
and modern members developed. Today a range of doctrine is
practiced, explains the Rev. Barry Loop of the Bahia Vista
Mennonite Church. The largest community is in Holmes County, Ohio,
followed by Lancaster County, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there's Amish, there's Mennonite. We have a shared
historical perspective,'' said Loop, whose church celebrates its
50th anniversary next year.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, different sects decide where they want to draw
the lines between themselves and society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people build fences high because they want to put a hedge
around their family to keep the world from coming in. Some people
build them low,'' Overholt said. ``Those of us conservatives kind
of keep our fences high.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the family drives a car, but doesn't watch TV. They
have a telephone and are weighing whether to surf the Internet, but
don't educate their children beyond the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is guard our families,'' he said.
``The closer a person walks with society, they lose their
distinctiveness and start embracing society. They start
integrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the 1950s, the families in Sarasota continued to farm
the area, traveling south when winter froze fields up North, Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Population boom
</P>
<P>
   World War II brought a brief boom in the local population
because young men came to perform their voluntary service, a deal
with the government that excuses Amish and Mennonites from military
service and instead allows them to work at other jobs, like picking
oranges. (Their belief in peace also led to unpopular stands on
other matters: they were among the first to oppose slavery and they
object to nuclear weapons. They rarely file lawsuits.)
</P>
<P>
   Church services were usually held in homes. Up North, benches
were loaded into buggies and hauled from house to house.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1934, Miller's grandfather helped establish one of the
first churches in a two-room schoolhouse in Fruitville. By 1945,
the congregation had outgrown the building. So, after uniting with
other denominations, they bought the Sarasota Baking Company
building for $7,500. Today, it is the Tourist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's family sold their farm in 1955, with others quickly
following as property values rose and Sarasota became more
developed, he said. They continued the yearly trek and some, like
the Overholts and the Millers' children, moved down permanently.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, Pinecraft became a colony of retirees.
Younger family members vacation here, usually after the Christmas
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite as easy to find work anymore. You have to have
your own business, pretty near,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Sue Miller, who is not related to Bob Miller, is one of the
exceptions. Waiting for the 8:20 a.m. Sarasota County Area Transit
bus to take her to a housecleaning job on Longboat Key, she says
she moved from Ohio a year and a half ago with her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fond of the summers, but I like it. It beats snow and
ice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The balancing act
</P>
<P>
   Balancing their beliefs with fast-paced Florida is not always
easy. Without horses and buggies, they rely on the SCAT buses to
travel across town or to the beach on Lido Key. More modern members
drive. Old order members ride their bikes, sometimes their lawn
mowers, Overholt said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 21, Overholt succumbed to the lure of the outside
world and left home. He moved in with an uncle and started dating a
girl ``involved in the occult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the whole disco scene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he returned to the fold and today helps promote
the family's publishing business which includes a hymnal compiled
by his father and tapes of his three sisters, brother and
brother-in-law singing its selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some incongruities here,'' he has decided.
</P>
<P>
   Cottage industry serves Amish
</P>
<P>
   He's also observed over the years that carpet-baggers are
cashing in on the Amish reputation for honesty. One restaurant,
Yoders, was started by some Indiana Amish. Eventually they fell
victim to society yet continued promoting their restaurant as
Amish, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing against Yoders, but I don't like to capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   A cottage industry to provide services has also sprung up. At a
house off Kaufman Avenue, rental bikes are parked in the front
yard. The Pioneer Trails bus line to Sarasota caters to Amish
almost exclusively, making a stop every Thursday at the
neighborhood post office and heading north to Amish Country on
Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, Pennsylvania Amish, who tend to be
wealthier, have started coming to the area, sometimes to the
chagrin of original settlers, Bob Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just buy up everything. They have big farms up there and
have a lot of money. Some houses are not too good, but the land
brings a good price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement isn't necessarily leisurely here.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Miller _ no relation to Bob or Emma Sue _ has been coming
south since 1979. He no longer farms his Ohio property full-time
but works part-time in construction while his wife cleans houses.
Self-employed Amish do not pay social security, so in old age they
rely on families and what work they can get for income.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has built models in an Orlando housing development. In
Sarasota, he stacks wood when he can.
</P>
<P>
   He left farming partly because it became so unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up North, the church used to be 95 percent farmers. You go now
and there aren't 3 percent,'' he said. ``They go to work in the
trailer factory so they can have their hobby (the farm).''
</P>
<P>
   Older women keep working
</P>
<P>
   Women do likewise. Abigail Overholt, Matthias's sister, runs the
produce stand at the busy intersection of Bahia Vista Street and
Kaufman Avenue. Emma Miller _ no relation to Bob, Emma Sue or
Nelson _ makes quilts.
</P>
<P>
   Over three days 20 to 25 women will gather in Ada Detweiler's
carport _ because it is the only space large enough _ to quilt the
fabric pieced together by Miller. As Miller and Sarah Schlabach
folded up a quilt one day last week, another woman arrived to
spread her quilt. Miller keeps a notebook with the names of the
women who helped ``so I know who helped and I can help them.''
</P>
<P>
   This winter, she will make two quilts and sell them at the
February craft sale for about $500 each. Last winter, she sold
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pastime, especially for these older ladies and
widows,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, Pinecraft is a retirement community. Of all the
bicycles in the neighborhood, very few belong to children. A more
likely sight is Sarah Overholt walking alongside her father's
electric wheelchair and stopping to talk to an elderly neighbor who
relates the latest news from back home: her recent buggy accident.
Like a lot of other retirement villages across South Florida, lines
form at the shuffleboard courts in winter time. Only here, scores
are called out in Pennsylvania Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
