<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6383 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-GOP-CLEMENTS02-CO     12-01 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-GOP-CLEMENTS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Gov. Clements credited with GOP revival
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Twenty years after he pulled off the
Texas political upset of the century, ex-Gov. Bill Clements, the
Republican who started it all, has gone to the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Now a robust 81, Clements observes, but does not play, politics.
He spends several days a week at the ranch in Forney, near Dallas,
that he has owned since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he watched something that seemed unfathomable in
1978, when he beat Democrat John Hill and became the first Texas
Republican elected to a major state government post since
Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't ever anticipate in my lifetime that I'd see
it,'' Clements said of the Election Day sweep that will put all
statewide offices in Republican hands come January. ``The political
system in Texas has just turned itself inside out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his place in the state's political history, Clements has
never been afforded a high-profile thank-you from the Republican
Party. And for Clements, who didn't do much politics before his
1978 race and hasn't done much since he left office in 1991, that's
fine.
</P>
<P>
   He said he turns down invitations to state Republican
conventions. He has been to Austin only twice since he was replaced
by Ann Richards in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never in politics until I was elected governor,'' he
said. ``I was a drilling contractor. So when I left office, I went
back to do the things I like to do and associate with the people
that I was the closest to.''
</P>
<P>
   That group does not include many politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a part of my past I don't care anything about
continuing into my later years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctant hero
</P>
<P>
   Recently, at the George Bush Presidential Library at Texas A&AMP;M,
Clements' one-man role in reshaping the state's political landscape
was in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak today in honor of an extraordinarily important figure
in modern Texas political life,'' Austin political consultant Karl
Rove, who was on board for the 1978 race, said in a lecture
entitled ``One Man Did Make a Difference.''
</P>
<P>
   That extraordinarily important figure was an audience member,
clad in a patterned sport coat more understated than the screaming
plaid ones that burdened his closets while he was in office.
</P>
<P>
   Rove argues that Clements gives lie to the conventional
political wisdom that says no one candidate or campaign can spark
major change unless that change was already in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers in 1978 give context to the magnitude of Clements'
accomplishment. Texas Republicans held one U.S. Senate seat, two
U.S. House seats, 18 of the 150 state House seats and three of the
31 state Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   It had been 116 years since a Republican had been elected
governor. And GOP presidential candidates had carried Texas only
four times in the 28 White House races since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``In East Texas, they said they hunted Republicans,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Farming rural roots
</P>
<P>
   Clements won in 1978 by working hard in rural Texas, offering a
businessman's background and dipping into his deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``His personal resources made it possible for him to promise
victory-starved Republicans that he wouldn't run out of gas like
Republican candidates had done in the closing months of other
campaigns,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Clements benefited from a Democratic Party rift slow to heal
after then-Attorney General John Hill defeated Gov. Dolph Briscoe
in the spring primary. Hill, and most thinking Texans, assumed form
would hold and that the primary win was tantamount to election.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill, and Texas, had not seen anything quite like the crusty
Clements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clements was different,'' Rove said. ``While he lived in
Dallas' tony Highland Park, Bill Clements is more a product of
Forney'' and the rural towns where he worked as a roughneck.
</P>
<P>
   He knew rural Texas, and he knew that he had to cut into
Democratic margins there to win.
</P>
<P>
   After winning in 1978, he was defeated by Democrat Mark White in
1982 but came back to unseat White in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tactically and strategically, knowing or unknowing, Bill
Clements built the Republican Party in Texas in a way that no other
Republican president or senator or congressman could do,'' Rove
said.
</P>
<P>
   Courthouse by courthouse, coffee shop by coffee shop, candidate
Clements built a ground game to support the high-dollar airwaves
game he mounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In small-town Texas, it matters what goes on at the coffee
shops,'' Rove said. ``That was the chatter around town for the next
several days. And it was a chatter that affected people's
attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   The coffee shop circuit, generally, went well for Clements,
whose style was molded in oil fields and boardrooms and is not
necessarily long on warm and cuddly.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign curmudgeon
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, campaigning at a McKinney ice cream parlor, Clements
was disgruntled when he wasted a pitch on two families who were
from out of state and not much interested in the gubernatorial
race.
</P>
<P>
   A third family, unaware of what had happened at the other
tables, was confronted with an agitated man who opened with this
line: ``Where are you from, Timbuktu?''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after he became the first Texas Democrat since
Reconstruction to lose a statewide race, Hill is aware _ and leery
of _ his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely you are not going to run a story blaming John Hill,''
he said of the recent GOP sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican trend would have set in even if he had won, Hill
said. He believes he fell victim to things over which he had
control and things over which he did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought that the fact I was showing a strong lead
with about a week to go _ 11 points _ that might have lulled us to
sleep a little bit,'' he said. ``We didn't spend a lot of money on
television those last critical two weeks. And he did. That made a
big impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that hurt Hill was a precursor to the religious
right movement that has played a significant role in GOP growth. As
attorney general, Hill led the effort to force Corpus Christi
evangelist Lester Roloff to get state-required licenses for his
children's homes.
</P>
<P>
   Roloff mounted a high-volume, high-profile campaign to paint
Hill, a church-going man, as a political anti-Christ.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Hill believes he fell victim to the genesis of what
became a major religious-political force in Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the great ironies of Texas politics, Roloff died in a
plane crash in November 1982 on the day Democrat Mark White
unseated Clements.
</P>
<P>
   Clements and wife Rita, who was a player in Republican politics
long before he got involved, now split time among their home in
Dallas, their ranch in Forney and their Taos, N.M., summer place.
</P>
<P>
   Clements said the ranch is his primary interest. ``The rest of
the time, I'm trying to improve my golf score,'' said Clements, who
usually shoots 90 to 95.
</P>
<P>
   A big Bush backer
</P>
<P>
   The first GOP governor of Texas since Reconstruction counts
himself as a major fan of the second GOP governor of Texas since
Reconstruction. Clements, who skipped over home-state Sen. Phil
Gramm and backed California Gov. Pete Wilson's short-lived 1996
presidential bid, believes Gov. George W. Bush will run for
president and win in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll help him in any way I can,'' Clements said. ``I think he
would be outstanding. He has a good mind. He physically is a strong
person. He has a great background because of his association with
his mother and father. He is different than his father; he is a
tougher individual than his father. He is stronger-minded. He is
his mother's son.''
</P>
<P>
   Clements' critics, including some who worked for him, say
privately that the 1986 run was motivated solely by a desire to
unseat White.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, said Clements, insisting that his comeback was
motivated by pure thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a serious contribution to make,'' he said,
adding a hint of a note of revenge. ``And I didn't like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellowed by age, and long removed from front-line politics,
Clements still sometimes shows his prickly side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (Paul) Hobby would be stronger than he was,'' he
said, referring to the Democratic comptroller nominee who lost a
close race to Carole Keeton Rylander last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Might have been if he had a different father,'' Clements
added, calling on his longstanding animus for former Lt. Gov. Bill
Hobby, who is considered an icon among many Texas Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   From his elbow came a word or two of advice from the always more
politically attuned half of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to quit being so outspoken about that,'' Rita
Clements told her husband, as if he is an 81-year-old looking to
change his ways.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
