<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6384 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-TEACHERS-HOUSES02     12-01 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-TEACHERS-HOUSES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheaper homes on the range lure teachers
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNI, Texas _ With demand for teachers so acute in Texas that
big-city school districts are offering cash signing bonuses,
out-of-the-way districts such as Webb Consolidated _ which draws
students from the small towns and ranches east of Laredo _ are
relying on subsidized housing to lure new educators.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrecting a practice that dates back to the frontier days,
when towns built living quarters for the schoolmarm, Webb
Consolidated Independent School District is offering teachers an
apartment in a district-owned complex next to the football field or
in any one of a dozen houses and mobile homes spread out over
district property in Bruni and nearby Oilton.
</P>
<P>
   The rent: $250 a month for two bedrooms, $300 a month for three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the school not had housing, I wouldn't have come,'' said
Phil Worley, an Austin native who has taught at Webb Consolidated
for 10 years and lives in one of the district's gray double-wide
mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   This little-known teacher perk isn't unique to Webb County.
Although the state doesn't keep track of how many districts offer
housing, as many as two dozen Texas school districts, mostly in
West Texas and along the border, own ``teacherages'' as
school-owned housing is known, said Dane Adkinson, a personnel
consultant at the Texas Association of School Boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think perhaps it's making a little bit of a comeback,''
Adkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Webb Consolidated, which covers 800 square miles of oil-rich
brushland and has 45 teachers for about 450 students, got into the
housing business a decade ago out of necessity, said David Jones,
the district's superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   In this part of South Texas, where oil and gas and livestock pay
the bills for many families, land rarely changes hands, and rental
property is virtually nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place to live, and if you're going to attract a
decent staff, one of the things you can do is provide teacher
housing,'' Jones said. ``The amenities of life are an hour to an
hour and a half away. Doctors, Wal-Marts, things like that are just
not in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   So over the past decade, Jones' district has built a 12-unit
apartment building and six houses and has bought six manufactured
homes _ becoming the biggest renter in Bruni and Oilton, which have
a combined population of about 1,150.
</P>
<P>
   The district is the area's social hub _ Jones said more than
1,200 people packed the gymnasium last year to watch 37 seniors
graduate _ and has a healthy tax base, a well-equipped vocational
technology center and an enviable teacher-to-student ratio.
</P>
<P>
   But housing, Jones said, has become one of its most valuable
recruiting tools.
</P>
<P>
   Districts such as Presidio, near Big Bend, and United, on the
outskirts of Laredo, are now taking a hard look at building their
own housing in the near future as their enrollment _ and need for
teachers _ grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're going out and looking for beginning teachers, it's
a big draw,'' said Bob McCall, superintendent of the
Iraan-Sheffield Independent School District in Pecos County, east
of Fort Stockton. The district, with 600 students and 53 teachers,
owns 12 apartments and 27 houses and rents three-bedroom homes for
$165 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of times it's the difference between (teachers)
coming here and going somewhere else because we're so isolated,''
McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   District as developer
</P>
<P>
   This 19th-century solution has run into 20th-century problems,
however _ particularly at Webb Consolidated. The district has
repeatedly tangled with the county planning department, which has
at times refused to approve electricity connections for district
housing, saying the district has become a developer and must abide
by local development codes _ particularly those that set a minimum
size for lots to allow room for proper septic tank drainage. The
towns where the schools are located have no sewer systems.
</P>
<P>
   County officials say their refusal to connect electricity has
forced the district to reluctantly comply with the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Jones says the district's housing should be considered school
buildings and should be exempt from rules applied to developers.
Earlier this month, however, the Texas attorney general's office
sided with the county, handing down an opinion that the district
indeed has become a ``subdivider.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing's just ridiculous,'' said Jones, adding that
the district's housing has water and sewage systems that meet
county codes. ``We are not in the development business; we are in
the teaching business.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkinson, the school board association official, said some urban
districts have cut deals with local apartment owners to waive
security deposits or offer reduced rents for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Other districts offer signing bonuses, additional retirement
accounts and bonuses for teachers who go back to school and get
certified to teach other subjects, said Stephanie Korcheck,
director of policy and planning for the State Board for Educator
Certification.
</P>
<P>
   Perks falling short
</P>
<P>
   Still, there aren't enough teachers to go around. With the
economy booming, the private sector has plucked many educators from
schools, and 40 to 50 percent of newly certified teachers are
taking nonteaching jobs with better pay and benefits, Korcheck
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere that I go . . . (school administrators) are out
there going to other states and even other countries to bring
people to their school districts, and they're just not finding
anyone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of teachers is a big reason why Presidio
Independent School District, on the Rio Grande northwest of Big
Bend National Park, is thinking about building housing or
converting existing buildings into dwellings, said Teloa Swinnea,
the district's director of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment has increased by 200 students this year to 1,380, she
said, and the district has gone as far away as Germany _ where it
found two teachers through an international exchange program _ to
fill vacant positions. District officials hope to bring teachers
from Spain under a similar program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so remotely located, we need ways to attract teachers
to our district,'' Swinnea said.
</P>
<P>
   Schools ponder projects
</P>
<P>
   At United Independent School District, which wraps around Laredo
and is growing so fast that four new elementary schools will be
added next year, construction manager Greg Chavarria said the
school board is mulling over a plan to build a 48-unit apartment
complex on school property.
</P>
<P>
   The building would ideally be paid for with tax-exempt bonds,
which would be paid back with the reduced rents teachers would pay,
Chavarria said.
</P>
<P>
   In Valentine, another West Texas town where teacher housing has
been around for years, Superintendent Mike Pate said expansion is
being considered.
</P>
<P>
   The Valentine Independent School District, with 11 teachers and
just 55 students, already has eight housing units _ three mobile
homes, a triplex and two houses. Pate thinks the lack of available
housing in town has stunted the district's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Housing is a problem here, and the school district has a lot
of property around town, so we're thinking of getting into
(building) even deeper,'' Pate said. ``We feel like if we had a few
more family dwellings that we might have a few more kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
