<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6385 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SUGAR02-COX     12-01 1815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SUGAR02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Sugar refines its product in new plant
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEWISTON, Fla. _ Corporate secrets don't keep in this company
town.
</P>
<P>
   But it was imperative the Delta project _ the code name U.S.
Sugar Corp. gave its new refinery _ be kept under wraps while in
the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to look without creating a big furor in the
industry,'' said Murray Brinson, who in 1992 began touring sugar
mills and refineries in the United States and abroad as a company
spy, of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   As senior vice president of sugar processing, Brinson had to
gather enough information on the sly to allow U.S. Sugar to make
this important decision: to build or not to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we decided not to do it, we wanted to just quietly fold our
tent,'' said Brinson, whose company for 67 years has produced raw
sugar and sold it to refiners that then made it into white sugar
and resold it.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of folding its tent, U.S. Sugar put one up last
month to welcome the more than 600 people who came to tour its new
refinery _ the computer-driven, $70 million-plus crown jewel of its
sugar empire.
</P>
<P>
   As the first cane sugar refinery to be built in the United
States in more than 25 years, the complex includes the industry's
most highly automated and sophisticated machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Brinson and his team shopped the world for the very best,
picking a Swiss company to make its high-speed packaging lines and
South African and German firms for other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sugar will say only that it cost more than $70 million to
build the Clewiston refinery _ though sugar industry analysts put
the cost closer to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude, size and capabilities of it were just a little
bit beyond anything I've ever seen,'' said Moira Saucer, a
spokeswoman for the Sugar Association, a Washington group that
promotes the nutritional aspects of sugar, who attended the grand
opening.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of how automated the 12-story,
300,000-square-foot plant is, consider this: It can be run by four
people.
</P>
<P>
   All that's needed is one operator in the computer control room,
one at the centrifugals _ machines that separate sugar crystals
from liquid _ and two roving operators.
</P>
<P>
   Another 150 people handle packaging, warehousing, distribution,
lab work and other support activities. Many U.S. Sugar workers
transferred to the refinery from other positions, leaving openings
elsewhere in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Once the refinery is running at its 1,800-tons-a-day capacity _
as the sugar harvest hits full swing in the next couple of months _
it will add about 170 jobs to U.S. Sugar's total employment.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, a typical refinery of this size would employ
about 300.
</P>
<P>
   An international operation
</P>
<P>
   ``The most amazing thing to me was the lack of people,'' said
Dalton Yancey, executive vice president of the Florida Sugar Cane
League, a research and lobbying group whose members include U.S.
Sugar, the sugar companies owned by the Fanjul family of Palm Beach
and other growers.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the warehouse, a robotic arm plucks 40-pound bundles
from packing lines and swiftly but gingerly places them this way
and that on pallets that are then stacked by forklift drivers.
</P>
<P>
   SIG, a Swiss company that makes industrial machinery, guns and
other tools and equipment, made two of the three packaging lines,
which pack 2-, 4- and 5-pound bags for retail sale.
</P>
<P>
   The machines are controlled by computers hooked by modem to
Switzerland, where technicians troubleshoot from nearly 5,000 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure the lines worked with materials the Clewiston plant
would use, the company shipped nearly 1,000 pounds of sugar along
with giant rolls of packaging paper to Switzerland for testing.
</P>
<P>
   SIG assembled the lines and ran them with Florida-grown sugar
before sending them to Clewiston. In addition, U.S. Sugar sent
about a dozen mechanics, operators and electricians to Switzerland
for training.
</P>
<P>
   The long trips and 60-hour workweeks took their toll on
Clewiston families. ``They've put up with a lot in the last three
years,'' said Brinson, who is married and has two grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   But folks in Clewiston understand one thing, Brinson said:
``When the company does well, we do well.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sugar, which employs about 3,500 during the sugar cane and
citrus harvests, is owned primarily by its employees and charitable
foundations set up by its founder, Charles Stewart Mott.
</P>
<P>
   The Clewiston refinery is clearly the biggest investment the
company has ever made _ and it's one U.S. Sugar, with nearly a
half-billion dollars in annual sales, is counting on for its
future.
</P>
<P>
   With raw sugar prices essentially flat for years, U.S. Sugar
decided in the early 1990s that it needed a vehicle for growth.
</P>
<P>
   After considering businesses as diverse as making ethanol to
manufacturing cosmetics ingredients from sugar cane byproducts, the
company settled on refined sugar _ which fetches a higher price
than the raw product.
</P>
<P>
   Raw sugar sells for 21 to 22 cents a pound, while bulk white
sugar goes for 28 to 30 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Building, rather than buying, a refinery made the most sense
primarily because the company's Clewiston mill can feed raw sugar
directly to the refinery.
</P>
<P>
   Further adding to its efficiency, company officials say, U.S.
Sugar has removed three steps that take place in a typical
refinery: affination, which strips molasses from sugar crystals;
clarification, which removes organic matter from liquid sugar; and
remelting, which extracts sucrose from molasses.
</P>
<P>
   The company has made some proprietary changes to these processes
and does them in the mill, instead of at the refinery.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sugar is counting on these efficiencies to help it make a
better return than its competitors on the table sugar it will sell
to a growing South Florida population and a legion of giant
industrial users such as candy makers Nestle and Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   Effect on other refineries
</P>
<P>
   The sugar refining industry has shrunk over the past 20 years,
with smaller stand-alone refineries closing. Since 1981, 12 U.S.
refineries have closed, according to the U.S. Cane Sugar Refiners'
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Those closings happened after sugar prices fluctuated wildly in
the 1970s and again in the 1980s when the federal sugar program,
which regulated the amount of sugar in the U.S., was not renewed.
</P>
<P>
   The price swings spurred soft-drink makers to switch from sugar
to high-fructose corn syrup, further hurting the sugar refiners.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Kominus, president of the Washington-based Refiners'
Association, said he hopes U.S. Sugar's entry into refining doesn't
force more cane refiners out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. Sugar, which had been shipping raw sugar to other
refineries, is now going to be siphoning off a good slug of that
and refining it themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group's members, which refine and sell sugar to large users
such as candy makers, is at odds with U.S. Sugar and other sugar
producers over the federal sugar quota program, which limits
imports to protect the domestic crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be less raw sugar out there (now that U.S. Sugar is
refining much of its sugar product), and it's going to be a
difficult period for the existing refineries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Including the new U.S. Sugar refinery, there are just 11
refineries left in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is owned by U.S. Sugar competitor Florida Crystals
Corp., which controls the Florida businesses owned by the Fanjul
family. But the Florida Crystals' refinery _ at the Okeelanta mill
near South Bay _ can handle only about a third of the 700,000 tons
of raw sugar the company produces each year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the U.S. Sugar refinery can produce 540,000 tons of
refined sugar a year and has room to double that capacity by adding
more equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Crystals, which is looking to expand its refining
capacity, made an unsuccessful bid for a Georgia refinery last year
and reportedly is close to reaching a deal to buy a refinery in
Yonkers, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the situation say the Belle Glade-based
Sugar Cane Growers Cooperative of Florida, made up of smaller sugar
farmers, is joining Florida Crystals in its bid.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side will comment on the deal, though industry analysts
say it's common knowledge the parties are talking.
</P>
<P>
   Word travels quickly in the sugar industry _ that's why U.S.
Sugar was so keen to keep its refining plans quiet.
</P>
<P>
   From the company's perspective, if any of the refiners who buy
its raw product caught wind of its plans to get into the refining
business too early in the game, it might be bad for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the outset, it was very closely held,'' recalled Don
Griffin, manager of specialty sugar, who joined Brinson in his
globe-trotting quest for refining knowledge. ``There were some in
the executive suite that didn't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But by early last year _ six months after the company picked
project engineer Stone &AMP; Webster Engineering Corp. of Boston and
about the time the board OK'd the project _ all of Clewiston and
most of the sugar industry knew what U.S. Sugar had cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Construction began in March 1997 and wrapped up 18 months later.
</P>
<P>
   Pest control at the plant
</P>
<P>
   While the company at one point predicted a July completion, El
Nino rains and construction delays pushed that back to September.
By October, the plant was ready for its grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   As a food-grade plant, the refinery must be in tiptop shape at
all times.
</P>
<P>
   Large users of refined sugar have inspected the plant in recent
weeks. Nabisco, Pillsbury and Wrigley came through last month;
Nestle stopped by early this month.
</P>
<P>
   The American Institute of Baking helped in the plant's design
and conducted a three-day inspection _ poring over pest-control
records and probing into corners _ before certifying the refinery.
</P>
<P>
   The institute will inspect the facility four times a year _ at
about $4,000 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   To keep pests away, U.S. Sugar planted 50 traps _ referred to as
``tin cats'' _ that cage rodents inside the refinery. The building
is surrounded outside by more than 100 poison bait stations.
</P>
<P>
   All workers wear hair nets and no tobacco or chewing gum is
allowed in the building _ not even inside employees' pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three months, the company even uprooted and
replanted in other areas about 80 trees from around the refinery in
an attempt to keep birds away. That trick was learned from touring
a bird-plagued cake factory in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now dealing with a product that goes on people's
tables,'' Brinson said. ``There are a lot of things that weren't in
our culture that are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waresh writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
