<HEADER>
A6387 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movies definitely aren't what they used to be
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Movies were killer simple when I was a kid.
There were two
</P>
<P>
   plots: ``Boy meets girl, boy gets girl, boy loses girl, boy gets
her back again''
</P>
<P>
   (my favorite), and ``Good guys always win'' (usually starring
John Wayne). My
</P>
<P>
   playmates and I lived what we watched.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday matinees stoked the fires of our imaginations for an
entire week. I
</P>
<P>
   daydreamed of Pepe le Moko (Charles Boyer) foolishly abandoning
his sanctuary
</P>
<P>
   in the Casbah for the love of a beautiful woman (me). And when
Roy Rogers astride his trusty Trigger galloped across the screen in
search of a damsel in
</P>
<P>
   distress, I knew what nobody else in that darkened theater knew
- Roy wasn't
</P>
<P>
   looking for Dale - he was looking for me (the skinny kid in the
front row with a box of half-melted Milk Duds clutched in her hand.
</P>
<P>
   The only psychological mindbender I remember on the double bill
at the
</P>
<P>
   neighborhood theater was ``Gaslight,'' another Boyer film. In
this one he was the
</P>
<P>
   bad guy trying to scare Ingrid Bergman out of her mind (and her
money) by
</P>
<P>
   messing with the light fixtures. For weeks I listened for
footsteps in the attic and stared at my bedside lamp for a telltale
flicker.
</P>
<P>
   Monster movies intrigued us. We watched ``Frankenstein'' through
our fingers,
</P>
<P>
   squeezing them tightly together during the really scary parts.
Later, when
</P>
<P>
   Abbott and Costello met Frankenstein, we were older and a little
braver. We
</P>
<P>
   didn't hide behind our hands, but on our walk home at dusk, we
gave wide berth
</P>
<P>
   to garages, hedges, and tall bushes. And when we played
``Frankenstein'' nobody
</P>
<P>
   wanted to be the victim.
</P>
<P>
   We loved the John Wayne war movies. After ``Flying Tigers'' we
all wanted to be
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne. For days we made strafing runs on my back yard
sandbox. Once in a
</P>
<P>
   while, one of us would get shot down but one way or another, we
always made it
</P>
<P>
   back to base. One time, in the heat of battle, Tootie yelled,
``Damn it! I've been hit!'' which brought the game to a screeching
halt. We told her John Wayne didn't talk that way and she couldn't
play if she was going to swear. Dialogue in those days was
different. Every fifth word did not begin with ``F'' and end with a
slur on somebody's mother. Heck, things were so tight back then,
even Blondie and Dagwood slept in twin beds. Made sense to us. We
didn't know where Cookie and Baby Dumpling came from anyway.
</P>
<P>
   We all wanted to swim like Esther Williams and emerge from the
depths of a
</P>
<P>
   crystalline pool with every hair in place and droplets of water
clinging to our
</P>
<P>
   ruby lips. We practiced in the back yard sprinkler, prancing
around like lame
</P>
<P>
   swans, while our mothers yelled at us to stay on the grass so we
wouldn't catch
</P>
<P>
   infantile paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted to purr like Veronica Lake when she looked into Alan
Ladd's eyes. We didn't know he was standing on a box in the
closeups. It wouldn't have made
</P>
<P>
   any difference anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For days after we watched Greer Garson as ``Mrs. Miniver''
weathering the WW2
</P>
<P>
   blitz without ever losing her cool OR her impeccable manners, we
were so gracious around the house that even our mothers commented
on the change in our
</P>
<P>
   demeanor. Mine thought I'd been up to something, and Tootie's
thought she had a
</P>
<P>
   fever.
</P>
<P>
   Movies were our inspiration back then, and movie stars our role
models. Nothing affected our behavior like those larger-than-life
folks with whom we
</P>
<P>
   spent Saturday afternoons in the dark. Movies taught us how to
act. Luckily, they were pretty innocuous. Good guys were invariably
handsome, brave, and honest. Girls were smart, strong, warm and
loving. Killer simple, just like I said.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie bunch around my neighborhood grew up, so did the
movies. We went from Gable's ``Frankly my dear, I don't give a
damn,'' to Monroe's skirt over
</P>
<P>
   her head in ``The Seven Year Itch,'' and thought it was all too
cool for words. But
</P>
<P>
   over the years we've found ourselves lamenting the scarcity of
flicks that inspire us to drop a day's pay at the Bijou much less
act out the main characters. Tootie says we're jaded. Mary Ann says
we're just fed up with trash. Either way, we're not having as much
fun as we used to.
</P>
<P>
   These days we watch a lot of reruns. Tootie and I are stuck
somewhere between
</P>
<P>
   Cher's ``Loretta'' in ``Moonstruck'' and Annette Bening's savvy
babe in ``The
</P>
<P>
   American President.'' Mary Ann's happy with 'Sleepless in
Seattle,' hoping a
</P>
<P>
   slightly older version of Tom Hanks might be listening in.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Hollywood to wake up and smell the popcorn. Or
haven't they
</P>
<P>
   read the statistics. Our generation is better educated and
living longer than
</P>
<P>
   ever before - and (this is the biggie) - we've got most of the
money. Trouble
</P>
<P>
   is, we're not going to spend it on junk.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett a writer and teacher, writes for Cox News
Service. Send
</P>
<P>
   mail to: 320 West Madison, Gibsonburg 43431 or e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
