<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK02-COX     12-01 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONEYTALK: Roth IRA is useful tool for many people, not all
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Individual retirement accounts _ particularly Roth IRAs _ are a
rich source of both tax breaks and confusion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the choices you may need to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing to a Roth IRA rather than to a traditional IRA.
</P>
<P>
   _ Converting an existing IRA into a Roth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Switching your converted money out of a Roth and back into a
traditional IRA _ then switching it right back again. Strange as it
sounds, that could save you some taxes if you converted before the
market stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Roth IRAs are a wonderful retirement savings vehicle. Like
traditional IRAs, Roth IRAs allow individuals to put away as much
as $2,000 a year in tax-favored investments.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional IRAs are attractive in part because they yield an
immediate tax benefit. You can deduct the amount of your
contribution from taxable income, assuming you meet certain
qualifications. And you can defer taxes on the money your
investments earn. You pay when you withdraw the money.
</P>
<P>
   A Roth IRA, by contrast, offers no deduction now. But your
withdrawals are tax-free when you take the money out, if you keep
the account for at least five years and are older than age 59 1/2.
That means your payout can be much, much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts recommend the Roth IRA if you expect your tax rate
to be the same or higher when you take the money out.
</P>
<P>
   The law also allows individuals to convert an existing IRA to a
Roth. You can make the switch if your adjusted gross income is less
than $100,000. You must do it by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   There is a catch: Technically, you take the money out of the
traditional IRA and, in a separate transaction, put it into the
Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   When you take the first step, the money becomes income. You must
pay taxes on it. In return, you get that potentially huge benefit
of tax-free withdrawals later on.
</P>
<P>
   You can get some relief if you make the transaction by the end
of this year. The IRS will allow you to spread the income over four
years, thus spreading out the tax liability over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can, 1998 is the year to do it, because you have the
advantage of that four-year spread,'' said Roger W. Lusby III, a
certified public accountant with Frazier &AMP; Deeter.
</P>
<P>
   But is the trade-off worth it?
</P>
<P>
   The experts say conversion is the best choice if:
</P>
<P>
   _ You pay the income tax out of current income, not the money
you withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   _ You expect your tax rate to remain the same, or go up, when
you retire.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to find the dollars-and-cents impact of conversion
in your circumstances, you can find a first-rate, interactive
worksheet at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .vanguard.com/cgi-bin
</P>
<P>
   /RothConv.
</P>
<P>
   The third choice (switching your converted money out of a Roth
and back into a traditional IRA _ then switching it back again) may
be useful if you converted from a traditional to a Roth IRA earlier
this year, and the value of those investments has declined
substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that you created taxable income when you took money out
of your traditional IRA.
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that your investments are worth a lot
less now. But you still owe taxes based on the higher values that
existed on the day of your withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   You can reduce that tax liability by moving the Roth money back
to a traditional IRA, then turning around and putting it right back
into a Roth. Suppose you converted a $200,000 portfolio earlier
this year, and the value of that portfolio has since fallen to
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   You now owe taxes on $200,000 in income. But if you do this IRS
two-step, moving a $100,000 portfolio back and forth, your taxable
value on the same portfolio drops to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has approved this gambit, but you can do it only once.
</P>
<P>
   Is it worthwhile?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only generalization is the higher your tax bracket, the
more likely it is that you will want to examine this possibility,''
said Christine Fahlund, a certified financial planner with T. Rowe
Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, it's more a subjective, personal value judgment as
to what is a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you converted $6,000 and now your stock is worth
$5,500, ``is it worth going back and forth?'' asked Lusby.
``Probably not, but that's a decision for the taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: hezell(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
