<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-AUCTIONS02-COX     12-01 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-AUCTIONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On-line auction can offer thrills of real-life bidding
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're near a personal computer,
you're within arm's reach of America's biggest garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people who just don't have enough stuff and don't
want to leave home to get more have made on-line auction site eBay
the Internet's latest why-didn't-I-think-of-that phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   A computer programmer whose girlfriend wanted to find other Pez
dispenser collectors started eBay three years ago, and it has grown
from 340,000 registered users to 1.27 million during the past 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   The California-based company's stock, offered for the first time
in September, zoomed from $18 to $218 in two months, and founder
Pierre Omidyar's stake approached $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction is powerful but simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man's junk is another man's treasure,'' said Jennifer Chu,
eBay's associate public relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a million items for sale, eBay is the World Wide
Web's version of a vast, tin-roofed flea market, at
http://www.ebay.com. Sellers, all independent of eBay, post nearly
100,000 new items daily _ new to eBay, but mostly more thrift store
than Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   Just a sampling of what you could buy (or try to) on eBay: an
old dental extractor ($205), a burp gun that shoots pingpong balls
($13), a rotary valve tuba ($510), a 1988 Ferrari ($62,800).
</P>
<P>
   Plus, of course, loads of Beanie Babies, Furbys and other hot
toys.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar figures are bids, not prices, and they're followed by the
time remaining until the auction ends. It may be days, hours or
less.
</P>
<P>
   If your heart pounds when you discover that someone is offering
a bronze bust of Liberace like the one Mom loved, it may pound even
harder when you realize you have 12 minutes to decide whether you
really want it in your living room.
</P>
<P>
   Feverish pace attracts bidders
</P>
<P>
   Even if you do, you might lose out to someone who wants it more.
The fever of the bidding is one of eBay's main attractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thrill of it,'' Chu said. ``It's so exciting to bid
and so frustrating when you don't get an item.''
</P>
<P>
   Add the thrill of the unknown. On-line auctions are gauzy
bazaars where bidders can't touch the merchandise and may find the
seller identified only by nickname.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainties were underscored recently when a Lake Worth
man became the only person barred for life from doing business on
the Internet. He settled a Federal Trade Commission complaint that
he failed to deliver more than $20,000 in computers that he offered
on eBay and another on-line auction, Up4Sale.
</P>
<P>
   While eBay says risks for buyers are small, it acknowledges the
potential for fraud, warns users to beware and says it makes no
guarantees about goods or the people who hawk them. The service's
users cover a wide range.
</P>
<P>
   ``All walks of life, all income levels,'' Chu said. ``It's not
only a place to buy and sell but to meet other people with similar
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Success has brought increased competition: Yahoo Auctions
(www.yahoo.com) went on line in September, joining an auction site
of competing search engine Excite (www.excite.com), as well as
dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   But eBay has responded by buying out the 50,000-user Up4Sale
(www.up4sale.com) and agreeing to pay America Online $12 million
for a three-year agreement that will make it easier for AOL members
to buy and sell through eBay.
</P>
<P>
   One of eBay's primary distinctions is its person-to-person
nature. Most previous on-line auctions were run by companies
offering products, mostly electronics, directly to buyers. Most of
eBay's sellers are individual entrepreneurs looking to make a few
dollars on things they'd otherwise donate to charity, or looking to
make a lot of dollars on their hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start businesses this way,'' Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   Some have found a new way of doing business. Margaret and John
Cantrell have had an antique/collectibles shop on Dixie Highway in
West Palm Beach for seven years, but they haven't opened the doors
much since they started offering their wares on eBay last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son's on the computer all day, my husband's taking
pictures, and I'm packing things,'' Margaret Cantrell said. ``We've
sold more on eBay in the last month than we have in the past year
at the store.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cantrells have found eBay perfect for the small items they
specialize in: jewelry, pottery, vintage clothing. They've found
eBay buyers in Sweden, Italy and Monaco, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Renault is also impressed with the international reach eBay
has given him from Boynton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold an American watch to a guy in Taiwan,'' Renault said.
``And I just sold a one-armed, one-legged doll to a guy in
Australia for $860. That's pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Renault, who runs Robert Renault Estate Liquidators, is a
computer fan who found eBay about a year ago while searching other
on-line auction sites. He now lists about 10 items at a time and
sells about 80 percent of what he lists.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Renault's a regular at local antique fairs, eBay
has become a dependable source of collectibles for his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a slot machine, a Tiffany bowl, dolls for my kids,''
he said. ``You can find anything in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Renault shoots pictures of everything he offers on eBay with a
digital camera and posts them with the descriptions. He says
everyone he's bought from has described flaws and other important
details properly.
</P>
<P>
   Renault's only complaint is mild: Access to eBay has slowed as
users increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot more people have been browsing recently since eBay
started advertising,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing eBay is free. So is bidding. All that's needed to make
an offer is to register, which requires an e-mail address that can
be verified by return message. Registered users can post any item
by paying a fee ranging from 25 cents for anything under $10, to $2
for anything $50 and up.
</P>
<P>
   The seller has a choice of auction length: three, five or seven
days. As bids come in, the posted dollar figure rises and the
seller is updated regularly by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   High bid binding
</P>
<P>
   Sellers are encouraged to start with their lowest acceptable
price, but it's not mandatory and some find that an artificially
low listing draws more bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The final, high bid is binding on the buyer, although some
occasionally back out. The seller is required to pay eBay a second
fee of up to 5 percent of the high bid (but only 1.5 percent on
bids over $1,000) _ even if the seller decides he can't part with
Uncle Jerry's toupee after all.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few other rules, conditions and variations (such as
Dutch auctions for multiple-but-identical items), but it never gets
complicated enough to require a degree in either business or
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the profusion of obscure items, eBay boasts a high
success rate. ``A conservative estimate is that 70 percent of the
items listed result in a sale,'' Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for some items is so intense that several companies
offer software that can program a bidder's computer to dial in with
an offer moments before an auction's close. Such software isn't
condoned by eBay, but it's also not outlawed as long as the bidder
follows all the rules, Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   But the company is sensitive to the possibility of bid
manipulation and forbids practices such as shilling, in which a
seller enlists a friend to help drive up the price with phantom
bids. It has a team that investigates complaints and has revoked
the registration of users who break the rules, Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also investigates complaints about merchandise and
sellers and revokes privileges when warranted, Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission at
the time of the stock offering, eBay noted that its success depends
on sellers describing items accurately and delivering them
reliably. But eBay takes no responsibility for either.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC filings acknowledged that the company has received
complaints from sellers and buyers. They also noted that a state
attorney general's office had received complaints that the company
did not provide adequate warning that it doesn't guarantee
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it believed its disclosures were adequate. The
Florida Attorney General's Office has taken no action against any
on-line auction company, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Although bidders don't get a guarantee, they do get plenty of
advice on how to protect themselves. And eBay offers several
features to help, including feedback ratings and notices about
sellers based on past buyers' experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Feedback feature effective
</P>
<P>
   The feedback feature is effective, said local user Renault.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants negative feedback,'' he said. ``If a dealer sees
negative feedback, he won't buy from you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyers are encouraged to e-mail the seller with questions before
bidding and to ask for a phone number. Escrow agents will act as
intermediaries for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think most people are good, but there are always a few bad
apples,'' Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the company lists protection tips from the National
Consumers League's Internet Fraud Watch, Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Grant, fraud watch director, said on-line auctions account
for 65 percent of the more than 5,500 complaints the nonprofit
organization has received about Internet businesses this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the different categories of Internet fraud we track,
on-line auctions are number one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of complaints is small compared to the number of
users and is spread across various auction sites. Grant warned of
several common pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know who you're dealing with and where they are
physically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're sure, it may be difficult to pursue a complaint.
</P>
<P>
   While individual sellers actually may be operating businesses,
that can be hard to prove long-distance. Grant also warned that a
seller can plant positive feedback.
</P>
<P>
   But many regular bidders and sellers get to know each other,
particularly those with special collecting interests.
</P>
<P>
   There are eBay chat areas for people who collect just about
anything, and eBay recently began offering users free Web pages to
tell more about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are millions of people who have had happy on-line
transactions,'' Grant said. ``I do think you have to be cautious.
It's nothing to hurtle into blindly.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
