<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-HELP02-COX     12-01 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-HELP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For the love of Mildred: Radio listeners reach out to help
longtime caller
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The phone lines at WZZR-FM's lunchtime
Love Doctors show are full with bozos and potty-mouth quipsters.
But they'll have to wait. Mildred Malmsteen is calling.
</P>
<P>
   During the six years she's been phoning the show, the
67-year-old mother of six from Port Salerno has become a surrogate
radio grandma to listeners who know her only as ``Mildred.''
</P>
<P>
   This day, show hosts Rich Dickerson and Glenn Curtis decide to
toy around and quiz her on history. As usual, Mildred's a little
fuzzy on the facts. But with her Gracie Allen charm and Minnie
Pearl know-it-all style, she gives it a whirl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know about the journey of Christopher Columbus to the
New World, Mildred?'' Curtis asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, what was America like in those days?'' Dickerson begs,
suppressing a giggle. From his voice, you can tell, this is gonna
be a funny one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there was Indiannnnnnns,'' Mildred says in a sing-song
Michigan twang. ``And they had a big feeeeeeeeast.'' With her
accent, the word feast comes out as a four-syllable noun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah? What did they eat?'' Dickerson asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corn meal ... Oh, and corn pudding ... '' she says
authoritatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ewwwwwww!'' Curtis groans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corn mush ... roast corn ... corn meal ... corn mush ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson and Curtis bust a gut laughing. Mildred plays it
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you're saying that Columbus had the first Thanksgiving
dinner?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe to say that as part of the show's regular cast of twisted
callers, Malmsteen's natural charm stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why, when she was absent from the airwaves for
several months this summer, listeners were alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone called and asked, `Hey, where's Mildred been?'''
Dickerson said. ``I didn't want to say anything. It's her business,
but I had to tell them she was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Struck with fever, weakness and excessive weight gain, she went
to the hospital in July and was diagnosed with advanced ovarian
cancer. Doctors tried to perform a hysterectomy but closed her up
without removing a cancerous mass almost a foot wide. She began
chemotherapy in August, but chances of her surviving longer than a
year were slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors said I shoulda had this taken care of 20 years
ago, but I didn't even know I had it back then,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After Dickerson announced the diagnosis on the air, the
station's lines lit up with offers to help. One caller pledged
money to send her granddaughter to private school through eighth
grade. Dozens of listeners dropped by her room at Martin Memorial
Hospital, asking simply to see ``Mildred.'' The radio station
channeled thousands of dollars in donations to a medical fund in
her name.
</P>
<P>
   With no insurance and little money _ she collected aluminum cans
and copper scrap to pay her taxes, buy food and purchase Christmas
presents for her family _ Malmsteen had no way to pay for medical
care, much less make herself more comfortable. She lives with her
son and daughter-in-law at their house just off Salerno Road
because the doctor won't let her live alone anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But she'll be done with her chemotherapy in a few months. And
when word went out that she wanted to fix up the home she had lived
in since 1962, contractor John Young dropped by the Port Salerno
house.
</P>
<P>
   What he found was a ramshackle building he pronounced ``just not
livable.'' There was no air-conditioning, exposed wires hung from
ceiling beams, the windows were boarded, and the yard was overgrown
with weeds and debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked her in the eyes and said, `I'm going to build you a
new home,''' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen other contractors joined his effort, pledging
everything from architectural plans to help with getting permits.
Martin County firefighters will soon destroy the existing home in a
practice burn so that construction on the new house can begin in
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Young) is a man with a big heart,'' Mildred said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, along with the promise of a new home, Mildred has other
good news: Her tumor is shrinking. She thinks it's because a
guardian angel _ whom she swears she saw in the middle of the night
at her hospital bed in August _ told her she'd get better. Whether
she'll live to set foot in the new home is another matter, but she
doesn't dwell on the prognosis. The chemotherapy has stolen her
shoulder-length brown hair, but not her sense of humor or her
positive outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a purpose for me to be here,'' she said. ``God put me
here for a reason. If not, I'd have been dead a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Donations in Malmsteen's name can be made at any NationsBank
branch in Martin and St. Lucie counties. Checks must be payable to
the ``Mildred Benefit Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
