<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6392 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-DEERSEASON02-COX     12-01 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-DEERSEASON02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wildlife officials gear up for busy, short deer season
 &HT;    By Jim Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Kevin Behr stepped out of his car, his ears tuned
to every sound.
</P>
<P>
   Behr, the Warren County wildlife officer, slowly approached the
pick-up truck from the rear on the driver's side. He saw a dead
deer, a small buck, sprawled across the tailgate. But the clicking
sounds held his interest.
</P>
<P>
   In a few seconds, a man appeared from the driver's side. Behr
offered a friendly greeting, even though he knew he would end up
citing the man _ a $143 fine _ for a safety violation.
</P>
<P>
   Behr and every other wildlife officer in Ohio had their busiest
day of the year Monday, the first day of Ohio's deer gun hunting
season. The season, which might draw half a million hunters
statewide, ends Saturday in all parts of Ohio except the
southeastern portion, which gets one extra day, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be this way all week,'' Behr said. ``You start before
the sun comes up and you don't finish until after 10 at night. You
just have to expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   In past years, wildlife officers were inundated with trespassing
complaints during the deer gun season. This year, however, stiffer
fines for hunting without permission are likely to result in fewer
calls to catch trespassers.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few minutes of each other Monday morning Behr ran into
safety violations _ carrying loaded weapons. Checking hunter safety
is a big part of an officer's patrol during deer gun season.
</P>
<P>
   When he approached the pick-up truck, the clicking sounds came
as two passengers quickly ejected shells from their shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you know there is a law against carrying loaded weapons
in a vehicle, because as soon as you saw me coming, I heard them
unloading,'' Behr told the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to tell people that breaking the law just isn't worth
it,'' Behr said. ``Sure, the monetary loss can be substantial, but
even more important is the chance for loss of life or serious
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after leaving those hunters, Behr came across a
young man walking alone along the side of a road, carrying a
shotgun in a case. That looked innocent enough, but when Behr
checked the gun, he found a shell in the chamber. He issued the
youngster a warning with hopes he will be more careful in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrying a loaded gun like that can be dangerous any time,''
Behr said. ``You can trip and fall and the gun can go off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunters can take only one deer this year in most parts of
western Ohio. But there's an exception: In the state's four urban
zones, hunters can take up to six deer. Those zones cover the
eastern edge of Montgomery County, the western side of Warren
County, the eastern side of Butler County and all of Hamilton and
Clermont counties.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's 1998 estimated deer population is lower across the state
than in recent years _ between 400,000 and 425,000 compared with
500,00 in 1996. But many deer have been concentrated around the
state's largest cities, mostly because hunting is not allowed
within city limits. The urban zones have been established next to
those city boundaries, hoping to thin the deer population where
deer-human conflicts, such as deer-vehicle accidents and damage to
trees are prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   The zones are among efforts nationwide to curtail the deer
population in or near urban centers. Some municipalities offer
permits to hunters that allow them to use bows or shotguns to kill
more female deer. One group is even trying deer contraceptives. And
in one instances, the increasing number of deer had spawned a
business _ a team of sharpshooters will contract with a
municipality to kill deer.
</P>
<P>
   Some city park systems in Ohio have become so inundated with
deer that they've put on controlled hunts to reduce the herd. Two
such hunts are planned for suburban Cleveland parks this week,
which has drawn protests from animal rights groups. Similar
problems have cropped up in other cities across the nation. In
Minneapolis suburbs, teams of sharpshooters, using night vision
equipment, have been hired to take out 150 deer.
</P>
<P>
   The Five Rivers MetroParks system, around Dayton, has not had an
overpopulation of deer and hasn't had to put on controlled hunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Warren County there has been a great deal of development in
recent years,'' Behr observed. ``People are moving into areas that
once were woods and fields. They're finding the deer are still
around, and that sometimes causes problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
