<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GHOST02-COX     12-01 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GHOST02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ghost of seasons past said to roam at WSB
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't adjust your TV set. That shadow on your screen
just might be the ghost of a Civil War soldier _ miffed at
Atlanta's ABC affilliate, WSB-TV, for building its new studios
atop, or near, trenches used in the Battle of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The ghost, dubbed ``the General'' by bemused WSB staffers, is
said to have rattled everything but chains since the station moved
into its $50 million building on West Peachtree Street in June.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Patton, who works in the accounting department, points
toward an empty cubicle down a long hall. ``He lives back there,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The noises come from empty spaces. There is . . . this feeling
someone is here. Then you hear things. Things moving. That's why we
keep that door closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Eve Whitaker, a sales executive, says she had a close encounter
while working alone one night. ``Something came up behind me and
flipped my hair, playfully. I turned around and there was nothing,
only this feeling of a presence,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted to the alleged haunting by an employee, a team of
self-styled ghost hunters has checked out the building. Not only
did the haint register on their electromagnetic and thermal
sensors, but an image said to look like a cap-wearing young soldier
showed up in a photo.
</P>
<P>
   The ghost hunters were led by Cheri Mohr Drake of the 70-member
Georgia Haunt Hunt Team, which investigates reports of ghosts
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Drake says people can feel the presence of ghosts and measure
them with instruments, but they appear only on photos. At WSB, when
she got sensor readings, she and another team member snapped
pictures furiously, capturing the supposed face, some ``orbs'' and
a beam of light _ all displayed on their Web site,
http://www.geocities.com/(tilde)gahaunt.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds crazy, but many WSB staffers, from receptionists to
reporters and even executives, say they're convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night there was nobody here. No machines were on,'' says
Florence Hatcher, who works in human resources. ``I heard furniture
rolling across the floor, papers shuffling. He was here.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stone, an executive producer, concedes she's haunted by
the photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look and say, `That's something.' It has on one of those
Civil War caps. You know, you have a powerful reason to believe in
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the tale's credibility is the building's location _ at
a Civil War battlefield. ``We were built on the Confederate
trenches, you know,'' says Hatcher. ``Our thinking is, he was
disturbed with all the digging that was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   WSB's top managers seem amused, though doubtful, about the
ghost. ``I'll believe it when he comes up to me and shakes my
hand,'' declares operations manager David Lamothe.
</P>
<P>
   But the brass maintains the story about Civil War fortifications
is off-base. ``We didn't see any signs of trenches,'' says Lamothe.
``It's true there were trenches nearby, fighting here, a big battle
down at Peachtree Creek. We told everyone if they found anything to
let me know, and nobody did.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who've studied the war in Atlanta are less sure that WSB
avoided the fortifications. Franklin Garrett, 92, Atlanta's
unofficial official historian, is positive the new WSB studios were
erected on the trenches. Standing on mud churned by bulldozers
still working on the WSB site, Garrett points behind a row of
portable toilets: ``That's about where they were. That was about
the center of the outer Confederate lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Many WSB staffers have bought into the story. Janie Pope, a
secretary in the accounting department, says the General was never
heard at WSB's old building, known as White Columns. ``He must have
been aroused by something,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And, Hatcher sniffs, who cares what the doubters say?
</P>
<P>
   ``They can believe what they want,'' she says. ``He looks like a
private in the pictures, but we promoted him to general. It never
hurts to be on the good side of a ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
