<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6394 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VONFURSTENBERG02-COX     12-01 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VONFURSTENBERG02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charmed by a prince, Von Furstenberg married him
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ She's slouched way down like a kid bored in
class, nearly sliding right onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   This plopped-on-the-sofa posture is surprisingly bourgeois for
Diane Von Furstenberg _ princess, world traveler, '70s wrap-dress
creator and bearer of one of the most recognized names on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   This is her very last chat _ done, kaput, finito _ on a wearying
two-week jaunt to promote her autobiography Diane: A Signature
Life, released this month. And she's been back to her hotel just
long enough to change into a white cotton Jil Sander shirt (``it's
tailored like a man's, but it's cut for a woman'') and Romeo Gigli
striped leggings. She wears a large, rectangular diamond on her
right hand. (``I like it,'' she jokes, ``because it looks like
Barbie's ring.'') And there are still little round dents on her
earlobes, a telltale sign of clip earrings just removed. Ahhhhh.
</P>
<P>
   She resembles one of those Palm Beachers you see at the green
market downtown on Saturday mornings _ untucked, not much makeup or
jewelry, but still something that whispers rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did three television interviews this morning, and then I
spoke at the Miami Book Fair _ a big crowd, about 400 people,'' she
says, fiddling with the cap from her Aquafina water bottle. ``So,
yes, I've done the dog-and-pony show.''
</P>
<P>
   The author yawns, then sits up straight. Time to focus.
</P>
<P>
   We're in The Marlin lobby, all stainless steel and South Beach
slick. The silver sofas have big rubber wheels that look as if
they've been swiped from an industrial cart. (The hotel is owned by
her buddy Chris Blackwell, who founded Island Records _ as in U2
and Bob Marley. DVF, you see, knows everybody.)
</P>
<P>
   She says the book is more business memoir than autobiography.
But A Signature Life provides enough dish that even daughter
Tatiana found it revealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it to be inspiring for women,'' Von Furstenberg says.
``Besides, the heroine is my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Furstenberg's mom, Lily Halfin, is a Holocaust survivor who
gave birth to her only daughter in 1947, just 18 months after being
freed from a concentration camp. Her dad, Leon Halfin, spent the
war in Switzerland and married his wife in Belgium, where he
prospered in electronics. Six years later, the couple had a son,
Philippe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My childhood was perfectly happy, but I didn't particularly
enjoy being a child,'' recalls Von Furstenberg, 51. ``I never
played with toys or dolls, and I loved when people thought I was
older than I really was.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   She pauses. ``Yes, I think I would still consider it a
compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   But this grandma-to-be (her daughter-in-law, the jet-set
Alexandra Miller, is due in the spring) is nobody's bootie knitter.
Even in the sunlight, which can be unforgiving, Von Furstenberg
looks regal. Her fingernails are short and natural, but her
toenails are bright red. Plenty of spunk remains.
</P>
<P>
   In short, here's how Von Furstenberg nailed a prince and landed
in the States:
</P>
<P>
   Splits Brussels at 13 for boarding schools in Switzerland and
England.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, studies economics at the University of Geneva,
where she meets European aristocrat Prince Eduard Egon von und zu
Furstenberg at a nightclub. Isn't enthralled at first, but finds
herself attracted to his ``helplessness'' when their car gets stuck
in the snow. (``I love vulnerability in men.'')
</P>
<P>
   Egon heads to New York for training at Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Her mom gives her a plane ticket to visit him in America on her
21st birthday, and Egon introduces the slim brunette to fashion
dominatrix and Vogue editor Diana Vreeland.
</P>
<P>
   The couple marry July 1969 in Paris, DVF three months pregnant.
Lily Halfin ``liked Egon very much.'' Egon's German relatives,
however, were outraged. His father attended the wedding but ditched
the reception. (Later, with her logo attached to more than $1
billion worth of merchandise, his family grew to accept her as
``the smart Jew,'' Von Furstenberg has said.)
</P>
<P>
   They return to New York, and their first child, Alexandre, is
born six months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I was an inexperienced young girl, I was also a
European princess and embraced by the city,'' Von Furstenberg
recalls. ``It opened doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Tatiana, came along in 1970, and just two years
later, the Von Furstenbergs were on the cover of Town &AMP; Country as
``the couple who conquered New York.''
</P>
<P>
   But DVF literally made a name for herself after showing Vreeland
a few dress designs she'd been peddling around town in a suitcase.
One was a snug jersey knit deal that wrapped and tied on the side.
Conservative yet sexy. And perfect on just about any figure.
</P>
<P>
   The ``wrap dress'' would become the defining frock of the
decade, worn by suburban matrons, socialites and secretaries alike.
</P>
<P>
   (Trivia: She planned to call her fashion company Diane
Furstenberg, but jewelry designer Kenneth Jay Lane, a friend of
Egon's, said the Von added ``so much.'')
</P>
<P>
   On March 22, 1976, the cover of Newsweek featured a victorious,
wrap-dressed Von Furstenberg _ hands on her hips.
</P>
<P>
   And she hadn't even hit 30.
</P>
<P>
   Enough names, enough dates. What are the trappings of a charmed
life? What lipstick, for instance, does she wear?
</P>
<P>
   Von Furstenberg is amazingly accommodating, spilling her purse.
</P>
<P>
   Out falls a silver tube of MAC ``3-D.'' A Swiss Army knife
``that I never use,'' she says (although she carried a switchblade
in her early New York years ``that I only peeled apples with'').
Some keys, one of them a Medeco you can't duplicate without an act
of Congress. A wallet with the corner of a $50 bill sticking out. A
cell phone. Sunglasses. And two Pilot Varsity disposable fountain
pens in black.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just the most marvelous pens,'' gushes the gal with
a signature known 'round the globe. ``Here, try it. The ink just
flows. I love how it just flows. But once you're finished, you can
throw it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please keep it,'' she says, refusing to take it back. ``Of
course you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrap-dress rage faded in the late '70s, and not long after,
Von Furstenberg's label disintegrated into a handful of cheap
licensees (luggage, eye wear, kids' clothes and such).
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, she begged Wal-Mart for a chance to revive her brand,
but no dice. They considered her a has-been.
</P>
<P>
   About that same time, divorce from Egon became final after years
of separation. (She dedicates the book to her ex, though, ``who
gave me the children and the name.'') The prowling princess dated
Richard Gere, Ryan O'Neal, ``countless men who appeared on the
cover of Rolling Stone,'' she says, and even a college kid named
L.J. who's mentioned in her book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being in love,'' she says, pulling her legs under her
on the sofa. ``But to be honest, I'm afraid of really being
committed. I hate to admit this, but I fear rejection. I change
myself with every man.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children tease me. They say that I have no personality
because I'm different depending on whom I'm with.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Brazilian Paulo Fernandes, a dealer of primitive art who
lived in a bamboo beach house. She joined him in Bali and wore
cotton sarongs for 4 1/2 years. Then, in 1984, came Italian writer
Alain Elkann. She joined him in Paris and wore tweed skirts for
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a leopard-print hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, she flew back and forth to New York dabbling in
couture, cologne, cosmetics, you name it. Nothing really soared,
and her heart wasn't in it.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one constant: media mogul Barry Diller, now 56,
whom she met at a Hollywood party when she was 28. Currently the
chairman of USA Networks, he's the guy who put Fox on the map; gave
QVC its clout (including Von Furstenberg's Silk Assets line); and
is now in control of Home Shopping Network (on which DVF hawks a
private-label brand).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're intimate, we're in each other's lives, we're like
family,'' she says of their no-strings-attached amour. ``We still
may marry, who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovers, friends. Sometimes both, but always one or the other. He
adores her, period.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, to hail the end of her book tour, Diller's whisking her
away on his boat for five days.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Von Furstenberg grabbed the coattails of '70s
nostalgia and relaunched her wrap dress with a smaller, more
rounded collar and shorter length. The updated version flew off the
racks at Saks and onto the likes of Claudia Schiffer, Gwyneth
Paltrow ``and other young, hip women,'' the designer says with
glee.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in her new Diane line _ exclusively for specialty
stores _ are sporty knit separates.
</P>
<P>
   She refers to her brand as her ``third child,'' and you sense
she's at peace. At long last, she again owns her name.
</P>
<P>
   She recently opened her design firm, Diane Von Furstenberg
Studio, in a 15,000-square-foot, 19th-century building in New
York's West Village.
</P>
<P>
   Vie boheme!
</P>
<P>
   Children, Alexandre, 28, and Tatiana, 27, are doing well, too.
Her son, who married Alexandra Miller in 1995, is a New York
financier, and Tatiana's an L.A.-based writer and foster mom.
(Alexandra, by the way, is creative director of Von Furstenberg's
new venture.)
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in my life, I'm seeking coherence,'' the
designer says, brushing back her shoulder-length hair with her
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want everything to reflect who I am and to be in order
_ the books I read, the food I eat, the decors I live in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line is, Diane Von Furstenberg bounces back like one of
those blow-up punching toys. Again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, she's been well-connected along the way. But the decisions
have always been hers. Freedom, she says, is what she prizes most.
That and independence.
</P>
<P>
   Von Furstenberg stands up, slings her purse over her shoulder
and says she needs to take a walk.
</P>
<P>
   All by herself?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' she replies, heading out onto the South Beach
sidewalk. ``That's how I prefer to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
