<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Now here's a nice puzzle for those of us who
fancy ourselves First Amendment absolutists, or something so close
to it the difference hardly counts. A federal judge in Virginia, in
the first-ever such ruling, has held that a public library cannot
install computer filters to keep kids away from Internet
pornography. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ It is obvious that democracy doesn't work
everywhere, not quickly, anyway. And not without a lot of help from
the outside. Last week, a poll showed that 51 percent of Romanians
feel life was better under their previous Communist government.
(Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ It's time for Hollywood to wake up and smell
the popcorn. Or haven't they read the statistics. Our generation is
better educated and living longer than ever before - and (this is
the biggie) - we've got most of the money. Trouble is, we're not
going to spend it on junk movies that don't inspire us. (Schuett,
Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ A buddy and I were riding
around, going nowhere in particular, something we've been doing
since back in high school. ``Last Kiss'' by J. Frank Wilson was
playing on the CD. ``There's not one thing wrong with that song,''
my friend said. Such was our tribute to J. Frank Wilson, someone
we'd known since grade school. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
