<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Dec. 1, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALIEN-PRISON (San Antonio) _ Bairon Morales-Oliva is behind bars
without bail partly because of what he did _ drive drunk _ and
partly because he was born outside the United States. Officails
want to deport him because of a 1993 felony DWI conviction. A new
federal law requires immigration officials to lock up criminal
aliens while deportation proceedings wind through the system. By
MARO ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-DEATH (San Francisco) _ In what may be the nation's
largest verdict of its kind, a federal jury awarded more than $2.3
million to the family of a convicted murderer who was shot and
killed by a guard in San Quentin, the latest rebuke of the state
prison system's use of deadly force. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITIS (Albany, N.Y.) _ A blood test may have saved Lucy's
life. Last year, after a routine physical and blood test, Lucy's
doctor discovered she had elevated liver enzymes. Further tests
showed hepatitis C, a liver infection that can lead to cirrhosis,
liver cancer and liver failure. Hepatitis C kills an estimated
10,000 people annually and is the leading reason for liver
transplants in this country. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE-BROWN (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
has racked up more than 75,000 international travel miles _ perhaps
more than any of his predecessors and enough to qualify him for one
free round trip in a coach seat to his beloved Paris. By GREGORY
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIG-DIAPERS (San Antonio) _ More and more children are being
potty trained later in life, according to the firest large-scale
study of toilet training in 30 years. And the $4 billion diaper
industry is responding to _ some might say driving _ that trend,
introducing diapers that are made specifically for the huskier
toddler and the older child who is not ready to start potty
training. By CINDY RAMOS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ A lot of investors want to know how
they can protect themselves against bad advice from stockbrokers.
The stock market watchdogs have come up with a new way to help. By
PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McGEGAN-MUSIC-REVIEW (Houston) _ As music director of San
Francisco's acclaimed Philharmonia Baroque Orchestra, conductor
Nicholas McGegan is closely associated with the operas, oratorios
and concertos of the Baroque era. That his experience and musical
sympathies extend far beyond that era has been evident in his
appearances with the Houston Symphony. The latest was a charming
evening of music by Elgar, Haydn and Richard Strauss. By CHARLES
WARD.
</P>
<P>
   LOVETT-MUSIC-REVIEW (Houston) _ The Aerial Theater and the
Anderson Fair folk club are separated by a 10-minute car ride. But
that distance can sum up a career for many musicians. Lyle Lovett,
one of the handful of Houston-based artists to successfully
complete the jump to national touring act, led a full house of new
and old fans back across that great divide at the Aerial. By RICK
MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   FUNNYGIRL-THEATER-REVIEW (Houston) _ Every musical contains a
make-or-break moment early on that indicates whether the show will
fly or fall. In ``Funny Girl,'' the classic backstage musical based
on the life of entertainer Fanny Brice, it's the title character's
first song, ``I'm the Greatest Star.'' By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-INJURY (San Francisco) _ Ken Norton said he wasn't
sure how Bryant Young fractured his right leg Monday night. He said
he just remembered a collision, and ``a scream I'll never forget.''
It was the kind of scream football players know almost
instinctively, the kind they know can erode their own will to keep
playing this dangerous game if they get too close or stay too long.
By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-RICE (San Francisco) _ Jerry Rice made a great cutback
move on Monday night. He was wearing a gray flannel suit and a
bright smile when he did it. ``This might be the season I have to
play a different role,'' he said in the locker room after the 49ers
beat the New York Giants, 31-7. ``You've got to swallow deep and
live with it.'' By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Pope John Paul II has issued a
papal bull proclaiming 2000 a Holy Year, and prescribing good works
and penitence to be done that year. The pope also said Catholics
could give up smoking or drinking for a day and obtain an
``indulgence'' to get on the fast track into heaven. Due to the
rigors of being a San Francisco columnist, I've given up drinking
for a day many times _ sincerely, as the bull specifies. Now it
qualifies me for the express line to heaven. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The comment by a lawyer
representing one of two cops accused of beating up a suspect in
handcuffs compared John Dorfman, the special prosecutor in the
case, to Kenneth Starr. Apparently, from now on, whenever a
prosecutor does his job vigorously _ whenever a prosecutor does
anything but roll over and play dead in any criminal case _ he can
expect to be likened to Ken Starr. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
