<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     12-01 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG-ADULT READERS NEED BETTER BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many years ago I read in, I believe, Reader's Digest, a critical
article written by, I believe, Clifton Fadiman, titled, I believe,
``The Decline of Attention.'' The decline was in attention to
literature, more specifically toward ``serious'' fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Fadiman or otherwise, was confident that the
impending death of seriously constituted fiction was a myth, and
gave evidence that such rumors had been alive for more than a
century. I was consoled then; but now I believe the decline is
real, has already happened, is near to bottoming out.
</P>
<P>
   When that article appeared, television was with us, but only in
a minority of American homes, and in fewer homes elsewhere.
Television had not taken over our lives, had not gained absolute
dominion over children.
</P>
<P>
   In today's educational environment, children still learn to
read, and there is statistical indication that they read with
better facility than did earlier youth cycles. That's good, of
course, because high literacy is mandatory for progress in the
business and professional pursuits of adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   But reading for pleasure? Reading for pleasure and
enlightenment? Reading for artistic appreciation? That's where the
``decline'' is marked so sourly.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive me for sounding, inevitably, like one of those
``everything was better in my day'' codgers. But if things weren't
better, they sure were different.
</P>
<P>
   Look out on the streets today, and in front and back yards and
vacant lots. How many children are out playing? In summer, I played
baseball, tossed footballs in autumn, shot baskets the year 'round;
and there always were pick-up games to get into in all sports. I
even got in on the last gasp of marbles as a popular activity for
boys. I was never sure what girls did, apart from the neuterless
games they played with us _ kick-the-can or whatever _ but girls
were outside, too; and when we all went indoors, we all read, and
we read good fiction.
</P>
<P>
   This was a discussion topic among contemporaries at a high
school class reunion. All of us read then; and almost all of us
read today _ for pleasure and enlightenment and artistic
satisfaction _ but now we're the grandparent generation that isn't
``with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet our little grandchildren also read. Picture books have
magnetic pull for them; and secure in their comprehension of the
elementary stories, they enjoy demonstrating their reading skill.
Small children can have their books and television, too.
</P>
<P>
   But when they're older _ no longer small but not yet big _
reading loses out. Adolescents forsake reading for pleasure simply
because there isn't pleasure in sufficient degree. They aren't
regaled, aren't captivated by what they're reading. I can't blame
them.
</P>
<P>
   The failure, I believe, is in what may be termed transitional
literature. Books for children are unmistakable, as are books for
adults. But there is a nebulous in-between; and the dilemma is
compounded by publishers on the one hand, and educators on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Over three professional decades I have monitored the realm of
``young adult'' fiction, sometimes specified for ages 10 to 14, and
occasionally for the 13-to-16 age group. With few exceptions, these
books are insults to juvenile imagination and curiosity. Hardly any
YA titles remain in print very long, or otherwise hold value for
chasing those well-known puberty blues.
</P>
<P>
   Adolescents well-oiled for reading may do much better _ and
experience high adventure _ by going directly to adult fare. It's a
noble challenge for their sophistication. Rather than writing down
to them, we should push them to read ``up'' _ taking on not the
schlock genres but the classics and serious, relevant contemporary
fiction. The likelihood is of their finding that the novel on its
best artistic behavior truly is what D.H. Lawrence called it _ the
``bright book of life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
