<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-VISIT-WASHIN     12-01 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-VISIT-WASHINGTON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 Nawaz Sharif's Visit: The View From Islamabad  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.)  By NASIM ZEHRA  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ISLAMABAD _ Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who took
office in February 1997, arrives in Washington this week a
confident and hopeful man.
 &HT;    At home, the stark economic crisis prompted by the May nuclear
testing is somewhat under control _ at least for now. Politically,
Sharif faces no imminent threat from traditional political forces,
including Pakistan's former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto.
 &HT;    An opposition bloc struggling to mount an anti-Nawaz Sharif
political offensive has failed to capitalize on his blunders
including his introduction of the highly controversial Islamic
``shariah'' law. Sharif has even managed to establish
constitutional control over the army and the judiciary.
 &HT;    So now, in Washington, Sharif hopes to benefit from the ``sole
player'' position he currently occupies in Pakistani politics.
 &HT;    A great believer in conducting official business in a
personalized style, the Pakistani leader is pinning hopes on his
recent intensive and candid contacts with Bill Clinton. Beginning
with the May 17 Indian nuclear tests, Sharif and Clinton have
conducted at least six telephone calls and exchanged at least a
dozen letters. The two have also met twice during the 1997 and 1998
U.N. General Assembly sessions.
 &HT;    With this background, Sharif and Pakistan's Foreign Office team
expect that the ``summit'' will lead to progress on four issues.
 &HT;    _ First , on the economic front. Islamabad is banking on some
American largesse to help Pakistan 's economic recovery.
 &HT;    _ Second, on the military front. Pakistan's armed forces are
greatly handicapped by the ban imposed under the 1990 Pressler
Amendment on the supply of military equipment and military spare
parts. Since the United States has remained a virtual sole supplier
for Pakistan's conventional weapons, non-availability of spare
parts, including those for its F-16 fighters and air force radar
systems, further aggravate an imbalance of conventional weapons in
India's favor.
 &HT;    Sharif hopes the U.S. establishment will lift the sanctions
under Pressler. Indeed, an optimistic Sharif told journalists in
Islamabad on Nov. 25 that Washington would lift military sanctions
realizing their ``futility.'' However, striking a warning note for
Washington's non-proliferationists, he added that if the imbalance
in conventional weaponry continued, ``Pakistan would have to rely
on its nuclear capability.''
 &HT;    Significantly, in also maintaining that ``most problems will be
solved and there would be forward movement on other issues if this
imbalance is rectified,'' Nawaz Sharif linked progress in the
Pakistani-U.S. strategic relationship and in peace and stability in
South Asia to Washington's decision to lift military sanctions.
 &HT;    _ Third, on the Kashmir front. Having observed a substantial
policy shift in Washington on the Kashmir issue, Sharif expects
Clinton to signal American willingness to mediate between Pakistan
and India for the settlement of the bloody war. Unlike its
pre-nuclear-test position, in which Washington viewed Kashmir as a
problem created by Pakistan-supported terrorists and by India's
denial of democratic rights to the Kashmiris, Washington now sees
the flashpoint as a major international issue which needs to be
addressed bilaterally and internationally.
 &HT;    With much satisfaction, the Pakistanis observe that global
players ranging from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to the
chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement, Nelson Mandela, and Clinton
himself all recognize that only settlement of Kashmir can establish
genuine peace in the region, promote non-proliferation and avert a
nuclear war in South Asia.
 &HT;    What perhaps has remained unpublicized is the fact that after
the Palestinian-Israeli Wye River Accord was signed in late October
1998, Clinton received a letter from the Pakistani prime minister
urging him to play a similar role in the Kashmir tragedy. Sharif
told Clinton he was destined to play a historic role in resolving
the Kashmir issue and that he was morally obliged to play an active
role.
 &HT;    _ Finally, Islamabad is hoping that Washington will propose an
``acceptable solution'' to the F-16 issue. Islamabad has repeatedly
indicated to the Americans that an acceptable solution is either
the return of almost $500 million that Pakistan paid for 26 F-16
planes or their delivery.
 &HT;    American officials who already have pleaded an inability to do
either are, however, proposing a debt draw-down against the arrears
incurred by Pakistan from various credit lines opened for it to
import wheat. This year alone half a million metric tons of wheat
have been imported. But this debt-retirement option has been
repeatedly rejected by Pakistan.
 &HT;    In Islamabad, officials maintain that Pakistan is under no
pressure to settle the American loans which are made available on
easy terms for more than a 25-year term.
 &HT;    Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed has told his counterpart, U.S.
Under-Secretary Strobe Talbott, that such an offer is
``unacceptable to Pakistan both economically and militarily.''
 &HT;    Washington has its own concerns. Primarily Clinton would hope to
get some concrete date from the visiting prime minister for the
signing of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, or CTBT, and
similarly, dates for when Pakistan's Parliament would legislate
nuclear-technology export controls laws.
 &HT;    Clinton has in a Nov. 6 letter to Nawaz Sharif spelled out the
American expectation that Pakistan make concrete movement on the
nuclear non-proliferation front. This would justify Clinton's
decision days ago to lift some sanctions on Pakistan in the
aftermath of the nuclear tests.
 &HT;    There is another issue on which Clinton will specially focus:
Osama bin Laden. Washington, having failed even after the Aug. 20
deployment of its latest batch of Tomahawk cruise missiles to bring
death to bin Laden, who is suspected of masterminding the August
bombings of U.S. embassies in Africa, is now seeking Pakistan's
help to acquire his capture. Clearly, however, the Pakistani prime
minister has neither the ability nor the inclination to plead
America's case with the Taliban of Afghanistan, where bin Laden
lives.
 &HT;    Yet, standing at the threshold of the new millennium, a nuclear
Pakistan, many believe, should go the distance to articulate the
basis of Pakistan-U.S. relations in terms of genuinely shared
interests. Today, in the post-Cold War era, these go beyond the
mindset of the '50s, '60s and '80s when the projection of
Pakistan's strategic significance referred only to Washington's
agenda _ whether it be anti-Arab nationalist, anti-communist or
anti-fundamentalist Islam. Instead, the common interests would
include peace in South Asia, regional economic development, nuclear
nonproliferation and peace and stability on the subcontinent.
 &HT;    As a country located at the crossroads of four key political,
economic and civilization zones _ Central Asia, South Asia,
Southwest Asia and China _ Pakistan enjoys a multi-civilizational
identity. It could be a natural breeding ground for cooperation and
cross-civilizational harmony.
 &HT;    Instead of perpetuating an ethos of servitude, presenting
Pakistan for the use of the West as a readily available ``link,''
Nawaz Sharif should invite Washington into a real partnership
relationship. How attractive a partner Pakistan proves to be
depends inevitably on the home realities of economics, security and
politics.
 &HT;    For the United States, which still operates in the largely
troubled zone with Muslim countries ranging from Iraq to Iran and
from Sudan to Afghanistan, Washington needs to judiciously
cultivate bilateral relations with Pakistan. For it is one Muslim
country that remains genuinely engaged with the others.
 &HT;    Instead of sounding like a Washington protege offering
cooperation with Washington's agenda of human rights, narcotics
control and anti-terrorism, Nawaz Sharif in Washington is in a
position to offer real partnership to Clinton in defining and
promoting the agenda of human progress and global security.
 &HT;     c.1998 Nasim Zehra 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Nasim Zehra is a syndicated columnist based in Islamabad,
Pakistan.)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
