<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6659 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POVERTY-LATIN-AMERICA     12-01 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POVERTY-LATIN-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATISTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 LESSONS IN POVERTY, or, A LOOK BEHIND THOSE `MIRACLE' ECONOMY &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELLIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.) 
 &HT;    
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago I went to Cartagena de Indias to lecture at a
seminar for journalists on the theme of poverty in Latin America. A
dozen reporters participated _ from countries as diverse as
Guatemala and Bolivia, Argentina and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   My turn to speak was at siesta time, at an hour when Cartagena
is so humid and hot that no dog is seen on the streets nor birds in
the thick yellow sky. Nothing of what I said was important, but
what we heard was enough to keep us not only awake, but full of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   First, two lecturers from the Interamerican Development Bank
proved, with numbers and statistics, that the various free-market
reforms in the region were not as bad as they seemed: education and
health, for instance, had improved slightly.
</P>
<P>
   They did point out that inequality and corruption have worsened,
and by now seem to be endemic woes. Among the nine countries most
affected by official corruption, the statistics show, five are
Latin American. The number rises to six if Haiti is included, but
it seems that all statistics from that country are as mysterious
and inscrutable as voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   I also learned that one clear tragedy is the growth of
unemployment. Ten years ago it was shameful that up to 10 percent
of workers didn't have a job. Now this rate is nearly double and
governments seem incapable of solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The answers were complex _ the obvious need for productive
employment was a quickly discarded idea. Productive jobs are not
possible, the journalists agreed, when what really counts in the
work market is not efficiency, but political patronage, paying back
favors and being allied with those who have power. Another salient
fact: the mass migration of the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Every reporter was able to present at least one example of
extravagant or inexplicable spending in places where misery was
rampant: great airports and wide freeways that end at the foot of
local political strongmen's homes, first-rate hospitals in lost
villages where there are no doctors, five-star hotels built in
inaccessible deserts.
</P>
<P>
   But the true tragedies of poverty were discussed later in the
day. One of the most moving was narrated by a Bolivian journalist:
the hopeless condition of families in the garbage dumps of
Cochabamba, where whole neighborhoods of houses are built with
cardboard and plastic bags. The principal means of survival is the
scavenged plastic waste people sell to factories, earning about $1
per day.
</P>
<P>
   In these neighborhoods, nurses at the small clinic or female
nursery school teachers earn less than a beggar: about $45 per
month. Almost all of them had better jobs in the past _ in
electronics factories that closed, in tin mines that ran out, in
banks that failed.
</P>
<P>
   In Bolivia, as in the other countries of Latin America, state
reform may have restored the statistics and appearance of health to
national economies and revived the confidence of those
all-important foreign investors, but there is chaos among the lower
classes. Most people who lose their jobs are never able to return
to their former status.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox is that the opposite is happening in the United
States. Here the economy is healthier every day, the boom times are
felt in the very air of the cities and employment is a very serious
problem, but only because there are too many jobs and not enough
people to fill them.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the manager of a large bookstore chain told me it's
difficult to find salespeople for their new outlets. Everybody has
other things to do, and $25,000 annual salaries aren't enough to
attract many people.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the news of this economic boom is spreading like
wildfire in Latin America and migrants are turning the U.S.
frontier with Mexico into a curtain of sand.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why the story that most impressed us in Cartagena's
seminar was the one told by a woman reporter from Puebla, Mexico.
She spoke about the odyssey of Felix Sanchez, a peasant from
Piaxtla who arrived in Los Angeles without immigration documents
and worked in a small electrical lamp factory while his wife worked
at home as a seamstress.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of hard labor and suffering, he managed to save
$12,000 and bought a machine to make tortillas so he could sell
them door to door in the homes of the city's Mexican community.
Now, 20 years later, Sanchez owns a strong company, Puebla Foods,
with annual sales of $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago he tried to take his good luck back to
Mexico and worked to establish a chile canning factory in Piaxtla.
He couldn't do it, though, because the town's road infrastructure
is abominable and everything that's produced in the region _ which
is still racked by poverty _ stays there.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are crowds of immigrants on the streets of New York,
Chicago, Boston or Boulder _ not to mention Los Angeles and Miami.
Even the Latin Americans most proud of their national culture, such
as Brazilians and Venezuelans, are running away by the thousands
toward the North, and with a frightening desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they are coming to collect everything we took from them,''
the bookstore manager told me, with a clear irony. Nevertheless,
nothing of what was taken from us in the past _ if that is anything
at all _ has the immense value of what is being offered now: the
people.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America has lived for more than five centuries in a state
of poverty. The one that's starting now, with its great exodus to
the North, may be the worst privation of all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
