<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUICK WAY TO HEAVEN IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pope John Paul II has issued a papal bull
proclaiming 2000 a Holy Year, and prescribing good works and
penitence to be done that year. The rich can help the poor, the
free can help the incarcerated, and the church can seek forgiveness
for past errors.
</P>
<P>
   The pope also said Catholics could give up smoking or drinking
for a day and obtain an ``indulgence'' to get on the fast track
into heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, an indulgence gives you time off from purgatory for
good behavior. Purgatory and indulgences, by the way, are
inventions of the medieval church and not mentioned in Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   The clause about getting an indulgence for a day without tobacco
or beer was down in the fine print of the papal bull, but naturally
it became the lead of all the newspaper stories. You can see why it
appeals to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Due to the rigors of being a newspaper columnist in San
Francisco, I've given up drinking for a day many times _ sincerely,
as the bull specifies. Now it qualifies me for the express line to
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that simple, of course. Nothing is in theology. But
what's the waiting period for becoming a Catholic?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton must be sorry he's a Baptist and has to go around
apologizing, asking forgiveness and getting spiritual counseling
from Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Think of all the things he can give up for a day, even those
things he doesn't inhale. Of course, no amount of indulgences will
release him from the purgatory of Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The only people this papal bull doesn't reward are those who
have nothing to give up. Sorry, but vegetarian, Evian-swilling
joggers will have to go to San Quentin and skid row to visit
prisoners and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   After Roman Catholic services on Sunday, indulgences were all
the talk. One nun who has served the church for five decades (and
obviously must remain anonymous) said: ``Oh, God. I hate it when
they do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Once more, Catholics have to face doubt, and ironically because
of a document written by the remarkable John Paul II. Maybe someone
tinkered with the fine print of the appendix when he was finished.
</P>
<P>
   This is the pope who in 1991 asked the affluent to find
fellowship with the poor, and true meaning in life, by escaping the
``web of false and superficial gratifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, unfortunately, he'll be known as the inventor of the
one-day, one-step stairway to heaven plan. That isn't fair, and
getting to heaven isn't that easy in Catholic doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   As I understand them, indulgences give people time off from
suffering in this life or purgatory as purification for sins
already forgiven in confession. Many liberal Catholics see them as
an anachronism. It's been decades since they've talked about
purgatory or counted indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   They see them as brownie points, and don't want to go back to
the pre-Vatican II days of amassing them toward escape from
purgatory. Or putting them toward other souls stuck in purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   Does God know about these get-out-of-purgatory-free cards? And
does Windows have an indulgence-tabulation spreadsheet?
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II is the greatest champion of the poor on Earth.
His effort to get believers, rich and middle class, to attend to
the poor on the 2,000th birthday of Christ is to be cheered.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I don't get any of this. Here I admit being from a
family that's half lapsed Catholic and half lapsed Protestant. I
have little background in theology or even Sunday school. But I
have always admired the good works of the Catholic Church, and
stand in awe of the spirit and intellect of John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't people care for the poor because they want to, not
because they want an indulgence? The pope has taught that a
spiritual transformation must be willed, and is its own reward.
</P>
<P>
   And why give people the easy way out of giving up smoking or
drinking for a day? Lent takes longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16th century the church often sold indulgences, offering
access to heaven the way modern campaign contributors get access to
politicians. The sale of indulgences _ and later, indulgences
themselves _ was Martin Luther's biggest complaint against the
church, ultimately leading to the Protestant Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   Over-indulging in indulgences seems like an odd way to celebrate
2000. It's like looking back one millennium to the Middle Ages
instead of two millennia to the birth of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, I'm not knocking the Catholic Church. I guess I'm just
envious.
</P>
<P>
   If I could escape purgatory by giving up one vice for a day, I'd
do it _ that is, if I believed in purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this is modern neo-puritanical America, and we're
supposed to give up drinking and smoking for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what they say. The first lifetime is the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
