<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE OLDEN DAYS, WE HAD TO WALK TO SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to my sons, I'm ancient.
</P>
<P>
   I'm practically in heaven's waiting room. They can't even
understand how I survived my youth in the prehistoric era without a
cellular phone or a microwave.
</P>
<P>
   When I remind them that we didn't have cable television either,
they literally shudder. Isn't it ironic? I reacted the same way
when my mother told me she attended a school without air
conditioning and her family's telephone had a party line. Imagine
trying to have a conversation with the constant interruption of
other people attempting to use the line. Come to think of it, with
call-waiting, three-way calling, call-forwarding, caller-ID, and
conference calling, we still have party lines!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, whenever my boys start in on me about the ``olden
days,'' I always recall the statement that Bernard Baruch made on
his 85th birthday in 1955. He said, ``To me, old age is always 15
years older than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many young adults, I aggressively collected birthdays,
longing for maturity yet still thought that I would be young
forever. Now my sons' friends call me ``ma'am,'' and the only time
I'm ever asked to show ID is to prove that I haven't stolen a
credit card. Yes, life is indeed ironic.
</P>
<P>
   Some evenings when my kids are really bored, they ask me to tell
them a scary story about the olden days. We turn out the lights and
sit in the middle of the floor with a candle. As the flame casts
eerie shadows on my face, I begin, ``Long, long, ago _ back in the
early '70s ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooooo!'' they moan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ssshhh!'' I say. ``I haven't gotten to the scary part yet.
Every weekday, me and my friend Pam, would wake up at 6 in the
morning, dress, eat breakfast, and walk to school!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, you walked all the way from grandma's house to that
school on the other side of town?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was almost a full mile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where were the buses?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no buses. We didn't even have backpacks. We just
carried all 20 of our heavy books in our hands as we trudged
through the rain, sleet, and snow. And if our books got wet, the
teacher would punish us by making us beat the chalk out of the
erasers until we sneezed.''
</P>
<P>
   They start to look skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, you grew up in Fort Worth. It never snows around here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't anymore. They stopped it with those satellites, but
back then it snowed year 'round. Plus, when we got home, we had to
wash the dishes by hand and sweep the carpet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding!?''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, we had a vacuum cleaner, but it was really heavy.
Sometimes I just swept the carpet with a broom to make it look like
I had vacuumed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, Mom, how did you ever survive without a VCR or video
games?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We read a lot of books and talked to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really? That sounds totally boring. Aren't you glad that
things are so much better now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but sometimes I wish for the days when I could run
around in my bare feet all summer long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No kidding? With those feet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooooo! That is scary!''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
