<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   This is a test from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6717 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CHILES02-COX     12-01 2300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CHILES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't expect Walkin' Lawton to slow down
 &HT;    (Resending to fix garble.)
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Klas
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _Just hours before Lawton Chiles was to face
Jeb Bush in the only televised debate of the 1994 governor's race,
the governor of Florida played hooky on his handlers.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign staff had assembled at his Tampa hotel with mock
questions to warm him up for a feisty debate against his younger,
more telegenic challenger.
</P>
<P>
   But Chiles slipped out for a few hours and got ice cream. It was
vintage Chiles, breaking schedule to give himself some thinking
time and do something he really enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   That night, in what is considered the defining moment of his
final campaign, he delivered this line: ``The old he-coon walks
just before the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people understood what he meant _ he clearly confounded Bush
_ but the phrase crystallized the folk-hero image Chiles had
developed during four decades in public office. The line gave him
new momentum and he defeated Bush in the closest gubernatorial
election ever in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   No Florida politician has captured the imagination of the
electorate longer than Lawton Mainor Chiles Jr., first a state
representative, then a state senator, U.S. senator and, finally,
the state's 41st governor.
</P>
<P>
   His Cracker expressions were foreign to many who understood
little about the ways of old Florida. Yet the same man who wore a
coonskin cap and fired a potato gun at his second inauguration also
used his 1997 State of the State address to call attention to brain
research and the importance of a healthy early childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The avid outdoorsman who chews tobacco and hunts turkeys also
spent every ounce of his political capital to fend off a
legislative assault on a state lawsuit against the nation's
cigarette giants. The victory will reap $13 billion for Florida
during the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   When Chiles retires in January at age 68 and hands over his
command to Bush, he will end a 40-year political career that began
when Eisenhower was president and Bush was in first grade. It will
be the end to a job he never expected to have but enjoyed more than
any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 10 times better than being in the (U.S.) Senate,''
Chiles said recently, referring to the job of his boyhood dreams,
which he quit in 1988 out of frustration. ``The game doesn't start
until you blow the whistle and if you don't like something in the
main ring, you can start something somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles was good at starting fights. He forced legislators to
focus on children's issues, government reform, managed care,
welfare reform and tobacco litigation long before most other
politicians were ready to talk about them.
</P>
<P>
   His skills made admirers out of many Republicans, even political
opponents. Florida Republican Party leader Tom Slade called him a
clever strategist whose political timing and instincts are ``the
best I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Smith, former Florida secretary of state who unsuccessfully
sought the Republican nomination for governor in 1994, believes
Chiles ``will be a legend in Florida politics,'' and, ``because of
the tobacco settlement, will be recognized nationally as a governor
that gave that issue prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chiles never lost an election, he did lose his share of
battles. Faced with a recession in 1991 that forced $2 billion in
budget cuts, Chiles accelerated his government reform efforts and
was compelled to seek tax reform earlier than he had planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my head handed to me,'' Chiles recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of cronyism pained him
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to abandon a sweeping health insurance reform when
legislators refused to give it a hearing. And his image was
tarnished by multiple allegations of political cronyism and charges
that his 1994 campaign was behind a smear campaign that used
misleading phone calls to senior citizens to frighten them away
from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in what is perhaps the most paradoxical failure, this
popular and influential governor leaves office with his party in
such disrepair that he may be the last Democratic governor for a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the last of the true Southern Democrats in
Florida,'' said David Colburn, a history professor at the
University of Florida and a gubernatorial scholar. He believes
Chiles belongs alongside Leroy Collins, Reubin Askew and Bob Graham
as moderate Democrats whose progressive policies and political
skills left lasting change.
</P>
<P>
   But Chiles' shortcoming ``is not recognizing and not doing
enough to ensure his party's viability,'' Colburn said.
</P>
<P>
   When Chiles began his political career in 1958, he registered as
a Democrat out of sheer convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, there was sort of a no-party situation in
Florida,'' Chiles recalled. ``As Republicans slowly became more of
a factor, they were always more disciplined, more organized.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Democrats had no unified message. Their top
officials were elected on the sheer strength of their personality
and often sounded like Republicans. What's more, Democrats had
failed to groom proteges.
</P>
<P>
   So when former U.S. Rep. Buddy MacKay persuaded Chiles in 1990
to step out of retirement and run for governor, the Democratic
dream team was created with recycled talent. Its success delayed
the Republican takeover of Florida government, but did not stop it.
(The Florida Legislature went Republican in 1996 and Bush won the
governor's race this year, signaling the first complete takeover in
more than a century.)
</P>
<P>
   Chiles simply didn't believe that invigorating the party was his
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the only person that could have had the coordination to
make the organization work,'' said Buzz Ritchie, former House
Democratic leader. ``It wasn't a priority for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawton Chiles is a study in contrasts. He always seemed aware of
nuances regarding dozens of issues that swirled around him each
day. But he was never able to say much about them spontaneously.
Pundits alternately described him as vague and befuddled or folksy
and charming. All fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' said Doug Cook, his former Washington aide
whom Chiles named head of his Agency for Health Care
Administration, ``he's not a new-age communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   Gump skit stumped him
</P>
<P>
   During the 1995 press skits, an Orlando Sentinel reporter
portrayed Chiles as Forrest Gump, the movie character whose
simpleness was perceived as wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the skit, Rhea Chiles turned to her husband and
whispered: ``Honey, you're Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredulous, Chiles whispered back: ``I'm not that dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhea replied: ``You're not that smart either.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles never came across as an intellectual, but most who have
worked with him say he has a swiftness of thought, a shrewd sense
of the public and an understanding of government that made him a
formidable leader.
</P>
<P>
   A consistent rap on Chiles among Tallahassee lobbyists and
lawmakers is that he is detached, uninterested in details. But
those who have worked closely with him say that was how Chiles kept
people from bombarding him with arguments when he wanted those
conversations to be handled by staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has won more than one battle by having someone
underestimate him,'' said Dan Stengle, Chiles' general counsel.
``It doesn't bother him a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final State of the State speech in March, Chiles ended
his remarks with this advice: ``The best way to achieve leadership
is to learn more about your subject than anyone else and to work
harder. . . . Be bold _ dare to look foolish. Reach beyond your
grasp and go beyond the path you can see.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents ingrained values
</P>
<P>
   Chiles was reared during World War II in Lakeland by a father
who worked on the railroad and a deeply religious mother. They
ingrained in him the values that have guided his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles believes that, to follow his faith, he has a spiritual
and moral obligation to serve others, said Cook, his long-time
aide. The governor regularly conducts a Bible class for a small
group of friends and staff, often assigning them readings. And he
keeps a worn, leather-bound Holy Bible in his small, private
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a much more religious man than he ever lets you know,''
said Dexter Douglass, his former law school buddy who was his
general counsel in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's upbringing also inspired a profound sense of
loyalty to his friends, a virtue some of his staff admit has been
his Achilles' heel. His willingness to overlook the faults of his
friends produced some of his most trying days. He was forced to
withdraw the nomination of a hunting buddy and political activist,
Joe Bruner, from the game commission after it was revealed Bruner
had been cited for hunting without a license. He was chided for
accepting dozens of plane rides from friends, most of them hunting
partners, without reporting them as gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But his most painful experience was his decision to fire one of
his dearest friends, his chief inspector general, Harold Lewis,
whom he had known since they met at Boys State. The Florida
Department of Law Enforcement had begun investigating Lewis when
questions surfaced about loans between him and a private lawyer
working on the tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Firing friend hurt him deeply
</P>
<P>
   The incident ``broke his heart,'' said Mallory Horne, a longtime
friend and adviser to Chiles. ``He just didn't talk about it. It's
like none of that ever existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was one of many longtime friends Chiles hired to work in
the top jobs of his administration. ``He wanted people he could
trust,'' Douglass explained. Public service was the greatest
calling to Chiles, ``He walked the line between total loyalty to
his friends and his loyalty to government.''
</P>
<P>
   When life in Tallahassee got too intense, Chiles would get back
on the road, his staff said, where he learned from his now-famous
walk across the state in 1970 that he could get direction,
inspiration and energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have him in the office too long, it shows,'' said April
Herrle, the governor's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes getting on the road meant getting behind the wheel.
Before he was first inaugurated, Chiles was caught going 80 mph in
a 50-mph zone driving his red Sterling through Bainbridge, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   With Chiles in his old hunting clothes, the officer didn't
believe him when Chiles said he was Florida's new governor. The
officer's response to the news: He gave Chiles a Breathalyzer test.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of many ``car incidents,'' which have prompted
Rhea Chiles to quip: ``I always said he had to start walking
because nobody wanted him to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone so energized by people, Chiles is, by most accounts,
a solitary man.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loner among thousands,'' observed Horne.
</P>
<P>
   Craves solitude of preserve
</P>
<P>
   Chiles spends much of his private time time hunting and fishing,
often at his 209-acre hunting preserve west of Tallahassee, called
Chemonie. The place became somewhat of a pauper's Camp David for
Chiles, a back-to-nature refuge from the relentless demands of the
office, equipped with only a one-room log cabin and a cook shack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't like to talk much when he's out there,'' said
Horne, who often accompanied Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   He loves turkey hunting but he won't shoot the turkeys on his
land. When he bags his prey, he is known to put them directly into
the mansion freezer, feathers and all, and is fond of cooking it
himself.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite snack is icebox cookies, a spice cookie he insists
be made using his mother's recipe. He also loves coarse grits and
Cuban food. He also acquired an enduring taste for sushi while
serving as an Army artillery officer in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles is best known among his friends as a practical joker for
his famous ``gotchas.'' When President Clinton had dinner at the
mansion, Chiles arranged to have a server return a full plate of
food to the kitchen to make his worried chef think it was the
president's.
</P>
<P>
   And when former press secretary Ron Sachs was losing sleep over
allowing the governor to don a flak jacket in front of television
cameras while touring Miami in the wake of a series of tourist
shootings, Chiles convened a meeting of the state's top law
enforcement officials and had them all wear flak jackets when Sachs
walked into the room.
</P>
<P>
   During eight years as governor, Chiles has remained lean and
lanky. His once-sandy hair is now solidly silver. His round
shoulders have gotten a bit more stooped. He now wears a tiny
hearing aid in his right ear. He is off Prozac, the anti-depressant
he took after leaving the U.S. Senate in a bout of depression. But
he keeps a vigorous schedule that begins at dawn on his stationary
bike and continues long after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles has preferred not to speculate on his legacy, except to
say that he hopes politicians will fight over who among them can do
better for children. He and Rhea have bought a home on 40 acres
north of town and renovated it, complete with a bird observation
window.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles plans to enjoy his last month at the Governor's Mansion.
His four children and their families joined him and Rhea for
Thanksgiving there and the first couple has lined up more than a
dozen goodbye events at the mansion for staff, colleagues and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he doesn't know what he'll do when he retires. His
friends expect him to extend a hand of friendship to Bush and stay
active in children's issues.
</P>
<P>
   But many are worried he won't be busy enough.
</P>
<P>
   Said Horne: ``I don't even think he'll be able to stand it for a
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Klas writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
