<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ANTARTCTIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIARIES, PHOTOS BRING INTIMACY TO SURVIVAL TALE OF ENDURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Caroline Alexander happened upon the unbelievable true
story of Ernest Shackleton's Antarctic expedition and, like so many
before her, became enthralled, even obsessed. She read one book on
the expedition, then another, then another, all in growing wonder
at how the entire 28-man expedition managed to endure nearly two
years amid the ice and cold and storms, and still survive.
</P>
<P>
   The pack ice that froze their ship in place did not defeat
Shackleton and his men. Nor did the final crushing of their beloved
144-foot Endurance by the relentless grinding force of the moving
ice. Nor did the tempest-tossed seas they had to cross in three
lifeboats to reach a rocky sliver of land called Elephant Island,
the first ground under their feet in 497 days.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the hurricane that their stalwart party of six,
including Shackleton, encountered when they set out for help from a
whaling station that was 800 miles away across the most perilous
seas on Earth during the dead of winter, with their only hope for
survival resting on the fate of a 22-foot boat called the James
Caird.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a 42-year-old former Rhodes Scholar, was so moved by
the Shackleton story that she wrote one book for children, from the
perspective of the ship's cat, then convinced the American Museum
of Natural History in New York to mount an exhibition with the
stunning photographs of crew member Frank Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so amazing about the Shackleton expedition,''
Alexander said yesterday in Seattle, ``is this was a real trial by
fire, a visit to the dark night of the soul, the sort of test of
character that almost no one encounters. And yet none of these
randomly selected men came out debased or much worse off than how
they set out. It is a tribute to real human character, something
that would be hard to replicate, or probably impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's immersion in the Shackleton story, which has already
consumed three years of her life, is not about to stop soon. She
has just published a new Shackleton book to accompany the museum
exhibition, and it will be followed by at least a year's work on
writing and co-producing a PBS-TV documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Her new book, ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic
Expedition'' (Alfred A. Knopf, 212 pages, $29.95), is a chilling
and inspiring testament to the instinct for survival and the power
of human unity. Alexander's spare, yet evocative 55,000 words of
prose recapture the expedition in a page-turning narrative with a
distinct late 20th-century sensibility. It is accompanied by the
largest published collection of Hurley's photographs, unforgettable
images of Shackleton and his men, often tiny dark figures on a
great white icescape.
</P>
<P>
   The Shackleton expedition story has been retold many times
before and often very well, including Shackleton's own account,
``South,'' which is considered a classic. And the story will be
told again, not only in the documentary that Alexander is doing,
but also in a film next year directed by Wolfgang Peterson of ``Das
Boot.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither the past accounts of Shackleton's 1914-1916
expedition, or possible future accounts, daunted the self-aware
Alexander when she sat down to write her own book at the behest of
the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole amazing story _ you approach it with complete
humility, or you don't bother to do anything with it at all,'' she
summarized. ``The story has existed, the facts have existed, so
your task is to assemble from what is there and what you can find.
This story is so epic that I made a determination very early on to
let the story write itself as much as possible. That's why I use
the men's diaries so much instead of paraphrasing them. I had no
illusions about my own role.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Alexander's modesty is somewhat misleading. She did manage
to unearth two prime nuggets of new research for her book, an
unpublished diary by one crew member and an unpublished
autobiography by another. And her crusading on behalf of Hurley's
remarkable work is bringing long-overdue attention to
photojournalism performed under the direst personal circumstances
that ultimately produced documentary art.
</P>
<P>
   That the photographer himself had to rescue his glass plate
negatives while bare-chested in 4 feet of icy slush in the dark
hold of the sinking ship only adds to the mythic aura surrounding
the expedition. So does the fact that the negatives were too heavy
to transport across the ice floes, which forced Hurley to spend a
day scanning all his shots and then throwing out 400 of his 520
negatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This unfortunate reduction is essential,'' Hurley wrote in his
diary, a statement displaying the sort of resigned resolve that
Shackleton and his men exhibited, time and again.
</P>
<P>
   One of the particular strengths of Alexander's account is the
way she has captured the entire 28-man expedition, which hoped to
accomplish the first land crossing of Antarctica. She provides
telling portraits of both the famous and the little remembered,
from Shackleton to Buenos Aires stowaway Perce Blackborow to
Hurley, who had been enlisted to provide photos and movie film for
later commercial exploitation of the expedition, including lecture
tours and books.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton emerges as a textbook leader, strong-willed and
savvy, yet always acutely attuned to the needs of the others. But
the expedition's survival also depended upon its lowliest members,
who weathered extreme conditions that sometimes left them on the
verge of madness, but with surprisingly little complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Those left on Elephant Island endured seven months in frigid
temperatures wearing the same sodden clothes, existing on a diet of
almost nothing but penguin, and still they kept their daily routine
despite dwindling hopes of ever being rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander often found herself beset by tears during her
research, including her visit to the impossibly tiny James Caird.
But nothing affected her more than the word from a library in New
Zealand that one of the key crew members, carpenter Henry McNish,
had died a pauper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened that envelope,'' Alexander recalled, ``and I felt
like I had opened a telegram from the war front telling me that
someone in my own family had died. I was just devastated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
