<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CLINTON'S CUTENESS UNDERMINES THE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The comment jarred me.
</P>
<P>
   It was made by a lawyer representing one of two Albany police
officers accused of beating up a suspect in handcuffs. The initial
charges had been thrown out on a technicality. John Dorfman, the
special prosecutor in the case, had managed to get a judge to
essentially reinstate the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Dorfman, the defense lawyer said, was behaving in an evil,
vindictive way by pursuing this case. Do you know who Dorfman
reminded the lawyer of? Kenneth Starr, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful. Apparently, from now on, whenever a prosecutor does
his job vigorously _ whenever a prosecutor does anything but roll
over and play dead in any criminal case _ he can expect to be
likened to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   With a shaky Congress trying desperately to find some way not to
impeach Bill Clinton, an image has popped into my mind that I
haven't been able to shake. It's a picture of Richard Nixon, gazing
up from Hell at Washington, D.C., shaking his head and muttering to
himself, ``How is this guy pulling this off?''
</P>
<P>
   Through a masterful manipulation of public opinion, that's how.
Clinton has successfully managed to divert attention from what he
did to the conduct of the independent counsel. To a startling
degree, public debate on this from the beginning has focused not on
whether the president committed a felony _ and he did; I saw him do
it on television _ but on whether Starr is a good guy or a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Clinton's good fortune has been to have enemies viewed
by most Americans as mean and weird. Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., for
example. Here's this vengeful, sanctimonious geek from somewhere
out in the boonies. He's howling about the president's immorality
while, it turns out, he fathered an illegitimate child in an
illicit affair of his own.
</P>
<P>
   With enemies like that, who needs friends?
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's surly paranoia and utter paucity of personal warmth made
almost everybody nervous, even those who agreed with his politics.
But Clinton is a shrewd, calculating, matchless charmer. He's a
good-looking guy with a nice smile and a spectacular line of
bullfeathers. Few see in him the dark, brooding malice that
virtually everybody saw in Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Clinton is getting away with the purposeful
commission of perjury _ with lying under oath not once but twice.
To most people, the gravity of this crime counts far less than the
warm and fuzzy public persona of the man who committed it compared
to the sinister, worrisome images of the men who condemn him for
it.
</P>
<P>
   We're watching the ultimate political spin job. To somebody like
me, who has spent most of a lifetime watching spin jobs, this
operation's effectiveness is nothing less than breathtaking. Nobody
would have bought a used car from Nixon, but Clinton could make
millions peddling old Yugos.
</P>
<P>
   I've never had a big political problem with this guy. Sure, I
have specific complaints, but he's basically a
middle-of-the-roader, and so am I. Like the framers of the
Constitution, though, despotism worries me. There's little doubt in
my mind that James Madison, for example, would have voted to bounce
Clinton for perjury just as Madison would have voted to oust Nixon
for obstruction of justice and Lyndon Johnson for lying to Congress
about the Gulf of Tonkin incident.
</P>
<P>
   But Madison formed his values before television and 401(k)
accounts, before greed and a public passion for cuddliness
overpowered conscience, before charm and cant trumped principles.
Cute now counts more than right.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, I expect, any prosecutor lacking a towering level
of charisma can expect to be painted as a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the guy accused of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
