<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAFT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONLINE DRAFT REGISTRATION BEGINS WEDNESDAY
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Proving that the times they are a-changing yet
again, four suburban high school seniors will race on computer
keyboards Wednesday to become the first young men to register on
line with the Selective Service.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Vietnam War era, when Bob Dylan sang protest songs
and the military draft haunted a generation of American men, hardly
anyone was in a hurry to sign up with the Selective Service.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 25 years since the last draftee entered the army,
though, and the young men who will register at the Selective
Service's Internet site (http://www.sss.gov) have known only the
all-volunteer military services. At a time where the PC is
universal and the VC exists only in history books, the new system
should make it easier to comply with federal requirements to
register.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real, interactive, online registration,'' said Gil
Coronado, director of the Selective Service. ``For nearly two
decades, men have gone to post offices, completed and mailed a
registration form, and waited 60 to 90 days to receive an
acknowledgement card from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men can still register through the mail, but there is now a
better way,'' he said. This ``better way'' will be demonstrated
Wednesday morning by four 18-year-old male students at George Mason
High School in Falls Church, Va., a suburb of the nation's capital.
After Coronado throws a switch symbolically activating the Internet
system, the young men will race on personal computers to become the
nation's first cyber-registrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new online service, a man with a valid Social
Security number will be able to connect to the Selective Service
Web site, ... link to the agency's computers, type in his
registration information, click on the 'Submit' button which
appears on the screen, and instantly be given his Selective Service
number,'' said Coronado.
</P>
<P>
   The online registrants will also receive a formal
acknowledgement postcard in the mail within two weeks, said the
director.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all male citizens and many male aliens living in the
United States are required to register with the Selective Service,
an independent federal agency created by President Franklin D.
Roosevelt in 1940 to oversee the military draft. The law requires
young men to register with 30 days of their 18th birthday, and
about 1.8 million sign up with the Selective Service each year.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to register is a felony and causes young men to be
ineligible for student loans and grants for college, for federal
jobs and for federal job training.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, the draft ended and the nation converted to an
all-volunteer military force. The registration requirement was
suspended in 1975, but resumed in 1980 and has been the law ever
since _ although no American has been conscripted in a quarter of a
century.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the past year, recruitment and retention of
personnel have become a problem in the military, and there has been
talk in Congress about a potential need to revive the draft. With
the services not meeting their quotas, the draft was discussed at a
September hearing of a House National Security subcommittee on
military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The draft filled the ranks of America's armed forces during the
major wars of the 20th century. About 2.7 million men were inducted
during World War I, 10.1 million in World War II, 1.5 million
during the Korean War and 1.7 during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado said online registration represents ``a historic
milestone for the Selective Service System.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As increasing numbers of men gain access to the Internet
through home computers, in schools, at libraries and many other
places that are connected to the Web, we hope that online
registration becomes the primary method of registering,'' said
Coronado. ``It is faster, simpler and easier for all concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
