<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-TRIO-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-01 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-TRIO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ORLANDO, Fla.: ... new information.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing they have heard has heartened them. In fact, psychic
Sylvia Brown of Seattle, who appeared with the families on ``The
Montel Williams Show,'' has said the men are underwater, killed
with a guide in an airboat accident in the northwest Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The guide was a hermit without family and friends, the psychic
said, and the GMC Jimmy will not be found because the guide's
cabin, where the vehicle is parked, is so remote.
</P>
<P>
   Because DesVergnes owns an airboat, Ray has seized on this
vision and prodded police to search the Everglades and area lakes.
</P>
<P>
   But to Bergin, the suggestion is preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are over 300 lakes in central Florida,'' she said.
``Where do I start? I can't search the state of Florida. I can't
make those people happy right now because I have limitations on
what I can reasonably do. They have no idea from our point of view
about what is practical.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, members of all three families are accepting the idea
that the men are dead. But without any bodies, a faint hope
continues to flicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the situation, and you say they're probably no
longer alive. But on the other hand, who really knows?'' said
Poillucci, Nelson's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson had been expected to attend another sister's wedding in
Warwick, R.I., on Oct. 4, two days after his scheduled return.
Nelson missed the rehearsal dinner on Oct. 3, but his absence did
not alarm relatives who suspected he had spent an extra day in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But when Nelson did not appear at the wedding, where his son
served as ringbearer, concern began to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cloud hung over the wedding,'' Poillucci said. ``We were all
wondering what happened, but tried not to show it. You know, it's
supposed to be the best day in my sister's life. So how do you put
her in a panic on her wedding day?''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ray became alarmed when DesVergnes' once-a-day
calls from Florida stopped. When he did not return to
Massachusetts, Ray called Renquin's parents, whom she had never
met, to share her worries.
</P>
<P>
   Renquin's mother relayed the news to Paul, her oldest son, and
he reacted with an unworried shrug born of the knowledge that
sometimes, even men can be unpredictable boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother said, `Do you know your brother's missing?''' Paul
Renquin recalled. ``I said, `Huh? So what? He's a single guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the seeds of concern had been planted, and the Renquins
called the Orlando police the next day to ask for a check of the
condominium.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the lives of the families have been irrevocably
changed. ``It's taxing my family terribly,'' Renquin said. ``It's
the most stressful situation I've ever been in.
</P>
<P>
   ``One minute you're saying, `I'd do anything to get him back.'
And the next minute, you're saying, `The S.O.B., why did he do
this?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renquin's mother, agonizing over her son's fate, is wracked by
sudden nausea at work. Ray clings to a prayer that she and
DesVergnes can marry next October as planned. And Poillucci wonders
what will become of her brother's small son.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's maybe a one-quarter of 1 percent chance that he'll
walk through that door,'' Paul Renquin said at his home, stroking
Scott's black cat, Voodoo. ``But the family needs to have closure.
That's what's tearing us apart.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Scott Renquin's apartment in Attleboro awaits a
tenant who may never return. When his brother broke in, he found a
handwritten note among the bachelor furnishings that included
Nintendo games and a beer keg hooked up to a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The note read: ``If anything was ever to happen to me when I'm
away, then everything I own is to be left to my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma about what to do with Scott's belongings is just one
of many wrenching problems for the Renquins _ and for relatives of
the other missing men.
</P>
<P>
   Active searches have stopped in Florida, and the next
development in the case will probably be a grim one.
</P>
<P>
   This month, a Providence TV station interrupted its noon
newscast to carry the live broadcast of a van being pulled from a
lake near Orlando. Commentators speculated that the vehicle might
be carrying the bodies of the Attleboro men.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Renquin rushed into his home from the adjacent garage where
he repairs BMW and Mercedes automobiles. As he watched, anxious
with anticipation, a rising hope turned to crashing disappointment
when the vehicle was not his brother's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went back to my shop,'' Renquin recalled. ``By that
point, I was pretty much disgusted. I thought, `Is this the way I'm
going to have to find out?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
