<HEADER>
A6739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-2TAKES-BOS     12-01 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE REFORM: IT'S A NEW DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG AND FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In dry print, tucked in the pages of a dictionary
between ``weightless'' and ``well-born,'' the definition sounds as
plain as it is innocuous.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare: ``The state of being or doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years after a New Deal president created a system to
rescue ``unemployables,'' welfare continues to generate the
fiercest debate over how, and whether, a democratic society should
care for its own. Now, after all the good intentions and bad ideas,
the political attack and public outrage, it comes down to this.
</P>
<P>
   A new ``new deal,'' and, for as many as 5,800 families in
Massachusetts, a single day of reckoning: Dec. 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after Thanksgiving, and four weeks before Christmas,
the welfare rolls were to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's vow to ``end welfare as we know it''
becomes a reality in Massachusetts, state officials will eliminate
cash benefits for families who have been receiving benefits for two
consecutive years, as part of a welfare overhaul some advocates say
is among the strictest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Though the plan will spare the disabled and those whose youngest
child has not yet reached age 2, the plan means an end to monthly
checks for any family headed by an able-bodied parent once the
youngest child reaches the age of 4.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the 41,000 recipients who initially faced the
deadline, the ticking of the two-year clock of welfare reform was
deafening. The vast majority moved off the rolls, about half of
them for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   With the number down to 5,800 at the end of October, the
question, welfare officials and advocates say, is as much who they
are as why they have been unable to find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Those who clamored for rigid reforms are betting that the
remainder of people left to face the deadline are the chronically
dependent who have no motivation to work. But advocates who have
been helping still-struggling recipients brace for the final day
warn that the deadline may leave behind a population of recipients
so troubled or needy, they may be impervious to even the state's
strict hand of reform.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; No one is certain whether the final cutoff will spur those who
remain to self-improvement, or relegate them to the desperate
poverty that welfare was originally created to remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-six percent of the 5,800 are actively doing something
_ working, in education and training or in structured job
searches,'' said state welfare commissioner Claire McIntire. ``We
expect those families will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rest, McIntire said, are doing nothing. And what happens
to them will tell much of the story about how the massive social
experiment to overhaul welfare ended.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging picture of the thousands facing the deadline is a
portrait of paradoxes that defies easy characterization. On one
hand, the picture reveals an older population that tends to be
better educated than the overall pool of recipients. They are more
likely to be working in part-time jobs, but they are also more
likely to be living in subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   It also points to another, more vulnerable subset: the poorest
of the poor, uneducated, and unskilled, who face serious obstacles
to employment, from language, literacy, and cultural barriers to
poor work experience. They confront those obstacles without the
buffer of relatives or additional support systems that might
otherwise fill gaps in child care and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that critical layer of support may be the only thing
separating the so-called working poor _ who manage to keep their
families afloat _ from those who depend on a government check.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say, `There's no excuse. There are plenty of
people out there who are working and making it who don't have great
jobs,''' said Conny Doty, director of Boston's Office of Jobs and
Community Services. The agency offers training and education for
children and adults, including welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``But I guarantee you almost every single one of those people
who are making it have a family support system that is taking care
of child care, which is a major issue,'' Doty said. ``It's not as
easy as just saying `Get a job.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it were that easy, some, like Malikkah Phillips, could
not make it.
</P>
<P>
   When House Speaker Newt Gingrich pledged four years ago to do
whatever he had to to ``help, cajole, lure or force adults off
welfare,'' he was not talking about Phillips. A 26-year-old single
mother of four who lives in Dorchester and has been on welfare
since 1989, Phillips resolved months ago to spend her last two
years building a ladder that eventually would help her climb to a
higher level of earning.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the crush of a deadline, she has found no wages, and
no window of opportunity either.
</P>
<P>
   Taking long strides as she marched through commencement at
Bunker Hill Community College this spring, she felt the world of
dependence she had entered at age 17, two years after she had her
first child, would soon be behind her. She was counting on the
human services associate's degree to help her land the
$9.50-per-hour job she felt she would need to support herself and
her family. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After mailing out 300 resumes in four months and going to 50 job
interviews, she has not had a single offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them told me to come back when I get a bachelor's
degree or get more experience,'' said Phillips, who planned to take
a seasonal retail job at $6.50 per hour. ``People think I can find
a job anywhere, but that is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips lives in subsidized housing, which means the government
would pay her entire rent if she has no income after losing her
$702 monthly welfare check. But that hardly makes her secure. Once
the grant stops coming, she will have to scrape together $315 each
month to keep her apartment heated, the lights on, and the phone
connected. She will also have to figure out how to supplement the
$318 she gets each month in food stamps to pay for her family's
$600 monthly grocery expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Those pressures put Phillips in a broad category with many
recipients like herself who may not have to worry about paying
rent, but will have utility and food bills that welfare grants once
helped them pay. Indeed, a recent report by the US General
Accounting Office suggested that residents of public housing were
less likely to move off the rolls because they face more barriers
to finding jobs than the larger welfare population.
</P>
<P>
   The missing links of her welfare story Phillips chooses not to
talk about _ the absent father, the missing relatives _ tells as
much of the story of struggle she and others face as the hard
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
