<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6741 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNISEX-JOHNS-BOS &LR;      12-01 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNISEX-JOHNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IMITATES TV AS BATHROOMS GO UNISEX  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From profit sharing to potty sharing, the path to corporate
enlightenment takes many strange twists. In the case of a company
in Bristol, Conn., employees _ sorry, associates _ will soon see
whether real life and the television version are truly compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Yarde Metals, a privately owned 300-employee metals distribution
firm, has made news lately with its plans to install a unisex
bathroom in the company's new office facility, slated to be built
in the spring. The concept, which is to include six stalls and a
shared sink area but no urinals, is an unabashed rip-off of ``Ally
McBeal,'' the hit Fox TV show in which a gender-blended restroom
figures heavily in the weekly plot gyrations.
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside about life imitating art, though, or about
what passes for art on network television these days, Yarde Metals
founder and president Craig Yarde is dead serious when he tells
media heavyweights like The New York Times that the flush handle
could become the next potent symbol of male-female equality in the
already-confused American workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an `Ally McBeal' fan, I love that show,'' says Yarde, 47.
``But I also really believe that everyone who works here is equal
and should be treated that way. Even when it comes to the bathroom,
as quirky as that sounds. How many times have you gone into the
restroom and had a discussion about what's going on?''
</P>
<P>
   Having already eliminated designated parking spaces and private
walled offices _ even the term ``employee'' was dropped for the
more status-neutral ``associate'' _ Yarde maintains that it fits
with his philosophy to offer men and women adjoining toilet stalls
as an option. Not the only option, to be sure; men's and women's
restrooms will also be available. But a visible, viable,
McBeal-able option that merges plumbing and human behavior with
postmodern management philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig does a lot of wacky things, but he also walks the walk
when it comes to progressivism,'' says company vice president Brad
Urban, 59. ``To me, as far as unisex restrooms go, what's the
difference anyway? I have one at home. My wife might not be as open
to using one here, but so what? Most women probably wouldn't. I
look at it like doing business at men's clubs or on the golf
course. You have to start breaking those barriers down, and not
everyone jumps on the idea at first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd use it as long as there are no frogs in there,'' jokes
Ginny Aiken, 38, referring to the show's amphibians. ``Seriously,
it doesn't bother me. I'd actually like to find out what the guys
talk about in there.''
</P>
<P>
   And what do the women of Yarde Metals talk about in the privacy
of their own privy?
</P>
<P>
   ``The men, of course,'' says Aiken. Not everyone is what you
might call in sync with Yarde's vision. In Tewksbury, where Yarde
Metals maintains a satellite office, Dawn Sullivan votes a
resounding ``no'' on this little piece of social engineering, which
she regards as touchy-feely management run amok.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's asinine, no pun intended,'' says Sullivan, 41, a
member of the sales support team. ``I told my boss, `If you put one
of those in, I'm driving home to go to the bathroom.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cerat, 44, a sales associate, says Yarde customers have
been chortling over the publicity about the unisex. Like Sullivan,
he's no fan of the experiment and believes that it flies in the
face of human nature _ and especially human nature with its
knickers down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't get the concept _ or the benefit.'' He says if
he's using the toilet and ``a woman wants to come in, ... I suppose
that's her business. But is it really a place they want to go?''
</P>
<P>
   Cerat notes another toilet truism that he says argues for
separate facilities. ``In my experience, guys don't talk much in
the john. Most men like their privacy. Women tend to travel more in
herds.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he says, Yarde Metals is hardly the kind of company
where people have to hide in the bathroom to talk about the boss.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Young, 35, a Yarde telephone operator and the spouse of
another company employee, counts herself among the curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not shy, I'd check it out,'' she says. ``I'd see who goes
in there to talk, maybe. Although there's not a lot of gossipy talk
that goes on in the women's room, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarde is, if you'll forgive the expression, plunging ahead just
the same. And unisex toilets aren't the only controversial aspects
of his blueprint. Those eight proposed nap rooms for employees are
drawing attention, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think this way at Harvard Business School,'' says
Yarde, whose staff may soon face another key business question:
whether to leave the seat up or down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
