<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH EXPERTS URGE AWARENESS ABOUT HEPATITIS C 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A blood test may have saved Lucy's life.
</P>
<P>
   That's not her real name, but the story of this nurse in upstate
New York is true. Last year, after a routine physical and blood
test, Lucy's doctor discovered she had elevated liver enzymes.
</P>
<P>
   Further tests showed hepatitis C, a liver infection that can
lead to cirrhosis, liver cancer and liver failure. Hepatitis C
kills an estimated 10,000 people annually and is the leading reason
for liver transplants in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would lay awake at night thinking about how I was going to
die,'' Lucy, 41, said from her home near Albany. ``It was unnerving
to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a year later, Lucy is responding well to treatment, a
regimen of regular injections of interferon.
</P>
<P>
   Some people aren't so lucky. Hepatitis C afflicts an estimated
3.9 million Americans, many of whom don't know they're infected
with the potentially fatal virus. The leading cause of infection is
sharing intravenous drug needles, but anyone who came into contact
with infected blood before 1992, including through blood
transfusions or organ transplants, is at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy believes she contracted the disease on the job as a health
care worker, before the virus was identified. She didn't want her
real name used in this article because of the potential stigma. ``I
don't want to have to defend myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this fall, health officials announced a plan to start
notifying people who may be at risk: Their goal is to encourage the
hundreds of thousands of Americans who had transfusions or
transplants before 1992, to get tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what we know, it's appropriate to tell people they're
at risk,'' said Dr. John Balint, director of the Center for Medical
Ethics and professor of medicine at the Albany Medical College.
Most people don't give their liver a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take it for granted, because it quietly does what it has to
do,'' Balint said. ``When the liver gets sick, a lot of things can
go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy agrees. Since her diagnosis, she has developed a new
appreciation for the liver's important role in keeping us healthy.
``It just does its job silently until it stops doing it and then
you're out of luck,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Balint likens the liver to a chemical factory, with the job of
manufacturing products the body can use and detoxifying those it
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis C is only one of a class of three hepatitis viruses
that can affect liver function.
</P>
<P>
   If your mother has told you to stay away from raw shellfish,
she's worried about hepatitis A, the least serious of the viruses.
</P>
<P>
   It thrives in fecal matter, and is passed on from person to
person through contaminated food and water. Eating raw shellfish
can be a problem, if it's harvested from waters containing raw
sewage.
</P>
<P>
   The best precaution is to eat only food that's been fully cooked
and boiled. However, beware that most shellfish are cooked only
until they open, usually at a temperature less than boiling. ``If
you don't know for sure where it was caught, you need to be
careful,'' Balint said.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is hepatitis B, a liver virus that is
spread through sexual contact and also through sharp instruments
contaminated with infected blood, including razors, toothbrushes
and needles.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 100,000 people contract hepatitis B each year and
nearly all recover within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are vaccines against both hepatitis A and B.
Many states now require children to be immunized against hepatitis
B.
</P>
<P>
   To date, no vaccine is available against hepatitis C. That means
the best defense is early testing and treatment, if you think
you're at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy believes it helped save her life. ``So far, I'm doing
pretty good,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
