<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MINIVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MRS. MINIVER' YEARNED TO BE MISS MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A ROSE FOR MRS. MINIVER 
The Life of Greer Garson 
By Michael Troyan 
University Press of Kentucky, 463 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are reasons that Greer Garson, queen of the MGM lot in the
'40s, faded so quickly from America's collective memory. Katharine
Hepburn, Bette Davis, Joan Crawford, Marlene Dietrich, and other
divas of the period are remembered and celebrated for their strong
personalities, their combativeness. Instead of rolling with the
punches, they punched back _ publicly. But as the title of Michael
Troyan's new biography, ``A Rose for Mrs. Miniver,'' reaffirms,
Garson was perceived as strong, gallant, refined, quietly enduring.
She won an Oscar for ``Mrs. Miniver'' in 1943, embodying the
stubborn but decorous preservation of self-sacrificing British
civilization at a time when Hitler's aircraft were trying to bomb
it into rubble.
</P>
<P>
   There actually was a rose named after Mrs. Miniver, whom author
Jan Struther had made the personification of British steadiness and
decency. (Struther took the name Miniver, in fact, from English
heraldry, where it refers to the white trim on robes.) The world
needed a Mrs. Miniver figure and Garson became it. Later, she
regarded the role as having stunted her career. Gregory Peck called
her an Irish cut-up, but this was a side seen by comparatively few.
Although one of her early roles was that of Jane Austen's Elizabeth
Bennet in ``Pride and Prejudice'' (opposite Laurence Olivier), and
though she brought to it the right edgy cleverness, the die was
pretty much cast with Garson's first film, ``Goodbye, Mr. Chips,''
in which she played another forbearing Englishwoman, Mrs. Chips, to
Robert Donat's beloved headmaster.
</P>
<P>
   It was a role she didn't want; she unflatteringly described
Katherine Chipping as a sparrow of a woman. But she was impatient,
ambitious, and almost desperate, having been subjected to the kind
of treatment all too common with Louis B. Mayer. Seeing Garson play
a murderess on the London stage, he signed her and whisked her and
her mother (and near-lifelong companion and solace), Nina, to
Pasadena in 1937. There they sat for almost three years. Her screen
test was unprepossessing _ though during it she met the actor who
was to become her favorite leading man over the years, Walter
Pidgeon, who projected his own brand of warmth and dignity to
provide counterpoint to hers.
</P>
<P>
   So Mrs. Chips it was. Then, after ``Mrs. Miniver'' opposite
Pidgeon, it was ``Random Harvest'' with Ronald Colman. A star was
born, and so was a persona. Ironically, Garson had made her British
stage debut in an American play, Edgar Rice's ``Street Scene,'' in
1932. And though she told people she was Irish, she actually was
born in London, in 1904, and had as much Scottish ancestry as Irish
(Scandinavian, too). Greer, her mother's last name, was an Irish
contraction for the Scottish MacGregor. Garson loved Ireland, where
she spent summers on her relatives' farm in County Down. And one is
surprised to learn of a woman who lived to be 92 (she died in 1996)
that Garson was a sickly child, whose survival was a tossup, and
whose career and other anxieties invariably affected her health.
</P>
<P>
   She not only had style, she had brains. She graduated from the
University of London, worked in advertising, made her first
theatrical connection _ with the Birmingham Repertory Company _
through an agency acquaintance. After seeing her in a production of
his ``Too Good to Be True,'' George Bernard Shaw called her the new
Ellen Terry. Her quick tongue was not always appreciated in
Hollywood. When MGM starred her opposite returning war veteran
Clark Gable in ``Adventure'' in 1946, she was furious to see
posters saying, ``Gable's Back and Garson's Got Him!'' ```They're
ungallant,' she indignantly replied. `Why don't you say, ``Garson
puts the able in Gable''?'''
</P>
<P>
   Troyan's diligent, solidly researched account is punctuated by
Garson's attempts to break out of her dignified persona. She almost
never did. When her career entered its final phases, she was cast
as Eleanor Roosevelt in ``Sunrise at Campobello,'' as a prioress in
``The Singing Nun,'' and as Fred MacMurray's wife in ``The Happiest
Millionaire.'' Two early marriages failed, including one with
Richard Ney, a younger actor who played her son in ``Mrs.
Miniver.'' In 1949, she married a third time. This one, to a Texas
oilman, Buddy Fogelson, lasted until his death, in 1987. They
mostly divided their time between Dallas and Santa Fe, where she
helped establish a theater that was named after her. In Dallas, as
in Hollywod, tea with Greer Garson became something of a state
occasion. ```Gracious' is a word that has haunted me all my life,''
said the woman who wanted to be known as mischievous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
