<HEADER>
A6754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     12-01 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... the hard numbers.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris's struggle is so private, she did not want to use her last
name. The mother of two, who lives in Sagamore, thought that after
two years on welfare, she would finally leave it this fall. She
started working for $10.50 per hour as a home health aide in
September, and her 7-year-old son _ who had witnessed his
now-absent father whip his mother with cords and push soiled
diapers into her face _ was doing fairly well with counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Then, within days of starting her job, she began getting calls
from her son's school. Her son was out of control, they told her.
She needed to come and fetch him.
</P>
<P>
   The calls came more and more frequently until finally, last
month, she felt she had no choice but to quit her job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to work and I was making good money,'' she said.
``But with all the stuff going on with my son, it was crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris has no answer to the question of what she will do when the
checks stop coming. She has a live-in boyfriend who has no steady
work, and no government subsidy to help her pay for the $600
monthly rent on her apartment. And, like the majority of families
on welfare, she gets no child support from the father of her two
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the people we work with to help place in work programs, a
lot of them don't have high school credentials, they can have a
poor working history, problems with drug abuse or violence, and a
whole host of other issues,'' said Nancy Snyder, deputy director of
the Private Industry Council.
</P>
<P>
   The organization works with the city, regional companies, and
community-based organizations to place welfare recipients in job
programs and provide counseling and case management for the first
year after recipients find work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk to these people, you can sense that they really
want to work,'' Snyder said. ``But they always have at least one
kid, and some have as many as six or seven, and the biggest
question for them is their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, those who have watched the effects of the
looming welfare deadline say it has spurred most parents to action.
But while many continue to walk a tightrope _ balancing low wages,
high rents, lack of child care and health insurance, irresponsible
partners, violence, and sometimes drug abuse _ there are others who
seem unfazed by the coming changes.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Anne Stewart is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has lived in public housing in South Boston since 1983.
She has been on welfare for six of those years, after she was laid
off from a job at a print shop. Though she has yet to find a
permanent job, she seemed unrattled that the checks that have
sustained her and her two children will soon stop coming.
</P>
<P>
   Her relative calm in the face of the impending deadline comes in
part from the fact that, even if Stewart does not find a job after
losing her grant, the 36-year-old and her children will still have
their home. Their food stamp allotment of $192 a month will likely
be adjusted upward and they will still be covered by Medicaid. The
end of the $525 monthly welfare check she gets would be largely
offset, because the state would grant her the entire $416 per month
she gets from the children's father in child support. The state, as
a matter of policy, gives families on welfare $50 of child support
payments, keeping the rest to offset the cost of the welfare
grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be just the same as I am concerned,'' said Stewart
matter-of-factly of how her family's life would change after being
dropped from the welfare rolls. ``It will be difficult. It's
difficult now.''
</P>
<P>
   If the system of welfare has not lived up to its definition _
being or doing well _ neither has much of the public debate about
the policy or its overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   At its most fevered pitch, the controversy around a flawed
system has spawned its own stereotypes. The ghetto girlfriend, food
stamps in one fist, Cadillac keys in the other. The drifting,
able-bodied drunk, huddled over street gates but never standing in
an unemployment line. &UR;  &LR; The images contain kernels of truth, but
many say they have clouded the complex issues that feed the welfare
system.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after all the truths, myths, and guesses, there will
finally be an accounting of what kinds of welfare recipients emerge
beyond the stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor say the deadline spells certain doom for
some families, thrusting already desperate people into poverty,
onto the streets, back into the arms of abusive partners, and into
criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are going to have to do what they have to do,'' said
Randy Albeda, a University of Massachusetts professor of economics
specializing in low-wage and welfare issues. ``They are going to
take care of their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Albeda predicted the deadline also will leave some parents
unable to adequately feed, clothe, and look after their children,
leaving them open to charges of abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the number of recipients who have left the rolls
proves there is a job for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe if you want to work, there is a job for
you,'' said McIntire. ``There are help wanted ads everywhere. Two
part-time jobs might work as well as one full-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; To McIntire, there is no reason why every current welfare
recipient cannot be a Marlene Wynter, a 25-year-old Dorchester
success story once considered among the hard-to-serve.
</P>
<P>
   A high school dropout who had been on welfare for five years
since the birth of the first of her two children, Wynter was in the
first class to graduate from the welfare-to-work training program
at the Copley Marriott in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   She has been &UR;  &LR; employed full time since September as a
$9.50-per-hour housekeeper. &UR;  &LR; The thing that prompted her, she said,
was the barrage of mail from the welfare department, pointing her
toward job programs and warning her about the ticking clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really better off now,'' Wynter said. ``I sleep well. I'm
not thinking about welfare anymore, worrying about being cut off. I
feel good about myself. ''
</P>
<P>
   With a monthly salary of nearly $1,500, Wynter is earning almost
double the $718 a month in cash assistance and food stamps she had
been receiving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But Wynter has also been lucky. Her mother has been able to
look after Wynter's children while she works 3:30 p.m. to midnight,
a shift most daycare providers could not accommodate, and a luxury
that many single mothers struggling to get off welfare dream of.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of state child-care vouchers, which will still be
available to recipients after the deadline, advocates for the poor
say the vouchers are often useless because there are so few
available slots, and because those that are available do not allow
parents to work odd shifts or in jobs where they are far away from
their children.
</P>
<P>
   Already some say the ultimate test of the state's, and the
nation's, commitment to welfare-to-work lies in the state cutting
another set of long rolls _ waiting lists for day care that is
affordable and convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to find good child care even if you have a lot
of money. So you can imagine what it's like if all you have is a
state voucher,'' said Doty, of the Office of Jobs and Community
Services. ``Child care is a major issue. It's just so clearly
linked to people being in and staying in the work force. And that
just keeps coming up every time you talk to people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
