<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-TRIO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT A TRACE, WITHOUT A WORD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The Sunshine Resort is a pink-and-white oasis in
a monotonous jumble of fast-food restaurants, franchise
storefronts, and algae-covered drainage ditches.
</P>
<P>
   Its four pastel floors face the optimistically named Fun Spot, a
cramped amusement park whose relentless pop music bounces off the
Sunshine's timeshare condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Renquin of Attleboro, Mass., a part owner of Room 105, was
seen here Sept. 28, three days after arriving in Florida with two
Attleboro friends for a week of relaxation and outdoor adventure.
</P>
<P>
   They have not been seen since. In a city where nearly every
missing person is eventually found, Renquin, 35; Dan Nelson, 32;
and Roger DesVergnes, 31, have vanished without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of any clues, any credible leads, and any evidence
that the men had staged their own disappearance has anguished their
large families back home and baffled seasoned investigators here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how we're going to find them,'' said Orlando
Police Detective Barbara Bergin, who is in charge of the case.
</P>
<P>
   For the men's relatives and friends, that thinking is
unacceptable. To them, three responsible adults do not vanish near
the world's most popular tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   But to police in Orlando, what may seem logical in metropolitan
Boston does not necessarily apply in the boomtowns and scrubland of
central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite our growth, we still have wilderness,'' said Jim
Solomons, spokesman for the Orange County sheriff's office. ``There
are places where you can disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergin suspects that the men had an accident in a remote area,
possibly while driving the all-terrain 1999 GMC Jimmy that Renquin
rented for the week. Foul play is highly unlikely, she said; most
killers in the Orlando area ``don't take the time to dispose of
bodies. And it would take quite a bit of time and energy to dispose
of three bodies and a vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The missing men, all single, do not seem to have had lifestyles
that would intersect with deadly criminals. Renquin, who towed cars
in Attleboro &UR;  &LR; with a self-built flatbed truck, enjoyed camping,
pool, and tinkering with automobiles. He also was a certified pilot
and scuba diver.
</P>
<P>
   DesVergnes, who operated a small construction company in
Attleboro, was an impulsive outdoorsman who could cajole his
fiancee, Cindy Ray, into a skiing or camping trip on a moment's
notice. He kept an airboat for skimming across the 100-acre
cranberry bog he owned near his home.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a machinist who worked in Rhode Island, was drawn to
water sports when he was not working overtime to support his
5-year-old son, who lived with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny was very concerned about his child,'' said Nelson's
sister, Dawn Poillucci of North Smithfield, R.I. ``He is not the
type who wouldn't return and not tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Orlando police, Renquin's condo looked like a
vacation pad left behind for a day trip. Investigators found a
refrigerator stocked with $200 worth of hamburger, hot dogs, beer,
and chips; $500 in a safe; clothing; and unmade beds.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card and cellular telephone records show no transactions
or calls after the men's disappearance. And nothing in their past
suggests they might have tried to disappear and reinvent themselves
outside Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, this is the first time we've had three adult
people disappear under these conditions,'' Bergin said.
</P>
<P>
   The GMC Jimmy that Renquin rented has not been found, despite
massive publicity. Aerial surveillance has turned up nothing. And
ground searches have been fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   None of the few people who saw the trio here have reported
anything unusual. A boyhood friend of Renquin's, who now lives in
an Orlando suburb, talked to them Sept. 28 _ the day they vanished
_ and made plans to meet Sept. 30 for a night of fun.
</P>
<P>
   One area of agreement is that the men were not typical Florida
tourists. With a four-wheel-drive vehicle at the ready, and their
love of the water as a bond, the trio were likely to have explored
the lakes, canals, and remote dirt roads that infiltrate the
nearby, uninhabited flatland.
</P>
<P>
   And if that's where they are _ undiscovered in a secluded ditch,
invisible from the air, and miles from civilization _ the trauma of
their disappearance may linger for years for three families that
desperately want closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the days go by, I just get more angry and more sad,'' said
Ray, DesVergnes' fiancee. ``I want someone to say something,
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the two months that the men have been missing, the families
said, two or three weeks may pass before the Orlando police contact
them with an update.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really wonder, with three missing guys who aren't from
there, do they really care?'' asked Paul Renquin, Scott's brother.
</P>
<P>
   But the police say they are doing everything they can in a case
with no leads. ``I can't call them every day and tell them nothing
happened,'' Bergin said.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the families have taken their story to the news
media, to TV tabloid shows, and to a psychic in the hope of
uncovering a kernel of new information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
