<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN01-COX-1     12-01 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN01-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Sad song of the rock 'n' roll star
 &HT;    (Eds: Fixes song plot in grafs 8-9.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A buddy and I were riding around, going nowhere
in particular, something we've been doing since back in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Kiss'' by J. Frank Wilson was playing on the CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one thing wrong with that song,'' my friend said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No there isn't,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Such was our tribute to J. Frank Wilson, someone we'd known
since grade school.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you remember that ``Last Kiss'' hit No. 1 on the charts in
1964, making J. Frank a rock 'n' roll idol and, for a short while,
the most famous guy to have graduated from Lufkin High.
</P>
<P>
   You can read all about him on the album notes of the new CD,
``The 'Last Kiss' Sessions,'' previously unreleased recordings by
J. Frank Wilson and the Cavaliers, on the Collectables label
(www.cicadelic.com.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Kiss'' tells the story of a teenage girl who dies in the
arms of her boyfriend after a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   It's no more tragic than the real life story of J. Frank. It
just took him a lot longer to die.
</P>
<P>
   J. Frank had graduated from high school in 1960, a year behind
me. I remember him playing rock 'n' roll at school assembly. Along
the way he got the nickname ``Greasy Frank,'' because of the way he
slicked back his hair, rock star-style.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1964, he had the talent to go with the look.
</P>
<P>
   Singing with the Cavaliers, a group he had met up with while
stationed in San Angelo, Texas, during a stint in the Air Force, J.
Frank was touring the country with his hit song.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Lufkin, a bunch of us got together to watch him
perform on national TV. In a brief interview afterward, the emcee
asked him if he'd had a nickname back in high school. J. Frank
mumbled something without really answering the question.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of us around the TV yelled out in unison, ``Greasy
Frank!''
</P>
<P>
   But not one of us resented his good fortune. We were proud of
him for doing what we'd all thought we'd do, become rich and
famous. Not so rich, as it would turn out for him, and not so
famous for very long.
</P>
<P>
   Early on the morning of Oct. 23 near Lima, Ohio, a station wagon
the band was traveling in crashed head-on with a tractor-trailer
when their driver fell asleep at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The driver died instantly. J. Frank was severely injured with
head lacerations, broken ribs and a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Within in a week he was back on the stage, performing on
crutches and in a cast. Some say it was an example of his
professionalism. Others blamed the greed of the people making money
off of his success.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, in the process, J. Frank became addicted to pain
pills, and as a result of the head injuries, would later suffer
from seizures.
</P>
<P>
   As for the money: Along with the million-seller gold record, a
``Last Kiss'' album had sold over 100,000 copies, but the record
company had to be sued in order to collect any royalties.
</P>
<P>
   According to the album notes, ``after all the lawyers and
expenses were paid, J. Frank ended up with around $3,000 ...''
</P>
<P>
   J. Frank would release other singles in the coming years, but
with little success. Ten years after ``Last Kiss'' hit No. 1 on the
charts, he was back in Lufkin working as a nursing home orderly.
</P>
<P>
   That's where he ended up himself, as a nursing home patient,
never having fully recovered from the injuries he received in the
car crash. He died Oct. 4, 1991, a couple of months short of his
50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Saddest of all, after his death was noted in Billboard magazine,
it came to light that another performer had been billing himself
for years as J. Frank Wilson in rock 'n' roll revues. Such is the
greed that took away his success, his money and even his name.
</P>
<P>
   If J. Frank Wilson's story could ever have a happy ending, it's
yet to be written. The album notes of the new CD suggest that
possibility:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this CD will change rock historians' perception
about his talent to reveal the unique flair and great style J.
Frank had when the world was waiting to be conquered by him and The
Cavaliers.''
</P>
<P>
   There's not one thing wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
