<SLUG> BC-YUKON-QUEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUKON SLED RACER TRUSTS HIS LIFE TO DOG'S INSTINCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAMPTON, N.H. _ So dogs are smarter than humans after all.
</P>
<P>
   At least certain dogs, of certain breeds, on certain Alaskan
peaks, during whiteout blizzard conditions in the middle of the
night with the wind chill at something way below zero.
</P>
<P>
   George Cook discovered this fact the hard way _ he lived through
it. But consider the alternative: winding up in a tangle of husky
and harness at the bottom of a 1,000-foot cliff, perhaps never to
be heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he wound up crossing the finish line of the Yukon
Quest, regarded by many as the world's toughest sled-dog race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it because it was an extreme sport or an extreme
challenge,'' said Cook. It was just, well, there. ``Nobody had ever
come up from the lower 48 with their own team of dogs and entered
the Yukon Quest and finished it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He did finish, albeit in last place.
</P>
<P>
   Mushers, as sled-dog racers are known, call the Yukon Quest ``A
Thousand Miles of Hell,'' and this is not a term of endearment.
While the Iditarod is the better-known sled-dog race, the Quest,
says Cook, is tougher and more dangerous. The trail runs along
ice-jammed rivers and across a trio of mountain ranges, with vast
distances between checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Cook ran the Quest in 1992. His wife and handler, Ann, has
written a book about the journey titled ``Running North,'' a
chronological account of how the Cook family hitched its sled team
to a star, moved temporarily to Alaska and mushed their way to
notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   But back to that really smart dog.
</P>
<P>
   Cook and his team of 12 Siberian huskies were riding a
knife-edge on the American Summit. It was the middle of the night.
Cliffs dropped off on both sides. Cook was nearly blinded by the
driving snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at that point when you realize that you have just
consigned your life to your dogs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Quest trail followed a road at the summit. Cook, thinking he
had his bearings, was following tufts of grass that he assumed were
on the left shoulder of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Then his lead dog, Minnie, suddenly turned and lept over the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Cook hollered at the dog, sure that she was about to pull him
and his team down the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she had pulled them _ against his commands _ up onto
the level road. He had been off the shoulder of the road, riding
alongside it. Had the dog listened to him...
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one who was driving off the 1,000-foot cliff,'' said
Cook. ``Minnie tolerated it just long enough and said `Buzz off, I
ain't dying,''' added Ann Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' she continued, ``you wonder who the superior
species is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cooks have long competed on the eastern circuit of sled-dog
racing, from Ontario to Pennsylvania, and in 1991 they decided they
were ready for Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly find it fun being a big fish in a small
pond,'' explained George Cook.
</P>
<P>
   So he took a leave from his job as a geologist and the family
packed 32 sled dogs, one 2-year-old human and all the equipment
they needed into a truck and went north to Alaska. (It is not, of
course, as simple as that _ running the Iditarod, by one estimate,
costs between $20,000 and $30,000, and the Quest requires more
supplies).
</P>
<P>
   While George trained for mushing glory, Ann and a fellow handler
went about the work _ the child care, the sewing of dog boot-ies,
the food preparation _ that makes the glory possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Cook is often asked _ by men, she points out _ how she felt
about doing the ``women's work'' while her husband ran the race.
The question annoys her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to emphasize that teamwork is a big part of''
sled-dog racing, she said. And team members tend to play to their
strengths. Ann Cook races sometimes, too, with her husband acting
as her handler. But she says she is the better handler.
</P>
<P>
   When she finished one race, Ann Cook recalls, her husband met
her at the finish line. He had remembered to bring beer. What she
really needed was a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to deify the person'' who actually runs the race, Ann
Cook said. But behind every respectable deity is an entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Running North,'' actually focuses on the travails of
the entourage: faulty trucks, sick dogs, cramped accommodations.
One of the toughest things about being an ``Arctic Mommy,'' said
Ann Cook, is that kids hate snowsuits.
</P>
<P>
   While attempting to hitch the team for one race, she put her
fully-bundled toddler in the cab of the truck. It was 22 degrees
below zero.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, the child was screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had taken every bit of her clothing off and was wondering
why she was so cold,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooks met at Phillips Exeter Academy. She muses that, if
melded into one person, the pair would have the perfect set of
skills for winning sled-dog races.
</P>
<P>
   George Cook finished about five days behind the Quest winner _
at 16 days, 8 hours, and 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When you ask him about finishing last in the Quest, George Cook
grimaces slightly. ``It's not that I finished last,'' he said,
pointedly. ``It's that I was the last finisher. There were 11 other
people who crashed and burned (and did not finish). I feel I beat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to do it again,'' he added, sitting in his elegantly
appointed living room as a kennel full of huskies howled outside.
Then he pauses. ``Would I want to? I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
