</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING LANGUAGE SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Language can be a tough customer, but it has its vulnerable
side, too, and many a word has had its character changed by the
company it keeps. Sheldon Brown of Newton, Mass. sees it happening
in headlines these days, when white supremacist is abbreviated to
supremacist. There are, potentially, all sorts of supremacists, so
this shortcut seems lazy and inaccurate to him.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Gordon of Wayland, Mass. has a similar problem with quality,
as in ``quality care for all.'' ``Am I a dying breed in thinking
that quality is not an adjective?'' she asks. ``Aren't we really
striving for high-quality care?''
</P>
<P>
   This shortened supremacist is a newish usage; quality is much
older, as is the debate over its adjectival use. But there's no
generalizing about the outcome of such innovations; sometimes the
new usage storms the castle, sometimes it drowns in the moat.
</P>
<P>
   Take chauvinism, for example, which traces its lineage to
Napoleonic superpatriot Nicolas Chauvin. A synonym for showy,
extreme patriotism, it was sometimes borrowed for other senses _
scientific chauvinism, cultural chauvinism _ but it kept its
essential meaning for more than a century. Then male chauvinism
(the term, not the fact) came along. And because plain old
chauvinism was relatively underused, while male chauvinism was a
key concept for the growing feminist movement, chauvinism's other
meanings faded into the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Their exile didn't last, though. Other chauvinisms _ New York,
Hindu, neighborhood _ are back, at least as frequent in these pages
as the male variety. The same may well happen to supremacist _ when
we have less reason to assume supremacists are white, and fewer
occasions for headlines about them.
</P>
<P>
   Quality, however, is not likely to be ousted from its adjectival
role. Though many of us were taught to avoid it, and some
authorities still dislike it, quality for high-quality has been
spreading since the 16th century, and dictionaries now accept it.
</P>
<P>
   But other such truncations are resisting the pressure. Explicit
still means something more than ``sexually explicit,'' despite the
influence of movie-ratings language. Graphic has the same problem,
but thanks to its usefulness in other realms, it's unlikely to be
reduced to mere code for ``filled with graphic sex/violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of another strange coinage, though, is hard to predict.
You hear it on the radio on a bad traffic day: When there's too
much to say, a curiosity slowdown _ a useful recent coinage meaning
a traffic jam caused by rubberneckers _ sometimes gets shortened to
curiosity. ``There's a pile-up on 93 North,'' the traffic guy will
say, ``creating a major curiosity southbound.'' Yes, it could
become another local language quirk, but I'm hoping it's just a
passing curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
