<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' VICTORY A PRODUCT OF PLUCK AS MUCH AS LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Understand that we will never get the
complete, unfiltered truth.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll is not going to walk into his day-after press
conference and say, ``Ernie, Sid, Dante, and the rest of us were
sitting around this morning saying, `Man, can you believe how lucky
we were Monday? I mean, take away those two sick calls, and our
season is over.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's not going to do that. Steve Mariucci is not going to do
that. Chan Gailey is not going to do that. The Tuna is not going to
do that. There might have been a time when Mike Ditka actually
would have done that, but now he is curiously neutered, so the fact
is that (itals)nobody(unitals) is going to do that, however obvious
it is to you and me that Buffalo had a legitimate victory taken
away from it at Foxboro Stadium Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But we must thank Carroll for not insulting our intelligence. He
did acknowledge his team's good fortune when asked how he would
have liked to be Buffalo coach Wade Phillips in the aftermath of
the Great Foxboro Heist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be bitter,'' Carroll acknowledged. ``I'd hate to think
you'd lose on a call in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wasn't just the bogus pass interference call on
Henry Jones _ psst, Terry, you've got to catch that ball, son _ on
what turned out to be the game's penultimate play. It was the play
before, too, and not just because Shawn Jefferson was not inbounds,
or because he was shy of the first down on top of that. No, no, no.
It was because there was a zebra standing there and (itals)he
didn't want to make the call.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happened to me,'' said Carroll, ``I'd probably be
talking the way Wade is talking. I don't know what else to tell
you, other than that I'd be reacting in bitter fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The only word to describe officiating conduct such as we
witnessed on Sunday is ``unacceptable.'' The Conduct Police
probably will wind up fining Doug Flutie, but they should fine the
official who gagged on the call three times whatever they take from
Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll says it really was pass interference in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry was shoved,'' Carroll insisted. ``He wound up moving a
long way, or else he would have caught the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Terry Glenn is a big-time, big-city wide receiver. The
ball was eminently catchable. At the same time, Carroll agreed with
what everyone has been saying about pass interference on a Hail
Mary pass; namely, that he never has seen that call made in that
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Gift that the final play was, the Patriots did indeed take
advantage of that largess. Everyone from Presque Isle to Pawcatuck
knew that Drew Bledsoe was going to be looking for Ben Coates, but
the Bills acted as if ol' number 87 was some kid off the special
teams. Earth to Buffalo: Next time the Patriots are at the 1-yard
line, forget about play-action fakes. Put four guys on Coates and
let Bledsoe figure out something else to do. In other words, let's
see if he can think as fast as Flutie does.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Carroll seems to be in the proper spirit. He knows very
well that his team remains a viable playoff contender because of
the whims of incompetent referees. He is undoubtedly realistic
enough to know that the next time he won't be so fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to another encouraging Carroll admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (itals)have(unitals) to improve,'' he said. ``There are
areas where we need to improve. The feeling in my mind is that we
need to be very balanced in dealing with what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallelujah! Praise the Lord! We have a coach who actually does
understand how fragile his team's recent ``success'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Let's skip the adjectives and verbs and rely solely on the
numbers for just a minute. Let's examine the following statistics
over the last six games, during which the Maybe They're Going To
Connecticut And Maybe They Aren't Patriots are 3-3: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rushing  &UR;  &LR; $ Rushing $ Passing  &UR;  &LR; $ Passing
</P>
<P>
   attempts $ yardage $ attempts $ &UR;  &LR; yardage
</P>
<P>
   111  &UR;  &LR; $ 250  &UR;  &LR; $ 257  &UR;  &LR; $ &UR;  &LR; 1,520
</P>
<P>
   ($ used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's more than a 6-1 ratio in favor of passing yardage. Can
this continue if the Patriots are to be successful in their
remaining four games, not to mention any playoff games they might
stumble into?
</P>
<P>
   Well, coach? Can they? Huh, huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to try to get it (i.e. the running
game) in better shape,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   This is something shy of full disclosure. We can be sure of
that. There is no way that professionals such as Carroll and Ernie
Zampese aren't scared bleepless over the deterioration of the
running game during the past two months. Neither man will ever come
right out and say, ``Geez, our offensive line can't run-block worth
a damn,'' or, ``Robert Edwards is an inconsistent runner,'' both of
which are irrefutably true facts, as we say.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have one (on-paper) easy game remaining, and even
that one, against the St. Louis Rams, has an element of peril
attached since it's on the road. Can they beat Pittsburgh, San
Francisco, and the Jets if the offense consists of Drew, Drew, and
Drew, mixed with an occasional Derrick Cullors kickoff return to
the 45?
</P>
<P>
   Are you nuts?
</P>
<P>
   The coach knows. There is no doubt whatsoever that the coach
fully realizes how little chance his team will have of winning any
more than one of the three tough games left on the schedule if
passing is forced to constitute more than 80 percent of the
offense, as it has the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a broken record on that one; I know,'' he said. ``We need
to run the football, and we are not going to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The final item is a defensive matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yardage is piling up on us in the passing game,'' Carroll
pointed out. ``We are giving up too many big plays, and normally we
are pretty good at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Examined in the sober light of day, the comeback victory over
Buffalo was a kiss from the Pigskin God, nothing more. Justice did
not prevail. The coach knows it, too, and that's very good.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep all this in mind. These things always even out in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   (ob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
