<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TAX-EQUITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET PRAGMATIST FOR THE `AVERAGE GUY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ James St. George's eyes brighten behind big round
glasses. He would like nothing better than to give you his favorite
statistical gem of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Massachusetts since 1995 have paid less of their
income (10.88 percent) in state taxes than have residents of
Mississippi (10.92 percent), says St. George, executive director of
the Tax Equity Alliance of Massachusetts and lobbyist for the
average guy. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The comparison with Mississippi says a lot about the fiscal
transformation of a state tagged only a decade ago with the
nickname, ``Taxachusetts.'' St. George, 43, hopes the comparison
won't sit well with Bay Staters.
</P>
<P>
   As TEAM's leader &UR;  &LR; during a time the lobbying organization has
suffered numerous legislative defeats, St. George culls reports for
facts and figures to hammer home a central point: Wealthy people
and businesses received the vast majority of recent tax cuts in
Massachusetts, which accounts for why Massachusetts residents have
paid less of their income in taxes than people in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   His skills as policy wonk _ polished at the Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities in Washington _ contrast to the rhetoric-slinging
of his predecessor, James Braude. But St. George's admirers argue
his quiet pragmatism may be the only way to lobby for tax policies
that favor the average person in a state Legislature dominated by
special interests and in a mood to use a budget surplus for tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Jim St. George not been there the results of this year's
tax cuts would, I believe, have been even worse'' says Arline
Isaacson, a lobbyist for the Massachusetts Teachers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is not much appetite these days on Beacon Hill for
progressive tax policy. Even before St. George's arrival two years
ago, TEAM had lost the influence the organization enjoyed during
its 1990 heyday, when Braude led the charge to defeat a ballot
question that sought a $2 billion tax rollback.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, state lawmakers passed the biggest tax
reduction in Massachusetts history, voting overwhelmingly to slash
in half the tax rate on income from stock and bond investments. The
tax package was heaped on top of big breaks granted in prior years
to financial firms and investors. In 1994, for example, capital
gains on investments held more than six years were made tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   St. George, however, has had some victories.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he &UR;  &LR;  successfully lobbied for the only &UR;  &LR; tax change
targeted to middle-class  &UR;  &LR; earners: Doubling the personal exemption
for individual taxpayers. In 1997, he helped state senators and
advocates push through a tax credit for low-income workers, making
Massachusetts one of seven states with such a provision.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his successes, St. George has big shoes to fill. Braude
had keen political instincts, and he led TEAM during an era that
was more friendly to the group's &UR;  &LR;  mission. Under Braude's
leadership, unions and human services organizations staged public
rallies over tax policy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``contentious atmosphere'' on Beacon Hill ``has been
replaced with one where there is virtually no debate on fiscal
matters,'' says Braude, who is now a political consultant. ``That
is not a very fertile environment for progressive tax reform.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Michael Widmer, president of the conservative Massachusetts
Taxpayers Foundation, says that Braude was able to argue his
position ``quickly and facilely'' during frequent debates between
the two in the Legislature. As antitax sentiment built on Beacon
Hill, Braude's brashness began rubbing people the wrong way. His
wins turned to defeats.
</P>
<P>
   While St. George is low-key, he does not possess Braude's level
of political savvy. For example, in legislative hearings in &UR;  &LR;  May
on the bill to cut taxes on dividends and interest, a Westport
woman gave gripping testimony about how the existing 12 percent tax
rate had reduced the proceeds from a life insurance policy left by
her late husband, money she used to raise her two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   When St. George testified against cutting the 12 percent rate,
he launched into his arguments and ``acted as if she didn't make
those statements,'' said one person at the hearing. ``Braude might
have played that a little differently. He would've seen the
politics of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But to St. George's credit, Beacon Hill observers say, the
deliberate crafting of his own style may be more suited to the
times.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview in his office on a narrow street across the
Boston Common from the gold-domed State House, St. George describes
that style as seeking to ``appeal to people's wisdom _ that does
make me sound naive doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``Over the past several years, there have been enough
defeats to say, `Let's try it another way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself a ``lunch-pail Democrat,'' St. George criticizes
members of the left who have taken on too many issues. Take gay
rights. Though important, says St. George, who is gay, ``it's not
as fundamental as the economic rights, the economic condition, of
people being left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   His family was among those left behind. His parents and their
six children first lived in a house on a dirt road outside Duluth,
Minn. They then moved to a house with a coal furnace in the
basement. St. George's father, a laborer for US Steel, was often
laid off, once for five months through a Minnesota winter.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, St. George joined the US Navy and went to the
University of Minnesota with funding from the GI bill. He won a
federal Harry S. Truman Scholarship, which awards tuition to one
college sophomore from each state.
</P>
<P>
   St. George, whose father is Chippewa Indian, worked on economic
development for the Native American community in Minneapolis as a
31-year-old intern for the American-Indian Business Development
Corp. He then went off to graduate school at the Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard University, where he met his partner, Mark
Sullivan, who is the director of Joseph Kennedy II's staff in the
Boston area. They moved to Washington, where St. George was an
analyst for the American Federation of State County and Muncipal
employees.
</P>
<P>
   He was then recruited to direct a project at the Center on
Budget Priorities which works &UR;  &LR; with states on shaping fiscal
policy. St. George left the center because he and Sullivan wanted
to move to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   St. George is also trying to broaden the organization's mission.
Whereas TEAM has been most focused on tax issues, St. George says
he would like to devote more time to analyzing the entire state
budget and monitoring how government spending priorities shift and
who benefits or loses from those shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Again, he plucks another statistic out of the air to demonstrate
a point: Tax policy and budget policy are inextricably linked. ``I
like to remind people,'' he says, ``that we have the worst school
buildings and the third-highest per-capita income in the nation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
