<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLEDSOE-FINGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS IMPRESSED BY BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Credit the custom-made three-quarter cast that
stabilized his finger but left the tips free to grip the football.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the ``very tiny bit'' of painkiller doctors administered
to the fracture to numb it while preserving the sensation needed to
control the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, his doctors and others say, credit quarterback
Drew Bledsoe for having the stamina and skill to steer his team to
come-from-behind triumphs in back-to-back games despite two
fractures in the index finger of his tossing hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew himself, the person, probably is the most important
part,'' said Bert Zarins, the Patriots' team physician. ``It's his
attitude, and pain tolerance, and ability to concentrate and
function in spite of distractions. That's what has gotten him where
he is and is keeping him up there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just helped him a bit, but 99 percent of the credit goes to
Drew.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sports medicine specialists were in awe of Bledsoe's
performance, much as fans were.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sucking it up on a very high scale,'' said Dr. Robert
Leach, editor of the American Journal of Sports Medicine and former
chief physician for the US Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a defensive lineman doing it, I would say he
sucked it up and that's pretty good, but a lot if not most of them
would do it,'' Leach added. ``As a receiver or passer, and with the
injury being on the hand he has to use, I think it really is very,
very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to play with pain. It's another to play with
pain, and play the whole way through, and be effective. That is
quite remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe did what he did eight days ago in Miami on his own,
shaking off his newly fractured finger to lead his team on a
last-minute, game-winning drive. Sunday evening against Buffalo,
however, he had a lot of help from the medical crew at
Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Herndon, a renowned hand specialist, took a movable
X-ray called a fluoroscopy of Bledsoe's finger to determine just
where the breaks were and how stable they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were at the outer two joints,'' Zarins said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Using that information, the hospital's Department of Orthotics
took a plastic mold of the quarterback's finger, then fitted him
with a special plastic cast on the back two-thirds of the digit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves the front of the finger exposed for sensation. It's
solid, in the same position he holds the football,'' Zarins
explained. ``It stabilizes the finger in that position but leaves
the fingertips free for sensation and control.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe will likely be wearing the splint again next week, and
for at least two more after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually takes three to four weeks to heal,'' said Zarins.
``We possibly will protect it for a week or two longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there a risk of Bledsoe reinjuring the finger by playing
Sunday? A slight one, according to Zarins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not prohibitive,'' he said. ``He didn't do anything that
I think could give him permanent harm. Football is a risky game,
nothing is without risk in football, but this was not an
unreasonable risk because he had his finger protected. We tried it
out once in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Louis Meeks, senior orthopedic surgeon at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center, agreed that the danger of reinjury was
limited: ``They didn't burn any bridges by letting him play. If it
got crooked they could make a little incision and use a little pin
or small screws to hold the bone together and it still would
heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his colleagues across the city, Arnold Scheller Jr., the
Celtics' team doctor, was profoundly impressed with what Bledsoe
did Sunday, calling it ``a gutsy job.''
</P>
<P>
   But does it rank with the kind of toughing-it-out performances
turned in regularly by Celtics legend Larry Bird, as some have
suggested? Not yet, said Scheller, who helped nurse Bird through
perpetual back pain, not to mention his inspired return after he
smashed his face on the Garden floor during the 1991 playoffs
against Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comparisons with Larry are a little early in Bledsoe's
career,'' said Scheller. ``He just hasn't had the history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
