<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENCE FLAGGING IN NFL OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Expansion has affected professional football
in many areas, none more than officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Not so many years ago, believe it or not, people seldom noticed
the officials. Certainly errors were made from time to time, but as
the first advent of instant replay demonstrated, it was far less
frequently than anyone had thought.
</P>
<P>
   But as the NFL has expanded, it needed to find more qualified
men to officiate more games, and, like quarterbacks, it seems there
are fewer of such men than the game is now demanding. A case in
point is that in a span of six days in Foxboro Stadium, the
Patriots tried to play football with two sets of officials who
seemed to have different ideas of what constitutes pass
interference in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, pass interference was nothing short of mayhem
for a crew headed by referee Ed Hochuli. Assault was allowed, and
so was battery, as long as they didn't happen simultaneously.
Patriots tight end Ben Coates, Miami middle linebacker Zach Thomas,
and New England rookie cornerback Tebucky Jones made that clear
when they all got away with mugging the opposition on various plays
without being penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, a crew led by Walt Coleman apparently defined
pass interference as letting the thought cross your mind that you
might possibly touch someone before the ball arrives if you think
no one's looking. How any team is supposed to play consistently
under such a circumstance is difficult to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're seeming to see more calls on pass
interference,'' Patriots coach Pete Carroll carefully conceded one
day after a big interference call on the Buffalo Bills at the end
of Sunday's game kept New England's playoff hopes alive. ``We were
told before the season the biggest issue is if the defensive back
is playing the ball, then contact is basically allowed but it does
seem there's been an increase in those calls recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Since no one announced a rule change, it's difficult to fathom
why that would be, but what is more difficult to fathom is why in
the Miami game Coates was allowed to run over a defensive back
while getting into position to catch a touchdown pass and later
Thomas was allowed to hold Coates's jersey and nearly drag him down
with the ball in the air and Jones was allowed to knock a receiver
over with the ball in the air and his back to it when just six days
later Henry Jones is called for barely pushing Terry Glenn on a
play when Glenn was so ``interfered'' with that the ball still hit
him in the chest before he dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember ever seeing a flag called on a Hail Mary like
that, to tell you the truth,'' Carroll said. ``At first I thought
it was on us. But after watching it, Terry was interfered with.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he was, but Shawn Jefferson was clotheslining Buffalo
defensive back Thomas Smith around the neck on the same play, and
who knows how much other pushing and shoving was going on? That is
why, in 24 years of covering the NFL, I can't think of three times
when I've seen a call made on such a last-gasp pass. So why wasn't
it a no-call Sunday, as is the longstanding tradition on such
plays? You'll never get an answer from the NFL on that.
</P>
<P>
   But, then again, why were eight penalties called during the
drive on which Buffalo took the lead, half of then assisting the
Bills dearly? Why was a Doug Flutie scramble that so obviously
ended a half-yard short of a first down ruled a first down? And why
was Jefferson's fourth-down reception on the sideline ruled
inbounds when at the very best he had only one foot inbounds and
very well may have had neither in, when the official charged with
making the call ruled him out of bounds before being talked out of
it?
</P>
<P>
   Most damning of all, though, were the claims of at least four
Bills that one official said, ``Just give it to them,'' before
Jefferson's catch was ruled good.
</P>
<P>
   If these were just isolated incidents, in one or two games, it
would be bad enough. But they are not. Such indecision and
inconsistency has become a constant drumbeat of small errors since
Jerry Seeman took over the oversight of NFL officials, and it has
begun to undermine the credibility of the game.
</P>
<P>
   What, for example, could be worse than a referee blowing a coin
flip?
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving, referee Phil Luckett went to flip a coin before
overtime in the Lions-Steelers game, as most people know by now.
Pittsburgh's Jerome Bettis was clearly heard on a CBS tape calling
``tails,'' yet Luckett insisted he heard him say ``heads-tails''
and gave the Lions the right to receive the kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Bettis, an Eagle scout by all accounts, said after the game _
which Detroit won on a field goal on the first possession _ ``I
didn't say, `heads-tails.' That's a lie. That's a bald-faced lie.''
</P>
<P>
   On the videotape, Bettis says, ``Tails.'' Period. Luckett,
however, does say, ``Call it in the air, heads-tails.'' A version
of the tape with enhanced audio done by a Pennsylvania TV station
indicates that someone says, ``heads,'' as well, but it's not
Bettis. Luckett would have had no idea who it was, though, because
he neglected to do the simplest thing. He did not look at Bettis,
which would seem to be of more import than watching the coin spin
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to think they could at least get that right,'' said
a disgusted AFC coach.
</P>
<P>
   The absurdity of it all became clear Sunday when Atlanta
linebacker Jesse Tuggle walked out for the opening coin toss
against St. Louis with a small sign that said, ``heads.'' It was an
amusing moment in what has become the ``No Fun League,'' but it
also was a sign of the mockery NFL officials have begun to bring
upon themselves by seldom admitting their errors.
</P>
<P>
   As Detroit defensive back Robert Bailey said after the Steelers
game, ``It seemed like every time you looked up at the replay on
the scoreboard, you were disappointed again.'' And that's from a
guy whose team won.
</P>
<P>
   So what can the NFL do? First, it can do what every other
professional sports league does. It can demand that officials work
full-time, all year, because, as Carroll pointed out Monday, ``Who
wants to go to a part-time doctor?''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean they'd do a better job? You'd have to think so,
if they're spending each week watching tape of the two teams
they're about to work and studying possible odd circumstances or
mistakes of the past. Perhaps they even could visit the training
sites of the teams one day apiece to briefly explain how they call
certain actions, something they already do during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Second, bring back instant replay. At least for the coin flip.
</P>
<P>
   Third, hire people with no connection to the officials to run
the replay operation, instead of ex-members of the fraternity who
have been reluctant to overrule their brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, make the damn calls and get on with it. There are more
powwows in NFL stadiums than there used to be on the land of the
Plains Indians. It's fine that officials want to get things right,
but constant meetings and flags flying from 40 yards away are doing
as much to undermine our faith in the game as the blown calls
themselves are.
</P>
<P>
   Last, stop insulting everyone's intelligence about how often
mistakes are made. No human being is right all the time, not even
Jerry Seeman. Officiating a high-speed game played by huge men is
impossible to do perfectly, so when mistakes are made, say so.
Don't say you heard ``heads-tails'' when (A) the guy didn't say it,
and has got audio to prove it, and (B) you wouldn't know anyway,
because you didn't even look at him.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that NFL officials are trying to do their best
each Sunday, but no one can argue anymore that their best is good
enough. It is time commissioner Paul Tagliabue and most of all
George Young, who deeply loves the pro game and is now in charge of
its quality in many ways from New York, step in and admit that
changes have to be made _ before the fans start to think there is
more going on here than simple human error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
