<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S THE CASE AGAINST THE PRESIDENT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- When the maneuvering overshadows the case, we
reach for our collection of one-liners about lawyers and pols.
</P>
<P>
   But when the maneuvering is the case, an air sickness bag is
more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   As the endgame (we hope) of you-know-what nears, for example,
House Republicans scrambling for 218 impeachment votes are
privately beseeching independent counsel Ken Starr for help in
firming up GOP ``yes'' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the official answer is ``no,'' but the fact is that
timing considerations are involved in pending decisions about the
possible charging of peripheral figures in the Monica Lewinsky
case. Any pre-Christmas indictments will have been sought with
Starr's knowledge that they can be fairly interpreted as a form of
lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, House Judiciary Committee Republicans are talking
about putting out still another videotape, this one of President
Clinton's deposition in the Paula Jones suit last January. Like the
release two months ago of Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony,
the purpose would be to sway opinion on the House floor, just as
the grand jury tape was supposed to sway voter opinion until it
backfired.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just for starters. As the endgame progresses, so to
speak, four schools of ``thought'' are converging almost like
vehicles fated to arrive at an intersection in the same, horrific
moment. The result will make an absurd shambles out of the remnants
of what was conceived in the 18th century as the last line of
constitutional defense against presidential abuse. Three come from
the president's opponents, but the Democrats are making a
contribution of their own. And all of the schools of thought share
a fanatical desire to avoid actual consideration of a case for
impeachment based on direct evidence for a reason that can be
summarized in three letters, s-e-x.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the Democrats first, the typical response in the House is
that the allegations contained in Starr's original referral and
Judiciary Committee counsel David Schippers's rewriting of them
don't come within a country mile of what the framers meant to be
impeachable offenses. It is the political equivalent of a dismissal
motion in criminal court or a request for summary judgment in a
civil matter. It is willing to assume, for argument's sake, the
veracity of Starr's allegations without testing it.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans similarly are looking for ways around the
evidence, such as:
</P>
<P>
   _In their latest formal statements in response to Hyde's 81
questions, the GOP members are typically saying that Clinton and
his lawyers have not provided exculpatory evidence that refutes
Starr's charges, as if that were the defendant's burden in this
country. In fact, he has.
</P>
<P>
   _The Republicans also are selling their House members the line
that a vote on impeachment is the rough equivalent of a grand jury
indictment and that therefore the mere fact of allegedly serious
charges should be enough to prompt a vote to ``send it to the
Senate'' for trial. This challenges the Watergate precedent, in
which House Judiciary Committee members approached the issue of
Richard Nixon's guilt as jurors needing to be convinced by the
evidence beyond any reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   _The GOP membership is also being told that the House is not the
proper forum for consideration of alternative approaches like
formal censure, these being more appropriate for the Senate in a
``punishment'' phase.
</P>
<P>
   All of this babble obscures the absence of a case against the
president as most people would understand the term _ meaning direct
evidence from witnesses and/or documents. Above all, both parties
are ignoring the crux of the entire matter _ whether Clinton
committed perjury in the Jones deposition and compounded it before
the grand jury because he answered ``no'' to the Jones lawyers'
question about is relationship with Lewinsky based on a tortured
definition of sex, and they are ignoring it because, as Starr
discovered to his regret, the only way to confront it is to focus
on the president's and Lewinsky's versions of what each did to the
other physically in private.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Judiciary Committee is likely to send to the floor
a piece of junk in which the only witness has been the prosecutor
himself, and the only evidence has been the uncross-examined
testimony and statements of witnesses _ most of which (Monica
Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan, Betty Currie, the president, to name four)
conflict on key points and disagree with Starr's selective
characterizations of their information.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast to the solemnity and care taken during Watergate 24
years ago could not be more complete, or more damning.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
