<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-01 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEED AND THE EGG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, the election results in Massachusetts last
month (November) could be taken as the repudiation of an old
progressive dream by a new one _ the dream of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   First voters obliterated _ by a ratio of four to one _ the
80-year-old distinction between ``earned'' and ``unearned'' income.
It was the largest ``yes'' vote in the history of ballot
initiatives. They backed a decision by the Legislature last summer
to roll back the old 12 percent tax on savings and investment
income to the same 5.95 percent that workers pay on wages. (That
was Question 3 on the ballot.)
</P>
<P>
   Next, citizens ratified the state's plan to deregulate publicly
traded electric utilities. Price competition in electricity rates
will begin in earnest next year. (That was Question 4.)
</P>
<P>
   In a state long noted for its enthusiasm for progressive
taxation _ in which many traditional modes of government regulation
of commerce and banking literally were invented _ such measures run
pretty strongly against perceived stereotypes. Look a little
deeper, however, and you'll find the state remained true to form.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the double tax on savings &UR;  &LR; and investment income is
the third and final triumph for those, led by former Governor
William Weld, who have sought to bring Massachusetts' tax profile
into line with other states. It follows recent reductions in
inheritance taxes (1994) and in the treatment of long-term capital
gains (starting in 1996.) ``This was the last sore thumb.'' says
Michael Widmer, executive director of the Massachusetts Taxpayers
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Only the cumbersome oversight by the attorney general of the
Division of Revenue's conduct of tax administration remains to be
eliminated before ``Taxachusetts'' ceases to exist as a statistical
fact.
</P>
<P>
   No one who believes that the keys to economic growth are peace,
low taxes, and a tolerable administration of justice can be sorry
to see the prohibitive 12 percent tax bracket go. It is difficult
to retain a highly skilled work force and foster the kind of
economic development that benefits the poor when taxes are
seriously out of line.
</P>
<P>
   Look a little harder at what happened in November, however, and
you may conclude that Massachusetts once again is in the vanguard
of those seeking the betterment of the human condition. Doubling
the income tax exemption (from $4,400 to $8,800 for couples filing
jointly) and thereby maintaining a degree of progressivity,
important though it was, was the least of it.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away on the ballot last month was an initiative that
points the way to serious political reform in the 21st century.
That was Question 2, a mechanism for socializing the funding of
elections, which passed by a 2-1 ratio. The Clean Elections
Initiative befits an American community that for nearly 400 years
has distinguished itself among all the others by a pair of traits:
ingenuity and its social conscience. The Clean Elections Initiative
was designed to short-circuit the power of money to buy elections
through lavish campaign contributions. Statewide candidates who
raise modest qualifying funds receive public funding for the rest
of their campaigns, within agreed-upon spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to spend more may raise it privately _ but
opponents would recieve comparable support from public funds.
``Soft'' money _ contributions funneled through party organizations
_ would be banned. Such a mechanism could begin to restore the
balance between public and private. It could serve eventually as a
model for the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to feel much sorrow about the demise of the double
tax rate on investment income. It was based on an outmoded and
ultimately wrong idea about the sources of economic growth. The
voters who repudiated it by such a lopsided margin clearly were
influenced by the 15-year boom in asset prices _ and the fact that
mutual funds have surpassed banks as a vehicle for savings. But it
is Question 2 that was exciting, even though many impediments
remain. The Legislature, which is generally opposed to it, must
appropriate the funds for its implementation, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, the poet James Russell Lowell discerned in the
rise of the New England town meeting the law of unintended
consequences: ``Puritanism, believing itself quick with the seed of
religious liberty, laid without knowing it, the egg of democracy.''
The tax revolt may have done something of the sort in our own time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
