<HEADLINE>
CONCENTRA PROVES A TEXTBOOK CASE FOR YOUNG FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We should all be this loved.
</P>
<P>
   Months after it was formed by the merger of two smaller
companies, Concentra Managed Care Inc. of Boston had won over the
stock brokerages and institutional investors who work Wall Street
with breathtaking success.
</P>
<P>
   Concentra, which helps manage workers' compensation cases for
corporate clients, made the Zacks Investors Service monthly list of
most widely recommended stocks early this year. First Call Corp.
pinpoints the apex of Concentra's popularity as Jan. 12, when 13
brokerage analysts carried ``strong buy'' recommendations and four
others rated it a ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Concentra's list of leading institutional owners read like a
who's who of aggressive growth mutual funds: two big Putnam
Investments funds owned a combined 4.6 million shares. T. Rowe
Price New Horizons, AIM Constellation, and AIM Aggressive Growth
were also among 13 funds that each owned more than 500,000 shares
of Concentra.
</P>
<P>
   But things changed. Concentra's performance faltered, though not
drama-tically. Then its chief executive departed abruptly. Many big
investors fled, and the stock plunged by nearly 80 percent from
January highs in its darkest moments. Perhaps worst of all, a
series of unpleasant surprises has damaged the credibility of
Concentra's managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you've got a period of three to nine months in which it is
a show-me stock,'' said Brian Stack, a mutual fund manager at
Massachusetts Financial Services who owns a large block of
Concentra. ``Given all the ambiguities in the market in general and
in health care in particular, it's kind of cast a pall over the
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Concentra has formed a special board committee and
hired investment bankers to evaluate unsolicited offers from
unidentified suitors. A New York venture capital firm, involved
with two public health care companies taken private this year, has
acquired 4.3 million Concentra shares in the last two months and
left its options open in public securities filings.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh, Carson, Anderson &AMP; Stowe, which now owns about 10 percent
of Concentra's stock, struck a $290 million deal last month to take
private Centennial Healthcare Corp. of Atlanta and this summer
joined Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. to pull off a similar
arrangement with Medcath Inc. of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh, Carson has more than a passing interest in Concentra and
its managers. It helped fund one of the two merged firms that
created the company and one of its executives sat on Concentra's
board before resigning in May. Welsh, Carson also invested $38
million this year in Magella Healthcare Corp., a private
neonatology physician practice management firm operated by John K.
Carlyle, Concentra's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Concentra chief executive Dan Thomas, named to that post just
six weeks ago, said the board committee was examining offers and
would soon be presented with an operating budget for 1999. ``The
board and the special committee have to evalute that,'' Thomas
said. ``They are valuing the company and deciding what makes the
most sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe Concentra still has a reasonably bright
future, though not at the pace of growth that was once assumed. But
even they aren't sure how long the battered stock would need to
recover and whether it's worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing new about a young company facing stern
punishment by the market for its missteps. In fact, Concentra
became a textbook example of how the market can embrace and drop
growing companies with the subtlety of a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Concentra was created in the summer of 1997 by the merger of two
companies that did not compete but worked the same kind of clients.
</P>
<P>
   CRA Managed Care of Boston and its chief, Donald Larson,
administered and managed workers' compensation cases, oversight
that could help limit expenses and get employees back on the job
faster. Occusystems Inc. was a Texas-based physician practice
management company that specialized in treating workers' comp
patients. Carlyle was the chief executive and Thomas served as his
number two at Occusystems.
</P>
<P>
   Their merger made Concentra the biggest company in its field.
Practice management companies were hot on Wall Street and the case
administration was seen as an engine for internal growth.
</P>
<P>
   Larson took over as chief executive of the combined company.
Carlyle became chairman, but gave up the position months later, and
Thomas became president by January. In the first quarters,
Concentra committed one of the most dangerous acts for a young
public company. It beat Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't last. Concentra's results for the second quarter of
1998 disappointed and analysts began to worry, mostly about the
company's physician practice management.
</P>
<P>
   Concentra shares, which had traded above 30 through most of the
spring, plunged to their lowest point on Sept. 8 when the firm
announced third-quarter performance would fall short of
expectations and more problems were expected in the final quarter.
Concentra stock fell to 6 3/32 that day, but even more problems
were about to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days later, Larson resigned without explanation and, by
Sept. 25, had given up his board seat. Carlyle returned as chairman
and, with Thomas moving up, reformed the team that had run
Occusystems. Thomas declined to comment on the management change
and Larson did not recall a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, guidance Concentra managers had given to
institutional investors and analysts about the third quarter proved
to be wrong. Earnings were even worse than expected and problems
that had never been discussed suddenly surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty significant disappointment,'' said analyst
Robert Mains of Advest Inc. ``Concentra had been billed as a
company that could sustain 30 percent growth and I think that was
overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts today are reluctant to recommend Concentra, but
most like its business. Mains offers a buy recommendation, but that
has as much to do with the prospects of sale as anything else. Most
believe Concentra stock, which finished Monday at 11 13/16, would
be worth 15 per share or perhaps more in a deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One possible wild card in Concentra's future: Larson. He still
owns about 1.7 million shares and could influence how and whether a
deal takes place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity watcher Eric Kobren, who once worked for money manager
Scott Black's Delphi Management Inc. in Boston, has enlisted his
old friend to run a mutual fund. The fund, Kobren Delphi Value,
marks the first time Kobren Insight Management in Wellesley has
teamed with an outside manager. Kobren Insight now offers three
mutual funds, which invest in other funds. Delphi manages about $1
billion in institutional assets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
