<HEADLINE>
MARADONA RETAINS BOLDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a serendipity about two of the most outspoken figures
in Italian soccer being at the Stadio Olimpico in Rome Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Maradona and Zdenek Zeman did not come close to meeting,
however. Maradona was in the VIP section with his wife, Claudia
Villafanes, and advisers. He had returned to Italy for the first
time in seven years, thanks mostly to Zeman, who was on the field,
coaching AS Roma to a 3-3 tie with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Zeman's observations about drugs in Italian soccer led to a
judicial inquiry, lifting the lid off some scandalous coverups,
similar to the charges Maradona made when he was suspended for
cocaine use in 1991. Maradona returned to testify in Turin and to
collect more than $300,000 for appearing on a television variety
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw me out the window like a delinquent,'' Maradona
said upon his return. ``Now, I want to return through the front
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Maradona always has claimed that drug testing is selective, and
that he was a victim of a conspiracy. Certainly, the singling out
and banning of Maradona during the 1994 World Cup was an obvious
punishment for his campaign against former FIFA president Joao
Havelange. Maradona claimed to have purchased an over-the-counter
spray containing ephedrine from a Tremont Street pharamacy. After
Argentina's 2-1 win over Nigeria at Foxboro Stadium, he was
selected for a ``random'' test, then banned.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Maradona tested positive for cocaine while playing for
Napoli in 1991. He departed in disgrace, returned in good form for
USA '94, and with teams in Argentina and Spain, but mostly has been
discredited and ignored by the powers that be ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Maradona is not an angel, though millions of Neapolitans regard
him as a deity, but his contention about selective enforcement has
proven to be correct.
</P>
<P>
   Since the investigating judge, Raffaele Guariniello, started
proceedings, the head of the drug-testing center at Aqua Acetosa
has resigned, there have been revelations of urine samples
disappearing, and positive tests being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Maradona always has made establishment figures uncomfortable,
sometimes because of his lower-class background, more often because
he is un-afraid to state his unvarnished comments. Few sided with
him when he was down.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Maradona has continued to attack soccer's
hierarchy. Now, his words have a better chance of being seriously
considered. But there is a danger that Maradona _ like Zeman _ will
be portrayed as a prophet of doom.
</P>
<P>
   You do not have to be a Maradona acolyte to admire his boldness.
He retains the directness, the street smarts, and ingenuousness of
his background. Maradona is described as a ``rebel with a cause''
by Argentine author Sergio Levinsky, who notes that Maradona is
uncomfortable with compromise and diplomacy, unlike Pele, the man
he succeeded as the king of soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Maradona possesses saintly qualities _ the ability to
attract a massive following, to inspire through almost magical
conjuring abilities on the field. After he was placed on an
unrealistically high pedestal, many forces emerged to bring him
down. The enormous amount of money that was invested in gambling on
Napoli, much of it in the black market, virtually trapped Maradona.
He also signed a long-term contract that further restricted his
freedom. Eventually, the only escapes Maradona could find were
self-destruction and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should Maradona be crucified for drug use or Zeman shot as
the messenger of bad news. There have been major problems with
drugs in soccer for many years.
</P>
<P>
   At the top levels, soccer is a punishing game, and players are
pushed beyond reasonable limits for the purpose of generating more
money. Recently, the influences of television have increased the
pressure for more games, and a fast-er-paced game, which could be
taking an even greater physical toll.
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Maradona easily can become addicted to
pain-killing injections. Dependence on other drugs is a natural
progression.
</P>
<P>
   As Maradona testified, his cocaine use was ``a personal problem.
Cocaine certainly did not help me play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer, unlike size-and-strength-based sports such as basketball
and football, still places a premium on skill and tactical
awareness. This gives it a built-in resistance to rampant use of
so-called ``performance-enhancing'' anabolic steroids. But this
resistance erodes as more emphasis is placed on physicality over
technique. Substances such as creatine have become popular to help
increase muscle mass, others to accelerate recovery from injury.
</P>
<P>
   Maradona came from the poorest sections of Lanus, on the
outskirts of Buenos Aires. He now stays in the most expensive
hotels on the Via Veneto in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Should Maradona be obliged to set a saintly example for all? Or
should he simply be accepted as a flawed human being with
exceptional athletic talent and the courage to speak the truth?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Argentina celebrates
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Argentina hardly missed Maradona. His former team,
Boca Juniors, won the Apertura Championship for the first time
since 1992 and has a 12-0-5 record with two games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After Boca's clinching 0-0 tie with Independiente, millions of
fans began celebrating across the country. Boca supporters claim
more than half of Argentina's 31 million population, and the
estimate is only slightly exaggerated. One fan died of heart
failure at La Bombonera, Boca's stadium, an Uruguayan fan was shot
in a Buenos Aires suburb, and dozens of arrests were made around
the country. Two days before the game, a 6-year-old student was
expelled from school for dying his hair in the shape of a
blue-and-gold (Boca's colors) heart.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster was inspired by striker  &UR; Martin Palermo &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is
certain to be transferred to an Italian or Spanish club. Also on
the way to Europe could be  &UR; Carlos Bianchi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been
mentioned as a replacement for Barcelona coach  &UR; Louis Van
Gaal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; if Barca wants to honor Van Gaal's $5.7 million buyout
clause. Bianchi struggled with AS Roma and likely wants another
chance in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Another Argentine coach on the rise is  &UR; Enzo Trossero &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is
interested in moving to the US. Trossero, 45, has been head coach
at Sion in Switzerland, and Huracan, Estudiantes de La Plata, Colon
de Santa Fe, and San Martin de Tucuman in Argentia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
