<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY, YES, TRAVEL NO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celebrities get to travel a lot. But that doesn't mean they're
always aware of their surroundings, as evidenced in these quotes
from ``Stupid Celebrities: Over 500 of the Most Idiotic Things Ever
Said by Famous People'' by Ross and Kathryn Petras (Andrews McMeel,
$9.95):
</P>
<P>
   _``Where's Austria?'' _ attributed to actor-singer David
Hasselhoff, after being told he had gold albums in that country.
</P>
<P>
   _``New Jersey?'' _ actress Tori Spelling, when asked what the
capital of New York is.
</P>
<P>
   _``I can't really remember the names of the clubs we went to.''
_ basketball star Shaquille O'Neal, when asked if he visited the
Parthenon while in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   _``Out here, young man, we pronounce it Ohio.'' _ producer Sam
Goldwyn, after a newly signed actor told him he was from Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   _``Somewhere near Africa.'' _ singer-actor Barbra Streisand,
describing where Rangoon is.
</P>
<P>
   _``Oh, dear. Who was she?'' _ actress Joan Crawford, upon being
told that the Japanese had destroyed Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  Which of these countries is not landlocked: Zambia,
Afghanistan, Cambodia, Paraguay, or all four? (Answer at end of
column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  Los Angeles may have smog, but some parts of Hawaii
have vog _ smog caused by the gases emitted by a volcano.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``To travel is to discover that everyone is wrong about
other countries.'' _ Aldous Huxley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson:  &LR; A Saugus, Mass. man reports that
he once tried to get a meal late at night in Rome but was told,
``The chicken is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Big bucks: &LR;  For $1.5 million, you can book the 155-room Fizpatrick
Grand Central Hotel in New York City from Dec. 31, 1999, to Jan. 2,
2000. Thus, you and your closest friends can ring in the False
Millennium in style. For more information, call 800-367-7701.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And the winner is:  &LR; Marianne Cusick of Randolph, N.J., was the
lucky 1 millionth passenger on Boston Duck Tours. In addition to
winning a boatload of ducky prizes for herself, she won 1 million
in pennies (that's $10,000) to be given to her favorite charity, El
Primer Pasa (The First Step), a preschool in Dover, N.J., that
teaches English to Hispanic children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie: &LR;  Central Florida loop tours wind through Lake County,
taking drivers through historic communities and showing them
countryside vistas _ in short, the ``real'' Florida. For a brochure
describing 10 of these off-the-beaten-path tours, call the Lake
County Convention and Visitors Bureau at 800-798-1071 or the
Central Florida Convention and Visitors Bureau at 800-828-7655. For
more information on Lake County, visit www.lakecountyfl.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mailbag: &LR;  Bob McGee of Westborough, Mass. offers an inexpensive way
of seeing Nepal, a destination featured in a recent Travel section:
``Fly to Katmandu, spend a few days there, then take the minibus to
Pokhara. From that city, you can trek to different villages in the
Himalayas. You don't need a guide. Simply follow the trails with a
backpack and a few dollars. You can stay in the villages for very
little money while traveling at your own pace.'' McGee spent a
month trekking in Nepal in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   To Basil of Boston: Sorry, but Qantas says its name does stand
for Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Services Ltd., which
is what we said last week, give or take a couple of letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Cambodia is not landlocked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
