<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATE AS YOU STROLL AND SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best things about the holiday season is that it
provides a good excuse to get away for a weekend filled with
relaxing things to do and the holiday spirit.
</P>
<P>
   New England resort towns in particular love to hold holiday
strolls _ weekends filled with caroling, festivities, and shopping
far from the crowded malls. You might even save money on the
shopping spree.
</P>
<P>
   Such festivities are all the more interesting when you consider
Christmas wasn't celebrated until the 1830s in puritanical New
England.
</P>
<P>
   In its earliest days, Bethlehem ``was clothed with primeval
upland grandeur and beautified by nature's own adornment,'' an 1883
history noted. This Bethelem is in New Hampshire, and it was named
on Dec. 25, 1799. The weekend of Dec. 4-6 is an ideal time to
visit. The town will be festive, you can send your cards with a
Bethlehem postmark (the post office is staying open late on Dec.
5), and there are farms where you can cut your own tree. Weekend
events include a crafts fair, a homes and inns tours ($10), a gala
dinner ($20 adult, $10 children) followed by a gingerbread house
auction on Dec. 4, children's activities, snow sculpting, and more.
For complete information and ticket purchases, call the Bethlehem
Chamberof Commerce at 603-869-3409.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem lives also in Connecticut. The 18th annual Bethlehem
Christmas Town Festival will be Dec. 4 from 5 p.m. to 10 p.m. and
Dec. 5 from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. There will be arts and crafts, music,
and the opportunity to have your cards mailed with an
artist-designed cachet from the Bethlehem Post Office, where for 60
years more than 250,000 people have had their cards posted. (If you
can't make it to Bethlehem, Postmaster Joan Manzi said her staff is
happy to receive packages of cards, open them, and then stamp
individually; for details, call 203-266-7910). Other festivities
include open houses, a tree lighting, and a visit to the
17th-century Neapolitan creche at the Abbey of Regina Laudis on
Flanders Road. More than 80 porcelain figures preside over the
Madonna and Christ Child. Next door at the Abbey's Little Art Shop
are some wonderful handmade Christmas gifts. Also available in
Bethlehem is a limited edition pewter Christmas ornament produced
by Carey Cabin Pewter. For more information on Bethlehem's
festival, call 203-266-5557.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Litchfield Hills area is an open house tour of
Washington, Conn., homes on Dec. 12 (call 860-567-4162 for
details), and from Dec. 12-23 the annual Hands On Toy Train Display
will be held at the Railroad Station in New Milford. For
information on those activities, lodging, and other events, call
the Litchfield Hills Travel Council at 860-567-4506.
</P>
<P>
   In New London, N.H., ``Christmas in Our Towns'' offers all the
festivities plus shopping discounts. Festivities begin Dec. 4 at 5
p.m. with a twilight parade down Main Street, followed by caroling
and events at a Christmas Village designed by Tomie de Paola, a
children's author/illustrator and resident. On Dec. 5 and 6, there
will be a Christmas Walk &AMP; Ski. Shoppers buying a special button
for $3 get to save 10 percent on purchases at participating stores,
and on Dec. 6 the button allows skiing at Mount Sunapee Resort for
just $20. Button sales ?proceeds? and part of the lift ticket price
go to a local charity. For a complete guide to these and other
December events, call toll free, 877-526-6575.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Snow in southern Vermont marks the Nights Before Christmas
through Dec. 24. There will be visits by Santa Lucia and her
helpers, tree lightings, a live nativity manger, fanciful
gingerbread houses, snowmobile races, snowboarding events, and the
Women's East Cup Slalom ski competition. Mount Snow is about 2 1/2
hours from Boston. For more information on events and lodging, call
toll free 877-VTSOUTH.
</P>
<P>
   Nantucket island modestly claims that walking through the town
of Nantucket on any December day makes one feel like a character in
a Dickens novel. Curtis Barnes, Nantucket's town crier for the last
24 years, goes farther, saying, ``Nantucket during December is the
remedy for the `bah humbugs.''' Nantucket's Noel festivities
continue through New Year's Eve and include theatrical and choral
performances, concerts, holiday and crafts shows, and the annual
Gingerbread House competition. Nantucket's famed stroll is Dec.4-6,
with most events on Dec. 5. With only 1,200 licensed hotel/guest
rooms on the island, accommodations book fast. For last-minute
reservations, call Visitor Services at 508-228-0925. The island is
easily reached by airplane and ferry, including a one-hour
high-speed ferry service.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one of the best holiday celebrations is held on Cape
Cod in the picturesque village of Sandwich _ the oldest town on the
Cape. Festivities run from Dec. 3 through Dec. 12 and include
caroling by candlelight, a live Nativity scene, holiday home tours,
a door decorating contest, church fairs, open house in shops,
seasonal plays, visits with Santa Claus, distinctly decorated
museums, and a Jingle Bell Walk. For a complete schedule of events,
call the Cape Cod Canal Region Chamber of Commerce at 508-759-6000.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Plantation (508-888-3300) will be open with free
admission Dec. 5 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. and Dec. 6 from noon to 4
p.m. with a holiday boutique featuring handmade crafts, pictures
with Santa in the museum's 1913 Ford Touring Car (at noon on both
days), decorated trees, and a special exhibit by the Barnstable
County Garden Railway Society.
</P>
