<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-01 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Railway Society.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most events are repeated both weekends in Sandwich. Bring your
Christmas cards and have them sent with a special Sandwich
pictorial cancellation (available both weekends). There's so much
that you'll probably want to stay over: The Dan'l Webster Inn
(508-888-3622) is a great choice.
</P>
<P>
   Just up Route 6A, you might also want to take in the Yarmouth
Port Christmas Stroll on Dec. 6 from 1 p.m. to 4 p.m. The
bed-and-breakfast innkeepers will offer tours, the Yarmouth
Colonial Minutemen will be marching, there will be music,
entertainment, raffles, jewelry-making demonstrations, and food _
hot dogs, chili, cotton candy, hot chocolate _ will be served at
various locations along the stroll. Events end with the lighting of
the Christmas tree on the Village Green. Parking areas will be
marked, and there will be free shuttle service to the various
sites.
</P>
<P>
   On Cape Cod, Orleans will mark Christmas in the Old Town, Dec.
12-13. The Historical Society will have its Meeting House decorated
with a Santa Claus exhibit and an Angel Tree with handmade angel
ornaments. There also will be a Christmas stroll, music programs,
caroling, and more. With reservations, the Barley Neck Inn is
offering an Angelic Repast both evenings (call 508-255-8355).
</P>
<P>
   A lively weekend is promised in Provincetown, Dec. 4-6, when it
marks Holly Folly, the Annual Gay and Lesbian Holiday Festival.
Adding to the festivities is the Provincetown Monument, with more
than 5,000 lights on the 255-foot structure. There will be live
music, entertainment, dining, house tours, shopping, and even time
for quiet walks along the sand dunes. Last year's festival was a
huge success, so if you're thinking of heading that way, call now
for reservations. For information, call 888-830-1843.
</P>
<P>
   In the Berkshires, Stockbridge will have its ninth annual
Holiday House tour Dec. 5 from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. as one part of its
weekend-long Stockbridge Main Street at Christmas. The weekend is
inspired by Norman Rockwell's famous painting of the Main Street
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Now if you'd like to see New England before it celebrated
Christmas, head to Old Sturbridge Village, where the 1830s village
will mark ``The Beginnings of a New England Christmas'' from 10
a.m. to 6 p.m., Dec. 6, 13, and 20.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jack Larkin, the village's director of research,
the Puritans who founded New England held profound religious
convictions and were determined to ``prune away'' everything not
directly commanded or described in the Bible. The Bible never gives
the date of the birth of Christ, and most Puritans considered
Christmas a pagan festival. In the 1830s, Larkin noted, New
Englanders were just hearing about Christmas in ``far off places
like New York'' and perhaps worrying that their children might
accept Christmas and abandon their Puritan traditions.
</P>
<P>
   So, head out to Old Sturbridge Village and learn more about the
holiday's origins, enjoy 19th-century parlor games, hearthside
tales, music, and dance, and stroll the candle-litvillage at dusk.
Old Sturbridge is located near the intersection of the Mass. Pike
and Interstate 84. For information, call 800-SEE 1830.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Polar Express
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate this holiday season though the eyes of a child as
Chris Van Allsburg's festive and heartwarming Christmas tale, ``The
Polar Express,'' comes to life at Steamtown National Historic Site
in Scranton, Pa. The story, which features a magical Christmas Eve
journey to the North Pole on steam-powered train, is sure to
captivate young audiences, who ride through Steamtown's own winter
wonderland while feasting on cookies and hot cocoa. The Polar
Express runs Dec. 14 through Dec. 28, with three trips from 4:30
p.m. through 7:30 p.m. Tickets are $7.50 and can be obtained by
calling 888-693-9391.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Disney celebrates
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, what can you expect at Walt Disney World in Florida this
holiday season? A lot. Take 130 tractor-trailer truckloads of
decorations; 126,000 red, white, and pink poinsettias; 5.2 miles of
garland; 1,200 Christmas trees; 760 feet along Residential Street
at Disney-MGM Studios, where you can view the Spectacle of Lights
that includes two 30-foot tall holiday carousels, 20 giant candles,
20 snowmen, 50 Mickey Mouse figures, 50 bells, 178 angels, 100,000
bulbs illuminating the 70-foot Tree of Lights and 4 million holiday
lights; 11 countries dressed for ``Holidays around the World'' at
Epcot; a 50-piece orchestra with a live mass choir for Disney's
Candlelight Processional at Epcot; 18,000 decorated red apples at
Fort Wilderness Resort; a 100 percent chance of snow flurries
during Mickey's Very Merry Christmas Party; 5,000 square feet of
outdoor ice-skating rink frozen solid; great shows; lots of fun;
and a lot more for a great holiday getaway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Coolidge yule
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A free Christmas Open House will be held at the President Calvin
Coolidge State Historic Site on Dec. 12 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. The
Coolidge Birthplace will be decorated in the style of 1872, the
year Coolidge was born. ``A few evergreen boughs, some fruits and
nuts, perhaps a small gift or two _ that was a Coolidge
Christmas,'' said William Jenney, site admisistrator. The Plymouth
Notch, Vt., site is a pristine mountain village that remains much
as it was when Calvin sledded down hillsides as a boy. Treats from
the past can be found at the Florence Cilley General Store,
formerly owned by the president's father, and the Plymouth Cheese
Factory (unique granular curd cheese), where cheese is made the
same way it has been since 1890 when Coolidge's father and three
area farmers started the business. Also check out historic spinning
and tabletop knitting activities, and attend a carol service at
7:30 p.m. (seating is limited, so arrive early).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lantern tours
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What will Mrs. Buckingham do now that her son, Henry, has run
off and made a pet of her Christmas dinner goose? Will Henry's
sister, Mary, wait for her beloved Tom Greenman as he heeds the
call of the sea? The answers to these burning questions can be
found by embarking on a Mystic Seaport Lantern Light Tour. Now in
their 20th season, the tours are offered from Dec. 3 through Dec.
20, Thursday through Sunday evenings. Tours depart every 15 minutes
from 5 p.m. and take about an hour and 10 minutes. Reservations are
required ($18 adult, $14 for youths 5-15; not recommended for those
under 5); call 888-9-SEAPORT.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trek for disabled
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A guided trekking expedition to Everest Base Camp for the
physically disabled is being offered by Guided Journeys. ``Nepal
has an incredible trekking infrastructure, which has opened the
door to disabled travelers that otherwise could not visit the
Himalaya,'' said Kimberly Balaza of Guided Journeys. Depending on
individual ambulatory levels, clients have the option of walking
the trail independently, walking with the assistance of trained
Sherpa guides, traveling by yak or in a basket carried by a Sherpa.
For information on the 23-day trek, call 800-543-1171.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cape Air to San Juan
