</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGEGAN-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGEGAN AND ORCHESTRA MAKE MERRY WITH HAYDN, STRAUSS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As music director of San Francisco's acclaimed
Philharmonia Baroque Orchestra, English conductor Nicholas McGegan
is closely associated with the operas, oratorios and concertos of
the Baroque era.
</P>
<P>
   That his experience and musical sympathies extend far beyond
that era has been evident in his appearances with the Houston
Symphony. The latest was a charming evening of music by Elgar,
Haydn and Richard Strauss, heard Saturday evening in Jones Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners could savor the performance of Haydn's ``Military''
Symphony (No. 100) for a very long time. Buoyant, brisk and tautly
unveiled, it nonetheless showed that Haydn's music was not merely
an exemplary model of classical form.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction, for example, McGegan established a mood of
crisp, elegant intimacy that was perfect preparation for ominous
interjection soon to follow from the winds. Here was music with
great drama and feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The nickname ``Military'' comes from Haydn's use of the bass
drum, cymbal and triangle in the second movement.
</P>
<P>
   The regular occurrence of such music in Haydn's period reflected
the then-current Viennese craze for Turkish things (as well as the
lurking military threat of the Ottoman Empire in the nearby Balkan
peninsula). As late as the early 1820s, the idiom popped up in the
last movement of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Thought similar ``militaristic'' elements occur elsewhere in the
symphony, for McGegan it was an occasion for almost happy-go-lucky
music-making _ a celebration in the spirit of the holidays.
Propulsive tempos, brilliantly clear textures and a sure sense of
pacing brought sustained listening pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason McGegan could achieve the transparency and
crispness was the reduced-size orchestra available during the
holiday week. The other was the consistently fine playing.
</P>
<P>
   McGegan put both to splendid use in Strauss' Suite from ``Le
Bourgeois gentilhomme,'' written for a chamber orchestra (36
players Saturday evening).
</P>
<P>
   The suite emerged from an odd project now principally known for
the opera ``Ariadne auf Naxos.'' In 1912, Strauss and librettist
Hugo von Hofmannsthal staged an opera-within-a-play centered on the
Moliere comedy ``Le Bourgeois gentilhomme.''
</P>
<P>
   The project flopped because the evening was too long, and few
people attending it could decide whether it was drama or opera. So
Strauss retrieved the opera and, later, a suite of incidental music
for the play itself.
</P>
<P>
   The suite reflects both Strauss' superb skills of orchestration
and his equally sure instinct for conveying drama, character and
mood through music. Here, it is chock-full of interesting sounds
and funny aural descriptions, as in the lumbering gait heard in
``The Entrance and Dance of the Tailors.''
</P>
<P>
   The suite's core spirit is intimate, centered musically on the
frequent playing of string soloists. The first-chair violin has an
extensive solo part, and concertmaster Uri Pianka played with
gritty commitment, balanced by the more poignant playing of
principal cellist Desmond Hoebig.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall impact came from playing that was zestful and
sonically brilliant. Despite a lack of subtle Straussian finesse
from McGegan, the performance was a rewarding chance to hear
seldom-performed music.
</P>
<P>
   The only disappointment for me was Elgar's Introduction and
Allegro for strings. Mostly, the music seemed a little turgid,
perhaps because McGegan didn't sufficiently seek out a strong pulse
for the music.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as the violins careened along in extended
melodies, they lost rhythmic character because of the lack of
sufficient pulse. Even in calmer, slower music, the performance
didn't seem rhythmically energized.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
