<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNNYGIRL-THEATER-REV     12-01 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNNYGIRL-THEATER-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-FRILLS `FUNNY GIRL' WORKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Every musical contains a make-or-break moment early on
that indicates whether the show will fly or fall.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Funny Girl,'' the classic backstage musical based on the
life of entertainer Fanny Brice, it's the title character's first
song, ``I'm the Greatest Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Ousted from auditions at a neighborhood music hall because she
is not chorus-girl ``pretty,'' the teen-age Fanny determinedly
pleads with Eddie, the sympathetic dance director, for another
crack at a spot in the show. As her song builds from its tentative
beginning, Jule Styne's propulsive music and Bob Merrill's wryly
conversational lyrics build into a clarion cry for recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1964 Broadway original, with Barbra Streisand in the role
that would catapult her to international fame (as in the show's
1968 film version), the number worked like gangbusters.
</P>
<P>
   In Stages' current intimate production, Holli Golden makes the
moment her own and makes it come vibrantly alive not only with the
brash power of her singing but also with the tension between her
uncertainty and determination to succeed. Golden never imitates
Streisand but projects her own humor and warmth as she veers from
playful self-deprecation to self-assured bravado. As required, by
the song's finish she has convinced not only Eddie but the audience
as well that this kid deserves a chance.
</P>
<P>
   And then another nice thing happens. Both director Rob Bundy's
resourcefully spare treatment of this much-loved musical and
Golden's appealing performance in the all-important starring role
just keep getting better as the evening progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny Girl'' is an interesting case: a huge hit that is rarely
produced _ perhaps because the demanding title role, tricky to cast
in its own right, remains so strongly associated with Streisand. It
underscores the fact that the lion's share of the musical
repertoire (even many big hits) continues to go neglected. If
enterprising midsize theaters like Stages can find a way to do
these full-scale Broadway shows, more power to them. They make
meatier programming than most of the pocket-size off-Broadway
novelties that smaller theaters usually attempt (``Nunsense,''
``Forever Plaid'' and so forth).
</P>
<P>
   As Stages' production demonstrates, with the right actress in
the spotlight, a no-frills ``Funny Girl'' works (even without
Streisand).
</P>
<P>
   True, the whole show is set squarely in the time-honored
tradition of backstage bios: the struggle to achieve success; the
thrill of newfound fame; the agony of backstage heartbreak. In
Fanny's case, that means keeping up the brave front performing in
the Ziegfeld Follies, while her rocky marriage to smooth-talking,
big-dealing gambler Nick Arnstein disintegrates. In the final
reprise of ``Don't Rain on My Parade,'' as Fanny wipes away tears
and prepares to storm out onstage, Merrill's lyrics sum up the
whole story: ``Let's give 'em hell, Brice/We'll cry a little
later/Well, Brice/That's life in the the-ater.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all familiar but neatly crafted. Isobel Lennart's book gets
the story across with earthy humor and reliable heart-tugs. Lennart
was a pro at this sort of thing. By the time she got around to
``Funny Girl,'' she had written the screenplay for ``Love Me or
Leave Me,'' chronicling Ruth Etting's onstage triumph and offstage
heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Styne, one of Broadway's giants, was in top form for ``Funny
Girl,'' and very much in his natural habitat _ remember another
gritty Styne backstager called ``Gypsy''? Styne's strong feeling
for the theater world of this period, the color and zest of his
music, are indispensable assets of ``Funny Girl.'' This holds true
in pastichelike onstage numbers like the wedding extravaganza ``His
Love Makes Me Beautiful'' and the World War I patriotic ditty
``Rat-Tat-Tat-Tat'' and even more in the character ballads such as
``People'' and ``Who Are You Now?'' Merrill's lyrics likewise seem
to have the atmosphere and character nailed down perfectly, adding
fun with outbursts of those antic Merrill rhymes: ``Kid, my heart
ain't made of marble/But your rhythm's really horr'ble.''
</P>
<P>
   The bonus is that (save for one minor number) Stages has put
back the entire Broadway score _ about half of which was dropped
from the film version. That restores a lot of terrific material
that will seem new to patrons familiar only with the movie _
including such gems as Fanny's torch song ``The Music That Makes Me
Dance,'' one of Styne's best ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Staging a little production of a big show, Bundy wields both
feeling and skill. He demonstrates that, despite the few
Ziegfeldian routines to represent Fanny's ``Follies'' career,
``Funny Girl'' is essentially an intimate saga: Fanny and her
mother, Fanny and Nick, Fanny at the mirror in her backstage
dressing room. Not only is nothing lost, but the emotion of these
moments comes across more powerfully in the intimate framework.
</P>
<P>
   Golden rises to the occasion of her challenging task as Fanny.
Starting out playful and affable, she gradually reveals the womanly
yearning, the tough pragmatism of a gal who will finagle behind
hubby's back if she thinks it might boost his career and save her
marriage. And since Styne and Merrill bestowed Fanny with one of
the most generous programs of songs in Broadway history, Golden
sings her heart out _ lowdown in ``Cornet Man,'' tender in
``People,'' driving in ``Don't Rain on My Parade,'' comical in
``Sadie, Sadie,'' wounded yet defiant in ``The Music That Makes Me
Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about the stage version is that, while ``Funny
Girl'' still is Fanny's show, other characters do get a look-in (in
the film version, almost no one else did).
</P>
<P>
   David Grant makes a dapper-looking, smooth-singing Nick. As his
business and marriage go sour in the second act, Grant gives the
dramatic scenes the needed gravity; from the look on his face and
the tone of his voice, the problems seem real.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan McVay proves a snappy song-and-dance man as Eddie and
adds a dramatic dimension by showing that the guy carries a
lifelong torch for his pal Fanny.
</P>
<P>
   Peg Glazer contributes a rich and colorful characterization as
Rose Brice, Fanny's well-meaning, tart-tongued mother. William
Hardy makes an authoritative Flo Ziegfeld. Melinda deKay is all
fussy, meddlesome concern as neighbor Mrs. Strakosh.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a few rushed or cluttered spots here and there, Chesley
Santoro Krohn has supplied some enlivening choreography, especially
in that tap-happy WWI routine.
</P>
<P>
   Musical director Steven Jones leads a sensitive rendition of the
famous score. Thom Guthrie's production design, with detailed set
pieces moving in and out of the central proscenium arch on wagons,
is effective. Matthew Bartkowiak has created some pleasing period
costumes, particularly for the more glamorous Fanny of later scenes
(although those early ``ugly duckling'' bloomers may be a bit
problematic).
</P>
<P>
   All in all, there's little rain on the horizon for Stages'
winning ``Funny Girl.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
