<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORM LETS INVESTOR GET QUESTIONS RIGHT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of readers ask how they can protect themselves against bad
advice from stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is simple enough: Ask lots and lots of questions and
keep good records of the broker's answers.
</P>
<P>
   So the next question is, what are the questions?
</P>
<P>
   The stock market watchdogs have come up with a new way to help
you get it right.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Securities Administrators Association in
Washington, D.C., the umbrella group of state securities
regulators, has developed a notepad for investors to help guide
them to ask the right questions while talking with a broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors who keep good records of their dealings with their
brokers have a leg up in any dispute,'' said Peter C. Hildreth,
president of the association. ``While the vast majority of brokers
are honest, hard-working professionals, disputes do arise.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions cover two sides of a single sheet of paper. They
aren't technical. They prompt you to ask for basic information such
as the name of the broker, the date of the call, the nature of the
proposed investment, how it was described and the broker's name.
</P>
<P>
   The notepad contains crucial questions you should ask to help
judge the broker and an investment idea:
</P>
<P>
   Why is the broker making that particular recommendation?
</P>
<P>
   How does it fit in with your investment objectives?
</P>
<P>
   What are the risks?
</P>
<P>
   How will an investment make money? Is it going to offer income
from dividends or interest, or is it supposed to pay off with
capital gains?
</P>
<P>
   What are the total fees to purchase, maintain and sell this
investment? After you've added up those costs, find out how much
the investment has to gain in value before you break even.
</P>
<P>
   How long has the company that's issued a stock been in business?
Has it made money? Is the management experienced and has it been
successful in the past? Has it made money for investors before?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get the broker's number &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A crucial piece of information that you should list on the form
is what is known as the broker's CRD number.
</P>
<P>
   That number can be used to look up a broker's record in the
Central Registration Depository. That is the computer database
operated by state securities regulators and the National
Association of Securities Dealers, the brokerage industry's
self-regulatory organization.
</P>
<P>
   You should check this database to see if the broker and his or
her firm are registered in Texas and whether they've been
disciplined by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   To make that check, call the NASD's public disclosure hot line
at 800-289-9999 or the State Securities Board in Austin at
512-305-8300 during regular business hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should not be doing business with a broker unless you've
checked out their CRD record,'' said Marc Beauchamp, spokesman for
the national securities administrators.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ask for information in writing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' information sheet also has spaces for you to
record whether you asked to receive written information on a
prospective investment (always ask) and what type of information
will be sent to you.
</P>
<P>
   The form enables you to record what you told the broker to do _
buy, sell or take no action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be vigilant and skeptical and remember that you're
dealing with your money and this is not a trivial matter,''
Beauchamp said. ``You're trying to determine if the person you're
talking to on the phone is experienced and trustworthy to handle
your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping thorough notes could mean the difference between winning
and losing a dispute against your broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, it's more of a `he said, she said' type of
problem, and the better records that the complainant who comes to
us has, the better we are positioned to clearly articulate the
nature of the problem and get a response that helps the investor,''
said Denise Crawford, Texas securities commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the customer has kept good records, the customer is much
more likely to get restitution from the brokerage firm,'' Crawford
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come in with a shoebox full of records that aren't
organized or come with a hazy memory of a conversation that
occurred a year ago, you're going to be at a disadvantage when
you're up against a firm that has records,'' Beauchamp said.
</P>
<P>
   You can print out a copy of the notepad from the association's
Web site at www.nasaa.org or order the form by calling
202-737-0900.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to pamela.yip (at) chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
