<SLUG> BC-PRISON-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS $2.3 MILLION TO FAMILY OF SLAIN INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal jury awarded more than $2.3 million to
the family of a convicted murderer who was shot dead by a San
Quentin prison guard, the latest rebuke of the state prison
system's use of deadly force.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of inmate Mark Adams is a former prison employee who
allegedly hid him after his escape and helped him find religion in
Puerto Rico. She said Monday that the verdict was divine justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave us justice,'' said Elsie Diaz, of Humacao, Puerto
Rico. ``I'm just so glad that maybe somebody will take notice and
see what goes on behind those prison doors.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 jurors on Monday unanimously found fault with the
California Department of Correction's policy on when guards may
shoot inmates and with the shooting death in 1994 of Adams, who had
been recaptured and returned to the prison.
</P>
<P>
   A corrections official expressed shock at the verdict and said
the award was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded a total of $2,302,500 against the state:
$465,000 in compensatory damages for Adams' lost life, wages and
companionship, and $1,837,500 in punitive damages to punish the
defendants and deter them and others from similar conduct in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Jury foreman Robert Resner told reporters the jury was sending a
message to the corrections department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a problem with their firearms policy and a failure to
have less than lethal means'' of controlling inmates, he said. ``He
was a prisoner and a convicted murderer, but he shouldn't have been
killed. He was in the custody and care of the department. The
general feeling was that the state needed to get a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors concluded that San Quentin guard Timothy Scott
Reynolds _ an expert shot who allegedly boasted of killing Adams _
had either been grossly negligent in shooting Adams in the back of
the head from 25 feet, or meant to kill him, Resner said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury was swayed by the testimony of Reynolds' former
girlfriend, a clerk for the Modesto Police Department who said
Reynolds ``bragged'' about killing Adams, Resner said. The state
did not challenge her testimony, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was convicted in 1982 of a murder and robbery he committed
when he was 16 and sentenced to 43 years to life. But on June 10,
1986, he escaped from San Quentin. Exactly how has never been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   He was recaptured in 1993 when a neighbor saw him on the
television program ``America's Most Wanted'' and phoned in a tip
leading the FBI to arrest him in Humacao. By then he had married
Diaz, who had supervised his prison work program.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of his return to San Quentin, Adams was shot by
Reynolds during a fight with another inmate in the prison's
high-security exercise yard under what his lawyers called
suspicious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Adams' survivors sued the state, claiming that Reynolds
used excessive force and that the corrections department was the
nation's only law enforcement agency to maintain a ``sadistic''
policy allowing guards to shoot inmates to halt fistfights.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds and the department denied the allegations, saying the
shots were necessary. But after three days of deliberation in U.S.
District Judge William H. Orrick's San Francisco courtroom, the
jury disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is the latest finding that California's prison
system has used excessive force on inmates.
</P>
<P>
   An independent panel of former law enforcement officials found
last month that 24 of 31 fatal or serious shootings at Corcoran
state prison from 1989 to 1995 were unjustified, and that the
state's system for investigating such incidents had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a federal ruled that guards at Pelican Bay state prison
needlessly and recklessly used firearms and engaged in
``staggering'' amounts of excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can no longer be any doubt that there is a severe
problem,'' said Steve Fama, a lawyer with the Prison Law Office, a
private prisoners' legal services group in San Rafael.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
