<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GAYRIGHTS _ MIAMI _ In a meeting certain to touch off fiery
debate, Miami-Dade County leaders will vote Tuesday on whether to
restore the county's ordinance banning discrimination against gay
citizens. The debate renews a stormy episode in Dade history: 20
years ago Christian activist Anita Bryant led a high-profile
campaign to overturn a gay-rights ordinance. (Williams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-INTERVIEW _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Interview with John Glenn for
the first time since his return from space; talks about his flight
and upcoming retirement. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-INSTITUTE _ Advance of the big dinner Wed. nite that
announces the John Glenn Institute of OSU; event at the Air and
Space Musuem. We'll also explain what the institute does.
(Montgomery, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-CURRIE _ KENNEDY SPACE CENTER _ Space Shuttle Endeavour
is set for a 3:59 a.m. launch on Thursday, but its launch
``window'' is only 10 minutes long. Timing is critical because it
must rendezvous with another spacecraft to begin assembly of the
International Space Station. Among the shuttle's six crewmembers is
former Troy, Ohio, resident Nancy Currie. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT-COUNCIL _ ATLANTA _ A group called the Environmental
Council of States, a national meeting of state, environmental and
transportation officials, meets in Atlanta today. Maryland Gov.
Parris Glendening, who's been active in growth issues and has done
some of the things Georgia Gov.-elect Roy Barnes will grapple with,
will be among those here. We'll cover meeting and do an interview
with Glendening afterward . (Goldberg, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-PIRO-SLAYING _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Update on the murder of
Janette Piro and her missing husband, Chris Benedetto. We expect
autopsy results on Piro's body. (Brogan, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   CARPET-PLEA _ ROME, Ga. _ Beaulieu of America, the large carpet
maker, is expected to plead guilty Tuesday morning in federal court
in Rome to violating campaign finance laws with regard to giving
money to Lamar Alexander's presidential campaign. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MONKEY-DEATH _ ATLANTA _ Yerkes and OSHA are expected to
announce a settlement Tuesday afternoon in the death of primate
assistant Beth Griffin. The hearing was to begin this morning but
was postponed. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-AMISH _ SARASOTA, Fla. _ To the outside, they know their
world appears insular; its strict tenets forbidding cars and TVs,
portable phones and divorce a little queer. Lest the funny hats
obscure what this is really all about: ``First of all, we want to
be known by what we believe.'' Welcome to Florida Amish Country.
(Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-TEACHERS-HOUSES _ BRUNI, Texas _ With demand for teachers so
acute in Texas that big-city school districts are offering cash
signing bonuses, out-of-the-way districts such as Webb Consolidated
_ which draws students from the small towns and ranches east of
Laredo _ are relying on subsidized housing to lure new educators.
Resurrecting a practice that dates back to the frontier days, when
towns built living quarters for the schoolmarm, Webb Consolidated
Independent School District is offering teachers an apartment in a
district-owned complex next to the football field or in any one of
a dozen houses and mobile homes spread out over district property
in Bruni and nearby Oilton. The rent: $250 a month for two
bedrooms, $300 a month for three. (Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FIREARMS-REVENGE _ ATLANTA _ After watching states wring
billions from Big Tobacco, U.S. cities are embarking on what
lawyers describe as Tobacco II: an all-out legal assault on the gun
industry. The pitch is simple: Guns wreak such mayhem in our cities
_ about 35,000 Americans die from gunfire each year _ that
manufacturers should pay. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHILES _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ No Florida politician has
captured the imagination of the electorate longer than Lawton
Mainor Chiles Jr., first a state representative, then a state
senator, U.S. senator and, finally, the state's 41st governor. His
Cracker expressions were foreign to many who understood little
about the ways of old Florida. Yet the same man who wore a coonskin
cap and fired a potato gun at his second inauguration also used his
1997 State of the State address to call attention to brain research
and the importance of a healthy early childhood. Don't expect him
to slow down, just because he lost re-election. An in-depth look at
a political legend. (Klas, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-GOP-CLEMENTS _ COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Twenty years after
he pulled off the Texas political upset of the century, ex-Gov.
Bill Clements, the Republican who started it all, has gone to the
ranch. Now a robust 81, Clements observes, but does not play,
politics. He spends several days a week at the ranch in Forney,
near Dallas, that he has owned since 1950. A profile of Clements,
as well as his thoughts on the big Republican gains in both Texas
and Congress. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
