<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 3
 &HT;    Brews offer a ho-ho-whole lot of flavor
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years, folks have left Santa Claus everything from
brownies and cookies to rum balls and hot chocolate. As midnight
snacks go, they beat a bowl of raisin bran, but why do we never
offer the man a drink? No one, to my knowledge, has affixed to the
fireplace a note that says, ``Help yourself to a beer. They're in
the fridge.''
</P>
<P>
   I should think he'd like one, working as hard as he does.
Granted, he's not going to stay on schedule if he lingers over it
too long. And there is, of course, the matter of sleighing drunk. A
beer at every other house, and he's going to be crashing his sled
and his reindeer through windows. We don't want that.
</P>
<P>
   But somebody at the end of his route should let him sit a spell
as the fire's embers glow warm and welcome.
</P>
<P>
   That's what winter beers are for, after all, and not just on
Christmas Eve. These are beers for firesides on a cold evening,
heartier and stronger than what you'd drink at a picnic. And if
snowmen and chimneys puffing white aren't a part of where you live,
well, sometimes you have to use your imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of Wassail, a festival that predates the
Christian era, many are also spiced. Ancient pagans, celebrating
the solstice and toasting one another, would add cinnamon, nutmeg
or clove to their wine or beer.
</P>
<P>
   But spices alone do not make for a good winter or holiday brew.
The best seasonal beer you're not going to taste in Georgia _
Sierra Nevada Celebration Ale _ is simply a super India Pale Ale,
enormously hoppy (60 International Bitterness Units or more) with a
complex malty backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, though, at a smidgen more than 6 percent alcohol by
volume, it's too much for Georgia, where the 6 percent legal limit
keeps out many of the world's great beers. Among them are not only
beers fractionally higher than the limit but also barley wines,
extra-strong ales that reach 10 percent and 11 percent alcohol.
What a cognac is to the grape, a barley wine is to the grain. But
you cannot buy one in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   What you can buy are annual classics like Anchor's Our Special
Ale, a spiced brew whose recipe changes each year. Most years you
can detect spruce in it (which is why people say it's like drinking
a Christmas tree), and sometimes ginger and nutmeg. Flavoring a
beer is usually a mistake, but this singular ale _ which was not in
the market at the time this was written _ is the benchmark for
exquisite seasonals.
</P>
<P>
   The prettiest seasonal has to be _ as it is every year _ Samuel
Smith's Winter Welcome. But you can't drink the label. Against all
reason, the famous old brewery from the Yorkshire town of Tadcaster
persists in bottling its exceptional ales in clear glass, exposing
them to light and thus to oxidation. (Not to mention the fact that
an imported beer will almost never be as fresh as a domestic beer.)
</P>
<P>
   What a pleasant surprise, then, to find this year's Winter
Welcome in such good condition, the toasted malt flavors perfectly
set off by East Kent Golding and Fuggles hops. It only makes you
imagine how good it must taste in a Yorkshire pub.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Solstice Winter Ale is an excellent version of an
English Strong Ale, fuller bodied and higher in alcohol than its
tamer cousin, a brown ale. Made for Denver's Wynkoop brewpub by
Broadway Brewing Co., also in Denver, Solstice Winter Ale has a
more roasted maltiness than Samuel Smith's Winter Welcome and
slightly more hop character.
</P>
<P>
   Other seasonal beers worth trying:
</P>
<P>
   Winterhook. The annual seasonal from Redhook of Seattle,
Winterhook has been consistently rich and full-bodied, with a
porterlike character. The 1998 version is one of the best in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Goose. Back in the Atlanta market after a three-year
absence, Snow Goose, now made by Frederick Brewing Co. in
Frederick, Md., has always been a ``look for'' beer. Strong and
rich, it doesn't seem to have quite the character it had when it
was made by Wild Goose Brewery. But a good winter beer, even so.
</P>
<P>
   Snowball's Chance. An ordinary winter beer. Not at all bad, but
not exceptional either. Also made by Frederick Brewing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Aass Juleol. Founded in 1834, Aass is Norway's oldest brewery.
The bottle and the label are more charming than the beer. A
slightly sweet aftertaste that's surprising in a dark beer.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetwater Festival Ale. The hustling Atlanta brewery made an
outstanding seasonal beer last year, and has made another this
year. Not only that, but it's $2 cheaper. Sold in numbered 1-liter
bottles priced at $8, Sweetwater Festival Ale tastes a bit like a
Scotch Ale, but with hints of spice.
</P>
<P>
   Red Brick Winter Brew. One of Atlanta Brewing Co.'s best
offerings last year, Red Brick Winter Brew returns in pretty much
the same form. Not as full-bodied as the Sweetwater, and a little
more forward with the spice.
</P>
<P>
   Dogwood Winter Ale. Brewed from barley, wheat, oats and rye.
Hearty but not as silky as one might have expected from an ale with
oats and wheat in the grist.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Grant's Winter Ale. Brewed exclusively with Mount Hood
hops, this might have been the best of Bert Grant's four seasonals
last year. This year's also uses Mount Hoods, which impart an
earthy, herbal aroma and flavor. As with all of Bert Grant's beers,
the yeast has a ``house flavor'' that can be an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   I know Santa would appreciate the Samuel Smith's, the Solstice
or the Sweetwater. But I think what he really wants is Sierra
Nevada Celebration Ale. If this keeps up, he just might stop coming
to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Adams Winter Lager. In the past, Boston Beer Co. has made
both Winter Lager and Old Fezziwig, a spiced ale with a Dickensian
motif. The latter has been dropped this year, but the flavorsome
Winter Lager has perhaps greater versatility and appeal. This is
one of the few lagers among winter beers, and it can best be
compared to a German Dunkel (dark). Like everything from Sam Adams,
it's well-made and smartly marketed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
