</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH WRAPS UP VISIT TO ISRAEL
 &HT;    EDs: Bush is scheduled to leave at 5 p.m. EST (1 a.m. Tel Aviv
time).
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush was wrapping up his first
visit to Israel Tuesday night, after a helicopter tour that edged
slightly into the highly-sensitive world of peace process politics.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli government official, who asked not to be identified,
said that a request of U.S. Embassy officials prompted Bush and
three other Republican governors to cancel short visits to two
Israeli settlements in the occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Settlements, Jewish neighborhoods spread throughout the
largely-Arab West Bank, are a source of controversy in the peace
process. Palestinians view them as encroaching on their land, which
was captured by Israel in 1967. Many Israelis believe that the
settlements help protect the country's security.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have asked that Israel stop expanding settlements
and occasionally ask visiting dignitaries to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   The National Jewish Coalition, a Republican Party group that
supports the settlement policies of Israel's right-wing government,
organized the three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   The group would not release schedules, but an Israeli government
schedule listed two 15-minute stops at settlements that are often
used as observation points over the West Bank. The schedule
included no meetings with Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians claimed that the visits, especially because of
Bush's potential candidacy for the president, would be used by the
Israelis as a small validation of settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter tour did not make the stops Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter did touch down briefly at another settlement
where Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, who was leading the tour, left
the group to board another helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Tuesday, the group visited an Israeli Aircraft Industries
plant, toured the area around the Sea of Galilee and, further
north, the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the focus of attention from Israeli officials but has
repeatedly declined to make anything but brief comments to the
press during the trip. He has said he would hold his remarks for a
press conference in Austin, Texas, on Wednesday. The group was
expected to leave Israel on a late-night flight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
