<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Festivals around the south
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Eatonton, Ga. _ A birthday party for Joel Chandler Harris,
author of the ``Uncle Remus Stories,'' is the centerpiece of
Christmas in Downtown Eatonton Thursday. Parade at 5:30 p.m.
includes Br'er Rabbit, Br'er Bear and Santa, followed by
storytelling and ice cream and cake on the courthouse lawn for
children. Also, ongoing entertainment, face painting, pony rides,
hayrides, clowns and more. 706-485-1171.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rome, Ga. _ ``Candles and Carols of Christmas Past'' Friday
and Saturday at Oak Hill, Berry College founder Martha Berry's
antebellum home, features candlelight tours, local choirs and
re-enactments of a Berry family Christmas, storytelling and tour
guides in period costume. 706-291-1883.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cartersville, Ga. _ A Victorian Christmas at Roselawn Friday
through Sunday features tours of the home of evangelist Sam Jones.
Also, Magnolia's Magnificent Market inside the carriage house for
holiday gifts and goodies. 770-382-4127.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calhoun, Ga. _ New Echota State Historic Site offers its
annual candlelight tours Saturday (6-9 p.m.), featuring historic
pathways lined with luminarias; hot cider and coffee and music at
Vann's Store; and decorations throughout the former Cherokee
capital. Bring flashlights. 706-624-1321.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hiawassee, Ga. _ Mountain Country Christmas in the northeast
Georgia towns of Hiawassee, Young Harris and Blairsville includes a
tour of seven homes, shopping, bonfire for roasting marshmallows
with Santa Claus, a 5K Jingle Jog and a tour of outdoor lights.
706-896-4911.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  McConnells, S.C. _ Historic Brattonsville's annual Christmas
Candlelight Tours are Friday through Sunday at the living history
village. The Christmas seasons of 1780 and 1843 will be depicted at
12 venues by 80 interpreters dressed in period clothing. Music by
Nation Ford String Band and refreshments at the Bratton General
Store Friday and Saturday nights only. 803-684-2327.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Norris, Tenn. _ The Museum of Appalachia presents ``Christmas
in Old Appalachia'' at the Museum of Appalachia opens Sunday with a
free open house featuring sheep herding, buggy rides, spinning and
open hearth cooking in the turn-of-the-century homestead house,
sassafras tea brewing and checker playing demonstration at the
Twain Family Cabin. The decorated cabins and log schoolhouse will
remain decorated through Dec. 31 (except Christmas Day) and
old-time musicians will play daily. 423-494-7680.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Goodlettsville, Tenn. _ ``The Trail of the Longhunter: A
Celebration of a 1700s Christmas at Mansker's Fort'' includes
Yulefest, Mansker Fort's 1780 Candlelight Christmas, on Saturday
with roaring fires inside hand-hewn log cabins, mulled cider and
cookies, and strolling musicians and singers on the grounds of
Mansker's Station. Each cabin in the fort presents a different
aspect of 1700s Christmas customs. Also, day-time tours Saturday
and Sunday feature interpreters who will live in the cabins and
shelters around the fort. 615-741-7994.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hendersonville, N.C. _ The Historic Johnson Farm Country
Christmas Open House is Saturday, Sunday and Dec. 12, featuring
music, hot cider and tours of the late 19th-century tobacco farm
that became a summer retreat in the early 20th century.
704-891-6585.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dillsboro, N.C. _ The 14th Annual Dillsboro Lights and
Luminaire is Friday and Saturday and Dec. 11-12. The four-block
downtown will glow with luminaries and thousands of white lights.
The 50-plus shops, galleries, restaurants and inns will be open.
Also, the Great Smoky Mountains Railways' ``Santa Express''
excursions are under way and you can take home a fir tree from one
of Jackson County's many ``choose and cut'' farms. For a list of
farms and directions, call the Jackson County Chamber of Commerce
at 1-800-962-1911. 1-800-962-1911.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Black Mountain, N.C. _ The Seventh Annual Holly Jolly
Christmas Friday night features carolers strolling downtown,
lumninaries lining the sidewalks, Santa Claus at the Old Depot and
shopping. 1-800-669-2301.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ Alabama Shakespeare Festival presents ``Toad of
Toad Hall,'' A.A. Milne's adaptation of the classic Kenneth Grahame
story, ``The Wind in the Willows.'' Opening Thursday. Through Dec.
31. 1-800-841-4273.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Ga. _ The Fifth Annual Nights of Lights
features more than a million sparkling white lights and special
events including holiday-themed re-enactments Friday through
Sunday; Christmas Tour of Homes, Sunday; Regatta of Lights boat
parade Dec. 12; and Luminaries in the Plaza Dec. 13. Through Jan.
31. 1-800-653-2489.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
