r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-01 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE CAREFUL WHAT YOU WISH FOR WITH AOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Quick! What computer titan recently said: &QL; 
``We share . . . a vision for the future in which consumers will be
able to access (our) brands anywhere, at any time, and from any
device.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah. It sure sounds like good old Bill Gates pushing Windows
again, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Guess again. It was Steve Case, the head honcho at America
Online, commenting a few days ago on huge $4.2 billion AOL
acquisition of Netscape and the pair's agreement to work with Sun
Microsystems through the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The entire quote was, ``We share with Sun a vision for the
future in which consumers will be able to access America Online
brands anywhere, at any time, and from any device.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers were quick to predict that last week's
AOL/Netscape/Sun deal would create a computing and online megabeast
capable of giving that nasty ol' Microsoft a good beating.
</P>
<P>
   Before you start cheering, though, remember that age-old
warning: ``Be careful what you wish for . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The way Case is talking, the world could just be trading a nasty
ol' Microsoft for a nasty ol' AOL.
</P>
<P>
   The Dulles, Va., online behemoth has more than 14 million
customers and one of the top three or four most-popular Web sites
on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Couple that with the widely used Netscape browser, Navigator,
and add in the 20 million people who regularly visit Netscape's
existing Web site, and you've got yourself one heck of a 500-pound
gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   And we all know that old joke: ``What does a 500-pound gorilla
eat for lunch? Anything he pleases!''
</P>
<P>
   If you are an AOL customer, or if you ever have been, you know
that the browser in AOL's proprietary software is kinda stinky.
Even in the last year or so, when the AOL browser was supposed to
have been a version of Microsoft's Internet Explorer, it still
failed, running slowly, badly or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   How long do you think that will continue now that this merger
has surfaced? I bet software developers the world over are already
retooling their products to better serve AOL and Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be long before the world starts complaining about
the power of the AOL/Netscape gorilla, much like it now does about
the domination of Microsoft and its Windows operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   That will only leave consumers, once again, with fewer choices,
despite what Case tells interviewers on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask me, we ought to take some of that worry we've
assigned to the Y2K problem and redirect it toward megamergers like
this one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Your take on Microsoft &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I tossed out a request for people to write in
with their thoughts on the government's antitrust lawsuit against
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what some of you had to say:
</P>
<P>
   From Tom: ``I just wanted to write and comment on Microsoft,
mainly on the people who say they hate Microsoft and people that
say they won't use Microsoft products. Microsoft has created an
operating system as well as compatibility with hardware and
software that makes production quicker, jobs simpler and Web access
a breeze. It has also created hundreds of thousands of jobs
creating and supporting not only their software, but many other
applications. So what if their OS has a mind of its own, so do most
automobiles and VCRs. People, quit complaining and start enjoying
your computer on behalf of the best software company in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   From Floyd: `Questions that I would love to see Department of
Justice put to Microsoft:
</P>
<P>
   1. Why does Microsoft package and sell its Word, Powerpoint &AMP;
Excel products separately and NOT the browser Explorer?
</P>
<P>
   2. Put another way: Why was it necessary to integrate Internet
Explorer with the Windows operating system and NOT Word, Powerpoint
&AMP; Excel?
</P>
<P>
   I suggest the following answer: Because Microsoft could not put
Netscape out of business if they priced and sold Explorer
separately to start with.''
</P>
<P>
   From Jim: ``I believe they're a great company, but one that has
abused its power for the want of even greater control of anything
involving software for computers and/or computer communications. In
addition, I find Microsoft very devious in that you buy a product
with seemingly no connection to them and suddenly discover that the
program is dependent on Microsoft's browser. Unbelievable. This has
personally happened to me with two programs.''
</P>
<P>
   From David: ``I agree that Microsoft should be a little less
aggressive and a little more focused on product features and
quality. However, I would add that lots of us could be less
sensitive to the `bad' things Microsoft is supposedly doing. Just
use the stuff, and be glad we don't have to put up with the way
computers used to behave just a few years ago. I think Microsoft
has been a godsend, and I like most of their products.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
News from all over &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - IBM recently unveiled what it says is the world's highest
capacity hard drive for desktop PCs. The company calls the
25-gigabyte monster the ``Deskstar 25GP.'' To put that capacity
into perspective, IBM says the drive is large enough to hold ``the
double-spaced typed text on a stack of paper more than 4,000 feet
high, more than six full-length feature films or 20,000 digital
images.'' Hmm. That would take a while to fill! No word yet on what
this baby costs.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't know where the computing world is headed? Don't feel
bad. Apparently nobody else does, either. A recent conference in
Santa Clara, Calif., made that fact painfully obvious. Such
high-tech gurus as analyst Esther Dyson and editors of the
investment magazine ``The RedHerring'' were full of opinions on the
future. And many of them were contradictory. ``Herring'' editors,
for example, said that Internet access will be close to free within
10 years. Dyson, however, said top-quality Net access will continue
to cost money.
</P>
<P>
   It all seemed so nice . . . &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's dose of humor comes from my friend Owen in Silicon
Valley:
</P>
<P>
   One day, a highly successful Wall Street executive was hit by a
bus and died. Her soul went to heaven, where she met St. Peter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Heaven,'' St. Peter said. ``However, before you get
settled in, it seems we have a problem. You see, strangely enough,
we've never once had an executive make it this far and we're not
really sure what to do with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem, just let me in,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'd like to, but I have higher orders. What we're going
to do is let you have a day in hell and a day in heaven and then
you can choose whichever one you want to spend an eternity in.''
</P>
<P>
   So, St. Peter put the executive in an elevator and it went
down-down-down to hell. The doors opened and she found herself
stepping out onto the putting green of a beautiful golf course. In
the distance was a country club where everyone was dressed in
evening gowns and formal wear. They all cheered, and welcomed her
warmly.
</P>
<P>
   Four of them played an excellent round of golf and at night they
all met at the country club where she enjoyed an exceptional
dinner. She met the Devil who was actually a really nice guy and
she had a great time telling jokes and dancing. She was having such
a good time that before she knew it, it was time to leave.
Everybody shook her hand and waved good-bye as she got on the
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   The elevator went up-up-up and opened back up at the Pearly
Gates where she found St. Peter waiting for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's time to spend a day in heaven,'' he said. So she
spent the next 24-hours lounging around on clouds and playing the
harp and singing. She found it very comfortable and relaxing and
before she knew it her 24 hours were up and St. Peter came and got
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you've spent a day in hell and you've spent a day in
heaven. Now you must choose your eternity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman paused for a second and then replied, ``Well, I never
thought I'd say this, I mean, heaven has been really great and all,
but I think I had a better time in hell.''
</P>
<P>
   So St. Peter escorted her to the elevator and again she went
down-down-down back to hell. When the doors of the elevator opened
she found herself standing in a desolate wasteland covered in
garbage and filth. She saw that everyone was dressed in tattered
clothing and were picking up the garbage and putting it in sacks.
</P>
<P>
   As the Devil came up to her, she said, ``I don't understand.
Yesterday I was here and there was a golf course and a country club
and we ate lobster and we danced and had a great time. Now all
there is a wasteland of garbage and everyone looks miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil looked at her and smiled. ``Yesterday we were
recruiting you _ today you're staff.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
