<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS FILE LAWSUIT OVER FEDERAL DEPORTATION LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Bairon Morales-Oliva is behind bars without bail
partly because he drove while drunk and partly because he was born
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Morales-Oliva, a longtime resident of Victoria, Texas, and a
legal immigrant, has spent nearly three months in a Texas lockup
while federal officials try to deport him because of a 1993 drunken
driving conviction, a felony offense.
</P>
<P>
   He was denied bail. It didn't matter that his wife and his six
children are American citizens, and that his boss of more than 12
years trusts him with the keys to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his ties to Texas, a federal law enacted in
October requires immigration officials to lock up criminal aliens
while their deportation proceedings move through the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Morales-Oliva, in a lawsuit filed Monday, contends that the law
is unconstitutional. Locking him up while denying him a chance to
prove he poses no threat of fleeing or danger to his community
violates his right to due process of the law, the lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Omar Rodriguez, a Mexican national fighting
deportation in a 1993 marijuana possession case, Morales-Oliva is
suing Attorney General Janet Reno, as well as Immigration and
Naturalization Service officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astounding that we have a law that says we can hold
people in detention indefinitely until we can decide if we can
deport them,'' said Simon Azar-Farr, the San Antonio attorney
representing the two men.
</P>
<P>
   He is asking that the lawsuit be classified as a class action on
behalf of all immigrants being held without bail while facing
deportation in the Western District of Texas, which stretches from
Waco to El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Azar-Farr wants a federal judge to halt enforcement of the
mandatory detention law, which was passed as part of the 1996
Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act but did not
take effect until Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights advocates argue that some immigrants may indeed be
flight risks or pose threats. But they say the defendants are
nonetheless guaranteed a court appearance to argue their cases
before they can be locked up for months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The defenders of the law say it added teeth to otherwise weak
immigration rules.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said that 90 percent of immigrants
who were deported but not detained never actually left the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we don't detain those who are ordered deported, we mock
immigration laws and allow 90 percent to avoid deportation,'' he
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials, already struggling to hold an increasing number
of deportable immigrants, braced for the 1996 law by adding or
contracting for more cell space. The agency added 4,000 beds in
fiscal 1997 and another 2,900 in the fiscal year that ended in
September, bringing its capacity to 16,000.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials, however, estimate the agency will need at least
17,000 cells to hold all the people targeted by the mandatory
detention law. In the agency's Dallas region, which oversees 18
states, there are some 5,700 immigrants in detention _ about twice
as many as anticipated.
</P>
</TEXT>
