<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS LOSE THEIR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - When I was a boy, with my curiosity still wide as a
barn door, I spent a lifetime at the American Museum of Natural
History in New York. It was a second home to me _ the true home for
my hungry brain. I went there every chance I got.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, a block-square monolith of sandstone and statuary,
housed in it what seemed like the complete set of everything in the
world. There were the dinosaur skeletons, the stuffed gorillas in
their African panorama, the tusks of mastodons, a full-size model
blue whale and an entire room of quartz specimens, with small faded
typewritten labels indicating from where they were collected.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what I was currently interested in, the American
Museum had the basic stuff to answer my questions. You could learn
the bare facts from a book, but you could only experience the
reality by seeing the specimens.
</P>
<P>
   I have gone back to visit the museum many times as an adult, and
each time, the museum has seemed diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of the diminishment probably comes from the
comparison of the bland present with the rich broth of nostalgia,
but I know that does not account for the whole change.
</P>
<P>
   For some of my favorite exhibits have not been altered over the
years, and they still excite me as they used to. The ``soil
profiles of New York State,'' for instance, or the stuffed Alaska
Brown Bears, or the totem poles from the Northwest Coast Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Or the small altar to nature writer John Burroughs.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the museum has changed, and it is in those changes I
sense the shrinking of the magic I used to feel.
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs are a good example.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms containing those fossils are undoubtedly the most
popular in the museum. And changes in paleontology have rendered
obsolete some of the old exhibits. The new model for the dinosaurs
on display is no longer the lumbering Godzilla, upright with a
dragging tail, but rather the neck-forward-tail-straight blue jay.
The bones had to be reset and redeployed to make that change.
</P>
<P>
   I'm OK with that. I want my science up to date _ even though I
know that the current dinosaurs will be out of date sometime in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But the new exhibit is like many in modern museums: short on
bones, long on graphics and videos.
</P>
<P>
   The current dinosaur rooms are bright, uncluttered and
graphically concise _ not too much stuff to take in in a single
brief visit.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be the museum was a place to come back to over and
over, because you could never take it all in.
</P>
<P>
   No longer.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the basic mission of museums has undergone a
epochal shift, as if we have passed from some Mesozoic to some
Cenozoic vision of a museum's raison d'etre.
</P>
<P>
   The old museum is itself a dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, museums such as the American Museum in New York, or
the Smithsonian in Washington, or the Field Museum in Chicago
served as a kind of cultural Noah's ark, preserving examples of the
world we live in.
</P>
<P>
   They served to educate us in the process, but the preservation
of the vast variety of life and nature was the museum's purpose.
Scholars could count on that quartz, so they could look at a piece
from New Jersey and compare it to a chunk from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   They could learn something new.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, museums have become part of the vast entertainment
industry, meant to keep us _ and particularly our attention-deficit
children _ from being bored.
</P>
<P>
   There are buttons to press and video screens to watch (although
the clips shown are never long, not wanting to try the visitor's
patience or attention span).
</P>
<P>
   So, that quartz exhibit, which used to contain hundreds of
rocks, is reduced to a single clear, white cobble with an
explanatory wall panel, most likely with a video screen showing
lava splattering from the tip of a volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it has to wiggle.
</P>
<P>
   Museum directors increasingly see their job as educators, and as
educators, they see that job best fulfilled if they are
entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if, instead of taking on two of every species, Noah
booked a trained chimp act and marketed the ark as a cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   As such, I am afraid museums have become a part of the
cheapening of American intellectual life, its thinning of content
and smoothing of the difficulties of learning.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is serious. What museums do now is present a version
of the world that is prepackaged and gift wrapped, and thus,
presents only the ``official version'' of science and history.
</P>
<P>
   When the museums showed us a raft of specimens and very little
summation, we had to create our own versions of truth. We were
active participants in the understanding of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, museumgoers are a passive audience, fed a three-sentence
version of reality that distorts the contradictory variety for the
sake of coherent simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Television can do that just as well. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nilsen is online at richard.nilsen(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
