<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-INJURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYER'S PAIN PUTS FOOTBALL IN PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ken Norton said he wasn't sure how Bryant Young
fractured his right leg Monday night. He said he just remembered a
collision, and ``a scream I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of scream football players know almost
instinctively, the kind they know can erode their own will to keep
playing this dangerous game if they get too close or stay too long.
It breaks down the iron masks and stony hearts football players
must wear to maintain their demeanor, which is why Norton did not
linger long near Young, the great defensive tackle whose season had
just ended and whose career had just been dramatically changed.
</P>
<P>
   Norton knew he was involved in the injury _ he dived at New York
quarterback Kent Graham late in the fourth quarter of the San
Francisco 49ers' 31-7 win Monday and in missing Graham his helmet
snapped Young's tibia and fibula grotesquely. He may even have
known how it happened, although nothing in football happens in real
time for the players involved. He was surely among the first
players to wave frantically for the 49er doctors to come onto the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he was among the very few. Graham cradled Young's head
and said something meant to comfort. Defensive linemate Roy Barker
ran onto the field from the sideline (``I ran out on the field
trying to get his attention to take his mind off it,'' Barker
said). Head coach Steve Mariucci walked on and let Young squeeze
his hand ``just to give him something to grab onto.''
</P>
<P>
   The other players on both sides watched from a good 10 yards
away, alternately staring at Young and looking away
self-consciously, trying to contain their own horror with the
comforts of distance without seeming too callous _ a difficult line
to straddle by any means.
</P>
<P>
   And when Young was carted from the field, to be taken to the
hospital for surgery to repair the damage, they resumed their game,
albeit halfheartedly. Graham, whose improvised dash from the pocket
led to Young's injury, tried and failed to coax the Giants into the
end zone, the fans roared their approval at another defensive stop,
and life sort of resumed in this surreal world.
</P>
<P>
   Norton's did, too, but when he came off the field, he walked to
the far 20-yard line to be alone with his misery. Special teams
coach George Stewart walked over to try to comfort him, but the
attempt was doomed to fail, and Stewart knew it. He was telling
Norton with a hand and a whisper that he would not be left alone,
that his compatriots understood.
</P>
<P>
   Norton knew the drill, too. He has played in the NFL for 11
years, and four years at the University of California at Los
Angeles before that. He has seen other men hurt catastrophically,
like Joe Theismann. He has seriously injured three players himself
with the fury of his play _ Los Angeles Raiders running back
Napoleon McCallum in the opening game of the 1994 season, whose
knee was essentially destroyed so that he never played effectively
again, and teammate Richard Dent a week later against Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Young's injury, though, was particularly gruesome, because there
is no ambiguity about a leg snapped at the mid-shin and left at a
40-degree angle. The ABC ``Monday Night Football'' crew made a
point of not showing the injury repeatedly, as it had in 1985 when
Lawrence Taylor of the Giants snapped Theismann's leg, or in 1994
with McCallum. Still, once is enough, and more than enough for
Norton.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I guess I don't want to see it ever again,'' he said
forlornly. ``The way he screamed, the pain I knew he was in, that
was enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a football matter, he explained Young's loss in
easy-to-understand terms: ``Losing Bryant Young is like losing
Jerry Rice or Steve Young. He is very strong, a force on this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   As a personal matter, though, he could only fall back on the
kind of deal-with-the-devil philosophy that all football players
must agree to if they are to last in a game this haphazardly
violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is so strange ...'' he said, ``and we're all so
fortunate to play it ... but I don't think people realize the
chances we take to play this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He may not have known it, but he was speaking to his fellow
players, many of whom have never seen an injury of this scope up
close. They've know blown knees, hyperextended elbows, concussions
all too well, but fractures that cause a visible change in a man's
silhouette strike them all to their souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell how we handle it,'' Mariucci said, looking
ahead so that he wouldn't have to look behind. ``I'm optimistic we
will all handle it properly, as we have had to handle things like
this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there will always be those screams. No player who hears
them once ever forgets them, because they say so much that players
don't want to hear. Surely Ken Norton will never forget them. He
has been too close to them too many times ever to forget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
