</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOCATION'S THE KEY TO EFFICIENT HOLIDAY SHOPPING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If reducing Christmas bills and shopping stress are
your goals this holiday season, two of the keys are making a list
and setting a budget, consumer experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Consumers Union, the group that publishes
Consumer Reports magazine, said smart shoppers know what they want
to buy and how much they're willing to spend. To balance selection
and expense, they said, it's important to know the strengths and
weaknesses of today's galaxy of retailers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Department stores: For shoppers who place a higher priority on
quality than price, department stores carry the newest and latest
items. Although prices tend to be higher than at discount stores,
cost comparison between department stores is often unnecessary
because most carry the same merchandise at comparable prices.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for electronics mega-stores, but inventory is
often very limited. Electronics are one of the hottest sellers
during the holidays, so if you find the item you want at one of
these stores, it's best to buy it then and there.
</P>
<P>
   But beware of store credit cards that lure shoppers with special
offers such as ``no payments, no interest for six months'' unless
you intend to pay off the entire balance on time. If you don't, a
whopping finance charge may apply.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discount stores: Chain stores that offer discount prices may
be worth the bargain, but selection is limited. To get the best
deals, you have to visit often.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlet malls: Those seeking the lowest of prices this season
may consider taking a trip to an outlet mall. Prices at outlet
stores can be between 5 and 50 percent lower than full price at
retail stores, and shoppers often can find a greater variety of
designer brands. But the quality of the merchandise is slightly
lower at outlet malls, so check your potential purchases very
carefully before buying.
</P>
<P>
   Don't underestimate your ability to bargain for a better price
at outlet stores. Shoppers who point out a defect in a piece of
merchandise or mention a competitor's lower price are more likely
to get a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online shopping: If you're turned off by crowded parking lots,
cash register lines and long drives to an outlet, online shopping
may be for you. The high-tech version of catalog shopping, online
purchases can be delivered directly to your home.
</P>
<P>
   While there is a wide variety of stores to choose from online,
finding the perfect gift in the sea of merchants can be a
challenge. To cut down on time and hassle on the Web, start with a
search engine such as like Yahoo or Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping on line, make sure you know when to expect
delivery and be aware of the shipping and handling charges. There's
little risk to consumers in using a credit card on a ``secure''
Internet site, but if you're nervous, start out by buying something
small or sticking to companies you know and trust.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where you choose to shop, to avoid hassles after the
holidays, be aware of each store's return policies and keep all
receipts. Many companies are very liberal in what they will take
back, but sometimes such items as software, jewelry and certain
types of clothing are non-returnable.
</P>
<P>
   One last word of advice on shopping smart is to start early.
Prices near the end of the holiday season usually aren't any lower
than they are now, and procrastinators will only get a limited
selection to choose from, making it even more difficult to find the
right gift for loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   For more advice, visit the Consumer Reports ``Guide to a
Hassle-Free Holiday'' at
(http://www.consumerreports.org/news/holiday).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
