<P>
   Editors, attention wire editors:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a 4-page package of stories on the
Exxon-Mobil merger.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL (Undated) _ Ledeall: Exxon buys Mobil for $77.4
billion in stock, the biggest takeover ever. The companies say they
plan $2.8 billion in annual cost reductions but give no details
about layoffs; analysts expect that more than 10,000 jobs will be
cut. The combined company will have 22 percent of the nation's
gasoline market and will refine more oil than any other company in
the world. It will rank at the top of the Fortune 500. The merger
reunites the biggest pieces of John D. Rockfeller's Standard Oil
monopoly. Exxon's chief executive, Lee Raymond, will be chairman
and chief executive of the new company, and Mobil's chief
executive, Lucio Noto, will be vice chairman. By Allen R. Myerson
and Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   With a timeline graphic and a world operations graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-CULTURE (Undated) _ The prospect of a corporate culture
clash: Uniting a collection of terse engineers and loquacious
energy ambassadors won't be easy. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Having already been the target in
two of the biggest antitrust cases in history _ the 1911 breakup
and the oil cartel cases of the 1950s and 1960s _ Exxon and Mobil
now face a three-dimensional legal fight: against state attorneys
general, federal regulators and the European Commission. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ Unlikely as it may seem, the merger
of the nation's two biggest oil companies is likely to benefit
consumers more than harm them, consumer groups and other industry
watchers say. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ASIA (Hong Kong) _ Nowhere will the merged company have a
vaster reach than in Asia, where the two own and operate oil
fields, refineries, pipelines, and gas stations from the arctic
chill of Sakhalin Island, Siberia to the tropical swelter of Natuna
Island, Indonesia. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-DEAL (Undated) _ The money makers among the dealmakers. By
Laura Holson.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
