<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUFFLE DISHES TO PIG SPITS: RENTING FOR A BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMAND HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have just sent out the invitations for your holiday party.
You have invited tons of people for drinks and hors d'oeuvres. But
you own a total of eight glasses and no punch bowl. And if you want
to make that spiked cider, you'll need to use all your pots, and do
it in batches.
</P>
<P>
   There, of course, is the rub when it comes to holiday parties.
You want it to be big, festive, too grand for paper cups. But few
people _ especially those who live in New York apartments _ have
the equipment to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious cooks plot it out weeks in advance, scurrying all over
town to borrow things from friends. By the time the party is over,
they have reduced their life span by several years. The smart ones,
on the other hand, will rent.
</P>
<P>
   There are warehouses in New York City filled with plates,
portable stoves, blenders, even pig spits, waiting to be rented.
</P>
<P>
   At BROADWAY FAMOUS PARTY RENTALS, in Brooklyn, plates, of
course, are the item most in demand. ``Everyone does it because you
don't have to clean anything,'' Gail Hillyer, a saleswoman, said.
``You just scrape the food off and put the plates back into the
container.'' The company cleans them. Linens and chairs come next.
You can also rent glassware, and not just wine glasses. They have
everything from shot glasses ($.55 a glass per day) to lead crystal
stemware ($1.25).
</P>
<P>
   But the company also rents equipment most people would never
want to buy, like a 50-cup coffee urn ($53), ice tubs ($5.50), a
large refrigerator ($250), a small convection oven ($50) and a
20-quart stockpot ($15).
</P>
<P>
   Though once you go the rental route, orders add up quickly:
Broadway's minimum holiday order is an unusually high $500 and
delivery fees are $18, regardless of the size of the order. So, if
you're going to do it up with this company, you will have to do it
up in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Famous Party Rentals is at 134 Morgan Avenue in the
East Williamsburg section, (718) 821-4000 or (212) 269-2666.
Appointments to tour the warehouse may be made, or orders may be
placed over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   SERVICE PARTY RENTALS , 770 Lexington Avenue (60th Street),
(212) 752-7661, rents a similar slew of equipment, from ramekins
($1.35) _ in case you dare do souffles for 20 _ to triple-tier
plate stands ($15) to 18-by-27-inch sheet pans ($2.50). The minimum
order is $250, and the delivery fee is $25 during the week for
orders under $500. Orders are by appointment only.
</P>
<P>
   KUTTNER PROP RENTALS, 601 West 26th Street, (212) 242-7969,
offers a large and precious array of antique kitchenware and
tableware. If you're planning on making a Babette's feast, you can
rent antique copper pots, a cast-iron cauldron, 19th-century wooden
spoons, serving platters and mortar and pestle. They're guaranteed
conversation pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Fees, which vary from item to item, are weekly, and there is no
minimum order. Because most items are antique, there is a high
deposit.
</P>
<P>
   THE PROP COMPANY KAPLAN &AMP; ASSOCIATES also rents decorative
kitchenware and their collection is more eclectic. They have
burled-wood cutting boards, copper pots, enamelware, pitchers and
country pine tables. Prices vary depending on the item and rental
is by appointment only, (212) 691-7767.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the realm of the esoteric is IDEAL CHEESE, 1205 Second
Avenue (63rd Street), (212) 688-7579, a cheese shop on the Upper
East Side. They rent fondue pots or grills for making Swiss
raclette, in case you want to add a spin to your party. Rates are
$10 a day, and $15 for a weekend, with the purchase of the
appropriate cheese, of course.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do not want to deal with the stress of it all,
there is THE MAIN EVENT, a party agency. ``We fill a very unique
void in this world,'' Daniel Vater, an owner of the company, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do anything you need really. If you need rentals we can
arrange it, or waitstaff, transportation, clowns, jugglers.'' Think
of them as a contractor _ and they don't charge a fee to the
client. The Main Event is at 167 Madison Avenue (33d Street), (212)
213-9295. Orders may be made by phone or by appointment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
