<SLUG> BC-INFANTFORMULA-BACTERIA-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORMULA FOR BABY'S HEALTH: GOOD `GERMS' (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention bacteria, and most parents think germs, infection and
disease.
</P>
<P>
   But experts in pediatric nutrition say live bacteria may soon be
added to infant formulas to help babies digest lactose, the sugar
commonly found in milk, and to prevent and treat diarrhea, to
improve carbohydrate digestion and to control intestinal
infections.
</P>
<P>
   Probiotics, or ``good bacteria,'' have also exhibited
anti-cancer, anti-allergy and cholesterol-lowering properties, says
Dr. Jose Saavedra, director of the Pediatric Nutrition Center at
the Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are already, in several parts of the world, including
Europe and Asia, formulas that are nutritionally adequate for
infants and children which do contain probiotics (good bacteria),''
Saavedra says. ``How much bacteria and which bacteria to put in the
formula is still open to question.''
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra has studied hospitalized children and healthy children
4 months to 18 months old who received supplemental live bacteria
in their formula, and she says the bacteria appear to regulate
bowels as well as relieve diarrhea and diaper rash. All the
children were receiving more than 10 million _ and close to 1
billion _ bacteria as a dose once or twice a day, with no adverse
effects.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``probiotics'' _ bacteria that can be given orally to
an animal host to improve its intestinal health _ was not coined
until the 1960s, but the use of good bacteria to preserve fermented
foods such as yogurt and cheese has been around for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra served this month as course director for the Johns
Hopkins Advances in Pediatric Nutrition symposium, attended by more
than 200 health-care professionals concerned with the nutritional
care of infants and children.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of papers presented at the symposium were discussed
in a telephone media briefing, in which experts noted that breast
milk is the ideal, most nutritionally complete food for baby during
the first year of life. It contains the perfect balance of
nutrients and other important ingredients, evolves to meet a baby's
changing nutritional needs, protects baby from disease and fosters
an intimate mother-child bond, researchers agree.
</P>
<P>
   The best alternative or supplement to breast milk, say the
experts, is an iron-fortified formula that provides the recommended
percentages of vitamins, minerals, protein, fat and carbohydrates
necessary for healthy growth and development. Infant formulas
marketed in this country must meet nutritional requirements from
the Food and Drug Administration and are almost universally safe,
says Dr. Alan Lake, an assistant professor of pediatrics at Johns
Hopkins and a member of the American Academy of Pediatrics'
committee on nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the studies being done with probiotic additives
to formulas, researchers are working on ways to customize and
enhance formulas with a host of functional additives, including
fiber, rice starch (to prevent spitting up) and nucleotides to
enhance the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our desire to maximize breast feeding, many of the formulas
are attempting to take advantage of some of the contents of breast
milk, even if supplements are begun,'' Lake says. ``The use of
bacteria or the use of other materials in breast milk that promote
bacterial growth within the intestine will all be addressed with
formulas over the course of the next year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasis on how much of each nutrient is recommended has
switched over the years from a focus on providing the minimum
required to prevent deterioration and acute disease, to the concept
of consuming much larger amounts in order to optimize health and
suppress the development of chronic diseases, many of which begin
in childhood, notes Dr. Ben Caballero, director of the human
nutrition at the Johns Hopkins School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   RDAs, or recommended daily allowances _ first created in 1941 by
the Food and Nutrition Board of the National Academy of Science _
are revised about every 10 years and are currently under
examination. The last revision was in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   For children, the revisions are based primarily on observational
data from children who are considered to be in good health and
growing at the normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   For infants during the first year of life, breast milk intake is
the reference standard, and recommendations are developed by
analyzing the content of nutrients in breast milk and estimating
the volume of breast milk that healthy infants consume.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
