A7020 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     12-01 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RR FANS HIT A MAJOR CROSSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Almost all of us had played with toy trains
when we were kids. The difference between me and the rest of the
crowd inside a giant white tent at Scottsdale Embassy Suites was
that at some point I stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I wasn't bidding in the auction portion of the
Desert Division of the Train Collectors Association's Turkey Meet
on Sunday afternoon. No offers from me on what could have passed
for the contents of the world's largest attic _ table after table
of toy engines, boxcars, tiny water towers, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I was watching the bidders, looking for whatever spark
ignites inside these men, turning a hobby into a full-bore
obsession.
</P>
<P>
   A swap meet was held the day before, but Sunday's auction was
where the real model railroaders held forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the collectors,'' Fred Hunter, the president of the
Desert Division, said as he eyed a 736 Berkshire engine he had
wanted since he was a child. ``These are the ones who are serious
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Toy trains are interesting enough, but serious collectors are
fascinating. It's one thing to mount a license-plate frame that
says ``I'd rather be running my Lionel trains'' on your Ford F-150,
as someone in the parking lot had done. It's another to set up one
of the largest model-railroad layouts in the state in your home,
one so large it can run 11 trains at once.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of Tom Stange, collector extraordinaire. &QL; 
Rail addition &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the trains for their historical value,'' Stange
said. ``Not to say I don't like to see them run and operate. I do.
But I get as much pleasure seeing them on the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Stange considers himself ``not necessarily obsessed,'' though he
allowed as to how some people might think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have added on to the house'' to make room for trains, he
said. ``The room is over 1,000 square feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I can see how people might use the O-word.
</P>
<P>
   Cole Gibbs doesn't consider himself obsessed, either. Oh, sure,
he does have the three layouts at home in a large train room.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I don't bring them into the house _ into the living
quarters _ I'm OK,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So why does he collect trains?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why stamps?'' he answered. ``By the way, I do have stamps and
coins, too. My wife says it's a gene you inherit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like she's onto something.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better word would be (begin ital) intense (end ital),'' he
said. ``Some people are more intense than others.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Matter of perspective &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, in this crowd there would be no out-and-out confession
to obsession. But then I realized the problem. If you were in the
middle of a room full of midgets, it wouldn't do you much good to
ask which one was the short guy. In some ways, Gibbs was right _
it's all a matter of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Jerry Morris wasn't obsessed with model railroading,
either, even though he and his friend, George Farkis (who wore a
striped engineer's hat while he thumbed through a well-worn
paperback guide to Lionel trains), drove from El Paso for the
auction. Just intense.
</P>
<P>
   Morris tried to explain the attraction of the trains, of what
might lead to an obsession _ not that he had one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I grew up, most travel was by train,'' he said, ``and I
lived near a railroad depot. Definitely, if you have a little
wanderlust, it imprints on you.''
</P>
<P>
   That imprint may fade, he said, but it doesn't disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put (the trains) away when you're 15 and you pull them
back out when you're 25, and you realize you missed out on 10
Christmases,'' he said. ``You find out you missed 10 different
engines when you were out of it. You've got to play catch-up
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   So he has, and then some _ he's 60 now. Maybe he could argue
that for him model railroading is still a hobby, not yet an
obsession.
</P>
<P>
   But for my money, that train's already left the station. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
