   For a long time, officials worried mainly about photocopiers.
Tom Ferguson, acting director for the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing, the agency that makes U.S. currency, remembers how
``everybody in this business, in the late '70s and '80s, was seeing
huge color-copying machines. Currency people were saying, `Uh-oh,
how can we defeat them?'''
</P>
<P>
   Copiers became smaller and more widely available. And sure
enough, in 1993 the National Academy of Sciences put out a
disturbing report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total value of counterfeits produced by color copiers and
printers ... has been doubling every year,'' it said. In 1990
counterfeiters produced $1 million in fake banknotes on ``office
machines''-copiers, laser printers, and ink-jet systems. ``In 1991
this doubled to $2 million, and in 1992 the amount increased to
between $6 million and $8 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of growth marks the early stages of disease
epidemics. Projecting it into the future, the report concluded that
office-machine counterfeits might cause ``severe problems for the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   To head off this threat, the Treasury Department approved the
first noticeable changes to U.S. currency in 70 years. In this
``next-generation'' design, new features that are difficult to
reproduce, such as bigger portraits and watermarks in the paper,
will appear on all large notes. The redesigned $100 bill came out
in 1996 and the $50 in 1997, but consumers don't see many of those.
The greatest shock to eyes numbed by the familiar greenback is just
arriving now, with the new $20 bill.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like the new look, wait a few years. Currency
experts are already thinking about the next next-generation design,
which Ferguson expects will be needed in seven to ten years.
``There's now a need for rapid change,'' he says. If you were just
starting a career in currency manufacture, ``you couldn't pick a
more exciting time.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason his business has become so lively is that more and
more ordinary citizens now have an opportunity to share the thrill
of printing money. So far this year, according to the Secret
Service, the amount of counterfeit currency successfully passed
into domestic circulation has jumped 25 percent over last year's
rate. If the trend continues, $40 million in bogus bills will be
culled from the money supply, versus $32 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every fake note that anyone reports, anywhere in the
world, eventually makes its way to the Secret Service-charged since
its formation in 1865 with protecting the integrity of U.S.
currency. At Secret Service headquarters, a block from the White
House, Dennis Lynch, special agent in charge of the Counterfeit
Division, coolly interprets the 25 percent jump in counterfeits
being passed this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Counterfeiting has not been, and is not now, a significant
economic problem,'' Lynch insists. Look at it this way: the 32
million counterfeit dollars pulled out of circulation last year, if
printed in twenties, would be 1.6 million notes, or an average of
4,400 per day. Meanwhile, during an average day the Bureau of
Engraving and Printing churns out 38 million legal-tender Federal
Reserve notes. Stacked straight up, they would stand 2.6 miles
high. Counterfeiters chimed in with 19 more inches. That's
practically nothing. This year they've raised their daily share a
few more inches-a mere blip.
</P>
<P>
   Yet looked at more closely, the recent rise in counterfeiting
seems ominous. That's because it represents not more of the same
but a new technology coming into play. While other office-machine
methods hold fairly steady, the rate of ink-jet counterfeiting
skyrockets. Of counterfeit notes that entered domestic circulation,
the ink-jet proportion rose from 0.5 percent in 1995 to 3 percent
in 1996 to 19 percent in 1997, and so far this year it's running 44
percent. From that perspective, the blip looks explosive.
</P>
<P>
   If you own an ink-jet printer and you can't believe it's capable
of imitating the currency you have in your wallet, your printer is
outdated. For a few hundred dollars these days, you can buy a good
color ink-jet printer that does ``nice work,'' as Ferguson admits.
``Not perfect by any means, but certainly deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   For most purposes, ``deceptive'' is good enough. Lynch guesses
that 98 percent of all phony bills that get passed fail to
reproduce key security features-no watermark, no security thread,
no color-shifting ink in the lower right corner. Usually the
counterfeiters don't even try. And such uncraftsmanlike
nonchalance, he says, highlights the most important reason these
bills get passed: ``The American public is not paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That puts a heavy burden on police to take up the slack. In the
good old days Secret Service agents could handle the challenge,
because counterfeiters belonged to an identifiable breed. They
spent many hours making plates, ran off huge numbers of fake
hundreds, fifties, or twenties to cover their considerable time and
expense, and then had to pass all those bills without raising
suspicions. Inevitably they left a trail-purchasing or gaining
inside access to specialized equipment; recruiting others to help
pass the bills; or selling trunkloads of bogus cash at a discount
to criminals. The Secret Service could catch those guys with
standard gumshoe work.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, desktop counterfeiters don't need a bill-passing
network. Instead they print cash as needed. And they certainly
don't need specialized equipment. As Lynch knows all too well, at
least 25 million ink-jet printers have been sold worldwide, and
sales show signs of accelerating. ``The nightmare,'' he says, ``is
when the system changes from 500 counterfeit printers passing
$100,000 each to 100,000 passing $500 each. We can't be everywhere.
We can't be in everybody's basement and den.''
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare is happening now. In 1995 there weren't many
$9,000 Tektronix printers in basements and dens. Today, color
ink-jet printers can be bought for under $100. What's more, there
are stand-alone scanners that don't need a computer; they plug
right into an ink-jet or laser printer. Hook them together, and you
have a color copier-all for as little as $200, compared with
$40,000 in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no stopping the digital revolution, why shouldn't
policing go digital, too? Indeed, several manufacturers of color
copiers have installed chips that recognize the world's major
currency notes and block attempts to copy them. Unfortunately, such
a chip might raise costs. Another suggestion is to modify printers
to add a unique, covert mark to every piece of paper, allowing
counterfeits to be traced to particular machines. The Secret
Service is looking into all these possibilities and more. ``The
technical issue,'' Lynch says, ``is really the linchpin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Engraving and Printing is also eyeing new
technical fixes. Many promising countermeasures have already been
adopted in other countries. Australia, for example, is spearheading
a push to plastic money. Printing on plastic allows designers to
add translucent effects to foil counterfeiting. And plastic would
make a suitable base for holograms.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. currency experts are following those experiments with keen
interest. ``There are advantages but also disadvantages in security
with plastics,'' Ferguson says. ``We're years away from making that
decision.'' Tests show that the bureau's huge, high-speed intaglio
presses can print money on plastic stock. But then, so can ink-jet
printers.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Over its long history, counterfeiting has
continually leapfrogged preventive measures, behaving like certain
diseases-like the flu, say. Yet all epidemics eventually run their
course. New variants spread explosively at first, but finally new
defenses kick in and the rate of infection levels off.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the idea is to deter the new breed of counterfeiters
with enough technical barriers and currency changes to restore
equilibrium. Yet the printing techniques used for both
counterfeiting and genuine currency are mutating faster than ever.
</P>
<P>
   As Ferguson says, ``It's a very interesting period.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Will Hively is a contributing editor of Discover magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
