</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKWARD-EVOLUTION-SCIENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOLVING BACKWARD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: THREE COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight
delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at NO EXTRA
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.)  
 &HT;    
 By JARED DIAMOND 
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The blind mole rat _ a fat, furry sausage of a rodent with tiny
legs and no eyes visible _ is helping evolutionary biologists
figure out how the human lost his tail.
</P>
<P>
   Most discussions of biological evolution concern the acquisition
of useful traits. But evolution is also about losing traits.
</P>
<P>
   The long list of ancestral traits that were lost or reduced in
the course of human evolution includes tails, body hair and the
bony browridges over our eyes. Snakes lost their legs, and whales
lost most of their sense of smell.
</P>
<P>
   The process is common enough to be unsurprising. But why would
any animal cavalierly dispense with such hard-won victories? What
evolutionary force drove their loss?
</P>
<P>
   Those turn out to be difficult questions. Darwin proposed two
alternative solutions but was unable to decide between them. One of
the explanations invokes normal wear and tear, which goes
unrepaired when a gene for a biological trait falls into disuse.
</P>
<P>
   Once ancestral apes were spending much of their time on the
ground, for instance, mutants with shrunken tails were at no
disadvantage, and eventually mutants whose tails were shrunk to
nothing became the norm.
</P>
<P>
   The other explanation can be described as motivated wrecking for
profit. Any physiological structure occupies space in an animal's
body and costs energy to make and maintain. A mutant proto-ape that
lost its tail could have devoted the freed-up energy, protoplasm
and space to a larger brain. Hypothetically, the proto-ape got more
benefits from its newly enlarged brain than from its old lost tail.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin's two competing theories would be nothing more than good
cocktail party conversation if we couldn't figure out how to test
them. To resolve this debate, we'll examine the story of a
remarkable Israeli animal that has nearly lost its eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Spalax ehrenbergi resembles a muddy-colored, furry, fat sausage
about eight inches long. Once you have figured out which end is the
head (the end on which a mouth opens to show teeth that bite you),
you realize that all the rest of the head except for the mouth has
an uninterrupted covering of fur.
</P>
<P>
   But that strange appearance makes perfect sense functionally
because blind mole rats spend most of their lives in underground
tunnels, where eyes would be of even less use to them than a tail
would be to us.
</P>
<P>
   Blind mole rats are not entirely eyeless. Eyes the size of
pinheads lie concealed beneath the fur and skin of their heads.
Each eye is embedded in a thick gland; its lens is shriveled; and
it has no pupil, nor eye muscles to move or focus it. Not
surprisingly, if you flash a light at Spalax, it exhibits no
reaction whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Spalax's eyes have not evolved completely out of
existence. What, if anything, is that tiny eye doing?
</P>
<P>
   Spalax exhibits photoperiodic responses _ daily and seasonal
cycles of sleep, activity, reproduction and other physiological
functions. Those responses disappear in Spalax from which the tiny
eyes have been surgically removed.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently Spalax's eyes are still being used to recognize the
difference between light and dark whenever Spalax sticks its head
out of its tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   How has such drastic yet precise reduction of Spalax's eyes been
accomplished? The answer came from Israeli evolutionary biologist
Eviatar Nevo's collaborations with French scientists Howard Cooper
and Marc Herbin, who studied the microanatomy of Spalax's eyes and
brain, and his work with German scientists Reinhold Necker and Gerd
Rehkdmper, who studied brain electrophysiology.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of Spalax evolution, the original eye inherited
from sighted rodent ancestors was reconfigured very selectively.
The eye and brain structures that sighted animals use for forming
images are smaller by 90 percent to 99 percent in Spalax compared
with those of sighted rodents of the same body size.
</P>
<P>
   But the brain structure involved in controlling the
photoperiodic response is as large in Spalax as in sighted rodents.
The part of the brain cortex that in humans or sighted rats would
be devoted to vision and image formation is devoted to the body's
sense of touch in Spalax and has thereby expanded to be almost
twice as large as that of a similar-size sighted rat.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, Herbin and Nevo did some calculations to understand why
natural selection led to such a selective dismantling of the Spalax
eye. They estimated that by getting rid of most of the
image-forming part of the visual system, Spalax saves over 2
percent of its whole energy budget. This is a fantastic windfall
for Spalax: energy to convert into milk for rearing pups, into
searching for food or into tunnel construction to locate a mate.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason that the reduction of Spalax's
visual system produced a huge advantage: Spalax has better uses for
its brain space. Consider what other senses it needs for a life
spent in a labyrinth of unlit tunnels: an exquisite sense of touch,
a good sense of hearing and a keen sense of smell. It also has a
remarkable system of magnetic compass orientation.
</P>
<P>
   These multiple sensory modalities place a big burden on
underground rodents. Getting rid of the visual cortex and turning
its space over to the sense of touch is one way Spalax copes with
the problem of how to navigate blind without its brain becoming
even larger.
</P>
<P>
   In short, when spalax entered a dark world, its visual system
didn't just rust away. Natural selection favored mutants that
jettisoned the visual system piece by piece, depending on how
useful each part was.
</P>
<P>
   This message extracted from mole rats may resolve Darwin's
puzzle about how natural selection destroys as well as creates.
Let's take just one specific example: Why did our ancestors lose
their tails?
</P>
<P>
   The way to think of your hypothetical tails is as a
lost-opportunity cost. Ask yourself about the sacrifices that you
would have to make elsewhere in your body to free up protoplasm for
a tail. Fewer pounds of brain? Then you would revert to being a big
speechless monkey. Fewer pounds of muscle? Then you would be a
wimp, easy prey for lions. Fewer pounds of kidney? Then how do you
propose to make enough urine? No, tails are fortunately gone
forever, as far as we humans are concerned. Our ancestors didn't
use them, they did lose them, and we profited.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jared Diamond is a professor of physiology at UCLA Medical
School and a member of the National Academy of Sciences.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
