<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEGAMARKET FROM ELI ZABAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Romanesque entrance is flanked with streaming banners at
Eli's Manhattan, 1411 Third Avenue (80th Street). It's Eli Zabar's
cathedral of food, which opened Tuesday, the latest and grandest
addition to a 10-block strip that has more than its share of big
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Though the goods for sale are pretty much the same here as at
the Vinegar Factory on East 91st Street, Eli Zabar's other huge
market, the elegant buff-colored Jerusalem stone interior, with its
arches and soaring vistas, offers a sharp contrast to the rustic
uptown store.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fresh food is on the lower level, including 280
linear feet of prepared foods, fish and meat departments, a huge
pickle barrel, an oyster bar, a rotisserie and a cheese section
where cheeses, some aged on the premises, will be cut to order.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight is the produce, which is banked against one wall
and kept cool with a new gravity system: cold air naturally
replaces warm, a nice change from the sprayers that drench the
lettuce in many supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   On the main floor are breads, pastries, sandwiches, candy,
flowers and a coffee bar and cafe. A 150-seat restaurant with an
open kitchen is planned for the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Zabar said he was not concerned that he was adding a market to
an avenue already overflowing with food. ``This neighborhood is so
dense, there's room for everybody,'' he said, adding that the
prices at Eli's Manhattan will be the same as at the Vinegar
Factory. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants and chefs have been putting their names on bottles
of extra-virgin olive oil for some time now. But not Jean-Georges
Vongerichten, the chef whose restaurant empire includes Jean
Georges and Mercer Kitchen. Instead, he has just introduced a
signature grape-seed oil, a product that he has spent four years
developing.
</P>
<P>
   Why grape-seed oil, a relatively unknown ingredient in America's
kitchens?
</P>
<P>
   French chefs like it for its high smoke point (485 degrees) and
its relatively neutral flavor, making it preferred for many saute
jobs and sauces. It is also rich in mono-unsaturated fat and is not
highly processed like canola oil or corn oil.
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten's oil, made from California wine grapes, has a
subtle hint of nuttiness and comes in a handsome one-liter tin.
It's $15.95 at Citarella, 2135 Broadway (75th Street) and 1313
Third Avenue (75th Street). The same oil, produced in San Francisco
by the California Grape Seed Co., is also available at
Williams-Sonoma for $16, but without Vongerichten's name on it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's steakhouse and gift shop in Grand Central
Terminal sells more than autographed basketballs for $1,500: there
are also sets of four steak knives for $50. The knives may be more
useful than the basketball, now that the restaurant has started
selling its steaks. They come packed in a special insulated sueded
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Four 16-ounce boneless strip sirloins are $100, and four
12-ounce filets mignons are $84. The best buy of the lot is the
four 28-ounce double rib-eyes, at $108. These are hefty hunks of
meat, tender and flavorful, and though they come with fat and bone,
each provides two ample servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
