<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGBOOKS-AZR &LR;      12-01 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISUAL DELIGHTS FILL COFFEE-TABLE TOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could do worse than to look at the world through the camera
of Jacques Henri Lartigue.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what you see there: Lartigue's family and friends
during the first decade of this century, engaged in all manner of
play and invention. There are men flying huge box kites, and women
romping in the surf in their long dresses. Later, there are the
first flying machines _ ethereal contraptions that seemed to rise
into the air on the wishes of the men who made them.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the charm of these photographs is serendipity _
Lartigue's family was wealthy, eccentric and ingenious (several
members were inventors), and provided wonderful moments to capture.
But more important was the fact that Lartigue, who was born in
1894, was a photographic anomaly: a child prodigy. He made his
first photographs when he was only 6, learned to develop them the
following year and continued to take pictures all of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 12 years after Lartigue's death, you can buy a sumptuous
monograph on the beloved Frenchman that includes 126 duotone
photographs and an introduction by New York Times photography
critic Vicki Goldberg. ``Jacques Henri Lartigue, Photographer''
(Bulfinch, $95) is one of the best books in a Christmas crop that
covers everything from beer and baseball to the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the more interesting ways to spend your money
this season:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pulp Culture: The Art of Fiction Magazines'' by Frank M.
Robinson and Lawrence Davidson (Collectors Press, $39.95). For many
years, they were the chief source of entertainment in a country
that was starved for it. The ``pulps'' were wildly popular during
the Depression and had all but disappeared by the 1950s. This is a
collection of magazine covers that gave their audiences what they
wanted to see _ sex, violence, lurid insinuation and most of all,
drama, so thick and suggestive that it made readers forget their
troubles for a while. Look at them, and you might wish they were
still around.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bird's Eye Views: Historic Lithographs of North American
Cities'' by John W. Reps (Princeton Architectural Press, $65). In
the years following the Civil War, people hungered for images of
their communities, and their favorite way of seeing them was from
an imaginary viewpoint high in the air. Before the demand for such
views waned in the early decades of the 20th century, artists _
many were itinerants who recorded the places they saw on their
travels _ had produced images of some 2,400 cities and towns. These
views are delightful not only for the contrast they offer (C.J.
Dyer drew Phoenix and Prescott in 1885, when both were sparse), but
for the idiosyncracies of the artists who created them.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Into Thin Air'' by Jon Krakauer (Villard, $40). An
illustrated edition of Krakauer's bestseller about the disastrous
day on Mount Everest in 1996 when five climbers died after they
were caught in a snowstorm near the summit. Included are more than
250 black-and-white photographs, many taken by members of the dead
climbers' expeditions, and a new postscript by Krakauer in which he
addresses the controversy that followed original publication of his
book last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Halsman: A Retrospective'' (Bulfinch, $75). This book
coincides with an exhibit of photographs that will open at the
Center for Creative Photography in Tucson next March. It includes
Halsman's famous portraits of Albert Einstein (taken as the
melancholy scientist talked about the atom bomb, and how his work
had made it possible), Marilyn Monroe, Alfred Hitchcock and John
Steinbeck. Also here are ``jumpology'' photos, for which Halsman
had dumbfounding luck in convincing subjects to jump up and down
for his camera. Among those who complied: Richard Nixon, Edward
Steichen, J. Robert Oppenheimer and the Duke and Duchess of
Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The American Century'' by Harold Evans (Knopf, $50).
Beginning in 1889, this is an engaging overview of how America and
its international influence has evolved over the last 100 years
(the Clinton years are a frustrating omission, even if Evans did
run out of time and space). It is illustrated with lesser-known
archival photographs, and includes side stories on participants in
world and national events. Once you've hauled this onto your lap
(it is a hefty 700 pages), you won't want to put it down.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Louvre: Portrait of a Museum'' by Nicholas d'Archimbaud
(Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $60). ST&AMP;C puts out beautiful books, and
this one had a head start _ its subject is one of the most
extraordinary museums in the world. D'Archimbaud and a team of
writers profile the Louvre, a city of art within the grand city of
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Naked &AMP; the Dressed: 20 Years of Versace by Avedon''
(Random House, $50). You won't even notice the clothes. Or the
words _ there aren't more than 50 in the whole book. These are
flamboyant, ribald, in-your-face photographs of nude people,
vamping people (Elton John is on the cover, in drag), painted
people, contorted people, people you know (The Artist Formerly
Known as Prince, Jon Bon Jovi, Claudia Schiffer) and people you
wouldn't want to meet in a million years. But aren't they great to
look at? And aren't they having the time of their lives?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Story of Opera'' by Richard Somerset-Ward (Abrams,
$49.50). With chapters on the great Italian, German, French,
English and Russian operas and personalities, this volume marks the
400th anniversary of the first performance of the first opera
(``Dafne,'' in Florence in 1598). With a brief foreword by Kiri Te
Kanawa.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Baseball's Greatest Players'' by Ron Smith (The Sporting
News, $29.95). Babe Ruth is Number One. After that you're welcome
to quibble. Here are the 100 best players of all time, chosen by
the staff of ``The Sporting News.'' With a foreword by Willie Mays,
who is happy to be Number Two. In addition, the ``Sporting News''
has teamed up with the St. Louis Post-Dispatch on ``Celebrating
70,'' a record of Mark McGwire's pursuit of the single-season home
run record.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tributes: Celebrating 50 Years of New York City Ballet''
(Morrow, $50). A handsome collection of photographs, artworks and
essays inspired by New York City Ballet, its stars and the driving
forces behind it. Contributors include Susan Sontag, Henri
Cartier-Bresson, Ernst Haas, Richard Avedon, Alfred Eisenstaedt,
W.H. Auden, Marianne Moore, Joan Didion, Annie Leibovitz, Roy
Lichtenstein, Robert Rauschenberg and George Plimpton. With a
preface by Peter Martins and a wonderful foreword by Mikhail
Baryshnikov.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Illustrated Oxford Dictionary'' (DK, $45). The complementary
strengths of two publishing houses _ Oxford University Press on
language and Dorling Kindersley on illustration _ come together in
a handsome (if airy, for dictionary purists) reference manual. DK
also offers the 720-page ``Art: A World History'' ($59.95), and
Michael Jackson's ``The Ultimate Beer'' ($29.95), a different sort
of reference manual altogether.
</P>
<P>
   _ NASA and the Exploration of Space'' by Roger D. Launius and
Bertram Ulrich (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $60). The story of United
States space exploration, illustrated with paintings and sketches
from the NASA Art Collection. Among the artists are Peter Hurd,
Jamie Wyeth, Norman Rockwell, Robert Rauschenberg and Robert
McCall.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Rolling Stones: A Life on the Road'' (Penguin, $50).
Lots of photos crammed on the page and a text that is straight from
the band _ don't let your kids read it. Or try ``Songs'' by Bruce
Springsteen (Avon, $50), more than 300 pages of photographs, lyrics
and reflections on his music and career. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
