<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee
approves a dramatic expansion of its impeachment probe to include
alleged financial irregularities in the 1996 Clinton re-election
campaign. Democratic committee members scoff at the Republicans'
plan to finish the panel's work by the end of the year. By MARK
HELM and DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AIDS (Washington) _ As death rates from AIDS have
dramatically plummeted in America, President Clinton announces that
the government will focus more attention on helping developing
nations defeat the disease. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SEARCHES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
short-term business guests have no constitutional protection
against unreasonable searches while in someone else's home. The
justices, in a 6-3 decision, reinstate the drug conviction of two
men whom a police officer, peering through a partially shaded
window without a search warrant, saw bagging cocaine. By STEVE
LASH.
</P>
<P>
   BRADY-GUNS (Washington) _ The National Rifle Association files a
lawsuit against the Justice Department seeking an injunction
against what it calls an illegal retention of lists of firearms
purchasers. By JOHN DRAKE.
</P>
<P>
   FEINSTEIN-GUNS (Washington) _ In an interview, Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., outlines her plans to introduce new gun
control legislation next year. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL (Undated) _ Exxon Corp. agrees to buy Mobil Corp.
for a record $77.2 billion, bringing together the nation's two
biggest oil companies and reuniting the largest pieces of John D.
Rockefeller's Standard Oil empire. By MICHAEL DAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOMINIQUE-MOCEANU (Houston) _ Brian Huggins, a former gymnast
and confidant of Olympic medalist Dominique Moceanu, is scheduled
to file legal papers to intervene in Moceanu's lawsuit seeking a
protective order against her father, who reportedly threatened
Huggins. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   IMPLANTS-FINDINGS (Houston) _ A court-appointed panel of
scientists says it found no proven links between silicone breast
implants and diseases claimed by women suing implant manufacturers.
The long-anticipated findings of the independent committee will
help shape the future of implant litigation because the information
can be used in courts nationwide. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INVITRO-DISEASE (Houston) _ Researchers for the first time have
identified the transmission of a genetic disease from donor eggs to
children born as the result of in-vitro fertilization. By RUTH
SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ESCAPE (Huntsville, Texas) _ Prison sources say that once
a death-row inmate attempts an escape, he is to be forever removed
from the work program. But that wasn't the case for convicted
killer Ponchai Wilkerson, who attempted to escape in 1993. He was
eventually put back on the work detail where he had the access to
try another escape. By KATHY WALT and ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-VENDING (Austin, Texas) _ The attorney general has ruled
that the Alcoholic Beverage Commission cannot approve the use of
alcohol vending machines. The commission had earlier allowed an
Oklahoma City company to begin marketing machines that use a
personal identification number, despite a prohibition on the sale
of alcohol from coin-operated machines. By STEVE OLAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN-EXECUTION (Undated) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright is backing a Canadian effort to keep an Alberta man from
being executed in Texas. Albright has written to state officials
asking for a stay in the execution of Stanley Faulder, condemned
for the 1975 murder of the elderly matriarch of a Texas oil family.
By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-COUNTDOWN (Undated) _ The countdown continues for the
Thursday launch of the shuttle Endeavour, which will carry into
orbit components for the international space station. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Although Jack Kevorkian's assisted
suicide on television was widely disturbing, Americans are
increasingly sympathetic to the concept of helping the terminally
ill end their suffering and die with dignity. It's a tough call,
but anyone who has helplessly watched a loved one in needless pain
can understand what Kevorkian is trying to say. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PERFECTION (Undated) _ The Denver Broncos are three-fourths
of the way toward accomplishing what only one other NFL team has
done in the history of the league _ go undefeated and untied during
the regular season. Denver would join the 1972 Miami Dolphins, who
went 17-0, including a Super Bowl championship, as the only teams
to complete a perfect regular season. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
