<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE WORLD OF WILLIAM STEIG &QL; 
 &UR; Lee Lorenz (Artisan, $60)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone loves William Steig for his drawings and cartoons, but
we love him for the title of his 1950 book, ``The Agony in the
Kindergarten.'' That volume conjured up the excruciating horrors of
childhood in drawings that were as simple as they were profound.
And yet, writes John Updike in an introduction to this wonderful
retrospective, ``Steig, for all his insight into stunted and
inhibited children, seems to be one of those adults in whom the
creative child has never met discouragement. He has the dauntless
energy of prelapsarian innocence. An Edenic nudity gaily haunts
him.'' Steig began his association with ``The New Yorker'' in 1930,
and over the years became indelibly linked to the look and the
personality of the magazine. Lorenz, who was its art editor for 20
years and cartoon editor until 1997, allows that Steig's
relationship with the magazine was not always an easy one (he
includes, in its entirety, a letter to editor Katharine White in
which the magazine's founder, Harold Ross, picks apart a series of
Steig cartoons). But all was smoothed out in the end, and we are
lucky for it. ``He was, in those citified, civilized pages,
something of a wild man,'' Updike writes, ``but one who knew things
better not forgotten, and whose freedom all could envy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SEXUAL MCCARTHYISM &QL; 
 &UR; Alan M. Dershowitz (Basic, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz says he got the idea for this book when he used the
term ``sexual McCarthyism'' during dinner conversation with Philip
Roth, and Roth insisted that he write something about it. Do you
believe him? Neither do we. We think Dershowitz thought it up all
by himself, from the depths of his media savvy. Having appeared on
television repeatedly to discuss President Clinton's alleged sexual
adventures, he knew there was more to gain by writing it down. But
if there's opportunism around every corner, Dershowitz, at least,
has good timing. While you await the outcome of the impeachment
discussion, read what he thinks about Monica Lewinsky (a ``young
blabbermouth . . . she really did want oral sex: she wanted to talk
about it''), Paula Jones (``a vindictive woman represented by
politically motivated lawyers''), and other attorneys (Robert
Bennett behaved like a ``rank amateur'' and William Ginsburg was
worse). And finally, there are the principles. ``Which is more
dangerous to our liberties?'' he writes. ``A president who may have
had a sexual encounter with a willing intern and then tried to
cover it up? Or a prosecutor who may have leaked secret grand jury
testimony in an effort to get potential witnesses to change that
testimony, and who hid his conflict of interest from the court?''
More important, perhaps: Do the two men deserve each other? After
you read this book, you'll have no doubt about what Dershowitz
thinks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; I WILL BEAR WITNESS: A DIARY OF THE NAZI YEARS 1933-1941 &QL; 
 &UR; Victor Klemperer (Random House, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   March 10, 1933, Friday evening: ``Hitler Chancellor. What, up to
election Sunday on March 5, I called terror, was a mild prelude.
Now the business of 1918 is being exactly repeated, only under a
different sign, under the swastika. Again it's astounding how
easily everything collapses.'' Victor Klemperer, a German and a Jew
by birth, had kept a diary since he was 17. By the time Hitler
began his rise to power, Klemperer was a scholar, a literary
journalist and the husband of a Protestant woman, and it was this
final, fragile stroke of luck that helped him survive the
Holocaust. In 1945, he was one of 198 registered Jews left in
Dresden _ since 1941, more than 1,000 others had been deported to
concentration camps, many murdered upon arrival. Klemperer's
diaries of the Nazi years record the momentous, the horrific and
the mundane, including random acts of goodness and conscience by
ordinary Germans that serve to rebut the indictment made by Daniel
Goldhagen in his controversial book ``Hitler's Willing
Executioners.'' Klemperer's remarkable diaries were found by one of
his students after his death in 1960, and were published in Germany
in 1995 to great acclaim. They will be released here in two
installments _ the second, covering 1941 to 1945, will be published
next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HUNDRED DOLLAR HOLIDAY &QL; 
 &UR; Bill McKibben (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $12)
</P>
<P>
   We are, McKibben writes (``The End of Nature''), ``a species
hemmed in by stuff.'' Christmas for our children has become a loot
fest, the holidays a time to ``get through.'' This little book is a
pep talk, of sorts, a call to reverse the process and celebrate in
a more meaningful way. It grew out of a project that began nearly
10 years ago at McKibben's church in rural New York. Participants
encouraged their friends and families to limit the amount of money
they spent on the holiday to $100. As McKibben traveled to
neighboring churches to enlist them in the program, he realized
that they were not searching for a simpler Christmas. ``We wanted a
more joyous Christmas,'' he writes. ``We were feeling cheated _ as
if the season didn't bring with it the happiness we wanted.''
McKibben's suggestions are gentle and non-threatening, and he
admits that it might take years to work your family down from the
materialistic heights. Even if you never make it to $100, it's
worthwhile to stop and think about what you have, and about what
you're missing. &QL; 
Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
