<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-RICE-HNS &LR;      12-01 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE ACCEPTS DIMINISHED ROLE WITH 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jerry Rice made a great cutback move on Monday
night. He was wearing a gray flannel suit and a bright smile when
he did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the season I have to play a different role,'' he
said in the locker room after the San Francisco 49ers beat the New
York Giants, 31-7. ``You've got to swallow deep and live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the new, mellow Jerry Rice, the antidote to the
perfectionist Jerry Rice, the flip side of the petulant, frustrated
superstar who stalked out of the locker room a week before.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the two guys looked the same, making three catches
each week, unable to shake the cornerbacks who would have knotted
themselves into ineffectual pretzels trying to cover the Jerry Rice
of yore.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Rice needed to shake off more than pesky
defensive backs. He had a selfishness rap to lose.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, he threatened retirement. This week, he said he
planned to savor what remained of his career. Last week, he was the
picture of misery. This week, he almost made fun of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said he went up to Terrell Owens after the young receiver
went 79 yards for a touchdown and said: ``I remember doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he couldn't imagine why defensive coordinators would
still bother double-teaming him. After all, he is a gimpy old dude,
playing on a reconstructed knee and borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he'd like to prove otherwise. On Monday, he couldn't,
even though 11 passes went his way, six of them in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He caught three all night, for just 25 yards. The good ones, the
high-flying footballs, fell short or long or right out of his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   But the Niners still won big, while Rice tended to his other
mission. He knew that after last week's outburst, everyone was
watching him. The ABC cameras followed him constantly, panning to
him on the sidelines whenever possible, gauging his response.
</P>
<P>
   He knew this would happen. He had become national news, bigger
even than officials who don't know heads from tails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard I was on the Internet, I was all over the place,'' he
said, smiling, aggressively jovial.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Rice, the receiver, may have lost a step this year. But
Jerry Rice, the consummate star, the immaculate dresser, still
knows how to tidy up a mess.
</P>
<P>
   When Owens scored, he raced down to offer congratulations. He
did it again when Irv Smith scored. The cameras would not catch him
being anything less than the ideal teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Even when guard Kevin Gogan ran into him late in the first
quarter, he turned it into a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does he weigh? 320 pounds?'' Rice said, wide-eyed, in
mock horror.
</P>
<P>
   Gogan managed to wrench Rice's neck slightly, putting him on the
bench with an ice pack for a good part of the second quarter. Gogan
thought he was doing Rice a favor when he ran toward a stack of
Giants gang-tackling the receiver. They were standing Rice up, and
Gogan anticipated a cheap shot. He went barreling in to disperse
the Giants, and got Rice by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was laughing about it later, but I think he was kind of
bitter at first,'' Gogan said. ``The guy I was playing against
said: `You know, if you hurt him, they're probably going to cut you
at halftime.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rice spent a lot of time after the game trying to clarify what
he had said last week. He said he was hurt to hear people calling
him selfish, and he insisted that he hadn't gone into a snit over
catching only three balls against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Rice repeated his midweek argument that he was only trying to
rejuvenate the offense, push it to be better. The news media, he
contended, blew his remarks out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said: ``I was unhappy about catching three balls,
but who wouldn't be, as a competitor?''
</P>
<P>
   He kept smiling the whole time. Someone asked whether he might
break out during the playoffs. He agreed that it was a possibility.
Or maybe, he said, ``next year, come out more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rice said he could accept a lesser role this year, while his
knee perks up, and while Owens and J.J. Stokes grow into
accomplished veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to enjoy myself, smile, watch these young guys
make plays and do what I can,'' he said. ``I don't want to lower my
standards, but I've got to enjoy (football) because it's going to
end soon.''
</P>
<P>
   This had to be a hard admission for Rice. He and Steve Mariucci
met this week, and perhaps the head coach helped him see that he
has a lot to contribute, as long as he doesn't insist on doing
everything.
</P>
<P>
   It is a process every superstar faces in the final years of a
long career. Rice may have a lot of time left, and a better season
ahead. But every game brings the end closer.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Niners were reminded of their professional mortality
when Bryant Young's leg snapped late in Monday's game. Almost a
year ago, on another Monday night, Rice lay in the end zone, his
knee cracked, the very knee that had blown out in September.
</P>
<P>
   He came back too early for his own good, trying to set healing
records that aren't meant to be broken. He was Icarus that night,
with melted wings. For most of this season, too, he has expected
too much, from himself, from a team in transition.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he said he had arrived at acceptance. It's not quite
the end zone, Rice's usual habitat. But he had to show that he
could get there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
