<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unruly topic, critics won't derail a writer
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Ann Waldron, writer and very special human being, is
having a time with critics these days. Some like her new book on
Eudora Welty, ``A Writer's Life'' (Doubleday, $25.95), and some are
tearing it and the author apart.
</P>
<P>
   Annie herself says that writing it with no help from Miss Welty,
in fact total hindrance from the author, was ``pure hell.'' But
having known Annie for most of her life, I know she isn't wringing
her hands and weeping somewhere in Princeton, N.J. She is taking
praise and mean criticism in good heart and probably even now
planning her next book.
</P>
<P>
   Ann came to The Atlanta Constitution fresh out of the University
of Alabama shortly after I got here in the early 1940s. I didn't
cotton to her at first because she filed things. I never knew a
newspaper reporter who had files. I do now. But then I thought it
was a business office attitude and sheer pretension.
</P>
<P>
   So I wasn't taken with the bouncy dark-haired Alabama kid until
a great thing happened. She couldn't decide whether to file 4-H for
the 4-H clubs of Georgia under ``F'' for four or ``H'' for what is
it, head, heart, hands and health? I knew she couldn't be all bad,
and I warmed to her immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, she came to live at my house on 13th Street,
transforming the little sun parlor into a bed-sitting room suitable
for receiving company. She did complain that the street light on
the front sidewalk was a deterrent to romance.
</P>
<P>
   Her dates, mostly young fellows from the newspaper, were
reluctant to kiss her good night under that bright beam. One,
however, took the street light in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Young Martin O. Waldron from Pelham was so devoted to Ann that
when my youngest child, all broken out with mumps, crawled in his
lap and hugged him, he didn't complain. He didn't even suggest
postponing their wedding, although friends told him if he caught
Mary's mumps he would be rendered impotent. I guess he wasn't,
because they had four children.
</P>
<P>
   We all went to their wedding in Birmingham, and I stood in as an
older female friend, driving Mr. Waldron's old car around to meet
friends at the airport, pick up the music for the soloist and
transport the wedding cake. The back door of the car kept popping
open, and I nearly lost the cake and a couple of my children.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, called Mow for the initials he typed at the top of his
copy, became an outstanding reporter, winning a Pulitzer Prize for
his series on highway corruption in Florida. I worked beside him
when we both covered the James Earl Ray trial for the killing of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and the murder trial of novelist
Jesse Hill Ford in Humboldt, Tenn. While her husband was doing
that, Ann was writing books and working on The Tallahassee
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   I met her on the Lady Bird Johnson campaign train. She invited
me and Claude Sitton of The New York Times to go home with her for
baths when the train overnighted in Tallahassee. You couldn't get a
bath on the train.
</P>
<P>
   Ann has written a lot of books. The two immediately preceding
the Eudora Welty biography were on Caroline Gordon, wife of poet
Allen Tate of the celebrated Fugitives, and Hodding Carter Jr., the
liberal Mississippi newspaper editor. I'm sorry Miss Welty didn't
realize that she had a fine biographer in Annie and cooperate, but
when you're that old _ 89 _ and that accomplishing, I suppose you
can choose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
