<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
EGYPTIAN-REOPENING (Los Angeles) _ When the Egyptian Theater opened
in 1922 it was the poshest theater in Hollywood, premiering both
``The Gold Rush'' and ``Ben Hur.'' It fell into disrepair over the
years, closing in 1992. But in 1996, the American Cinemathique
bought it and plans a gala reopening Dec. 4 for an invitation-only
crowd, followed by three nights of public events. By Carol
Bidwell. 
. 
JANE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ English actress Jane Horrocks can do a
dead-on imitation of just about any singing diva you can name. Judy
Garland warbling ``Over the Rainbow''? Shirley Bassey belting out
``Goldfinger''? Her impersonations are so good that the producers
of her showcase film, ``Little Voice,'' felt it necessary to add a
prominent postscript at the end of the movie declaring that the
actress did indeed do all her own singing. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
TALKIN-RADIO (Los Angeles) _ Whoever said music is ailing on the AM
dial surely hasn't heard KGIL-AM (1260), whose syndicated ``Music
of Your Life'' format is winning fans across the country. The
format _ known as adult pop standards _ features such core artists
as Frank Sinatra, Tony Bennett, Barbra Streisand, Johnny Mathis and
Nat King Cole, plus contemporary singers like Natalie Cole, Diana
Krall, James Taylor and Harry Connick Jr. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
. 
