<P>
   PINOCHET-U.S. (Washington) _ The United States, treading into a
political and diplomatic thicket it has tried to avoid, will
declassify secret Government documents on the killing and torture
conducted under the former dictator of Chile, Augusto Pinochet,
whose predecessor was the target of American coup plots in the
early 1970s. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ Two of China's most prominent
dissidents, each of whom has spent over a decade in jail, were
suddenly arrested for criminal offenses on Monday evening in an
apparent crackdown on their efforts to form China's first
opposition political party. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-ALBRIGHT (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright chose the opening session of a three-day international
conference on Holocaust-Era Assets here Tuesday to talk emotionally
about the Jewish roots she acknowledged only two years ago and her
own loss of family members she never knew. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ORTHODOX (Jerusalem) _ For years, the Israeli government
has resisted court orders to appoint Reform and Conservative Jews
on the all-Orthodox, taxpayer-financed religious councils that
wield tremendous power in every town and city of this country. Now,
with all appeals exhausted, the Religious Affairs Ministry faces a
Supreme Court deadline to integrate the councils. By Deborah
Sontag.
