   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-GAYS (Miami) _ More than 20 years after Anita Bryant's
``save our children'' crusade led to the repeal here of one of the
country's first gay rights city ordinances and galvanized anti-gay
sentiment in the nation, the Miami-Dade County commission is
expected to vote on another law to ban discrimination on the basis
of sexual orientation. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-PREMIUMS (Washington) _ While insurance premiums at
many large employers are expected to rise 8-20 percent next year,
the gap is spreading as premiums for the many of the 16 million
people under 65 who buy their own health insurance _ some
self-employed, some unemployed, some who work for small employers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL (Undated) _ Exxon, already the nation's largest oil
company, announced its agreement to buy Mobil, the next largest,
for $77.2 billion in stock to form the world's biggest corporation,
on a scale surpassing that of many sovereign nations. The
agreement, certain to face close examination by regulators, would
reunite the two largest pieces of John D. Rockefeller's Standard
Oil Trust, broken up in 1911 in the nation's most celebrated
antitrust case. By Allen R. Myerson and Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-CULTURE (Undated) _ The prospect of a corporate culture
clash: Uniting a collection of terse engineers and loquacious
energy ambassadors won't be easy. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Having already been the target in
two of the biggest antitrust cases in history _ the 1911 breakup
and the oil cartel cases of the 1950s and 1960s _ Exxon and Mobil
now face a three-dimensional legal fight: against state attorneys
general, federal regulators and the European Commission. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ASSESS (Undated) _ An analysis of the reasons driving the
merger. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ With the merger announced Tuesday
between Exxon and Mobil, the hardest part now begins. As a target
in two of the largest antitrust challenges in American history _
first at the beginning of the century with the breakup of the
empire of John D. Rockefeller Sr., and then 50 years later in the
notorious Oil Cartel cases _ Exxon and Mobil will once again have
to confront antitrust enforcers. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
