<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-GIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRENCH GIN ASSERTS ITSELF AND LEAVES OUT LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   French gin? Mais oui. After all, the word itself is English
shorthand for genievre, the French word for juniper berry, which is
the dominant flavor in all gins. And if anyone needs historical
precedents, Alexandre Gabriel and Jean-Dominique Andreu _ the young
French hotshots behind Pierre Ferrand Cognac, Daron Calvados and
Cerbois Armagnac _ have a dossier full of them, compiled during
research expeditions in the Netherlands and northern France.
</P>
<P>
   It is the evidence in the glass, however, that makes the case
best. Citadelle, named in honor of an 18th-century distillery once
situated in Dunkirk's historic fort, is a crisp, full-bodied gin,
florid and assertive, even insolent.
</P>
<P>
   In historical terms, it represents a slap in the face to the
understated, recessive style known as London dry. The dominant note
is juniper, of course, with a citric snap from orange and lemon
peels, but the plot thickens very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel and Andreu, working from archives in Dunkirk and using
old-fashioned pot stills, set out to reproduce the full-flavored,
mouth-filling gin that Dunkirk's distillers shipped to England 200
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are 19 botanicals in the mix. Some of them, like licorice,
angelica and coriander, are often found in other gins. Others are
exotic, like cubeb, cardamom, cumin, violet root and grains of
paradise, a peppery West African berry.
</P>
<P>
   The team effort combines to produce a highly complex, deep gin
with floral, spicy and even earthy undertones. A bottle is about
$20.
</P>
<P>
   Now all it needs is a cocktail. But why shouldn't a commanding
personality with a name like Citadelle simply take one over? Armed
with an olive or a lemon twist, it can storm the martini and win it
for France. Behold the martinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-SEARCHES-HNS &LR;      12-01 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SEARCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES BUSINESS GUESTS HAVE NO CONSTITUTIONAL PROTECTION
AGAINST POLICE SEARCHES WHILE IN ANOTHER'S HOME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided Supreme Court ruled Tuesday that business
guests, such as insurance salesmen or cosmetics dealers, enjoy no
constitutional protection against unreasonable police searches
while in someone else's home.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the justices said people who enter another
person's house solely to ply their trade inside have no
``reasonable expectation of privacy'' entitling them to the Fourth
Amendment's safeguard against unwarranted searches. By contrast,
the justices, also by a 5-4 margin, indicated in their various
opinions that temporary social guests, such as friends who come for
lunch, would be constitutionally protected.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the high court reinstated the drug convictions of
two men whom a police officer, while peering through a window
without a search warrant, saw bagging cocaine in another person's
apartment. The Minnesota Supreme Court had thrown out the
convictions, ruling that Eagan, Minn., police Officer James Thielen
violated Wayne Thomas Carter's and Melvin Johns' Fourth Amendment
rights by conducting a warrantless search of Kimberly Thompson's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Supreme Court overturned its Minnesota counterpart,
saying Carter and Johns were merely business visitors who lacked
the expectation of privacy _ and constitutional protection _ of a
home owner or overnight guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no suggestion that they had a previous relationship
with Thompson, or that there was any other purpose to their visit''
besides business, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the
5-4 majority. ``While the apartment was a dwelling place for
Thompson, it was for these respondents (Carter and Johns) simply a
place to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was joined in his opinion by Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota prosecutor who argued the case hailed the decision
as a victory for law enforcement. However, the American Civil
Liberties Union called the ruling ``disappointing but not
surprising'' in light of the Supreme Court's recent narrowing of
Fourth Amendment protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news for the protection of public safety in
America,'' said Dakota County, Minn., attorney James Backstrom.
``It's good news for keeping our communities safe from drug dealers
and others involved in the commission of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Shapiro, the ACLU's national legal director, said the
high court misread the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a court that has not generally been responsive
to Fourth Amendment claims,'' he said. ``I think the court's view
of privacy in this case runs contrary to the expectation of most
Americans, who assume when they are invited guests in someone's
home they will not be subject to government snooping.''
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg assailed the
court for its narrow reading of the Fourth Amendment. She said the
decision will hurt home owners and renters who, while entertaining
business guests, will have no protection against police
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, when a home owner or lessor personally invites a
guest into her home to share in a common endeavor, whether it be
for conversation, to engage in leisure activities, or for business
purposes licit or illicit, that guest should share his host's
shelter against unreasonable searches and seizures,'' Ginsburg
wrote. ``As I see it, people are not genuinely secure in their
(homes) against unreasonable searches and seizures if their
invitations to others increase the risk of unwarranted governmental
peering and prying into their dwelling places.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens and David H. Souter joined Ginsburg's
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer agreed with Ginsburg that the Fourth
Amendment should be interpreted broadly to include business and
social guests. But Breyer voted with the majority in reinstating
the drug convictions, saying the police officer did not need a
warrant before he observed Carter and Johns through partially open
Venetian blinds while standing in a public place.
</P>
<P>
   Any person in the same area as the officer could have seen
Carter and Johns, Breyer said, intimating that the two men should
have taken greater care in closing the blinds to guard their
privacy. ``One who lives in a basement apartment that fronts a
publicly traveled street, or similar space, ordinarily understands
the need for care lest a member of the public simply direct his
gaze downward,'' Breyer added.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, in a concurring opinion, agreed with the dissenters
that the Fourth Amendment protects social guests, who, he said,
generally have ``a legitimate expectation of privacy, and hence
protection against searches in their host's home.'' However,
Kennedy reiterated the majority's view that business visitors do
not enjoy constitutional protection.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia, in a concurring opinion that Thomas joined, said the
Fourth Amendment protection in the home applies only to owners,
renters or overnight guests, who have taken ``temporary residence''
in another person's house. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
