<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- ARMED. Sen. Mary Landrieu was appointed Tuesday to
the Senate Armed Services Committee, signaling Landrieu's elevation
of defense interests over agriculture, at least in the short run.
Defense issues, such as terrorism and local spending items, figure
to play a more prominent role in Congress during the next two
years, congressional experts say. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- CLOUT (3-story package). In Congress, size matters
and time counts. With 435 members and a strict system of seniority,
the House of Representatives demands that congressmen band together
and use their years of clout whenever possible -- that is, if they
want to pass national legislation or work on local issues, such as
securing funding for roads, universities or federal buildings.
That's why the Colorado delegation has been scrambling to make up
for the loss of seniority when long-time Reps. Dan Schaefer,
R-Lakewood, and David Skaggs, D-Boulder, retire from office next
year. Three stories: one on the clout issue, one on Skaggs and one
on Schaefer. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- VIDEO. While the video game industry has created
an effective ratings system, children still have too much access to
``ultra-violent'' games, said Sens. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn.,
and Herb Kohl, D-Wis., at a Washington press conference with the
National Institute on Media and the Family. Story will include part
of the institute's list of kid-appropriate games and those that are
too violent. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN -- HOEKSTRA. Rep. Pete Hoekstra, R-Holland, said
Attorney General Janet Reno should appoint an independent counsel
to investigate whether Harold Ickes, a former deputy White House
chief of staff, lied to a congressional panel last year. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY -- DSCC. Moving up a step among Senate Democrats,
Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., Tuesday assumed the leadership
of the political committee charged with returning Democrats to the
majority in the 2000 elections. Kane
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- GEKAS. Rep. George Gekas, R-Harrisburg, voted
along with Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee to expand
the impeachment investigation of President Clinton to include
campaign finance. The committee voted to issue subpoenas seeking
campaign finance documents. (Brief.) Fine
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- PARSONS. It's especially critical for leaders
to always tell the truth, former University of South Carolina
women's basketball coach Pam Parsons said Tuesday to the
congressional committee considering impeaching President Clinton.
(Sidebar.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- PRISONS. After four days on the lam, Martin Gurule is
so far an exception -- escape from death row is rare and almost
never successful. (Possible.) Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- KOHL-VIDEO. Sens. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., and Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn., released their annual report card on the video
games rating system at a press conference Tuesday. The senators
praised the video game industry for developing a comprehensive
ratings system, but said there was still a long way to go before
parents could feel at ease about the video games their kids can
access. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- FEINGOLD. In his first real post-mortem of his 1998 race,
Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., said his focus on keeping spending
down and ``soft'' money out of the race was a success with voters
and may increase chances for passing campaign-finance reform in
Congress. Feingold spoke Tuesday at a conference on campaign
quality hosted by the Annenberg Public Policy Center of the
University of Pennsylvania. Butler
</P>
