<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDRENSBOOKS-SPIRIT     12-01 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDRENSBOOKS-SPIRITUALITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRITUALLY MINDED CHILDREN'S BOOKS OFFER THE BEST OF BOTH WORLDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDY GUERRA-CLINE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Different parents start with different books. In my case, it
began with Robert Munsch's ``Love You Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of a precious baby boy _ is there any other kind?
_ and a stubborn mother. As the pages turn, the boy turns, too.
Into a mischievous toddler, a muddy boy, a limits-testing teen-ager
_ is there any other kind? But there's that mom ... still sneaking
into his bedroom to watch him sleep, to rock him back and forth,
back and forth, until she's too old to sing anymore, too old to
rock that 30-year-old man with a newborn daughter of his own. I'm
generally in tears by page 10. Over the years my oldest daughter
has learned to pick up reading where I trail off.
</P>
<P>
   There's another tenacious mother in Margaret Wise Brown's ``The
Runaway Bunny.'' And tenacity pays off in Dr. Seuss' ``Oh, the
Places You'll Go,'' too. These are picture books in the traditional
sense (easy words), but they tackle difficult concepts (life,
death, career traps).
</P>
<P>
   That's what good books do: teach. Some teaching books for
children can be described as religious in nature, and they relay
important Bible stories in words our kids can understand. Some,
like the ones above, aren't strictly religious, but can still be
defined as spiritual, tackling topics like discrimination and the
cycle of life and death. They explain the need for sharing,
understanding thy neighbor, and being kind in unkind situations. In
these books, the gentle guy gets the world.
</P>
<P>
   I never thought to teach my children from my own mistakes.
Instead, I read them books. And sometimes, at the end of a trying
day, that's enough for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the best books I've found that introduce big
subjects to little readers.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Molly's Pilgrim'' by Barbara Cohen (Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shephard
Books, $15). In this 1983 classic, which has been reprinted, Molly,
a modern-day pilgrim, teaches her classmates the meaning of
Thanksgiving. The story is based on a true story of the author's
Russian immigrant family.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Tale of Three Trees,'' a traditional folk tale, re-told
by Angela Elwell Hunt (Lion Publishing, $14.99). Three little trees
grow side by side, each dreaming of a glorious future. One wants to
hold treasure, the second wants to be a mighty ship, and the third
wants to remind people of the power of God. Their wishes come true
_ in ways that will surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When the World Was New'' by L.J. Sattgast (Gold 'N' Honey
Books, $13.99). The Creation story is told in rhyming text for
children who are just learning to read and who will sing along with
you until Day Seven _ when everybody takes a rest.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Go Away, Dark Night'' by Liz Curtis Higgs (Waterbrook Press,
$14.95). Dedicated to ``anyone who has ever been afraid,'' this
book tells the story of Griffin, the boy who dreaded bedtime. A
reassuring read for the preschool set _ a must for any parent who
has ever performed a closet check ... twice.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Just in Case You Ever Wonder'' by Max Lucado (Word
Publishing, $14.99). In simple words, this San Antonio-based writer
shares the promises he has made his three daughters. Among them:
``I'll always love you. I'll always hug you. I'll always be on your
side.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mary's Treasure Box'' by Carolyn Walz Kramlich (Thomas
Nelson Inc., $12.99) and ``Mary, Did You Know?'' by Mark Lowry
(Waterbrook Press, $14.95). Two unconventional and enchanting
versions of the Christmas story.
</P>
<P>
   The following two books are suggestions from Sandy Wade,
director of religious education at St. Christopher's Episcopal
Church in Fort Worth:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Little Book of Prayers,'' selected by Caroline Walsh
(Kingfisher Books, paperback, $8.95). Simple yet profound lines
from the likes of Robert Browning, Ogden Nash and Mother Teresa,
along with traditional prayers.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Kids' Random Acts of Kindness'' (Conari Press, $8.95). This
book is small and square, but its concept is anything but. It's
prefaced by this little story that sold me.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little girl was late getting home from school and her mother
began to scold her, but then she stopped and asked, `Why are you so
late?'
</P>
<P>
   `I had to help another girl. She was in trouble,' explained the
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   `What did you do?' the mother asked.
</P>
<P>
   `Oh, I sat down and helped her cry.'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
