<SLUG> BC-LOVETT-TEXASSONGWRITERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MUSIC: LYLE'S NOT THE ONLY ONE TO LOVETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, a coterie of folk singers played a small group
of clubs on or near college campuses in Austin, Houston, College
Station, Arlington and other Texas cities.
</P>
<P>
   Their songs were studies of relationships (usually going
downhill, often extinguished entirely), mornings spent nursing
hangovers, the call of the open road, growing up in Texas, and
friends met along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Clark, Steve Fromholz, Fort Worth's own Townes Van Zandt,
Dallas' Michael Martin Murphey and the others were called
``progressive country,'' if they were called anything, and each
made some wonderfully small-scale records.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Lovett was a stringy journalism major at Texas A&AMP;M in those
days, and he listened hard. That music struck such a deep chord
with Lovett that this fall he released a two-CD set, ``Step Inside
This House,'' covering songs of Texas songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lovett is the most famous acolyte of those acoustic
mavericks, he certainly wasn't the only one. The legacy of such
performers is today's alternative country, the music of Lone Star
honky-tonkers such as Jack Ingram and Charlie Robison, and quieter
acoustic singer-songwriters such as John Gorka and David Olney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy and Townes are a huge influence on the current generation
of people in the way they wrote,'' says Peter Blackstock,
co-founder of the magazine No Depression, the alt-country bible.
``The way they approached playing music _ the `art is its own
reward' approach. The idea was playing songs you wanted to play.
And a lot of people took that to heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The music was closely related to the redneck country of Willie
Nelson and Waylon Jennings. But numerous songwriters, such as
Olney, recall being impressed by the to-the-bone quality of the
lyrics, the directness of the sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   They also possessed a deep romanticism: They were singing in and
about the most mythologized state in the nation, and they seemed
like a little outlaw posse, bent on nothing more than honesty and
writing good songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They influenced how I grew up listening to music,'' says
Ingram, who went from being a solo folkie playing Deep Ellum bars
in Dallas to a well-known regional honky-tonk favorite. Like
Robison, he records for Sony's Lucky Dog imprint. ``It became a
fabric of my being. It's how they set up their songs. Guy was
writing about how he'd get through the morning after a one-night
stand _ he was writing about something that happened to him and the
emotions of a moment in his life. It was so real.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the guys coming out of Austin and Houston went on to
decent, if not spectacularly popular, careers in the '80s and '90s.
Van Zandt died in 1997, but Clark, Fromholz and Murphey continue to
record and play small to medium-sized venues in the United States
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And outside of Lovett and Robert Earl Keen, so do most of the
younger guys who followed their leads. Which suits Charlie Robison
just fine; if Guy and Townes and Steve taught him anything, it was
to do good work and not worry about the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear these guys writing for themselves,'' he says.
``It was, `This is my art. I'm going to stick it out no matter
what.' The honesty of their songs was unbelievable. And their songs
were the first ones I heard that sounded like my life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
