A7356 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADIAN-EXECUTION-HN     12-01 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPARTMENT JOINS CANADIAN GOVERNMENT SEEKING INTERVENTION IN
SCHEDULED EXECUTION IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The U.S. State Department has joined the Canadian
government in trying to persuade Gov. George W. Bush to spare the
life of a Canadian citizen scheduled to be executed next week for
the 1975 murder of a prominent East Texas woman.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Foreign Minister, as well as various human rights
organizations, have argued in recent weeks that 61-year-old Joseph
Stanley Faulder's death sentence should be set aside because he was
not told when he was arrested that he had the right to contact his
government _ a violation of the 1969 Vienna Convention on Consular
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consular-notification issues in this case are sufficiently
troublesome that they may provide sufficient grounds for according
discretionary clemency relief,'' U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said in a Nov. 27 letter to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is in the Middle East, has not seen the letter but
``will be briefed when he comes back to Texas,'' spokeswoman Linda
Edwards said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will read the letter and consider it carefully, as will the
Board of Pardons and Paroles,'' she said. ``The governor takes
capital cases very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy filed a
friend of the court brief in support of Faulder's final plea to get
his case before the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vienna Convention requires the `competent authorities' to
give prompt notice to detained foreign nationals of their right to
see a consular officer of their own government,'' the brief states.
``It is undisputed that the state of Texas denied Mr. Faulder's
rights of consular notification and access.''
</P>
<P>
   The brief also argues that ``Texas refusal to comply (with the
treaty) is neither accidental nor aberrant'' and represents a
pattern of non-compliance throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Warren, an official with Amnesty International-Canada, said
there are 70 or so foreign nationals from 24 countries on death row
in the United States. ``The majority,'' he said, ``were never
informed of their Vienna Convention rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials have maintained that Faulder had a U.S. driver's
license when he was arrested in Colorado more than a year after the
murder and, therefore, officers may not have known he was Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, who has spent six years gathering material on Faulder's
case, said the documents clearly show that Faulder's nationality
was known to Texas investigators long before he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew he was born in Alberta and they even had his social
insurance number,'' he said, citing correspondence between
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's cause has been taken up not just by his government,
but by a number of private and official organizations. United
Nations Human Rights Commissioner Mary Robinson, after meeting with
Axworthy last week, called for the lifting of Faulder's death
sentence and human rights groups have weighed in with fax
campaigns, Internet messages and press conferences. Others are
planning to descend on Austin from as far away as Toronto to lobby
for clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most troubling death row cases in the
U.S.A.,'' said a fax distributed last week by Chicago-based
Citizens Alert, a ``humane law enforcement'' advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's appeal to the Supreme Court raises not only the
international treaty violation issue, but also the odd nature of
his prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   He has been on death row for 21 years for the 1975 robbery and
murder of Inez Phillips, 75, the matriarch of a wealthy oil family
in Gladewater, 110 miles east of Dallas. The Canadian government
and his family did not know of his whereabouts until 1992, when
they were notified by Sandra Babcock, a young attorney with the
Texas Resource Center, who had taken over his case.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Canadian government has attempted to have his
death sentence commuted to life on the grounds that had his
government and his family known of the charges, they could have
provided legal assistance and testimony that may have resulted in a
different sentence.
</P>
<P>
   At the punishment phase of the trial, Faulder's attorney,
Bernard Solomon, of Gladewater, Texas, did not call a single
witness to testify on his behalf _ a point that the prosecutors
emphasized in urging the jury to return a death verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the treaty had not been breached, there were people who
could have testified for Faulder,'' Warren said. ``The jury would
have known he was not a monster. The jury would have had an
alternative explanation of what happened that night.''
</P>
<P>
   The right to consular services for a foreign national, he said,
``rises to the level of Miranda (which requires arresting officers
to inform suspects of their rights). It raises the same issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Often described as a drifter, Faulder left his home in Jasper,
Alberta, in 1973, after his marriage went sour, and two years later
turned up in East Texas with some biker friends. In Gladewater,
just east of Longview, Texas, he and an accomplice, Lynda McCann,
broke into the home of Inez Phillips and killed her during the
course of the burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years later, he was arrested on an unrelated charge
in Colorado and returned to Longview to stand trial. His accomplice
refused to testify against him and there was no physical evidence
tying him to the crime, but Faulder was convicted and sentenced to
die on the strength of his own confession.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals later reversed the conviction
on the grounds investigators violated Faulder's Fifth Amendment
rights in obtaining the confession. Without it, the prosecution had
no evidence to present at a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   What ensued was a rare, but legal, maneuver by the victim's son,
Jack Phillips. At a cost of $100,000, he hired two attorneys to act
as private prosecutors: Otis Hill, the former Gregg County district
attorney, and Phil Burleson, the Dallas lawyer who had achieved
fame by getting Jack Ruby's conviction for killing Lee Harvey
Oswald overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Burleson and Hill made a deal with Lynda McCann: If she would
testify against Faulder, they would grant her immunity in the case
and give her $15,000 to ``relocate.''
</P>
<P>
   Because an accomplice's testimony alone is not enough for a
conviction, it would have to be corroborated by a non-participant
in the crime. Lynda's husband, Ernie McCann, testified that the
murder happened just as she said. He was paid $2,000 by the
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, Babcock discovered in Burleson's files a
handwritten notation: ``Ernie in on all talking and planning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Brady material,'' she said, referring to a Supreme
Court ruling that requires prosecutors to turn over to the defense
materials that might be beneficial to the accused. That note was
not made available to Faulder's trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The note was critical, she said, because if it meant the husband
was a participant in the crime, his corroborative testimony was
invalid and, therefore, ``The state had no case.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the issue could be clarified, however, Burleson died in
1995 and the state's lawyers have since argued that the notation
was irrelevant and did not pertain to the husband's involvement in
the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important to the case, Warren said, was the fact that
Faulder's history was not made known to the jury _ particularly the
severe head injury he suffered at the age of 3, when he was hurled
from his family car after accidentally opening the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was severe enough that his brain was exposed,'' Warren
said. Growing up, Faulder suffered spells of manic hyperactivity
and blackouts, he said, and neurologists who examined him concluded
that he was unable to distinguish right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Had the jury known that history, he said, it might have decided
on a lesser penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder has twice come within days of execution before being
granted stays. Each time, however, the courts were not swayed by
the issues of international treaty violation and questions about
the private prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Moore, a spokesman for the Canadian Embassy in
Washington, D.C., suggested that while the Foreign Ministry's
office has intervened in the Supreme Court petition, the most
effective route may be diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Article 36 (the right to consular notification) is a very
important aspect of the Vienna Convention,'' he said. ``The
violation of it may have prejudiced his right to a fair trial.
Government's have to take that treaty seriously.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
