<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLEDGES NEW EFFORT TO HELP CHILDREN ORPHANED BY AIDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the world marked AIDS Day for the 11th year,
President Clinton pledged Tuesday a new effort to help children
orphaned by the disease and more measures to help AIDS sufferers in
poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, during a poignant White House event attended by
children whose parents succumbed to the disease, also continued his
push for the development of an AIDS vaccine with a recommendation
for a 33 percent funding increase for research.
</P>
<P>
   New combinations of AIDS drugs and continued research have
helped drive down the rates of death from AIDS in the United States
and developed nations. But the disease remains rampant and deadly
in many developing nations where infection rates continue at
alarming rates and treatment is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When so many people are suffering, and with HIV transmission
disproportionately high, still, among our own young people here in
America, it's all right to celebrate our progress, but we cannot
rest until we have actually put a stop to AIDS,'' Clinton said. ``I
believe we can do it, by developing a vaccine, by increasing our
investment in other forms of research, by improving our care for
those who are infected and our support for their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agency for International Development estimated that 40
million children worldwide will be orphaned by the disease by 2010,
90 percent of them in developing nations with few resources. In the
United States, there currently are 80,000 children whose parents
have died from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced the United States would provide $10 million in
emergency funding to community-based organizations overseas to
support orphans, to take steps to help prevent the spread of HIV
from mother to child and to improve medical care for children with
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot restore to them all they have lost, but we can give
them a future _ a foster family, enough food to eat, medical care,
a chance to make the most of their lives by helping them to stay in
school,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he will dispatch Sandra Thurman, his AIDS policy
adviser, to sub-Saharan Africa where 90 percent of the AIDS orphans
reside.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed the National Institutes of Health dedicate $200
million to AIDS research, a $47 million increase from the current
funding level, for the next fiscal year. And, he proposed NIH
dedicate $164 million, a $38 million increase, to international
projects to help AIDS orphans and fight the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, at a separate event, also announced a
series of grants totalling $220 million from an existing program to
help fund housing for people with AIDS. Texas will receive $14
million in grants with Houston receiving more than half the amount,
$7.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also pledged to a room
full of AIDS-funding advocates to put the AIDS issue on the
international agenda as she meets with world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to make progress, governments must understand what
you and your overseas counterparts already understand, and that is
that HIV-AIDS cannot be denied or ignored or patronized or put off
until tomorrow,'' Albright said. ``This is an urgent, deadly global
threat. It cannot be appeased; it must be confronted.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Slemmer, a Washington, D.C., woman who adopted an AIDS
orphan, spoke of the mother's anguish over who would care for her
daughter, now 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most painful conversations I've ever had was
discussing with Carla her wish that I raise Cynthia after Carla
died. Carla was desperate to be sure that Cynthia would have the
love and guidance to hang on to her dream. Knowing that Cynthia
would not be left alone gave Carla comfort and peace,'' Slemmer
said, who had been a volunteer working with the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of children around the world just like Cynthia need a
second chance and do not get it. Millions of mothers around the
world just like Carla search for that feeling of peace just before
they die and they never find it,'' Slemmer said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
