<HEADER>
A7378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY02-COX     12-01 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCIAL SECURITY HEAD SAYS NO CONSENSUS ON REFORM
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a year of discussing Social Security and a
week before a major White House conference on the issue, Americans
have not reached a consensus on how to reform the federal old-age
insurance program, its director said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the National Press Club, Social Security
Administrator Kenneth S. Apfel said America cannot afford to miss
the opportunity next year to reform the program, which covers 45
million people, nearly a third of them disabled people or the
survivors of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is one of those defining moments for our
country,'' Apfel said. Referring to projections that the federal
budget will run a surplus for years to come, he asked, ``do we use
the surpluses for tax cuts, for spending increases, or for
strengthening Social Security?''
</P>
<P>
   Without reforms, Social Security benefits would exceed payroll
taxes in 2013, Apfel said. By 2032, the program's trust fund
surplus would be depleted, and taxes would cover only 75 percent of
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Apfel's speech came amid a flurry of news conferences aimed at
setting the stage for the White House conference Dec. 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the conference will include presentations from
a variety of experts about the nature of the problem and potential
solutions. The second day, which will be closed to the public, will
involved discussions between Clinton and congressional leaders over
how to proceed with the reform process.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of the first day of the conference will beamed by
satellite to sites around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to begin discussions with Congress early next
year, but Apfel would not indicate when _ or whether _ the
administration would offer its own plan to reform the system.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, William Shipman, co-chairman of the Cato
Institute Project on Social Security Privatization, suggested that
the public would be better served by allowing people to take 4 or 5
percent of the 12.4 percent payroll tax paid by workers and
employers and invest the money in individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But Brookings Institute senior fellows Henry J. Aaron and Robert
Reischauer, at a news conference unveiling their analysis of
various reform proposals, said such a ``carve-out'' proposal would
weaken the existing system and impose an administrative nightmare
on businesses while failing to adequately protect retirement
income.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron and Reischauer suggested that Social Security could be
preserved by investing the trust fund surplus in private equity
accounts managed by a quasi-independent governmental agency, plus a
series of minor reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement among experts highlights what Apfel called the
``very big, very tough and very important issues. It's fair to say
that I have not heard a consensus among the American people about
how to protect and strengthen Social Security. Nor have I heard any
consensus here in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Apfel, who said that with the exception of a ``major increase''
in the payroll tax rate, all reform proposals are on the table,
noted that most carry tradeoffs which the American public generally
oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Such tradeoffs include raising the eligibility age, raising the
tax rate by a smaller amount, or reducing benefits. Proposals to
allow individual investments are popular among young workers who
are willing to take more risks than older workers and retirees, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the Social Security system is not facing an
immediate crisis, Apfel said now was the time to act because any
changes could be gradually implemented and cause a minimum of
disruption.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he noted that the robust economy and the first
federal budget surplus in a generation set the stage for reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House conference gives us an opportunity to start
talking about common ground for the common good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
