<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      12-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TARGETS AIDS FUNDS FOR ORPHANS ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As death rates from AIDS have plummeted
dramatically at home, President Clinton announced Tuesday that the
government would provide more money and attention to help
developing nations defeat the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``All around us there is ... fresh evidence that the epidemic is
far from over, our work is far from finished,'' Clinton said at a
White House ceremony commemorating World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot forget our profound obligation for the heartbreaking
youngest victims of the disease _ the orphaned children left in its
wake,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton singled out Zimbabwe, where experts believe that 11
people are infected every minute. ``There are still too many
children orphaned by AIDS, tens of thousands here in America, tens
of millions in developing nations around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright joined Clinton and called
the spread of AIDS ``an urgent, deadly, global threat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do all I can to see that this imperative is raised as a
matter of international security at the highest levels, at every
opportunity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a package of AIDS-related programs targeted abroad,
the president pledged $10 million to help care for foreign children
whose parents have died of AIDS, and he also said he would dispatch
to Africa his AIDS policy adviser, Sandra Thurman, to determine how
the United States can do more.
</P>
<P>
   The money, which will come from emergency funds and does not
require congressional approval, will be used for training foster
families and schooling orphans.
</P>
<P>
   The aid likely will have the most impact in Africa, where most
AIDS orphans live. The United States Agency for International
Development estimates that about 40 million children will be
orphaned by AIDS by 2010, with the vast majority living in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced that the National Institutes of Health
would spend $200 million this year to develop AIDS vaccines, an
increase of $47 million over the previous year. The money is
already included in this year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Countries devastated by the disease will be major beneficiaries
of preventive AIDS vaccines, which currently are under development
at U.S. pharmaceutical companies and the NIH. An effective,
low-cost vaccine is eagerly awaited in destitute countries that
cannot afford the costly drug cocktails used to treat AIDS
patients.
</P>
<P>
   NIH also will spend $164 million this year, $38 million more
than the last year, to develop worldwide AIDS treatment and
prevention efforts, Clinton said. Some of the money will go for
training foreign scientists and devising new ways of blocking AIDS
transmission from a pregnant mother to her unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcements came as AIDS organizations criticized
Clinton for not doing enough to slow the spread of the disease both
abroad and at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing skyrocketing infection rates and an AIDS
holocaust in Africa because of our failure to address prevention
and international efforts,'' said Daniel Zingale, executive
director of AIDS Action, which represents over 3,000 AIDS
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Government- and industry-sponsored research has resulted in
increasingly effective anti-viral drugs and a new class of
treatments known as protease inhibitors. As a result, the AIDS
death rate in the United States has plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, the number of deaths from AIDS fell 29 percent in 1996
and 47 percent last year, the largest decline for any major disease
in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   But because most developing nations cannot afford the drugs, the
disease is spreading in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   According to a United Nations study released last week, 2
million Africans will die of AIDS this year, four times the total
for the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Africans also are infected at a higher rate that Americans.
About 33 million people around the globe are infected with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS _ two-thirds in sub-Saharan Africa.
Worldwide, approximately 6 million people will be infected this
year with the human immunodeficiency virus, two-thirds of the cases
in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
