<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY FUN FOR CHILDREN AND PARENTS ALIKE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holiday books teach kids about the rituals of Christmas and
Hanukkah. Curling up on the couch with a favorite story year after
year also creates a family tradition _ a quiet time to reflect on
the deeper meaning of religious celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Here are highlights of new children's books for the season: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Christmas With Teddy Bear &QL; 
 &UR; Jacqueline McQuade (Penguin Putnam, $6.99)
</P>
<P>
   A brown cuddly Teddy Bear counts through the days till Christmas
in this delightful board book for toddlers. Teddy Bear walks young
children through the season's rituals: window shopping, building a
snowman, writing to Santa, singing carols, tree decorating,
wrapping presents, hanging his stocking, opening presents from
Santa _ and most important of all _ giving to others. The
illustrations of the Bear family and its pet kitten are
heartwarming, with familiar scenes little ones will enjoy. For ages
1-4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Maccabee Jamboree: A Hanukkah Countdown &QL; 
 &UR; Cheri Holland; illustrated by Roz Schanzer (Kar-Ben Copies, $4.95)
</P>
<P>
   The countdown to Hanukkah is celebrated by eight Maccabees who
disappear one by one as they polish the menorah, wrap gifts, twirl
dreidels, cook latkes, sing songs and light candles. When one
Maccabee is left alone wondering where everyone went, his friends
rush back with a big surprise! This and other Hanukkah books are
available through Kar-Ben, based in Rockville, Md. For ages 2-4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The Mitten &QL; 
 &UR; Jan Brett (Penguin Putnam, $14.99 gift box)
</P>
<P>
   Very young children will get a kick out of donning a pair of
real mittens embossed with mole as they listen to this board book
gift edition of Brett's 1989 classic.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a Ukrainian folk tale, the story is about Nicki, who
lost one of his white mittens in the snow. A mole found it and
crawled inside, followed by a rabbit, a hedgehog, an owl, a badger,
a fox, a bear, and a tiny little mouse, who made the bear sneeze.
Off went the mitten, flying back to Nicki. Brett's realistic,
detailed paintings of snowy winter scenes have a cozy holiday feel.
For the kindergarten set, Brett has illustrated a newly released
version of ``The Night Before Christmas.'' For ages 2-5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Max's Christmas &QL; 
 &UR; Rosemary Wells (Dial Books, $8.99)
</P>
<P>
   Max the bunny and his ever-exuberant sister, Ruby, experience
the excitement of Christmas Eve. Ruby insists on going to sleep
fast so Santa will come, but Max is determined to stay up late and
see the Big Guy himself. Wells, one of the most prolific authors of
children's literature, captures the zaniness with her goofy
characters in this board book. For ages 2-5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The First Christmas &QL; 
 &UR; Adapted by Sindy McKay; illustrated by Mary O'Keefe Young (Treasure
Bay,
 &UR; $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   Parents and children can read together the Christmas story about
Mary, Joseph and baby Jesus in this holiday release from the
creators of the ``We Both Read'' series. Parents read the left-hand
pages, which contain more complex sentences and vocabulary, and
kids read the right-hand pages, written in simple language and
short sentences. Some words that carry over from the adult to child
page are highlighted in bold type for recognition.
</P>
<P>
   This is an excellent method to teach young readers, as well as
to encourage family togetherness. Other new titles are: ``The Three
Little Pigs''; ``Ben &AMP; Becky Get a Pet''; and ``About Bugs.'' For
ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Franklin's Christmas Gift &QL; 
 &UR; Paulette Bourgeois; illustrated by Brenda Clark (Scholastic, $4.50)
</P>
<P>
   A Christmas toy drive for needy families teaches Franklin the
turtle about the joy of giving . . . but not without considerable
internal struggle. He digs through his 60 jillion old toys and
decides there is maybe ONE he could live without _ a rusty truck
with a missing wheel. But his Dad says that isn't even close to
being ``gently used.''
</P>
<P>
   More struggle follows before Franklin decides to give away
something near and dear to him. Far from making him sad, Franklin
gets ``that good-all-over feeling.'' Clark's illustrations of the
animal characters going through human activities are charming. For
ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Dear Santa &QL; 
 &UR; The Best-Ever, Busiest Christmas Fun Book (Dutton, $16.99)
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation is one of the best parts of Christmas. This
activity book contains 24 envelopes for kids to open each December
day preceding the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The envelopes on the left side contain notes from Santa, craft
ideas, ornaments and song lyrics. On the opposite page are short
stories about Christmas customs in other parts of the world _ such
as luminarias in Mexico and Boxing Day in Australia. Suggestions
for activities such as baking cookies and making gift tags also are
included. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; This Is the Star &QL; 
 &UR; Joyce Dunbar; illustrated by Gary Blythe (Harcourt Brace, $6)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Christ child, born to be king, while hosts of
heavenly angels sing. . . .'' Dunbar's rhythmic text guides readers
through the story of the Nativity, beginning and ending with a lone
star in the night sky. Blythe's museum-quality paintings are so
realistic they are like photographs with an artist's soft touch.
First released in hard-cover in 1996, the volume won a ``Publishers
Weekly'' Best Book of the Year award. Now, it is in a more
affordable paperback version. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The Nutcracker &QL; 
 &UR; Story adapted by Natalia Merentseva and Michele Spirn; illustrated
by Azat
 &UR; Minnekaev (Harry N. Abrams, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   This Christmas favorite, penned in 1816 by German author E.T.A.
Hoffmann, is interpreted by a Russian husband-and-wife team with
help from children's author Spirn.
</P>
<P>
   Minnekaev's illustrations of young Clara's journey through the
wondrous land of fairies and make-believe have an ephemeral quality
_ almost like the ballet. But unlike the ballet, the text includes
a sub-plot from the original story about a sausage-hungry Mouse
Queen who casts a spell on the young prince, transforming him into
the Nutcracker.
</P>
<P>
   Oversize pages and easy-to-read type make this authentic version
of the tale a bedtime treat. For ages 7-10. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Beverly Medlyn can be reached at
bevmedlyn(at)aol.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
