<HEADER>
A7426 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-COUNTRYSIDE-960     12-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-COUNTRYSIDE-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITORS ESCAPE TO ITALIAN COUNTRYSIDE, DISCOVERING BEAUTY,
MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHY FRISINGER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unbelievably, our 25th anniversary was approaching. To
celebrate, my husband and I planned a trip to Italy with our best
friends, also marking that anniversary. The four of us pored over
maps and travel books, plotting out an itinerary that would take us
through Rome, Florence, Venice _ all the usual tourist places. But
then I talked to my friend Carol, who had lived in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just going to the cities?'' Pause. I swear I could hear
a frown over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Capri is my favorite place in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So we eventually found ourselves on the Circumvesuviana, the
train that rings the Bay of Naples.
</P>
<P>
   But things weren't going so well. There had been an unpleasant
misunderstanding about luggage at the Naples train station, a black
and gloomy place, and then a race to the train. By the time we
boarded, it was standing-room-only in a compartment where
passengers were packed like anchovies. And the air conditioning
wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   But after a while, the crowd inside the rail car thinned, and
outside the window we saw an intriguing sight: rows of trees heavy
with smiley-face-yellow fruit. Lemons!
</P>
<P>
   When the train made a stop on a bridge over a deep gorge where
picturesque homes dotted the sides of the rock and the blue of the
Mediterranean sparkled in the background, I breathed a sigh of
relief.
</P>
<P>
   That view turned out to be a preview of our experience in
Sorrento, where sheer cliffs drop off to the Mediterranean and a
gorge cuts through the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a place for darting about seeing churches and museums,
but rather a haven to kick back, sleep late in the morning, swim in
the afternoon and lounge at an outdoor bar for hours at night.
</P>
<P>
   Though not exactly inexpensive, hotels in Sorrento are a bargain
compared with tourist-thick cities like Rome and Florence. Our room
at the Hotel Caravel was by far the largest, most luxurious room of
a two-week Italy trip, but, at $120, cost less than any of our
accommodations in the northern cities.
</P>
<P>
   We slowed our pace to match the tempo of the town, sleeping in
in the morning and then taking a swim.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, after a hot, dusty day of sightseeing in
Pompeii, we found a trattoria _ a casual dinner spot _ not quite on
the water, but close enough to it that cool breezes came in through
the open doors and windows. A white cat came through one of the
windows. Maybe it was attracted by the seafood, which was perhaps
the best meal of our trip. We fondly remember the linguine mare, an
artfully displayed dish of pasta, mussels and clams in their
shells.
</P>
<P>
   POMPEII: Pompeii knocked our socks off.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get there _ the Circumvesuviana stops right outside
the entrance to the city (about 30 minutes east from Sorrento or
south from Naples). And it's a bargain, too. Admission is about $7,
and an audio tour is about $5.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting tourists enter the excavated ruins of the city _ buried
by the eruption of Mount Vesuvius _ via a tunnel through the
defensive walls that surround it, just as visiting traders did
2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   You can see Vesuvius in the background; its last eruption was in
1944.
</P>
<P>
   The tour begins with the forum, which was the center of life of
the ancient city. It's surrounded by the remains of public
buildings, including the temple of Jupiter and Minerva, a market
and theaters.
</P>
<P>
   As you leave the public area, you enter into a maze of narrow,
cobblestone streets. I had seen pictures of rows of small, square
rooms that I had taken to be the homes of Pompeii's residents.
Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The well-to-do lived in large, multiroomed, sometimes
multistoried houses, with hallways, courtyards, murals, tiled
mosaic floors, gardens in the back, a form of indoor plumbing, and
even indoor pools. The rows of small rooms turned out to be shops
attached the fronts of the homes of the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The audio tours proved invaluable. The tavern owners were
considered to be disreputable women, we were told. People rose
early, and everyone, including slaves, finished work in the
morning, which made the baths popular afternoon recreation for all
Pompeii's residents, we learned.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ghoulish but intriguing prizes of Pompeii is the
excavated bodies of people who were buried in ash and stones from
the eruption in A.D. 79. Most of the 20,000 residents escaped the
eruption, but about 2,000 lingered and were buried alive.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies we saw seemed tiny. ``The fingers show the
characteristic curl of oxygen starvation,'' the tape noted.
</P>
<P>
   Farther on into the city, in the entryway of a dwelling dubbed
the ``House of the Tragic Poet,'' a black-and-white mosaic picture
of a dog bears a neighborly warning: cave canem, (beware of the
dog).
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Following cobblestone streets rutted by ancient wagons to the
far side of Pompeii brings visitors to the most impressive home of
the site, the Villa dei Misteri (the House of Mystery). The
palatial house is a maze of rooms, one of which contains a
beautifully preserved series of murals.
</P>
<P>
   CAPRI: The fabled beauty of Capri has drawn men and women of
wealth for thousands of years. When Augustus Caesar needed to get
away from it all, he escaped to Capri. Tiberius made his court on
the island. George Bernard Shaw and D.H. Lawrence found inspiration
on its heights.
</P>
<P>
   Now hydrofoil boats make the island in the Mediterranean a
convenient day trip for travelers of more modest means.
</P>
<P>
   The ride from Sorrento to Capri is a delight in itself. With
summer temperatures in southern Italy that almost rival Texas
scorchers, skimming across the sea on a hydrofoil with cool air
rushing across your face was a welcome experience.
</P>
<P>
   The towering island has three towns: Marina Grande, at sea
level, where the hydrofoils and ferries dock; Capri, partway up the
island, with the best views and the best restaurants and the best
shops catering to the ``best'' people; and Anacapri, higher up
still but with less lofty standards.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unexpected pleasures of Capri was the fun of just
getting around from place to place. A funicular hoists people from
Marina Grande up to Capri town. We mostly traveled by bus, the
highest, narrowest buses I'd ever seen, on the narrowest roads I'd
ever ridden along.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous sight on Capri is the Grotto Azure _ the Blue
Grotto. But if Pompeii was the biggest success of our trip, the
Blue Grotto was the biggest disappointment. It's not that the
cavern isn't as pretty as reputed, or that it's hideously expensive
(about $10 per person) _ it's just that the whole experience takes
only about three minutes. Hoping to earn a tip, our boat driver
offered to sing for us. ``No, please don't,'' I said. He sang
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to have traveled all the way to Capri and not to have
seen the ethereal blue light in the grotto would be unthinkable. A
little rest and a little limoni (a liqueur that looks like liquid
sunshine and tastes like liquid fire) revived us.
</P>
<P>
   Capri, like much of Europe, takes a nap in the afternoon. But in
the early evening, when the daytrippers have departed and the
temperatures have dropped, the place gets gussied up.
</P>
<P>
   Then the upper-crust visitors _ men decked out in white suits,
women in summer evening dresses _ stroll the streets of Capri town,
admiring an Armani suit in a shop window, stopping in at Cartier to
pick out a little bauble as a souvenir of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Our traveling companions went to Capri for the evening, but we
decided to stay in Anacapri and walk out to a scenic overlook on
the far side of the island.
</P>
<P>
   We headed down Via Magliara, a street that is little more than a
paved path. It took us through what I decided must be the most
intensely farmed spot in the world. Each gate that we passed led
into a two-level garden. At the ground level there were rows of
beans or potatoes or some other garden staple. But each yard also
had a second story, about 12 feet above ground level, thick with
grapevines.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't imagine that the understory vegetables would get
enough light to grow successfully, but all the doubledecker gardens
seemed lush and green.
</P>
<P>
   The yards we passed had high walls in front, but we could see in
through the gates and we could hear cooking sounds and voices
coming from inside the homes as we strolled past. Behind one gate,
an elderly woman, her head wrapped with a kerchief, sat reading to
three small children. Her voice rang clear in the quiet of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Via Magliara ends at a gorgeous overlook with a view of the Puta
del Tuono lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   After an admiring pause, we turned around and headed back a few
hundred yards to Da Gelsomina, a recommended trattoria, where we
stopped for dinner. There were a half-dozen other tables occupied,
all by stylish young Italians. How had all those other people
gotten to this place, I wondered? We'd walked for 40 minutes and
had only passed one other couple along the path.
</P>
<P>
   As we sat there sipping wine, pondering _ but not too hard _
this mystery, I decided I agreed with Carol. Mixing a little of
Mother Nature's artwork in with our tour of the Renaissance
masterpieces was a wonderfully romantic idea. And, yes, I think
Capri is my favorite place in the world, too.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
