<HEADLINE>
QUEBEC ELECTION DOES LITTLE TO EASE UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A joke has it that what Quebecers really want is an
independent Quebec in a strong unified Canada.
</P>
<P>
   That was exactly the contradictory message that emerged Tuesday
as the smoke cleared from Monday's closely-watched provincial
elections.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, voters in the only Canadian province with a
French-speaking majority handed Premier Lucien Bouchard's
separatist Parti Quebecois a strong reelection victory: 75 seats in
the 125-seat National Assembly, or provincial legislature. Plus,
the Parti Quebecois may capture another seat in a special election
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the same voters refused to lay electoral
waste to the federalist challengers, led by Jean Charest, with
anything like the savagery pollsters and pundits so confidently
predicted right up until ballot tallies showed a tighter race than
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of either crushing federalism in Quebec or giving the
separatist movement irrestible momentum, the elections did little
more than reinforce the political uncertainty that has bedeviled
Canada for four years, since the Parti Qubecois vaulted to power in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of secession is still pressed against the nation like
the muzzle of a loaded gun. For now, the separatists don't have the
strength to pull the trigger. But Bouchard has five more years in
office to work on bulking up that trigger finger.
</P>
<P>
   The Parti Quebecois victory, although impressive, failed to
become the landslide that Bouchard had so fervently wished. At the
same time, the drubbing taken by federalists stopped short of total
rout.
</P>
<P>
   One bizarre result: the victors wore mostly scowls, while the
losers couldn't stop strutting and grinning into the television
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard ducked and weaved around questions about the prospects
of another referendum on independence, promising only that Quebec
would ``carry on in pursuit of its destiny. We are committed to
stay the course.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he admitted, ``winning conditions for a referendum do
not exist at the present time.''
</P>
<P>
   Charest, meanwhile, was happily holding court with supporters
and journalists, assuring everyone that federalist defeat was
really a ``moral victory,'' while separatist victory was defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Quebec and the people of Canada all want this
country to work together,'' he told a news conference. ``The
members of the Parti Quebecois today have to be very uncomfortable
with the results.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if he'd engineered one of the great upsets in
political history. He hadn't. All Charest had done was confound
analysts by losing somewhat less spectacularly than projected.
</P>
<P>
   But appearances count for a lot in politics. And Charest did
score one indisputable victory by garnering a slightly larger share
of the popular vote _ about 0.7 percent larger _ than the
separatists. Because of the composition of electoral districts in
Quebec, however, the Liberals still captured only 48 seats in the
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Charest's ``popular victory,'' as jubilant
supporters described it, owed little to the federalist campaign.
Instead, the separatists suffered as a larger-than-anticipated
number of votes were siphoned off by a tiny third party, Action
Democratique-Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Led by 28-year-old Mario Dumont, Action-Democratique is a
right-leaning party, opposed to secession, that won surprising
support from young people disaffected by the endless bickering
between federalists and separatists. Although Action-Democratique
won nearly 12 percent of the vote and was arguably the only true
``moral victor,'' Dumont was the sole party member to actually win
a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Action-Democratique was the only Quebec party to gain supporters
since the 1994 election, roughly doubling its ballot tally to
454,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quebecers want constitutional peace,'' Dumont said. ``More and
more Quebecers are sick and tired of the old squabbles of the old
parties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
