<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIXTONBOUND-960(2Tak     12-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIXTONBOUND-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS LONDON 'HOOD, THE BOYZ HAVE MANY ACCENTS AND SHOPPING IS
ECLECTIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANETTE RODRIGUES 
and NICHELE HOSKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's Saturday morning, and the sun is shining as we
board the underground (subway) in Paddington, a predominantly
white, middle- to upper-middle class section of London. We're
headed for the 'hood _ Brixton.
</P>
<P>
   As African-American children of the '80s, we couldn't NOT go to
Brixton, immortalized by singers like Eddie Grant and second-wave
ska bands like the Specials.
</P>
<P>
   In south London, Brixton is a 20-minute tube ride on the
Victoria Line from our Paddington hotel. When we step onto Tunstall
Road, one of the neighborhood's main drags, its sidewalk is crowded
with people heading to or from the indoor/outdoor bazaar on
Electric Avenue. A Rastafarian we encounter on the way gives us a
handbill advertising a rally to protest police actions in the case
of Stephen Lawrence, a black man slain by racist thugs.
</P>
<P>
   The cloying smell of incense and the occasional whiff of rotting
garbage are a sharp change from deodorized Central London. Brixton
is a 180-degree change from the formal splendor and British Tourist
Authority appeal of Trafalgar Square, Buckingham Palace and
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   With its small shops, eateries and neighborhood feel, it's
reminiscent of the Shaw neighborhood in Washington, D.C.
Ironically, both were the sites of urban unrest, ignored by the
establishment for years, and then finally resurrected through
economic development and gentrification.
</P>
<P>
   We step into an Italian coffee bar for some strong joe and flaky
croissants. As we sit at the bar, we eavesdrop on an animated
conversation between the owner and his friend. They're speaking
Arabic, not Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Fortified, we leave in search of the bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Brixton is to London what Brooklyn is to New York. Blacks have
lived in the U.K. for centuries, but in the 1950s, Brixton became
the center of migration from former British colonies such as
Jamaica, India and Nigeria. Today, it has become a haven for
refugees from war-torn countries: Vietnam, Somalia and Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   Brixton's Electric Avenue bazaar caters to this ethnically and
culturally diverse clientele. Electric Avenue was made famous in
the 1980s by the eponymous Eddie Grant song; the street got its
name when it became the first shopping street in London to get
electricity, in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a shopping hub ever since. Located behind the tube, or
subway, stop, the bazaar is packed with browsers and vendors. The
entire city of London is so crammed that people often bump into
you. But only in Brixton do they say, ``Excuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   The bazaar's shops _ some no larger than booths _ are an
eclectic mix, selling everything from vintage clothes and vinyl
records to synthetic hair for braids and novelty lighters.
</P>
<P>
   In one booth, a Nigerian seamstress takes a modern turn on
traditional clothing. The fitted, hip-length jackets have wide,
embroidered drop collars, and they come with skirts that skim the
leg line. Nice, but not at $100 American.
</P>
<P>
   Janette finds a West Indian bakery that specializes in Jamaican
beef patties and coco bread. She buys two of each for about $4.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the bazaar are signs praising the Reggae Boys, the
Jamaican soccer team that made it to the World Cup. The borough
where Brixton is located has the highest proportion of
Afro-Caribbean residents in London, and the third highest of
Africans. The local business community is heavily Nigerian.
</P>
<P>
   Produce, fish and meat, as well as dry goods, dominate the
bazaar. There's fresh coconut and cassava as well as fenugreek and
whole nutmeg. The scotch bonnet peppers are twice as big as your
eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   The tangy-sweet smell of mango mingles with the chemical stench
of hair straighteners.
</P>
<P>
   We raid the ATM machine, which gives us the best exchange rate.
Then we buy hand-painted glass candlesticks for $15 a pair; a
silver-and-garnet snake armlet and a rainbow sweater for $30 each
and some African-looking fabric from a West Indian woman for $1.60
a yard.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of shopping, we duck into Joseph's Bar and Cafe.
Our waitress disappears after seating us, so we order our food at
the bar. The nouveau Jamaican food arrives via dumbwaiter.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth the wait. Delicious salt cod and ackee and a side
dish of fried plantain cost $14; salmon with a lime beurre blanc on
a bed of calaloo, or cooked greens, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop is Red Records, where a member of the Fruit of
Islam tells one of us he knows she is American because she's
friendly and wears her hair natural. Red's is known as the place to
buy everything from jazz and R&AMP;B to ska and reggae. We purchase
some Nina Simone albums that we've been unable to find in the
States.
</P>
<P>
   Brixton is also known for its night life, but we are too tired
from an earlier foray in Central London to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days earlier in Central London, we'd tried to get
into Heaven _ the one on Charing Cross Road known as the city's
largest gay/straight dance club. Unfortunately, Heaven is closed
for renovation.
</P>
<P>
   There's a country song in there someplace.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, we chat up a ``gypsy'' cabdriver and we're off to
his favorite haunt, the Tube. Located on Falconberg Court in Soho,
the club has low ceilings, black lights and hand-painted
fluorescent decorations. The groove is thumping techno-funk.
</P>
<P>
   At about 2 a.m. Friday, we find a licensed cab easily. No such
luck the next night in Soho. After a long walk along The Strand
through Piccadilly Circus and Trafalgar Square, we arrive at
Charing Cross Hotel. About 100 people are lined up waiting for
cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is a drunken fellow with a shaven head who looks as
if he just lost a fight; dried blood cakes his nose and jeans. When
one driver loads a group of posh women into his cab, the drunk
calls him dirty names. Loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Not the best tactic. The cabby who finally picks us up says he
chooses weekend fares carefully to avoid the drunks.
</P>
<P>
   The cabbies in the roomy black cabs are friendly, and unlike the
independent ``gypsy cabs,'' they must pass ``The Knowledge'' _ a
rigorous test to prove they know London's streets by heart. The
Public Carriage Office, or PCO, which is run by the London police
department, tests drivers, issues licenses to those who pass and
makes sure their vehicles are road ready.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Like any first-time visitors to the city on the River Thames, we
also visit sites like the Royal Albert Hall in South Kensington and
the royal jewels at the Tower of London.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tower, we first watch videos of the pretties and the
ceremonies in which they are used. Then a conveyor belt glides us
past glass cases containing the loot: crowns, scepters, ceremonial
spoons and other sparklies.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide, George the Yeoman Warder, is the best part of our
Tower visit. Yeoman Warders once guarded the Tower, which is
actually several towers built over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   In a booming voice, George tells us why the well-fed ravens hang
around. The romantic legend is that if the ravens ever leave, the
Tower of London and the Crown will fall.
</P>
<P>
   The tale gets grisly and involves ``soggy bits.'' Back in the
old days, folk got beheaded at the Tower with gruesome regularity.
George tells us how the noggins of the unfortunate were stuck onto
pikes near the Thames, where fat, happy ravens dined upon their
soggy bits: eyes, tongues, lips, etc.
</P>
<P>
   We recommend spending the $14 to see the Tower. The Big Bus Tour
Company of London is also worth the $18 ticket. You can hop buses
and routes to travel throughout Central London for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The bus puts us off on Piccadilly Circus. We stroll past St.
James's Palace, cut through calming Green Park and arrive at
Buckingham Palace in time to catch the changing of the guard with
about 900 other tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The show in front of the queen's crib is overrated, but it's
free. And we do see Emperor Akihito of Japan ride through the
palace gates.
</P>
<P>
   The Keeper of the Chrysanthemum Throne waves. We wave back.
</P>
<P>
   We go to Harrods in Knightsbridge, just to say we did.
</P>
<P>
   There, we skeptically look for a lawn mower in the famously
swank department store _ and find one. We're taken with the
Egyptian Hall until we realize that the sphinxes bear a freaky
resemblance to Harrods' owner, Mohammed al Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   Even the store's restrooms are exclusive. If you're a mere
window shopper, expect to pay $1.60 to answer the call in Harrods.
The loo is free only if you've bought something.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   On our last night in London, we buy tapas at a restaurant near
our hotel, unwrap the beef patties and coco bread and uncork a dry
riesling. We drag some chairs out on the balcony, put on thick
sweaters and enjoy the view of Norfolk Square. We feel like
characters in a Merchant and Ivory film.
</P>
<P>
   Then we hear a voice from below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to speak to you,'' says the voice.
</P>
<P>
   We look down and introduce ourselves to a young black man named
Yusef. He tells us he lives in a two-bedroom flat and is one of the
few blacks residing in Paddington. The apartment was a gift from
his Senegalese father; that's the only way a 26-year-old struggling
musician could afford such a tony neighborhood. We banter
flirtatiously about music, race relations and how much we love
Brixton.
</P>
<P>
   Yusef tells us he visited the United States but returned to the
U.K. because it's home; this despite harassment by bobbies who
constantly stop him and ask him what he is doing in Paddington.
</P>
<P>
   Yusef says he is surprised that we ventured into the 'hood. He
says most tourists and even some London residents don't visit.
</P>
<P>
   Having experienced Brixton for ourselves, we honestly can't
imagine why not.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
