<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT02-COX     12-01 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUN WITNESS: MICROSOFT SEEKS TO MONOPOLIZE JAVA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft is seeking to ``fragment'' the promising
Java software technology in order to protect its Windows monopoly,
its creator charged in antitrust testimony released by the
government Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 34-page brief, Sun Microsystems Inc. vice president James
Gosling warned that ``if Microsoft successfully fragments the Java
technology, the cross-platform benefits to vendors, developers, and
users ...will be damaged and any threat that (it) poses to
Microsoft's dominant Windows operating system (for personal
computers) will be neutralized.''
</P>
<P>
   Since software written using Java can run independently of
operating systems, developers refer to it as a ``write once, run
anywhere'' technology. Fearing that the rise of Java could reduce
the importance of Windows, Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates once wrote
in an e-mail message that the Java cross-platform threat ``scares
the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its wide-ranging antitrust suit, the government
contends that Microsoft Corp. has illegally encouraged developers
to write software using a Windows-only version of Java while
ignoring Sun's universal standards.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, David Boies, the Justice Department's lead attorney
in the landmark trial, called the government's charge that
Microsoft tried illegally to maintain its Windows dominance ``the
core of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosling's testimony was released only after U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is trying the case without a jury,
blew up at Microsoft's legal team for stretching out its attack on
a government expert witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be brought to a halt,'' Jackson told Michael
Lacovara after the company's lawyer sought to extend his
cross-examination of economist Frederick Warren-Boulton into a
seventh trial day.
</P>
<P>
   As the next move in the legal chess game, Boies plans to play
about two hours of Gates's videotaped testimony on the Java issue
before the Microsoft team challenges Gosling on the witness stand
for the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   As Gosling sees it, Microsoft, Sun's arch-rival in the software
business, ``has used its ubiquitous operating system to flood the
market with its Microsoft-dependent implementation'' of Java.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's actions threaten to make its implementation, called
Java Direct, ``the de facto standard, thus eliminating the threat
posed by the Java technology to Microsoft's operating system
monopoly,'' Gosling wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a federal judge in a related lawsuit issued a
preliminary injunction against Microsoft that prevents the company
from selling any version of Java incompatible with Sun's so-called
``pure Java,'' which is both a programming language and a set of
mini-applications that run mainly on Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Gosling, in his testimony, also said he was told in February
1997 by a Microsoft official that the software giant ``wouldn't be
cowboys'' and develop a Windows-specific version of the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the widespread availability of products that distribute
Sun's Java technology, its relative lack of success in the
marketplace cannot be blamed on Microsoft,'' the corporate
defenders said in a statement aimed at refuting Gosling's testimony
before he is sworn in as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun set unreasonable marketplace expectations and failed to
deliver on its promises. Further, it is Sun that is attempting to
foreclose developer and customer choice by insisting Java cannot be
used efficiently to develop applications that take full advantage
of a particular operating system, despite the fact the majority of
developers today are using Java in this way,'' the Microsoft
statement concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
