<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-EMMONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWARD EMMONS, 86; INFLUENCED STUDY OF FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.J.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howard W. Emmons, a retired professor of engineering at Harvard
University known by some as the ``the father of fire science,''
died of complications of liver cancer Nov. 20 in Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston. He was 86 and resided in Lexington,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Emmons's early research focused on the firestorms that
engulfed German cities after Allied air raids during World War II.
His application of the principles of high-temperature plasma
dynamics to the spread of fire led to the development of computer
models of building fires.
</P>
<P>
   Those models contributed to the understanding of disasters such
as the fire in the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas in 1980 and had
many implications for the construction industry.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the National Academy of Science's committee on
fire research, he was influential in the passage of the National
Fire Research and Safety Act of 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Morristown, N.J., he graduated from Stevens Institute of
Technology in Hoboken, N.J., and earned a doctorate at Harvard
University in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career he worked on the design of jet engines. He
first described the phenomena of turbulence in fluids, which became
known as Emmons's turbulent spot.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former resident of Sudbury, where he was chairman of
the School Committee for many years. He was also a member of the
town's Board of Selectmen from 1969 to 1972.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement from teaching in 1983, he continued
research. In June he presented a technical paper at the 14th
meeting of the joint US-Japan Panel on Fire Research and Safety in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a daughter, Beverly, of Brooklyn, N.Y.; two sons,
Scott W., also of Brooklyn, and Keith of Los Gatos, Calif.; and
three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
