<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWDER-HER-FACE-OPERA     12-01 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWDER-HER-FACE-OPERA-$ADV06-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VETERAN AT 27, THOMAS ADES MAY ONLY BE STARTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Great Britain)   (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)  
(mk) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the second act of Thomas Ades' opera ``Powder Her
Face,'' which opens at the Majestic Theater of the Brooklyn Academy
of Music on Tuesday, the central character _ a duchess, anonymous
but based on the Duchess of Argyll who gave Britain some widely
enjoyed scandal in the 1950s _ is being interviewed. She will not,
she says, speak about certain ``matters'': matters the opera has
already disclosed, including the rapid social ascent that her money
gained her and the lurid divorce that came when she was revealed to
be treating male servants and hotel employees with too much
attention.
</P>
<P>
   She does warm up when she realizes that the ``secrets'' the
journalist wants are those of her success, but then is led by her
own eloquence into making a stream of unhealthy remarks about
modern society. These the journalist seems not to notice, being too
busy taking down the beauty tips she has confided: ``Always wash in
cold water,'' ``Cold cream is best for the maturer skin.'' But who
knows what will appear in print?
</P>
<P>
   Ades does not take such risks anymore. Having seen his
personality evaporate, leaving unrecognizable shadows on the pages
of newspapers and magazines, he has called a halt. His reticence is
understandable. Though only 27, he has been relentlessly acclaimed
in his native Britain for nearly a decade, and the appetite for his
music is now international.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powder Her Face,'' which was first performed three years ago
at the Cheltenham Festival in England, has since been seen at the
Aspen Music Festival in a production on which the semistaged
version to be presented by BAM and the Brooklyn Philharmonic is
based. Further stagings are to follow next year in Europe and
Australia. Most of the young composer's output is already available
on three EMI albums, and performances of his smaller works are
everywhere, with attendant publicity. Everyone wants a piece of
him. But the only pieces he wants to give, at this point, are his
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   To quote the duchess again: ``Ev'rything now is solitude,
ev'ryone is alone.'' The irony is, though, that Ades has been
driven to isolation so that he can safeguard his ability to
communicate publicly and to challenge, through his music, a social
disintegration that he seems to regret as much as his duchess does.
A lot of his work so far has been in chamber music, in ideal little
societies of collaboration. ``Catch,'' one of his earliest pieces
(dating all the way back to 1991), makes the point dramatically: a
piano trio, seated onstage in the normal way, lures a passing
lone-wolf clarinetist to take a place in its midst.
</P>
<P>
   Ades is clearly concerned, too, about how and why musicians and
audiences sit down together. In his most recent big piece, the
symphonic ``Asyla,'' which had its first performance under Simon
Rattle just over a year ago, the search is on for places of safety
(as the title denotes), where ears can join with other ears. Ades
has noted the marginal place accorded new work in the current
musical world, and he does not like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asyla'' sounds like a quest for music with which we can all
feel comfortable again, but music that is not just reiteration of
the past or reiteration, period. The third movement is a ferocious
assault of mindless repetition and a ferocious outcry against it,
hugely powerful and disturbing. In other passages, the music
beautifully and tricklingly cavorts in the upper treble, in
textures and harmonies that are already identifiably Adesian. This
is one asylum he has won, but it is small, and he wants more.
</P>
<P>
   The duchess, for her part, has very different ideas about what
one can expect of and for oneself and what one should do for other
people. ``Society'' is the name of a club to which most of us do
not belong. Perfume, furs, champagne and parties help make the
world tolerable. Mostly, one does not ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   It is this lack of self-observation, or indeed, of any evident
interior life, that makes the duchess such an enigmatic but also
compelling operatic creature. There can be few other leading opera
characters who enjoy themselves so little. She sings a lot, but she
is in command of what she sings only when she is giving
instructions. In her fellatio aria, necessarily sung on ``mm,''
``ng'' and ``ugh'' sounds, she communicates only the most
generalized and automatic excitement. She is absent. And
ultimately, she gains a kind of dignity in her absence, fully
expressed in her final lament and withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Ades accords her this dignity by his refusal of easy satire. The
popular idioms he evokes _ the tango that starts the opera and
often comes back, a wonderful '30s-style song for crooning _ are
re-created with as much fastidious workmanship as everything else
in the score, and with no camp anxiety. He must love this music as
much as the duchess does. Probably he loves champagne as much as
she does, too.
</P>
<P>
   His opera is not really about the follies and iniquities of the
idle rich. Rather, it is about a more widespread problem, that of
finding things about which to care and in which to trust. The
duchess, caring for her appearance and trusting in nothing,
nevertheless retains a nobility, which Ades' music for her
reinforces. Degraded in her behavior and stupid in her beliefs, she
is still admirable for harboring no pretensions. She is not
assailed by the drama, which is somewhere between Jean Genet and
English bedroom farce. Meanwhile, the score, of which she also
remains sublimely oblivious, juggles around her with magical and
gorgeous musical notions, and its circumspectness is sweet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The quality of the piece comes across strongly in the new EMI
recording. A crack instrumental band, conducted by the composer,
swaggers with expressiveness and virtuoso craft. The vocal writing
proves sharply pointed, whether in pithy phrases or glorious
extended melodies. In the central role, Jill Gomez sings with
perfect poise, and there are excellent performances by Valdine
Anderson and Niall Morris, both sounding young, fun-loving and
vulnerable as the hotel employees who take on various parts in
enacting the charade of the duchess' career.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other two EMI albums, they show that there was reason
for the adulation Ades' earlier music won. ``Living Toys,'' for the
usual modern-music ensemble of soloists, is unusual as a strikingly
brilliant array of memorable inventions, evoking angels, dancers,
soldiers and ancient cattle. The string quartet ``Arcadiana'' is a
similarly fresh set of images that appeal this time, hauntingly or
menacingly, to musical locations from Astor Piazzolla's Argentina
to Edward Elgar's England. ``Under Hamelin Hill'' tells the Pied
Piper story in goblinlike music for a chamber organ.
</P>
<P>
   But the best piece here is the one written since the opera:
``Traced Overhead,'' a piano solo, superbly performed by the
composer. Within a context of rippling figurations in the upper
treble, it includes a humorous section that knocks chords off their
regular rhythmic and harmonic perches to place them in precarious
new balances, and later it uses the instrument's ability, when
certain combinations of notes are played, to sound high harmonics
way beyond the top of the keyboard. As in other Ades pieces,
descending chromatic scales tell one exactly what to expect, but
not when and how to expect it. Here they also contribute strongly
to the combination of melancholy and joy.
</P>
<P>
   With the added example of ``Asyla,'' and with the promise of a
new opera for Covent Garden and a big piece for the New York
Philharmonic, it may be that Ades' real work is only now beginning.
</P>
</TEXT>
