<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIPASTI-BOOK-REVIEW     12-01 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIPASTI-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIPASTI THAT LOOK GOOD, AT LEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some cookbook authors are one-hit wonders. They come out with
one big splashy book, then fall off the map, presumably retreating
to their home kitchens and making local cooking appearances. Others
are like Lorenza de'Medici, who has produced more than twenty books
during her lengthy career. To most cookbook collectors, she is the
familiar name to which they are unable to put a face. ``She has
pretty books,'' they might remark.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, many of her books are beautiful _ large and
impressive, laden with pictures. They are so visual that if you
place them side by side, you will have a better review of the
progress of food photography over the past decade than you will
have of the progress of Italian cooking over these years.
</P>
<P>
   This is how I know Ms. de'Medici's books. I had never cooked
from them. With the publication of ``Lorenza's Antipasti''
(Clarkson Potter, $40), I decided it was time.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de'Medici begins this latest book with a history of
antipasti that feels a bit like a sports recap on the news. You get
a small hit of antipasti examples from Roman times to the present,
without much sense of Italy's important regional differences. There
are great prints and photos in this section, but unfortunately, no
captions describing what they are or where they come from.
</P>
<P>
   I moved on to the recipes and I quickly learned why no one I
know cooks from Ms. de'Medici's books. The recipes simply aren't
that good, if they work at all, and they are filled with errors,
vague instructions and ingredients out of order.
</P>
<P>
   The best antipasto I made was a bruschetta with sausages, which
tasted delicious. It was essentially a ragu spread on toast, and
the recipe yielded enough to coat both the bruschetta and spaghetti
for a family of four. I dismissed it as a minor proportion error,
figuring it was better to have too much than too little.
</P>
<P>
   The fig and goat cheese tart, which I had been dreaming about
for days, on the other hand, turned out to be a disaster. My first
try at the pastry failed completely: it was all crumbs. The second
time, I added half a stick more butter, more milk and a second egg
yolk. It worked, but it was now  &UR; my  &LR; recipe, not Ms. de'Medici's.
And because both the cheese filling and the pastry needed salt, the
resulting tart was bland. I ended up picking off the figs and
eating them alone.
</P>
<P>
   Matters did not improve. Chickpea focaccias with rosemary were
more like chewy crepes, and cheese and pear truffles made with
gorgonzola and mascarpone cheese amounted to, well, cheese balls.
They were far too rich for an antipasto.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, I was annoyed with Ms. de'Medici, but what really
did it was a recipe on the same page as the cheese balls. It was
for white truffles with pancetta. They were the only two
ingredients. If I could actually afford white truffles, I thought,
I certainly wouldn't trust this book to tell me how to cook them.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to answer all my questions about Ms. de'Medici's
book. So I stopped cooking.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSCHETTA WITH SAUSAGES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Lorenza's Antipasti'' by Lorenza de'Medici &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces sweet Italian sausages
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces boneless pork, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil, more for brushing
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   4 ripe plum tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   10 large 1/2-inch thick slices coarse country bread.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel the sausages and crumble the meat into a medium bowl.
Add the pork. In a large saute pan, heat the oil over medium heat.
Add the carrot, celery and onion and cook over medium heat,
stirring constantly, for about 3 minutes, or until the onion is
translucent. Stir in the sausage and pork and cook for another 3
minutes. Add the fennel seeds, tomatoes, wine and thyme. Season to
taste with salt and pepper. Cover the pan, reduce the heat to low
and cook the ragu for about 1 hour, stirring from time to time and
adding a little water if necessary to keep moist.
</P>
<P>
   2. Uncover the pan and let the juices evaporate completely.
Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Place the bread slices
on a baking sheet and toast in the oven for about 5 minutes, or
until barely golden, turning them once. Brush with olive oil and
arrange on individual dishes. Spread with the sausage ragu and
serve immediately while still very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 10 appetizer servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
