<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADY-GUNS-HNS &LR;      12-01 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADY-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA SUES JUSTICE DEPARTMENT, SEEKS DESTRUCTION OF RECORDS OF PEOPLE
BUYING FIREARMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A gun rights group is suing the Justice Department
to force it to destroy records of people buying firearms
immediately after they are cleared by a new instant criminal
background check system that began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new computerized system is the second phase of the Brady
law, a bill passed in 1993 that required a five-day waiting period
to conduct a criminal background check for all handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   This second phase now requires federally licensed dealers to
call an FBI record center with the name and other information of
anyone purchasing a handgun or any rifle or shotgun. FBI staff at
the West Virginia center then conduct an ``instant'' criminal
background check using several national criminal databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration, acting through (Attorney General)
Janet Reno's Justice Department, has now twisted implementation of
the system into a national surveillance system that puts a higher
priority on tracking gun purchases by law-abiding citizens than it
does on the arrest and prosecution of those who attempt to violate
our federal firearms laws,'' said James Jay Baker of the National
Rifle Association, the organization leading the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, along with several individuals and another gun rights
organization, said Tuesday that portions of the Brady law require
the FBI to destroy records of the firearms purchase after it tells
a dealer to proceed with a sale.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI and Justice Department officials said records are kept
on file for six months only ``to perform audits of the system to
protect the privacy of gun owners and detect fraud and abuse of the
system,'' said Paul Bresson, FBI spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The audits will serve as a track record of how the database is
used, to make sure employees at the database center are not
misusing records and to make sure dealers only do checks on people
buying firearms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI must publish suggestions for a shorter record retention
period in the Federal Register in February, and make an official
announcement by May, said Jim Kessler, program manager for the
National Instant Check System (NICS) in Clarksburg, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory King, a Justice Department spokesman, responded to the
lawsuit's contentions by saying: ``We're reviewing the NRA suit and
we believe our policy of retaining records of approved firearms
purchases for a very limited period of time is consistent with
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow us to protect the security of the system and
the privacy of gun purchasers. We will respond to the suit in court
early next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits convicted felons, the mentally incompetent
and those convicted of domestic violence misdemeanors from buying
firearms. Some states have more restrictive conditions and any
waiting periods states impose will remain in place. Texas law
enforcement agencies have converted to the federal system.
</P>
<P>
   Most background checks will receive a ``proceed'' or ``deny''
response within a few minutes, FBI officials have said. If a
``delay'' order is given and the dealer gets no other information
within three days, the sale is approved automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Once a purchaser passes the background check, the law orders the
FBI to assign an identification number to that particular purchase,
which is also given to the dealer to put with the record of sale.
According to the text of the NRA lawsuit, the next step in the law
reads: ``destroy all records of the system with respect to the call
... and all records of the system relating to the person or the
transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the statutory issue, the records constitute an
invasion of privacy, said Wayne LaPierre, NRA executive vice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask any American. They don't believe the government ought to
keep a centralized list of names and addresses of law abiding
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy groups also expressed concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Solange Bitol of the national American Civil Liberties Union
said the ACLU has not examined this particular issue and lawsuit,
but it has a general policy against the government having a giant
database about citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, this is government intruding into the lives of
individuals,'' Bitol said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
