</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-01 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TO DIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It happens more often than people like to admit. We
are helpless in dealing with the last illness of loved ones who
desperately need a legitimate way to ease the suffering and bring
some dignity to the process of dying.
</P>
<P>
   We do not want them to leave us. But they may be ready to go.
When death is hopelessly imminent, we do not stop caring. But we
watch silently as they suffer with pain that could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   This is difficult to talk about because the Catholic Church is
the leader of a movement preaching that euthanasia without
exception is a sin and that dying must be left strictly up to fate.
It is important to consider questions of ethics and morality.
Euthanasia inevitably stirs unreasonable fears that children may
murder their parents or doctors may murder their patients for
having, say, a bad cold.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a concept that is easier honored in the abstract than
during the tortured months preceding the death of a relative or
friend who is needlessly in agony and wishes release.
</P>
<P>
   My late husband, suffering from kidney failure and other
ailments, asked me a few months before he died to help him leave
painlessly with dignity. ``This is no life,'' he whispered on his
hospital bed. I could not muster the courage to do as he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over I have heard similar stories, told with love and
regret, from families who have coped with the misery of terminally
ill loved ones and are horrified by suffering that seems
unnecessarily prolonged.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced medical technology can often keep people breathing for
no real purpose, long after they have passed into a vegetative
state.
</P>
<P>
   Administering morphine and other pain-killing medication can
ease one agony but cause another, sending the patient into a coma
or mental confusion. And there are legal restrictions on its usage.
</P>
<P>
   As my 93-year-old mother moaned in pain caused by cancer, I had
an angry exchange with her doctor (well, I yelled at him) because
he refused to increase her morphine dosage. He contended it might
slow her breathing and hasten her death. Breathing slowly anyway,
she died two days later, still in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kevorkian is a controversial figure because he seems
unhealthily obsessed with suicide as the ultimate solution.
</P>
<P>
   And he often goes to extremes to get attention, as he did when
he mailed CBS's ``60 Minutes'' a videotape of his latest assisted
suicide, during which he administered a lethal injection that
killed a disabled victim of Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevorkian's basic crusade to win support for an enlightened
legal and political system that would allow the terminally ill to
choose the method and the timing of their death is a just one. We
may be uncomfortable about the messenger, but the message is
crucial to a civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   His latest publicity stunt succeeded spectacularly. Some 22
million people watched the CBS show, its biggest audience of the
season. CBS has been criticized for exploiting a death for the sake
of ratings, but I think it was a public service. Nobody who was
offended was forced to watch. We need to confront this whole
subject and debate it.
</P>
<P>
   A Michigan prosecutor promptly charged Kevorkian with
first-degree murder, setting up a trial that will test a new state
law that heartlessly prohibits anyone from assisting in a suicide.
Defending the law, a euthanasia opponent observed coldly that
rather than seek suicide, the disabled man could have ``stopped
eating or drinking'' _ adding another level of heightened suffering
_ if he wished to die.
</P>
<P>
   Polls over the years show that a majority of Americans are
compassionate toward the dying and want to find legitimate ways to
ease suffering and pain, including assisted suicide if justified. A
CBS poll following the ``60 Minutes'' videotape found that 52
percent of those surveyed approved of doctor-assisted suicide and
37 percent opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian has already been tried four times for murder in
Michigan for helping the terminally ill to die. In three cases,
sympathetic juries acquitted him, and once there was a mistrial.
This time he faces not only a tough new law but the fact that he
actually administered the lethal medicine rather than giving it to
the patient to self-administer.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the law and common sense is being tested in
other ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, a Louisville, Ky., woman named Michele Finn
asked care givers at a Virginia nursing home, where her husband
Hugh was in a persistent vegetative state, to withdraw his feeding
tube. Mrs. Finn has my sympathy because I have known friends kept
technically alive by feeding tubes who were not alive in any other
sense. It is horrible.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Gov. James S. Gilmore III intervened, filing suit in a
circuit court to prevent Mrs. Finn from controlling decisions about
her husband's medical care. The judge tossed Gilmore's suit out of
court, called the intervention frivolous and ordered the state to
pay much of her legal costs. The judge further told Gilmore to
express his views on euthanasia in the political arena instead of
the courts. Hugh Finn died Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Several states are considering various forms of right-to-die
laws, either through ballot initiatives or legislative measures. So
far, Oregon is the only state with such a law. The Supreme Court
has ruled that assisted suicide is neither constitutionally
protected nor forbidden. It is for the states to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some people are taking matters into their own hands.
Recent news stories have highlighted a new pattern of
homicide-suicide involving elderly couples who are ill, depressed
and unable to cope any longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
