<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANEY02-COX     12-01 0245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANEY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BODY-BUILDER HANEY NAMED TO PRESIDENT'S FITNESS COUNCIL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans to name Atlanta
body-building champion Lee Haney to the President's Commission on
Physical Fitness and Sports, an administration official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Haney would fill the council seat vacated by the late track
star, Florence ''Flo-Jo'' Joyner, who died earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Haney, 38, won eight consecutive ''Mr. Olympia'' world
body-building titles before retiring from competition to run
commercial fitness centers in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is someone who is devoted to improving the physical
fitness of the American people, both by setting an example and by
encouraging others,'' an administration official said, speaking on
background.
</P>
<P>
   The official said he did not know when Clinton would publicly
name Haney to the Council, but said ''It is going to happen. It is
a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner had been the chair of the 20-member council until her
death earlier this year. The administration official said it had
not been determined who would become the next chair of the council,
a presidential body that works to improve the overall fitness of
the nation through an emphasis on sports and other types of
physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
