<SLUG> BC-STATES-GEKAS-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  GEKAS DECRIES ``GIGANTIC LEFT WING CONSPIRACY,'' IN
IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, December 1, 1998 -- Rep. George W. Gekas,
R-Harrisburg, called Democrats ``part of a gigantic left wing
conspiracy'' for criticizing a vote Tuesday that expanded the
impeachment inquiry to include campaign fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearings, Gekas also said he ``inching closer'' to
voting for impeachment, based on the perjury allegations against
President Clinton involving his testimony in the Paula Jones case
and before the Starr grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Democrats who say we are on a fishing expedition have
rushed to the side of the president without looking at the
evidence,'' Gekas said in an interview. ``They choose to protect
their political leader without even wanting to look at the evidence
... no matter what the evidence would tell them. They have been in
complete harmony that he should be exonerated of all charges right
from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That to me is a left wing conspiracy,'' said Gekas, the only
Pennsylvanian on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members voted 20-15 along party lines to approve
subpoenas for Attorney General Janet Reno, FBI Director Louis Freeh
and others regarding White House involvement in alleged fundraising
abuses in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are wanting to look just a bit farther. We want to look
into anything that came across our desks that holds the possibility
of turning up other impeachable offenses,'' Gekas said. ``There is
no reason we should turn our heads to new evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas will seek evidence, including internal memos, used
by the Justice Department in its fundraising investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the committee decried Republicans for expanding the
scope of the inquiry weeks before it is slated to wrap up.
</P>
<P>
   But Gekas said he would vote to conclude the aspect of the
inquiry pertaining to Monica S. Lewinsky by the end of the month,
but continue the campaign finance inquiry next year if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., has said he
still wants to wrap up the inquiry by Christmas, and take a vote on
possible impeachment articles against Clinton. One or more of those
articles will deal with perjury, which was the focus of Tuesday's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses testified about the criminal punishment they faced
after being convicted of commiting perjury in civil cases, and
other legal experts testified about whether Clinton should be held
to the same standard as anyone convicted of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas said he believes Clinton might have to face such stiff
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very close to considering perjury, or giving false
statements under oath to a grand jury, if it is an impeachable
offense,'' Gekas said. ``If perjury is one of the articles of
impeachment, I lean toward supporting that article of
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
