<SLUG> BC-INVITRO-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS FIND TRANSMISSION OF DEFECTIVE GENE TO CHILDREN BORN
THROUGH IN VITRO FERTILIZATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston and San Antonio researchers have for the first
time documented the transmission of a defective gene to children
born as a result of in vitro fertilization using a donated egg.
</P>
<P>
   The rare genetic defect called ocular albinism reduces the
clarity of vision, said Dr. Richard Lewis, professor of
ophthalmology at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston. The report,
published in this month's edition of the journal Fertility and
Sterility, documents that one male child actually has the disorders
and two girls received the mutated gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's a rare event, those people involved in the ovum
donor programs need to be exceedingly careful to prevent the
unintended transmission of a genetic disease,'' said Lewis, who
consulted on the case and is one of the authors of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Previous abnormalities in children born as a result of in vitro
fertilization have occurred as a result of spontaneous mutation,
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees in life,'' said Mark Rothstein,
director of the University of Houston Health Law and Policy
Institute. ``People need to realize that there are spontaneous
mutations as well. Even if you screen for everything under the sun,
something could happen of a genetic or nongenetic nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The children involved were born as a result of in vitro
fertilization involving eggs donated by a 24-year-old woman through
the Ooctye Donor Program at the University of Texas Health Science
Center at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The woman went through all the screenings recommended by the
American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the screenings are not sufficient to identify all
genetic disorders, particularly those like this one that are
extremely rare, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four children were born as a result of the woman's oocyte
donations, including one set of twins.
</P>
<P>
   The boy twin's parents became concerned that his eyes appeared
to shift and that he could not focus properly on an object at age 2
months.
</P>
<P>
   Examination by Lewis and a pediatric ophthalmologist in San
Antonio confirmed that the boy had ocular albinism. In its most
severe forms, ocular albinism can leave a person legally blind.
This child, now about 5 years old, has reduced vision but will be
able to function and read, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Several months after the twins' birth, two other pregnancies
resulted from the egg donations by this woman.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic tests of the youngsters found that the boy did have the
gene for the X-linked disease. His twin did not carry the mutated
gene, and she is free of disease.
</P>
<P>
   However, the two other girls born to two different sets of
parents carry a single mutated gene.
</P>
<P>
   Because the disease is X-linked, the mutation affects only boys
who carry it. However, the girls could possible transmit the
disease to their offspring, when they are old enough to have
children.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned further, the woman who donated the egg remembered
that an optometrist once told her that there was funny pigment in
her retina, which is typical of women who carry the gene mutation,
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic tests confirmed that the woman carried the defective
gene, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, many couples seek egg donation because the wife
carries a genetic disease that could be passed on to an offspring.
However, identifying extremely rare conditions such as this one in
egg donors will be extremely difficult. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
