<HEADER>
A7513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERM-LIMITS12-02-COX     12-01 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERM-LIMITS12-02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME MEMBERS OVERLOOKING SELF-IMPOSED TERM LIMITS
 &HT;    765 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years ago, U.S. Rep. J.C. Watts assured voters
in his Oklahoma district, ``I will not serve more than six years''
in Congress. That was before he was re-elected twice and then won
the post of chairman of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Now Watts, an ascending star in his party, is not so sure about
his promise to bid Congress adieu after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he alone among lawmakers who since 1992 have been issuing
pledges to limit their terms in response to a national movement to
establish a ``citizen legislature'' in which members would spend a
few years in Washington and then return to their home districts.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Term Limits, a private group urging tenure limitations at
all levels of government, has pushed for a constitutional amendment
without success and now is focusing on self-imposed limits. That's
the message the group plans to stress Wednesday at a Washington
conference where the featured speaker will be U.S. Rep. Matt
Salmon, R-Ariz., who is making good on his promise not to run again
after his next term.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Congress that will take office in January, 55 House
members and three senators have pledged to limit their terms. But
the true test will come in the year 2000 when 11 House members will
reach their self-imposed deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 who have said they would depart, five, including
Watts, are wavering.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler had told her Jacksonville, Fla., district
when she was first elected in 1992 that she would stay no longer
than eight years. She has just been elected to be House Republican
Conference vice chairman, and she now is saying she might run for
re-election in 2000, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people had advised me that to be fully effective, it
might take more than a single term'' in her new leadership job,
Fowler said Tuesday. She said she will spend next year getting
``feedback from my constituents'' and assessing whether she needs
an additional term for her House post.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., already has told his district he
plans to renege on his promise to leave after four terms, and he
won re-election last month by 66 percent of the vote. Rep. Martin
Meehan, D-Mass., also has declined to reaffirm his promise to
depart in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most disturbing for term-limit advocates is Rep. George
Nethercutt, the Republican who defeated former House Speaker Thomas
Foley in Washington state in 1994 by attacking him for being a
Washington insider and career politician. Now Nethercutt himself
appears to be a bit wobbly on his promise not to run again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the poster child for the movement,'' said Jason Miller,
spokesman for U.S. Term Limits. ``We'll see if he'll make good on
his pledge to the people there or if he'll get a little 'Potomac
fever.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt is eyeing a run for governor but keeping his options
open for staying in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an agenda'' of issues to work on, said Ken Lisaius,
spokesman for Nethercutt. ``Really, what he's trying to do is find
the best way to serve Washington state.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional reform movement has seen other troubling signs
this year, including an announcement by the designated new House
Speaker Bob Livingston, R-La., that members deserve an increase in
their $136,700 annual salary, a proposition that runs counter to
the push for temporary citizen lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not there for a career,'' Miller said. ``They're there
to serve their constituents, ideally for no more than six years,
and then head back to the district. They're not there to make
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the term-limit advocates won one key victory this fall.
As the new House leadership organized itself last month, it
resisted calls for removing the six-year term limit voted in 1994
for chairmanships of House committees. The next test may be whether
the new House keeps in place a stiff ban on gifts that took effect
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And some members who say they may extend their own stay are
renewing their backing for passing term limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is to keep this issue to the forefront,'' said
Fowler, who helped lead the ill-fated attempt to pass a
constitutional amendment in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to move it forward again,'' she said, adding that it
might have more success if the lawmakers could unite behind a less
stringent term limit of 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   As for Watts, he plans to continue voting for term limitations
if the measure comes before the House. But his spokeswoman Tobi
Edwards said, ``If the people in the 4th District decided they
wanted him to run again, he would consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
