<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-WORK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIRING WELFARE RECIPIENTS CAN BENEFIT SMALL FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Beti (NOTE: CQ) Ward, owner of a growing air cargo
company, was looking for a motivated worker to do the kind of
entry-level tasks every business has: filing, typing and basic
computer work.
</P>
<P>
   Darkina Burris, (NOTE: both CQ) single mother of two, was
looking for the kind of job that would give her her own desk, her
own computer and, more importantly, a way out of her old
neighborhood and the welfare trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't interviewed before, so I was nervous. And she was
tough,'' Burris recalls of Chief Executive Officer Ward. But since
she was hired at Phoenix-based American International Cargo in
1996, Burris has been promoted twice _ from file clerk then to
billing supervisor now _ and is one of the shining examples of how
small businesses can take a chance and win with people once deemed
unemployable.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for workers to fill jobs as companies boom and
Arizona's unemployment rate falls to a record low, small businesses
like Ward's are turning to a riskier pool of hires _ welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the idea makes sense: Small businesses need workers;
welfare recipients are an available supply. Since 1996 welfare
reform laws took effect, federal officials have been pushing large
and small businesses to get people off the rolls and into
hard-to-fill entry-level jobs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`In a shortage'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot more requests than ever before, because
everybody is in a shortage,'' said Andrea West, executive director
of Northside Training Center in Phoenix. The non-profit center
trains and counsels about 500 people a year in hopes of matching
them with jobs at 80 mostly small companies.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, though, the idea is no wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Department of Economic Security didn't track how
many of its 11,000 welfare-to-work participants were placed in
small companies last year. But Bill Hernandez, director of the
Division of Employment and Rehabilitation Services, says the agency
deals with a cross section of employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our experience that small businesses are trying it
out, but they're not a key player,'' said Janette Torres, economic
development program manager for the city of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people require a great deal more than the average worker
in terms of benefits. Mentoring is important, and small businesses
don't have the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition from bigger businesses is another reason for the
spotty record. About 200 welfare recipients in three years have
gone through a training program started by DES and the Arizona
Restaurant Association, Executive Director Joe Yuhas said. However,
``our success led to other industries jumping on board, so now
we're competing with the others for a shrinking labor pool.''
</P>
<P>
   The people in the pool are typically women with two children,
little or no work experience, and an average of 18 months on
welfare, Hernandez said. Contrary to stereotypes, West said, many
turned to welfare after falling on bad times, such as having a
spouse leave or being hurt on the job. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advantages &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burris estimates she was on welfare six to 12 months, during
which time she went through a DES program that trains recipients in
basic skills like interviewing and filling out applications.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, frustrated with trying to attract job applicants to her
company's site near Sky Harbor International Airport in Phoenix,
had listed her jobs with DES' Job Service. The agency referred
Burris to the company, and it was up to her to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and others say hiring from the welfare rolls has several
advantages for small businesses:
</P>
<P>
   - They can hire at entry level, mold that person to their needs
and promote from within.
</P>
<P>
   ATC/Vancom of Arizona, which provides bus service at Sky Harbor
and for Phoenix Transit, has hired about 20 percent of its
workforce through Northside Training Center and other programs,
said Wil (NOTE: cq) Jackson, assistant general manager of
operations. It seeks people with positive attitudes and common
sense who are willing to learn the new skill of driving a bus, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward believes promoting from within gives her company people who
know what they're doing and who are more faithful to the firm.
Studies confirm that once welfare recipients are employed, they
tend to stay longer, Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   In Burris' case, Ward said, ``She was motivated enough to pick
things up going on around her, learn from them and assume more
responsibility. When we saw that, we started training her in other
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   - New workers are surrounded by good examples, including owners
who know firsthand what it's like to build something from nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, as a female business owner, has become a positive role
model for Burris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get away from the negative energy and be surrounded
with positive energy,'' Burris said. ``When I went to American
International Cargo, I was surrounded with positive energy.''
</P>
<P>
   - Smaller companies, often touted for their family atmosphere,
may be less intimidating than big companies filled with hundreds of
new faces and books full of rules.
</P>
<P>
   American International Cargo has 10 employees in its Phoenix
office and another 150 at its Los Angeles and Hawaii locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a huge company with 10 managers, they're busy,
busy,'' Burris said. ``Here, we can work around the corner and I
could get the attention I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   - Small companies may be more flexible regarding workers'
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who had raised three children herself while working in
real estate and as a beautician, knew what it's like to be short of
babysitting money and arrange one's workday around a sick child.
When that happened to Burris, Ward made sure the company let her
catch up by working different hours or different days.
</P>
<P>
   - Tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Though the need for dependable workers is a bigger driving
force, tax credits are available for hiring welfare recipients. The
federal government gives credits for 35 percent of the first
$10,000 of first-year wages, and 50 percent of the first $10,000 of
second-year wages. Employees must have been on welfare at least 18
months and must have been hired after Jan. 1, 1998, and before May
1, 1999. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Drawbacks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of these hires are countered by a number of
disadvantages, employers and officials say. These include:
</P>
<P>
   - Uneducated or unmotivated job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Many welfare recipients have little or no work experience, or no
recent work experience, DES' Hernandez said. Other would-be workers
have below-average reading, writing or math skills that programs
like Northside's try to improve.
</P>
<P>
   - The time it takes to train these workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ward thinks training is manageable when a business hires for
entry-level positions, in which the person will be doing tasks such
as filing documents in numeric or alphabetic order.
</P>
<P>
   For more specific skills, DES contracts with community colleges
and non-profit organizations to run training programs, including
ones for restaurants, electronics assemblers and call centers.
</P>
<P>
   - The level of pay and benefits needed to keep people off
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Many small businesses can't afford to pay for health care
coverage or subsidize child care, said Marie Sullivan, executive
director of Arizona Women's Education and Employment. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Give them a chance' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Job applicants have told Ward that by the time they paid for child
care, they would be losing money by going to work. She replies that
unlike staying home, a job gives them a chance for advancement and
a chance to better themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan and other experts agree that solving transportation and
child care problems would be a big help in the effort to link
welfare recipients to small-business jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Phoenix area's buses run at poor times, Burris is
saving to buy her own car. Until then, she often must depend on her
roommate to drive her the five miles to work.
</P>
<P>
   And though DES helped pay for child care as Burris made the
transition to work, Ward notes that the subsidies drop as workers
earn more, penalizing people who try to advance.
</P>
<P>
   An open mind, mentoring and communication also are vital to
making the welfare hire a successful one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at these people without any bias or preconceived ideas,
and give them a chance,'' ATC/Vancom's Jackson said. ``Sometimes it
just takes a hand, and once they get their footing they are as good
as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward says she encouraged Burris to ask, rather than keep quiet,
when she didn't understand something. E-mail was an easy,
non-threatening tool.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship has turned into a personally satisfying one,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have anyone to believe in me, and she did,'' Burris
said of Ward. ``I don't doubt myself now. I will (begin ital) never
(end ital) let my confidence go to the bottom of my feet again.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
