<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BROWN-ART-NYT     12-01 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BROWN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION INSTITUTE'S NEW PRESIDENT SETS HER OWN COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a shirtsleeve day, and Dr. Joyce F. Brown, the
newly appointed president of the Fashion Institute of Technology,
has just finished meeting with a finance committee. Her desk is
cluttered with papers and she wonders if she should have her
picture taken behind such a jumble.
</P>
<P>
   As the new head of FIT _ not to mention the first black and
first woman to hold that $140,000-a-year position _ Dr. Brown is
understandably concerned with her image, but not overly concerned.
She is asked if she feels added pressure to perform well because
she is the first black to run the college. ``Being black is never
incidental,'' she said. ``It's central to who I am. But I don't
think FIT set out to make a statement about gender or ethnicity.
They wanted to find the best person to lead the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brown is also the wife of New York's second most powerful
state official, Comptroller H. Carl McCall. And while for some that
may have raised eyebrows, many say that Dr. Brown was the person
best suited for the job.
</P>
<P>
   While no one questions her qualifications, there has been
speculation in political, fashion and academic circles that the
appointment was approved by the State University Board of Trustees
in part because Gov. George Pataki, who controls the board, wanted
to dissuade her husband, the state's highest-ranking Democrat, from
campaigning vigorously in last month's election and drawing a
strong black turnout that could help Democratic candidates. Dr.
Brown herself repeats another theory making the rounds: that Pataki
did not want McCall running against him for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is when you're in public life people
say all kinds of things,'' said Dr. Brown, who, at 52, looks a
decade younger than her age. ``They try to denigrate our abilities
and contributions. I told Carl the other day they might as well
say, `Brown's husband for state comptroller' if they're going to
say `McCall's wife for FIT president.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stop people from adding two plus two and getting six.
We can't stop them from saying, `The fix was in all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The journey to president of FIT was a long one that started with
a working class childhood in Harlem. Along the way she held a
number of senior administrative positions in public higher
education. She also served as deputy mayor for public and community
affairs under Mayor David Dinkins, who remembers her fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's terrific,'' he said. ``FIT is lucky to get her. She's
bright, tenacious and works awfully hard. In my administration
everyone had a voice. Joyce was somebody whose opinion I
respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brown, who took the helm at FIT in early June, was most
recently professor of clinical psychology at the Graduate School
and University Center of the City University of New York. From 1990
to 1992, she held a number of posts at the City University,
including vice chancellor for student affairs and urban programs
and for urban affairs and development. In 1990, she was acting
president of Bernard Baruch College.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she has only recently taken the FIT post, she has
big plans. The four-year college, which bills itself as a school of
art and design, business and technology, is starting a capital
campaign, which among other things would add 300,000 square feet to
the campus, which is headquartered at 27th Street and Seventh
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to have the industry have a real presence,'' Dr.
Brown said. ``We would love to have a facility that would allow
greater interaction with the industry, a place for real fashion
shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Another goal is to make people aware that FIT is a public
institution. Many people mistake it for a private school. ``I think
that people don't typically think of SUNY as being in New York
City,'' Dr. Brown said. ``But it's important for people to know
that we're part of SUNY because as such we provide opportunities
for kids who don't have opportunities to go to private schools and
to do the things that we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brown and McCall (when he isn't in Albany) live in an Upper
West Side co-op, but hope to sell it soon; one of the perks of her
job is a campus apartment on 27th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Harlem, the youngest daughter of Robert Brown, a
postal clerk, and Joyce Brown, a clerk with the New York City
Housing Authority, Dr. Brown went to Roman Catholic schools. Her
older sister, Donna Levy Wray, is the director of an executive
program at Harvard's Kennedy School of government.
</P>
<P>
   How does Dr. Brown account for her success and that of her
sister? ``It was always a given that we would go to college and be
the best we could be in whatever we chose to do,'' she said.
``There was a strong work ethic and the belief that if we worked
hard and did not expect that it would be easy and we kept at it, it
would work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
