<HEADER>
A7542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIT-12-02-COX-1STLE     12-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIT-12-02-COX-1ST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE &HT;    CLINTON AND DOLE BROKE SPENDING LIMITS, AUDITORS REPORT
 &HT;    Eds: Updates to insert 6th graf with comment from Common Cause
president.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the 1996 presidential race, Democrat Bill
Clinton exceeded federal spending limits by more than $45 million
and Republican Bob Dole exceeded them by nearly $23 million,
according to federal auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Reports released Tuesday by the staff of the Federal Election
Commission note that in return for receiving federal money, each
candidate agreed in writing to spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors recommended that the FEC order Clinton to repay $7
million and Dole to repay nearly $17.9 million to the U.S.
Treasury. The auditors also asked the commission to require Dole to
repay $1.1 million in overcharges to news organizations and $65,000
to the Secret Service for travel with his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns dispute the findings, which led to a Justice
Department probe of the Clinton campaign and may lead to a similar
probe of Dole's.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign lawyers described the audit findings as
``grossly inequitable.'' Dole's denounced them as an attempt at
``circumventing enforcement procedures'' by trying to distort the
audit requirement into ``a punitive process or to recapture private
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The full FEC will start trying to sort out the dispute Thursday.
It takes four votes for a decision from the commission, which
consists of three Republicans and three Democrats. That process,
and subsequent appeals to the commission and within the courts,
could take years.
</P>
<P>
   Ann McBride, president of Common Cause, a national civic group
that uncovered much of the activity the auditors described as
illegal, urged the commission to approve its staff's
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have we seen presidential candidates act in such
utter disregard of the law, `` McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the simultaneous release of the reports on questionable
activities by both Clinton and Dole makes it harder for Republicans
to portray the Democratic president as the only major violator of
the much-abused campaign finance laws during the 1996 campaign.
That could undermine efforts within the House Judiciary Committee
to add such violations to any bill of impeachment now under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors said that in addition to uncovering an array of
minor discrepancies typical of past campaigns, they concluded that
Clinton exceeded the limits by $45 million in the primaries and
nothing in the general election, while Dole exceeded the limits by
nearly $23 million -- about $9 million in the primaries and $14
million in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors reported:
</P>
<P>
   Though each candidate agreed to spend only $31 million in
private contributions and matching federal funds in the primaries,
Clinton spent more than $76 million and Dole spent more than $40
million. The excess consisted mostly of polls and TV ads that
helped the candidates but were paid for by the Democratic and
Republican national committees.
</P>
<P>
   Each would have to repay only the federal portion of that
overspending. That would cost Clinton $7 million and Dole $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   After each agreed to spend only $62 million in federal funds on
his post-convention campaign, Clinton abided by the limit, but Dole
spent about $76 million. Dole would have to repay the entire $14
million in overspending, because general-election campaigns are
supposed to be financed 100 percent with federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The audits took more than 2 1/2 years to complete. Blaming
heel-dragging by the Clinton campaign, the auditors said they had
to resort to subpoenas more than 30 times to extract routine
records and other financial information from Clinton's
close-mouthed campaign aides and consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-01-98 1814E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
