<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANKS-SPIELBERG MINISERIES; RATINGS, MOVIES, TREE-LIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   World War II, The Miniseries
</P>
<P>
   Acting in the movie ``Apollo 13'' helped inspire Tom Hanks to
pursue his fascination with space travel by creating the 12-hour
HBO miniseries ``From the Earth to the Moon,'' which won an Emmy
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hanks and director Steven Spielberg, inspired by their
experiences making the World War II film ``Saving Private Ryan,''
in which Hanks starred, have signed on as co-executive producers of
another HBO mega-miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   The two will make ``Band of Brothers,'' based on the 1992 best
seller by Stephen Ambrose, also about a special group of American
soldiers in the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, the historian, has written numerous books about the
war, including a two-volume biography of Dwight D. Eisenhower. The
book's full title is ``Band of Brothers: E Company, 506th Regiment,
101st Airborne From Normandy to Hitler's Eagle's Nest.'' Its
subject is an elite rifle company that parachuted into France on
D-Day and later captured Hitler's mountain retreat at
Berchtesgaden.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been decided whether Hanks will act in the drama,
which is scheduled to appear in late 2000 or early 2001. Chris
Albrecht, president of HBO original programming, said Hanks had
been working on the overall story outline and outlines for
individual episodes ``for a couple of months now, on his own, and
we're about to announce a deal with a co-writer in the next day or
so,'' adding that the script would closely follow the book.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks was not available for comment, but Jeff Bewkes, HBO's
chairman and chief executive, said Hanks had done an
``extraordinary, hands-on, high-integrity job as executive producer
for `From the Earth to the Moon,''' and wanted to have similar
involvement with this project, which would be co-produced by
Dreamworks (in which Spielberg is a partner) and the Playtone Co.
(in which Hanks is a partner). Will it also have a similar price
tag of about $68 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can safely say it will cost more than that,'' Bewkes said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Young Viewers
</P>
<P>
   The November sweep month is gone, leaving a trail of
disappointment, if not tears.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, NBC held off Fox and won the only competition most
of the networks care about: commanding the most young-adult
viewers. But NBC's ratings fell off by the most of any network from
last season.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, relying mostly on its regular viewers, had the most
viewers. But its audience was older than ever; CBS finished fourth
even among viewers between 25 and 54.
</P>
<P>
   Fox spent the last week of the sweep excited by the prospect of
knocking off NBC, and pulled out every stop to do it. But
predictions that Fox would tie NBC fell short: NBC finished with a
5.9 rating among 18- to 49-year-olds, with Fox scoring a 5.7. (In
that group each rating point represents 1.24 million viewers.)
</P>
<P>
   The main culprits? Dinosaurs. Never has $80 million bought so
little. A second run in the same month of ``The Lost World'' was so
lackluster it guaranteed NBC the victory.
</P>
<P>
   More disconcerting to Fox may have been what happened the next
night, one night after the sweep ended: Another movie, ``Jumanji,''
dominated Thanksgiving night, knocking off NBC's perennial holiday
film, ``Home Alone.'' Had Fox used that movie on Wednesday, it
probably would have tied NBC. But Fox had a deal with a sole
sponsor, Toys R Us, to run that movie on Thanksgiving night.
</P>
<P>
   Without its powerhouse Thursday lineup, NBC's weaknesses were
more exposed in the ratings for the week that ended Sunday. Fox
clobbered NBC in the ratings among young adults. ABC also beat NBC
in that category. ``The X-Files'' took over as the top-rated show
among young adults. CBS easily won among total viewers for the week
as well, with NBC plummeting to fourth. ``60 Minutes'' was the most
watched show of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ABC finished the sweep strong, thanks to the powerful end to
Jimmy Smits' character on ``N.Y.P.D. Blue.'' But the network still
has to contend with the coming end of its most reliable ratings
performer, ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC has yet to announce an official new Monday lineup, but it is
likely that a new edition of ``20/20'' will fill the 9 p.m. hour,
as it did last winter, while the struggling Saturday-night drama
``Cupid'' looks the best bet for 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC is facing the most crucial schedule decisions. Will the
network change its Thursday night in light of how effectively Fox
counter-programmed last month with action-oriented video specials?
</P>
<P>
   Not yet. One proposed NBC schedule circulating at competing
networks had NBC returning ``Frasier'' to Tuesday, sliding
``Friends'' to 9 p.m. Thursday and relocating ``Just Shoot Me'' at
8 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday NBC executives were working on a schedule that
would leave Thursday intact, but revamp Tuesday and Wednesday. NBC
wants to give ``Will and Grace,'' the show it most wants to turn
into a hit (because it owns it), the best possible shot at building
an audience. That will almost surely mean moving it off Monday
night, where it has been suffering declines almost every week.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   TNT, TBS Acquire 97 Movies
</P>
<P>
   Cementing its identification as the cable empire with the
biggest library of recent movies, the Turner cable channels TNT and
TBS announced the acquisition Tuesday of a huge trove of recent
films, including such titles as ``Men in Black,'' ``My Best
Friend's Wedding,'' ``Ransom'' and ``The Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   The channels concluded deals with Columbia, Disney and Warner
Bros. studios that will bring in 97 movies.
</P>
<P>
   These are all films that will have previously been shown on
broadcast networks. ``Twister,'' for example, has been on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   But they will join a long list of films that the channels have
acquired to show before they are broadcast on network TV. Most
recently the Turner channels acquired the first network runs of
such films as ``As Good as It Gets,'' ``L.A. Confidential,''
``Pleasantville,'' ``Rush Hour,'' ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer'' and ``Living Out Loud.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Bright Lights, Big City
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after smiling their way through three hours of
the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade, Matt Lauer and Al Roker of NBC
are back on holiday-cheer duty Wednesday, this time in the evening
hours as hosts of the Rockefeller Center Christmas-tree-lighting
show.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Couric got a break this time. ``Katie said two hours a day
is enough with us,'' said Roker, the weatherman who appears on
NBC's ``Today'' show with Ms. Couric and Lauer. ``She's saddling
Jane Pauley with us for this show.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of being shown live only in New York, the
hourlong tree-lighting festivities will be televised live
nationally (8 p.m. Eastern time) this year, with an additional hour
just for New York-area viewers (Channel 4 at 7 p.m.). Performers
include the singers Garth Brooks, Cyndi Lauper and Baby Face; the
Radio City Rockettes, and Kristi Yamaguchi skating to ``Rudolph the
Red-Nosed Reindeer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying for 10 years this should be a national
show,'' Roker said Tuesday. WNBC station president Dennis Swanson
agreed. Last year, he sold the show in syndication and stations
around the country snapped it up. But what really influenced NBC
was the live show's ratings in New York: about three million
people, and a quarter of all homes watching television, tuned to
Channel 4 that hour.
</P>
<P>
   And all the jollity isn't wearing thin for Roker _ not this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on auto-grin right now, with the birth of my new daughter,
Leila Ruth,'' he said. The baby's mother, Deborah Roberts, is a
correspondent for ABC's ``20/20.'' Leila Ruth was 2 weeks old
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
