A7554 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-H     12-01 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANDED IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY COULD STRETCH INTO 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee voted Tuesday to
expand its impeachment inquiry into whether President Clinton
violated campaign finance laws _ a move that threatens to drag the
investigation into next year.
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted 20-15 along party lines to subpoena evidence
from a Justice Department investigation of fund-raising in
Clinton's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., committee chairman, insisted that the
expansion of the investigation would not destroy his self-imposed
deadline of Dec. 31 for ending the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely committed myself to wrapping this up this
year,'' he said. The chairman also said: ``We're not going on a
wild goose chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee spokesman Paul McNulty conceded to reporters that
adding campaign finance to the committee's agenda could force it to
abandon the year-end deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be tough _ if credible evidence of wrongdoing is
discovered _ to stick with our schedule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCullum, R-Fla., said he hoped the investigation into
possible campaign finance violations would not delay the committee
but that ``this committee cannot in all conscience turn away from
information that could ... bear directly on what this committee
must do.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is seeking internal memos from FBI Director Louis
Freeh and former Justice Department prosecutor Charles LaBella, who
headed a task force investigating campaign finance violations, that
reportedly urge Attorney General Janet Reno to appoint an
independent counsel to investigate the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The memos were introduced in evidence before a federal grand
jury investigating allegations that foreign contributors may have
tried to influence administration policy by donating large sums of
money. The panel also is investigating accusations that the
president and his aides orchestrated a massive fund-raising effort
from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee's Republican leadership moved to expand
the impeachment investigation and to subpoena the Freeh and LaBella
memos after U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson turned down
a committee request last week that she turn the documents over to
the panel.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty also said the committee wanted to expand the
investigation because a ``credible'' source had given it
``information which suggests that the campaign finance abuse memos
may contain allegations of criminal wrongdoing by the president.''
McNulty would not identify the source or indicate whether the
person worked for the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats ridiculed the committee's GOP majority for expanding
the investigation beyond Clinton's involvement in the coverup of
his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the committee has tentatively scheduled a debate and vote
on articles of impeachment for Dec. 10 through Dec. 12, senior
Democrat Rep. John Conyers of Michigan said: ``One week away from
such a monumental vote is not time to commence an entirely new area
of investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's my worry that this is becoming an impeachment
inquiry in search of a high crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., called the expansion the ``last gasp
of people who want to impeach Clinton but haven't been able to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican committee members defended the move.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said the committee has ``the right
and obligation to follow leads wherever they take us.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the committee heard testimony from two women convicted
of perjury resulting from false testimony in sex-related civil
cases in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The committee presented the witnesses in an effort to draw a
parallel to Clinton's case. The president has been accused by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr of committing perjury in the
now-withdrawn civil lawsuit brought by Paula Jones, who claimed the
then-governor of Arkansas made a crude sexual overture to her when
she was a state employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because a president is not a king, he or she must abide by the
same laws as the rest of us,'' said Barbara Battalino, a former
Veterans Affairs hospital psychologist from Los Osos, Calif., who
is serving a home detention sentence after pleading guilty in a
case in which she lied about a single instance of consensual oral
sex with a male patient in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if justice does not prevail, Mr. Clinton's consequences
will be reserved for God and history to determine.''
</P>
<P>
   The other witness, former University of South Carolina women's
basketball coach Pam Parsons of Atlanta, pleaded guilty to a
federal perjury charge in a civil case about a sexual relationship
she had with a player.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons told lawmakers she pled guilty in 1984 to lying under
oath when she said she had never been to a particular gay nightspot
in Salt Lake City. She served five years on probation from 1985 to
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have done what no one else has been able to do,'' said
Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C. ``You have thrown a wrench in the White
House spin machine.'' Inglis said the women had been able ``to stop
the attack on the attacker,'' a reference to White House efforts to
demonize Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the committee heard from a panel of active and
retired judges and military personnel on the consequences of
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. 11th Circuit Court Judge Gerald Tjoflat compared perjury to
dropping a pebble in a pond, saying it produces a ``ripple effect
... that breeds disrespect for the rule of law throughout the
judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Adm. Leon A. Edney, former vice chief of naval
operations, said the country's military could not function if lying
were permitted. ```Do as I say, not as I do' doesn't hack it the
armed forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But retired Judge Leon Higginbotham Jr. said the committee
should take into consideration the fact that removing the president
for perjury could seriously ``disrupt'' the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
