<HEADER>
A7577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KSTATE-KELLY-HNS &LR;      12-01 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSTATE-KELLY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
When Jeff Kelly left La Grange High School to play football at
Stephen F. Austin, he intended to spend his entire college career
at middle linebacker for the Lumberjacks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I thought I would stay there for four years,'' Kelly said.
``But (SFA) coach (John) Pearce was really good to me. He told me I
had the talent to play at a bigger school if that's what I wanted
to do. He really helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches might not be willing to give up their best player,
but Pearce knew Kelly belonged on a bigger stage and wanted what
was best for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got there, he gave me the option of playing fullback or
linebacker,'' Kelly said. ``I started at linebacker as a true
freshman, then he helped me pick a junior college so I could move
on. He told me if it didn't work out, I always could come back to
Stephen F. Austin. But he thought I would end up elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearce was right. Kelly became a junior-college All-American at
Garden City (Kan.) before transferring to Kansas State. Now, he is
an All-American for a team that is undefeated and hoping for a shot
at the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   As he heads for St. Louis to play Texas A&AMP;M on Saturday in the
Big 12 Championship Game, Kelly realizes he's a long way from where
he could have been had he stayed in Nacogdoches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Pearce and my parents took me where I needed to go,''
Kelly said. ``Coming here was the best thing that ever happened to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearce, a former head coach at Willowridge, found out last week
that his contract at SFA would not be renewed, which Kelly was
disappointed to hear. Maybe Kansas State coach Bill Snyder needs to
send Pearce a thank-you note, because Kelly is the best player on
one of the best defensive units in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is sitting in the middle of the whole thing for us,''
Snyder said. ``He's a guy with a great knack for the football. He
loves to play the game, and he has fun practicing. He runs
extremely well, and he's a very physical player to go with it. He's
very athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-0 and 245 pounds, Kelly has the strength to take on
interior linemen and the speed to run down wide receivers. With
senior linebacker Travis Ochs and junior Marc Simoneau flanking
him, many consider the Kansas State trio the best linebacker group
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``On any defense, the linebackers are instrumental in your
success,'' Snyder said. ``All three of our starters have been an
integral part of the success we've had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate that the three of them have played a lot of
games together. They are the backbone of the defense. They have
gotten better in the last two years by playing together more and
more. They have a great understanding of our defense, and they know
each other well. They have learned how to complement each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The two linebackers who will be in the spotlight Saturday are
Kelly and Dat Nguyen of A&AMP;M, both of whom already have made
All-America teams this season. Kelly spent part of his Thanksgiving
weekend at Royal-Texas Memorial Stadium watching Nguyen and the
Aggies (10-2) lose to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dat runs to the ball everywhere it goes,'' Kelly said. ``He's
a great player, and I know people are going to compare us. But
we're just two guys trying to help our teams reach a major goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate goal for the Wildcats is to give Kansas State its
first Big 12 championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough game,'' Kelly said. ``A&AMP;M lost a
close game, and they will come out there Saturday with something to
prove. Believe me, (the loss to Texas) will be a power boost for
them. They will come out ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger goal that might be out of reach for the Wildcats is
the national championship. Kansas State would be 12-0 with a
victory over the Aggies, but Tennessee and UCLA are in line to play
in the Fiesta Bowl unless one of those teams loses Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly insists he won't be disappointed if the Wildcats are left
out of the title game. Besides, since Kansas State is No. 1 in the
coaches poll, it's possible it could stay there if it remains
unbeaten with a win over Ohio State or Florida State in the Sugar
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Kelly said. ``If we win all our games, we
would accomplish what we set out to accomplish. We just have to do
what we can do, and God willing, we'll get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
