<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ As the House Judiciary Committee voted
along party lines to approve new subpoenas, Rep. Dick Gephardt, the
House Democratic Leader, appealed to the Republican leadership to
``bring some order out of the chaos.'' By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-REPORT (Washington) _ A report by auditors for the
Federal Election Commission has concluded that President Clinton
and Republican presidential candidate Robert Dole violated election
spending limits during their primary campaigns and should be
required to repay millions of dollars. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-U.S. (Washington) _ The United States, treading into a
political and diplomatic thicket it has tried to avoid, will
declassify secret Government documents on the killing and torture
conducted under the former dictator of Chile, Augusto Pinochet,
whose predecessor was the target of American coup plots in the
early 1970s. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ Two of China's most prominent
dissidents, each of whom has spent over a decade in jail, were
suddenly arrested for criminal offenses on Monday evening in an
apparent crackdown on their efforts to form China's first
opposition political party. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-GAYS (Miami) _ More than 20 years after Anita Bryant's
``save our children'' crusade led to the repeal here of one of the
country's first gay rights city ordinances and galvanized anti-gay
sentiment in the nation, the Miami-Dade County commission is
expected to vote on another law to ban discrimination on the basis
of sexual orientation. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
