<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS PROPOSE ANOTHER SHUTTLE TRIP TO MIR AS SALVAGE OPERATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The Mir space station may not have logged
its final U.S. shuttle visit, and the Russians are exploring the
prospect of extending the aging outpost's orbital life beyond next
year with commercial funding, officials from the two countries said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came on the eve of the U.S. launch of the second
major component for a new international space station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Endeavour was to blast off from NASA's Kennedy Space
Center on Thursday at 3:56 a.m.,EST. Forecasters predict a 60
percent chance that low clouds and rain showers either in Florida
or at one of the shuttle's emergency runways around the world could
force a delay.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour carries a 25,000-pound component the shuttle crew will
link to the much larger Russian-built propulsion and power
generation module called ``Zarya'' that was successfully launched
from Central Asia on Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   It was at a round of prelaunch meetings in Moscow for Zarya that
the Russian Space Agency chief Yuri Koptev asked NASA Administrator
Dan Goldin to consider a 10th shuttle voyage to Mir to collect
laboratory research equipment that could be transferred to the new
station, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are compiling a list of equipment, their own,
European and U.S., that might be transferred, either on a combined
mission with the new station or for return to the ground and
relaunching, said Mike Hawes, NASA's chief station engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to admit we don't have a surplus of scientific
equipment. So any equipment that can be used for implementation of
the science program would be helpful, a benefit for both
countries,'' said Valeri Ryumin, the RSC-Energia aerospace company
official who serves as Russia's operations manager for the station.
``The issue will be rigorously assessed,'' he said through a
translator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the discussions are going on at a fairly top
level,'' said Frank Culbertson, NASA's space station operations
manager. ``We'll make a recommendation based on our assessments of
risk versus gain.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. shuttles flew a series of nine docking missions to Mir over
three years, culminating in what was to be the final mission last
June. However, the original agreement between the two countries for
the flights prior to the first flight called for up to 10 such
missions.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle/Mir missions included lengthy visits by seven U.S.
astronauts, which were considered a rehearsal of operations planned
for the new international space station.
</P>
<P>
   As the program came to its close, the Americans obtained an
agreement from the financially-troubled Russians to scuttle Mir in
the Pacific Ocean as soon as mid-1999 in order to ensure that it
would not compete with the new station for scarce funding.
</P>
<P>
   Though the agreement is still in place, another top Russian
space official said Tuesday that its technical experts believe Mir
could fly for another three years and may continue beyond next year
if an unidentified commercial source provides the funding.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect arises on the heels of a U.S. commitment to pay
the Russians $60 million to complete their massive service module,
the first habitable component of the new station. Russian financial
difficulties with the module forced a one-year delay in the start
of construction of the new station.
</P>
<P>
   The service module is undergoing extensive ground tests at its
Moscow-area production facility, and the July launch date listed by
the Russians is probably the earliest it could be launched, Hawes
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mikhail Sinelschikov, the chief of the Russian
Space Agency's human space program, Mir will be adequately funded
by his government through the middle of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But if it can secure funding from what he characterized as a
nongovernmental prospect, perhaps even a foreign one, Mir's
operations may be continued. Sinelschikov acknowledged the issue of
preserving the 13-year-old outpost has become a political one
within his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do have money, we will keep flying,'' said Sinelschikov,
also speaking through a translator. ``This is our choice. This is
our say. We are sovereign, an independent country. This is up to us
to decide''
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize there is not enough funding to support two programs
at the same time; we would have to make a hard choice,'' said
Sinelschikov. ``We will make that choice. There is no doubt about
that. There is no alternative to our participation in the
international space station program.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mir is scuttled, the Russian's plans are to launch a final
crew in February. They would make preparations that would include
the arrival of the four Progress cargo capsules with the propellant
that would be required to lower the station's orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The cosmonauts would abandon the Mir while it was still at a
safe altitude. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
