</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEINSTEIN AIMS FOR GUN CONTROL LEGISLATION IN NEW CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who spearheaded
the move for the 1994 law that banned the manufacture of 19 types
of semi-automatic assault weapons, said Tuesday she wants to plug a
loophole in that law next year and impose more federal controls on
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said recent shootings involving children with firearms
have persuaded her to renew her gun control efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it gets down to five-year-olds and children bringing guns
to school to kill other children, it ought to be a major wakeup
call that we'd better take some precautions,'' Feinstein said in an
interview in her Capitol Hill office.
</P>
<P>
   She referred to a five-year-old in Memphis, Tenn., who was
arrested in May after bringing a loaded pistol to school because he
wanted to kill his teacher for disciplining him by separating him
from his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Feinstein noted, a 15-year-old boy from
Springfield, Ore., who had murdered his parents, walked into his
high school cafeteria and fired a semi-automatic rifle with a
50-round clip into a crowd of students, killing two and wounding 22
others.
</P>
<P>
   But Feinstein acknowledged that ``any legislation with respect
to guns has a tough row to hoe'' in a Republican Congress that has
a history of defeating gun control efforts. ``This is an unfriendly
Congress, but these are ideas that have wide acceptance and make
common sense,'' she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she intends to push a gun control package that
would ban the import of ammunition clips that hold more than 10
rounds. Under a loophole in the 1994 assault weapons law,
large-capacity clips made before the law's enactment continue to be
imported from 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she also plans to include measures that would
require trigger locks on guns to prevent them from being discharged
accidentally, ban inexpensive handguns called Saturday night
specials and call for background checks for firearm purchases at
gun shows or from collectors as well as from dealers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Feinstein said she looking at extending a pilot
program now in Richmond, Va., that requires federal prosecution of
crimes committed with guns.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said her gun control crusade stems from her own
personal history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, she escaped an attack by the New World Liberation
Front, a group that had targeted prominent business and political
leaders. The terrorists placed a bomb at the door of her San
Francisco home beneath her daughter's bedroom, but the detonator
failed to work after the temperature dropped below freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, terrorists shot out the windows of Feinstein's
beach house near Santa Cruz. After she was told that her first
husband, Dr. Bert Feinstein, was terminally ill with cancer, she
said she got a concealed weapons permit and learned to use a pistol
so she could protect herself at night when she went to see him in
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She became mayor of San Francisco 20 years ago after the Nov.
27, 1978, assassination of her predecessor, George Moscone.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting happened on her first day back as president of the
city's board of supervisors after a leave following Dr. Feinstein's
death. She recalled that she spotted former supervisor Dan White
walking past her office door. White, who had resigned because of
financial difficulties, wanted to reclaim his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan, can you stop? I want to talk to you,'' Feinstein called
out. But White went on, saying, ``I've got to do something first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the shots, smelled the gun powder and he came rushing
by me,'' Feinstein said. Besides Moscone, White also shot and
killed Supervisor Harvey Milk, whose body she found that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible saga in the history of San Francisco,''
Feinstein said. ``For me the assassination was a linchpin event in
my life and in my feelings about weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also said she was prompted to fight for a ban on
assault weapons by the July 1993 murders of seven people in a San
Francisco law office who were attacked by a crazed man armed with
such a gun.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is disturbed by ``the absolute enormity of the
amount of guns that float around society and the inability to know
where they are. There are so many weapons it is easy for the
criminal to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she added, fighting for gun control has been hard
``because the Second Amendment has been construed by some to mean
anybody can possess anything anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
