<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-STOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net stocks gyrating on e-commerce expectations
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The post-holiday buying frenzy is not limited to those
who line up outside the malls before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Internet-related companies kept up their erratic
activity this week. After closing Monday down 3.32 percent, the
Nasdaq composite index closed up 2.79 percent Tuesday. The jump was
the Nasdaq's biggest since Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of local Internet-related companies have been fluctuating
as much as the index. MindSpring, the Southeast's largest Internet
access company, closed at $62.62 1/2, down $1.93 3/4. MindSpring
had a wild Thanksgiving ride, rising $14 to close at $72.12 3/4
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Security Systems, based in the Perimeter Center area,
was down $2.75. The network security company closed at $33.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the pre-Christmas season,'' said Jeff Sadler of
Robinson-Humphrey in Atlanta. ``And certainly one of the early
e-commerce applications is shopping by the Internet. It's one of
those `if you're not there you're square' applications.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened late last week to Birmingham-based Books-A-Million
is one of the more recent and illustrative examples of the Internet
sector's unpredictability. Two weeks ago, the price of the regional
bookseller was sleeping around $3. Then, last Wednesday, on news
the company's year-old Web site had been revamped, shares shot from
$4.37 1/2 to $14. After a day off for Thanksgiving, the stock went
nutty, closing Friday at $38.93 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Books-A-Million has settled. Shares dropped $5
Tuesday, closing at $24.50.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey's Dave Magee said the stock's volatility last
week was less about the company than the hype surrounding all
things Internet when it comes to the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Internet discussion groups are helping fuel the buzz. As of
mid-November, people had posted 3,000 messages this year regarding
Books-A-Million stock on the Yahoo! Finance site. In the past two
weeks, that number more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a lot of hype going on in the Internet
space,'' Sadler said. ``You have a lot of factors. You have
companies without a lot of shares. Then the Internet gets hot, the
company gets speculated upon and there's not a lot of shares to go
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that provide part of the backbone for e-commerce, like
CheckFree, have not reaped the benefit of the stock market's
Internet wave.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree traded at $6 on Oct. 6, before closing at $17.68 3/4
Tuesday, up $1.43 3/4. CheckFree is trying to make the Internet the
place where you receive and pay your bills.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Koprucki, who covers the company for the Ohio Group, rates
its stock a ``strong buy'' and predicts its shares will trade at
$47 in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``CheckFree is going to be one of the big beneficiaries of
e-commerce,'' he said. ``They, more than anyone, are a beneficiary
of the increased volume and increased traffic. It's been kind of
frustrating in some ways that the stock has not moved more. But it
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
