<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLINK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roswell firm tries to open new page in paging business
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The wireless wave is building, and a quiet Roswell,
Ga. company is hoping to be a winner when it crests.
</P>
<P>
   Satellink Communications, founded in 1988, is still a niche
player in a market dominated by the likes of Skytel, Arch and
PageNet, concedes Jerry Mayfield, company president and co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than a dozen companies control 75 percent of the paging
market, with the rest fragmented among several thousand other
companies _ including privately held Satellink, he said. ``But 25
percent is still a big number. There's an opportunity to
consolidate some of those 2,000, and that is what we are looking
at.''
</P>
<P>
   With that growth in mind, the company recently added 70,000
subscribers with the purchase of Cape Fear Broadcasting Cos.,
bringing Satellink's base to about 240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Satellink, which has 300 employees, really has two businesses.
One is a standard paging business, reselling the paging service of
various carriers that hold paging licenses. However, Satellink got
its start in 1988 as an affiliate in the Cue Nationwide Paging
Network, a confederation of companies that provides a paging
umbrella over the United States using part of the frequency given
to FM radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   A page from Satellink or any other company on the network is
beamed to more than 600 stations. The signal is carried on a
``sideband'' of the station's signal that a pager hears but not an
FM radio. ``It's transparent to the listener,'' said Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Cue's network covers 95 percent of the country's population.
Because the national paging companies are focused on major cities,
Satellink and other Cue affiliates can appeal to people who cruise
the vast spaces in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of truckers,'' Mayfield said. ``If you are
anywhere within range of any stations, you are going to get
paged.''
</P>
<P>
   Satellink handles Georgia, Alabama, western Louisiana and
eastern Texas for Cue. The purchase of Cape Fear Broadcasting adds
Tennessee, Kentucky and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Limited services
</P>
<P>
   The Cue affiliation accounts for about 75,000 Satellink
subscribers, but it has a limited appeal. The Cue network permits
only phone calls to a pager and lets the caller leave only a string
of numbers _ no more than a dozen digits. No pager-to-pager
messaging, no voice messages, no return messages from the receiving
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a niche business,'' Mayfield said.
</P>
<P>
   And while it's a good business, the company's long-term growth
more likely will come by extending its second business from mere
paging to the more muscular use of technology that appeals to
professionals and business people.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless communications are increasingly being used to carry
numeric pages, written messages, data, voice conversations and even
links to the Internet. While Satellink owns no wireless licenses,
it can resell those kinds of services, combine them in a variety of
ways and run them through its own high-speed switches.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that strategy, the company now offers a feature
called Starnet that lets customers use one number for services that
include paging, voice mail, calling card long-distance and the
``find me'' function that tries a series of phones looking for the
customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pushing to be an enhanced paging and communications
service,'' Mayfield said. ``We want to take that one phone number
and do a lot of things with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts for some time have predicted a one-number feature will
become hot, but similar services from BellSouth and others have not
taken off. While declining to critique BellSouth's PowerCall
feature, Mayfield said he believes a well-marketed approach can
work for Satellink _ especially in the places ignored by the big
companies. And unlike its FM-based service as a Cue affiliate,
Satellink has no geographic limits on its other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a market for enhanced services in the smaller area,''
he said. ``We could go anywhere we want to with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Satellink was founded by Mayfield, Marc Comeaux, who is no
longer in management, and Robert Poche, who is currently senior
vice president. The company registered for an initial public
offering of stock in the spring but withdrew when the market took a
dive. Eventually the company will need cash and will get it either
by IPO or private investors, Mayfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
