<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fulton banks on financial system readiness
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fulton County says it'll be ready for the millennium.
And Jarvis Aldridge, the Y2K program manager for the county,
indicated there won't be interruptions facing those who depend on
the county to provide medical and welfare benefits along with other
check-based forms of financial help.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the systems, all financial systems, that have top
priority within our Year 2000 program. Testing should be completed
by the second quarter of next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources of Y2K risk for the county's mainframe computers include
3.9 million lines of in-house computer code, six programming
languages and 4-to-5 supporting languages.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are about 3,500 PCs in 500-plus offices, divided
evenly between stand-alones and those that are networked. In all,
these PCs use about 200 different desktop software products.
</P>
<P>
   What systems are mission critical? About 120-plus mainframe
applications and about 24 mid-range applications. Some are in
remediation; some will be tested in the first quarter. It'll be
done in stages and finished by the third quarter, Aldridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its official optimism, the county faces two hurdles:
Money and a maze of different vendors to contact.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County has spent the $5.5 million budgeted in 1998 to
solve Y2K. The county had planned to spend another $9 million in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   But, whoops, a recently discovered $85 million shortfall in
overall county revenue has put the Y2K budget in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the county's systems are mostly maintained by
vendors, a plus in the instance of those who provide Y2K upgrades,
but a minus for the county, given the sheer number of suppliers
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County has depended on about 10,000 vendors in the past
ten years. These suppliers may or may not be compliant and may or
may not still be in business.
</P>
<P>
   Aldridge said the county has a dedicated group working on vendor
management and cited the example of the staff having contacted Ford
Motor about county vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But there's much to do. The county, for instance, has not yet
coordinated any activities with Georgia Power.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the matter of embedded chips, those potentially
date sensitive slivers of silicone that could knock-out phone
systems, elevators, traffic lights, hospital equipment and all
manner of automated devices used by the county.
</P>
<P>
   Aldridge said Fulton County has inventoried about 10,000
automated devices, representing about 3,000 different types.
</P>
<P>
   The county plans to replace its vulnerable embedded chips but
has as yet to devise a comprehensive testing strategy. ``But that's
part of our program that will be produced within the coming year,''
Aldridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
