<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON HOME STAYS WITH THE OWNER AWAY  
 FERRY FROM TAMPA TO THE MEXICAN COAST  
 IN MIAMI BEACH, AN ALMOST NEW HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)  
 (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Temporarily vacant private homes in London can be a reasonably
priced and comfortable alternative to the city's hotels. Go Native,
a London company, offers more than 150 fully equipped and furnished
homes there, including a warehouse apartment overlooking the
Thames; lofts and studios in Clerkenwell, Soho and Bloomsbury;
apartments and townhouses in Chelsea, Little Venice, Knightsbridge
and Notting Hill; a houseboat on the Thames, and a cottage in the
former stable block of Kensington Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $602 a week for a studio apartment five
minutes' walk from Sloane Square, based on $1.72 to the British
pound, to $4,300 a week for a five-bedroom townhouse in Chelsea.
Most homes are one- or two-bedroom apartments in the $860 to $1,720
range.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners include lawyers, artists and diplomats, many of whom
live abroad or in the country and use their city homes only
occasionally. Others live in London most of the time and rent out
their homes just a few weeks of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Prices include weekly maid service and all utilities. Telephone
calls are charged separately. Every guest is met at the home on
arrival and checked out on departure. The agency is available 24
hours a day. Homeowners supply a guide to the best of local
amenities such as restaurants, markets and parks.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (44-171) 221 2028, fax (44-171) 221 2088. The
company's Web site is www.gonative.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Collis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Viking Lines has begun offering European-style ferry
service twice a week between Tampa, Fla., and Progreso, Mexico on
the Yucatan coast. The 630--passenger vessel Scotia Prince also
operates as a cargo ship. It departs from Tampa on Tuesdays and
Fridays and leaves Progreso on Sundays and Wednesdays. The trip
takes 36 hours. Two decks carry cargo as well as passengers' cars
and recreational vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Cabins on the Scotia Prince, which are described as utilitarian
rather than luxurious, come with or without toilets and bathrooms;
suites are also available. The ship has a sun deck with a bar and a
fully equipped casino. Passengers pay separately for meals, which
are served in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   American Viking also offers one-day tours in Mexico. Progreso is
about 20 miles from the colonial city of Merida and within driving
distance of Chichen Itza. Tours are also available to the Celestun
National Wildlife Refuge and to the town of Uxmal. Tour packages
can be bought on the ship and include transportation and meals.
</P>
<P>
   Round-trip fares are $124 a person, double occupancy, for cabins
with sinks only and $144 a person for cabins with full bathrooms.
Prices for the suites had not yet been set in late November, but
are estimated at about $100 higher. An extra $199 is added to ferry
a car. One-day tours vary in price from $57 to $79.
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast buffet costs $7.95; the dinner buffet, $14.95. A
four-course a la carte dinner runs $19.95. A beer or glass of wine
costs $3 to $6.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: (800) 450-8633 or (813) 248-1222.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Mercer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a decade or more, Miami Beach has been restoring its famed
Art Deco hotels, making them as much a tourist attraction as the
wide beach. This month, what is described as the first major new
hotel built in 30 years is to open on that famed spit of beach and
bravura.
</P>
<P>
   But the Loews Miami Beach Hotel, at 16th Street and Collins
Avenue, four blocks from the convention center, didn't start from
scratch. It combines a new 17-story, 700-room beachfront tower with
the restored 100-room St. Moritz, which was built in 1939 and has
been closed for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel will open its doors by the third week of December,
with a grand opening scheduled for March 6.
</P>
<P>
   The total of 800 rooms includes 74 suites. Rooms have touches of
Art Deco, Palm Beach and Caribbean style; the St. Moritz rooms,
which are smaller than the new tower rooms, will have elaborate
moldings and ceiling coves. Most tower rooms have balconies.
</P>
<P>
   The 85,000 square feet of space for meetings and parties will
include two ballrooms and a multitiered lawn for outdoor
entertaining. There are six restaurants and lounges, including
Preston's in the new tower, serving American fare (entrees run from
$14 for the grilled portobello patty melt to $36 for the
goat-cheese-stuffed rack of lamb), and the Gaucho Room, an
Argentine restaurant with other South American influences in the
St. Moritz section ($17 for the trout to $21 to $28 for American
and Argentine steaks).
</P>
<P>
   The 4,500-square-foot fitness center will offer a range of
equipment and aerobics classes. Besides the 900-foot-wide beach,
swimmers can float in the free-form pool surrounded by tropical
gardens and 20 cabanas served by butlers. Valet and self-service
parking for 1,000 cars will be available in an underground garage
and mostly in a lot across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Major facilities and services will be up and running this month,
according to Debra Kelman, a spokeswoman for Loews, but cosmetic
work like landscaping may not be finished.
</P>
<P>
   Through Jan. 3, the Loews Miami Beach is offering a rate of $199
a night for standard rooms; normal winter rates will be $309 to
$499. Suites cost $600 to $5,000. Reservations: (800) 235-6397 or
(305) 604-1601, fax (305) 531-8677.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Cormier
</P>
</TEXT>
