<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coverdell re-elected to Senate leadership
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans on Tuesday returned their
leaders to power for another two years, re-electing Sen. Trent Lott
(R-Miss.) as majority leader and Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) as the
number five player in the six-man team.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the House, where House Speaker Newt Gingrich
(R-Ga.) resigned and other posts changed hands in the wake of the
Nov. 3 elections, the Senate leadership elections were remarkably
calm.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) successfully defeated a challenge
by Sen. Chuck Hagel (R-Neb.) to chair the Senate fund raising
committee in the GOP's only contested leadership election. Hagel,
who said the party needed leaders capable of delivering a clearer
message, was defeated 39 to 13 in the 55-member GOP conference,
with three absences.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, also returned most of their leaders to
leadership positions. Sen. Harry Reid (D-Nev.), who barely won
re-election Nov. 3, succeeded retiring Sen. Wendell Ford (D-Ky.) as
minority whip, the number two position behind minority leader Tom
Daschle (D-S.D.).
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Torricelli (D-N.J.) assumed the chairmanship of the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, taking over from Sen. Bob
Kerrey (D-Neb.), who is mulling a possible presidential bid in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from both parties are responsible for fashioning the
legislative agendas of their parties, developing legislative
strategy and ensuring the re-election of their members in election
years.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, Coverdell's re-election as conference secretary
assumes larger significance in the wake of Gingrich's resignation
from the House. Coverdell is now the only member of the Georgia
delegation in the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in a position to carry the ball forward, but
obviously any state that loses the speakership _ that is a big
change for us,'' Coverdell said. ``It puts an added responsibility
not only on me but the entire delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond broad generalities, both parties declined to offer much
in the way of specific legislation that they will pursue when
Congress re-convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Republicans will focus on reducing the size of
government, giving married couples some tax relief by removing the
so-called marriage penalty and improving education. Lott pledged to
work more closely with Republican governors in shaping policy and
legislation, a tacit acknowledgement of critics who charged that
Congress ignored the pragmatic conservatism of many GOP governors.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he is anxious to address the future insolvency of
Social Security, but indicated that he will wait for President
Clinton to come forward with a plan for fixing the retirement
system before initiating anything in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lott blamed the GOP's failure to gain seats in the Senate Nov. 3
on the party's inability to deliver its message to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have an agenda that reflects what the American people
want, and we do,'' Lott said. ``But we have got to do a better job
explaining it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
