<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-CABLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Western Show a forum for digital technology
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For Mike Wearsch, the big cable TV convention
that starts in Anaheim, Calif., today is something of a technology
fashion show. The vice president of Atlanta-based Antec's digital
systems comes to see and be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always make sure to check out the competition,'' explains
Wearsch, whose company supplies hardware to the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   His crosstown rival, Scientific-Atlanta President and Chief
Executive James F. McDonald, adds, ``You go for the visibility with
customers. If you want to participate in this industry you have to
be at the Western Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 30,000 cable TV industry executives are expected to attend
this year's Western Show, today through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This show is shaping up as especially important to Atlanta's
media and high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the show's focus is on the rise of new digital
technologies that use the cable industry's fiber optic networks to
carry everything from telephone calls to television shows to
computer data. Many of these new services are being developed by
Atlanta high-tech hardware companies such as Antec and
Scientific-Atlanta and delivered by hometown players such as Cox
Communications and Knology.
</P>
<P>
   The city is also a home to cable programmers, such as Turner
Broadcasting and the Weather Channel, which are represented at the
Western Show.
</P>
<P>
   This year's show comes as the industry completes its first full
year for commercial rollout of these new digital services. A lot of
the convention is expected to focus on how well these services have
sold and how to refine them to sell even better.
</P>
<P>
   There are, for example, now more than 300,000 people using cable
industry modems that connect personal computers at ultra fast
speeds to the Internet. A key question for the industry is, will
this number likely grow at a faster pace or has it peaked?
</P>
<P>
   For Cox Communications Chief Executive and President Jim
Robbins, the answer is the market for cable modems is young. He
says his company can't distribute the modems fast enough in its
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue for us is getting enough trained people to handle
the business,'' says Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne, owner of Atlanta's largest single cable system, is
also offering cable modems and telephone service. It's coming to
the Western Show to scout out new technology and channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking for ways to push the signal faster down
the backbone of our system,'' says Ellen Filipiak, MediaOne's
senior vice president of the Atlanta region. That's cable-speak for
speeding up the workings of MediaOne's system.
</P>
<P>
   Filipiak also has two other special interests this year. She's
wondering how soon cable modems can be sold in retail stores such
as Circuit City. Right now, her company and most operators lease
them to subscribers. MediaOne has more than 2,000 cable modem users
in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Her other interest is high-definition television, or HDTV. At
present, MediaOne and most other cable operators are not equipped
to carry this digital signal, which offers super sharp images and
CD-quality sound.
</P>
<P>
   But HDTV requires a new television set to receive the signal,
and prices for it start at $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a chicken-and-egg kind of thing,'' says Filipiak.
``There aren't many people who can receive the signal yet but we
want to be ready to send it when they are. We're closely following
consumer acceptance of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another big issue at the show is cable telephony, the industry's
network to provide telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cox Communications and MediaOne are already doing so. And
Antec has just sold $900 million in telephone equipment to AT&AMP;T,
which will use it to provide service through cable operator
Tele-Communications Inc. AT&AMP;T is in the process of buying the
country's second largest cable TV operator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow us to tap into a huge new business,'' says
Antec's Wearsch, who also provides service to Cox Communications.
``We will demonstrate Internet telephone service at the Western
Show,'' says Wearsch. ``But it still needs a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cable operators, such as Comcast, are delaying offering
telephone service, hoping they can eventually do so at a lower cost
through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
