<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-CABLE-COXCOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Communications converts 65,000 cable users into digital
service subscribers
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Cox Communications has persuaded more than
65,000 of its cable TV customers to sign up for its new digital
television service in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   While representing only a small portion of the Atlanta-based
company's 3.8 million cable subscribers, this figure is big enough
to encourage both Cox Communications and the cable industry to
press on with the new generation of digital services.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers have definitely exceeded any business plan that
I ever submitted about digital television,'' said Lynne Elander,
Cox Communications director of product development.
</P>
<P>
   Elander made the comment to a roomful of cable TV programmers
who had come to see a demonstration Monday of the company's new
digital services at its Orange County, Calif., system.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications staged the demonstration as a preview to the
Western Show, an industry convention which will be held today
through Friday here.
</P>
<P>
   Elander told the programmers Cox Communications had now rebuilt
about one-third of its total cable plant to carry two-way digital
signals. These lines pass some 1.5 million households nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The company now offers digital television in eight markets and
plans to add another three markets in the coming months, says
Elander. Most of the new digital customers are located in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   She says Cox Communications is adding digital customers, who pay
up to $11.95 extra month for the service, at a rate of 1,500 to
2,000 a month. At that rate, Cox Communications expects to sell
digital services to between 25-30 percent of its subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're careful not to draw long-term conclusions from
these initial findings, we're delighted,'' says Virginia Gray, Cox
Communicatons' vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is digital television doing better than in the company's
Orange County system, where it was initially offered on Oct. 29,
1997. The system serves a largely affluent population, many of whom
already have computers and use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is also offering its 222,000 Orange County
customers high-speed access to the Internet and telephone service
through its digital cable system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first traditional cable market to get voice, data
and television simultaneously through a cable wire,'' says Elander.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications has been closely studying those who buy its
digital services. What it has found so far is digital services are
driving up television watching.
</P>
<P>
   That research shows digital customers are watching about 10
percent more television than they did before. And they are spending
50 percent of their viewing time with digital channels.
</P>
<P>
   What people are watching more of is movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies are driving up digital television,'' says Elander.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a movie lover's product.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not an unexpected finding, given movie channels represent a
big part of the digital services' 200 channels. And entertainment
has traditionally driven consumer acceptance of new technology into
the home.
</P>
<P>
   Take computers, for example. It was the rise of exciting
multimedia games, coupled with falling prices, that drove their
entry into homes.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
