<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENT-COUNCIL-C     12-01 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-COUNCIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor-elect hopes to use Maryland plan as example
 &HT;    By David Goldberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening had a message Tuesday
for governor-elect Roy Barnes: You can put the brakes on suburban
sprawl and live to see re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening garnered national attention last year when he
expended enormous political capital to pass the state's Smart
Growth program, which Barnes hopes to emulate in Georgia in some
form. Glendening was in Atlanta to share his experiences with a
national conference of state environmental and transportation
officials, who are meeting together for the first time to talk
about how to curb sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   The principle behind the Maryland program is simple: the state
will no longer pay to build schools, sewer lines, government
buildings and the like on farm and forest land when existing
developed areas can handle new growth.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Growth was greeted with jubilation by many advocacy
groups, but not so by home and road builders, who went after
Glendening during his re-election campaign this fall. ``They
attacked us, and some who had supported us stopped supporting us,''
Glendening said. But in the end he won by 170,000 votes, a larger
margin than his first election.
</P>
<P>
   To pass Smart Growth, Glendening and his staff spent several
months laying the groundwork with county and city governments.
Glendening, who was county executive of Prince George's County,
Md., before becoming governor, said he headed off certain rebellion
among county officials by leaving most decisions about how to grow
in local hands.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires counties to designate urban zones where growth
will be focused at ``livable'' densities, defined as an overall
average of 3.5 housing units per acre. State infrastructure money
is then directed to those places, rather than to pristine areas at
the fringes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as local governments follow their own plans, they get
the money,'' Glendening said.
</P>
<P>
   From Glendening's perspective, Maryland has squandered billions
of dollars chasing development farther afield even as cities and
inner suburbs deteriorated. He noted that Montgomery County had
closed 60 schools in older areas over the last 20 years while
spending a half-billion dollars to build 60-plus schools in new
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The state historically spent 57 percent of school construction
dollars in new suburbs. It's now spending 84 percent for expanding
and refurbishing existing schools, Glendening said.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland is also redirecting transportation funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, this nation has generally dealt with congestion
issues (by asking) `How can we move more cars farther and faster?''
Glendening said. ``Smart Growth, by contrast, demands that we take
a more people-oriented, more community-oriented view that actually
asks the heretical question, `How can we reduce the need to use the
car?''' He said Maryland is beefing up its mass transit budget and
has set up a fund to pay for streetscape improvements and
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   John Frece, Glendening's special assistant for Smart Growth, met
Tuesday with two Barnes aides charged with helping to craft
legislation for the Georgia legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear they are interested in trying to addresss this
issue right out of the box,'' Frece said. ``In Maryland we found
the need to lay the groundwork and listen to alot of constituencies
before we went into it. I don't think we would have been successful
if they hadn't been consulted. But on the other hand, if the stars
are in alignment here, maybe they would be right to do something
right away, given how fast Atlanta is growing and how long it takes
to make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint meeting of the Environmental Council of the States and
the American Association of State Highway and Transportation
Officials ends today.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
