<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCTIC-RESCUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER THAT MAROONED FILM CREW ENDANGERS ARCTIC RUSSIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The three-man film crew -- a Japanese television
producer, Australian cameraman and a Russian wildlife expert --
were marooned in an isolated Arctic wasteland, cut off from rescue
by subzero cold, perpetual blizzard conditions and the advancing
polar night.
</P>
<P>
   They had spent the past six weeks holed up in a cabin on Cape
Blossom, the cruelly misnamed tip of Vrangel Island. This dark and
stormy patch of land 300 miles northwest of Alaska is paradise for
the polar bears they had come to film, but a frigid hell for
humans.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the trio planned to leave. Tens of thousands of
Russians who live in the Arctic tundra face a winter without
adequate food and fuel to survive the brutal conditions because of
the country's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While the ordeal of the film crew resembled something out of a
Jack London story, their escape Tuesday was closer to Tom Clancy.
As the crew kept in touch with embassies, colleagues and loved ones
by satellite phone and the Internet ( To send e-mail!), a Russian
Mi-8 helicopter braved a blinding snow squall to snatch them and
their 800 pounds of cargo safely away to the Siberian mainland port
of Pevek.
</P>
<P>
   There, as the relieved crew members gave their first interviews,
an Arctic tragedy of far greater proportions was unfolding,
overshadowed by the dramatic events of the film crew's ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Russian citizens live in settlements along the country's far
northern and eastern coasts, forced to endure winter conditions not
much better than those on Vrangel. Once well paid by the Soviet
state to live in one of the harshest environments known to man,
these people have faced seven straight years of plunging living
standards in Russia's chaotic post-Communist economy. They too are
stranded by their newfound poverty and Russia's inability to create
a working program to resettle them. And this year, they have found
their food and fuel supplies nearly cut off because of Russia's
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit is the Chukotka region where Pevek is located, a
barren tundra land of about 80,000 people, rich in gold and little
else, where life expectancy for men in some regions is an
astonishing 34 years old, according to the International Federation
of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these regions are in a desperate state,'' Oleg
Chestnov, Director General of the Russian Red Cross, said last week
before a Red Cross delegation left for Siberia to study how to best
channel aid to the region. ``It is imperative that we bring help to
people who are on the verge of extinction.''
</P>
<P>
   This winter, there has been talk of evacuating entire towns in
Chukotka, including Cape Schmidt, a settlement of 5,000 across the
icepack from Vrangel Island where outside temperatures can drop to
as low as 45 below zero. As autumn set in this year, the town found
itself with no fuel to heat homes.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike producer Tatsuhiko Kobayashi, cameraman John
McGuiness and Nikita Ovsyannikov, the helicopters will not be
coming for anyone in Chukotka anytime soon. After a tour of the
region last month, Russia's Emergencies Ministry declared the
situation manageable. The regional government, which wants to build
up the local gold mining industry, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no plans to shut down towns,'' said Ivan Bagromov, a
spokesman to the region's governor, Alexander Nazarov, who plans to
travel to Chukotka this week to see how his constituents are
getting by.
</P>
<P>
   In Pevek, spirits were boosted Saturday when a Finnish tanker
loaded with 13,400 tons of fuel finally made port. The ship had
been expected in the summer, but the local government's cash
troubles because of the crisis delayed its departure from the Kola
penninsula in northwestern Russia until Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Like the film crew, who were supposed to leave Vrangel in
mid-October, the ship was delayed by early winter weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year the weather conditions were very unusual: heavy,
long cyclones, the weather was constantly bad, with powerful
blizzards,'' the film crew's Ovsyannikov told Russian NTV
television from Pevek.
</P>
<P>
   The same stormy weather left the tanker stuck in heavy ice.
There it stayed until a Russian atomic-powered ice-breaker was able
to free it.
</P>
<P>
   Now they will have fuel in Chukotka, once the fuel can be loaded
off to towns like Cape Schmidt on the beaten paths that pass for
roads there. But places that recently received shipments are
running out again. Petropavlovsk-Kamchatkatsky, a city of 300,000
and the capital of the Kamchatka penninsula, has a two-day supply
of fuel left. An local electric company official told Russian
television Tuesday that schools, kindergarten and hospitals would
be without power in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Farther up the penninsula in the Koryag region, home to 28,000,
there is not only a lack of fuel, but also medicines and qualified
doctors to stem a tuberculosis outbreak, said Tatyana Mekhed, an
aide to the region's governor.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Misnik, who heads the committee on arctic affairs in
Russia's lower house of parliament, said 10 northern and Siberian
regions, home to some 12 million people, are seriously short of
supplies this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Misnik also opposes evacuation, not because he thinks people
should live in the harsh cold and poor conditions, but because the
only places open to evacuees from Siberia are dormitories in other
poor Russian regions. When the state has tried to close towns and
move people out of the hardest-hit areas, people stay on for fear
of losing their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to close the village is made and deliveries of
food and fuel stop, but people continue to live there,'' Misnik,
himself a resident of the Kola penninsula in far northwestern
Russia, said in a recent interview. ``They tear down abandoned
houses and burn the wood for heat.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of migrant workers a legacy of a Soviet system that
first populated Siberia and the Far East with prison camps, then
tried to conquer these uninhabitable but resource-rich swaths of
land by offering better salaries and working conditions to workers
from other parts of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Misnik and others say the indigenous peoples of the far
northeast are the worst hit. In both the Chukotka and Koryag
regions, native peoples who were forced to abandon their
traditional way of life by the Soviet regime in the 1950s are now
finding it nearly impossible to live under a Russian system that
has eliminated most of the benefits of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The collective farms that took over their ancient reindeer herds
and their traditional whale- and seal-hunting grounds have
collapsed. The subsidies of the Soviet system have disappeared. And
without that, there is no way to support life there.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening to the indigenous peoples of northern Siberia
is a tragedy, but people ignore it because it's only a few thousand
people,'' said Mekhed of the Koryag region. ``But the rest of
Russia has all of our problems with just a slightly better climate.
I sincerely hope we are not a model for the future of the whole
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
