A7650 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWII-PRISONER-KAN &LR;      12-01 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-PRISONER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY GIVES DELAYED HONOR TO WWII PRISONER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LEAVENWORTH, Kan. _ In the fall of 1943, Capt. David
Beavers, a 29-year-old dentist and medical officer in World War II,
wrote to his parents: ``Now I know what Grandpa went through.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a cryptic message, intended to make it past Army censors.
But Beavers knew his parents would understand. Just as Union
soldiers had held Grandpa Charles Beavers prisoner during the Civil
War, German soldiers had held David Beavers captive for six days in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   During a surprise ceremony at Fort Leavenworth on Monday, 55
years after his imprisonment, Beavers was honored for having
endured that captivity. Wearing his original brown dress Army
uniform and choking back tears, the retired dentist from
Winston-Salem, N.C., accepted his honor humbly, thanking his
presenter before turning his attention to the 50 or so soldiers in
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who've gone before you should be very proud of
(all of you),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had received a P.O.W. medal in the mail several
years ago, Beavers' son, Maj. William Beavers, believed his
84-year-old father deserved better. He wanted his father to be
honored publicly, to receive a medal with his name on it. What
better time to do that than on the day William Beavers was being
promoted to major?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's terribly modest,'' Beavers said of his father after the
ceremony. ``So, I'm proud to get to tell the story he wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   William Beavers, who is assigned to the Battle Command Training
Program at Fort Leavenworth, learned much of that story in history
books. Although he'd known his father was held captive, he didn't
know much else. He didn't know where his father had served or much
about what he'd done.
</P>
<P>
   What he learned surprised him. His father, a dentist for the
36th Division, which grew out of the Texas National Guard, had
participated in one of the war's major operations: the invasion of
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, 1943, Beavers and thousands of Allied soldiers
stormed the beaches of Sorrento, just south of Naples. Three days
after the invasion, with his unit suffering large casualties,
Beavers was ordered to exchange his dentist's tools for those of a
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, not far from Sorrento, Beavers' battalion found
itself isolated from other troops. German forces saw this and
attacked the battalion on both its right and left flanks.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers heard the rumbling of a tank as he was digging a
foxhole. He turned and found a German soldier ordering, ``Stand
up.'' Beavers had just become one of about 500 Americans captured
that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans took some of their prisoners, including Beavers, to
a nearby school. His imprisonment, Beavers said, was one thing the
Army hadn't prepared him for. But he did know how to use his wits
to get himself out of jams. Almost immediately Beavers began faking
a limp to make his captors think he wouldn't be likely to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Sept. 18, with the sun going down, Beavers grabbed a
wad of paper, limped his way past a guard and headed to a latrine
near the school. A few minutes later, a fellow prisoner did the
same. The dark concealed them as they snuck behind some bushes. The
German soldiers, Beavers assumed, simply thought they had gone to
the bathroom, for no one followed them.
</P>
<P>
   For the next four days the two men evaded capture, hiding, on
two occasions, with sympathetic Italian hersdmen and surviving on
stale bread and raw potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   By Sept. 24 Beavers had been reunited with his division.
</P>
<P>
   His brief imprisonment didn't mark the end of Beavers' trials.
Nor was it the only event during the war that earned him honors.
Beavers also received the Silver Star and Bronze Star for risking
his life to save others. His toes suffered frostbite during the
long winter. And he was called upon several more times to abandon
his duties as a dentist to help out with surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on these events after the ceremony, William Beavers
just shook his head in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't understand or know (all this),'' he said. ``If
I hadn't got a book and started reading about it, I never would
have known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
