<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWII-FATHERS-KAN &LR;      12-01 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-FATHERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR LEFT GENERATION OF CHILDREN HUNGRY TO KNOW THEIR FATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) For decades, Chari House's memory of her father
remained in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get any warmth out of that, or see the love he
supposedly had shown me,'' House said. ``I want every little bit I
can get.''
</P>
<P>
   So she recently commissioned a friend to paint an oil portrait
of her father, based on an old black and white photograph. In
seeking to add color to sepia memories, House is like approximately
500 members of the American WWII Orphans Network (AWON), whose
fathers died in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Once discouraged from asking about their fathers' deaths, the
network's members now resolutely track down details. They overcome
red tape, the indifference or confusion of relatives and friends
and even their own ingrained reticence.
</P>
<P>
   One example is Norman Stahl, 53, a nonprofit-agency
human-resources director in Topeka, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl recently saw for the first time the morning report
prepared by the clerk of Company B, 184th Infantry, on June 22,
1945. That's the date colleagues apparently retrieved his father's
body on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   That also was three days after Stahl was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like reaching through the ages and touching my
father,'' said Stahl, who found the documents at the National
Personnel Records Center in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a concrete connection from half a world away, from
somebody who saw what happened and wrote it down.''
</P>
<P>
   As for House, 56, it was on a 1996 visit to the National
Archives in Washington that she found papers detailing how German
soldiers killed her father on Aug. 5, 1944, near Carhaix, France.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City, Kan., resident wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know what my father was like,'' said House, who
turned 2 years old Aug. 8, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother had told me how much he had loved me, but this man
couldn't be God, and he couldn't walk on water. I wanted to talk to
somebody who knew him as a regular person.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional journeys of House and Stahl are similar to those
experienced by other members of the American WWII Orphans Network,
founded in 1991 by Ann Bennett Mix, 57, a Bellingham, Wash.,
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Members sometimes convene, as they did in early November in St.
Louis, to share tips on finding documents. They also console one
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the orphans once dreamed of finding their
fathers,'' Stahl said. ``That was very common.''
</P>
<P>
   The network's members have known the occasional dramatic
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   One member used the network to locate a heart-breaking
photograph of his father, slain and face-first in the snow. Though
perhaps less dramatic, many breakthroughs are poignant.
</P>
<P>
   After finding documents, some members search out their fathers'
former colleagues. Finding them can be a mixed blessing, said Mix,
whose father died in 1945 in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   `` `We didn't get to know those new guys, and we didn't want to
know them,' '' one veteran told Mix.
</P>
<P>
   Until late 1943, the government usually passed over fathers with
children. But eventually the military drafted almost a million of
them. Often they were rushed through training.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was sent right over to Italy and brought up to the
front in the middle of the night,'' Mix said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lasted three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the American WWII Orphans Network know that meeting
their fathers' comrades can be uncomfortable. ``A lot of people
died in stupid, unglamorous ways,'' Mix said. ``It's like these men
know things that they believe you would be hurt to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   House's experience has been better. An Internet search led to
her father's executive officer, who found her father's body Aug. 5,
1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me my father didn't have to lead that platoon in, but
that he was the kind of man who wouldn't send other people to do
what he could do himself,'' House said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to hear that, because it meant what my mother had
told me had not been made up. She hadn't built him up like so many
orphan families do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Mother's Day 1997, House saw for the first time the small
leather photo wallet her father was carrying when he was killed. It
included a portrait of herself, at 18 months, sitting with her
mother. Her mother only recently volunteered the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Widows forced to fend for themselves decades before support
groups or grief counselors sometimes don't see the point in
dwelling on the unpleasantness.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people didn't get any help,'' Mix said. ``They just went
on with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't easy. Families quarreled over insurance money and
burial details. Mix's mother, for instance, decided to have her
late husband buried in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom signed the papers to leave my Dad overseas three days
before she married my stepdad,'' Mix said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family was furious. They wanted to bring him home. Because
of these fights, I was not allowed to speak to my father's family.
So I not only lost my dad, I lost a whole side of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl wants to learn if his father's name is on a memorial on
Okinawa. He wants to find the man _ or his survivors _ who wrote
his grandfather a letter in 1949, describing his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   He also is considering searching for his father's colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't taken that step, out of fear,'' he said. ``What if
there is no one out there?''
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Children of slain World War II servicemen can seek
information on the American WWII Orphans Network web site,
www.awon.org.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
