<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-DEATH-KAN &LR;      12-01 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO THIRD PARTY INVOLVED IN DEATH OF FEDERAL JUDGE AND HIS WIFE, FBI
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA and JOHN T. DAUNER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ U.S. District Judge Earl O'Connor and his
wife, Jean O'Connor, probably died in a double suicide or a
murder-suicide, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Connors each were shot once in the torso, investigators
said. Autopsies were performed, but Johnson County District
Attorney Paul Morrison said he would not announce what they
revealed until later this week. The autopsies did not reveal
anything unexpected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is get a handle on whether it's a
murder-suicide or a double suicide,'' Morrison said. ``But I think
everyone is confident that there's not a third party involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI bowed out of the case because investigators were certain
that a third person did not kill the couple. Any attack on a
federal judge falls under the FBI's jurisdiction, so federal agents
were dispatched soon after the 76-year-old judge and his
66-year-old wife were found dead Sunday in their Mission house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to make sure,'' said FBI agent Jeff Lanza. ``You
can't just take things at first glance; you have to jump through
all the investigative hoops.''
</P>
<P>
   The deaths produced sorrow and shock among judges and
administrative workers at the federal courthouse in Kansas City,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Chief U.S. District Judge Thomas Van Bebber said O'Connor was
very devoted to his wife and deeply distressed about her rapidly
failing health. He had spent the last three weeks helping care for
her.
</P>
<P>
   It never crossed anyone's mind that he was considering ending
his life, co-workers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are devastated,'' said U.S. District Judge John W.
Lungstrum.
</P>
<P>
   David B.B. Helfrey, a St. Louis defense attorney and former head
of the federal Organized Crime Strike Force in Kansas City, Mo.,
said he was shocked by the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor presided over several high-profile organized crime
cases tried by Helfrey, and the judge told friends they were among
some of his most interesting cases.
</P>
<P>
   In August, O'Connor set aside the conviction of an Overland Park
car dealer for bank fraud after Helfrey convinced the judge that
the jury was wrong and that there was no fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fairness and sense of justice is unquestioned,'' Helfrey
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Van Bebber said that some of his fondest memories of O'Connor
stemmed from the judges' Tuesday lunches, informal social affairs
to which they brought or ordered in sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor enjoyed telling World War II stories from his days as a
quartermaster officer on ammunition ships and stories about court
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got special satisfaction with the resolution of the Kansas
City, Kansas, school desegregation case,'' Van Bebber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a lawyers' judge and a judges' judge. A lawyers' judge
because he was diligent, respectful and even-handed, but in
control. A judges' judge because he was the kind we all try to
emulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tears are easy to come by in this courthouse today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
