<SLUG> BC-CONCRETE-HOUSE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING TECHNIQUES GIVE CONCRETE HOMES SOLID PROSPECTS FOR
SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENEXA, Kan. _ From the outside, the home looks like many others
along the winding streets in the Cedar Creek development _ large
and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath its sheath of stucco, however, it is unlike any of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being framed in wood, as are more than 90 percent of
the homes in this country, this $800,000 house was framed with
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that it doesn't look different than other
homes around here, that it doesn't feel like a cell,'' said Keith
Eymann, president of Ambassador Construction. Ambassador is
building the house of insulated concrete foam, a process that fills
Styrofoam blocks with concrete.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing prisonlike in this 4,700-square-foot,
French-country design home that is still under construction. It has
19-foot ceilings, a country kitchen and a master bedroom closet
that could serve as a den in some homes. Other accoutrements play
off its concrete theme, such as its concrete tile roof, stamped
concrete drive and walks, and the molded concrete tops being
fabricated for its kitchen cabinets. It also is being wired for all
of the high-tech tools and toys.
</P>
<P>
   The house is being built to introduce the Kansas City market to
what advocates of concrete homes consider their superior attributes
_ sturdiness, energy efficiency and quietness, with no sacrifice in
distinction, delicateness or style.
</P>
<P>
   Not by chance, the house is being financed by Ash Grove Cement,
one of the country's largest makers of cement, the key ingredient
in concrete. Ash Grove owns the Cedar Creek development.
</P>
<P>
   While the home is a speculative venture, built without a buyer
on hand, Charles Sunderland, an Ash Grove vice president, is
unshaken in his belief that a concrete home will sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really a demonstration home, a prototype for what we
hope is the home of the future,'' Sunderland said. ``It is a house
of the new millennium _ comfortable living with the latest
technology. We think it is the kind of house everyone would have if
they could get someone to build exactly what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   While the number of concrete homes in the United States remains
small, the homes inhabit a solid place in American building
history.
</P>
<P>
   A concrete barn built by editor Horace Greeley was converted
into a home by his daughter. Thomas Edison patented a system that
allowed an entire concrete home, including stairways and roof, to
be cast in less than a day. Of the 11 built in 1908, several
survive. Concrete construction was essential for American architect
Frank Lloyd Wright's most famous home, Fallingwater, near Mill
Creek, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such celebrated advocates, concrete construction homes
never really caught on in the United States, although they have
been popular in Europe. Of the 1.1 million new homes built last
year, about 7 percent were framed in concrete, according to figures
from trade associations. That is up from about 3 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of concrete homes think that when builders and
consumers get used to the idea of homes made from insulated
concrete foam, they will be impressed by their soundness and
sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   They say the superior insulation, tightness and wall mass of
concrete homes make them more energy efficient, cutting down on
drafts and keeping temperatures more even. The tightness of a
concrete home, paired with an air filtration system, can be a
selling point to those with respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   They point out that concrete homes are fire-resistant, can stand
up to severe weather and screen out more noise than traditional
wood-frame homes. Yet, with new construction techniques, they can
be built in any design that a wood-frame home could be built. When
covered inside with drywall and outside with any building material,
they are visually indistinguishable from wood-frame homes.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete construction will add $1 to $4 per square foot to the
cost of building a home, but that expense can be offset by lower
energy and insurance costs, Sunderland said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Donnelly, president of the National Lumber and Building
Material Dealers Association in Washington, disputes the claim that
a concrete home can stand up better in severe weather. ``If
constructed properly and fastened properly, wood-frame homes will
withstand hurricane-force winds,'' he said. ``We have proof of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly also disputes... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
