<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIT-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DOLE ADS MISUSED PUBLIC FUNDS, AUDITORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After two years of politically charged campaign
finance investigations, a federal audit released Tuesday found that
both the Clinton and Dole presidential campaigns illegally used
millions of dollars in public funds on television ads.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors recommended that the Dole campaign repay the
Treasury $17.7 million for the violations, while the Clinton
campaign should pay $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The audit is likely to have two immediate results. First, it
could put pressure on Attorney General Janet Reno to seek an
independent counsel to look into the issue by Monday, the deadline
for her decision whether to take that step. Second, with the House
Judiciary Committee expanding its impeachment probe to include
campaign finance, Democrats might well suggest that any such move
include a new look at alleged Republican abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited report, performed by auditors for the Federal
Election Commission, said both parties spent millions of dollars on
``issue ads'' that were thinly disguised efforts to boost the Dole
and Clinton campaigns. Such issue ads are supposed to be for
generic party-building purposes, not for the election of a certain
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen anything like this before,'' said Don
Simon, executive of Common Cause, after reviewing the audit. ``This
is a deliberate assault by both campaigns that resulted in truly
massive and unprecedented violations of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison to the much-publicized probe into foreign campaign
contributions and the investigation of President Clinton's
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky, Simon said, ``this is the
most important scandal that we have seen.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the campaign finance focus in the last two years
has been on alleged Democratic abuses, the report underscores that
both campaigns possibly violated the federal spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Dole campaign repayment of $17.7 million was much
higher than the Clinton campaign amount of $7.5 million because
Dole's alleged violations occurred mostly in the general election,
when the FEC requires a dollar-for-dollar repayment. For exceeding
spending limits during the primaries, the rate of repayment varies
and is often around 25 percent. In fact, the Clinton campaign
exceeded the spending limit by a higher amount than Dole, but
Clinton's violations occurred mostly during the primary season,
when the repayment requirement is lower, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended repayments will be reviewed when the FEC meets
Thursday. The six-member panel, equally divided between Democrats
and Republicans, could vote to accept or modify the proposed
penalties. The commission also could impose civil fines against the
political parties totaling tens of millions of dollars. In the
past, the commission has often rejected or modified staff
recommendations and lowered proposed repayments.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, the FEC in 1992 required repayments of $364,000
from the Bush campaign and $1.4 million from the Clinton campaign
for various offenses. Those amounts were reduced from the staff
recommendation of $1.6 million for the Bush campaign and $4 million
for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how Clinton and Bob Dole could come up with the
money to repay the Treasury since it is difficult to convince
people to contribute to campaigns after an election. Both Clinton
and Dole have said they believe the issue ads were legal and they
did not violate the law. The Democratic Party said in a statement
Tuesday the audit was based on a ``faulty and incorrect legal
analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee spokesman Clifford May predicted
the FEC would reject the audit. ``We followed all the relevant
laws,'' May said. ``These were not campaign spots. These were RNC
spots, and I think the commission will recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been questions about the use of issue ads since they
first aired in the 1996 campaign. Under a strategy developed partly
by Clinton, the Democratic National Committee ran ads that
criticized Republicans and showed pictures of Dole. The Democratic
Party said the ads fell into the generic ``issue'' category because
they did not explicitly call for the election of Clinton or the
defeat of Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans soon responded with similar ads that attacked
Clinton without calling for the election of Dole. Both the Clinton
and Dole campaigns said the ads were legal because they did not
include a reference to which candidate should be elected. But the
transparency of the ads was evident even to Dole, who said in June
1996: ``It never says that I'm running for president, though I hope
that it's fairly obvious since I'm the only one in the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The FEC audit spells out how both campaigns allegedly broke the
law in using the ads.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1996, for example, the Republican National Committee ran
an ad that said Clinton's spending on illegal immigrants went up
while wages for the typical US worker went down. In response, the
Democratic National Committee ran an ad saying Clinton had
increased border patrols to catch illegal immigrants. The audit, in
a section that referred to the DNC commercials, said the ads were
part of a ``deliberate effort to conceal the actual purpose and
strategy behind the advertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the political parties coordinated the ads with
the campaigns, and the ads sometimes were nearly identical to those
run by the campaigns, the audit said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit was released as the Justice Department and the House
Judiciary Committee are focusing on the same issue. Republicans for
months have criticized Reno for not asking for the appointment of
an independent counsel to look into whether Clinton and his aides
engaged in a broad conspiracy to violate campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee, which has been holding hearings on
whether Clinton should be impeached as a result of his relationship
with Lewinsky, voted Tuesday to issue a series of subpoenas related
to the campaign finance probe. Republicans on the committee have
said they want to learn why Reno so far has rejected advice from
FBI Director Louis Freeh and former Justice Department official
Charles LaBella that an independent counsel be named.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Fred Thompson, the Tennessee Republican who chaired
campaign finance hearings last year, said in an interview that the
audit provides one more reason for Reno to appoint an independent
counsel by Monday's deadline. While Thompson said alleged
Republican abuses should be examined as well, he stressed that
Democrats started using issue ads long before the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is Democrats started with this plan and
raised millions of dollars in their issue ads before Dole was out
of the blocks,'' Thompson said. ``If Dole engaged in that later, so
be it, but you are talking about watermelons vs. green peas in the
significance of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
