</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCRETE-HOUSE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING TECHNIQUES GIVE CONCRETE HOMES SOLID PROSPECTS FOR
SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENEXA, Kan. _ ....``We have proof of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly also disputes any claim that concrete is more
environmentally friendly than wood. ``You have all of the
environmental issues related to the cement-making process,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The energy efficiency of insulated foam concrete homes impressed
Craig Wolfe, an officer with the Kansas chapter of the Sierra Club
and a former builder of passive solar homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sierra Club is very aggressively trying to protect
old-growth forests on federal lands, and this would fall in that
category,'' Wolfe said. ``On the other side, and I am not informed
enough to answer this, but what are the resources that this system
uses and what is their impact on the environment?''
</P>
<P>
   Sunderland counters that the resources needed for concrete are
among the most abundant on Earth and that the amount of land needed
to make concrete is a fraction of that used to cut lumber.
</P>
<P>
   About six years ago, a spike in lumber prices and improvements
in the insulated concrete foam process kindled interest in the
homes, said Lionel Lemay of the Portland Cement Association.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike standard concrete blocks, which have often resulted in
homes that had the look of bunkers, the insulated forms easily can
be cut to shape a home from the simple to the complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows for features like bay windows, cantilevers and
curves,'' Lemay said. ``That is another reason people are
gravitating to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The forms used by Ash Grove are made from 17-inch-by-48-inch
Styrofoam blocks that have 2-1/2-inch thick walls and a 6-inch
interior space. The blocks have plastic webbing inside and
interlocking edges. They can be stacked, braced and filled with
steel reinforcing bars and then concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little like building with Legos,'' Sunderland said.
</P>
<P>
   The foam remains when the concrete cures, adding to air and
sound insulation. Plastic seams on the blocks allow attachment of
drywall. A hot knife is used to cut grooves in the foam for the
insertion of wiring or plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   With the cost gap between wood and concrete frame construction
narrowing, the concrete industry has begun promoting its process.
It has urged companies such as Ash Grove to build homes that could
speak to a growing interest in safe and environmentally sensitive
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Ash Grove and other members of the local Concrete Producers
Association built a small concrete home for the local Habitat for
Humanity housing program last year to demonstrate that the process
is viable for inexpensive homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that house came on the market, I would buy it,'' said
Winston Slider, executive director for Habitat for Humanity Kansas
City. ``I think we proved it is an affordable way to go for a
less-expensive house.''
</P>
<P>
   Slider said the energy efficiency of the home was amazing. He
thinks once the word gets out about the technology, consumers will
be eager to build concrete homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunderland said there had been a lot of interest in the new
Cedar Creek house and the process. Ash Grove sponsored barbecues
where about 600 architects, engineers and builders were encouraged
to poke around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the decorative touches, the house is being wired with
high-tech extras. The subdivision is wired with fiberoptic cable,
and the house will have an ISDN high-speed telecommunications line.
For show purposes, it will have at least two large-screen
televisions hooked to WebTV technology, as well as a couple of
computer terminals, all linked on an ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   Getting contractors and subcontractors to embrace concrete
construction is as important as getting consumers to buy in, Lemay
and Sunderland said.
</P>
<P>
   Subcontractors are so busy now building traditional-framed
homes, they have no incentive to learn a new technique. Eymann
enticed one of his subcontractors to take on the job, and Ash Grove
paid for the crew's two-day training on the concrete process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get it more in mainstream,'' said the cement
association's Lemay. ``We need to show people that it is available
to them and show the builder that the consumer is willing to pay
for the benefits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
