<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO ANNOUNCE NEW WATER PURITY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will travel Thursday to Newport,
R.I., to announce new federal measures to improve the quality of
drinking water and authorize the release of hundreds of millions of
dollars in loans to help states upgrade their water treatment
facilities, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations focus on eliminating the most harmful
pollutants in tap water, such as the cryptosporidium microbe, a
parasite that contaminated Milwaukee's water supply in 1993 and
sickened 400,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations are part of amendments to the Safe Drinking
Water Act, which Clinton signed into law in 1996. The measure
significantly tightened standards for clean water and authorized
billions of dollars in a revolving loan fund over seven years to
improve deteriorating water systems.
</P>
<P>
   During his brief stay, Clinton will tour the Bliss Mine Road
water purification plant in Newport and visit Fort Adams State
Park, where Narragansett Bay will serve as the backdrop as he lauds
the state for its comparatively high-quality water treatment
system.
</P>
<P>
   The president will be joined by Senator John H. Chafee, a
Republican from Rhode Island who co-authored the water act
amendments and is chairman of the Senate Environment and Public
Works Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The measure requires local water authorities for the first time
to annually disclose what chemicals and bacteria are in drinking
water and to give public notice within 24 hours of discovering a
dangerous contaminant in the water system. The measure also creates
a program to fight pollution at its source by keeping streams and
rivers clean and improving facilities that treat water before it
comes out of the tap.
</P>
<P>
   Citing data from the Centers for Disease Control, Chafee said
that about 900,000 people get ill each year from parasites such as
cryptosporidium, which causes most people to suffer cramps and
intestinal disorders. He said about 900 annually die from the
illness, particularly those with AIDS and weak immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   The parasite is commonly found in lakes and rivers, especially
if the water has been contaminated with sewage or animal wastes.
Often it enters the water system during or after stormy weather
when sewers overflow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
