<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLUNDERED-ART-BOS &LR;      12-01 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUNDERED-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAZI RECORDS SHOW THEFT OF MONET, FAMILY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The descendants of French Jewish art collector Paul
Rosenberg have more than an old family photo to prove that a Monet
waterlily now on loan to the Boston Museum of Fine Arts was looted
by the Nazis in 1940. They also have records that the Nazis
dutifully catalogued his substantial art collection after
confiscating it, the Boston Globe learned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That information emerged after the director of France's national
museum system, which has had the painting for more than a half
century, said that Rosenberg's descendants must prove that the
painting, ``Water Lilies 1904,'' was not sold by Rosenberg rather
than plundered by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear if it was looted or sold,'' Francoise Cachin,
who heads the museum system, said in an interview Tuesday. It is
clear, she acknowledged, that the painting was in Rosenberg's
collection before the war.
</P>
<P>
   But the descendants, some of whom live in the United States, say
they have documents from Nazi files to support their claim. The
Nazis, obsessive about keeping documentation of even their most
heinous crimes, catalogued each of the looted paintings, including
the Monet that is in Boston for an exhibition that runs until Dec.
27.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosenberg family Tuesday notified Cachin's office in Paris
of their intent to claim the artwork, one of 48 signature
waterlilies that Monet did.
</P>
<P>
   Documentation that the painting was looted from Rosenberg and
was then requisitioned for the wartime collection of Nazi Foreign
Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop was first reported Monday by The
Globe. The MFA borrowed the work from the French museum at Caen in
Normandy, knowing it was one of nearly 2,000 French artworks that
were recovered from Germany after the war, but whose ownership was
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Cachin spoke as the State Department opened a three-day,
45-nation summit on how to deal with the growing number of claims
for Holocaust-era assets, including art. But the US government made
it clear that the art claims of Holocaust victims must be balanced
against the need for a stable art market _ a signal that American
museums seeking protection against a rash of claims have found a
sympathetic ear at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   And though the conferees are deliberating in private, Lord
Greville Janner, a member of the British delegation, created
discomfort during a luncheon speech to the conference when he
challenged the US view that the conference will be the final
chapter on the asset issue.
</P>
<P>
   Janner, who is chairman of Britain's Holocaust Education Trust,
said there must be a follow-up conference a year from now to ensure
that separate commissions established in many countries _ including
one that President Clinton named on Monday _ will be held
accountable for opening archives and restituting art and other
plundered assets.
</P>
<P>
   Janner's remarks met with disapproval even within his own
delegation. One British conferee, who spoke on condition that his
name not be mentioned, said US State Department officials had
called Janner daily since last week in efforts to dissuade him from
issuing his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not what the Americans wanted, or wanted said. They
want this conference to end the process,'' the conferee said,
adding that the US has been under pressure from its European
allies, especially Germany, to find quick closure to the two years
of international turmoil over issues like Nazi gold and looted art.
</P>
<P>
   It was Janner who was resposible for pushing successfully for
last December's conference in London on gold the Nazis looted in
occupied Europe. And in an interview last week, the former Labor MP
said he also planned to challenge the Vatican to open up its
wartime archives to see what assets, if any, the Holy See might
have received during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of the conference, Stuart Eizenstat, the
undersecretary of state for economic, business and agricultural
affairs, opened the conference with public remarks in which he
stopped short of calling for the restitution of art to victims of
the looting, expressing approval for ``a just and fair resolution
of ownership claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said that families that lost art to the Nazis must
have a ``full opportunity to find and reclaim'' those objects. But
in remarks that were being closely dissected in art circles, he
also called for a ``speedier and far less confrontational
resolution to the problem of looted art. ... The international art
market must be open, stable, free of uncertainty that it might be
trading in works that are tainted by Nazi looting.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Rosenberg perspective, if not from Cachin's, there is
no uncertainty to the Monet claim.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Tuesday, Elisabeth Rosenberg Clark,
speaking for the family, said the late colllector/dealer's family
has no desire to interfere with the exhibition of the painting at
the MFA. The 85 Monets in the exhibition, ``Monet in the 20th
Century,'' are scheduled to move to the Royal Academy of Art in
London at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But Cachin, the French museum director, said the Monet will be
returned to Paris after the Boston exhibition, where the claim will
be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   By the family's account, the claim is a strong one. In September
1940, just after Rosenberg had fled southern France to Portugal,
and eventually to New York, Hitler's art-looting units descended
upon two caches of his valuable collection, 162 paintings in a bank
vault in Libourne in the south of France and scores more paintings
at a family home in Bordeaux. The Monet waterlily was at the
Bordeaux home.
</P>
<P>
   At the bank, Nazi officials even left a receipt for the French
bankers, listing each of the 162 paintings. At the home, they
simply carted off the artworks. But all the artworks were trucked
to the Jeu de Paume, a Paris museum. It was there that the ERR _ an
acronym for the art-looting unit _ catalogued each of Rosenberg's
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The family believes that it was at the Jeu de Paume where von
Ribbentrop, along with other top Nazis, including Field Marshal
Hermann Goering, took their pick of the looted collections for
their own homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   When the painting was repatriated after the war, French
officials failed to learn its connection to Rosenberg, even though
the French government's own 1947 list of missing artworks lists the
painting, notes Rosenberg's ownership and even cites dimensions
that are identical to the Monet. Despite those clues, the painting
was eventually shunted off to Caen, where it has been in the
collection since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In October, after the family asked the Art Loss Register to help
it locate 58 missing artworks, a Register official, Sarah Jackson,
took the family photo to the Witt Art Library in London. There, she
compared it to photos of Monet's waterlilies. In just under three
hours, Jackson said Tuesday, she matched the photo to the artwork
in the custody of the Caen museum.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after the Globe published an article about the
painting's uncertain ownership and an accompanying photo, Jonathan
Petropoulos, a historian at Loyola College in Baltimore, matched it
to a photo of von Ribbentrop's Monet that is included in his book,
``Art as Politics in the Third Reich.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
