<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE SPORTS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These sports stories for release Wednesday, December 2, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TENN-DEFENSE _ ATLANTA _ The Tennessee defense has been one
of the best in the SEC and nation this season and the Vols expect
to face a stiff challenge from Mississippi State's bruising running
game in Saturday's SEC championship game in Atlanta. The leader of
the unit has been senior Al Wilson, who has a habit of improving
his level of play in the big games. (Wilkinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-MSTATE _ ATLANTA _ Mississippi State running back James
Johnson has taken an interesting route to the SEC championship
game. Despite a standout high school career in Mobile, Ala.,
Johnson wasn't heavily recruited and spent one year in the Navy.
Johnson later resumed his football career at East Mississippi
Community College, playing there for two seasons, before arriving
at Mississippi State. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HUMMER-COLUMN _ On Randy Moss. (Hummer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TEXASAM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ How much did the lost to Texas
hurt the Aggies? Is there a hangover from losing to an arch rival?
There's little time to sulk with the Big 12 Championship on
Saturday. (Riggs, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-NUHN-COLUMN _ The bowl championship series is a fraud.
(Nuhn, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-COACHES _ Auburn's hiring of former Mississippi coach Tommy
Tuberville appears to be the first of several coaching changes
expected over the next few weeks at Southern schools. Florida
defensive coordinator Bob Stoops in expected to become the new
coach at Oklahoma, Tulane coach Tommy Bowden has been courted by
Clemson and Tennessee defensive coordinator David Cutcliffe appears
to be the leading candidate at Mississippi. Georgia's Jim Donnan
and Tech's George O'Leary have also been linked to job openings,
although both are expected to remain at their schools. For the
first time in many years, several Southern schools are looking for
coaches. There are currently two openings in the ACC and SEC.
(Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-REFS _ The NFL employs lawyers, doctors, a longshoreman and
businessmen as its officials each Sunday. Is there an optometrist
in the house? Questionable-to-bad calls are a weekly occurrence
this season. So why doesn't the league have full-time officials
spending all week studying the intricacies of, say, pass
interference? Jimmy Johnson isn't alone in his concern about
officiating, especially this week. The crew for Sunday's Miami game
at Oakland is the same that all but handed New England a victory
over Buffalo with the Hail Mary penalty. (Woods, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DOLPHINS _ The spotlight in this Sunday's Dolphins-Raiders
game will be on the offensive corrdinators, Miami's Kippy Brown and
the Raiders' Gary Stevens, the man Brown replaced in Miami.
(Skolnick, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS _ ATLANTA _ Falcons pass defense, ranked last in the
NFL several weeks ago, has improved dramatically. Ray Buchanan is
leading the charge. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LOCKOUT _ Short update on lack of progress in NBA labor
dispute. Players miss second round of paychecks. (Denberg, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-CLASSIC _ ATLANTA _ Press conference featuring Georgia coach
Ron Jirsa and Georgia Tech coach Bobby Cremins advancing the Delta
Air Lines Classic for Kids doubleheader at the Georgia Dome Dec.
19. Georgia meets Fresno State and Georgia Tech faces Kentucky.
(Arey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-DEERSEASON _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Wildlife officers in Ohio had
their busiest day of the year Monday, the first day of Ohio's deer
gun hunting season. The season, which might draw half a million
hunters statewide, ends Saturday in all parts of Ohio except the
southeastern portion, which gets one extra day, Sunday. (Morris,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
