<SLUG> BC-FAT-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY LINKS WAIST SIZE, HEALTH RISKS IN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not really overweight? That doesn't avoid the risk of too much
fat in the wrong place, judging from the largest study to date on
how fat distribution affects health.
</P>
<P>
   Women whose waists measure more than 30 inches or whose waist
and hip measurements are nearly the same have double or triple the
risk of heart disease compared to those with smaller waists, even
if their overall weight is not excessive, according to a study
published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The level of risk is comparable to the danger conferred by such
established factors as high cholesterol, high blood pressure,
cigarette smoking, or diabetes, the authors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about shape, not necessarily weight,'' said Dr.
Kathryn M. Rexrode of Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, the
study's leader.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time studies have suggested that ample girth
_ and especially a high waist-to-hip ratio, meaning the two
measurements are close together _ are independent risk factors for
heart disease. Research in men dating back more than 40 years, and
in women to 1984, has hinted that, when it comes to shape, an
``apple'' profile is more hazardous than a ``pear.''
</P>
<P>
   The news in the current study, which appears in the current
Journal of the American Medical Association, is that the risk of a
large waistline is so high, and that it affects even those who
would not be considered obese by conventional weight-to-height
standards. It also adds considerably to the data on this risk
factor among women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The association is stronger than I expected to find,'' Rexrode
said Tuesday. ``A 3-fold higher risk is higher than a lot of other
risk factors that get a lot of attention in the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to take the new results seriously is that they
come from the Nurses Health Study, a Boston-based project that has
followed nearly 122,000 American nurses for 22 years. In this
study, Rexrode and her colleagues examined the incidence of heart
attacks and cardiovascular deaths among nearly 45,000 women who
provided regular reports on their waist and hip measurements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier studies were much smaller and less sophisticated,''
said Dr. Richard Karas, director of the Women's Heart Center at New
England Medical Center. ``This study gives us more confidence that
an increase in abdominal girth is an independent risk factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexrode and her colleagues found that women whose waist-to-hip
ratio was 0.88 or higher had more than a three-fold higher risk of
a heart attack or death from heart disease over an eight-year
period, compared to women with a ratio of 0.72 or less. (A woman
with a 30-inch waist and 34-inch hips has a 0.88 ratio.)
</P>
<P>
   Although a waist measurement of 30 inches was associated with a
two-fold higher risk of heart disease, and a waistline of 38 inches
with a three-fold risk, the researchers found that the waist-to-hip
ratio was a somewhat more reliable measure of heart disease risk.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of excess abdominal fat seemed to be independent of
other risk factors, such as diabetes, high blood pressure, and high
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are not sure why abdominal fat poses a higher risk
than fat elsewhere. ``All fat is not the same,'' Karas said. ``It's
derived from different cell types as the body develops and may
actually have different physiology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexrode said that ``abdominal fat seems metabolically more
active'' and its metabolic byproducts have a greater effect on the
amount of cholesterol in the blood, on circulating insulin, and on
the body's resistance to insulin.
</P>
<P>
   She said doctors should be more aggressive about advising diet
and exercise for an individual with a high waist-to-hip ratio, and
also about lowering other cardiovascular risk factors when
individuals fail to shed abdominal fat despite dieting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
