<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-HISTORY-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER-HISTORY-2TAKES 
 
EXXON, MOBIL REUNITE WITH A LONG HISTORY OF SUCCESSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG HASSELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eighty-seven years after the U.S. Supreme Court busted John D.
Rockefeller's fearsome oil empire into 34 separate pieces, the two
largest chunks are reuniting to form the largest oil company in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp. _ known earlier in their existence
as Standard Oil of New Jersey and Standard Oil of New York,
respectively _ have negotiated a $75.6 billion deal that will
create a corporate behemoth with 123,000 employees and $200 billion
in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are historic twins that were separated early in life,''
said Ron Chernow, autor of ``Titan,'' a critically acclaimed
Rockefeller biography. ``This is an extraordinary event.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eight decades since their separation, the ``twins'' have
pursued different paths. And in that time, they have developed
distinct personalities.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing clue can be found in their corporate histories.
``A Brief History of Mobil Corporation'' does not include the words
``Standard Oil'' until the 12th paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   As if to distance itself from the old man's ghost, it spends
more than a page talking about Matthew Ewing, the man who founded
Vacuum Oil Co. A maker of kerosene and lubricants, Vacuum was
successful, but nothing on the order of Standard Oil, which bought
the company in 1879. Rockefeller made Vacuum a part of Standard Oil
of New York and set it on course to being the corporate giant it is
today.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Mobil, Exxon makes no bones about its link to
Rockefeller. ``Standard Oil'' is in the first sentence of ``A Brief
Informal History of the Exxon Corporation.'' On the first page
alone, the words ``Standard'' or ``Rockefeller'' appear a dozen
times.
</P>
<P>
   The Exxon history tells how the Supreme Court ruled in 1911 that
the various Standard Oil companies were a centrally controlled,
illegal monopoly. Rockefeller's empire was dismantled and the
separate companies became truly independent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surviving piece by far was Standard Oil of New
Jersey _ now Exxon. At the moment of the breakup, it constituted 43
percent of the old company. The second biggest piece, Standard Oil
of New York, was a mere 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup made Jersey Standard the biggest and wealthiest oil
company in the world. As its corporate history implies, the company
did not set out to shatter the mold that made it such a force to be
reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon is a chip off the old block,'' Chernow said. ``Over its
history, Exxon has been very conservative, disciplined, secretive
and methodical _ just like Rockefeller himself.''
</P>
<P>
   One of lingering personality traits of the company, which
changed its name to Exxon in 1972, is an appetite for being the
biggest and most powerful company in the oil business.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch/Shell has leapfrogged Exxon as the world's biggest
oil company. But when it completes the purchase of Mobil, Exxon
will again stand atop the world's energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon enjoyed being No. 1 in the world,'' said Carol
Freedenthal, principal of the energy consulting firm Jofree Corp.
``They are used to being No. 1. I am sure they didn't like being
No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon also has a long-standing reputation for being
conservative. The company has followed other, more adventurous
companies into deepwater exploration. It avoided places like
Indonesia because of the political turmoil and geological gambles
involved. But Exxon has extensive exploration ventures in Russia, a
risky place if ever there were one, proving no oil company can
explore for oil and be totally risk averse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon is very conservative. It doesn't like to take chances,''
Freedenthal said. ``Big Oil has always been conservative. Part of
their conservatism is that old fear of antitrust proceedings. They
are afraid the government will take notice and change the
regulations. They want to avoid government intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   As the biggest U.S. oil company, and therefore a prime target
for regulatory action, there are advantages to avoiding a
free-wheeling, swashbuckling reputation. But being secretive has
come back to haunt Exxon.
</P>
<P>
   When the Exxon Valdez spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil
in Alaska's Prince William Sound in 1989, the sight of pristine
coastlines and sea animals coated in black goo shocked the world.
For days, while the story played on front pages around the world,
Exxon's chief executive made no public appearance to express his
remorse. The company seemed to hide behind a wall of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valdez was a screw-up for Exxon because they did not publicly
come out and face the music,'' Freedenthal said.``They took a
legalistic approach, and it hurt them badly.''
</P>
<P>
   When Houston lawyer Dick Miller was representing Exxon in some
lawsuits with insurance companies concerning the Valdez debacle, he
asked to talk to the company's chief executive. Company officials
refused, something Miller has never encountered at any other
company, large or small. Disgusted at the bureaucratic
interference, the high-powered attorney quit in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his experience, Miller isn't sure his anecdote proves
anything about Exxon. ``I don't think they are all that much
different from other companies, except they are bigger and have
more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Vestiges of the company's secretive nature have remained in the
1990s, even after the lessons of Valdez. When a spokesman was
queried in 1994 about a company plan to sell oil leases in the
southern United States, she replied, ``If we didn't put a press
release out about it, it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While Exxon may struggle to shake off some of the limitations
imposed by its past, it has brilliantly exploited the advantages of
its birthright. Exxon has never shied away from using its bulk and
its wealth to its utmost advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon is the best technical company in the industry. They have
been since the 1880s,'' said Joseph Pratt, Cullen Professor of
History and Business at the University of Houston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
