<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TENN-DEFENSE     12-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-DEFENSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols regain the soul of their defense
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ On the field or in your face, Al Wilson is as
straightforward as his name. Yes, he's feeling much better. After
missing most of the Kentucky game and sitting out Saturday at
Vanderbilt, Wilson's pulled groin has healed nicely. So this
Saturday night, he'll be comfortably back on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not 100 percent,'' said Wilson, the senior middle
linebacker and soul of top-ranked Tennessee. ``But who knows? When
my adrenalin gets flowing in the Georgia Dome, I might not feel a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Mississippi State will feel surely something _ pain. Al
Wilson on an adrenalin jag is a sure-fire pain in the backfield. As
it is, ``He's all over the field, making plays,'' said Mississippi
State coach Jackie Sherrill, whose Bulldogs must contend with
Wilson and the rest of Tennessee's opportunistic defense in the SEC
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al does play the game like you want it to be played,'' UT
coach Phillip Fulmer said.''You're concerned about him being a
little rusty, not having played in two weeks. But we want to have
our most valuable and intense player on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   How valuable? Although just 6-feet, 226 pounds and despite
missing three games, Wilson is second among the Vols with 73
tackles, and has four sacks and 17 of what UT calls ``big plays.''
He had 13 tackles in the opener at Syracuse and 12 in the epic win
over Florida in which Wilson caused a school-record three fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   How intense? ``Of our four captains, he's by far and away the
most emotional (and) vocal of the bunch,'' Fulmer said. The coach
said he had to talk to his linebacker ``about how to lead. You
don't always have to berate. One thing people don't know is Al is a
very devout, Christian man. You wouldn't always know that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you wouldn't. Not watching Wilson roam and terrorize the
line of scrimmage _ and occasionally, his own sideline. ``He's got
that linebacker's mentality. He's like Jack Reynolds,'' Fulmer
said, referring to ``Hacksaw'' Reynolds, who played with Fulmer at
UT before starring in the NFL. ``One of the nicest guys you'll ever
meet, but he would fight you at the drop of a hat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al's very intense,'' Tennessee defensive coordinator John
Chavis said. ``I don't know if I've ever been around anyone more
competitive. He likes to compete, to be successful. He likes his
teammates to be succcessful, too. He's a great leader, doesn't mind
getting on his teammates. If he's calling on them, he's calling on
himself, too. They know it's not (directed) against them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just the type of guy, I want to make every play out
there,'' Wilson said. ``If I can't, I want to be around the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   He's around it even more this season since being moved from
outside linebacker to the middle with the departures of pass
rushers Leonard Little and Jonathan Brown. Fulmer said Wilson is
just as comfortable in the middle, and far more productive.
</P>
<P>
   But then, he's had help. A veteran, deep defensive line in which
Chavis rotates his ends and tackles. A surprisingly effective
secondary. And two superb linebackers on Wilson's flanks _ Raynoch
Thompson, UT's leading tackler who sat out last week with a
sprained ankle but will play Saturday, and Eric Westmoreland, whose
vicious hit led to a fumble return for a touchdown. Chavis calls
the three linebackers ``probably the best group we've had
overall.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill says he thinks it's Tennessee's best overall defense,
especially up front. ``They bring people in, it doesn't make a
difference,'' he said. ``They're still good.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially the man in the middle, who can't wait to get back in
the midst of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to pick up where I left off,'' Wilson said. ``I don't
want to go out and try to be Superman. Just make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
