<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-HISTORY-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER-HISTORY-2NDTAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  UNDATED: of Houston. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carol Freedenthal became familiar with Exxon when he worked at
Superior Oil, an independent Houston oil company that Mobil snapped
up in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Exxon, everything was first class. They paid their people
20 percent above the industry norm,'' Freedenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   When Superior was trying to figure out the commercial potential
of shale, it put one engineer on the project. Exxon assigned five
or six groups _ about 30 people in all _ to undertake the same
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always had enough people to do what they wanted to do,''
Freedenthal said. ``They could spend money other companies never
even dreamed about.''
</P>
<P>
   Another example of the company's readiness to do the big deal
was Jersey Standard's decision in 1919 to buy half ownership of
Houston-based Humble Oil, one of the biggest and best oil companies
to emerge from Texas. Standard later bought Humble lock, stock and
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Named after the Humble oil field, the company was founded by men
whose names became part of the fabric of Houston. They include
Sterling, Fondren, Wiess, Blaffer, Farish and Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humble had an incredibly talented group of executives,'' Pratt
said. ``One of them, William Farish, went on to run the entire
company. Humble is one of the great success stories of an acquired
company that did well.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a Humble-ARCO joint venture that struck paydirt in Alaska
in 1967. The Prudhoe Bay field they discovered was the largest ever
found in North America.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Humble purchase, the domestic operating company
known as Exxon U.S.A. is now based in Houston. Exxon employs 12,824
people in the Houston area, including 4,200 workers in its Baytown
refinery. Exxon also has scads of filling stations here and often
uses Houston as a testing ground for some of its retail
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Does the successful assimilation of Humble years ago indicate
Exxon will be able or willing to share power with its new brethren
from Mobil? Pratt isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon is very confident. Exxon is very insular. It raises its
executives from within, and it is immune to new management
theories,'' Pratt said. ``It is hard to imagine Exxon will do
anything other than absorb Mobil and go on its merry way.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mobil is clearly outsized by Exxon, those who have worked
with Mobil describe it as a hard-nosed company that can hold its
own in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to buying Superior Oil in the early 1980s, Mobil became
highly annoyed with the Houston company's habit of raiding rivals
to lure away talented workers. To stop the practice, Mobil sued. To
defend itself, Superior hired Dick Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a bunch of tough guys,'' Miller said of Mobil. ``If
they are in a negotiation, they will hold their own.'' The case was
eventually dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   When Mobil bought Superior several years later, it was gunning
for the company's huge stockpiles _ oil and gas reserves totalling
1 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobil has always been crude short. Almost everything they've
done since the beginning has had an element of that,'' Pratt said.
``Superior had a reputation as a great crude finder.''
</P>
<P>
   Within five years of the takeover, few Superior people were left
at Mobil, said Freedenthal, who accepted a severance package and
left Mobil a few years after the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobil knew what it wanted. It wanted those crude reserves, not
Superior's people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another noteable example of Mobil's combativeness was its war
with the press during the 1970s and 1980s. Then-president William
P. Tavoulareas sued the Washington Post and declared, ``There is
one law for the Post, and the other gods of the media, and another
law for other Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's feisty public relations man in those days, Herbert
Schmertz, also made a name for himself with his abrasive style.
Under his guidance, Mobil withdrew its advertising from newspapers
and television stations the company regarded as unfair. The company
also refused to grant interviews, opting instead to buy space in
news publications and publish its viewpoint with a series of
``editorials.'' Along with conservative commentator William Novak,
Schmertz wrote a book about his combative philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   While Mobil put up its dukes at home, it aggressively pursued
oil exploration abroad. It became the first U.S. company to drill
off the shores of Vietnam since the the end of the Vietnam War in
1975. Mobil also jumped into volatile Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobil has been more of a risk-taker in the business sense,''
Freedenthal said. ``It has a street-fighter's personality.''
</P>
<P>
   While some risks have paid off, others have cratered. The worst
was its ill-fated purchase of the Montgomery Ward department store
chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fiasco of the first order,'' Freedenthal said. ``They
knew nothing about how to run a consumer chain like Montgomery
Ward.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to evaluate the performance of Exxon and Mobil, former
Baker Hughes Vice President Ike Kerridge gives the thumbs up to
Exxon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobil is not an equal, in my opinion,'' said Kerridge, who
worked in the oil-field service business for 40 years. ``Exxon has
always had the top people. Look at their consecutive earnings
records and return on equity. It's among the best of the big U.S.
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Reunited, Exxon Mobil promises to be a powerful force in the oil
business. But the deal does not represent a return the age of
robber barons. Rather, it underscores how much the oil business has
changed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the Exxon-Mobil combination will control an
estimated 21 percent of the U.S. gasoline market. At the height of
his power, Rockefeller controlled 90 percent of the nation's
refining capacity.
</P>
<P>
   While America loves a winner, few men have been as hated as
Rockefeller. His ruthless business practices _ he not only forced
railroads to give him rebates on his shipments, but he also got
kickbacks for the shipments made by his rivals _ stirred national
outrage. His monopoly became popularly known as ``the Octopus.''
</P>
<P>
   A merger of this magnitude would have been utterly unthinkable
as recently as 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of putting pieces of Standard Oil back together was
taboo,'' author Chernow said.
</P>
<P>
   But the oil industry is facing lean times. Crude oil prices are
in the tank, and several energy companies have recently announced
sizeable layoffs in their work forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the oil companies seem so weakened,'' Chernow said,
``they don't inspire fear the way they used to.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
