<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COACHES     12-01 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COACHES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College coaching carousel: Out with the old, in with the new
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Oklahoma and Clemson could be the big winners, while
Florida, Tennessee and Tulane stand to be losers in college
football's coaching carousel, which hit full swing this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the regular season doesn't end until after this
weekend's slate of six games, nearly a dozen schools already will
have new coaches next year. Five of those programs _ Auburn,
Clemson, Duke, Mississippi and South Carolina _ are in the ACC or
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nature of the game,'' ESPN college football analyst
Lee Corso said. ``It happens in corporate America all the time. If
you don't produce the expectations imposed upon you by the higher
authorities, they're going to make a change. It's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss, which lost fourth-year coach Tommy Tuberville to
Auburn on Nov. 28, is expected to name Tennessee offensive
coordinator David Cutcliffe as its coach today during an 11 a.m.
news conference. Cutcliffe, 44, interviewed with Rebels athletics
director John Shafer on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cutcliffe, who will coach in Saturday's SEC championship game
against No. 23 Mississippi State in the Georgia Dome, refused to
comment Tuesday whether he would remain on the UT staff for the
team's bowl game. Cutcliffe, an assistant coach at Tennessee since
1983, was promoted to offensive coordinator when Phillip Fulmer was
named the Vols' head coach in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In that capacity, Cutcliffe tutored quarterbacksAndy Kelly,
Heath Shuler and All-American Peyton Manning, as well as current
starter Tee Martin. Vols running backs coach Randy Sanders could be
promoted to coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, which fired John Blake on Nov. 22 after three losing
seasons in a row, landed Florida defensive coordinator Bob Stoops
as its coach on Tuesday. Stoops, 38, helped rebuild the Kansas
State program as defensive coordinator, then put bite in the
Florida defense, which ranked in the top 15 nationally each of his
three seasons in Gainesville. Stoops, given a five-year contract
worth $700,000 annually, will begin his duties immediately; he also
had been a candidate to replace Hayden Fry at Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not shy away from the expectations here at Oklahoma,''
Stoops said. ``In fact, I will embrace them. I know we'll operate
with no excuses. ... Oklahoma was a very easy decision. I've been
talking about this job with so many coaches for many years, that
I've thought this was always a very special job.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clemson and South Carolina both could be close to
ending their searches. Tulane coach Tommy Bowden toured the Clemson
campus on Monday and could make an announcement about his future
today, according to Tulane assistant athletics director Scott
Stricklin.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, who guided the Green Wave to an improbable 11-0 record
this season and a berth in the Liberty Bowl, is the top candidate
to replace Tommy West, fired after a 3-8 year. Bowden is mulling an
$800,000 offer from Clemson, which reportedly was matched by
Tulane. Bowden's current contract with the Green Wave has a
$750,000 buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia (S.C.) State reported Tuesday that South Carolina
has offered former Notre Dame coach Lou Holtz $1 million a year to
take over its struggling program. The newspaper said that Holtz met
with Carolina athletics director Mike McGee on Sunday night. Holtz,
61, retired after the 1996 season, in which he led the Fighting
Irish to an 8-3 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer, who met with both Clemson and
South Carolina, withdrew his name Tuesday after receiving a new
contract from the Hokies.
</P>
<P>
   Florida could be affected by other coaching changes. Gators
assistant offensive coordinator/running backs coach Carl Franks
appears to be the top candidate at Duke, where Fred Goldsmith was
fired Monday after four losing seasons in a row. Franks, an
assistant at Florida since 1990, played running back and tight end
for the Blue Devils, 1979-82.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut coach Skip Holtz and Marshall coach Bob Pruett also
have been mentioned as candidates at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia offensive line coach Chris Scelfo, who already has
interviewed for the vacancy at Southwest Louisiana, could be a top
choice at Northeast Louisiana, where he played center, 1981-84, and
served two years as an assistant coach. The Indians fired coach Ed
Zaunbrecher on Monday after he failed to earn a winning record in
five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
