</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CLASSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fresno, 'Cats Delta foes for Dogs, Jackets
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's Ron Jirsa and Georgia Tech's Bobby Cremins
got together Tuesday morning to promote the 1998 Delta Air Lines
Classic For Kids. The Bulldogs will open the tournament at 5 p.m.
Dec. 19 against Jerry Tarkanian's Fresno State team, and then the
Yellow Jackets will take on defending national champion Kentucky at
7:30 in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The one-day event, which benefits the Scottish Rite Children's
Medical Center and Camp Twin Lakes, is expected to draw more than
20,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia, it will be a rematch with the Bulldogs from Fresno
State, whom they beat 95-79 in the third-place game of the NIT in
March. Georgia Tech lost to Kentucky 85-71 in Lexington, Ky., last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fresno State is a great opponent with a legendary coach and
very athletic players,'' Jirsa said. ``But don't keep bringing up
that we beat them last year. Our team is playing pretty well right
now. Although we've got five seniors, we've got a sophomore center
(Robb Dryden) who hasn't had a great deal of experience, and our
top scorer (Jumaine Jones) is a sophomore.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins has been the driving force in bringing major programs to
play in the Atlanta event over the years and keeping the tournament
going when it went through sponsorship changes. ``If Bobby Cremins
hadn't been here, I can tell you that there would be no
tournament,'' said Shelton Stevens of the Scottish Rite Hospital.
``He has taken it on his shoulders and carried it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our in-state players to stay home,'' Cremins said.
``We want to bring big-time basketball to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins, whose team is 4-1, said he was pleased with its showing
in the Big Island Tournanent, where the Jackets beat New Orleans
and West Virginia before losing to No. 16 Washington in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of circling the wagons,'' he said. ``We've got one
more game left until we get (7-foot-1 Indiana transfer) Jason
Collier eligible. Then we've got help coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
