</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA talks resuming to clean slate on issues
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After two weeks of finger-pointing, the NBA and the
NBA Players Association are going back into full session Thursday
with an open docket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is back on the table,'' NBA spokesman Brian
McIntyre said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The union said Monday it would have no contact with the league
until commissioner David Stern phoned union chief Billy Hunter, but
McIntyre said he did not know which side initiated conversations
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they're meeting is enough,'' McIntyre said.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides will back away from decisions that became
contentious after a marathon negotiating session Nov. 20.
Apparently there were misunderstandings over issues that involve
the timing of free-agent signings and escrow proposals. So positive
was the session that Hawks center and executive committee member
Dikembe Mutombo cheerfully said he expected to be playing after New
Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes were dashed when the league canceled last Saturday's
bargaining session, and the league's chief legal officer, Jeffrey
Mishkin, pointed to an inflexible stance by the union. Hunter made
similar remarks about the league.
</P>
<P>
   The principal issue that stands between the parties, and hinders
an agreement, is the percentage of income that will go to the
players. The union is at 57 percent, the league reportedly at 52
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But there also is sharp disagreement on how an escrow system
would work and on the league's refusal to grant a salary-cap
exemption for teams that exceed it to sign outside free agents so
they can re-sign their own.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
