<SLUG> BC-FBC-MSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    J.J. a limited factor in Miss. State title run
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STARKVILLE, Miss. _ Being ``on the run'' with James Johnson
isn't only a nifty slogan that describes his offensive exploits
this season for Mississippi State; lately, it's the only way to
catch up with him off the field as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the talented senior tailback doesn't suit up for
practice, as was the case on Tuesday, the SEC's leading rusher
keeps a frenetic pace in street clothes and sneakers. He moves
between athletics department offices and football practice
facilities like a man late for a team meeting, which he is, pausing
just long enough to explain how his teammates won their last two
regular-season games _ clinching the SEC West title _ largely
without him.
</P>
<P>
   And how, despite being underdogs against top-ranked Tennessee in
Saturday's SEC championship game, they can confound the naysayers
who don't think they stand much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see my team win without me was a great feeling,'' he said.
``They've done it before, so why can't they do it again?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose playing status is questionable because of groin
and shoulder injuries, has been forced to slow himself down the
last two weeks, although they have been the biggest for Mississippi
State football in years. He was as animated as anyone in maroon on
Thanksgiving night after the Bulldogs capped their SEC West title
with a victory over Mississippi, a game in which he played little
but scored two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm day-to-day right now, but I can't let myself get
frustrated about it,'' Johnson said. ``I've had to learn how to
pick myself up. I'm not going to hold my head down about it. We've
got some guys on this team who are able to get a lot of things done
without me, and I'm going to be pulling for them whether or not I
play a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation to push himself was too great over the weekend.
Against the wishes of his coaches and trainers, Johnson did some
independent running Saturday and Sunday just to stay loose and
discovered that a bruise had developed near the pulled groin
muscle. An MRI test Monday was negative, but he might be held out
of practice again today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset that he did that, but that's J.J.,'' head coach
Jackie Sherrill said. ``He really's been fighting to play.
Sometimes, he fights the trainers to get out there. The groin looks
like it's healing, but how much he'll be able to play is still a
question right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He already has become MSU's single-season rushing leader with
1,369 yards, and had a single-game high of 237 against Alabama that
propeled the Bulldogs' late-season charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the top echelon of running backs in the country,''
Sherrill said. ``When he steps out there, he produces. We've got
backs who are capable, but they're not J.J.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 24, fits the MSU profile of a late-budding star. After
graduating from high school in Mobile, where he played street
football with Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin, he spent a year in
the Navy, then moved on to East Mississippi Junior College, just a
short drive from the MSU campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was meant to play football,'' he said. ``I got a lot
out of being in the Navy, but I wanted to get on with my career.''
</P>
<P>
   In just two seasons with the Bulldogs, the 6-foot-2, 232-pounder
has jumped into fourth place among career rushing leaders and
figures to draw plenty of interest from NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   How he finishes his college career is paramount, for the moment,
and his teammates play down Johnson's assertions that they don't
need more from him than what they've gotten the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he wasn't out there, we learned how to do some other
things and won some big games that way,'' quarterback Wayne Madkin
said. ``But we're still going to need him bad out there on
Saturday. There's no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson knows that whether or not he can go is out of his
control: ``I'm just going to hope and pray for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
