<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Booker's improvement bolsters pass defense
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons occasionally ``hide'' Michael
Booker with the help of a safety, but there's no hiding that he has
improved and that Atlanta's pass defense has done the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, the Falcons' defense has improved its
ranking from No. 23 to No. 17 to No. 9, allowing 301.3 yards a
game. Stronger pass defense is the biggest reason.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's last two opponents, Chicago and St. Louis, were poor
teams with struggling quarterbacks. But when a defense gives up 129
and 104 passing yards, respectively, as the Falcons (10-2) did,
plenty is going right.
</P>
<P>
   Before those two games, Atlanta's pass defense ranked last in
the NFL, giving up an average of about 250 yards, including 307
yards to the 49ers. The unit is ranked No. 25 now, allowing 225.4
yards per game, while the front seven is No. 2 against the run.
``We're covering better,'' said defensive coordinator Rich Brooks,
whose unit allowed net passing totals of 205 and 207 yards in wins
against St. Louis and New England before the 49ers game.
``(Cornerback) Ray (Buchanan) is playing very well, and Booker is
really improved. And (cornerbacks Ronnie) Bradford and (Randy)
Fuller have been very good in the nickel.''
</P>
<P>
   Booker, a second-year cornerback from Nebraska, was a
disappointment last year as a first-round draft choice. He had a
difficult time defending deep routes and keeping his balance when
he tried to play physically. When Bradford injured a knee on Oct.
25, Booker, a 6-foot-2, 203-pounder, moved into the lineup. In five
consecutive starts, all wins, he is playing more the way that the
Falcons expected when they signed him to a five-year, $8.2 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who usually covers the opposing team's best receiver,
is playing at a Pro Bowl level. He is tied for the NFC lead with
five interceptions and has defensed a team-high 18 passes.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Brooks has trusted Booker more, and the
resulting increase in man-to-man and bump-and-run coverage is
working. Booker, who is second on the team with eight passes
defensed, hasn't been beaten deep yet, although free safety Eugene
Robinson or nickel safety Devin Bush often roll behind Booker.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta beat San Francisco 31-19, Booker held 6-2,
218-pound 49ers receiver J.J. Stokes to one catch for 10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Michael playing better, we believe we can match up with
anyone,'' Buchanan said. ``He's running with receivers a lot
better. He's getting his hands on receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves has said that Bradford (5-10, 188) will start
again when he is healthy. But given the team's investment in Booker
and the way he's playing, there's no rush.
</P>
<P>
   More bump-and-run coverage means more blitzing, which helps
explain the Falcons' 14 sacks the past four games.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
