<HEADER>
A7695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN-COX     12-01 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moss wasn't for the Birds
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When last the NFL apportioned flesh, 19 teams chose to
pass on Randy Moss instead of pass to him. As of today, that stands
as the kind of mass blunder that gives lemmings and witch hunts a
bad name.
</P>
<P>
   Akin to 19 record companies auditioning the Beatles and telling
them, ``Cut your hair, get Ringo more involved, then we'll talk.''
Or to 19 editors informing John Grisham, ``Nobody wants to read
about lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the NBA, now officially the world's daftest league, got
around to drafting Michael Jordan by the third pick.
</P>
<P>
   Every catch Moss makes, every defensive back he turns into
statuary, every time he laps the ordinary, he also tightens the
collars of front-office soldiers from Seattle to Foxboro. He stands
to become a once-in-a-generation type of player, the latest in the
line, a Jerry Rice-squared. And leave in his wake more
second-guessing and regret than a week's worth of Las Vegas
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, against Dallas _ the team that was most likely to
draft Moss before he fell to Minnesota _ he exacted his latest
measure of revenge. Just three catches, that's all. But each a
touchdown, each 51 yards or more. It was a good, old-fashioned
holiday vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   Moss figures to get around to everybody sooner of later. He is
payback's personal chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, during a season otherwise free of vexing questions,
there is this: Would you rather have Randy Moss or Keith Brooking?
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to see the damage done by Moss and not picture
him working instead in the Falcons' dome. Can't help but think of
the artistic flourishes he could add to the Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not everyone is obsessing on this.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had it to do over again, we'd do exactly the same
thing,'' said the father of all things Falcon, Dan Reeves. What,
you were expecting him to break down and beg for a draft-day
mulligan?
</P>
<P>
   Regret, which once clung to the Falcons like a birthmark,
refuses to stick now.
</P>
<P>
   No, Moss never was as much as a tickle in the back of Reeves'
throat when their first pick arrived. ``With what we're trying to
do (in building from the foundation), we couldn't afford to take
the risk,'' he insists.
</P>
<P>
   Moss' character questions, heightened by the way he avoided
pre-draft exposure, made him a considerable risk. Much of the
damage was self-inflicted. And Minnesota might just be a unique
situation where Moss can flourish (although I'd take Terance Mathis
as a mentor anytime). All that tends to get drowned out in the
noise he now produces.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons went for a linebacker who is slowly becoming more
and more visible in limited playing time. While the player drafted
nine spots below him is the sensation of the season. This was a
vote for the certificate of deposit over the new-issue stock.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves still isn't ready to get speculative. ``(Moss) is doing a
tremendous job. He's been a great asset. The future is still one of
the things that concerns you. Anybody can deal with success. When
the going gets tough, will it all hold up?'' he wonders.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of franchises are looking at the huge one that got away _
Tennessee drafted another wide receiver instead, Cincinnati picked
over Moss twice. Reasons and rationalizations abound, many of them
sound. But I can't help myself. I am incapable of looking on this
player and not uttering, ``What if?''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: steve(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
