<SLUG> BC-MERGER-INDUSTRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER WAVE AMONG INDEPENDENTS COULD BUT NUMBER OF LARGER
INDEPENDENTS IN HALF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They tried cost-cutting. They formed alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the major oil companies _ faced with the specter of
depressed oil prices for years to come _ are trying yet another
strategy: creation of the mega-major.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Corp.'s planned $75.6 billion purchase of rival Mobil
Corp., if approved by regulators, would create the world's largest
oil company.
</P>
<P>
   This new behemoth would be big enough to take on another newly
forming giant, BP-Amoco and the current world heavyweight, Royal
Dutch/Shell Group.
</P>
<P>
   Further consolidation appears all but inevitable, analysts say,
as the world's remaining oil producers try to compete with this new
ruling triumvirate and reward their shareholders in an increasingly
difficult business climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low oil prices are pushing them over the cliff,'' said Fadel
Gheit, an analyst with Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York. ``Every
company is saying, `We can't do it alone. We can't do it alone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, France's Total announced plans to buy the Belgian
oil company Petrofina for $11.6 billion in stock to form the
world's sixth-largest publicly trade oil company.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. majors such as Chevron Corp. and Texaco, too small even
together to create a credible fourth competitor, are likely to get
absorbed by the Big Three, predicted Ron Oligney, a professor of
petroleum engineering at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   The industry will soon see ``probably one other mega-merger,
possibly between a large European oil company and a large U.S.
major,'' suggested Victor Burk, Arthur Andersen's managing
director, energy industry, in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Not all observers are delighted to see this consolidation
unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next merger will be Germany acquiring France,'' said Ed
Rothschild, a longtime oil industry critic with Podesta Associates
in Washington. ``This company has got more revenues than the GNP of
most of the world's nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon's bid to snatch up Mobil comes as crude prices _ adjusted
for inflation _ have plunged to their lowest levels since 1972,
prior to the Arab Oil embargo and the first oil price shock.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rothman, senior energy analyst for Merrill Lynch in New
York, calculates, using 1963 dollars, that crude was fetching about
$2.11 a barrel, or roughly a nickel a gallon, this week. ``I'd say
that's cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Few oil analysts are predicting a major rebound in oil prices
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The economies of East Asia, which for years represented the only
real growth markets for crude oil, have been hobbled by a severe
economic and currency crisis that could drag on for years. Last
month, the U.S. Energy Information Administration predicted that
the Asian economic downturn could haunt oil prices until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the once-formidable Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries _ which still accounts for about 40 percent of
world production _ failed to make commitments on further production
cuts _ sending crude prices tumbling toward $11 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the oil companies have faced an
extended period of low oil prices. But since the Oil Bust in the
mid-1980s, the oil companies have engaged in round after round of
layoffs and often-innovative strategies in an effort to keep their
costs in line.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco, for example, has drastically pared back the foreign
countries in which it operates. Amoco and Shell teamed up to
jointly operate their oil and gas properties in West Texas and
southeastern New Mexico, while Pennzoil Co. even reduced the
tea-drinking choices of its corporate staff.
</P>
<P>
   But the oil companies could find only so much fat to trim. In
today's price environment, analysts say, the they have been forced
to take more drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of energy companies had done most or all of the
cost-cutting that they could do themselves, and the only way to
achieve additional significant cost savings is to merge with
somebody else and eliminate the duplication,'' said Kerry North,
managing director of Wasserstein Perella's Dallas office.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil estimate their merger would generate an annual
cost savings of $2.8 billion, while BP and Amoco have pegged their
savings at $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   By launching a new wave of consolidation, the majors also are
following a pattern set back in the early 1980s, when oil prices _
instead of heading ever upwards _ veered south. Texaco bought Getty
Oil. Chevron picked up Gulf Oil. Mobil acquired Superior Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation is under way in nearly every aspect of the energy
business, including the oil-field service sector and among
independent oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the few months, oil-field service giant Halliburton Co.
purchased Dresser Industries, Baker Hughes bought Western Atlas and
Schlumberger acquired Camco.
</P>
<P>
   But the factors driving those acquisitions _ a desire to extend
their product lines and better serve their customers _ are
different from those prompting mergers such as the Exxon-Mobil
deal, said Matt Simmons, president of Houston's Simmons &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The independent oil producers, often more sensitive to low oil
and gas prices than the majors and much less able to carry their
debt loads, are looking for deals of their own. Last week,
Houston-based Seagull Energy Corp.'s unveiled a proposed $1.1
billion merger with Ocean Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Gheit believes the merger wave among the independents
could cut the number of larger independents in half. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
