<HEADLINE>
499-3333.  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 Hanukkah Bushes? Bah, Humbug!  
 To publish this article, it must be purchased. For purchase
information and to obtain photos, call New York Times Syndicate
sales representative Nirdi Relis at (800) 972-3550 or (212) By EVE GLICKSMAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    I come from humbug beginnings. Raised as a Jew, I sat on Santa's
lap once at a department store, but it wasn't encouraged. My mother
likely gave in because I was too young to understand the cosmic
implications.
 &HT;    Today, I consider it treason when Jews create ``Hanukkah
bushes'' or exchange gifts on Christmas. Me, who doesn't belong to
a synagogue or light sabbath candles, yet still feel my roots erupt
when assaulted by Christmas.
 &HT;    The unbidden feelings come from years of singing Yuletide carols
in elementary school and being asked too many times what I did for
``The Holiday.'' When I answer indifferently that I worked, went to
a movie or grabbed a bite in Chinatown, people are suddenly quiet.
 &HT;    There's nothing like Christmas to make a Jew feel like a
minority. I know someone in Harleysville, Pa., who looked high and
low for Hanukkah candles. After painfully trying to describe to
clueless salespeople what menorah candles looked like, a clerk
suggested he use birthday candles _ a ludicrous concept to anyone
who knows the difference. The same person complained to a local
Wal-Mart manager when he couldn't find a Jewish New Year's card in
stock at Rosh Hashanah.
 &HT;    Most of the holiday cards I receive are bald-faced Christmas
cards usually from people who: 1) know I am Jewish, and 2) do not
know that Hanukkah began two weeks before Christmas.
 &HT;    While some feature neutral winter landscapes, others are
foil-embossed nativity scenes or living rooms steeped in candy
canes and boughs of holly. Sure, it's the thought that counts, but
a little more thinking could have gone a long way.
 &HT;    One year I happened upon a great series of cards called ``Mixed
Blessings.'' These cards use playful interdenominational pictures,
such as Santa skating a Star of David on ice or a reindeer with
antlers shaped like a menorah. Perfect to send anyone in the spirit
of unity.
 &HT;    Still, if you want to get technical, Hanukkah is not top billing
in the ranks of Jewish holidays. When you care enough to send the
very best, send a card for the Jewish New Year, usually in
September.
 &HT;    Really, I'm not a grinch. I think the holiday season is a great
nudge for keeping tabs on faraway friends. Bragging family form
letters aside, I enjoy receiving their cards with news of a new
baby or a career switch. Likewise, I, too, have been known to think
about the people in my life each December who deserve a note from
the heart, seasonal or otherwise.
 &HT;     c.1998 Eve Glicksman   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eve Glicksman is a free-lance writer based in Bala Cynwyd,
Pa.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ( &UR; To publish this article, it must be purchased. For purchase
information and to obtain photos, call New York Times Syndicate
sales representative Nirdi Relis at (800) 972-3550 or (212)
499-3333.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
