<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7709 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOW-XMAS-EVOLVED-(HOL     12-01 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOW-XMAS-EVOLVED-(HOLIDAYS)-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ORIGINS OF OUR CHRISTMAS CUSTOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  Photo of first Christmas card available 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased. For purchase
information and to obtain photos, when available, call New York
Times Syndicate sales representative Nirdi Relis at (800) 972-3550
or (212) 499-3333.)  
 &HT;    
 By HAL MALEHORN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    As almost everyone knows, more than 100 years ago in Manhattan
8-year-old Virginia O'Hanlon wrote a letter to the editor of the
New York Sun to ask if there really was a Santa Claus.
 &HT;    Had that youngster lived 50 years earlier in certain parts of
the United States, she might well have asked if there was even a
Christmas.
 &HT;    Until the middle of the 1800s, throughout much of America,
Christmas was much like any other day of the just-begun winter.
Most families then were farm folk, and the darkening days before
the winter solstice were simply times to rest up, fix up and save
up for the hard work of the coming agricultural season. Perhaps the
butchering of a hog enlivened the cold-weather chores, or a
quilting bee quickened the social scene.
 &HT;    This widespread indifference to the holiday can be explained by
the fact that most of our ancestors had no knowledge of the
traditions that were beginning to arrive here from Europe, and many
harbored strong religious objections to an event that sprang from
ancient pagan festivities.
 &HT;    In truth, beginning with the Puritans in early New England, and
continuing two centuries through the Great Awakening, many
sobersided naysayers deeply disliked the celebrations that came
from the Old World. ``Blasphemy'' and ``mockery,'' such persons
grumped. One prominent Protestant preacher of that era stoutly
announced, ``To me Christmas is a foreign day, and I shall die
so.''
 &HT;    Most rural people thus spent Christmas ignoring the celebrating,
with doors and minds shut to seasonal merrymaking. Indeed, by 1850
there was so little regard in America for Christmas that only a few
of our 31 states had declared it a legal holiday.
 &HT;    In the latter half of the 19th century, however, religious
opposition declined. Christmas then became a more secular season,
as Old World customs evolved into an American Yuletide culture.
 &HT;    For instance, from England came the exchange of greeting cards,
a tradition traced back to one Henry Cole. In 1843 he impulsively
dashed off picture cards in place of his long-overdue seasonal
letters that were required by strict Victorian etiquette.
 &HT;    In 1851 the card-exchange idea arrived in this country, when
Richard H. Pease decorated his business cards with holiday
messages. More than 20 years later Louis Prang commercialized the
idea with the release of a line of Christmas cards, spawning a
profitable business for Hallmark and a harrowing job for the postal
system.
 &HT;    The Germans contributed the Christmas tree, though people who
migrated to areas devoid of evergreens had to settle for other
native species.
 &HT;    In 1848 the tree-as-centerpiece notion was given a boost in
America when Godey's Lady's Book published an engraving of Queen
Victoria and Prince Albert admiring the tree they had decorated for
their royal young. However, the tree then was just a tabletop
ornament. Only later did it evolve into its floor-to-ceiling
splendor.
 &HT;    In 1850 Charles Dickens, already famous for his ``Christmas
Carol,'' described one such upper-class evergreen: ``It was
brilliantly lighted by a multitude of little tapers, everywhere
sparkling with bright objects, rosy-cheeked dolls, domestic
furniture wonderfully made of tin, jolly broad-faced men, fiddles,
drums, paint boxes, guns, banners, humming tops, and imitation
fruit made dazzling with gold leaf.''
 &HT;    That was all well and good for the wealthy set, of course. But
since the mass manufacture and marketing of toys was only in its
infancy in America, ordinary children lucky enough to observe
Christmas at all likely got homemade ``playpretties'' _ products of
a mother's sewing basket or a father's workbench.
 &HT;    Our modern image of Santa similarly came from overseas _
Holland, Scandinavia, Germany and France. But the picture that
eventually became fixed in our minds _ a jolly bewhiskered,
red-garbed fellow with more than an ample waistline _ was largely
the gift of Clement C. Moore, whose poem ``A Visit From St.
Nicholas'' not only defined the man himself but also set forever
the belief that Santa flies through the air on a reindeer-drawn
sleigh.
 &HT;    Today, of course, Christmas is big business, with its sales
pitch beginning well before first frost. Children snuggle fitfully
in their bed with fond hopes that Ninja and Nintendo will (not so
magically) appear in their stockings come morning.
 &HT;    When Francis Church, editor of the New York Sun, replied to
Virginia O'Hanlon so long ago, he little realized what Santa and
Christmas were to become. But he did assure his young correspondent
that Santa was and is more a matter of heart and hope than of
things in hand.
 &HT;    ``He lives in terms of love and generosity and devotion,''
Church wrote, adding, ``No one can imagine all the wonders that are
quite unseen.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Hal Malehorn  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Hal Malehorn, a resident of Charleston, Ill., is a retired
teacher and professor with a lifelong interest in history.) &LR; 
