<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FEC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEC RECOMMENDS HUGE REPAYMENT FROM CAMPAIGN ADVERTISING FROM
CLINTON, DOLE  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Election Commission officials recommended
Tuesday that the presidential campaigns of Democrat Bill Clinton
and Republican Bob Dole repay millions of dollars in taxpayer
funds, charging they illegally benefited from advertising done in
coordination with their political parties.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an audit of the 1996 campaign, the officials said
that the Dole campaign should repay $17.7 million and the Clinton
campaign $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors alleged that both campaigns violated election laws
by coordinating with the Republican National Committee and the
Democratic National Committee in the creation and airing of so
called ``issue ads.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff recommendation will be reviewed by the six-member
Federal Election Commission on Thursday. The commission, which is
equally divided between Republicans and Democrats, has often
altered or ignored recommendations of its staff in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen from the Republican and Democratic parties Tuesday
denied there was any illegal coordination with the presidential
campaigns and vowed to fight the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is an outrageous opinion,'' said Clifford May, a
spokesman for the RNC. ``It is wrong to be subjecting Bob Dole to
this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   DNC General Counsel Joe Sandler and Clinton Gore '96 general
counsel Lyn Utrecht issued a statement saying ``we have a
fundamental disagreement with the recommendations of the Federal
Election Commission staff regarding the party issue advertising in
1995 and 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings come at a particularly sensitive time as the
Justice Department and congressional committees are investigating
alleged abuses during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One of the abuses being probed was the widespread use of issue
ads, or spots run by parties or outside organizations that are
supposed to promote various issues but not specifically promote one
candidate over another.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC auditors contended that the Republican and Democratic
parties crafted ads that benefited their presidential candidates
even though they did not specifically urge voters to vote for them.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the auditors determined the cost of the ads should
have been counted as contributions to the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Since both candidates received federal funds for their elections
they were subject to contribution limits for the primary and
general election races.
</P>
<P>
   When the auditors added up the cost of the issue ads they found
both candidates had exceeded their contribution caps and determined
they should refund the excess money to the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   FEC spokesman Ian Stirton said that issue ads are a fairly new
phenomena and that the agency has increasingly grappled with
whether such spots fall under federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Stirton said that the agency's auditors have taken the more
expansive view that an ad can be interpreted as promoting a
candidate even if it doesn't outright urge voters to back one
candidate over another.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the 1996 Democratic and Republican ads, he said
``they were clearly intended to get the candidate elected. They
weren't just issue ads on the issues of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   One of 37 ads run by the DNC contrasted Dole's purported
attempts to cut funding for certain programs, such as new police
hiring and anti-drug programs, with Clinton's efforts to save those
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC report concludes that the ad is ``designed to garner
public support for a certain candidate, namely President Clinton
and diminish public support for Bob Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the report also pointed to several GOP ads, including
one highlighting Clinton's promise not to raise taxes on the middle
class and then claiming that he pushed the largest tax increase in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with other ads, this message appears to have the purpose of
diminishing support for President Clinton in the election year,''
the auditors concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors also stressed that officials with the campaigns
meticulously coordinated their advertising efforts with the
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that Dole campaign manager Scott Reed attended weekly
strategy meetings held by then RNC chairman Haley Barbour. It also
stated that the party and the campaign used the same vendors,
pollsters and consultants for the advertising effort.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise the FEC report contends the Democratic Party and the
Clinton-Gore campaign coordinated events, placing their ads in the
same market, using the same consultants and pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Representatives from the White House, the DNC, and
Clinton/Gore would meet at the White House approximately once a
week to discuss media, polling, speech writing and police and issue
positioning,'' the FEC auditors stated. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
