<HEADER>
A7719 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH02-COX     12-01 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign finance practices to be scrutinized by Judiciary
CommitteeBy Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _As it heard new testimony about the importance of
perjury, the bitterly divided House Judiciary Committee voted along
party lines Tuesday to subpoena new information about whether
President Clinton violated campaign finance laws. The committee is
seeking internal memos from FBI Director Louis Freeh and former
Justice Department official Charles LaBella about their findings
during investigations of Democratic campaign fund-raising
practices. Both Freeh and LaBella have urged Attorney General Janet
Reno to appoint an independent counsel to investigate the
allegations of fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh and LaBella were also subpoenaed to get their analysis of
the evidence the memos contain.
</P>
<P>
   Their memos were introduced in evidence before a federal grand
jury investigating allegations that foreign contributors may have
tried to influence administration policy by donating large sums of
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is critical in our investigation as it was in the campaign
fund-raising investigation,'' said Georgia Republican Rep. Bob
Barr, who sits on both the Judiciary Committee and the House
Government Reform and Oversight Committee, the panel that has spent
the better part of the last two years and $7 million investigating
the campaign fund-raising scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he suspects that that the memos describe the
president's involvement in the questionable way money was raised
during the 1996 presidential election, and that makes it the duty
of the impeachment panel to obtain them to see if the president's
actions rise to the level of an impeachable crime.
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee is seeking the memos from Reno, their
release must be approved by U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway
Johnson, who called a closed-door hearing for today to discuss the
matter. Johnson issued a sealed ruling last Friday stating that the
committee had not demonstrated sufficient need for the memos, which
she kept under seal because they include secret grand jury
material. Committee Republicans believe the subpoena will
strengthen their argument to disclose them.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also subpoenaed material from Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr on John Huang, a former Democratic fund-raiser whose
ex-employer paid money to presidential friend Webster Hubbell.
Starr is investigating whether that payment and other consulting
fees represented ``hush money'' to keep Hubbell quiet about any
wrongdoing by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, (R-Ill.), committee chairman, insisted that the
expansion of the investigation would not destroy his self-imposed
deadline of Dec. 31 for ending the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely committed myself to wrapping this up this
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But committee spokesman Paul McNulty conceded the new line of
inquiry could expand the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be tough _ if credible evidence of wrongdoing is
discovered _ to stick with our schedule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the escalating tension between the two sides,
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt wrote out-going House Speaker Newt
Gingrich (R-Ga.) a letter expressing his ``deepest concern'' for
the way the impeachment inquiry has turned into ``chaos due to the
lack of direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it is incumbent on you to provide the
leadership necessary to move this process forward,'' said Gephardt.
Gingrich spokesperson Christina Martin said that there is a
structure in place that should be followed and that structure is
under the leadership of Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans viewed the day-long hearing as an
opportunity to do exactly what Gephardt is requesting.
</P>
<P>
   By having a hearing featuring the likes of federal judges,
including Judge Gerald Tjoflat of the 11th Circuit in Atlanta, and
convicted perjurers, Republicans said they hoped to educate the
public about the seriousness of lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minority Leader Gephardt says he fears that the inquiry lacks
direction,'' said Hyde. ``It is my view his real fear is not the
lack of direction, but rather that we are moving in the right
direction--getting to the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said that he found it ``particularly disturbing and indeed
shameful, that many who generally claim to represent the weak now
argue that the powerful should be allowed a pass when they break
the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee heard from judges, military officers and two women
prosecuted for lying in sex cases
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Republicans had staged the perjury session to
rally support for impeachment articles, which House leaders hope to
bring to a floor vote later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Tjoflat was asked what would happen to the nation's system of
justice if perjury became commonplace. Comparing the system to a
three-legged stool, Tjoflat said the system functions only when
there there is an impartial judge, lawyers who obey the canons of
ethics and witnesses who take the oath sincerely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any one of those legs collapses, then the system is unable
to render justice,'' Tjoflat said. ``And of course, if it happens
repeatedly, then the people lose respect for the law, they lose
confidence in the system of justice, and they resort to other means
to resolve their disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the panel heard from Atlanta resident Pam
Parsons, a former University of South Carolina women's basketball
coach who pleaded guilty to a federal perjury charge in 1984 for
giving false testimony in a civil case about a sexual relationship
she had with one of her players.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said she was relieved to come before the committee to
describe her ``spiraling journey through hell'' to get to become a
truthful person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I could finally say I'm guilty,'' Parsons said. ``To
turn around and take a look at the other side of me took more guts
than it ever took to win a ball game. Now I truly know what it's
like to be a part of a team, and when that team can't trust you,
you've lost it all, and I would rather be who I am today than to
have continued coaching with a lie. ``
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
