<HEADLINE>
NO MONEY-BACK SATISFACTION FROM BILL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Hanks &LR; , who has overnighted three times at the White House
during the current administration, told the New Yorker that he
regrets a donation he and his wife made to &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 's legal
defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave 10,000 bucks,'' he said. ``Very early on. In all
honesty, in the light of events since, it would be awfully hard to
say now, `Oh, here, let me help you out with this problem.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks said he had few other regrets. ``I wish I had learned how
to floss my teeth sooner. I wish I had taken piano lessons when I
was 8 years old. If I wanted to go way, way, way, way, way, way
back, I could say, `Jeez, I should have got out of high school and
gone right across the bridge into San Francisco and tried to get
into the American Conservatory Theater.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But hey, you know what? I turned out to be a movie star! So it
worked out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Specialized Bicycle in Mountain View has put the
president's face atop a very buff cyclist's body in a poster for
its new bicycle seat. The line on the poster, which was made for
distribution to bike shops: ``Introducing a saddle designed to help
alleviate impotency.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's  &UR; Chip Smith &LR;  told Personals that political figures
have had &LR;  been used in previous Specialized promotional campaigns
and that lawyers had assured them the president's status as a
public figure made use of the image allowable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE MERGERS TO REMEMBER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adding to last week's list of imaginary corporate mergers,
 &UR; Myles Nye &LR; 's suggestions include descriptions of the resulting
companies:
</P>
<P>
   _ FedExLax provides laxatives delivered to your doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   _ AlPony Express makes use of old horses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pepsi-Bismol is the choice of the senior generation.
</P>
<P>
   _ CrackerJack Daniel's makes the perfect ballpark snack.
</P>
<P>
   _ Juicy Fruit of the Loom manufactures chewable briefs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For the (see above) merger-minded, a little something to make
things easier:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maureen Hardy  &LR; sends word of the Good Catalog Co.'s $40 Lip
Enhancer, ``first developed for patients who suffered from uneven
collagen procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   This device, which works by vacuum suction, leaves lips fuller
for as long as 12 hours, increasing ``circulation to transform thin
or uneven lips, making them fuller, smoother, more youthful looking
and evenly shaped. ... Be sure to condition your lips for a few
weeks first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In answer to Premiere magazine's question, ``What movie makes
you cry?''  &UR; Kristin Scott Thomas &LR;  names ``The Sound of Music'';
 &UR; Charlize Theron  &LR; names ``Sophie's Choice'';  &UR; Anne Heche &LR;  names
``The Full Monty'';  &UR; David Duchovny &LR;  names ``Brian's Song.'' And
 &UR; Samuel L. Jackson  &LR; says, ``I don't cry in movies. I'm a little too
analytical for that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Postcard from the ESPN Sports Center Bar at Disney World in
Orlando, Fla. Inside the men's room, writes  &UR; Stephen Vincent &LR; , ``I
found a (TV) monitor between each urinal, ceiling monitors hanging
at a tilt over each stall and several little monitors at both
ceiling and eye level on the walls around the sinks.'' In addition
to all this visual stimulation, little speakers broadcast ``the
voices of commentators bouncing off the black and white tile walls.
... Instead of Utopia, it was more like sports hell.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Time magazine's naming Mafia boss &UR; Lucky Luciano  &LR; as one of the
most ``influential business geniuses of the 20th century'' has
angered New York Mayor  &UR; Rudy Giuliani &LR; . ``This idea that most of
these Mafia people could have been successful businessmen ...
completely begs the question,'' he said. ``They have a tactic
available to them that people can't use in business, at least not
openly, and that is murdering lots of people.'' He said that most
</P>
<P>
   mafiosi he had prosecuted ``have sub-par intelligence.''
Suggesting that they would have been successful ``creates the
further romanticization of an organization that now is hopefully
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you ``Eat a Horse _ Go to Jail,'' as a bumper sticker
suggests,  &UR; Steve Bilan  &LR; wonders if eating three cans of dog food
will get you a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to put my tits on my back, they're mine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cher's comments about plastic surgery, expurgated by the
publisher from her new book ``The First Time,'' according to
Jeannette Walls of MSNBC.
</P>
