<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-CONTEST1202-COX     12-01 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CONTEST1202-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Radio station ends contest for 2 Beetles
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _They've run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   After 37 days, Top 40 radio station Star 94 (WSTR/94.1 FM) has
ended its wildly popular ``Live in It and Win It II'' contest
because ``we never imagined it could go on this long,'' says
general manager Mark Kanov.
</P>
<P>
   The station will hold a drawing at noon today to see which two
of the four remaining contestants will win the red and black
Volkswagen Beetles in which they have been living (with only brief
breaks) since before Halloween. No word yet on what the other two
contestants will receive.
</P>
<P>
   The news didn't seem to bother remaining car sitter Sonja Banks,
a Stone Mountain paralegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problems I've had are headaches. They've probably
stemmed from me being 6 foot and the positions I had to sleep in.
Thank God for the chiropractor they've had here. In a way, this has
been worse than incarceration. . . . If I don't win, I'll be
disappointed. But I knew at the beginning that I might not walk
away a winner. I endured until the end and prevailed. I won't be
going home and crying about it. I proved something to these guys
and I proved something to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the promotion began Oct. 26, thousands of Atlantans have
watched and listened to see who would last the longest in the two
cars parked inside North Point Mall(Alpharetta,Ga.). The contest
kicked off with eight people inside the Bugs, wearing their
mandatory seat belts. Jacqueline Sommers, 30, a homemaker from
Fayetteville(Ga.), bailed out after five days. Marc Azriel, 35, an
Atlanta sales rep, was disqualified on Day 6 when he returned from
a bathroom break 20 seconds late.
</P>
<P>
   When it looked like no one was going to budge, the station
managed to bribe two other contestants out of the cars. On Nov. 12,
Jennifer Roller, 25, of Suwanee, Ga., accepted a trip for two to
Los Angeles and a check for $2,000. A week later, Gainesville(Ga.)
mother of four Brenda Burke, 41, exited with $2,500 and a trip for
six to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining four contestants _ Douglasville(Ga.) bartender
Kevin Danley, 31, independent contractor David Stephenson, 23,
free-lance Marietta(Ga.) filmmaker John Crow, 29, and Banks, 31 _
dug in for the duration. Star 94 tried in vain to rattle their
determination, ultimately making all four move into one car.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are so tenacious they will be in there forever,''
Kanov said. ``We thought this would end before Thanksgiving. It's
gotten to the point we're concerned for their health and families.
The rules said we could end it at any time, and they agreed, so
this is no surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanov said the decision had nothing to do with the cost of
running the contest, which he estimated to be about $70,000 _ for
security, food, a live computer feed for the radio station's Web
site and the two cars themselves. Meanwhile, the radio station has
gotten a mother lode of publicity. Star 94 has experienced more
than 1 million hits on its Web site featuring live shots of the
people in the cars.
</P>
<P>
   After Kanov broke the news to the contestants Tuesday, the mood
was one of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got mixed emotions about it. It'll be nice to get out of
here and actually prepare for Christmas,'' Danley said. ``I think
it just got pretty clear to Star 94 that the four of us intended to
go the distance and that we weren't leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the first thing he's going to do when he gets out?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go home, take a long, hot shower . . . jog five
miles and have a few celebration drinks. All the stuff that normal
people get to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Richard L. Eldredge contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
