A7741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYRIGHTS-COX     12-01 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYRIGHTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami adopts gay rights rule
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With hundreds of impassioned partisans chanting, singing
and praying just outside, Miami-Dade County leaders Tuesday
narrowly approved extending their anti-discrimination ordinance to
include gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The fiery debate climaxed an intense campaign that cut across
the normal political dividing lines in this often-contentious
multicultural melting pot.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged mothers fearful of the values being passed to their
children, proud mothers of gay sons, thunderous black ministers,
rabbis, gay activists and Scripture-quoting evangelical Christians
all spoke passionately, many invoking their most deeply held
beliefs and fears about the direction of modern American society.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, commissioners approved the measure by a 7-6 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message this sends is that everybody is welcome in
Miami-Dade County,'' said George Mursuli, who led the drive for the
measure. ``I really didn't know how it was going to turn out. My
knees buckled.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents promised to fight on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over,'' said Josh Morales of the Christian Coalition.
``We've got a lot of options, including a referendum or possibly
recalling some of the commissioners. It's a sad day for the county
when we allow a minority to claim special rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote comes as the debate over gay rights is cropping up in
communities across the country. Similar measures have appeared on
the ballot in numerous states and cities, with differing results.
</P>
<P>
   Dade County was one of the first local governments to pass such
an ordinance back in the 1970s. But that law prompted a stormy
repeal campaign led by former beauty queen Anita Bryant, who drew
national attention to the issue. She won the measure's repeal in
1977, but became a lightning rod on the controversial issue and
subsequently lost a long-held endorsement contract for Florida
orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   The issue lay dormant in Miami for years, even as surrounding
governments in Palm Beach, Broward and Monroe counties banned
discrimination based on sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum began to build again in Dade in the 1990s, though, as
Miami Beach went through a stunning rebirth, much of it fueled by
gays who refurbished run-down hotels, attracting artists and the
fashion industry. Miami Beach passed its own anti-discrimination
ordinance in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign spread to the county government this year, as
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Katy Sorenson _ whose brother is gay _ agreed to
sponsor the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's vote showed the intensity of feelings on both sides.
Several hundred people gathered on the plaza outside County Hall,
rallying for hours as designated leaders went inside to give
impassioned pleas.
</P>
<P>
   Christians argued the measure was a violation of Scripture and
would further erode the country's moral foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't back down on this,'' said Rev. Bill Baggett, a
Baptist minister from South Dade. ``It impacts our lives. For you
to tell me I have to employ someone or rent a house to someone in
violation of my personal beliefs is wrong. We're talking about
people choosing a lifestyle and then forcing me to swallow their
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue split Hispanics, with several Latin ministers and lay
people arguing on both sides. Significantly, the powerful Catholic
archbishop of Miami, John C. Favarola, reached a public agreement
with gay activists to take no position on the matter. Under
questioning from commissioners, a spokesman for the Archdiocese
said the body opposes all discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Other Latin clergy were vehemently opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``God created Adam and Eve, not Adam and Steve,'' said the Rev.
Elizer Veguilla, a member of the Dade Baptist Alliance. ``It's
against the laws of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Also badly split were African-Americans. Many were outraged that
gay activists liken their struggle to the civil rights movement,
saying gays choose their lifestyle while blacks have no choice in
the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words cannot express the offense I feel as a black man when
told that,'' said the Rev. Richard Ledgister of the Sierra Norwood
Calvary Baptist Church in Miami. ``Don't talk about human rights to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the local branches of the NAACP and the Urban League
supported the measure, along with several other prominent black
leaders. In the end, Commission Chairwoman Gwen Margolis, who voted
in favor, told opponents that they should cool their rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the big deal?'' Margolis asked. ``Monroe, Broward and
Palm Beach have all passed these ordinances and nobody is moving
away because of it. Are the Christians in those communities unable
to practice their religion because of it?''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
