<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARPET-PLEA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Violation of campaign finance laws costs carpet company $1
millionBy Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, Ga. _ The world's largest privately held carpet company
was fined $1 million Tuesday for violating federal campaign finance
laws by funneling $36,000 in corporate contributions to the failed
presidential bid of former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulieu of America Inc. pleaded guilty to five misdemeanor
counts of making illegal contributions. The fine is one of the
largest ever for such a violation.
</P>
<P>
   The company is headed by Republican power broker and Dalton, Ga.
civic leader Carl Bouckaert, who transformed Beaulieu from an
industry upstart to a 7,000-employee company. Beaulieu is one of
three huge carpet makers in Dalton, where about one-third of the
world's carpet is produced. The industry drives the region's
economy and wields considerable influence in north Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bouckaert's enthusiasm for GOP politics that apparently
landed Beaulieu in hot water with federal investigators. Bouckaert,
who was not charged individually, was required by the plea
agreement to attend the court proceeding. Another requirement is
that Beaulieu's corporate officers perform 500 hours of community
service, 200 hours by Bouckaert himself. Bouckaert has begun
working at a homeless shelter, said Anthony Cochran, his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bouckaert was a member of Alexander's national finance
committee. According to court documents, Bouckaert was host for a
March 8, 1995, fund-raising dinner for Alexander's 1996 campaign.
At the direction of unspecified corporate officers, at least 36
Beaulieu employees or spouses contributed $1,000 each to the
Alexander for President Committee to buy tickets to the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulieu reimbursed the employees, disguising it in company's
records as ``bonuses'' or ``expense reimbursements.''
</P>
<P>
   Because corporations can give no more than $2,000 annually to a
federal campaign, the $36,000 contribution by Beaulieu was illegal.
Only a handful of companies have paid larger fines. The largest _
$8 million _ was paid last year by a Pennsylvania landfill company.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Nahmias said there was ``an
absence of any evidence of corrupt motive'' behind Beaulieu's
illegal contributions and that the Alexander campaign unwittingly
accepted them.
</P>
<P>
   A world-class equestrian rider, Bouckaert is friends with George
and Barbara Bush and his company will carpet Bush's presidential
library. The Belgium native is South Fulton's largest individual
land owner, with more than 8,000 acres. Two years ago, he spent
$32,500 to outbid heavyweight boxing champion Evander Holyfield for
the last of the promotional T-shirts counting down days until the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very, very sorry that this has happened,'' Bouckaert
told U.S. District Judge Harold Murphy. `` I guarantee to you that
this will never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy put Beaulieu on probation until Dec. 31, 2000, after the
next presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
