A7744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONKEY-DEATH-COX     12-01 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONKEY-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Primate center to pay fine for safety lapses
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie and Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Emory University primate center has agreed to pay a
$66,400 fine for worker-safety lapses in the wake of a research
assistant's death last year .
</P>
<P>
   In a settlement reached Tuesday with the Yerkes Regional Primate
Research Center, the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration agreed to drop a charge that the facility
``willfully violated safety practices.'' OSHA had initially
proposed fining Yerkes $105,300 for 10 infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth R. Griffin, a 22-year-old research assistant, died
Dec. 10 of complications from herpes B, contracted from an infected
monkey.
</P>
<P>
   Yerkes officials said the ``willful violation'' citation was
dropped, and the fine lowered, because ``OSHA recognized that the
safety conditions and practices at the Yerkes Center in no way
caused or contributed to the injury or death of any individual.''
</P>
<P>
   An OSHA spokeswoman said the agency would not comment on why the
charge was eliminated until the settlement was made final by an
administrative law judge.
</P>
<P>
   The citations involve only incidents that occurred after
Griffin's death, which came six weeks after she was splashed by
bodily fluids from a monkey infected with herpes B.
</P>
<P>
   Charles N. Jeffress, assistant secretary of labor for OSHA, said
Tuesday the settlement is fair. ``The proposed settlement upholds
the principle that research laboratories must protect their
employees from contact with animal fluids,'' he said, ``and
requires Emory University to pay a significant penalty for failing
to have appropriate safeguards in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Yerkes contested the original OSHA citations, saying it had
followed all standard safety guidelines known at the time, and that
it properly informed and trained its employees for the risks of
working with the research monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of the exposure, we were working under the
guidelines as we had since 1987,'' said Thomas Gordon, Yerkes
associate director. ``We took the guidelines very seriously and we
followed them scrupulously. Those guidelines did not require eye
protection for the activity the employee was doing at the time. It
was a low-risk activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Griffin's death, eye protection is now required any time a
person is working or in the same room with a primate.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie and Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
