u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-FUNDRAISE &LR;      12-01 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-FUNDRAISE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT PANEL TO PROBE CLINTON FUND-RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The impeachment inquiry, wracked by escalating
partisan strife, veered toward a new frontier Tuesday as the House
Judiciary Committee, over the White House's vehement protests,
issued subpoenas to probe President Clinton's fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Exposing Clinton to possible further jeopardy in the impeachment
case, the committee voted, 20-15, along party lines to pursue a
confidential Justice Department report that FBI Director Louis J.
Freeh has testified, according to Representative Bill McCollum, a
Florida Republican and senior committee member, ``may point to
illegal actions on the part of President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt move, less than 10 days before the panel is
tentatively scheduled to vote on proposed articles of impeachment,
ignited a political firestorm that overshadowed a nine-hour hearing
on the consequences of perjury and set back an effort to resolve
the inquiry short of trying to oust Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said they expect Freeh and Charles LaBella, a
former Justice Department prosecutor who wrote the confidential
report, to comply with subpoenas this week to be questioned
privately about Clinton's fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the panel's GOP majority also are seeking a federal
judge's consent to obtain LaBella's report, which contains secret
grand-jury information involving an ongoing criminal investigation
into 1996 campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last desperate grasp of a group of people who are
determined to impeach the president and haven't yet been able to
put it together,'' said Representative Barney Frank, a
Massachusetts Democrat and senior committee member.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart assailed the expanded
inquiry as a sign the panel ``has been hijacked by extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fraying relations between Clinton's allies and the
Republican majority on the committee, the panel's chairman, Henry
J. Hyde, accused Democratic lawmakers of trying to ``browbeat''
him, angrily clashed with Harvard law professor Alan Dershowitz,
and vigorously defended the expanded investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not exercising or participating in a wild goose
chase,'' Hyde said. ``We are trying to find some things, and we
have good reason to believe they may be there.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hyde's request, the committee approved subpoenas for
LaBella's report and a memorandum by Freeh, which both recommended
that Attorney General Janet Reno seek an independent counsel to
investigate White House fund-raising abuses. Two additional
subpoenas were issued for memos by Reno aides analyzing LaBella's
report.
</P>
<P>
   Reno rejected LaBella's recommendation for an independent
counsel, although the campaign-finance investigation continues and
Reno faces a Monday deadline to decide if she should seek the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde dropped plans to subpoena Clinton and Reno to turn over the
LaBella document.
</P>
<P>
   But the Judiciary Committee also subpoenaed evidence the
independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, gathered in his
investigation of John Huang, a former Democratic fund-raiser who
also is a key figure in the Justice Department's campaign-finance
inquiry. Starr has examined whether Huang or his former employer,
the Riady family of Indonesia, paid Clinton's friend, Webster L.
Hubbell, not to testify about Clinton's role in the Whitewater
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hyde said he does not expect the impeachment inquiry's new
direction to alter his plan to complete the proceedings before
Christmas week.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several committee Republicans downplayed the possibility
that the new subpoenas will yield evidence that would warrant a
lengthy investigation of Clinton's fund-raising activities. The
allegations already have been examined by two other committees _
one in the House, the other in the Senate _ without leading to
formal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe this is just a matter of making sure we have
tied up all the loose ends,'' said Representative Charles T.
Canady, a Florida Republican who is one of Clinton's harshest
critics on the committee. ``When all is said and done, I believe
our focus will remain on the referral'' from Starr about Clinton's
sexual affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were not appeased. Representative Charles E. Schumer
of New York charged committee Republicans with ``hurtling headlong
into constitutional crisis, which the American people, in their
wisdom, have begged us to rein in and reject.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri,
said ``chaos is reigning'' in the impeachment investigation. He
sent letters asking the speaker-elect, Robert L. Livingston of
Louisiana, and the lame-duck speaker, Newt Gingrich of Georgia, to
step in and ensure that the proceedings do not ``needlessly plague
the next Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Representative William D. Delahunt, a Massachusetts
Democrat, formally notified Hyde that he plans to offer a
resolution next week ``condemning the president's conduct and
censuring him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Hyde, Delahunt described ``a formal rebuke as the
best means of bringing to a proper conclusion this unfortunate
chapter in the life of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hyde told reporters Tuesday that he would consider a
censure resolution ``non-germane'' to the committee's action. As a
result, Democratic leaders may need to strike a deal with
Livingston to bring such a resolution to a vote in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no indication that the GOP leadership was open to
a compromise resolution. In fact, a Republican source said House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas, an ardent proponent of Clinton's
impeachment, has been actively trying to sway GOP members to
support sending the case to the Senate for an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   As partisan hostilities rose Tuesday, Representative Martin T.
Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, told reporters outside the
hearing room that the impeachment proceedings had turned into a
``circus'' and questioned why the vast majority of committee
Republicans opposed his bill earlier this year to overhaul the
campaign finance system if they cared so deeply about fund-raising
abuses in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan also said he doubted the Justice Department will turn
over the LaBella document to the committee. ``The last thing any
prosecutor with any sense would do is release grand-jury material
to these turkeys,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   The day-long hearing began with testimony by two women who were
convicted of lying under oath in civil depositions in lawsuits
involving sex, as Clinton is alleged to have done. Both women said
Clinton should be held to the same standard they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because a president is not a king, he or she must abide by the
same laws as the rest of us,'' said Barbara Battalino, a former
Veterans Administration psychiatrist who lied in a sexual
harassment case filed against her by a VA patient.
</P>
<P>
   Battalino is serving six months of court-ordered home detention
for obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also heard testimony from several judges and legal
scholars, nearly all of whom said Clinton should be censured for
his misdeeds rather than removed from office. The witnesses
supporting censure included former US Attorney General Eliot L.
Richardson and two Harvard professors: Alan Dershowitz and A. Leon
Higginbotham Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz engaged in angry exchanges both with Hyde and
Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who is considered the
panel's leading Clinton foe.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Hyde, Dershowitz accused the commmittee of
``trivializing the rule of law'' by focusing on Clinton's sexual
affair. And he called the proceedings ``a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagging his finger at Dershowitz, Hyde replied: ``I don't thank
you for criticizing the motives, saying that we're out to get the
president. You haven't the slightest idea of the agony that many of
us go through over this question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
