<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7752 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREG-OSBY-JAZZ-ART-2T     12-01 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREG-OSBY-JAZZ-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREG OSBY: THE MOVES OF A JAZZ CONTRARIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., N.Y.)   (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the best jazz records of 1998 dares you, at
first glance and listen, to take it seriously. Sold in stores at a
budget price, alto saxophonist Greg Osby's ``Banned in New York''
is a live recording with one original tune and a few standards, and
aside from a little professional editing, it was made for about $7.
The music was captured on a small minidisk recorder over the course
of a few nights last winter at Sweet Basil, a Manhattan club, with
a single microphone placed in front of the stage. As you might
expect, the drums sound a little too loud, the piano a little too
soft.
</P>
<P>
   But the modest surface of this album _ which would be considered
a bootleg if it weren't released on a major record label _ hides a
brash subtext. Osby seems to be making two points: one, that his
music is so changeable and electrifying that it deserves to be
bootlegged and studied, as Charlie Parker's was; two, that a great
band doesn't need the special-guests padding and lumbering concepts
about classic repertory that dull the edges of so many jazz
recordings. He's right on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Osby, 38, wears sunglasses on the bandstand and comes across as
cool, a bit detached. But one afternoon, talking about his new
album and his discontent with the jazz business, from record
production to advertising to nightclubs to critics, he seemed
vigorous. Sitting in the conference room of his record label, Blue
Note, he was dressed crisply and bristled with contrarian defiance,
his manner direct and his expression challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he said, he had been sifting through the Dean
Benedetti recordings with a friend, the saxophonist Steve Coleman.
Benedetti was be-bop's recording angel, who collected Charlie
Parker solos on his portable tape recorder; Mosaic records issued
the complete hoard on CD in the early '90s. ``We'd analyze them,
rewind, go over certain passages and break them down to the atom,''
Osby recalled. He regularly makes similar recordings of his own
band's performances, and having played back a couple of especially
good sets, he decided that a raw recording could be ideal for
communicating the spontaneity of his band. (Osby's band will next
perform at Sweet Basil from Jan. 26-31.)
</P>
<P>
   Osby has been criticized for the mathematical quality of his
music, for the ambiguity in the rhythmic and melodic material of
his lines; they can feel as if they're constructed of thin metal
rods rather than the stretchy, billowy stuff of most jazz saxophone
playing. But those who get their information about jazz solely from
records may not know that in performance Osby is a high-speed
improviser of idiosyncrasy and authority in charge of a blow-torch
band. His playing bears a formal precision from studying be-bop,
and though he spent the 1980s working in bands led by jazz heroes
in and out of the mainstream like Dizzy Gillespie, McCoy Tyner,
Andrew Hill and Jack DeJohnette, he plays like someone who has
thought at length about how not to sound like his peers. Typically,
he stresses the weak beats of a rhythm, pumps lots of fast notes
into a ballad or takes comfortable melodic shapes and inverts them.
He sometimes sounds as if he's playing jazz backward.
</P>
<P>
   His live sets are among the most rewarding experiences in jazz
clubs at the moment. Accurately represented on ``Banned in New
York,'' the performances never follow a predetermined set list.. He
uses a cuing system, in which a short signal from his horn impels
the band to move between complete tunes like Duke Ellington's ``I
Didn't Know About You'' or Sonny Rollins' ``Pent-Up House'' and the
tiny melodic ideas he calls ``germs.'' In this practice Osby is
obviously indebted to Miles Davis' 1960s band but also, as he
explained, to hip-hop disk jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hip-hop mix-show will go nonstop for an hour or so, mixing
recordings together,'' he said. ``As one tune is dying out, another
is fading in. So at one point you hear this nebula, a floating
zone, where there are two tunes going on at once. Now I want to
take it further and make up tunes on the spot with cues, take
fragments from certain songs and make compounds out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to be inside two different pieces of music at the same
time characterizes his general philosophy. When he was growing up
in St. Louis, Osby's mother worked for an LP distribution company;
he had a large record collection as a child, and proudly remembers
stacking Cream's power psychedelia on top of Sonny Stitt be-bop
records on the family turntable. Touring the Midwest from the age
of 15, all his early jobs were in soul bands, and he talks often
about using whatever your experience has been, about the need for
recombining different approaches _ not as pastiche but as a method
to increase your own originality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to live my life as a fence straddler,'' he said. ``I
want to go across borders and borrow tendencies and textures from
other perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   And he pursues young sidemen to straddle the fence with him,
writing exacting music for them and encouraging them to bring their
own styles to the band. ``He really trains you,'' said Rodney
Green, his 19-year-old drummer. ``Most other band leaders write
drum music that you can ignore; it's just a map. But Osby was the
first cat I met whose music was _ accurate. If he wrote `rim,' he
meant rim. If he wrote `bell of the cymbal,' he meant something
intricate. You can imagine how any other gig I do is super-easy
now.'' (At a recording session earlier this year, Osby made Green
go over the placing of a single grace note on the high-hat cymbal
through more than a dozen takes.)
</P>
<P>
   Osby hired his pianist, Jason Moran, on a recommendation,
without having heard him, inviting him to join the group in the
middle of a tour. He hired Green without an audition. ``I'd heard
some of his music, but I didn't really know who he was,'' Green
said. ``And I think he actually liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'80s, Osby was central to the loose aggregation of
New York musicians called M-Base, a group that sought new musical
and business paradigms for jazz. They put out their music on
independent record labels, exploring funk, polyrhythms and new
methods of collective improvisation. Seeking to establish his own
name apart from the collective, Osby went deeper into maverick
status. In 1993 he decided to make a full-scale jazz-rap album,
``3-D Life Styles,'' and even hired one of Public Enemy's producers
to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a true `fusion' record _ my boys meet your
boys,'' he said. ``When you put together samples from unrelated
genres, you can create deep zones that are indescribable,
undefinable. Not really chords, just a zone. My challenge was to
try to improvise within that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Osby's take on hip-hop paled at the time in comparison to
the real thing _ 1993 was the year of the Wu-Tang Clan's
breakthrough debut album _ there was no question of his
seriousness; he was trying to reach the teen-ager who had never
heard jazz and might respond with curiosity to a rap about
Thelonious Monk. But it didn't sell; neither hip-hop nor jazz
listeners wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   For his 1995 follow-up, ``Black Book,'' he had learned enough
about hip-hop production to do all of it himself, including
programming beats, making samples and scratching. Since then, he
has changed his mind about hip-hop. Asked if it still has a future
with jazz, Osby doesn't hesitate. ``I'm not sure that hip-hop has a
future,'' he replied. ``It's reached the inevitable impasse of a
folk music that's not fed from any creative source.''
</P>
<P>
   That intuition was one reason he returned to making acoustic
jazz in 1996, with the record ``Art Forum,'' a small classic. As
serious as Osby's intentions had been in working with hip-hop, the
static beats and limited structure of the music had held back a
remarkable compositional talent, one given to long, segmented
themes written in oddly phrased bunches of notes. The record used
slide guitar, flute, vibraphone, trombone and bass clarinet; it
alternated curious, easy-swinging original ballads with tracks
whose moods were as delicate as paper, and it set off a run of
exceptional work, including the studio album ``Zero,'' which
appeared last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The petulant title ``Banned in New York'' refers to the
logistical difficulties Osby meets in pursuing his art, even
though, it must be said, that playing two weeks each year at a
top-level New York jazz club, making an album or two a year for
Blue Note and producing records for the label (including the
forthcoming debut by Moran) isn't doing too badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult to maintain a steady working group,'' he
said. ``With every breakthrough, either one of the cats in the band
defects, or he's coaxed away, or there's a big lapse in the
gigging. I don't work that much, and I'm so backlogged. In the last
few years I've written 50 or 60 compositions, not counting the
little germs; I must have thousands of those on computer disks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I call my situation an art band. Rehearsals for me are like
a lab: we'll work on motifs and cycle them until cats start
thinking that way. I tell my guys, you're not going to make your
rent with this band.'' He gets the challenging look in his face
again. ``You have to do your other whore gigs,'' he said, ``and
then you can come with me and we can propel ourselves into other
areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
