<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      12-01 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING ABOUT TO CAST OUT HE WHO IS SINNER-IN-CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-NYT) 
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The way the Judiciary Committee billboarded the
day's hearing _ ``The Consequences of Perjury'' _ had the ring of
the pulpit to it, much as the sermon topic ``The Wages of Sin'' has
generated countless spiritual revivals across American history.
</P>
<P>
   Revival was most definitely the Republicans' hope, with their
attempt to impeach President Clinton still failing to win over the
American public. But instead of fire and brimstone, the Republican
majority presented two penitent miscreants _ two ordinary American
women who were convicted and seriously punished by the government
for having lied under oath about their sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   As the two told their tales, the impeachment inquiry, for all
the rush toward the New Year's deadline, took a poignant tangent.
The inquiry devoted its second public hearing on Tuesday to the
Republicans' effort to stoke popular concern about the president's
sex-and-mendacity scandal in the face of perjury crime and
punishment. Expert lawyers and retired military officers were
called and spoke from constitutional theory, while the women spoke
from bitter experience.
</P>
<P>
   One woman told of doing jail time and losing her career in
coaching women's basketball when she filed a libel suit and lied
about visiting a gay bar. The other, freed from home detention to
testify, sadly told of being furtively tape-recorded and
demolishing her career as a government psychiatrist in April by
lying about a single act of sex in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I could finally say `I'm guilty,''' Pam Parsons, the
former coach, told the lawmakers as she described her ``spiraling
journey through hell'' in trying to keep the truth from public
notice. ``When you're in a leadership position, no matter what it
is you must tell the truth about, you've got to search your soul
and recognize what it means if you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans beamed at this and even more when her fellow felon,
Dr. Barbara Battalino, drove the point home: ``Because a president
is not a king, he or she must abide by the same laws as the rest of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Minority Democrats shied from any hostile questioning of the two
obviously sympathetic witnesses, and Bob Inglis, R-S.C., exulted.
``You have done what nobody else has been able to do,'' he told
them. ``You have just thrown a wrench in the White House spin
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   But on closer hearing, the committee excursion touched on some
of the same basic predicaments the nation has sensed in the
scandal. For _ the disgraced coach finally warned _ every team
needs a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ranked second in the nation, 7 and 0, kind of like the
economy _ doing very well,'' said Ms. Parsons to gentle laughter in
recalling how her team at the University of South Carolina suffered
its own downfall after her departure. ``I sense that one thing we
don't need right now is to not have a leader, in a world where
leadership matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's delving into the consequences of perjury took a
midday detour when the Republicans opened a second front into an
old Capitol Hill scandal topic, the wages of campaign financing.
Democrats fumed as subpoenas were voted along party lines for
confidential Justice Department memorandums that argue for an
independent counsel to look into Clinton campaign financing _a
topic that fully frustrated Republicans in two earlier
congressional investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's justifiable that we take a look,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde,
the committee chairman, as Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., dismissed
the action as ``the wild goose chase of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last desperate gasp of a group of people who were
determined to impeach the president and haven't yet gotten their
way,'' Frank complained as the Republicans won the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury topic was also tackled by a panel of legal scholars
and retired military officers who ranged a now familiar spectrum.
``The initial wrongdoing was not criminal and did not, in contrast
to that of Richard Nixon, entail the abuse of power,'' said Elliot
Richardson, who resigned as attorney general when President Nixon
tried to thwart the Watergate inquiry. But Adm. Leon Edney, who is
retired from the Navy, said the president's leadership of the
military ``must be based on principle, not litigious double talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing room was far from filled most of the day, with
louder outcries over impeachment to be heard in the corridors and
in the offices of members openly wondering how the Congress might
resolve such a firmly unpopular issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take control of this runaway train before we go over a
cliff,'' pleaded Senator-elect Charles Schumer of New York, finally
voicing before the hearing the Hill's growing Democratic chorus
that the incoming speaker, Robert Livingston, must step into a
momentous inquiry he has assiduously avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., countered: ``I am now asking
the president of the United States to help us.'' Come forward
before the American people, Graham pleaded. ``Do what these two
ladies have done,'' he continued as the two women sat mutely, as
they had to through most of the day's partisan speechifying. As
they finally were allowed to go, Graham saluted the two as ``real
people who've suffered real consequences for something that we're
all wrestling with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
