A7755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXXON-ACCOUNTING-NYT &LR;      12-01 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-ACCOUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXXON MOBIL TO ADOPT CONTROVERSIAL ACCOUNTING METHOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EXXON-MOBIL, EXXON-CULTURE, EXXON-ANTITRUST, EXXON-ASIA,
EXXON-DEAL, EXXON-CONSUMERS, EXXON-ASSESS.) 
(bl) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Exxon and Mobil merge their financial ledgers, executives
plan to use an accounting method that will leave no trace of the
$50 billion premium that Exxon has agreed to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the accounting method, known as a pooling of
interest, is not in the best interest of shareholders because it
does not hold executives accountable for their actions if the total
price they pay _ stock valued at $74 billion in Exxon's case _ is
too high.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that Exxon and Mobil are using an accounting
method usually reserved for merging companies of equal size, which
is clearly not the case here.
</P>
<P>
   And, some accounting analysts add that pooling restricts how the
new combined company can run many parts of its business. For
example, the new Exxon Mobil Corp. will not be able to sell more
than 10 percent of its assets in the next two years, even if such
sales make the best business sense, without imperiling the
accounting treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And, because of the decision to use pooling accounting, Exxon
must now end its popular program of buying back its own shares.
Under the pooling rules, a company is greatly restricted in how
much of its stock it can buy back from the market _ a practice many
companies use to help maintain the price of their shares.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pooling method, the two companies simply combine their
balance sheets. And in this case, the $50 billion premium that
Exxon has offered to pay for Mobil's oilfields, refineries and
other assets, based on the value recorded on Mobil's balance sheet,
simply disappears.
</P>
<P>
   If the companies were forced to use the other accounting method
_ known as purchase accounting _ the $50 billion premium would be
added to the balance sheet by writing up the value of current
assets. And, it would then reduce future earnings because most
assets must be written off over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission must still review the oil
companies' proposed accounting method and could decide that the
merger transaction does not meet the strict requirements of
pooling.
</P>
<P>
   If the oil companies were forced to use purchase accounting,
analysts estimate that the $50 billion premium would be written off
over 20 years. The result: Exxon Mobil Corp. would have to reduce
earnings by $2.5 billion a year for the next two decades. The
annual $2.5 billion write-off would have eaten up 21 percent of the
$11.7 billion that the two companies reported in combined profits
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a pretty good hit to earnings and could affect
the landscape,'' said Jay Wilson, an oil analyst at J.P. Morgan
Securities. ``But Exxon and Mobil are quite confident they will be
able to use pooling-of-interest accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   Two giant accounting firms, PricewaterhouseCoopers and Ernst &AMP;
Young, have reviewed the transaction, Wilson said, and have told
the oil companies that they believe pooling can be used. And Exxon
chief executive Lee Raymond said in an interview Tuesday that both
companies and their boards had looked at the accounting issue in
detail and believed that it would not be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies must still overcome some significant
obstacles. Antitrust lawyers and government officials have
predicted that federal regulators, concerned by the merged oil
company's great size, could force it to sell important pieces of
its business. And if those divestitures amount to more than 25
percent of the oil companies' assets, securities regulators could
then force them to use purchase accounting.
</P>
<P>
   By using pooling accounting, Exxon is also better able to keep
away any other company that may be interested in Mobil. Robert
Willens, a managing director at Lehman Brothers, a securities and
investment banking firm, said that a recent change in the
accounting rules greatly increases the expense for any third
company that now tries to make Mobil a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   Under Tuesday's agreement, Exxon and Mobil have agreed to a
special provision that would allow Exxon to purchase up to 14.9
percent of Mobil's stock if another company makes Mobil an offer,
making the deal more costly for that third company. Last year,
accounting rule makers decided that such a provision would also
stop the third party from using pooling accounting if its offer
proved successful, Willens said, which makes the provision a
powerful insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the oil companies' proposed deal, Exxon will give stock in
the new combined company to Mobil shareholders and will not pay
Mobil any cash. The all-stock deal has been structured so that
Mobil's stockholders will not owe taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If securities regulators later force the oil companies to use
purchase accounting, stockholders will still not be forced to pay
taxes, Willens said, because the tax rules are less onerous than
the accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Time may be running out for other companies that want to merge
and use pooling accounting. The nation's accounting rule makers,
concerned that the merger accounting rules are being abused, are
expected to propose new rules next year that would eliminate
pooling. Companies then would be left to use purchase accounting,
which is already the only available method in most of the rest of
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
