<HEADER>
A7756 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXXON-MOBIL-BOS &LR;      12-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXXON-MOBIL MARRIAGE WOULD BE RECORD BREAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Exxon Corp., America's biggest oil company, said
Tuesday it would buy its No. 2 rival, Mobil Corp., for more than
$80 billion in a deal that would reassemble key parts of John D.
Rockefeller's Standard Oil empire to cope with a worldwide oil
glut.
</P>
<P>
   If consummated, the combination would break records: In a year
of mammoth mergers, it would be the biggest of them all, topping
its closest rival, the $72 billion Citibank-Travelers deal, by as
much as $14 billion. It would create the largest publicly owned
energy company in the world, surpassing Royal Dutch/Shell Group,
and the largest publicly owned company in the world, vaulting past
General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the increasing globalization, companies are looking for
big, global scale, and this certainly is big, global scale,'' said
Harvard Business School professor Rosabeth Moss Kanter. ``It's not
just that they want to be big; they want to be big everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives with the two companies said the deal's chief
attraction was that it would allow the companies to save almost $3
billion in overlapping costs, much of it in wages. Analysts
predicted layoffs of up to 20,000 workers, or more than 15 percent
of the companies' combined work force of 123,000.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers wondered whether there was another motive for
the combination as well, the same one that drove Rockefeller to
snap up the nation's refineries and retail outlets in the late 19th
and early 20th centuries in an effort to control overproduction
that had driven down prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's not so different now,'' said Eleanor Fox, a
New York University law school authority on antitrust issues. ``The
companies say there is no (antitrust) problem because there is so
much exploration'' by others, Fox said. ``But exploration wasn't a
problem'' in Rockefeller's time either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem may be in refining and retail,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and others predicted that federal antitrust regulators would
scrutinize the deal for signs the combined company could use its
substantial market power to reduce competition and raise prices.
And they are likely to find such signs, since Exxon-Mobil would
have 48,500 gas stations worldwide, about one third of them in the
United States, and the capacity to produce 2.5 million barrels each
of oil and gas a day _ or more than the oil-rich nation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal will probably go through, but it will require selling
off some refineries and stations,'' said John H. Lichtblau,
chairman of the industry-financed Petroleum Industry Research
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said there was heavy overlap between Exxon and Mobil
gas stations in the Northeast, especially, New York and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said the combined firm would retain both of its
predecessors' well-known names by calling itself Exxon Mobil Corp.,
as well as their valuable logos, the Exxon tiger and Mobil's red
Pegasus. It would operate in 100 countries, have a stock market
value of $250 billion, and annual revenues of $178 billion, based
on last year's results.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the companies said, ``This merger will
enhance our ability to be an effective global competitor in a
volatile world economy and in an industry that is more and more
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal came as oil prices hit a 12-year low Tuesday, a
downward spiral that most industry experts had not expected and one
that is likely to have all sorts of economic effects in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil for delivery next January fell to $11.13 a barrel in
trading during the day. At its decade-high during the Persian Gulf
crisis in 1990, the price was more than $40 a barrel. The main
reason for falling prices is a worldwide glut of oil, the result of
overproduction by OPEC and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   On the postive side, analysts said, falling oil prices mean more
money in the pocket for American consumers and more maneuvering
room for Federal Reserve policymakers who have been trying to keep
the US economy growing without sparking renewed inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, analysts said the price declines would
hurt energy-producing nations like Mexico and could spark another
round of financial crises like the one that swept Asia and damaged
stock markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who think the recent stock market rally
doesn't make sense have been looking for another shoe to drop. This
could be it,'' said Kathleen M. Camilli, chief economist for the
brokerage firm Tucker Anthony in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Falling energy prices have already set off feverish
consolidation in the oil industry. In addition to the Exxon-Mobil
deal Tuesday, France's Total SA said it would buy Belgium's
Petrofina SA for $11.8 billion to create a new European oil giant.
In August, British Petroleum agreed to buy Amoco Corp., in a deal
now valued at $55 billion, according to Securities Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of Exxon and Mobil would reunite the two biggest
pieces of the Standard Oil monopoly that the US Supreme Court
ordered dismantled on antitrust grounds in 1911. And it would
extend a merger trend in industries that the government until
recently required be broken up or kept apart, especially in
telecommunications and banking.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the stock-and-debt deal, Exxon shareholders would
own about 70 percent of the combined company with Mobil
shareholders owning the remainig 30 percent. Because the deal would
involve swapping Mobil shares for Exxon shares, it was difficult to
set an exact price on the combination. Estimates ranged from $77
billion to more than $85 billion. Securities Data, one of the
financial industry's chief record keepers, said late Tuesday that
the deal was worth $86.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Exxon, based in Irving, Texas, fell 3 3/8 to 71 5/8
after news of the deal. Shares of Mobil, based in Fairfax, Va.,
dropped 2 1/4 to 83 3/4, reflecting the decline in the value of the
Exxon offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2039EST &QL; 
