<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNORS-WEST-BANK-B     12-01 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-WEST-BANK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS VIEW DISPUTED WEST BANK TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Texas Governor George W. Bush and Massachusetts
Governor Paul Cellucci chose Tuesday to view the rocky and disputed
hills of the West Bank from above the fray in a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Cellucci, and the Republican governors of Utah and Montana
are on a four-day visit to Israel at the invitation of the National
Jewish Coalition, a Washington-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   The governors met with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and top Israeli officials, including the legendary hawk and Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon served as tour guide for the four governors on the
helicopter ride, pointing out Israeli settlements on the disputed
West Bank land at issue in the tortuous peace process. He also
showed them the Israeli military ``security zones'' and valuable
aquifers in the West Bank that straddle Palestinian villages and
towns. Some 160,000 settlers live in the West Bank along with 1.5
million Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Israeli and US media reports that the governors canceled
a trip to West Bank settlements because of angry protests by
Palestinian leaders, Cellucci said that the helicopter briefly
touched down Tuesday at the Maale Efraim settlement. This
infuriated Palestinian officials, who charge that the expansion of
these settlements is undermining the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Tel Aviv before leaving Israel,
Cellucci said, ``From the air, the sense you get is just how close
everything is, how important the land is because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The US State Department has called for a freeze on building of
settlements and criticized Netanyahu and Sharon's aggressive
expansion of existing settlements as ``not helpful'' to the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing the media spotlight at each stop on the visit, Bush, a
likely presidential candidate, remained tight-lipped about his
opinions on the Mideast peace process and whether he would run for
president in 2000. He refused to hold any press conferences and
insisted on a news blackout, a posture that one Israeli Foreign
Ministry official called ``rather bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Bush's father, President George Bush, was
frequently at odds with the Israeli government over the issue of
expanding Jewish West Bank settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some questions about why they keep expanding the
settlements,'' said Cellucci. ``But having a chance to see their
locations, I have a better understanding for why that is happening.
They provide a buffer zone for where Israelis are living inside
Israel. They are strategic.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit also included a wreath-laying ceremony at the Yad
Vashem Holocaust Memorial and a visit to Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he was struck by the economic disparity between
the Jewish settlements and Palestinian villages that were visible
from the helicopter, but the delegation did not meet with any
Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows it is complicated here,'' said Cellucci. ``But
I got the sense everyone is determined to keep moving toward
peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
