<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR-ELECT SETS HOPES HIGH, PROFILE LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For months, Gray Davis was mocked as California's
slow but steady gubernatorial candidate. So it was perhaps fitting
that he made one of his first full-dress appearances as
governor-elect, at a news conference this week in the children's
department of the Los Angeles Central Library, in front of a
display copy of ``The Hare and the Tortoise.''
</P>
<P>
   But since his 20-point victory over state Attorney General Dan
Lungren a month ago, Davis has behaved more like a groundhog,
burrowing down in private and reviewing his options as he prepares
to take over from Gov. Pete Wilson in January. He surfaced at the
library on Monday only to announce his first staff appointment _
that of his education secretary, in keeping with his campaign
pledge to revitalize the state's sagging public schools.
</P>
<P>
   And just as Davis' calm caution served him well in a campaign
that many pundits initially said he could not win, so his low
profile seems to be helping him now as he moves to step up from
lieutenant governor, put together a new administration and cope
with a flood of pent-up demands from Democrats, who have not had a
governor from their party since Edmund Brown Jr. 16 years ago, and
from state employees, most of whom have not had raises since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago the state Legislature's chief fiscal adviser said
the new governor could face a $1.2 billion shortfall in the state
budget of about $75 billion that he will be required to outline
just a week after taking office on Jan. 4, and other officials have
said the gap may be even larger. Davis, who enjoyed major support
from the state's powerful teachers' union and has plans for new
programs like $10,000 merit raises for teachers who agree to stay
in the field, sounded a cautionary note this week about any
across-the-board raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be looking at very limited'' flexibility, said
the governor-elect, who was generally careful during his campaign
not to promise much in the way of specific spending.
</P>
<P>
   State economic experts said they did not believe that the
projected shortfall, driven by higher-than-expected Medicaid costs
and a slowing in economic growth, marked any major downturn in the
California economy, which continues to outpace the nation
significantly in job growth. Instead, they said, it amounts to a
fairly routine dip that could be made up by a strong Christmas
retail season and greater-than-expected income tax receipts next
spring, by the time the real budget is put together beginning in
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think California is substantially stronger than the nation,
so much so that we may be the engine that is preventing a national
recession,'' said Philip Romero, Wilson's chief economist. ``Much
has been made, and quite appropriately, of California exporters'
exposure to the Asian downturn. But they're only about 40 to 50
percent of exports, and the next-largest is Europe, which is
holding strong. And a couple of mainstay industries, like
entertainment and multimedia, have remained strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, with revenue running about $2 billion ahead of
projections, pressure grew for election-year tax cuts, and the
Legislature and Wilson agreed to a vehicle-fee reduction that will
trim about $1 billion in revenue from Davis' first full fiscal year
in office, which starts on July 1. So the wary budget projections
give Davis some welcome political running room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a genius'' to know that ``surpluses are a
rare occurrence, and they should be disposed of on a one-time
basis,'' Davis said. ``In my 25 years in public service, there may
have been three or four surpluses over that entire time of any
consequence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Romero added, ``Having some reason to take some time before
making major fiscal decisions has the added advantage of being a
good idea, given that there'll be a lot of good information
available in April and May.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Davis is concentrating on education, the issue
that polls showed ranked No. 1 among voter concerns. At his news
conference this week, he broke with incoming governors' usual
practice of introducing a chief of staff or a finance director as
the first appointee and instead named former state Sen. Gary Hart,
a friend and fraternity brother from their days at Stanford
University, as his chief education adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Hart, former chairman of the state Senate's Education Committee
and most recently co-director of the California State University
Institute for Education Reform, has long been an advocate of
class-size reduction and charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   The education secretary's post, which Wilson created in 1991 to
gain greater control over education policy, is only a quasi-Cabinet
position, since the Democratic-controlled Legislature has declined
to grant formal status to it. The school system is overseen by an
independently elected state superintendent of public instruction.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis said that whatever the title, Hart would be his chief
education policy adviser as he begins his term with a special
legislative session intended to focus on improving school
accountability, increasing teacher preparation and assuring that
every child learns to read by the end of the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced,'' Davis said, ``that a back-to-basics,
high-expectation approach to education will greatly enhance the
future prospects'' of California's schoolchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
