<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEMPORARILY SUSPENDS CONTROVERSIAL DEATH ROW PROGRAM THAT
CONTRIBUTED TO INMATE'S ESCAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Texas Criminal Justice Chairman Allan
Polunsky Tuesday temporarily suspended a controversial death row
work program that contributed to last week's escape of convicted
killer Martin Gurule.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule, who has been on the lam for five days, and six other
death row inmates who attempted to escape with him were members of
the work program, which granted them relatively free movement in
their prison unit.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule, 29, convicted of killing two Corpus Christi men during a
robbery, was employed as a janitor. He was the only inmate who
succeeded in escaping. The others gave up when guards began
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky said death row inmates in the work program now will be
placed in administrative segregation, which means they will spend
all but a few hours a day in their cells.
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky opposes the work program because, he said, it offers
privileges to undeserving inmates. But he noted that it is mandated
in the settlement of a major prison reform lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The state, he said, will review its options for modifying or
abolishing the work program in coming weeks, and a full report on
the program will be made to the criminal justice commission during
a January meeting in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Texas Department of Criminal Justice Executive
Director Wayne Scott said that after five days of unsuccessful
search, authorities will modify the way the hunt for Gurule is
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday, the nearly continuous dog searches will be
replaced by sporadic searches and officers stationed on roadways
will be moved in an effort to ``confuse'' Gurule.
</P>
<P>
   An emphasis will be placed on mobile patrols on area roadways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to search diligently,'' he said. ``We will
just use a different method.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said authorities believe Gurule remains within the 17,000
acres of prison property surrounding the Ellis Unit, which houses
the state's death row. But they believe he deliberately has refused
to move from his hiding place.
</P>
<P>
   By seemingly lessening the pressure, Scott said, ``We hope that
he will decide to move, make a mistake and be re-apprehended.''
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky also announced Tuesday that he will ask Gov. George W.
Bush to assign Texas Rangers and other Texas Department of Public
Safety personnel to the search, which already involves 500 officers
and dozens of search dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to assure the people of Texas that we will bring back
this fugitive,'' he said. ``We will bring him back dead or alive,
and there really is not any difference in my opinion which it might
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky, a San Antonio lawyer, has called for a full
investigation of last Friday's pre-dawn escape, to be conducted by
in-house and independent criminal justice experts.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal Justice Commissioner Alfred M. ``Max'' Stringfellow
said the investigation ``is not a witch hunt. There will be no
scapegoat. We know we have a problem. We need to find what we can
do to correct it, whether it was unique to this unit or is
systemwide.''
</P>
<P>
   One of TDCJ's top lawyers said Tuesday that the death row work
program guidelines place security as the main concern when inmates
are selected to work in the prison's garment factory. That means
inmates with assaultive histories and those deemed escape risks are
generally excluded from being designated ``work capable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ponchai Wilkerson, one of the six inmates who attempted to
escape with Gurule, was in the work program, despite having been
involved in a 1993 escape attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that (escape attempt) was sufficiently far enough
ago they thought he had seen the light,'' the lawyer said. ``They
were wrong. What can I say.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson is under a death sentence for the murder of the
43-year-old jewelry store owner, a slaying that occurred at the end
of a one-month crime binge in 1990 in which Wilkerson and
accomplices shot and wounded seven people in four different
incidents. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
