<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS SAY EVIDENCE LINKING BREAST IMPLANTS TO DISEASE IS
INSUFFICIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A panel of four scientists appointed by a federal court issued a
report Tuesday concluding that scientific evidence has so far
failed to show that silicone breast implants cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, experts in immunology, epidemiology, toxicology
and rheumatology, said that some of the research they reviewed was
flawed, and as a result, they could not absolutely rule out the
possibility that a link between implants and disease might one day
be established.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sam C. Pointer Jr. of the U.S. District Court in
Birmingham, Ala., who oversees breast implant lawsuits in the
federal courts, appointed the panel two years ago to provide expert
testimony that was independent of either side in the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's detailed report, several inches thick, was filed and
made public Tuesday and is available on a Web site:
(http://www.fjc.gov/BREIMLIT/mdl926.htm). Now the four scientists
will give depositions under oath about their findings, and their
testimony will be videotaped for use in federal courts where breast
implant cases have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Implant manufacturers who are defending the suits were delighted
with the report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   John McGoldrick, a senior vice president and general counsel at
the Bristol-Myers Squibb Company, which has 6,000 cases pending
against it, called the report ``very strong'' and said it would
have ``significant impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Panel members ``have done their homework,'' he said, adding, ``I
think their conclusions are clear, and I don't think that will
change.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sybil Goldrich, a lawyer with implants who was a founder of
an advocacy group for women with implants, criticized the panel.
She said it had focused too closely on scientific studies and had
not paid enough attention to the experiences of individual women
with implants.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Robert Garry, a professor of microbiology and immunology
at Tulane University Medical School in New Orleans emphasized that
``nowhere does it say that implants are safe or that they don't
cause disease.'' He said that at this point there are ``still many
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel members, he said, ``very much leave open the question
as to whether these devices cause disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Implant makers concede that many women develop scar tissue or
even inflammation in their breasts after receiving implants, and
that the implants can rupture. But the litigation involves
assertions that the silicone in the implant can cause systemic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   As the litigation has gone on, settlements have been negotiated
between makers of the devices and women who say implants made them
ill. Some of the women now must choose between accepting
settlements or pursuing their cases, with the knowledge that the
courts will be relying on the report issued Tuesday. It was not
immediately clear how many plaintiffs would continue to press their
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as damaging a report from the plaintiffs' point
of view as I can imagine,'' said Michael Green, a law professor at
the University of Iowa who said he has no connection with the
implant litigation, but who studies the use of scientific evidence
in toxic substance litigation. ``If I were a plaintiffs' lawyer,
I'd be beside myself,'' he added. As a consequence of the report,
Green said, ``I think it will be hard to find a federal judge who
will permit a case to be tried or who will sustain on post trial
motions a plaintiff's claims to systemic disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Williams, a plaintiffs' lawyer in Portland, Ore., who
represents about 150 women with implants, said that the report
``will make it more difficult to get to juries and more difficult
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Law experts interviewed about the report cited its blunt
assessments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the toxicology section, written by Dr. Nancy
Kerkvliet, an immunotoxicologist at Oregon State University,
concluded that ``there is no evidence that silicone breast implants
precipitate novel immune responses or induce systemic
inflammation.''
</P>
<P>
   The immunology section, written by Dr. Betty A. Diamond of the
Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx, N.Y., concluded
that, ``women with silicone breast implants do not display a
silicone-induced systemic abnormality in the types or functions of
cells of the immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   The epidemiology section, written by Dr. Barbara S. Hulka, who
is chairwoman of the epidemiology department at the University of
North Carolina in Chapel Hill, reported that even when studies were
combined and analyzed together there was ``no evidence'' of a
relationship between implants and connective tissue diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The rheumatology section, written by Dr. Peter Tugwell, who is
professor and chairman of the department of medicine at the
University of Ottowa, noted that ``breast implant patients have
reported a diversity of signs and symptoms that are also associated
with rheumatic or autoimmune diseases.'' But, Dr. Tugwell added,
``For each sign or symptom showing an association with breast
implants in a given study, other studies showed no association.''
</P>
<P>
   In his instructions to the panel, Judge Pointer asked not only
for a review of the research on implants but also for an assessment
of whether the scientists' conclusions would be subject to
challenge from other experts. In their report, the panelists noted
that while some might disagree with their findings, ``It is our
informed opinion that the large majority of scientists in our
respective disciplines would find merit in our reviews and
analyses.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the fate of lawsuits involving thousands of women could be
determined by the panel's conclusions, every effort was made to
keep its members at arms' length from the dueling parties. The cost
of the panel, about, $800,000, was borne by the Federal Judicial
Center in Washington. And neither side in the implant litigation
was allowed to contact the scientists while they weighed the
evidence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of conflicting evidence in the breast implant
cases,'' explained Abel Mattos, the chief of court administration
policy staff of the administrative office of the United States
courts. ``Judge Pointer's role was to try to figure out a way to
cut through all this and to get a totally objective group of
scientists who had not been involved in the fray.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal rules of evidence allow judges to appoint
experts, few have done so and none has invested so much in getting
the opinions of an independent panel, Mattos said. But, he said,
the judicial center was eager to help because it saw the implant
litigation as a perfect test case for the use of expert panels.
``The hope is that it could save potentially millions of dollars in
trial time and lawyers; time,' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The report took two years to produce, during which time the
panel members sifted through about 2000 documents submitted by the
implant makers and the lawyers representing women with implants and
questioned scientists who argued for and against the theory that
implants cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   After the report was made public Tuesday, a telephone press
conference was convened by Fenton Communications, a public
relations agency that represents women with implants.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Diana Zuckerman, who is on the board of the National Women's
Health Network, an advocacy group, and did postdoctoral work in
epidemiology at Yale University, focused on the epidemiology. Dr.
Hulka, she said, ``did a good job of answering the question she was
asked, Is there evidence of disease? But that is a different
question than, Is there evidence that these women were healthy?''
And, she added, ``I think the conclusion here is we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goldrich said in the press conference that the real evidence
that implants are dangerous is in the women's medical records,
which are sealed in courtrooms. ``That's where the secret is, the
secret is in these real people who have these products and not in a
bunch of esoteric studies that really don't address the things that
people need to address,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Green, the Iowa law professor, explained in a telephone
interview that to win a case, plaintiffs' lawyers have to go beyond
showing that it is possible that implants might be associated with
disease in some future studies. Instead, he said, lawyers have to
show it is more likely than not that the devices caused a
particular woman to become ill. In general, he said, courts have
looked for evidence that a person's risk of disease is doubled
because of a device or drug.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Knowles, a plaintiffs' lawyer from Atlanta who was a
participant in the Fenton press conference, said, ``we're obviously
disappointed,'' by the report. But, he said, ``we think everybody
should hold their fire,'' until he and other plaintiffs' lawyers
have a chance to question the panel members in depositions. Then,
he said, he expects to ``ask some questions that we think might
yield a different result than someone might perceive in just
reading the report.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Williams, the plaintiffs' lawyer, noted that the
biggest study yet is still under way. That study, involving 13,500
women and directed by Dr. Louise Brinton of the National Cancer
Institute, will be published early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Brinton doesn't find anything, then probably that will put
an end to most of the litigation,'' Williams said. ``But, on the
other hand, if she does find something, then the tables will
turn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
