<SLUG> BC-GLENN-INTERVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Glenn still glowing after historic space mission
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Glenn said Tuesday he's ``still in the
glow'' of last month's space shuttle mission, even as the
earth-bound duties of a retiring Senator and American icon have
beset him.
</P>
<P>
   In his first meeting with Ohio reporters since he became the
oldest man in space, the 77-year-old Glenn talked with animation
and humor about his nine days in orbit; the medical exams he still
must endure to chart his body's reaction to that flight; and the
upcoming launch of the John Glenn Institute for Public Service and
Public Policy at Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said that he was back to feeling normal by the fourth day
after his Nov. 7 landing, having regained his sense of balance,
which was slow to readjust to earth's gravity. He said he now feels
no lingering ill effects of his nine days of weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that way,'' Glenn said. ``Now they're still analyzing
whether I really am that way.'' After weeks of medical tests back
on Earth, Glenn still must undergo extensive exams 30, 60, 90 and
180 days after his shuttle flight ended. Doctors want to know if
the weakening of muscle and bone, common among astronauts after
long stays in zero gravity, reverses in an elderly man like Glenn
the way it does in younger astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever those test results show, Glenn seemed nearly as happy
as he was during his free-floating days aboard the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at length about the almost church-like quality of
looking out a space shuttle window at the blue Earth set against
the blackness of space, The word ``awesome'' may be overused, he
said, but it aptly described the view he saw.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked if he could have landed the shuttle himself,
Glenn _ an accomplished pilot but the lowest-ranking crew member,
who didn't touch the flight systems _ said confidently, ``Of
course!''
</P>
<P>
   Then he dryly added a common boast of old-school test pilots:
``I could fly the box it came in!''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Glenn will make his first public appearance in
Washington since the shuttle flight when he attends a gala in his
honor at the National Air and Space Museum. The event, sponsored by
Ohio State University, is being billed as the kick-off for Glenn's
``next mission,'' the school's institute in his name.
</P>
<P>
   OSU President William Kirwan, who joined Glenn for Tuesday's
press conference, talked about the school's desire to create a
program of study in public service that rivals the John F. Kennedy
School of Government at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need a center like that in the Midwest,'' Kirwan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenn school will differ from the Kennedy school's
policy-heavy curriculum by focusing on developing citizenship and
community activism among students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use this institute as really a catalyst to excite
our young people about public service, volunteerism,'' Kirwan said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Glenn school will cater to undergraduates, rather than
the graduate student programs at Kennedy. The school will seek to
establish internship programs in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, policy issues will be part of the Glenn school,
especially topics that interested Glenn during his 24 years in the
Senate. For instance, the school plans a ``major conference'' next
fall to discuss the spread of weapons of mass destruction around
the globe, something Glenn made a focal point of his Senate career.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which was unveiled in October and will open in
January, is getting the Washington gala treatment to raise its
profile among heavyweight policy makers and potential corporate
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenn Institute has been added to a list of projects to be
supported by a $1 billion fund-raising campaign at OSU called
Affirm Thy Friendship. The Glenn school's $20 million start-up cost
will come from a mix of those funds as well as other OSU budget
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
