<SLUG> BC-OHIO-WEATHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This is Fall? Miami Valley residents enjoy Indian summer
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's about the time of year when ice skates and
snow sleds probably should be going into action. But around the
Miami Valley, it's the in-line skates and golf clubs that are
getting a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nov. 9, Dayton has had only three days when the high
temperate was less than 50 degrees, and that pattern is expected to
persist at least through Saturday when highs in the upper 50s are
predicted, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll often have an Indian summer warm spell in the fall here,
but it usually doesn't last as long as it has this year,'' said
Jeffrey Sites, lead forecaster for the National Weather Service
post in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Sites said the band of upper atmosphere winds called the jet
stream usually is perched over Ohio at this time of year. But the
jet stream currently is positioned farther north over Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``So instead of cold Canadian wind coming off the Great Lakes,
we get warmer air blowing in from the South,'' Sites said.
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with Kent Bobo, manager of Larch Tree Golf
operations in Madison Twp. ``We've been booked solid every day,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've even had to turn people away the last couple of
weekends. We're hoping this weather lasts until next April and that
then it starts to warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Leiwig, director of the Greene County Recreation, Parks and
Cultural Arts Department, said people taking advantage of the warm
weather are keeping park patrols and maintenance crews busy. Greene
County has more than 50 paved miles of paved bike paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at summer levels, but plenty of people are out every
day on in-line skates and bicycles,'' Leiwig said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Snyder, president of Groby's Garden Center and Florists,
said the weather is affecting plants but that serious damage is not
likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some flower bulbs have started to sprout, thinking it's
spring,'' she said. ``When it gets cold, the tops of those plants
will turn yellow, but it won't hurt them. Mother Nature will take
care of them, and they'll flower normally next spring.''
</P>
<P>
   One plant that is no longer a problem this year is ragweed,
according to Dr. Arturo Bonnin of the Allergy and Asthma Centre of
Dayton. Ragweed, a major irritant to some people, mostly died with
the first mild frost earlier this fall, Bonnin said.
</P>
<P>
   People sensitive to molds, however, still might be having a hard
time, Bonnin said. Molds grow on organic material outdoors in
moderate weather, and Bonnin said he's had lots of patients
recently complaining of allergy symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   He said outdoor molds will keep growing until hit by one or two
heavy frosts.
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather is generally good news for utility bill payers.
Neil Costello, managing director of Dayton Power and Light Co.,
said electrical consumption for November was 3 percent to 5 percent
below normal. But natural gas usage, which is more sensitive to
weather-related fluctuations, was down 20 percent from the average
November.
</P>
<P>
   The warm weather has had a chilling effect on snow blower sales,
according to Heil Brothers Lawn and Garden Equipment in Kettering
and Buchanan Power Equipment Center Inc. in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually by this time, people have come in to have snow plows
attached to their tractors,'' said Gary Campbell, Buchanan's
assistant manager. ``But they're still working on their yards.
They're pulling garden carts around and cutting the grass and
chopping up the leaves one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-01-98 2022E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
