u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-CURRIE-COX     12-01 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-CURRIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weather may delay flight for Currie
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla._ Former Troy, Ohio resident Nancy
Currie has been waiting for Thursday's scheduled space shuttle
launch for more than two years, but bad weather might make her wait
a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   Currie is one of six astronauts scheduled to lift off at 3:59
a.m. Thursday in space shuttle Endeavour. Their nearly 12-day
mission: To assemble the first pieces of the International Space
Station _ the Russian-built Zarya control module already in orbit,
and the Unity connecting node in Endeavour's payload bay.
</P>
<P>
   Because Endeavour must rendezvous with another orbiting object,
its launch ``window'' _ the time in which it can lift off and get
into the right orbit _ is unusually tight. If anything delays
Thursday's launch more than 10 minutes, NASA will have to wait
until Friday morning to try again.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook Tuesday wasn't promising.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Clif Stargardt, an Air Force meteorologist who produces
forecasts for space launches, said unstable local weather is likely
to produce low cloud ceilings and showers at launch time.
</P>
<P>
   Thundershowers producing lightning Wednesday afternoon could
even prevent the launch team from fueling the shuttle's enormous
external tank with flammable liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite the cheery forecast we've had the last few
missions,'' Stargardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Stargardt said the forecast calls for similar weather Friday,
but is expected to improve for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Longer delays could put the shuttle launch in conflict with a
Delta rocket launch set to blast an unmanned spacecraft towards
Mars on Dec. 12, shuttle program manager Tommy Holloway said. If
Endeavour doesn't launch before Dec. 8, he said, the launch might
be rescheduled for early January.
</P>
<P>
   This mission has already been beset with delays.
</P>
<P>
   NASA named the crew members for the mission in 1996, when the
launch was scheduled for December 1997. Delays in other parts of
the space station program pushed that launch date to last July,
then September.
</P>
<P>
   The space shuttle itself is in good shape, launch director Bob
Sieck said. The myriad mechanical systems of the 2,250-ton rocket
are ``behaving well,'' he said. The only mechanical glitch so far
was an electronic device that drives instrument displays in the
orbiter. It was replaced and didn't affect the countdown, Sieck
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once in space, Endeavour will chase down the Russian space
station module until they are about 10 feet apart. At that point,
it will be Currie's job to grab it with the shuttle's robotic arm
and position it for mating with the Unity node.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Currie said the job is especially difficult
because it will be a ``blind'' grab. Her view blocked by the Unity
node, she will depend on TV monitors and a computerized space
vision device to tell whether the 41-foot-long, 22-ton Zarya module
is in the right position for docking.
</P>
<P>
   Once positioned, Endeavour will fire its jets to shove the two
modules together.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Currie's third space flight, but it will be her
most challenging yet, she said. Besides using the shuttle's arm to
position hardware, she will be using it to move two astronauts
around on three spacewalks as they hook up dozens of cables and
mount equipment on the space station modules.
</P>
<P>
   But all of more than 30 shuttle flights scheduled for
construction of the space station will be tough, said Frank
Culbertson, space station operations manager and a former
astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a shade of what's to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
