<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-REPUBS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS RE-ELECT THEIR LEADERSHIP TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c. N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting themselves apart from their raucous
colleagues in the House, Senate Republicans left their leadership
untouched on Tuesday and approved the same crop of experienced
senators to lead them into the next elections in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the one contested leadership race, Sen. Mitch McConnell of
Kentucky, who was the Senate Republicans' chief fund-raiser and
election strategist, fended off a challenge by Sen. Chuck Hagel of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, the chairman of the National Republican Senatorial
Committee and a vehement opponent of overhauling the campaign
finance laws, won the race by a vote of 39 to 13, a reflection of
his fund-raising expertise and the uneasiness of many Republicans
with Hagel's relative inexperience as a first-term senator. The
position will be especially important in 2000 because Republicans
will have 19 seats to defend while only 14 Democrats are up for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to McConnell, a three-term senator who had the
backing of the majority leader, Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, was
heralded by some, especially a small group of conservative junior
senators, as a sign of dissatisfaction with the leadership and its
election strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, McConnell's years of experience and
fund-raising prowess prevailed. For the 1998 elections, McConnell's
campaign committee raised more than $77 million, slightly more than
was raised by his predecessor, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Republican leadership was re-elected without
opposition: Lott; the assistant majority leader, Don Nickles of
Oklahoma; the Republican Conference chairman, Connie Mack of
Florida, and the Republican policy chairman, Larry Craig of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need to introduce our leadership team here today
because it is the same leadership group we've had for Republicans
in the Senate, and I think that is news in itself,'' Lott told
reporters at a news conference after the election.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the House, where the post-election turmoil led to Rep.
Newt Gingrich's resignation as speaker, and the defeat of Rep. John
Boehner of Ohio as chairman of the Republican Conference, Lott and
his colleagues survived virtually unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this was because Senate Republicans fared better in the
November elections than their House counterparts. Republicans lost
five House seats, but neither gained nor lost seats in the Senate.
The leaders' hold on their positions also reflects the chamber's
more deliberative, less stormy nature.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders faced no opposition in their re-election bids
on Tuesday, but several senators were promoted. Sen. Robert
Torricelli of New Jersey will replace Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska
as chief fund-raiser. And Sen. Harry Reid, who survived a tight
race in Nevada, will take over as whip for Sen. Wendell Ford of
Kentucky, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota will remain the Democratic
leader.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the absence of challenges for the other leadership positions
in the Senate, it was the challenge to McConnell that garnered the
most attention. McConnell drew fire from a few Republican senators
who said that he had been too focused in the general election on an
effort to defeat Sen. Russell Feingold, a leading sponsor of
campaign finance legislation, at the expense of other races.
Feingold, D-Wis., was re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel, a telegenic decorated veteran of the Vietnam War who was
elected to the Senate in 1996, announced his challenge to McConnell
last week, speaking out against ``constant, demonizing, negative
campaigning.'' He also advocated de-emphasizing the ``soft money''
donations _ unlimited, unregulated contributions given directly to
political parties by corporations, labor unions and individuals _
that McConnell has deftly solicited.
</P>
</TEXT>
