<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      12-01 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT INVESTIGATION SHIFTS TO CLINTON'S CAMPAIGN FUND-RAISING
EFFORTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-led House Judiciary Committee opened
a new front Tuesday in its impeachment investigation of President
Clinton, shifting its focus to the president's campaign
fund-raising efforts in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The party-line vote to expand the committee's sex-and-perjury
inquiry drew howls of protest from Democrats who claimed that the
impeachment probe is ``in chaos'' and has been ``hijacked by the
extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadening the investigation ``is the last desperate gasp of a
group of people who are determined to impeach the president and
haven't yet gotten their way,'' said committee member Barney Frank,
a Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Pausing during a hearing choreographed to underscore the
seriousness of perjury, the committee voted 20-15 to subpoena
evidence from the Justice Department's two-year investigation of
campaign fund-raising irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seeking internal Justice Department memos which a
federal judge last week refused to let impeachment investigators
review, the committee approved subpoenas to secure testimony from
FBI Director Louis Freeh and federal prosecutor Charles LaBella.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also voted to subpoena evidence gathered by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr from John Huang, a former
Democratic fund-raiser who agreed to cooperate with Starr's
criminal investigation of the president in return for immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically targeted by the subpoenas are memos written by
Freeh in November 1997 and by LaBella in July and August 1998. The
documents lay out evidence of campaign fund-raising activities by
the president that Freeh and LaBella claim need investigation by an
independent counsel. LaBella is former head of the Justice
Department's campaign fund-raising task force.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who has refused to seek appointment
of an outside prosecutor to examine campaign fund raising, has
declined to disclose the contents of the memos, citing the need for
grand jury secrecy. The same position was taken last week by U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, who has overseen Starr's
grand jury investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Committee sources said Johnson issued a sealed ruling on Friday
denying a committee request to release the memos. She said the
documents were not relevant enough to the committee's impeachment
investigation to outweigh the need to keep grand jury matters
secret. By expanding the impeachment inquiry and adding the weight
of a subpoena, committee Republicans hope to change the judge's
mind, one source said.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief debate over issuing the subpoenas, committee
Chairman Henry Hyde argued that information received by committee
investigators indicates the Freeh and LaBella memos contain
information that should be included in the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The documents we're seeking ... have been kept in the deep
freeze,'' said Hyde, R-Ill. ``We just want to look at the documents
... and to see whether they lead to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said the agency ``will
work with the committee in every way possible, consistent with the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote to take the investigation beyond Clinton's effort to
hide his White House affair with former intern Monica Lewinsky
comes weeks before the committee's self-imposed, end-of-the-year
deadline to finish work. Until Tuesday, the committee had hoped to
vote on articles of impeachment late next week so the full House
could decide before Christmas whether to turn the case over to the
Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde insisted that the expansion of the investigation would not
change his deadline. ``I have absolutely committed myself to
wrapping this up this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing recent predictions from Republican moderates that the
impeachment issue would never survive a House vote, Democrats said
Tuesday's decision is an effort to prop up a faltering inquiry and
shows that the most conservative elements of the Republican Party
had seized control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is becoming an impeachment inquiry in search of a high
crime,'' complained Michigan Rep. John Conyers, the committee's
ranking Democrat. He called Tuesday's vote ``a rather desperate
attempt to breathe new life into a dying inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., wrote House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and incoming Speaker Bob Livingston _ who
takes over House leadership next month _ urging them to intervene.
``I fear that this investigation is in chaos due to the lack of
direction,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said Judiciary
Committee Republicans appear to be ``using the powers of the
committee to pursue a totally political end'' by opening an inquiry
into a topic already explored by two separate congressional
committees that found no wrongdoing by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a bad rerun of a show nobody wanted to watch the
first time,'' Lockhart said of the Judiciary Committee vote. ``My
guess is that ... committee has been hijacked by the extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's hearing, only the second public session held by the
full committee, saw a small parade of convicted perjurers, appeals
court judges, retired military brass and law professors. They
agreed that perjury or lying under oath, no matter who commits it
or why, is corrosive and should be punished without favor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 11 witnesses were divided over whether
Clinton committed perjury when he misled attorneys in Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit. And, if he did, whether that should be
enough for the House to impeach him and the Senate to remove him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perjury has gradations. Some are serious, some are less,''
said A. Leon Higginbotham, a former federal appeals judge. For
impeachment purposes, Higginbotham said, lying about a sexual
affair is about the same as lying about exceeding the speed limit
in a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because a president is not a king, he or she must abide by the
same laws as the rest of us,'' said Barbara Battalino, a former
Veterans Affairs psychologist who was convicted of perjury after
lying about a sexual relationship with a patient.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is not impeached, Battalino said, then he should
grant her a presidential pardon. ``If indeed there is no reason for
anything ... more than censure, then certainly I would hope that
the administration would consider leniency for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Navy Adm. Leon A. Edney testified that military forces
are weakened when their ethical guidelines are flouted by a
commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership of our armed forces must be based on principle,
not litigious double-talk,'' said Edney, who teaches ethics at the
U.S. Naval Academy. ``Military readiness and mission accomplishment
depends on trust and confidence in the integrity of the leader.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
