<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nixon coming back to Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves grew a little older Tuesday. They
also grew far deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Nixon is returning to the club after a five-year absence,
and Ozzie Guillen, who bailed the Braves out of a shortstop problem
last season, also agreed to terms, bringing to 16 the players now
under contract for next season. Together, Atlanta signed up 30
years of major league experience at a combined age of 73.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess from an experience standpoint, that's good,'' general
manager John Schuerholz said. ``From an age standpoint, that maybe
a little. ... But those guys really make our bench. Our bench is
going to be very strong and very versatile.''
</P>
<P>
   To make room on the 40-man roster, the team released outfielder
Curtis Pride and placed shortstop prospect Glenn Williams on
outright waivers. Pride appeared in 70 games last year and hit .252
but was a disappointing pinch-hitter at .184.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who will turn 40 next month, agreed to a one-year
contract after hitting .297 last season in Minnesota, which tied
his career-high average reached with the Braves in 1991. As a
Brave, he hit .286 with 160 stolen bases in his three Atlanta
seasons but has slowed little in the five years since, batting .284
with 242 steals in subsequent seasons with Boston, Texas, Toronto,
Los Angeles and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   His 37 steals in 1998 ranked eighth in the American League and
his .361 on-base percentage surpassed all Braves regulars except
Chipper Jones, Walt Weiss and Andres Galarraga. Nixon joins Ryan
Klesko, Brian Jordan and Gerald Williams as outfielders signed for
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings to us exactly the package we were looking for,''
Schuerholz said. ``A guy who can steal, with a high on-base
percentage, creates some tension for the other team when he's on
base, a guy we know, a guy who played well for us before. He was
sort of a perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, who hit .277 while starting in 58 games at short when
Weiss was hurt, became a critical component after being picked up
in May following his release in Baltimore. Though several clubs
showed interest this winter in picking up the 34-year-old, the
Braves made a two-year offer to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
