<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7810 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAMI-GAYS-2NDTAKE-NY     12-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-GAYS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MIAMI: from discrimination.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven states, 27 counties and 136 cities have passed
anti-discrimination laws protecting gays, and fewer than 10 of the
laws have been repealed, said the Human Rights Campaign, a national
advocacy organization on gay issues. Although some studies have
shown few claims are filed under the laws, partly because many gay
men and women are reluctant to publicly reveal their sexual
orientation, supporters of the ordinances say they deter unfair
treatment and set a tone that encourages similar policies in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at Tuesday's hearing included gay police officers,
attorneys and others who related instances of harassment in the
workplace and job opportunities lost because of their
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people see 1977 as the beginning of the rise of the
extreme right in this country, with a real focus on anti-gay
rhetoric. This shows how far we've come toward basic fairness for
gay Americans,'' said Elizabeth Birch, executive director of Human
Rights Campaign, speaking from Washington, D.C. ``This is a
wonderful victory for Miami-Dade County but it's a watershed
victory for gays and lesbians nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a gay rights ordinance in Miami was a particular
thorn for the gay rights movement because Miami had been the first
major urban area in the country to pass legislation protecting
homosexuals. But that show of leadership was severely eroded when
Ms. Bryant, then a singer, advertising personality and devout
Baptist who lived in Miami Beach but had a national reputation, led
a campaign to repeal a gay rights law county commissioners passed
in 1977, calling it an attempt to legitimize ``a perverse and
dangerous'' lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   At one point she argued the law was a license for homosexuals to
recruit and molest children.
</P>
<P>
   The law was repealed by voters by a margin of more than 2 to 1
that year _ but it also undermined the career of Ms. Bryant, who
took her campaign to other states. She lost entertainment
engagements and was dropped as spokeswoman of the Florida Citrus
Commission in orange juice ads. Efforts to reach Ms. Bryant by
telephone were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The issue remained dormant until last year, when a county
commissioner introduced a gay rights bill that did not survive to
the a public hearing stage or progress to a final commission vote.
Supporters regrouped in the last 18 months, and say they are
prepared to fight a repeal effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we turned the corner today as a community,''
Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas, who had urged a ``yes'' vote,
said. ``We're much more progressive, tolerant and mature.''
</P>
<P>
   It is striking, however, that it took the ordinance 21 years to
resurface in an area that encompasses cities like Miami Beach,
where homosexuals are an integral part of the culture. Gay rights
advocates say other priorities, such as the area's need to absorb
wave after wave of immigrants, have put issues such as gay rights
in the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   But for those like the Cuban-born Hazday, who has lived here for
25 years, the Anita Bryant campaign is etched in memory. He said he
was a college freshman when ``I saw the hatred and division Anita
Bryant brought to our county.'' He added, ``I promised myself next
time I would get involved,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
