 &UR; ENTREPRENEUR PACKAGE &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WEB  &LR; _ When the Starr Report was released in September, Palo Alto
resident Ron Jones got the bright idea of building a Web site to
sell marshmallows printed with images of political figures.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' e-business, Mellow Out Co.  &LR; (www.politicalroasters.com),
 &LR; began selling marshmallows for $1 a pop on October 1. The company
already has recovered its startup costs. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW  &LR; _ Question: How does a small business get clients to pay
on time. I sell document templates to law firms and don't have a
large cash flow. Most clients pay on time (within 15 days) but
some, notably the larger ones, ignore the invoice date and pay when
they feel like it, in 45 to 60 days. Columnist Peter Sinton has the
answer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7812 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      12-01 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Get Clients to Pay on Time  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  How does a small business get clients to pay on time. I
sell document templates to law firms and don't have a large cash
flow. Most clients pay on time (within 15 days) but some, notably
the larger ones, ignore the invoice date and pay when they feel
like it, in 45 to 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Collection chores for small businesses have been
compared to the duty of parents to change their kids' diapers.
Someone has to do it, but no one wants to.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, it sounds like more of an annoyance than calamity,
which is good. Given your clientele, you probably want to avoid
legal action. But experts say there are other steps you can take to
improve the process:
</P>
<P>
   _You might change the terms of your engagement letter. For
example, require more payment up front and less on delivery of the
final product.
</P>
<P>
   _Big companies are often notorious for paying late, partly
because they are governed by inflexible computer systems and
accounting programs. But that doesn't mean you can't be a squeaky
wheel and call until you get results. Alice Magos, small-business
analyst for Chicago's CCH Inc., which publishes how-to books,
suggests phoning the accounting department, not the purchasing
agent or person you normally do business with.
</P>
<P>
   _Offer incentives for paying early or disincentives for paying
late. Magos notes that car parts and other businesses sometimes
offer terms like ``2 percent 10 days Net 30,'' meaning a 2 percent
discount on the bill if the customer pays within 10 days instead of
30. That might be attractive in service businesses too, especially
to smaller customers who are trying to save money. Conversely, you
might impose a carrying charge if the bill is not paid in 60 or 90
days.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of these tactics will guarantee payment, prompt
or otherwise. There are books and Web sites filled with information
and form letters to improve your chances of extracting money from
customers. For starters, check Nolo Press ( &LR; www.nolo.com &LR; ) and CCH
( &LR; www.toolkit.cch.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Surviving Success
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you do when success overwhelms you? The phone is
ringing off the hook, but I don't want to hire anyone to help me as
I don't have the time to supervise them.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a dilemma but better than many of the problems facing
budding businesses, and luckily you have a bunch of options.
</P>
<P>
   A simple solution, but not necessarily the best for your
long-term prospects, is get extra choosy about whom you want to do
business with or even raise your prices or rates.
</P>
<P>
   A better option might be to hire someone to answer your phone.
That should not take much training, although you should still set
aside a specific time every day to respond to the calls.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring employees involves keeping track of state, federal,
Social Security and Medicare taxes and periodic filings that will
just about double your paperwork, according to CPA Bernard
Kamaroff, author of the best-seller ``Small Time Operator'' (Bell
Springs Publishing, 1998, $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   As a simpler alternative, he recommends the independent
contractor route and hiring an answering service. Be sure you
understand the differences between an employee and outside
contractor. For example, the Internal Revenue Service is likely to
consider a person an employee rather than independent contractor if
the person uses your materials and equipment, receives on-the-job
training, works on your premises, hires or supervises your workers,
and receives health insurance, vacation pay or similar employee
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the phone problem, Kamaroff suggests you might find
someone in a similar business and subcontract with that person to
provide service to your customers, much as building contractors
farm out work when they get swamped. You can then take back this
business as you hire more employees when your business expands.
</P>
<P>
   For more personal help, marketing consultant Jay Levinson
suggests calling the Service Corps of Retired Executives, whose
volunteers also are sometimes independent contractors. Temp firms
might also provide some help.
</P>
<P>
   Catching Customers
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the best way for a small consulting business that
provides a specialized technical/ professional service to obtain
clients when first starting out? I don't think cold-calling works.
</P>
<P>
   A: If your service is related to a specific product or
technology, you might talk to manufacturers about becoming a
resource for them. Many companies have ``technical support''
personnel, but their time and expertise are limited, according to
San Francisco career counselor and author Marty Nemko (``Cool
Careers for Dummies,'' IDG Books, $16.99). To help their customers
and take some of the hassle out of providing support services
themselves, companies might want to use you as a certified or
recommended consultant if you can demonstrate your competence and
show that referrals will be in the company's interest as well as
yours.
</P>
<P>
   You might also develop ``cross- referral'' relationships with
consultants in related fields. For example, if you are a wine
fermentation specialist, you might know or get to know an expert in
vineyard pest control whom you could refer clients to, and vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   Nemko also encourages attending professional conferences to make
contacts, or better yet, make a presentation. If you are
uncomfortable before a crowd, consider writing an article for a
trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Networking in any business is important. Make a list of people
you know in related fields, let them know what you are doing and
mention if they are in a situation where it might be appropriate to
mention your consulting business, you would appreciate it.
``There's no more powerful way to get business than for someone to
recommend you,'' says Nemko.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7813 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      12-01 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tech Rebound Puts Investors, Researchers in the Holiday Mood  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Perhaps technology investors have been nipping at the egg nog a tad
early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because suddenly these once-sober folks are starting to believe
that this is going to be a merry Christmas after all, and that 1999
could indeed be a happy new year.
</P>
<P>
   This resurgent holiday spirit is not about being naughty or
nice, either. Tech investors and researchers are simply starting to
think _ perhaps prematurely _ that personal computer sales could
continue their current boomlet well into next year, which would
kick-start sales of software, hardware, chips and computer-related
services.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel, Dell and Microsoft soared like St. Nick's
sleigh over a rooftop yesterday buoyed by anecdotal accounts of
robust PC sales across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Intel saw its shares vault $7.37, or 6.9 percent, to $115.
Shares of computer-maker Dell jumped $4 to $64.81, while Microsoft
stock soared $7.50 to close at $129.50.
</P>
<P>
   And believe it or not, nowhere is the glow of holiday PC sales
being felt more warmly than here in arid Arizona, where Credit
Suisse First Boston is holding a cozy confab for institutional
investors and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Who says you have to stroll through Union Square to get in the
mood for Christmas shopping?
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Scottsdale seems to be working well for this group of fund
managers. This is CS First Boston's first holiday party with its
new technology banking team led by Frank Quattrone, Bill Brady and
George Boutros _ defectors from the ol' Deutsche Morgan Grenfell
unit.
</P>
<P>
   And needless to say, these rather well-compensated Santa's
helpers are giving their clients opportunities to do some early
window shopping for future purchases for their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, while spirits among techies have been lifted, by no
means is the conference brimming with unbridled euphoria. It's just
that things are looking a little brighter than they were, say, in
August, says CS First Boston's director of research Michael
Kwatinetz.
</P>
<P>
   Because the weeklong salon is held shortly before many companies
implement self-imposed gag orders toward the end of the fourth
quarter, ``this is really an important week to get your hands
around things,'' Kwatinetz notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early in the week, but the reading so far is on the
positive side of things,`` he says.
</P>
<P>
   With the likes of Dell (CEO Michael Dell is speaking today),
Gateway, Intel and Microsoft offering their two cents on the recent
PC surge, money managers hope to garner a clearer notion of whether
the rebound is real, or just a ghost of Christmases past, Kwatinetz
says. Comparing the chipmakers' forecasts with the outlooks of the
PC-makers and the computer resellers should give investors an
inkling as to whether technology stocks are poised to make any kind
of run in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always worried. But this is a great opportunity to
try figure out what's going on,'' Kwatinetz says. We'll keep you
posted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
