<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-UNBEATEN-     12-01 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-UNBEATEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Even if the Denver Broncos win back-to-back Super Bowls and become
the first NFL team to finish 19-0, they will not be recognized as
the greatest team of all time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the greatest, but not the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos will be the greatest team of their era, but in this
age of a watered-down league in which expansion has diluted the
talent, and free agency and the salary cap allow players to switch
teams like mercenaries, they will not be recognized as superior to
such dynasties as Green Bay in the 1960s, Pittsburgh in the 1970s,
San Francisco in the 1980s and Dallas in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, are the Broncos better than the 1985 Chicago Bears,
who finished 18-1 and dominated the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are trying to join the 1972 Miami Dolphins as the
only unbeaten and untied champions in NFL history. But don't call
that Dolphins team the greatest ever. During the regular season,
Miami beat only two teams that finished with winning records _ the
Chiefs and Giants, both of whom were 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the year, if we're 19-0, there's no reason you
wouldn't consider this team one of the better teams in history, if
not the greatest,'' Denver owner Pat Bowlen says.
</P>
<P>
   With four games left _ against Kansas City, the New York Giants,
Miami and Seattle _ the Broncos could end the regular season 16-0.
They could be 18-0 entering Super Bowl XXXIII and lose to the
Minnesota Vikings, who might be as good or better.
</P>
<P>
   After beating San Diego 31-16 on Sunday when they overcame four
turnovers, including three interceptions by John Elway, the Broncos
became only the fourth 12-0 team in NFL history and the first since
the 1985 Bears.
</P>
<P>
   As the Broncos move closer to their rendezvous with destiny,
they are analyzed more and more by the so-called experts who want
to carve their place in history. The Broncos' mediocre first-half
performance at San Diego is being used as an example that this
Denver team is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``All great teams have bad games, but they find a way to win,''
Bowlen says.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have found ways to win decisively. They haven't come
close to losing. In this age of last-second miracles, Denver has
been boring.
</P>
<P>
   The closest any team has come to beating Denver was Oct. 11 at
Seattle, where the Broncos won 21-16. The five-point victory was
their closest game of the season. They beat New England 27-21 and
Cincinnati 33-26.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has beaten four teams that have winning records _ New
England, Dallas, Oakland and Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky's the limit for them,'' San Diego linebacker Junior
Seau says. ``Their offensive attack is balanced. They have two Hall
of Fame players (Elway and running back Terrell Davis). This is
their year.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos beat Kansas City at Mile High Stadium on Sunday,
they will tie an NFL record with their 18th consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos clinched the AFC West title against the Chargers. If
they defeat the Chiefs, they will earn the home-field advantage
throughout the AFC playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Broncos were the best team in the AFC,
securing the home-field advantage Dec. 1. Coach Mike Shanahan
rested his best players at times over the last few games. Then, in
the second round at Mile High Stadium, they were upset by
Jacksonville. Shanahan learned his lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be a situation like it was two years
ago,'' Shanahan says. ``I don't think it takes a genius to figure
out what we learned. We got our butts kicked by Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play each game, and we're not going to hold
back. We're going out there and playing each game to win,
regardless if we win out and regardless if we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Broncos winning and winning decisively is the
offense. They are the NFL's highest-scoring team, averaging 33.4
points per game. They have scored fewer than 27 points only once,
in the win at Seattle. They have scored at least 30 points in nine
games, at least 40 in three.
</P>
<P>
   Denver is third in the NFL in total offense (379.8 yards per
game) and first in rushing (162.7).
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, they may be as good as I've seen in the 20 years
I've been around this league,'' Chargers coach June Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan is an offensive genius, but he's blessed with such
outstanding coaches as offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak and
offensive line coach Alex Gibbs. Davis leads the NFL in rushing and
touchdowns and is the leading candidate to be named the league's
Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, of course, is one of the greatest quarterbacks in NFL
history.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego game was an example of how good Elway can be.
Having thrown only three interceptions all season entering the
game, he threw three in the second quarter, but Denver still led
21-10 at halftime. He finished with four touchdown passes, giving
him seven in his past two games since returning from a rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's John Elway, a Hall of Fame quarterback,'' San
Diego safety Rodney Harrison says. ``His confidence doesn't get
shattered. He threw three interceptions, and he was laughing on the
field. Hey, Denver's a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway might get frustrated over the nagging injuries that have
cost him four starts this season, but he never panics or loses his
poise in pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are not always going to go smooth for us, and we know
that,'' Elway says. ``We're ready for a battle every time we go out
there, and if we make a mistake, we're able to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of making the plays you have to make. There's so
much character on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's offense is so good, reserve quarterback Bubby Brister
is 4-0 in games he has started in place of the injured Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's defense doesn't get a lot of respect, because it isn't
loaded with stars and doesn't rank among the league leaders. The
Broncos are 12th in total defense, third against the run and 20th
in pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   But when Elway was struggling against the Chargers, Denver's
defense forced six turnovers, including five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple ugly parts of the game, but I don't think
there was ever any doubt as to what the outcome would be,'' Broncos
defensive end Harald Hasselbach says. ``Every interception they
made, we came back with one of our own. That's what has made this
team so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have outstanding special teams. Their return teams
are awesome, their coverage teams are good, and the kicking game is
exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   And the Broncos are an experienced team. Of the 53-man roster,
22 players are 30 or older.
</P>
<P>
   ``They find a way to win,'' Seau says. ``When they don't play a
perfect game, they still win. That's the key to playing in this
league. When they stumble, they get back up.''
</P>
<P>
   In their final four games, the Broncos have two chances to
stumble, according to those closest to the team. They visit the
Giants and the Dolphins. The Miami game Dec. 21 is on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Chiefs and Seahawks visit Mile High Stadium, where
the Broncos have been invincible over the past two seasons, they
don't stand much chance of pulling an upset. The Broncos are trying
not to look beyond Kansas City, one of their fiercest rivals. They
want to sweep the Chiefs and earn the home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be good to know you're going to be at home in the
playoffs, but two years ago we had the same scenario and we lost at
home,'' Denver receiver Rod Smith says. ``Hell, I would have rather
lost on the road. You could have something to blame it on.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1977, the Broncos beat their four AFC
West rivals on the road. Shanahan doesn't want conquests like that
to go for naught.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the playoffs, he says: ``If we play well
(Sunday), we will get a week's rest right before (the first
playoff) game. That's plenty of time. Hopefully, we'll do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got that bye week to rest. We did it the hard way last
year (making the playoffs as a wild card) with no rest, and we were
still able to win four in a row, three on the road. So we are going
to play it just like we did last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each game, we'll go in to win and hope that's good enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
