<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS PRINCE SHUNS UCLA KINGDOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Snubbed indirectly by his hometown team, Tayshaun
Prince traveled 2,500 miles to feel loved. Now the former Compton
Dominguez star is lighting up Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Prince, a 6-foot-8 freshman, is the starting shooting guard for
the defending national champs, averaging 8.7 points and shooting
47.8 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   He's keeping a low profile on the court, shooting when open and
careful not to exceed his rookie role. But when Kentucky needs a
spark, as it did Saturday against UCLA, Prince is happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the team needs somebody to give us a lift, I can hit a
couple shots to get us started,'' Prince said last week during the
Puerto Rico Shootout. ``I'm starting to feel more comfortable.
Since I'm starting, I'm trying to create something so we don't put
it all on the seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince's performance against the Bruins _ 11 points, including
eight in the second half _ was especially rewarding for his family.
Five years ago, his brother, Tommie, was set to attend UCLA until
his standardized test score was challenged and the Bruins abruptly
ended their recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   Tommie is now a senior at Pepperdine, but his younger brother
never forgave the Bruins. During his recruitment last year, he kept
UCLA on his short list so he could ultimately reject them as they
rejected his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never going to attend UCLA,'' he said with a scowl. ``I
was (angry with) them, the whole family was (angry with) them for
what happened to Tommie.''
</P>
<P>
   Clyde's fan club: Houston coach Clyde Drexler hasn't proven he
can recruit anyone but sons of former NBA stars (Gee Gervin, Moses
Malone Jr.). He hadn't proven he can coach, and he's almost two
years short of his degree.
</P>
<P>
   But Drexler can sell tickets. Within three months of his hiring
last March, Houston sold 4,200 season tickets. Its current total
(6,800) is a school record and five times greater than last year.
</P>
<P>
   More, the Cougars have added 24 luxury suites to the top
concourse of Hofheinz Pavilion and sold 23 of them _ for $15,000
each, with a three-year commitment. In addition, they've sold 261
courtside seats for $1,000 each. That's $1.3 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a guy who has won three college games, including
Monday's 67-55 victory over downtrodden Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler has surrounded himself with former Phi Slamma Jamma
teammates Reid Gettys (assistant coach) and Michael Young (strength
coach). So far, he hasn't hired my favorite Phi guy, Benny Anders,
who was last spotted playing pro ball in South America. Anders in
the Andies?
</P>
<P>
   Drexler gets his first chance at a legitimate victory Thursday
at California.
</P>
<P>
   Head of their class: So far, the nation's best freshman is
DePaul's Quentin Richardson, who leads the nation in rebounding
with a 13.8 average. He's also scoring 24.5 points per game and
shooting 55.7 percent from the field. The 6-foot-6 Richardson has
35 offensive rebounds for the 3-1 Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   While Duke's Elton Brand (15.8 points, 11.3 rebounds) looms over
the sophomore class like a 260-pound chandelier, its most improved
member is North Carolina center Brendan Haywood.
</P>
<P>
   Haywood had six blocks in the NIT finals against Stanford and
he's averaging 12.6 points and 7.6 rebounds for the unbeaten Tar
Heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned our inside game around,'' Cardinal coach Mike
Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   If he stays in school through his junior year and continues
developing, Haywood may be the No.1 pick in the 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: The most impressive newcomer, by far, is USC
forward Brian Scalabrine, from Highline Community College in Des
Moines, Wash. Scalabrine is big, skilled, athletic and plays with
limitless energy.
</P>
<P>
   One newcomer to watch is Oregon guard Alex Scales, from San
Jacinto (Texas) Junior College. He had 14 points and 10 rebounds in
a recent victory over Southern Illinois....
</P>
<P>
   And don't be fooled by Oregon's 72-61 loss at Minnesota on
Monday. The Ducks were good enough to build a 14-point halftime
lead, and that signals trouble for anyone visiting Mac Court this
season....
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Steve Lavin and Pepperdine's Lorenzo Romar have a
sensational learning opportunity Saturday in the Wooden Classic,
when they face Oklahoma State's Eddie Sutton and Kansas' Roy
Williams, respectively....
</P>
<P>
   Washington had a tough trip to Chicago for its Great Eight game
against Connecticut on Tuesday. The Huskies played Friday through
Sunday in the Big Island Invitational, then flew straight from
Hawaii to Chicago....
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's most impressive freshman doesn't wear UCLA blue (or
black). He's Arizona power forward Michael Wright, who had 21
points and seven rebounds at Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike teammate Gene Edgerson, Wright doesn't use his elbows
to make an impact. If you missed it, Edgerson flattened BYU's Bret
Jepsen with the worst cheap shot seen around these parts in years.
</P>
<P>
   Wildcats coach Lute Olson benched Edgerson, but because no foul
was called _ the refs didn't see it _ the Pac-10 probably won't
issue a suspension. Too bad. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
