<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON ISN'T EXPECTED TO FEEL BRUNT OF CUTBACKS FROM EXXON, MOBIL
MERGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL DAVIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While not immune to the cutbacks arising from the merger of
Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., Houston is not expected to feel the
brunt of the 9,000 layoffs planned in the wake of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The city may even add jobs, as the new company consolidates the
headquarters of its chemicals and worldwide energy exploration and
production businesses here, some energy executives suggested
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon has about 12,825 employees in Houston, including 4,200 at
its Baytown refinery _ the largest concentration of Exxon employees
in the United States. Mobil has about 600 workers in Houston and
2,200 at its refinery and related operations in Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials stressed that the expected layoffs will come
from its worldwide work force of 123,000, less than 40 percent of
which is in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something that we get any pleasure out of,'' said
Mobil Chairman Lucio Noto, who will become vice chairman of the new
company to be named Exxon Mobil Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Houston civic leaders expressed hopes that the deal will not
have an adverse effect on the city's already cooling economy.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kollaer, president of the Greater Houston Partnership, said
he was ``cautiously optimistic'' about how the deal will effect the
Houston economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to know what is going to happen, they have a
lot of regulatory hurdles to go over, but generally speaking the
consolidation in the energy industry has been good for Houston
because companies often move operations here when they
consolidate,'' Kollaer said.
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1980s and early 1990s, many energy companies
moved jobs to Houston as they closed offices in Denver, Midland,
Oklahoma City and other energy centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announced $75 billion acquisition of Mobil by Exxon Corp.
will certainly affect the Houston economy,'' said Mayor Lee Brown.
``While both companies have a presence in Houston, of the two,
Exxon has the largest operation here. The fact that they are the
purchaser of Mobil may hopefully result in less shrinking of the
work force and general business operations in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its Baytown refinery, Exxon has 10 other
significant business operations in Houston, including U.S. oil and
gas exploration, its coal and minerals unit, Exxon Yemen, Exxon
Company International Chad Doba, Exxon Production Research and
Exxon Chemical.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was formerly home to Exxon's domestic oil and gas
business, but all of its exploration and production operations were
consolidated here in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in merging the exploration and production
operations here will be to get Mobil and Exxon people together to
determine an organizational structure for the newly expanded group,
said Exxon Chairman Lee Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   Noto could not say how many Mobil exploration and production
employees might be moving here. Mobil has exploration and
production workers in Dallas, Fairfax, Va., and various locations
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas will likely see many of its Mobil exploration and
production employees shifted to Houston. The company employs about
2,200 workers in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Both Noto and Raymond declined to say how many jobs Houston
might gain or lose as a result of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Simmons, president of Simmons &AMP; Co. International, a
Houston-based energy investment banker, said he expects Houston to
be a beneficiary when the two companies move all of their worldwide
oil and gas exploration here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what they spent on (exploration and production) over
the last decade: Exxon spent $48.6 billion and Mobil spent $28.4
billion,'' Simmons said. ``That's a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobil divisions now represented in Houston include
petrochemicals, pipelines, Latin American exploration and
production and natural gas liquids.
</P>
<P>
   Since both companies already have their chemicals operations
headquarters here, it will not be as much of a logistical challenge
to combine those two groups.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon's Baytown refinery and Mobil's refinery in Beaumont, two
of the largest in the country, are unlikely to see significant job
cuts, said Ray Ory, president of Vector Associates, a Houston
consulting firm that tracks the refining business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies have invested a lot of money maintaining these
refineries, and they are pretty much state-of-the-art,'' Ory said.
</P>
<P>
   Ory does not see the two facilities being integrated in any
manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will continue to operate in much the same way
they always have,'' Ory said. ``Any concern about staff reductions
in the refineries is misplaced. The refineries today have very
efficient work forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ory's optimism, employees at the Beaumont, Texas,
facility were still concerned about their future Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers are apprehensive about what might happen, but we're
confident that we have a good, efficient refinery,'' said Melvin
Blackwell, chairman of the workmen's group for Oil, Chemical and
Atomic Workers Union Local 4-243, which represents most of the
workers at the Beaumont refinery.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond said there will probably be some efficiencies to be
gained at the two refineries. ``I suspect that with two large
refineries, almost by definition there will be some opportunities
for cost reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ory believes jobs in Exxon's and Mobil's marketing,
administration and pipeline businesses and distribution services
for the companies's retail outlets face a much bleaker outlook
because of redundant duties at each company.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond and Noto said they have no idea whether any of the two
companies' physical facilities in Houston will be consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   A combined Exxon Mobil, while the world's largest oil company,
will not be the largest oil and gas producer in Texas. That
distinction belongs to Altura, the joint venture of Amoco and Shell
Oil Co.'s Permian Basin properties, said David Garlick, director of
research and administration at the Texas Independent Producers and
Royalty Owners Association.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' oil and gas production in Texas has been
declining as they have sold properties off in the past 20 years,
Garlick said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Exxon was the No. 1 oil producer in Texas, pumping
223.7 million barrels of oil. Mobil that year was No. 9, producing
48.6 million barrels of oil.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Exxon was still No. 2 but was producing only 29. 2
million barrels, and Mobil was No. 6, producing 18.9 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of their market power, the effect of the merger would
have been much larger had it occurred in the past,'' Garlick said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
