A7852 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOFA-SFCHRON &LR;      12-01 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 New BofA Debits Female Executives   By Sam Zuckerman  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BankAmerica was once hailed for its promotion of female executives,
but since its takeover by North Carolina-based NationsBank, almost
an entire generation of top women leaders has been swept away.
</P>
<P>
   In the two months since NationsBank took over BankAmerica and
adopted its name, all of the old BofA's top 10 women executives
have either resigned or been demoted, current and former BofA
employees said.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 10 resigned after their jobs were give to NationsBank
executives. Several of them were offered lower-ranking positions
with less authority.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kathleen Burke, who as vice chairman for human
resources was the old BofA's highest ranking woman, resigned after
her job was given to NationsBank personnel chief Chuck Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   The other four top-ranking women now have jobs with less
authority and report to lower-ranking executives than they
previously did _ a move generally considered a demotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they had any intention of having me in a
position of influence,'' said one senior BofA woman who recently
left the bank. ``They harbor a feeling about women that they should
have bumble bees on their shoulders and be playing tennis at the
club.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half a dozen current and former BofA women spoke to
The Chronicle on condition that they not be identified. Several
said their severance packages prohibited them from commenting
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former BofA employees said what happened to the
women was a result of NationsBank's tradition of putting its own
people in charge after a merger, combined with insensitivity to the
gains female executives had made at the San Francisco bank.
</P>
<P>
   Several BofA women said they were personally insulted when
NationsBank Chairman and Chief Executive Hugh McColl distributed a
videotape to employees before the merger was completed in which he
boasted of having ``the best men in banking.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of so many senior women has become a source of
anguish both within the bank and throughout the larger community of
Bay Area women executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliminating that whole group just sends a tremendously
negative message,'' said Beth Parker, director of program
litigation at Equal Rights Advocates, a San Francisco
public-interest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Other high-ranking BofA female executives who resigned after the
acquisition was announced include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Group Executive Vice President Christine Garvey, head of
commercial real estate lending, who was replaced by a NationsBank's
Bill Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   _ Group Executive Vice President Barbara Rambo, whose position
as head of lending to midsize companies was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathryn Munro, head of BofA's Southwest region, who was
replaced by NationsBank's Tim Arnoult.
</P>
<P>
   Women executives who stayed on in lesser jobs include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Desoer, who headed California retail banking and
reported to a vice chairman. She now runs Northern California
banking and reports to Eugene Taylor of NationsBank, the new
western regional president.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Wikstrom, previously in charge of BofA's telephone
banking centers, now a project manager for direct banking and
specialty products.
</P>
<P>
   A similar pattern of resignations and demotions holds among the
next tier of female managers, although some BofA women at those
levels have kept their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the new BankAmerica rejected accusations of bias
and said senior women who left did so for personal reasons, not
because of pressure from the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the women made a decision based on a combination of
personal and professional factors,''said Lorraine Stimmel,
executive vice president responsible for diversity programs at the
combined bank and herself a manager at the old BofA. ``Many of the
female executives were offered what I would consider important
positions in the new company.''
</P>
<P>
   Stimmel said the women with reduced authority had not been
demoted, because they hold important positions in a larger and more
powerful bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at these women and say they didn't come out
ahead, that is absolutely not the case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stimmel said NationsBank has a good record of promoting females
and pointed out that women from the North Carolina bank hold such
top jobs as head of credit cards and president of Florida banking
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of women at BofA had a long history.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years ago, BofA signed an agreement to promote
female officers, settling complaints nine female employees had
brought to the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, BofA Chairman and Chief Executive Richard
Rosenberg personally backed the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, 11 of the bank's top 45 executives were female.
</P>
<P>
   ``BofA has been a pioneer,'' said Anne Golden, president of the
Financial Women's Association, which represents about 250 female
financial services executives in San Francisco. One former female
BofA executive, who sent The Chronicle a five-page memorandum on
the current status of women at BofA, wrote: ``In essence, the
entire generation of female executives created during (the past 25
years) has been wiped out.``
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the new bank said such comments do not express
the views of most women at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few women speaking anonymously don't represent the many
women managers and executives who have very senior roles,''
spokeswoman Melba Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   Some BofA employees point out that many male BofA executives
also lost out to NationsBank executives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, BofA women note that female executives have been hit
disproportionately hard.
</P>
<P>
   Two former BofA male executives sit on the bank's six-member
policy committee. And, BofA men have kept top jobs in global and
investment banking, where NationsBank historically was weak.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, generous severance packages, paying as much as
three years of salary, gave both male and female executives
incentive to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Then too, several BofA employees said they came away from
meetings with NationsBank managers impressed by racial and gender
diversity at the North Carolina bank.
</P>
<P>
   At bottom, BofA and NationsBank operated in vastly different
milieus for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a world of difference in the way women had to
operate in their culture _ it was much more old-school,'' said one
former BofA female manager. ``The NationsBank women were imbued
with quite a bit of that old-fashioned Southern charm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
