r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-SFCHRON &LR;      12-01 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tech firms help e-businesses get started  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
When the Starr Report was released in September, Palo Alto resident
Ron Jones got the bright idea of building a Web site to sell
marshmallows printed with images of political figures.
</P>
<P>
   Jones hired an artist to draw caricatures of Bill Clinton,
Monica Lewinsky and Ken Starr. He figured out how to stamp the
drawings on marshmallows with food coloring. And he found a Web
hosting company, City Online Communications of Oakland, to help him
get his site up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' e-business, Mellow Out Co.  &LR; (www.politicalroasters.com),
 &LR; began selling marshmallows for $1 a pop on October 1. The company
already has recovered its startup costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted with the site and want to add more products to
it,'' said Jones. ``Some people have been asking for the whole
Judiciary Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is among thousands of entrepreneurs who have turned to a
portal, an internet service provider or other Web hosting service
to handle the technological side of their e-businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who put up their own sites, but things like
handling credit card charges and configuring the server properly
can get pretty complex pretty quickly,'' said Jim Balderston, an
analyst with Zona Research in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   New e-commerce startups can lose customers if their business
takes off and they lack the technological prowess to handle a lot
of orders, cautioned Bill Burnham, an analyst with Credit Suisse
First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially for small businesses, if you don't have extensive
information-technology experience, outsourcing makes a lot more
sense,'' Balderston said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of Web hosting companies, which range from
big national names such as Yahoo to little local ISPs like City
Online.
</P>
<P>
   These companies offer a range of services for a variety of fees.
Their most important task is to ``host'' client sites on their
World Wide Web servers so that small companies don't have to buy
and maintain these expensive and complicated machines themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts also provide encryption technology so credit card
information can be sent over the Web relatively safely.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them also assist new businesses in setting up merchant
accounts with banks, something all business must have to accept
credit card payments.
</P>
<P>
   Other services that are commonly offered include:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Site Design.  &LR; Some hosting companies will provide graphic
design services for customers for an additional charge.
</P>
<P>
   Others simply provide page templates that clients can organize
and personalize with colors, images and text of their own choosing.
The templates are designed to be simple enough for even
techno-dummies to create a passable site.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants who create their own sites need to have either a
scanner at their disposal or another way to create and upload
digital images.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Domain name registration.  &LR; There is a $70 base registration
fee charged by Network Solutions, which has been in charge of
regulating regulates all  &LR; domain names. Some hosting companies will
register a name at no extra cost while others charge a service fee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Search engine registration.  &LR; Most visitors to small,
specialized e-commerce sites find the site by keying a search term,
such as ``marshmallow'' or ``Linda Tripp,'' into a search engine.
The search engine then lists sites that include that word.
</P>
<P>
   Some hosting services will register search words for each site
they host with anywhere from a handful to hundreds of search
engines and directories. Others leave registering up to their
clients, who may or may not choose to do it. (Many search terms are
picked up by search engines without registering.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Traffic analysis reports.  &LR; Most hosts analyze information
from their servers to track visitors to their client sites. The
sites then can use these reports to find out, for example, which
search engines most visitors used to find them and even which
search terms generated the most visits.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bull, who runs a site that sells educational games for
children with learning disabilities, cautions that designing a site
can be more complicated than would-be merchants might expect, even
when using a very user-friendly hosting service.
</P>
<P>
   Bull's site  &LR; (www.smartstuffgoodideas.com),  &LR; which he designed
himself, is hosted by Yahoo, which says even design novices can set
up a store in under an hour using its templates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put up one product on one page and you have all of your
(design elements) prepared in advance, it would take an hour,''
said Bull, a film and video director who runs Smart Stuff &AMP; Good
Ideas out of his Menlo Park garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find I spend hours tweaking it to make it nice,'' Bull
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
