<HEADLINE>
GATES CASE MADE IN E-MAIL TO STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an e-mail to his executive staff on Tuesday,
Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft Corp., said that the government's
antitrust case was seriously undercut by America Online's planned
$4.2 billion purchase of Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The government, Gates wrote, ``must be VERY dismayed at this
merger,'' because it proved that Microsoft's move to give its
browser away was not predatory pricing but a recognition of its
``competitive price, which is zero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is Netscape worth $4 billion,'' Gates wrote, ``despite
making its browser available for free,'' as it later did to match
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Browsers are like network TV,'' Gates said. ``The traffic
alone makes it a great business.'' It is not predatory to price a
product profitably, he said, adding, ``It's called the marketplace
at work, and it helps consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   David Boies, the Justice Department's lead trial lawyer, accused
Gates of revisionist history. Internal documents from late 1995,
when the company decided to give away the browser, he said
indicated ``it was Microsoft's explicit purpose to cut off
Netscape's air supply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
