<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EXXON ANNOUNCES PLAN TO BUY MOBIL FOR $80 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Exxon, already the United States' largest oil company, agreed to
buy Mobil, the next-largest, for $80 billion in stock, to form the
world's biggest corporation, on a scale surpassing that of many
sovereign nations.
</P>
<P>
   While the merger is not likely to have any immediate effect on
prices at the pump, antitrust regulators will certainly scrutinize
it and probably force the sale of some gas stations and refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say that they now confront global competitors and
plunging energy prices, making their merger and the resulting
savings a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Total, the giant French oil company, said it would acquire the
Belgian petrochemical company Petrofina in a stock swap worth $13
billion.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN DRUG MAKERS TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiating, Rhone-Poulenc of France and Hoechst
of Germany said they would combine their pharmaceutical and
agricultural units into a new company, Aventis, as the first step
of a merger between the drug makers. Aventis will be the world's
second-leading pharmaceutical maker behind Merck &AMP; Co. and the
globe's top seller of agricultural products. Jurgen Dormann
Hoechst's chief executive, will serve as the chairman of Aventis,
while Jean-Rene Fourtou, Rhone-Poulenc's chief, will serve as vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED SIGNALS ON ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing sector slowed for the sixth straight month in
November as industrial companies felt the effect of the global
financial crisis, but a separate report suggested the economy would
improve by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. EQUITY MARKETS RECOVER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks bounced back, led by a strong recovery in prices of
computer-related and Internet shares. The Nasdaq Composite index
rose 54.21 points, or 2.8 percent, to 2003.75. The Dow Jones
industrial average, down more than 100 points early in the session,
closed at 9133.54, up 16.99, or 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NEW MARKET FOR FUNDS IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Sales of mutual funds through banks got off to what may prove to
be a deceptively quiet start in Japan. But the banks, which have
vast branch networks throughout Japan, represent a huge opportunity
to reach groups of customers so far untapped.
</P>
<P>
   IBM EXTENDS NETWORK BIDDING
</P>
<P>
   IBM has postponed the deadline for companies to submit final
bids for its global communications network until next Tuesday,
executives close to the bidding said. The auction, expected to
raise between $4 billion and $5 billion, was originally scheduled
to close this Tuesday night, but IBM pushed back the deadline to
allow bidders to become more comfortable with their final offers.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG SALES AT DAIMLERCHRYSLER
</P>
<P>
   Unabated growth in demand for sport utility vehicles and pickups
pushed DaimlerChrysler's vehicle sales in the United States 7
percent higher in November. Toyota and Honda also reported strong
monthly sales.
</P>
<P>
   FDA BACKS MONSANTO PAINKILLER
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto won the backing of a Food and Drug Administration
advisory panel for the first of a new class of painkillers with
expected annual sales of as much as $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON MERGER APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Corp. of America, the biggest manager of prisons in
the United States, said its shareholders had approved the company's
planned $2 billion merger with CCA Prison Realty Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
