<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO IS SAID TO IMPROVE, BUT DOCTORS REMAIN CAUTIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Fla. _ The lead doctor in the medical team treating
Joe DiMaggio said Tuesday that his condition had improved following
a serious setback last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Earl Barron said in an interview that DiMaggio's temperature
had dropped and that his white blood cell count had improved.
</P>
<P>
   But the cardiologist noted: ``You have to put this in
perspective. You've got an 84-year-old man who had a major surgical
operation, which was for a cancer, which of course is also a
difficult situation. His lungs have responded with some
inflammation and some infection. It's a difficult situation. I
think he can survive. He's a tough guy; there's no question about
it. I would say the prognosis is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   After a short pause, Barron added: ``There are so many variables
and there are so many things that can happen. It's almost
impossible to give a blanket statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron said he was encouraged by the outcome of lung cancer
surgery Oct. 14. ``You can never be 100 percent sure, but we feel
strongly that all of the tumor was removed,'' he said. ``Ordinarily
in this circumstance, had he recovered quickly from the surgery, he
probably would have undergone radiation treatment as an adjunct to
the surgery to try to prevent any reoccurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio remains on a respirator, Barron said, and can be taken
off only ``for a short period.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the Yankee Hall of Famer's ability to speak
because of the weakening of his lungs, a speech therapist hopes to
plug DiMaggio's tracheotomy soon for 20 minutes a day so he can
begin talking again.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a dangerous drop in DiMaggio's blood pressure when he
takes certain medication, doctors treating him are left mainly to
react to new lung infections rather than preventing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't treat before because what happens is, if you treat
before, you select out organisms that are not sensitive to your
antibiotic, and it makes the situation worse,'' Barron said. ``You
just basically have to react to things that happen rather than
anticipate.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg, DiMaggio's spokesman and longtime friend,
said: ``They're more concerned with his pressure than anything else
right now. Because if his pressure drops, he could be in trouble. I
think they're trying to find a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Since being admitted to Memorial Regional Hospital here on Oct.
12, DiMaggio has twice been close to death, according to both
Barron and Engelberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost lost him on Saturday,'' Engelberg said. DiMaggio
also was in danger on Nov. 16, after his blood pressure plunged 30
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get on top of one infection and he seems to be OK, and you
turn around and get another one,'' Barron said. ``These are not
preventable things. We make every sterile precaution we can, and
you still have problems. You've got irritated lung tissue, which is
a very good culture medium, and bacteria love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
