s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     12-01 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ONLY STAN AND OLLIE WERE WAITING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of John Turtorro and Tony Shalhoub is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The landscape is empty, the horizon a flat, unbroken line that
meets itself behind you. There is no place bleaker or more
horizontal than this patch of arid earth at the edge of time. The
only sign of nature is a small, spindly, leafless tree.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of uncharacteristic despondency, Ollie and Stan, two
fastidious tramps in ancient derby hats, decide they can't go on.
Better to end it all. They will hang themselves from the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Ollie, the portly one and the more commanding of the two, tells
Stan to go first. Stan, who's as thin as a rail, is usually
passive, but this is one of those times when he can be stubborn.
``Why me?'' he asks. Ollie is patient. He points out: ``You're
lighter than I am.'' ``Just so!'' says Stan. Ollie reacts as if
dealing with a small boy: ``I don't understand.'' But his fluty
tenor has taken on a menacing bite.
</P>
<P>
   Stan feels cornered, as he often does with Ollie. He has trouble
expressing himself. He mumbles something about the branch. When
Ollie persists in being obtuse, Stan angrily tells him to use his
intelligence, to use his head. Ollie, his eyebrows arched, his tiny
mustache twitching, says with what he thinks is majestic sarcasm:
``You're my only hope.'' They seem to be at an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   This finally prompts Stan to put his thoughts in order. He
explains that, being skinny, he probably won't break the branch
when he falls. If he goes first, he will be dead as planned. But
then Ollie, who clearly weighs a ton, is likely to tear the branch
from the tree, if not uproot the tree itself, and thus survive the
suicide attempt. He will be left alone, forever denied the company
of his oldest friend. Stan seems about to cry, not only because he
fears his own death, but also because he can so intimately
understand Ollie's loss of him.
</P>
<P>
   In such moments, low comedy approaches bliss.
</P>
<P>
   That is a scene from Samuel Beckett's ``Waiting for Godot'' as
it might look and sound if Vladimir, called Didi, and Estragon,
called Gogo, were played by the great early film comedians, Oliver
Hardy and Stan Laurel. The immediate inspiration for this daydream:
the ``Waiting for Godot'' now being performed at the Classic Stage
Company with a cast of good actors who have established their
respectability elsewhere. The new production is far from
satisfactory, being earnest, actorly and filled with empty moments
that invite the mind to wander. Also to wonder: What if?
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Conversations With and About Beckett,'' my
colleague Mel Gussow reports that, in 1982, when he asked Beckett
if he would like to have seen Laurel and Hardy in ``Godot,'' the
playwright ``seemed tantalized by the idea.'' A moment later he
said simply, ``It's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's fondness for the comedy of music hall and early movies
has often been noted. What is of interest here is the particular
reference to Laurel and Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Since reading Beckett's response I've been haunted: every time I
go back to ``Godot'' I can hear Stan and Ollie as they say the
lines. I can also see them as they attempt to come to terms with
the playwright's universe in ways that are simultaneously
Beckettian and pure Laurel and Hardy. Is this a coincidence, or was
Beckett guided by the kind of subliminal impulses that may be
mysterious as a writer writes, and only later are recognized?
</P>
<P>
   However Beckett came to create Didi and Gogo, they remain for me
much funnier and more moving on the page, where Stan and Ollie are
the stars, than they ever have been on the stage. Actors, possibly
intimidated by Beckett's description of the play as a tragicomedy,
too often act the roles with grave signification, or they attempt
to jazz them up with comedic bits for which they have no gift, or
that are irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   A sad fact: I've never seen a production of ``Godot'' that
realized more than isolated portions of the Beckett text. But then
I missed what was reported to be the definitive ``Godot'': the
German-language production directed by Beckett for the Schiller
Theater of West Berlin, which was seen at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music in 1977. I also missed the Mike Nichols ``Godot'' at Lincoln
Center in 1988, when Robin Williams' ad-libs and interpolations
dismayed purists but helped to insure that the run remained a
sellout.
</P>
<P>
   The best ``Godot'' I've ever seen was the Gate Theater
production from Dublin, one of the prime attractions of the 1996
Lincoln Center Festival, but even it was imperfect. The production
not only reminded us of Beckett's lifelong Irishness; it also
reduced ``Godot,'' if only for the play's duration, to something
like a parable concerned with the Irish-English question.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett is probably the only modern playwright whose works do
not need, or benefit from, being located in a time and place
identifiable through topical allusions and visual aids. The
dazzling shreds of ideas that pass through the minds of the
characters, as well as the awesome intensity with which the
characters attend their crises, are specific enough. Sometimes, as
in ``Krapp's Last Tape,'' that specificity takes in a somewhat
larger community. Poor old Krapp will always be Irish-born and bred
no matter who the actor is or what language he speaks in.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the wasteland in which ``Godot'' is set, the play
doesn't take place in some never-never land. The location is the
tiny, utterly specific alternate universe of characters so
harrowed, desperate and self-absorbed that this is what they
comprehend. It's all there is.
</P>
<P>
   The Western world is filled with mannerly Didis and Gogos,
moving around in severely circumscribed landscapes, waiting for
something to take them out of themselves. The next block is full of
unknown terrors. Chance encounters are to be avoided. Their
carefree moments are few.
</P>
<P>
   The trading of insults can give one a sense of self. Says Didi
after he and Gogo have gone at each other as a form of therapeutic
exercise: ``How time flies when one has fun!'' When Pozzo, the
tyrant, and Lucky, Pozzo's slave, finally leave the stage, having
scared the wits out of Didi and Gogo, Didi observes in all his
wisdom, ``That passed the time.'' Responds Gogo (and you can hear
Stan's voice, unintentionally impertinent): ``It would have passed
in any case.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurel and Hardy as Gogo and Didi? It's a destructively
seductive idea, but one that could also be instructive. Stan and
Ollie are not a one-shot team. Like Gogo and Didi, they have been
together forever.
</P>
<P>
   First paired by Hal Roach in the silent-film era, they went on
to make nearly 90 comedies, mostly two-reelers but also a number of
features, between 1926 and 1951. The best, the funniest, of these
evoke landscapes that are much like Beckett's: small, hermetically
sealed, forgotten by God.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Music Box,'' a short that won an Oscar in 1932, the
fate of mankind depends on the two men moving a shiny new grand
piano from the bottom of a steep hill to the top without smashing
it. Do they succeed? Does Godot ever arrive?
</P>
<P>
   Didi and Gogo are longtime collaborators. Each has the run of
the other's mind as if it were a familiar old flat, cluttered with
the detritus of a life no longer remembered, foul smelling,
perhaps, but safe. This is why even very good, more conventional
actors have problems playing ``Waiting for Godot.'' It requires a
degree of intimacy that has the force of second nature, as with
Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Classic Stage Company production, directed by Andrei
Belgrader and supervised by David Esbjornson (his last assignment
after serving seven years as the company's artistic director), is
something of an all-star affair: John Turturro as Gogo and Tony
Shalhoub as Didi are the first among the equals, though each would
seem a better choice to play the other's role.
</P>
<P>
   Turturro is a big stage presence. He doesn't comfortably fit
into a part made to Stan Laurel's order. He has to work hard to
rein himself in. Shalhoub gives an intelligent reading of Didi's
lines but, being a physically smaller, more subtle actor, he would
seem to be a natural as Gogo. Together, Turturro and Shalhoub give
reasonable impersonations that never for a minute seem spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening moments of the play, Turturro wrestles with his
leg, twisting himself into the shape of a failed pretzel, trying to
remove a worn-out shoe from his aching foot. The audience applauds
the choreography of the shtick with rather more enthusiasm than it
laughs at the humor of what it sees.
</P>
<P>
   There is a similar situation later on when Didi and Gogo do a
carefully worked out show business bit, supplied by Beckett. Each
trying to find the derby that suits him best, they stand side by
side, trying on and then passing to the other, one of three
beaten-up hats that remain in constant motion between them.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old vaudeville routine that can be achingly funny in the
way of sleight-of-hand. Here, it looks like something learned at
home and then performed for friends at a New Year's party.
</P>
<P>
   More successful are Christopher Lloyd, who is maniacal and blunt
as Pozzo, and Richard Spore, whose performance as Lucky, Pozzo's
slave, is remarkable as long as the character remains mute. Lucky
looks inert, but he is a ticking bomb inside a plain brown paper
parcel. When at last he goes off, delivering a crazily poetic
screed against a system he doesn't understand, the words get lost.
But then many of the words in this production evaporate in thin
air.
</P>
<P>
   About the derbies: in an Act I footnote, Beckett instructs that
Didi, Gogo, Pozzo and Lucky wear derbies. They were also integral
to the costumes that defined Stan and Ollie. When Laurel's
biographer asked him if derbies had been an idea stolen from
Charlie Chaplin, Laurel told him they had long been used by comics
to announce social pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   Derbies, he said, in a very Stanley-Gogo way, ``were in the
public domain.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the New Victory Theater there is a holiday treat for adults
who want to accompany their kids (ages 6 and up) to the theater but
haven't been able to score tickets for ``The Lion King.'' It's a
London import, ``Grimm Tales,'' the Young Vic Theater Company's
adaptation of six stories and one riddle taken from the collected
works of Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm.
</P>
<P>
   The physical production is minimal, using a small, raked, round
stage platform as the playing area, and only essential costumes and
props. All of which makes the show's theatricality more astonishing
and magical.
</P>
<P>
   The tales are narrated as they are acted, which distances some
of the Grand Guignol stage effects. Compared to what comes later,
the very funny scene in which the wolf swallows Little Red Riding
Hood (here called Red-Cap) and her grandmother is tame indeed. It
is accomplished with the wizardly use of a long swath of imitation
black fur. The tale of Ashputtel (Cinderella) is something else.
Ashputtel's wicked stepsisters draw real stage blood when one
amputates a toe in order to put on the fateful slipper, and the
other sacrifices a cutlet-sized portion of her heel.
</P>
<P>
   Such brightly grotesque brutality prompted squeals of laughter
among the younger theatergoers around me at a recent matinee. I'm
not so sure that some of the adults weren't a bit shocked, however.
We are probably the ones who will end up with the nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grimm Tales'' is a bold, inventive, sometimes enchanting
theatrical endeavor, performed with great good humor and energy by
the members of the talented cast. Carol Ann Duffy is responsible
for the adaptation and Tim Supple is the director. The engagement
continues until Jan. 3. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbidden Broadway Cleans Up Its Act!'' is the title of the
latest installment of the long-running, irrepressibly irreverent
revue created and written by the tireless Gerard Alessandrini and
directed by Phillip George and Alessandrini. It is at a tiny boite,
rather grandly named the Stardust Theater, on Broadway at 51st
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Among the targets: Mayor Giuliani and his obsessive need to
clean up the city, the boys in ``Footloose'' who are thought to be
``a little too cute'' to be completely plausible, and ``The Beauty
Queen of Leenane,'' which inspires the song ``How Are Things in
Irish Drama?'' sung to the tune of ``How Are Things in Glocca
Morra?'' The answer: ``Glum, glum, glum.''
</P>
<P>
   There also are sendups of Karen Ziemba and Ute Lemper, who
replaced Ann Reinking and Bebe Neuwirth in ``Chicago,'' a
suggestion that Alice Ripley and Emily Skinner of ``Side Show'' had
themselves surgically joined to keep working, but then found they
had two left feet; funny, quite mean parodies of ``Titanic'' (both
the Broadway musical and the film); put-downs of body mikes and
Bernadette Peters, and a superb take on the male swans in ``Swan
Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately one third of the show is, in backstage vernacular,
delicious, and the cast of four divine: Bryan Batt, Lori Hammel,
Edward Staudenmayer and Kristine Zbornik. A hand also for Matthew
Ward, the musical director.
</P>
<P>
   A note of caution: the Stardust Theater is not for
claustrophobics. The room is small, cramped and just far enough
below street level to make you wonder where they keep the snorkels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
