<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARPET COMPANY FINED FOR ILLEGAL DONATIONS TO LAMAR ALEXANDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Tenn.)   (bl)  
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the country's largest carpet manufacturers,
Beaulieu of America Inc. of Dalton was fined $1 million Tuesday
after pleading guilty to federal misdemeanor charges that it made
$36,000 in illegal contributions to Lamar Alexander's campaign for
1996 Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The company is headed by Carl Bouckaert, a Belgian citizen who
was one of the roughly 30 finance co-chairmen of Alexander's 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its plea, the company acknowledged that it skirted
rules prohibiting corporate contributions to presidential campaigns
by instructing employees to make donations and then reimbursing
them with payments identified as bonuses or expense reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement, which was negotiated between the company and
the U.S. Attorney in Atlanta, absolves Alexander's campaign of any
responsibility for the illegal donations. ``As a result of the
defendant's conduct,'' the agreement states, ``the Alexander for
President Committee unwittingly and incorrectly reported as
individual contributions what were in fact at least $36,000 in
corporate contributions funneled through conduits.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Culvahouse, a lawyer for Alexander's 1996 campaign
committee, said the committee plans to refund the $36,000 to
Beaulieu of America. ``There were 22,000 contributions to Alexander
for President,'' Culvahouse said in a statement. ``This is the only
instance like this we have heard about and we hope it is the
last.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a former Republican governor of Tennessee and former
U.S. secretary of education, is considering running for president
again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to imposing the $1 million criminal fine, the plea
agreement states that the Justice Department will recommend that
the Federal Election Commission impose a civil fine of $200,000
against the company. The terms of the agreement were disclosed
Tuesday at a hearing in U.S. District Court in Rome, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Bouckaert, the company's chief executive, was not charged
individually as part of the plea agreement. But the agreement calls
for him to perform at least 200 hours of community service as part
of the 500 hours of service required of the company's officers.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against the company state that Bouckaert hosted a
fund-raising dinner in Dalton for Alexander on March 8, 1995, and
that corporate officers directed at least 36 employees and employee
spouses to buy $1,000 tickets. The company later reimbursed the
employees, according to the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulieu of America is a privately held company founded by
Bouckaert in 1978 as a unit of the Beaulieu Group of Belgium. It
employs more than 8,000 workers in plants around the country, most
of them in northwest Georgia, Bowers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
