</P>
<P>
   A team spokesman declined to comment on the specifics of the
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots expect continued involvement by many of these
companies at a new stadium in Hartford,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big assumption,'' Bonham said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dean Pagani, a spokesman for Connecticut Gov. John Rowland,
defended premium seating pricing, saying the product would be far
superior to that in other markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the price of a club seat in Hartford, it's attached to a
club and restaurant and they'll have year-round access to a health
club and conference and business facilities,'' Pagani said. ``It's
a much different product. It has a variety of privileges.''
</P>
<P>
   Underestimating all premium sales in its analysis, the report
assumed that 80 suites would be sold at $100,000 in 2001 and 6,000
club seats would be sold for $4,250.
</P>
<P>
   The report also noted a number of ``intangible'' benefits _ such
as national media exposure and economic spinoff _ the team would
bring to Hartford, a city that is struggling to regain a vibrant
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pagani: ``Again, the focus of the report was to show the
stadium could pay for itself. That's what it does based on
conservative projections.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft will get at least 90 percent of the stadium's direct
revenues, which come from ticket sales, sales of the luxury boxes
and club seats, advertising inside the stadium, concessions,
souvenirs and parking. KPMG estimates that revenue will be $97
million in the first year of the arena's operation, rising to $114
million in the fifth year, 2005.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Kraft also will receive an estimated $80 million from
the NFL's lucrative television contracts, as well as another $14
million or so from the team owners' licensing agreement and profit
sharing from NFL Properties, NFL Films and NFL Enterprises -- a
total of about $200 million, according to a source familiar with
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   When his expenses are subtracted _ $84 million will be the
players' salary cap and another $10 million to $12 million for
coaches' salaries, travel and other costs _ his profit could reach
$100 million in the year 2005, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings in the report:
</P>
<P>
   -- Total public borrowing for the project could rise to $374
million after inflation over the 26-month construction period,
equaling $25.5 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   -- The stadium would not generate enough revenue to cover that
$25.5 million in annual debt until 2012.
</P>
<P>
   -- The third year of construction would be the most costly for
the state, putting taxpayers on the hook for $20.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- Thirty years after the stadium is built, however, the state
would receive a projected $44 million in net revenue from the
facility over a 12-month period -- the largest annual amount over
the life of the 30-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   -- The greatest generator of direct stadium revenue would be $41
million in ticket sales in the first year, followed by $30 million
in premium seating, $12.6 million in concessions, $2.3 million in
souvenir sales, and $2 million in parking. The state would receive
a 10 percent tax on all of that spending.
</P>
<P>
   -- In addition, the state would receive the corporate and income
taxes generated by the team, an amount expected to grow as the
league's payroll skyrockets.
</P>
<P>
   -- Raw revenues would increase dramatically over time _ from
$15.6 million in 2001, the first year open, to $77.3 million 30
years later.
</P>
<P>
   -- KPMG estimated the cost of repairing and maintaining the
stadium would range from $1.6 million a year to $7.7 million,
adjusted for inflation, over the life of the deal. Those capital
costs were factored into the overall calculations.
</P>
<P>
   -- The report projected $7.2 million in attendee spending
outside the stadium in the facility's first year of operation on
such things as hotels, restaurants, retail and transportation. That
figure would grow to $8.2 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   A public hearing on the plan is scheduled for Dec. 9. The
General Assembly, whose Democratic leadership supports the
Republican governor's proposal, is due to vote on the measure in a
special session Dec. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
