</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-TEXAS-CONRADT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONRADT KEEPS TEXAS PROGRAM ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Jody Conradt has vague memories of her leisurely
pursuit of Scottsdale recruit Ellen Bayer _ and of a time when only
a few teams, including hers, dominated women's college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Today, recruiting is at the forefront of college women's
basketball and can be a losing battle for even the winningest coach
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   With two sub-.500 seasons out of the past four and a 1-3 start,
the University of Texas is in sore need of the talent to match the
tradition that threatens to turn Conradt into a museum piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep looking to see if I'm dead,'' said the 57-year-old,
inducted two months ago into the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall
of Fame. Conradt, in her 23rd season at Texas and 30th as a college
coach, is among 26 inaugural inductees into the Women's Basketball
Hall of Fame, which will open in the spring in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Conradt, in fact, is alive and in Tempe for her team's first
appearance against Arizona State (2-1), a program with three NCAA
Tournament appearances, compared with the Longhorns' 14, two Final
Fours and 1986 championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've won a national championship and had the success
they've had, anything less is unacceptable,'' said Arizona State
Coach Charli Turner Thorne.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot more parity and teams don't dominate anymore,
and Jody's had to suffer that in recent years. But she's still as
great a coach as ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne was a senior point guard at Stanford in 1987-88,
the year it lost in the NCAA Sweet Sixteen to Texas. As an
assistant coach at Washington and Santa Clara, she was 1-2 against
the Horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing that's given me is a tremendous respect for
their program,'' said the 32-year-old, in her third season at ASU.
``Obviously Jody has shown an ability to continue to adjust and
adapt. She flat-out knows how to teach her kids to win. To win over
the long run, you have to be able to teach that mentality, not just
the Xs and Os.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after Texas accomplished the first undefeated NCAA
title run, culminating with a victory over Southern California in
Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller's final collegiate game, Conradt signed
Bayer, a 6-foot-8 center out of Scottsdale Saguaro High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I came'' to the Valley to court Bayer, ``I only came
once,'' Conradt said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the current recruiting environment, she must invite
juniors to campus to sway them early with the still-fervent
atmosphere in Austin. Four of the premier prospects in Texas, and
the nation, were among more than 10,000 people at the Erwin Center
on Saturday for an 86-65 loss to three-time defending national
champion Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting is such an unrealistic situation,'' Conradt said.
``It's very difficult to go through that process and know that the
more highly recruited an athlete is, the longer it's going to take
them to get back to reality once they become a college freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a 15-, 16-, 17-year-old hears from hundreds of adults how
wonderful they are, sometimes it's difficult to cut away what's
real and what is flattery. Most of us would be influenced by that,
and it has become so distasteful from the coaching standpoint and
damaging to young people. It's hard to justify what we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What adult wants to write a note to a 16-year-old every day
for two years? We're not observing to evaluate talent, but to make
an impression. It's about who's going to come first and most.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayer, who grew to 6-9 while at Texas and remains the tallest
player in school history by five inches, is a throwback to the days
when players were hooked simply by the allure of the Horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not a basketball player when she came, just a tall
young woman,'' said Conradt, who would have redshirted the shy
Bayer had she not worried about her quitting the game if she
weren't around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was one of the most competitive people I've coached, but
it didn't surface in the normal way. Her skills didn't allow that
until late in her junior and senior years. At that point, she had
enough skill to brutalize people and became a tremendous shot
blocker.''
</P>
<P>
   The best in Texas history (289) and among the top 20 all-time in
NCAA Division I. ``By the time she left (in 1990), she was just
becoming a basketball player,'' Conradt said.
</P>
<P>
   But torn knee ligaments two years later prevented Bayer from
going overseas to play, and she was too far removed from the game
to turn a tryout at the American Basketball League combine last
spring into a job.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer could not be reached for comment this week.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Conradt's 593 Texas wins (she has 710 total) are over
Arizona and Northern Arizona, but her initial intersection with ASU
finds the programs in an oddly similar place.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are hoping to build on a 10-win season, their
first in double digits in five years. Texas is trying to prove that
12-15 was an anomaly. Both are coming off a loss last week to
11th-ranked Rutgers: the Horns, 66-59 in Austin; ASU, 67-48 in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison of those games and common sense favors Texas
tonight. But the Horns already have a road loss to Houston, 61-52,
and is a post-thin team without 6-4 Carla Littleton, who reinjured
the right knee that kept sidelined her all last season.
</P>
<P>
   Now when teams traditionally not in the Horns' league get
lathered up, they have a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the state itself has sort of a mystique, that everything
is bigger and better,'' Conradt said. ``We enjoy that. But the
other part of it, that's hard for teams I've coached to understand,
is why everybody hates us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year you're here as a player, the one thing you
learn is people don't want to beat you, they want to tear your
heart out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
