<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-KICKER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF-SAVVY JACKE JOINS CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Chris Jacke was asked his assessment of the
kicking conditions at the Cardinals' practice fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeccable,'' he said. ``There's 70-degree weather. The grass
is green, not painted.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't remind him of the eight seasons he spent in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll carry around a bag of ice to feel at home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke was so excited about winning the Cardinals' place-kicking
job in a tryout Tuesday, he kept reeling off one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   On his attire of shorts and a T-shirt: ``I had to buy the stuff
when I got down here.''
</P>
<P>
   On what he needs to do in practice over the next three days: ``I
have to teach the field-goal holder how to hold for a right-footed
kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke was kidding about the clothes. He wasn't joking about
spending a lot of time with punter Scott Player, the team's holder
who hadn't worked with a right-footed kicker until Jacke and Tucson
native Cole Ford attended Monday's tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down and sat on the (wrong) side the first time, I'm so
used to doing it from the other side all year,'' Player said.
</P>
<P>
   Player has held for Joe Nedney, who suffered a season-ending
knee injury in Sunday's loss at Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney watched the tryout along with Cardinals coaches,
personnel staff and other members of the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't miss,'' said Nedney, who met Jacke in 1995 when he
was trying out with the Packers to be their kickoff specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke didn't miss a field-goal try during the workout. He also
hit all of his kickoffs inside the 5-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin knows a lot about him. From 1989 to
'92, Tobin faced Jacke twice a year when he was defensive
coordinator for the Chicago Bears and Jacke was with the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin knew that Jacke had 15 game-winning kicks at Green Bay and
was 70 of 73 from inside 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been to Super Bowl and won them,'' Tobin said.
``Hopefully, some of that can rub off.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke's experience is a big reason why Tobin brought him and
Ford to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some younger kickers we opted not to bring in
here,'' Tobin said. ``We're coming down to crunch time this season,
and with the pressure of the moment, we needed someone who had been
there and done that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his eight seasons in Green Bay, Jacke has attempted 22 field
goals in the fourth quarter or overtime of close games. He made 19
of those kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he had been out of the league for nearly two seasons. He
didn't re-sign with the Packers in 1997 because of a contract
dispute and went to Pittsburgh instead. But he suffered an upper
thigh injury at training camp and was cut early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke signed with the Washington Redskins late in the year and
played in the final game.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he had tryouts with Denver, Jacksonville, Oakland and
San Francisco before landing with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was beginning to have a lot of doubts whether I'd play this
season,'' said Jacke, who had been working as an intern at American
Express in Green Bay but kept in shape by kicking on his own and
working with a personal trainer. ``I knew it was going to take a
situation like this with someone getting hurt or someone not
performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here not expecting a lot. If it didn't work out, I'd go
back to work in Green Bay. I don't know how long this will last. I
know the Cardinals are quite happy with Joe (Nedney). But I want to
prove I still can kick in this league.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
