<HEADER>
A7911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUHN-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Bowl Championship Series even more flawed than old system
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's T-minus four and counting until college football's bowls
fill up and the sour milk spills over the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Any system that leaves a team like 10-1 Miami at home is
horribly flawed to start with, but this system _ this new Bowl
Championship Series system _ should be euthanized at first
opportunity. Dr. Kevorkian, please check your e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote last week that in trying to fix a broken system, the BCS
broke it worse.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I meant:
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, as many as three or four bowls might have
national championship implications. That was a broken system, a
1938 Packard by the side of the road with smoke coming out the
front and back, because in the end, after the bowls were played, it
relied on subjective judgments.
</P>
<P>
   The next system, the so-called Alliance, managed to get everyone
together except the Big 10 and Pac-10; like a United Nations
without Russia and Germany. That was a broken system, a set of
railroad tracks that ended at a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Now everyone is together, but if you think when Sunday's
pairings come out that the No. 1 and 2 teams in the country will be
playing in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4, your faith in hocus-pocus is
stronger than mine.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know who No. 1 and 2 are, and neither does this system
with its computers and voters and magic beans.
</P>
<P>
   As I said last week, I think Florida State and Ohio State are
the best teams, but neither is likely to end the season in the sand
of Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State and Ohio State each have one loss. I concede that.
But check the unbeatens.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won a game in overtime, beat Oregon State (4-5 at the time)
on a last-minute Hail Mary and beat Stanford (1-6 at the time) when
Stanford fumbled the ball one step from the goal line as it was
about to go in for the winning score.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is good, but that's two too many squeezes for me to believe
there aren't 10 teams at least as good.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee won a game when Arkansas, leading and running out the
clock at game's end, watched its quarterback fumble without being
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State beat Nebraska with the help of two blatantly bogus
officiating calls, then had trouble with a Missouri team that Ohio
State tossed around the field like spare change.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State played the entire season with its No. 2
quarterback, then the No. 3 quarterback won its showdown with
Florida. How strong is that?
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's only loss _ in fact its only close game _ came on a
series of freak plays, including a short Michigan State punt that
hit an OSU blocker in the back and led to a Michigan State
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   I have difficulty with the concept that a Stanford kid fumbles
as he's about to beat UCLA, and an Arkansas kid fumbles untouched
as the Razorbacks are about to beat Tennessee, yet those plays have
more weight than a punt that bounces crazily and hits an Ohio State
kid in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, there are no great teams this season, just a lot
of good ones. Thus this season more than most begs for a playoff
system.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: Play the bowls the way they were played long ago.
Then a committee _ just like the one that selects the field for the
basketball tournament _ chooses four teams and in two weeks you've
got an actual, on-field champion.
</P>
<P>
   Every other NCAA sport from field hockey to fencing to water
polo plays it out. Every other division of NCAA football plays it
out. Only Division I-A football flails blindly to a pale,
unsatisfying conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series is a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-ESCAPE02-COX     12-01 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-ESCAPE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prison officials scale back search
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State prison officials, still convinced that a
killer who escaped from death row is hiding near the Ellis Unit
north of Huntsville, said Tuesday they are scaling back their
search, hoping the reduced activity would lull the fugitive into
making a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically going to cut back the search in that area,''
prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said, referring to a 17,000-acre
area around the prison that has been at the center of a massive
search since Martin Gurule jumped the prison fences early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give the inmate the illusion that it's okay to run,
and hopefully he'll make a mistake,'' Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Allan Polunsky, chairman of the Texas Board of
Criminal Justice, announced the suspension of the work program that
gave Gurule, as well as the six other death row inmates who
attempted to escape with him, greater freedom within their
cellblock and greater opportunity to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly one-third of death row's 454 inmates are on
``work-capable'' status, which allows them to work in the adjacent
garment factory or in janitorial service with less direct
supervision by prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which began in 1983 as part of a class-action
lawsuit related to prison crowding, gives inmates perks like larger
cells and the ability to leave their cells _ their cells doors open
automatically every hour _ to go to the day room or recreation yard
while other inmates remain locked in their cells 23 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky said a special committee will evaluate the program and
report to prison board member Mac Stringfellow, who expects to
finish his review in time for a January prison board meeting in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member committee will be headed by an independent
professional investigator who Polunsky did not name and will also
include representatives of different branches of the prison system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to assure the people of Texas that we will bring back
this fugitive,'' Polunsky said. ``We will bring him back dead or
alive and it really doesn't make any difference in my opinion which
that might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurule, 29, was one of seven death row inmates who cut through a
recreation yard fence with a hacksaw blade Thanksgiving night and
hid on the roof of a prison building for several hours before their
escape attempt shortly after midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule scaled two 10-foot high fences topped with razor wire and
disappeared into the nearby woods. The other six inmates
surrendered when guards, alerted when Gurule tripped a motion
detector on the outer fence, opened fire with automatic rifles. It
is not known if Gurule was wounded by the gunfire or injured by the
razor wire.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule was sent to death row for the 1992 robbery-murder of
Minas ``Mike'' Piperis, the co-owner of the U&AMP;I Restaurant in
Corpus Christi. Gurule also was charged with killing restaurant
employee Anthony Staton, but that case did not go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   After putting as many as 500 corrections officers and police on
the search team for the past five days, prison officials said they
will cut back that number by about one-half, using more mounted
patrols and eliminating many of the foot patrols around their
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesman Glen Castlebury said the prison dog teams,
which have been running along about a dozen trails 24 hours a day,
will now conduct random runs through the woods and bogs within the
search area.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters will still be part of the search effort, and on
Tuesday, more high-tech equipment was added when the Texas National
Guard brought in a helicopter able to detect heat sources on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told it can pick up a live turtle from several hundred
feet in the air, and it did not find any escaped inmate,'' prison
spokesman Larry Todd said after the helicopter's first day in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   While searchers continued scouring the ground, prison officials
pressed their own investigations on Gurule and how he became the
first inmate to escape from death row since 1934.
</P>
<P>
   The prison system's gang expert, Sammy Buentello, said he is
investigating rumors that Gurule was part of the Mexican Mafia
prison gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have him ID'd as a member of any gang,'' Buentello
said. ``We had people saying he was, and we're checking that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Houston Chronicle reported and prison
spokesman Larry Todd later confirmed, that two other death row
inmates tried to escape in virtually the same manner more than a
year ago but were foiled when they were spotted by a tower guard.
</P>
<P>
   Prison records reviewed by the newspaper showed that, like
Gurule and his colleagues, convicted killers Willie Pondexter and
Cedric Ransom cut through a recreation yard fence with a hacksaw
blade.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Walker County Sheriff's Office is investigating
two burglaries within a mile of the prison in which residents
reported bedding, clothes, knives and food stolen. Both burglaries
were reported within 36 hours of Gurule's escape.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gurule's escape, Fitzgerald said prison authorities have
received a number of ``ghost calls'' from people who claim they
spotted Gurule in restaurants, churches, even in the company of a
transvestite in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman offered to let them use her Chihuahua to track
Gurule _ as long as they let her relative out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Sapp is still wondering whether Gurule was the person who
broke into her mobile home in Riverside Harbor, a small subdivision
less than a mile down farm-to-market road 980 from the Ellis Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp said she left her home around 10:30 a.m. Thanksgiving day
and returned around 9 p.m. Friday to find her porch light unplugged
and a number of items missing: blankets and pillows from two beds,
a paring knife and a larger kitchen knife, a half-dozen cans of
soup, two eggs, some jewelry, and two pairs of jeans. More valuable
items like the television and a laptop computer were not taken, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy James, a detective sergeant at the Walker County Sheriff's
Office, said an investigation found no usable fingerprints and no
sign of forced entry. James said her office gave details of the
burglary to prison authorities, and Fitzgerald, the prison
spokesman, said prison investigators ``determined that (burglary
report) was not one they were concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp said she's been staying with her boyfriend ever since and
doesn't plan to sleep at home for a few more days.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, another resident near the prison reported a set of
sheets, garbage bags, toilet paper, and cleaning supplies missing.
James said fingerprints recovered from a broken window pane did not
match Gurule's.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
