<HEADER>
A7913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TOBACCO-ATTYGEN     12-01 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOBACCO-ATTYGEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cornyn to look into tobacco suit
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Once he takes office next year, Texas Attorney
General-elect John Cornyn promised Tuesday that he will scrutinize
the state's $17.3 billion settlement with the tobacco industry and
see whether private attorneys hired to represent the state acted
against the state's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's premature for me to know what I'm going to do,''
Cornyn said. ``I do intend to ask some questions. That's just one
of the things I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's reiterated concerns he and other opponents made in a
bitter and protracted fight over how much a handful of private
lawyers would be paid as as result of Attorney General Dan Morales'
tobacco lawsuit settlement, which had been the largest legal
settlement in history until last month, when several other states
announced a joint settlement with the industry.
</P>
<P>
   He raised the possibility of an inquiry during a Capitol press
conference called to announce four key appointments in his new
administration. Two of these appointments signaled Cornyn's
campaign resolve to tackle the attorney general's beleaguered
child-support enforcement division and bolster its criminal law
enforcement role.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning of his campaign for attorney general, Cornyn
sued to challenge Morales' authority to hire the private lawyers on
a contingency basis to handle the tobacco lawsuit. Morales hired
the lawyers with contracts that promised a 15 percent contingency
fee if the state recovered public money spent on treating
smoking-related illness.
</P>
<P>
   At 15 percent, the lawyers stood to recover as much as $2.3
billion or more _ itself the largest contingency payment in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's asked the Texas Supreme Court to decide what authority
Morales had to hire the private lawyers. Later, seven state
legislators and Gov. George W. Bush, in separate actions, sued to
intervene in the tobacco case itself.
</P>
<P>
   In arguments that the challengers made over the fees award,
various opponents raised the possibility that the private lawyers
breached their fiduciary duty to their client, the state, in part
by devising a settlement that paid them with money the opponents
claimed should have gone to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' spokesman, Ron Dusek, said Tuesday that Morales _ not
the private lawyers he hired to handle the trial _ negotiated the
tobacco deal. ``He has said very clearly that Texas, at the time
the deal was negotiated, had the best deal of any state involved in
the tobacco litigation,'' Dusek said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tobacco settlement, the private lawyers first would be
paid by the tobacco companies to the extent that three arbitrators
set their fee. The federal judge supervising the tobacco case also
awarded them their 15 percent fee, leaving open the possibility
that they could recover any difference from the state if the
arbitrators granted them less.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from Bush and others, who reached a settlement
deal with Morales, Cornyn later dropped his legal challenge to the
payment arrangement, but never dropped his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   His comments about wanting to question the fee arrangement in
his official capacity comes at a time when the arbitration panel
begins to review the case and determine what fees the attorneys
should be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cornyn moved on other fronts as he makes his
transition into office.
</P>
<P>
   His tapped Howard Baldwin as deputy attorney general in charge
of child-support enforcement. Baldwin, now with the Department of
Protective and Regulatory Services, helped his Democratic opponent
Jim Mattox set up a child support court-master program when Mattox
was attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin later served as master in San Antonio. His successor,
family law Judge Jim Rausch, said Tuesday that Baldwin was a wise
choice because of his knowledge of the system and his relationship
with the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the ins and outs of the child-support program
probably better than anyone else,'' Rausch said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn also announced Shane Phelps, who once headed Attorney
General Dan Morales' prosecutors assistance division before he ran
for Travis County district attorney, as deputy in charge of
criminal justice, and Andy Taylor of Houston as his first
assistant. Cornyn said Taylor would be his ``right-hand man.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a law partner with former Attorney General and Texas
Chief Justice John Hill, was Cornyn's campaign treasurer. He also
was instrumental in Hill's reply to critics who cited Cornyn as
leading among justices in the percentage of their campaign
contributions from lawyers and parties with cases before the court.
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
