<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HEARING-NYT &LR;      12-01 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HEARING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSEQUENCES OF PERJURY DEBATED IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas, Mass., S.C., Idaho, Pa., Fla.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-PERJURY) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee held a
nine-hour hearing Tuesday on the consequences of perjury, seeking
to stoke support in the House for impeaching President Clinton on
that charge.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats argued that Republicans had failed to prove
that Clinton had deliberately lied under oath to conceal his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Other Democrats said that if the
president had lied about the matter, it would not be an impeachable
offense. Even the Republicans' witnesses were divided on whether
the House should impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican witnesses differed from their colleagues in their
opinions on impeachment. ``I'd recommend you not vote for
impeachment,'' said Judge Charles Wiggins, a senior judge on the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, who was a California Republican
on the Judiciary Committee in 1974. Wiggins, who called the
evidence against Clinton ``vague,'' had voted against impeaching
President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   The other witness, Adm. Leon Edney, a retired four-star officer
who testified on the corrosive effects of lying in the military,
said in an interview, ``I'm not advocating impeachment. I think
it'd be deleterious and would not be healthy for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In the highly partisan hearing that featured a parade of
witnesses, from convicted perjurers to federal judges to a
decorated Army general who has retired, Republicans tried to
underscore perjury's harmful effects on the nation's justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If citizens are allowed to lie with impunity _ or encourage
others to tell false stories or hide evidence _ judges and juries
cannot reach just results,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the
committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, the courtroom becomes an arena for artful liars
and the jury a mere focus group choosing between alternative
fictions,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   With the committee expected to approve at least one article of
impeachment next week, House Republican aides say a vote on the
House floor to impeach Clinton on a perjury count, which has the
best chance of passing, would be too close to call. Republican
committee aides are also drawing up counts of obstruction of
justice and witness tampering, and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, and the witnesses they called, said that while
Clinton's conduct was wrong and should be punished, his offenses
were, according to one retired judge, no worse than lying about a
speeding violation and did not warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is not simply to abide by the public's understanding
of lying,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas. ``Our charge is
to determine whether these are impeachable offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also criticized a series of new Republican subpoenas
approved Tuesday in a party-line vote that broadened the
investigation into the president's 1996 campaign finance practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are indeed in a wild goose chase of the week,'' said Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass., who cited the Republicans' fruitless detour
this week into questioning of witnesses about whether they
influenced the testimony of Kathleen Willey, a former White House
volunteer who accused Clinton of making an unwanted sexual advance
outside the Oval Office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, barely controlling his anger, replied that the committee
was not engaged in a wild goose chase and was not confined to the
referral from Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's proceeding was in many ways a two-part hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In the first part, lawmakers heard testimony from two convicted
perjurers, whose remorseful, sometimes tearful comments seemed to
turn the cavernous, wood-paneled hearing room into a giant
confessional.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they called the perjurers to show the personal
consequences faced by some offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, I could finally say I'm guilty,'' said Pam Parsons,
a former women's basketball coach at the University of South
Carolina. She went to prison for four months in 1984, after a
perjury conviction for her testimony in a civil libel lawsuit she
filed against Sports Illustrated. The magazine reported that Ms.
Parsons had had a lesbian relationship with a team player and
recruited players with ``sex in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Tuesday that she had lied under oath about whether she
had visited a lesbian bar called Puss 'n Boots in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Battalino, a former Veterans Affairs psychiatrist at a
medical center in Idaho, lied in a civil deposition about whether
``anything of a sexual nature'' occurred in her office with a man
who was a Vietnam veteran seeking psychiatric help.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a very real sense, I am condemned to a life sentence,''
said Dr. Battalino, who is currently under house arrest in Idaho.
``I have lost my professional standing, my life as it had been, and
my cherished privacy _ these consequences are irrevocable.''
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, the tone turned serious as lawmakers grilled
a new panel of law professors, judges and retired military officers
on the seriousness of perjury and under what circumstances lying
would amount to an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., said that Clinton had engaged in a
``pattern'' of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., said, ``I'm concerned that some have
tried to diminish perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   But the three law professors, a former federal judge and a
former attorney general summoned by the Democrats said there were
no grounds for impeachment. Many recommended a censure instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``As serious a crime as perjury is, there exists a spectrum of
gravity with regard to false statements,'' said Judge A. Leon
Higginbotham Jr., a retired federal appellate court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham said there were perjuries that cause harm to the
country, for example, if the president had lied about selling
nuclear secrets to a foreign agent. The judge said the lesser
versions would include any lie under oath by the president about a
speeding violation. Higginbotham equated Clinton's relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky to the speeding violation.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Richardson, a former attorney general under President
Nixon, said that if committee members had decided in advance that
removing the president from office was too harsh a penalty for the
offense, impeachment was ``pointless,'' and lawmakers should adopt
an alternative, like censure.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the nine-hour hearing, tempers grew short.
Alan Dershowitz, a professor at Harvard Law School who testified
that no ordinary citizen would be prosecuted for what Clinton did,
criticized the Republican-led inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee is openly trivializing the rule of law,''
Dershowitz said. ``All Republicans care about is the perjury
committed by one Democrat'' _ Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, his lips pursed tightly, wagged his finger at Dershowitz
and shot back, ``You have disparaged us by leaping to
conclusions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
