r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-CUP-TALK-     12-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-CUP-TALK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS, FOES AGREE COYOTES ARE `FOR REAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB McMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ The ``Keeper of the Cup'' swore he would be
back. In fact, he guaranteed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we always make sure a city sees it more than once,''
Walter Neubrand said last spring when he toted the Stanley Cup on
its three-day visit to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of more than 50 stops that Neubrand, an employee of
the Hockey Hall of Fame in Toronto, and hockey's Holy Grail, the
NHL's championship trophy, made during the Cup's three-month
``tour'' of North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``In another couple, three years,'' Neubrand said, ``I'm sure
you'll see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a lot sooner than that.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Coyotes' incredible start _ a league-leading 14-2-2
mark entering tonight's game in Edmonton _ has many observers
around the league talking up the Valley's team not only as a
legitimate ``contender'' to win the Stanley Cup, but perhaps the
``favorite''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think they're for real,'' said Barry Melrose, a
hockey studio analyst for ESPN and former head coach of the Los
Angeles Kings. ``I thought they were for real the last couple
years, for that matter, but they underachieved for all that talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can they win the Cup? Absolutely. A couple things have to
happen, but yeah, I'd definitely put them at the front of the
pack.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Melrose tempers those thoughts, adding 18 games into
the season is still early to make a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not how you start a season, it's how you end it,''
Melrose said. ``But the've got all the tools. They've got excellent
goaltending. They've got solid defensemen who can move the puck.
They've got great forwards, two or three lines than can score. And
if they stay healthy and continue to battle, no question about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the Stanley Cup going to Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   No disrespect to the Arizona Rattlers, who have laid claim to
two Arena Football League championships, but a real major league
title team in the Valley? A Stanley Cup in the desert before an NBA
crown by the Suns, desert dwellers for more than 30 years? A
Stanley Cup before a Super Bowl by the Cardinals, who've been
around for 100 years, the past 11 in Arizona? A Stanley Cup before
a World Series by the young, but free-spending Diamondbacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that Coyote team a lot,'' said Scotty Bowman, head
coach of the two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red
Wings. ``They're playing like they've got something to prove this
year. And lately, they've been proving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman made that comment nearly a month ago, a day before the
Coyotes defeated his Red Wings, 3-1, on Nov. 6. That victory gave
Phoenix its fourth straight win at the time after a 2-2 tie in
Anaheim on Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes haven't been derailed since, running all the way to
the top of the standings.
</P>
<P>
   They are on a franchise-record, 14-game unbeaten streak
(12-0-2). They have won eight games in a row, one shy of tying
another club mark. Their winning percentage of .833 is tied for the
sixth-best winning percentage after 18 games in NHL history, and
four of the five teams above them made the finals in their
respective seasons. And if they hold the Oilers to two goals or
fewer tonight, it will be the 18th consecutive time they've done it
to the opposition, one shy of tying the Montreal Canadiens'
modern-era NHL record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a defense play this well or two goaltenders
completely shut down people like this in a long, long time,'' said
former NHL goalie John Davidson, an analyst for the FOX network.
``It's been an incredible run by the Phoenix Coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld has done his best to downplay all
the hype surrounding his team, which only figures to increase this
week during the team's trip to hockey-hungry Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won the Stanley Cup,'' he said. ``We're 100 miles
from where we want to be as a team and where we have to be as a
team. I think your recognition comes during the springtime, when
you're playing in May and you're playing in June and you're winning
playoff series.''
</P>
<P>
   If they keep it up, they will. According to Melrose's ESPN
colleague Bill Clement, there are four key components why the
Coyotes are a Cup contender:
</P>
<P>
   The break between games in the early part of the schedule has
allowed the players to rest and the coaches to coach.
</P>
<P>
   An attention to defense first, especially by 22-year-old Oleg
Tverdovsky, has made a strong group of blueliners even stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The team's top two players, left wing Keith Tkachuk and center
Jeremy Roenick, have proved they can co-exist and thrive on the No.
1 line as their combined 18 goals and 42 points attest.
</P>
<P>
   And, as they have evolved into a team, they have learned as a
team, specifically Schoenfeld, a career .500 coach in the NHL prior
to this season, who has done some of his best work with
less-talented teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've been able to accomplish this far is terrific,''
Clement said, ``and I don't think it's a farce at all. They're
definitely one of the teams people are going to have to contend
with.''
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, the Coyotes weren't even picked to make
the playoffs by a few publications. Veteran forward Rick Tocchet,
who won a Stanley Cup with the Pittsburgh Penguins in 1992, prefers
the underdog role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while, you'll hear stuff like, `What about those
Coyotes?' '' Tocchet said, ``but then you'll turn around and hear
something like, ``Well, yeah. But how 'bout them Toronto Maple
Leafs?' I kind of like that. I like us waltzing into rinks and
waltzing out.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't as if they have taken the NHL by surprise, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper,'' said Vancouver Canucks Coach Mike Keenan,
``they've always looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one damn good team over there,'' Tampa Bay Lightning
Coach/General Manager Jacques Demers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing everything right,'' Chicago Blackhawks
defenseman Chris Chelios said.
</P>
<P>
   During last Saturday's game against the Kings, the Coyotes
looked like anything but a Cup contender in the opening 20 minutes.
But in the second period, they scored three goals on their way to
an easy 4-0 win, which didn't exactly shock Los Angeles Coach Larry
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got soft,'' he said, ``and when you play against a team as
talented as Phoenix, you know they're not going to give you a lot
of chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit that to the Coyotes' goaltending duo of Jimmy Waite and
Nikolai Khabibulin, who rank first and second in the NHL with
goals-against averages of 1.15 and 1.57 and save percentages of
.956 and .938. A true Stanley Cup-type team, they say, can only go
as far as its goalies can carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, and it's the sign of a great team. A first-place
team that can't seem to lose after two months of the season. The
Coyotes, though, have advanced beyond the first round of the
playoffs only twice in their 20-year NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, my friend,'' Melrose said, ``will change this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
