<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-220&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS AND NBA TO TALK WITHOUT ANY PRECONDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 15 days away from the bargaining table, players
and owners on Thursday will make another bid to resuscitate the
National Basketball Association season.
</P>
<P>
   Union executive director Billy Hunter telephoned league
commissioner David Stern on Tuesday to set up the meeting as the
lockout entered its sixth month.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting in Manhattan will include full bargaining teams from
each side. There will be only one pre-meeting stipulation: every
issue on the table will be negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no preconditions,'' said deputy commissioner
Russ Granik. ``Whatever proposals we made two weeks ago, we're not
bound to. Whatever was put on the table at the last meeting is now
undone. I'm not optimistic, but like said I number of times, it
doesn't usually hurt to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, players missed their second payday. Union president
Patrick Ewing, who was due to earn $18.5 million this season, has
now lost nearly $4 million in salary. Total player salary losses
are projected above $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Concern is mounting on both sides as to whether the season will
actually be canceled. The NBA has refused to set an official
deadline, but if no deal is struck by mid-December the feeling
among many of the NBA's 29 owners is that there is no point in
having less than a 45-game season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The league has refused to use a mediator and will not declare an
impasse in negotiations, a tactic that major-league baseball
unsuccessfully used in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Given that it will take a month after an agreement is reached
for the season to begin, it would not be surprising if the league
soon announced the cancellation of the All-Star Game Feb. 14 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   If the league were to cancel the All-Star game, it would most
likely award Philadelphia the game in 2002. The NBA has already
committed itself to holding the event in San Francisco in 2000 and
in Washington for the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is the first since Nov. 20 in New York _ a 10-hour
affair that seemed to produce the most encouraging signs of a
possible settlement. Within two days, that progress was dashed when
the union and the league clashed over key economic issues. A
misunderstanding over how an escrow system would be implemented in
the fourth, fifth and sixth years of a seven-year plan led to
breakoff of the talks again.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, 10 hours of bargaining went to waste. While both
sides had moved off their desired numbers for total revenue
distribution _ the NBA wanted the players to make no more than 53
percent of income and the players proposed a 57-43 split, the
league is back to asking for a 50-50 share and the players want up
to 60 percent of the revenue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Refunds on the Way
</P>
<P>
   National Basketball Association teams are sending out refund
checks this week to season ticket holders for games that have not
been played. Each team must send back a pro-rated share of each
season ticket, along with 6 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams have five business days from today to send out the
checks,'' said NBA spokesman Brian McIntyre on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets offered season ticket holders cash refunds
or credits for four canceled home regular season games and one
canceled exhibition game, said Jim Lampariello, an executive vice
president of the team.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of credits included additional tickets for games
later this season if the lockout ends, or playoff tickets. About 70
percent chose refunds, which the team will start mailing out
Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks only offered fans cash refunds, and checks
were being mailed out Tuesday for five home regular season games
and two exhibition games, said Barry Watkins, a spokesman for
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   People with individual game tickets can get cash refunds at
outlets where the tickets were purchased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
