<SLUG> BC-OLY-HALL-PROTEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL WINS 2ND COURT ROUND, BUT STRUGGLES IN POOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Gary Hall Jr. won a second round in court Tuesday but
failed to get beyond the preliminaries in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Hall finished 13th in the 100-meter freestyle at College
Station, Texas, about 15 minutes after a federal judge in Phoenix
upheld a restraining order that allowed him to compete in the World
Cup despite a drug suspension by swimming's Swiss-based governing
body, FINA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an emotional roller-coaster for me,'' said Hall, who
won two gold and two silver medals at the 1996 Olympics. ``I did
have to contest this in court late last night and very early this
morning, so I'm not running on much sleep here. It makes it
difficult to concentrate on swimming, which is what I'm here for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's been a six-month suspension. I feel it's
punishment enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was warming up at the Texas A&AMP;M pool for his first
competition in more than six months as deliberations were under way
in Judge Roger Strand's courtroom in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Strand stood by his initial order, issued Monday night, after
hearing from Hall's attorneys and representatives of FINA, which
suspended the Phoenix swimmer for a positive marijuana test.
</P>
<P>
   FINA replied Tuesday morning with a 13-page fax from its offices
in Lausanne. Attorney Raymond Lembke of Cincinnati also argued in
FINA's behalf from his office in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   FINA contended that the Phoenix sprinter is still under
suspension. The restraining order would undercut FINA's ability to
enforce rules, according to Lembke, who said the governing body was
in jeopardy of becoming ``a toothless tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   But Strand's decision sided with Hall attorney Ed Hendricks, who
argued that FINA had ``manipulated'' the terms of the suspension.
Hendricks said it should have begun on May 15, the day of the
positive test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hall has been precluded from swimming in critical
international events for almost 100 days,'' Hendricks said.
</P>
<P>
   In a confusing scenario, the suspension started on June 15. But
FINA temporarily lifted it on Aug. 11 as it tried to determine
whether Hall's positive test was a first or second offense. He
tested positive for marijuana at the 1996 Olympics. But that was
before the substance was subject to Olympic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Nov. 12, Hall was informed that he had to serve 30 more
days of suspension or, through Dec. 12. He asked the Court Of
Arbitration in Sport at Lausanne to reconsider. He was told Monday
that his request had been denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just elated to be back in the pool,'' said Hall, who also
finished 11th in the 50 butterfly and is scheduled today to swim
the 50 freestyle as a prelude to the U.S. Open, Thursday through
Saturday. ``I didn't die and it didn't hurt. Making it to the
starting blocks was the real accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   FINA honorary secretary Gunnar Werner said from Sweden that Hall
still would be banned from competition abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is only valid in the United States,'' Werner
said. ``Hall is still suspended in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that FINA rules are prevailing in a case like
this. Our position is the court in the U.S. is not competent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall went on to criticize FINA by comparing it treatment of him
to the way it has handled the Chinese, who have repeatedly tested
positive for performance-enhancing drugs. Marijuana is not
considered a performance enhancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stuck it harder to me than they did the Chinese,'' Hall
said. ``It sends a confusing message.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
