<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER MAY START AT MIDDLE LINEBACKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TEMPE, ARIZ. -  &UR; Jamir Miller is going to have to learn the
nuances of playing middle linebacker in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who has been a starting outside linebacker during his
entire five years with the Cardinals, will work at middle
linebacker at today's practice because of knee injuries to starter
 &UR; Ronald
 &UR; McKinnon and backup  &UR; Mark Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jamir practices the way he's capable of practicing, we're
leaning on him starting him there,'' Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said of
Sunday's game against the New York Giants. ``I think Jamir might be
really, really good there.''
</P>
<P>
   With Miller moving to the middle,  &UR; Patrick Sapp, 6 foot 4, 258
pounds, likely will make his first start at left outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is to get the best football team out there,''
Tobin said. ``Patrick Sapp is getting better. I like the way he's
been practicing and I like his athletic ability. He has good size
and can match up on tight ends, and New York tight ends are very
good blockers and have given us trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon, who has started all 12 games this season, suffered a
sprained right knee in last Sunday's 34-24 loss at Kansas City. He
is the team's leading tackler with 112 and has a team-high five
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't expected to play against the Giants and is listed as
``week to week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll only be out one week and that's it,'' McKinnon
said. ``I can't miss games. But I also know I have to be smart
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said McKinnon could be out as long as two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox should be available after missing the past two weeks
because of a knee injury, but he might not be 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two weeks rest, I feel 100 times better,'' Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, an eighth-year pro who signed as a free agent in the
off-season, hasn't started since last Nov. 30 when he played for
Buffalo against the New York Jets. &QL; 
Surgery scheduled &QL; 
Injured kicker  &UR; Joe Nedney feared the worst and wasn't
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   A magnetic resonance imaging exam showed he suffered a rupture
of the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee and will have
surgery when the swelling goes down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Dr. Chick (team orthopedist  &UR; Russell Chick), and
he told me if I chose not to have surgery, I could kick without an
ACL, but I wouldn't be able to do anything else,'' Nedney said.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery will take place in Vail, Colo., and will be
performed by Dr.  &UR; Richard Steadman, who also is scheduled to
perform arthroscopic surgery on Cardinals defensive tackle  &UR; Eric
Swann next week.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery for an ACL tear lasts nine to 12 months for most NFL
players, according to team doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But Nedney is the first NFL kicker to suffer the injury to his
kicking leg. So, team officials are not sure how long he'll be out.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Jan. 1 comes, I want to be on the road to
recovery,'' Nedney said. ``I want to be ready for training camp (in
late July). I've had a few surgeries and healed much quicker than
expected.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
