<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SWANN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN DECIDES ON SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The Cardinals have given up hope that defensive
tackle Eric Swann will return this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said he expects Swann to have
arthroscopic surgery on his right knee and miss the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Swann is scheduled to have the surgery Monday in Vail, Colo.,
where it will be performed by Richard Steadman, the orthopedist who
consults with the U.S. Olympic Ski Team.
</P>
<P>
   Steadman has recommended that Swann have his seventh
arthroscopic surgery, fifth on his arthritic right knee, and then
be on crutches for eight to nine weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials had hoped that Swann would seek another
opinion before having the surgery. Several of Swann's teammates
also have said they hoped he would postpone the surgery and return
to action to help the team in its playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   He had arthroscopic surgery on Oct. 28 and was expected to
return this week. But he complained of soreness in the knee and
informed Tobin that he planned to have another surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, who signed a five-year, $25 million contract in the
off-season, would end the season with 33 tackles, four sacks and
two forced fumbles in seven games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
