<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO WHO'S GOING TO HIT FOR THIS TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - OK, so now the Diamondbacks are armed with the
second-best rotation in the National League. If all goes according
to plan, the club's starting pitchers will be the foundation for
what could be the most startling turnaround from 1998 to '99.
</P>
<P>
   With the rotation apparently set for years to come, the club's
primary concern will be getting the offense to somehow measure up
to the pitching.
</P>
<P>
   With six bona fide starters on the roster, it seems all but
certain that Brian Anderson will be the odd-man out. His trade
value is fairly high and the front office hopes to get a
run-producing outfielder in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Until such a deal can be worked out, let's assume the roster
will stay intact. If they had to play a game today the lineup would
look something like this: Andy Fox, RF; Jay Bell, 2B; Travis Lee,
1B; Matt Williams, 3B; Bernard Gilkey, LF; Tony Batista, SS; Kelly
Stinnett, C and Dante Powell, CF.
</P>
<P>
   True, it looks strikingly similar to the one from last season,
the one that managed to score a paltry 665 runs, just 21 more than
Montreal's NL-worst total. As with any December analysis, there are
intangibles the club hopes will work in its favor in 1999. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a jack-of-all trades, would start in right field and lead
off, which would alleviate pressure on Powell to try to break into
the majors and lead off. Bell needs to cut down on his strikeouts
and improve his on-base percentage. But the club would gladly take
another 20 home runs and 70 or so RBIs from him.
</P>
<P>
   Lee looks as if he just needs to be left alone to continue his
maturation into a big-league star. Is Batista for real? Well,
there's really only one way to find out, and that's to stick him
out there every day. Stinnett will combine with Damian Miller
behind the plate and although their offense is nothing out of this
world, the club would like for the pair to concentrate on their
catching duties.
</P>
<P>
   However, the two biggest question marks looming over the offense
are the projected No. 4 and 5 hitters, where the big RBI men
usually stand tall.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Williams nor Gilkey, who figure to hold down those two
spots, had a season worth remembering in 1998. However, each can
point to previous years and be confident of turning one horrible
season into little more than a bad memory.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has clubbed 299 home runs in his career, slumped
to his second least-productive season (20 home runs and 71 RBIs) of
his career. As recent as 1997 Williams hit 32 home runs with 105
RBIs for Cleveland. This is not a guy who is over the hill, no
matter how much hair he's lost.
</P>
<P>
   The club's primary reason to believe Williams will bounce back
and return to his usual 30 home runs and 100 RBIs hinges on
Williams' intense pride. This is a player who was seemingly never
content with his results during his All-Star seasons, so you can
imagine how disappointed the four-time Gold Glove winner was after
last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand there's Gilkey, who went from being an
undrafted high school kid almost to All-Star caliber. Gilkey
pounded out 275 extra-base hits from 1993-97, including slugging at
least 40 doubles in a season twice.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilkey managed just one extra-base hit in 101 at-bats after
arriving in a July 31 trade from the New York Mets, which is one
more than managing general partner Jerry Colangelo had last season
_ and he never stepped into the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking, even back to his days with the Mets, was that
Gilkey's eyesight was below par. After the Mets were unsuccessful
in prodding Gilkey into considering laser eye surgery, the
Diamondbacks were able to do so in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey has reported to management that his eyesight has not been
this sharp in years.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks only hope he can become a force. Gilkey does
not have to put up a season like 1996, when he hit .317 with 30
home runs and 117 RBIs. Anything near 20 home runs and 80 RBIs will
be more than enough to bulk up the middle of what was one of the
weakest lineups in baseball last season.
</P>
<P>
   One other thought, with this starting rotation in place the
Diamondbacks' hitters know they do not need to score five or six
runs to win. Just getting these type starters, any kind of early
run support should be more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre, Andy Benes, Omar Daal and
Armando Reynoso just ask for a couple of early runs. Then they will
do the rest. Still, the onus will be on the offense to take care of
its end of the bargain. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
