<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ALL-BIG-TEAM-COX     12-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALL-BIG-TEAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ricky Williams offensive player of the year in All-Big 12 Team
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While Kansas State's bid for a national football
championship has been conducted in relative _ and frequently
self-imposed _ anonymity, the University of Texas' revival has been
the Big 12's feel-good story of the year, at least for those of a
burnt-orange persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighted by Ricky Williams, who has run into the record books
and is in line to win the school's second Heisman Trophy, several
of the key components of the Longhorns' fairy-tale season have been
rewarded with major awards on the Austin American-Statesman's 1998
All-Big 12 Team.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, major-college football's all-time rushing leader, is
the offensive player of the year. While Kansas State quarterback
Michael Bishop had a marvelous season and earned first-team honors,
Williams had a season for the ages that capped a career for the
ages. He rushed for a national-best 2,124 yards this year, giving
him 6,279 for his career to eclipse Tony Dorsett's 22-year-old
national record. Williams has broken 12 NCAA records and tied four
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got my vote for the Heisman, if I had one,'' said Texas
A&AMP;M linebacker Dat Nguyen, the American-Statesman's defensive
player of the year. ``I don't think I'll ever play against anyone
as good as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   For having the good sense to let Ricky run, and for
orchestrating a four-game turnaround from last season and
re-igniting the enthusiasm for UT football that had been waning in
its disenfranchised fans, Mack Brown is the coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has been the most fun I've ever had in
coaching,'' Brown said after guiding the Longhorns to an 8-3 mark.
``I don't think I've ever seen a team improve this much, especially
with their self-image and their attitude and just having fun. It's
been a great year and it's been fun to see the way the fans have
responded to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-year UT coach edged Kansas State's Bill Snyder for the
honor. Snyder's Wildcats have done a marvelous job in positioning
themselves for a shot at a national championship, but that was
pretty much expected of them this season. And their title dreams
have been hurt because of Snyder's decision to play a weak
nonconference schedule, which has dropped them to third in the Bowl
Championship Series computer rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns' resurgence was due in no small part to the
transformation of their defense from a league laughingstock last
year to a respected unit this season. For that reason, UT defensive
coordinator Carl Reese is the assistant coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   With basically the same players who allowed 399.2 yards per game
last season to rank 10th in the Big 12 and 85th nationally, Reese
molded the Longhorns into a more aggressive, attack-oriented unit.
Texas' rush defense improved dramatically _ a must in the
tailback-rich Big 12 _ as the Horns allowed only 143.5 ground yards
per game after being at 241.5 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deserve it,'' Reese said of the honor. ``I've got a
lot of great assistants.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, despite being undersized, used his amazing football
instincts to become the all-time career tackling leader for the
Aggies. With 14 tackles in the regular-season finale against Texas,
Nguyen has a league-high 130 stops for the season and 500 for his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Riggs writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2246EST &QL; 
