<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-POLICE-PENSIONS-C     12-01 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-POLICE-PENSIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cities balking at proposed boost in police, firefighter pensions
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Police are sometimes called the thin blue
line, but Florida cities say their budgets will bleed a thin red
line if GOP legislators start 1999 by forcing them to boost
pensions for police and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will cost cities up to $55 million annually, including
$760,000 in Delray Beach, $1.9 million in Boca Raton, and $83,000
in Riviera Beach, according to a Price Waterhouse study
commissioned by the Florida League of Cities. The cities spent
$50,000 for the study. Its conclusions were immediately questioned
by unions and Republican leaders, who stand in rare alliance on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by the taxpayer group Florida TaxWatch, the cities called
the plan obvious payback for Republican political endorsements by
police and fire unions. Democratic Gov. Lawton Chiles vetoed the
bill last year, saying it wasn't right for Tallahassee to be
dictating to cities that they had to use certain tax revenues for
pension benefits that were not necessarily part of contracts they
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Delray city commissioners Tuesday night approved a resolution
supporting the veto. Mayor Jay Alperin said he talked with some
state representatives about the issue and they were ``very
resistant and reluctant. The power of the interests who are
promoting this is really overwhelming.'' But Boca Raton finance
director Meryvn Timberlake said he was not sure the city's costs
would be as high as $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker John Thrasher has said he wants to override the
veto as the first thing his chamber does, possibly in a special
session in January. ``It was clearly a political deal,'' said Scott
Maddox, mayor of Tallahassee and vice president of the Florida
League of Cities whose own father was a cop involved in politics.
``Clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited a second study by Tallahassee researcher Lance
deHaven-Smith showing Florida's pension benefits are already among
the most generous in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   David Murrell, executive director of the Florida Police
Benevolent Association, was not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go out and pay somebody $50,000 to say what we want
and it would have the same amount of credibility,'' Murrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Thrasher said no one outside the cities' payroll has verified
the report's claims. He said he had not changed his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to move ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Jeb Bush has indicated support for the bill, which he
confirmed again Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Toni Jennings, through a spokeswoman, said she
may be content to wait until the regular session to take up the
issue. There was only one ``no'' vote for the bill in the Senate
last year, but it came from Sen. Jack Latvala, R-Palm Harbor, who
is now majority leader and a Jennings ally.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the first salvo in a renewed campaign to beat a
bill that passed the legislature with overwhelming support last
year, though the pension battle has raged for years. Maddox said it
passed because legislators were told it wouldn't really cost
anything _ that only new taxes from insurance policies would be
used to standardize minimum pension amounts statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have four people in my family in that profession, and if I
were told it wouldn't cost anything I probably would have said sure
I'd vote for it,'' Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he said, is that cities are depending on the tax
money in question _ which comes from growth in tax revenues from
home and car insurance policies _ to pay for growing needs in other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers, city officials charge, are traitors to their own
party's principles of smaller government and lower taxes; it's a
classic case of passing a law and providing no money for it.
</P>
<P>
   QuickReadGOP leaders say the cost of boosting fire and police
pensions would be minimal, but cities commissioned a study that
found it would be a half-billion dollars over 10 years. Estimated
increased annual costs:
</P>
<P>
   Riviera Beach $83,000
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach $760,000
</P>
<P>
   Boca Raton $1.9 million
</P>
<P>
   Orlando $5.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Fort Lauderdale $3.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Statewide $55.7 million
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Study by Price Waterhouse Coopers LLP, Tampa office.
Paid for by Florida League of Cities.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981201.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHER-ATTEMPTEDMURDE     12-01 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-ATTEMPTEDMURDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mother held after trying to drown her children
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A suburban Boca Raton mother who faces
attempted murder charges after locking her two children in her car
and driving into a canal east of Boca Rio Road, was ordered held in
jail without bond Tuesday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Oviedo, 27, and her two children _ Maria, 7, and Michael,
3 _ were pulled to safety Monday night by her husband and Shimshon
Hazan, a motorist who stopped to help.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo had been living with relatives, police reports show. She
was temporarily separated from her husband, Miguel, 28. On Monday,
she got into a fight with her mother, telling her, ``Tomorrow you
are going to bury three, because you will not see the kids again,''
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she called her cousin, Leidy Manzo, and asked Manzo to tell
Miguel Oviedo to meet her by the canal. When he and Manzo arrived
around 10 p.m., Ingrid had locked herself and the children inside
the car, reports said. ``I have had it. I have no privacy. Everyone
meddles in my life,'' she told Manzo, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children (were) begging her to open the door'' of the 1995
Toyota 4Runner, the police report said, but ``Ingrid would not let
them. She told them, `No,' and to sit down.'' Then she drove the
car into the 15-foot-deep canal, sheriff's department spokesman
Paul Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, the husband was able to get a tire iron,'' Miller
said. ``He broke out the back window and pulled the two kids out of
the car.'' Miguel Oviedo told police that his wife helped him get
one of their children out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Hazan was on his way home when he noticed several cars parked by
the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk up and the car is almost under water,'' said Hazan, of
suburban Boca Raton. ``So I don't even think. I take off my shoes
and just jump in the water.'' Only about a foot of the car remained
above water, Hazan said, as he and Miguel Oviedo dragged a
semi-conscious Ingrid out of the car. ``I'm standing on top of the
car and it's sinking fast. If it goes under, she dies. It was pitch
black; there was no way we could save her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time I'm thinking about my family, and also the
other car they just pulled from the canal,'' Hazan said. In
February 1997, the remains of five teenagers who had been missing
since July 14, 1979, were found in a van at the bottom of the same
canal, just north of Glades Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so sorry for (the Oviedo) kids,'' Hazan said. ``Imagine
what this does to them emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria and Michael Oviedo were treated on the canal bank for
minor scrapes and bruises. They went home with their father, Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Oviedo, who does not speak English, was taken to West
Boca Medical Center, where she was interviewed by a detective and
charged with two counts of attempted murder and two counts of
aggravated child assault.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Oviedo was at his wife's court appearance Tuesday
afternoon, Miller said, and the two waved to each other toward the
end of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   A man who answered the door at the Oviedo home refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Mnookin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Palm Beach Post researcher Sammy Alzofon contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
