<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Another Switch on A-Weapons
</P>
<P>
   Prolonging a German zigzag on NATO's nuclear policy, Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder said his country had the right to suggest that
the alliance renounce first use of nuclear weapons. The proposal
was first aired last month by Foreign Minister Joshcka Fischer, but
then appeared to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Support for Hindu Party
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which lost state
elections last week to the opposition Congress Party, got a pledge
of continuing support from Jayalalitha Jayaram, general secretary
of the All India Anna Dravida Munetra Kazhagam Party. Other Hindu
allies have vowed to stay with the Bharatiya Janata.
</P>
<P>
   _ CELIA W. DUGGER
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Suharto's Forest Holdings
</P>
<P>
   Former President Suharto, his family and close associates own
more than 22 million acres of Indonesian forest according to a
report by the Forest Ministry. The Minister of Forestry and
Plantations, Muslimin Nasution, said that there was a ``strong
indication'' that the holdings were acquired by the Suharto family
through ``corruptive, collusive and nepotistic practices.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Money Supply Squeezed
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Central Bank has squeezed the money supply for the
sixth time this year in an effort to meet its 1999 inflation target
of 13 percent. The bank announced it would make available to the
country's commercial banks about $13 million less credit than they
need to meet their daily obligations, which is expected to increase
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAM DILLON
</P>
</TEXT>
