<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLBUS-DEATH-COX     12-01 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLBUS-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First grader killed by school bus
 &HT;    By Brandon Peterson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A Dayton first-grader was fatally run over by a
school bus Tuesday afternoon after he left the bus, then ran back
as the driver started up again, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Pendleton, 6, was taken to Franciscan Medical Center,
where he was pronounced dead of multiple trauma injuries at 4:26
p.m., according to a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton, a pupil at City Day Community School who had
celebrated a birthday Nov. 20, was struck after he and another
pupil were dropped off at the day care center at the Dayton Boys
and Girls Club, according to Dayton Police Sgt. George D. Hammann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy exited the bus, and for some reason returned to the
street to pick up something,'' Hammann aid.
</P>
<P>
   Hammann said the driver, who said she had seen both youngsters
on the sidewalk before she moved the bus, felt a thud under the
left rear tire and witnesses told the driver to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Children and adults stood behind yellow police tape as police
detectives marked streets and photographed the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was anything anyone ever wanted in a little boy,'' said
Jane Dixon, principal of City Day Community School, a charter
school. Dixon was visibly shaken as she gazed at the small Nike
tennis shoe and black hat in the street behind the school bus. ``He
had it all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Kirby, executive director of safety, security and
transportation for Dayton City Schools, said 15 children were on
the bus at the time. Kirby identified the driver as Sue Elkins.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Schools employee records list the driver's name as Sharon
Sue Elkins, employed with Dayton City Schools since April 25, 1984.
Kirby said Elkins had no disciplinary marks against her.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins was taken to Dayton Police Department Third District
headquarters for a urine specimen and questioning _ standard
procedure, according to Hammann.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Dayton City Schools must transport students who attend
charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby said the incident is something that shakes everyone
involved with Dayton City Schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a traumatic experience for kids and parents,'' Kirby
said. ``I pray every day that something like this doesn't
happen...This is the kind of thing you never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   It was believed the first school bus fatality in the area since
the Feb. 27, 1995, death of Brandie Browder, 13, who was killed
when her jacket drawstring snagged in the handrail of a Beavercreek
school bus and she was dragged under the wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's accident was similar to an April 15 mishap in Wooster,
Ohio, where a kindergarten student was run over and killed by her
school bus just after she had stepped off the vehicle near her
home. The driver, Ross Winkler, failed to see that Cherice Duncan,
6, was in front of the bus when he pulled forward, police said.
Witnesses said the girl had bent down to pick up a piece of paper.
The driver stopped when he heard someone outside the bus yelling.
</P>
<P>
   A similar fatality occurred in Oxford, Ark., on Aug. 21. A
7-year-old boy was crushed by the rear wheels of the school bus
that had just dropped him off near his home, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Peterson writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
Lynn Hulsey contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
