<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SITES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia in running for AOL facility
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cobb County is one of three Southeastern sites America
Online Inc. is considering for a $500 million computer operations
center. AOL is expected to make a decision by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic about this,'' said Cobb Commission Chairman Bill
Byrne, who confirmed AOL is looking at a location in Smyrna for a
major facility. Besides the economic impact of the jobs it would
bring here, the presence of AOL _ a nationally prominent company _
would bolster Atlanta's image as a technology center.
</P>
<P>
   Other county and state economic development officials confirmed
a major technology company is in the final stages of a selection
process that includes a site in Smyrna. But they cited
confidentiality agreements and declined to identify AOL.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the nation's largest commercial online service, with
about 14 million subscribers and 20 million users. In 1998, the
company reported revenue of $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The economic development officials said the prospect they've
been courting will build at least a 350,000-square-foot building
and invest $500 million, a figure that includes support technology
as well as the building. The firm will employ about 200 skilled
technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   A representative at AOL's headquarters in Dulles, Va., wouldn't
comment on the company's plans. ``It is premature to discuss any
infrastructure growth plans at this point,'' said Wendy Goldberg.
``We are always working to provide a state-of-the-art experience
for our members. We have just completed a 180,000-square-foot data
center in Northern Virginia that still has a great deal of capacity
that we haven't tapped.''
</P>
<P>
   But state and local economic development officials said Tuesday
they have been working through a Morristown, N.J., site selection
consulting firm _ Wadley-Donovan Group _ for the past several
months on a project that involves the location of a technology
center. They say the company has narrowed its list of possible
sites to Charlotte, Vienna, Va., and Smyrna.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a data center project,'' said Randy Cardoza,
commissioner of the Georgia Department of Industry, Trade and
Tourism, when asked about the prospect of AOL. ``We have been
working with a consultant on a project that fits the specifications
and requirements of what you are talking about. I'm confident that
Georgia is going to compete very well on this type of project as we
move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael H.S. Hughes, director of Cobb County's Office of
Economic Development, would not identify the project as AOL but
said, ``We are in a very delicate stage in discussions. We have
presented information about incentives. And they haven't made a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn M. Pitts, Georgia Power's general manager for projects,
also said a technology company is close to making a decision on a
Cobb location. While declining to name the company, he said, ``This
would be a prize catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
