<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANKOVICH NAMED INTERIM AD AT NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Sam Jankovich is no baby-sitter. When he
turns over the athletic department to a permanent replacement
sometime next year, he intends to leave behind a blueprint for the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, as expected, became Cal State Northridge's interim
athletic director on Tuesday. CSUN president Blenda Wilson
hand-picked the 64-year-old former University of Miami and
Washington State athletic director to steer an oft-troubled program
toward stability.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who introduced Jankovich at an afternoon news
conference, also announced a change in CSUN's command structure.
Jankovich, and his replacement, will report directly to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the athletic director reported to Ron Kopita, the
vice president of student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich's term began immediately and will run at least through
June 30, 1999, or until a permanent replacement is selected for the
athletic director's job. A national search for a replacement is
under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings the kind of background, experience, integrity,
knowledge of the collegiate sports world that we are certainly
looking for,'' Wilson said. ``It gives our student-athletes, our
coaches and our supporters a sense of stability and integrity and
confidence in our ability to move forward with the sports
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Former athletic director Paul Bubb quit under administrative
pressure Nov. 6 in the aftermath of women's basketball coach
Michael Abraham's arrest on federal drug charges and subsequent
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bubb's resignation, CSUN was without an athletic director.
Men's basketball coach Bobby Braswell served as
``administrator-in-charge'' of the athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich wields complete power with the authority to hire and
fire coaches, as well as extend and renew contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be more of a fact-finding mission than
anything else,'' Jankovich said. ``You won't see any abrupt changes
or decisions, but there will be a tremendous amount of meetings _
individually, collectively, with coaches, with student-athletes,
with administrators, with Dr. Wilson's cabinet, faculty and people
on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coming here I want to look at it like I'm going to be the
athletic director here for 15 to 20 years. Anything we do is going
to be looking at the long range.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich will be paid from a base annual salary of $112,008,
which works out to $9,334 per month. Bubb was paid $86,700
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, who spends most of his time in Hayden Lake, Idaho,
will live in the area. He said he isn't interested in being the
permanent athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go ahead and analyze what we're doing internally, as
far as raising money and selling tickets and getting people
involved,'' Jankovich said. ``But most important of all _
networking. There's no room for negativism. I really do not care to
hear complaints about people who were here before. I want to find
out the strengths of the program, and what can we do to build on
the strengths of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious discussions between Wilson and Jankovich began two weeks
ago after Charles Reed, chancellor of the California State
University system, spoke with Jankovich.
</P>
<P>
   Reed has known Jankovich for 15 years, dating back to their days
in Florida. Reed headed Florida's university system when Jankovich
was at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Jankovich knows college sports, that's No.1,'' Reed said.
``No.2, he's a tough guy. They could use some of that there now.
No.3, he has a great network in college sports, and that network
will really help Northridge.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Jankovich's strengths is fund raising, a weak area for
CSUN. Before his arrival at Miami, the school raised less than
$400,000 in 1983. Five years later, Miami raised $3 million in
athletic funds.
</P>
<P>
   There was also turmoil within the athletic program at Miami
during Jankovich's seven-year reign. He hired Jimmy Johnson to
coach the Hurricanes, but he was also there during the time in
which the school was investigated and sanctioned by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Among the NCAA's findings during part of Jankovich's tenure
were: excessive financial aid given to athletes, excessive benefits
provided to athletes by fraudulent Pell Grants, improper employment
of football players during the school year, cash awards for
athletes for performance and a lack of institutional control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows what happened there and he took actions to improve
that, to clean up that,'' Reed said. ``He changed some of the
policies, and we all know who he was working with. He understands
all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, who left Miami in 1990 to become CEO of the New
England Patriots before being ousted in 1993, has spent the last
few years as a consultant. He's a graduate of the University of
Montana, a fellow Big Sky Conference school, and worked at
Washington State with current Big Sky associate commissioner Kathy
Noble. Early in his career, Jankovich was an assistant football
coach at Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Jankovich is working with Miami on the development of
a new, on-campus multi-use arena, but he said that wouldn't take
away from his position at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell and Jankovich had breakfast Tuesday morning. Wilson
then held a lunch for the coaches and athletic administration to
meet Jankovich.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich said he plans on meeting with the head coaches next
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
