<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PHONE-CHARGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO TO CANCEL LONG-DISTANCE SURCHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican regulators announced Tuesday that they
would cancel a surcharge that Telefonos de Mexico SA collected from
other long-distance companies to complete calls into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The surcharge had drawn accusations of unfair competition from
U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mexico stopped short of addressing several issues that
have caused long-distance companies like AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom to
slow the once-vigorous pace of their investments in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Lozano Alarcon, president of the Federal
Telecommunications Commission here, said that the 58 percent
surcharge would be eliminated as of Jan. 1. Long-distance companies
that compete with Telefonos de Mexico, known as Telmex, will pay
the equivalent of 2.6 cents a minute for calls from the United
States into Mexico, about the same rate they were paying before the
surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom had protested the surcharge especially vigorously,
and earlier this year suspended a $900 million investment to expand
its fiber-optic network in Mexico, saying that regulations here
were giving a clear edge to Telmex.
</P>
<P>
   Telmex had monopolies in both long-distance and local phone
service until early last year, when Mexico opened to long-distance
competition. Telmex is still the monopoly carrier in local service,
but is about to face competition there as well.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom reacted cautiously Tuesday, saying
they needed time to study the measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
