<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATS FOR SCHUMER'S COLLECTION 
STRAWBERRY DOES STRAWBERRY 
BREAKFAST CHECK 
YOKO'S UNVEILING
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He got what he wanted, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   In the jockeying for congressional committee assignments,
Sen.-elect Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who defeated Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato last month, had asked for a seat on the Senate Banking
Committee or the Senate Judiciary Committee. The congressman said
he figured he would be named to one or the other before he moves
from one side of Capitol Hill to the other next month.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday he was named to both. He was also named to the Rules
Committee, which has jurisdiction over campaign finance laws. The
assignments were announced by the Senate Democratic steering
committee and are to be ratified by the Senate Democratic Caucus
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Banking and Judiciary assignments put him in familiar
territory _ he has been on the House Banking Committee for 18 years
and the House Judiciary Committee for 16. ``My experience,'' he
said, ``means that I can hit the ground running.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities Step Up to Charities' Plate
</P>
<P>
   Now the world knows what Darryl Strawberry, the 36-year-old New
York Yankees outfielder, has been doing since his operation for
colon cancer on Oct. 3: sketching a strawberry-shaped design to be
printed on a necktie by the V Foundation, a cancer research
organization started by the late basketball coach Jim Valvano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrote a letter to Darryl saying, `When you're feeling
better, we'd love for you to be a part of it,''' said Melissa
Lawrence, a vice president of the company that makes the ties for
the foundation. ``We got a letter back saying that he wanted to
jump in, and then we received the drawing.'' The $35 tie will go on
sale in March alongside ties based on drawings by other sports
figures, including Mark McGwire and Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``His is actually one of the better ones,'' Ms. Lawrence said of
Strawberry's sketch. ``None of these guys are professing to be
artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's chemotherapy continues, and he has been working out
at a gym, said a spokesman, Eric Grossman. ``He's progressing
nicely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Kennedy Jr. is scheduled to hand over a $25,000
check to an old school chum Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Kennedy's own money, but a grant from the nonprofit
Robin Hood Foundation. He will give the check to Hans Hageman at
the foundation's annual ``heroes award breakfast'' at Tavern on the
Green. Hageman is executive director of the East Harlem School, a
private middle school on East 103rd Street; his brother Ivan is the
principal.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Hageman, 40, was a classmate of Kennedy at the Collegiate
School in the 1960s. In the 1980s they were together again, as
assistant district attorneys in Manhattan. The school receives more
than $60,000 a year from the Robin Hood group.
</P>
<P>
   Still a Dreamer, Not the Only One
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Almost overnight, the Christmas decorations went up
in Manhattan. The big round wreaths appeared on the wide columns
beneath the vaulted sky ceiling in Grand Central Terminal. Long
strands of tinsel transformed whole buildings into full-size
ornaments. And Tuesday, Yoko Ono unveiled her holiday billboard.
</P>
<P>
   She and John Lennon did the same thing 29 years ago (Broadway at
43rd Street then, Broadway at 47th Street now.) ``War Is Over! If
You Want It'' the billboard says. ``Happy Christmas From John &AMP;
Yoko.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she saw no reason to change the wording.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I really felt the need to do this was I
went to Belfast recently, and I saw that after the peace treaty,
there was a marked difference,'' she said. ``The locals were
telling me that they were feeling totally frightened before.
There's no fear now.''
</P>
<P>
   How much does a 20-by-60-foot billboard cost?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got the bill yet,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
