<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA COMES BACK REFRESHED FROM BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA guard Andy Meyers had an ideal Thanksgiving.
He ate three turkey dinners, gained about 10 pounds, dominated the
couch and watched every football game he could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole weekend was a food festival,'' he said, grinning.
``My eyes hurt because I watched more football in four days than I
watched film all season.''
</P>
<P>
   One worry interrupted Meyers' fowl and football bliss: What if
four days off was too much? Would the Bruins return to practice
Monday sluggish and sloppy and unprepared for the monumental game
at Miami?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking to myself, `Four days off is a long time,'''
Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked into UCLA's weight room Monday morning, Meyers
got the answer he was hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was fired up,'' he said. ``We were thinking about
Miami, and people were ready to practice. We were away just enough
to feel good, for our knees and bodies to feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long, pressure-filled season, Thanksgiving gave UCLA the
respite it needed before a grueling stretch, what with Miami, final
exams and the bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Sunday, I was anxious to play football again, and I hadn't
felt that way all year,'' tight end Mike Grieb said.
</P>
<P>
   It showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're frisky,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Rain gang: UCLA practiced in the rain Tuesday for the first time
this season, but there was some dispute about previous rain
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo thought the last rain practice was in 1995, before the
USC game, while kicker Chris Sailer claimed it was last year,
before Washington. Either way, the players seemed to enjoy
themselves. Linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo finished practice with a
head-first slide, caking himself in mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned with alignments and assignments, but it's
hard to throw and catch and keep your footing,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami update: The Hurricanes are without their top receiver,
Reggie Wayne, who will miss the rest of the season with a knee
injury. Wayne led the Hurricanes in receptions (42) and yards (629)
before tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee in
practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Motivation? Three weeks ago, Toledo criticized defensive
coordinator Nick Aliotti for using a scheme that he felt was too
complicated and relied too heavily on man-to-man coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti, who worked with Toledo at Oregon in 1988, was surprised
and stung by the remarks, but they apparently made an impact. After
miserable performances against Stanford and Oregon State, the
Bruins held Washington and USC to 24 and 17 points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we did simplify, and we put in some zone,'' Toledo
said. ``Part of my job as a head coach is to motivate. You've got
to motivate players, and sometimes you have to motivate coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Weakness-of-schedule: Quarterback Cade McNown believes
strength-of-schedule is a flawed component in the Bowl Championship
Series formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that means is it's up to the athletic director, five or
seven years ago, to pick the right teams,'' McNown said.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Reserve receiver Jon Dubravac has a strained
hamstring and has not practiced this week. He's questionable for
Miami. Reserve tight end Randy Hakes had an appendectomy last week
and will not play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
