<HEADER>
A8132 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     12-01 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE NBA is enjoying one of its most competitive seasons, even
though, as you may have noticed, there hasn't been so much as a
practice game in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a 6-10 guy just signed a contract for more than $13
million a year, which is not bad for a fellow so skinny Shaquille
O'Neal could snap him like a matchstick just by leaning on him. So
in the absence of an actual game, you congratulate Randy Johnson
for at least reminding fans of the scent of NBA money.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't great enough, Clyde Drexler has won three of
his first five games as the rookie head coach of the Houston
Cougars, including victories over Texas and LSU. The really sweet
part is the fact The Glide has no reason to feel any regrets, or
any withdrawal symptoms, because he hasn't missed anything. In
truth, if Clyde had only foreseen the lockout, he could have stayed
with the Rockets for another year and still coached the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   What is really strange about the standoff between the players
and owners is how calmly the masses have accepted it. Perhaps they
understand that this is a war between the privileged and the
overprivileged, and in the end, the NBA can settle this beef in
January and still squeeze in six months of hoops, including all of
the only season that counts, the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Randy Johnson and how the Astros will
replace him, or not. The obvious, unemotional answer to that
question is that they would have won 92 games without him and still
perished in the first round of the National League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was swell to have Johnson racking up 10 wins against one
loss and toying with the minds of opposing teams. Having Johnson's
name in the pitching matchups was like keeping a werewolf in your
refrigerator. They make terrific watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will miss that fear factor, although we must admit
the Padres coped with it nicely, beating Johnson twice in tightly
pitched games. But we don't recall any visiting teams drooling at
the prospect of facing the rest of Houston's staff _ Shane
Reynolds, Mike Hampton, Jose Lima and Sean Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gerry Hunsicker, the Astros' general manager, will
continue his record of shrewd Christmas shopping and pick up
another ace from the as-is counter. Or simply one who has grown
disenchanted with his current team and needs a roof over his head
while waiting for another club to offer him a blank check.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, and how we adore that phrase, is this: The
Astros survived the loss of Darryl Kile, who chose the thin air of
Colorado, and they will survive their brief love affair with the
Big Unit, who went for the dry air of Arizona and a map to the Lost
Dutchman's gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if the Astros tried to woo him with table scraps.
They can, in fact, take the $11 million annual salary they saved by
not signing the scary lefthander and buy an entire outfield. Or
their own special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it would have been nice if Randy had wanted to stay
here, if he had liked Houston nearly as much as money. No one can
fault the effort he gave here, or his manners. He was surprisingly
modest and pleasant and grateful for the affection the fans showed
him. For all his talents, he made no waves. He wasn't one of those
haunted souls who can cross an intersection and make cars behind
him crash head-on.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can't sign someone to replace him, because there
isn't a pitcher out there who fits his description. You don't find
many southpaws who can hurl that 100-mph lightning and who
intimidate hitters without having to pitch inside.
</P>
<P>
   Offhand, we don't recall anyone accusing Johnson of being a
headhunter. You wonder what damage he might do if he had the
temperament of a Don Drysdale, Bob Gibson or Rob Dibble. Drysdale,
who was the righthanded enforcer for the Dodgers when Sandy Koufax
was their lefthanded genius, made life miserable for a lot of
hitters. He still holds the record for most hit batsmen in a
career, 154. It is a record that may last longer than Mark
McGwire's, because the umpires won't eject a player for hitting
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The game has undergone a sweeping change in this area. The umps
will banish a pitcher on suspicion of throwing inside. Drysdale,
and even the sweet-tempered Nolan Ryan, considered it a sign of
respect when they made a batter bite the dust.
</P>
<P>
   We will do Reynolds no service if we expect him to make us
forget Randy Johnson. But he has a touch of temper and the talent
to move up in class. Reynolds won 19 games last season, and that _
and a name like Shane _ will qualify you as the ace on most
pitching staffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-98 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
