<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CANUCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TIE CANUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They weren't particularly happy. They weren't satisfied.
However, sometimes earning a point is enough. The fact is, the
Bruins are unbeaten in six games (4-0-2) after Tuesday night's 1-1
tie with the Vancouver Canucks at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The game wasn't pretty. But the Bruins are 6-1-4 in their last
11, and there weren't many complaints in the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came hard,'' said defenseman Kyle McLaren. ``It took us a
while to respond, but we were lucky to have a goal and hold on. I
don't think anybody here is satisfied with the way we played. If we
play our best, we probably would've won that game. We had too many
bad plays all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a point. It keeps our unbeaten streak alive. We move on
and look forward to Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have gone to overtime in five of their last 10
contests, going 1-0-4 in them. If anyone felt as if there were a
victory here, it was the Canucks, who were mired in a five-game
losing streak and hadn't gotten a point since Nov. 19, when they
beat Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver is missing its scoring punch with Alexander Mogilny
out with a knee injury, Todd Bertuzzi sitting out with a broken
leg, and disgruntled star Pavel Bure refusing to play while he
awaits a trade.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canucks came out hard in the early going, pressuring
Boston and limiting the Bruins to four shots in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Messier got Vancouver on the board first with his 10th goal
of the season at 13:27. Markus Naslund dished an off-balance pass
to Messier in front, and Messier directed it past goalie Byron
Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:56 of the second period, Dave Scatchard was called for
high-sticking, but the Bruins couldn't convert. Just 12 seconds
after the power play expired, the Canucks thought they had a second
goal when Scatchard went right from the penalty box to the crease,
putting the puck past Dafoe after taking a pass from Trent Klatt.
However, Scatchard was so blatantly in the crease that he might as
well have been wearing goalie pads, and the score was nullified.
</P>
<P>
   With 29 seconds left in the period, the Bruins tied the game on
Sergei Samsonov's ninth goal of the year. Samsonov had the puck in
the far right circle and tried to pass to Dmitri Khristich in the
slot. Khristich was tied up by Brad May, and the puck pinballed to
Chris Taylor in the slot. Taylor got a whack at it before Samsonov
swooped in and buried the rebound past Garth Snow.
</P>
<P>
   And that was that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take the point, but I don't think we're satisfied with
it,'' said Ray Bourque. ``I don't think we played very well. We had
spurts, but overall, it wasn't a very good game. We played better
as the game went on, but that first half of the game wasn't our
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us a while to react the way we wanted to. When you get
pressured like that, sometimes you think you don't have as much
time as you do and you start throwing the puck around and you get
bottled up in your end for the whole shift and you're scrambling
and it's just chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're being checked like that, you have to pick up the
skating and intensity and start bumping and taking over that part
of the game. We knew what was coming. I don't think we reacted well
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns said it might not have been great, but he
didn't like the fact the team was booed at the end. Some nights, he
said, it just isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the most we've ever been hit by an opposing team,
but we knew that,'' said Burns. ``These guys are on a long road
trip and they haven't won a game. They're not going to come in here
and roll over and die.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out and hit us pretty hard. We fought back and got a
point out of it. We got booed for it. I don't think we deserve to
be booed _ we've lost one game out of our last 11. I don't think we
deserve any criticism tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
